</center></div>
<p align=center><font size=4><b>MEMORANDUM</b></font></p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>TO : THE PRESIDENT <br>
CHAMBER OF MINES <br>
55 HOLLARD STREET <br>
MARSHALLTOWN 2170<br>
</strong><br>
</p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>DATE: 17 AUGUST 1996</strong><br>
</p>
</blockquote>
<p>We, mineworkers and members of the National Union of Mineworkers, are gathered here today to remind the chamber of 
Mines of the historic struggles we have waged since the inception of the mining industry. We want to remind the Chamber of 
Mines that August has a special meaning in the struggle of mineworkers and that history has a way of repeating itself.</p>
<p>It was on 12 August 1946 that the African Mine Workers Union showed its muscle to demand a minimum wage of ten 
shillings per day. It was on 09 August 1987 that the 21 day strike shook the Chamber.</p>
<p>This mass action &quot;The Great Mineworkers Strike&quot; challenged the harsh working and living conditions created by the Chamber 
of Mines. It challenged the cruel migrant labour system, hostel accommodation, high frequency of accidents and starvation 
wages. It was a collective demand from the down trodden to be treated as human beings. Single sex hostel accommodation 
was and remains fertile ground for agent provocateurs in many cases in collusion with employers to instigate tribal faction 
fights. The unfortunate killings in East Driefontein, even during the course of this week is proof of the dangers promoted by the 
hostel system under the Chamber of Mines.</p>
<p>Today mineworkers are still subjected to injustices, inequality and racial discrimination which has been outlawed in the rest of 
the country. Like our comrades in 1946 we still demand :</p>
<ul>
<li>that the life of all mines be prolonged. That the mining industry be made safe and become the highest paying in line with 
the rest of the world. </li>
<li>a new and appropriate job grading system which rewards and encourages improved skills. </li>
<li>that this system replace the archaic Paterson Grading System meant to keep black mineworkers subservient and 
unskilled. </li>
<li>that employers should finance education and training with emphasis on collective bargaining and industrial relations and 
other life skills. </li>
<li>an increase in paid maternity leave and guaranteed job security. </li>
<li>the dismantling of inequality, especially racial discrimination in payment of wages. </li>
</ul>
<p>and finally<br>
</p>
<ul>
<li>a living wage. </li>
</ul>
<p>After 50 years of struggle, our demands are still as resonant and relevant as they were in 1946 and we demand that they be 
addressed now.</p>
<p>We demand that the Chamber of Mines responds within seven (7) days or take responsibility for the consequences.</p>
<p align=center>Signed in JOHANNESBURG on the 17th day of August 1996.<br>
<br>
<br>
</p>
<p><b>Signed : .....................................................</b> </p>
<blockquote>
<p><b>On behalf of the National Union of Mineworkers <br>
<br>
<br>
</b></p>
</blockquote>
<p><b>Signed : .....................................................</b> </p>
<blockquote>
<p><b>On behalf of the Chamber of Mines<br>
<br>
</b></p>
</blockquote>
