<li><a href="#BURSARIES">BURSARIES IN THE MINING INDUSTRY</a></li>
</ul>
<p align=center><font color="#008040"><font size=5><em><b><tt><img src="../images/linegr.gif" align=bottom width=402 height=5></tt></b></em></font></font></p>
<p><a name="MINERAL "><b>SOUTH AFRICA'S MINERAL WEALTH</b> </a></p>
<p>South Africa's mineral reserves are unique in the Western world. The extent and variety of its mineral products, many of 
strategic importance, and the sheer size of the mineral industry's research programmes make South Africa one of the mining 
giants. South Africa is self-sufficient in most minerals and has abundant reserves of many minerals which are scares in the rest 
of the world. The region contains 92 per cent of the free world's total manganese ores, 94 per cent of platinum group metals 
and over 70 per cent of vanadium and chromium ores. South Africa also has the largest gold deposits in the world, with 
impressive reserves of uranium, antimony, asbestos, vermiculite, fluorite and high-grade iron ore. </p>
<p>The value of South African gold production has increased eightfold since 1940 and the value of other minerals produced has 
increased by no less than for-fivefold. The mining and processing of minerals has played a major role in bringing South Africa 
to the stage where, in almost very respect, it is the most advanced country in Africa. </p>
<p>In 1995 some 400 000 people were employed in the South African mining industry. The vigorous growth of mining and 
minerals processing creates many opportunities for mining, mechanical electrical and metallurgical engineers and geologists. 
Expansion has been so rapid that for many years the manpower requirements have outstripped the available labour resources, 
especially in the more highly skilled categories. Increasing mineral exports will generate investment capital for new ventures for 
greater local processing of minerals and the manufacture of finished products. Minerals will remain South Africa's major source 
of foreign exchange earnings and there is no doubt that mining will dictate the pace of economic development for many years 
to come. </p>
<p><b>THE </b><a name="CHALLENGES"><b>CHALLENGES</b></a><b> IN THE MINERALS INDUSTRY</b> </p>
<p>Man has been fascinated by minerals since the dawn of civilisation. The names given to the epochs of human development - 
Stone Age, Bronze Age, Iron Age - reflect how human progress has been measured against man's ability to utilise minerals, 
smelt ores, and fashion metals into useful articles. Industrial society today would be inconceivable without mineral fuels, raw 
materials and processed goods. </p>
<p>As we move into the 21st century the challenges in mining and minerals processing become greater. Take, for example, the 
design problems created by Concorde. The faster a supersonic plane flies, the more stringent the material requirements 
become because surface temperatures and stresses rise dramatically. Originally, only titanium alloys were considered to have 
the necessary strength-to-weight ratio and resistance to high temperatures and corrosion for use in Concorde. But aluminum, 
at a tenth of the price of titanium, was considered to be an attractive alternative, if it could be alloyed to withstand 
temperatures of over 127&#186;C. This led to metallurgical and aeronautical engineers developing an aluminium alloy containing 
copper, magnesium, iron and nickel which now constitutes the 70 tones of metal that is used in Concorde's airframe and skin. 
the mining industry needs people who can think big; it also has the financial resources to convert bold thoughts into action. </p>
<p>Although some minerals are still mined at great depths, there is an increasing tendency to work low-grate deposits in large 
open pit (surface) operations. In this process, great tonnages of soil and ore are shifted by large earth-moving machines and 
ore carriers. Mechanisation, automation and computers help to keep costs down, increase production targets and maximise 
efficiency. </p>
<p>To ensure continued exploration and increased growth and efficiency, the mining industry spends hundreds of millions of rands 
on research and development, supporting the biggest research effort in the private sector of South African industry. Almost 
every category of scientist and engineer can be found amongst the many hundreds of researchers, technicians and technologist 
who are engaged in exciting projects which will take South Africa into the next century. Special emphasis is placed on safety, 
mechanisation and improved deep-level mining techniques. </p>
<p>Computers form an integral part of all mining and minerals processing operations. Engineers in the minerals industry rely heavily 
on these tools and have to know how to operate them. Mining operations are made more cost-efficient and South Africa 
remains competitive in world mineral markets with the help of computer technology. </p>
<p><b>UNLIMITED </b><a name="OPPORTUNITIES "><b>OPPORTUNITIES</b> </a></p>
<p>The vigorous growth in mining and minerals processing in the past decade has created wonderful career opportunities for 
school leavers and matriculants. South Africa is one of the most important mining countries in the world, having vast mineral 
deposits yet to be fully exploited. </p>
<p>Mining in South Africa has become one of the country's foremost technological industries, contributing nearly half of the money 
spent on research by private enterprise. The mines, mining finance houses and research organisations require an endless variety 
of technically skilled scientists and engineers to keep South Africa in the forefront of mining. The industry also needs many 
non-technical personnel to provide the legal, medical, financial and other services associated with an industry that has 
investments worth billions of rands. This is why the mining industry offers many valuable bursaries for different disciplines of 
university study. Furthermore, matriculants with potential and initiative who are interested in further study, may also reach top 
management positions. </p>
<p>The mining industry has a wide range of training schemes designed to make the most of young people's potential and, in many 
cases, regardless of the academic qualifications. The university graduate and technikon diplomate trained in scientific 
approaches to engineering problems have an undoubted advantage over others and are marked for rapid promotion to senior 
positions. This is, of course, assuming that their personal attributes match their academic background. Whatever the basic 
qualifications, competent personnel who are prepared to study and pass examinations can advance very rapidly in the mining 
industry. Although the demand is for good quality matriculants, with above average passes in mathematics and science, there 
are opportunities in many other fields as well! </p>
<p>Matriculants have the choice of a number of student official courses (mining and metallurgical engineering, mechanical and 
electrical engineering and, to a lesser extent, geology and personnel administration) designed to give them the practical 
grounding and theoretical knowledge necessary to obtain their national and higher diplomas. Matriculants, and in some cases 
persons with lesser qualifications, are sought for various apprenticeship courses. Those persons with standard eight and higher, 
can also do the more practically orientated student miners' course, provided that they are able to pass the necessary selections 
criteria. </p>
<p>Although not every graduate or diplomate engineer will become a mine manager, consulting engineering or managing director, 
those who show initiative and apply themselves will find considerable opportunity to reach senior positions. </p>
<p>The mining industry offers beginners a highly competitive starting salary, low-cost accommodation and meals and excellent 
recreational facilities. Don't get left behind, read on to find out more about a career in the minerals industry! </p>
<p><a name="PLANNING"><b>PLANNING</b></a><b> YOUR CAREER</b> </p>
<p>The word CAREER comes from the French word `carri&egrave;re' which means a chariot course. So it sounds as if a career should 
send one racing towards success. This is not always the case if you make an incorrect choice. </p>
<p>Choosing a career is probably one of the most important decisions that you will have to make during your lifetime, and careful 
though should be given to WHERE and IF you could be employed when you have chosen your career and study path. You 
should always try to establish if there is a demand for personnel in the type of career that you intend to pursue. Many pupils 
continue studying after they leave school, only to discover at a later stage that there are very limited work opportunities for 
people with their qualifications. Some qualifications, such as engineering, are always in demand in modern industrialised 
societies. for many kinds of further education at university, technikon and technical college, mathematics, physical science and 
technology subjects are important and necessary to gain entrance to these courses. Remember that mathematics and physical 
science are key subjects for many careers, so don't neglect them! </p>
<p>A career is a way of life and not only a means of living, therefore considerable time and though should be given to your career 
choice. Go out and talk to people in industry to find out what different careers offer and what courses and bursaries are 
available to assist you when you are studying. The career you choose should provide you with the following : </p>
<ul>
<li>Job satisfaction </li>
<li>Financial independence </li>
<li>Security </li>
<li>Job Mobility </li>
</ul>
<p><b>Here are some useful hints that you can use when preparing for an interview :</b> </p>
<ul>
<li>Make sure that you have the correct address, place and time of the interview </li>
<li>Try to establish beforehand who the interviewer will be </li>
<li>Always dress smartly </li>
<li>Relax during the interview but be articulate and positive when you answer questions </li>
</ul>
<p><b>These are some of the typical questions that you may be asked:</b> </p>
<ul>
<li>What can you tell us about your school career? </li>
<li>What do you know about the minerals industry? </li>
<li>Why do you want a bursary? </li>
<li>In what field do you want to study? </li>
<li>Do you have any plans for further study? </li>
<li>What sort of position do you see yourself attaining between the ages of 30 - 40? </li>
<li>How would you describe your character, abilities and weaknesses? </li>
</ul>
<p><a name="WHAT"><b>WHAT</b></a><b> IS ENGINEERING?</b> </p>
<p>Engineering is the application of scientific knowledge and imagination to everyday problems. The engineer is concerned with 
the improvement of people's living standards by designing and constructing buildings, developing new processes, machinery 
and equipment. Engineering in the minerals industry is responsible for extracting the raw materials and for processing metals 
and minerals which are the foundation for manufacturing. </p>
<p><b>What do engineers do?</b> </p>
<p>In most countries relatively few engineers are employed in innovative or creative activities. For example, not every aeronautical 
engineer gets the chance to be involved in the design of a new space shuttle or supersonic aircraft. The variety of engineering 
work opportunities lies in the operating and production fields. Whichever field of engineering you embark upon, your duties 
could include one or more of the following: production, design, research and development, construction, manufacture, 
planning, evaluation, operation and management. Many engineers attain management positions and must therefore be 
conversant with financial matters, have managerial skills and the ability to work with, lead and motivate people. They also need 
to be flexible and have a problem-solving attitude to work. </p>
<p><b>Who should become an engineer?</b> </p>
<p>ARE YOU CURIOUS AS TO HOW THINGS WORK? </p>
<p>Engineers must have enquiring minds and should ask questions to find out how and why things work. Engineers should be able 
to persevere on projects when the going gets tough and must strive for excellence at all times. Engineers must be concerned 
with the safety of the work place and the people who work there. </p>
<p>In order to gain admission to an engineering faculty at a university you will require, as a minimum, a matriculation certificate or 
an exemption from the Joint Matriculation Board, normally with C symbols and above on the higher grade in mathematics and 
physical science. Naturally, the better your marks, the greater are your chances of being accepted by an engineering faculty 
and of receiving a bursary. Many of the engineering students who enter the minerals industry have bursaries and scholarships 
from mining houses. </p>
<p>For admission to a technikon, you will require a senior certificate with an acceptable pass in mathematics and physical science. </p>
<p><b>What salary will you receive?</b> </p>
<p>Persons with engineering and technical skills may expect to receive above average salaries throughout the world. As in any 
large industry, salaries differ from company to company. To find out more about salaries and employment packages, please 
discuss this with your prospective employer when you attend an interview. Do remember that a career choice should not be 
based on salary alone. You should also satisfy yourself that your careers can : </p>
<ul>
<li>Provide further study, training and career development </li>
<li>Offer security </li>
<li>Give you job satisfaction </li>
<li>Allow you to develop management potential </li>
</ul>
<p><b>MINING </b><a name="ENGINEERING "><b>ENGINEERING</b> </a></p>
<p>Once discovered and evaluated, minerals must be mined, brought to the surface and extracted from the waste rock. There are 
two principal types of mining : open pit and underground mining. In open pit mining methods, the overburden must be removed 
by stripping the surface rock and soil to expose the orebody, which can then be removed and processed. </p>
<p>Deep-level underground mining and large scale open pit mining are developments of the 20th century, made possible by mining 
technology, modern equipment and advanced minerals processing techniques. South Africa leads the world in deep-level 
mining technology. In order to maintain this level of development, a high standard of education and training of mining engineers 
is vital. South African university mining and minerals processing degrees and the training received on mines are exceptionally 
good, and are recognised world-wide. </p>
<p>Mining engineering is a challenging career. The mining engineer requires a good knowledge of mechanical, electrical and 
metallurgical engineering as well as geology, finance, economics and people management. </p>
<p><b>What does a mining engineer do?</b> </p>
<p>Mining engineers plan, design, construct, manage and operate mines and the facilities that are used to extract raw materials 
from the earth. </p>
<p>They are responsible for the economic and safe operation of mines. Some mining engineers work with geologists and 
metallurgical engineers to evaluate new ore deposits. Others are involved in the research and development of mining equipment 
and processes. Mining engineers can also be involved in the protection and rehabilitations of the environment. The ability to 
manage people forms an important part of the mining engineer's work and those who have leadership qualities will generally 
progress to senior positions in the mining industry. </p>
<p><b>What educational qualifications do you need?</b> </p>
<p>In order to gain entrance to study a Bsc degree in mining engineer at university, you will need a matriculation exemption 
certificate, normally with C symbols or above in mathematics and physical science on the higher grade. </p>
<p>Since the mining industry is becoming more technologically sophisticated, an interest in computer sciences and technical and 
engineering drawing is advantageous. </p>
<p>Newly qualified graduates in all the major engineering disciplines are given intensive on-the-job training to give them further 
practical and academic experience in order to prepare them for the Government Certificates of Competency, and to comply 
with requirements for possible registration with the South Africa Council of Professional Engineers. </p>
<p><a name="METALLURGICAL"><b>METALLURGICAL</b></a><b> ENGINEERING AND MINERALS PROCESSING</b> </p>
<p>Initially, the word metallurgy meant `the art of extracting metals from their ores&#148;, but it now has a much wider meaning as it 
includes the science of the structres and properties of metals and their allos, ceramics and polymers. This is the fascinating field 
of the metallurgist, who uses sicentific expertise and knowledge to extract and process minerals in rocks in concentrations of as 
little as five parts per million. </p>
<p>Mining, minerals processing and materials fabrication are vital to all industrialised countires and the aviation industry is a good 
example of this interrelationship. Aluminium, normaly used in aircraft, is replaced by titanium in planes that exceed Mach ll. 
This is because titanium has a higher resistance to extreme temperatures and stresses. The lockhead A-11 Intercepter fighter 
plane, capable of Mach 111, is said to contain up to 85 per cent titanium by weight in the structure. Titanium is as strong as 
steel and half the wieght. It does, however, require specialised fabrication techniques and is costly, as an aluminium alloy is 
used in larger aircrafts. </p>
<p>With regard to the car industry, carbon fibre brakes have been specifically designed for formula one racing cars, resulting in a 
weight saving of more than 60 per cent when compared to conventional brakes. </p>
<p><b>What does a metallurgical and minerals processing engineer do?</b> </p>
<p>Metallurgical engineers need specialised knowledge of the properties of a very wide range of materials. They must have a 
detailed understanding of the physical and chemical characteristics of minerals an dhow they react under different conditions. 
The function of the extractive metallurgist is to manage the process of ores, the extraction of the valuable metal or mineral and 
further benefication or refining. Metallurgists design, test, operate and manage minerals processing plants, and must be 
competent to use the latest scientific technology. In addition, there are good prospects for metallurgists in research and 
development. </p>
<p>Because minerals are finite and because some ore grades are decreasing, metallurgists need to recover as much of the mineral 
possible. Modern processing and manufacturing plants, therefore, use the most up-to-date analytical instruments and 
computers to help monitor processes and maximise efficiency. </p>
<p>The metallurgical engineer, like the mining engineer, is a highly trained person and between them, they work out the probability 
of mining and processing various mineral deposits. The undergraduate has the choice of becoming an extractive metallurgist in 
the minerals industry or of becoming a physical metallurgist. Some metallurgists prefer to take employment in research and 
development organisations or academic institutions. Leaders in the industry forsee that the metallurgical graduate will leave 
more and more of the everyday plant operations to trained technicians and technologists so that the graduate can take the lead 
in research, process and development and management. </p>
<p><b>What educational qualifications do you need?</b> </p>
<p>A matriculation exemption certificate from the Joint Matriculation Board, normally with C symbols or above on the higher 
grade in mathematics and physical science, are the basic entrance requirements to study metallurgy at university. An interest in 
technology and computes is useful. </p>
<p>The mining industry also employs chemical engineers and preference is given to chemical engineers who have taken the 
extractive metallurgy/minerals processing option at university. </p>
<p><a name="MECHANICAL"><b>MECHANICAL</b></a><b> AND ELECTRICAL ENGINEERING</b> </p>
<p>Modern mining techniques, machines and equipment are far removed from the simple `pick and shovel' operations of our 
pioneers. today's miners use sophisticated technology to do their jobs. As we move towards the 21st century, there is an ever 
increasing demand for minerals and metals to provide for our daily needs and meeting these rising production targets is a 
constant challenge! In this atmosphere of dynamism, mechanical and electrical engineers play vital roles. No mine could 
function without power and the machines that depend on it. The responsibility for providing this power and the associated 
facilities rests with the engineering department on the mine and the consulting engineers' department at head office. </p>
<p>This enterprising world of deep-level and large-scale open pit mining, automation, robotics, computer-aided design, 
hydropower and environmental control and manipulation provides the challenges that engineers and engineering departments 
must face and overcome. </p>
<p>Fifty years ago most of us would not have believed that man would set foot on the moon, or mine gold at nearly four 
kilometres beneath the earth's surface. There are few of us who know what the future holds, but it will not be long before 
automated robots with laser technology will assist with mining orebodies which are difficult or dangerous to extract. 
Mechanical and electrical engineers are and will be involved in these developments. </p>
<p>The mining industry needs mechanical and electrical engineers who can create, innovate and manage systems that will take us 
through to the 21st century. The ultimate objective of engineering is to ensure that production targets can be achieved- by 
providing systems technology and machinery that will do the job as efficiently and as safely as is possible. Such mining 
equipment may be electronic and computer controlled, hydraulic or pneumatic in operation, driven by overhead wires, trailing 
cable or batter, or by diesel engines and gas turbines. </p>
<p>As part of their academic training, mechanical engineers need to study the principles design and testing of a wide range of 
mechanical devices and the types of materials and metals used in the construction of these machines. </p>
<p>The field of electrical engineering is divided into two main areas: </p>
<ul>
<li>Heavy current electrical engineering which is concerned with electrical systems and large currents of electrical power </li>
<li>Light current electrical engineering (or electronics) which involves the design, operation and maintenance of circuits 
which use smaller amounts of electricity </li>
</ul>
<p>Because so many students choose to work in electronics, there is a shortage of specialists in heavy current electrical 
engineering and this means that career and promotional opportunities are very good in this field in the mining industry. </p>
<p><a name="HOW"><b>HOW</b></a><b> TO BECOME AN ELECTRICAL OR MECHANICAL ENGINEER</b> </p>
<p>There are two main routes that can be followed to become either an electrical or mechanical engineer. These branches of 
engineering can be studied at either a university or a technikon. The university route is for the student with good grades and 
ability in mathematics and physical science. University students are required to work six to eight weeks per year in industry. 
The technikon route, while having an academic side, tends to relate to theory to the practical side of engineering, thus making 
the theory easier to understand. Students whose aptitudes do not lie so much with academic study tend to follow the technikon 
route. Technikon training alternates employment with periods of full-time study. </p>
<p>A third route to becoming an engineer is to obtain an N6 certificate through a technical college. This is the route normally 
followed by school leavers who join the mining industry as apprentices. </p>
<p>A Government Certificate of Competency as electrical or mechanical engineer is a prerequisite for certain mine appointments. 
Only applicants in possession of a degree, T4 diploma or N6 certificate are permitted to write this examination after they have 
worked on a mine for two years. Graduates only have to write mining law whilst applicants in possession of a T4 or N6 must 
write both mining law and plant engineering. </p>
<p><b>Learner Officials (Engineering) - Technikon study</b> </p>
<p>The learner official schemes are designed to provide the necessary training and education for young matriculants to progress to 
managerial positions in a number of fields. </p>
<p>Matriculants with university entrance passes in mathematics and science can become mechanical and electrical engineers 
through the learner official scheme offered by some mining houses. the intake of mechanical/electrical engineering students is 
limited and only the best applicants are selected. the learner official scheme in engineering offers similar benefits to those in 
mining and metallurgy. </p>
<p>Learner officials are eligible to be chosen for bursaries to study mechanical or electrical engineering full-time at a university. 
Others receive four years pratical training, interspersed by annual theoretical technikon courses of five months which prepare 
them for the engineering diploma examination (mechanical or electrical). </p>
<p>After obtaining their diplomas, learner officials join university graduates as junior engineers on a two year training course in 
order to prepare them for the engineer's Certificate of Competency examination. On passing this examination they become 
eligible for appointments as section engineers. </p>
<p>After acquiring sectional managerial status, mechanical and electrical engineers can rise to decision-making positions in 
industry. </p>
<p><b>Career paths in the mining industry</b> </p>
