<p><a name="LEARNER"><b>LEARNER</b></a><b> OFFICIALS MINING AND METALLURGY - (TECHNIKON STUDY)</b> </p>
<p>The learner official courses in the mining industry have been designed for matriculants with initiative and for those who are 
unable or do not want to study at university but would be able to attend technikon. Matriculants between the ages of 17 and 
24 who enter the mining industry as learner officials are one of the industry's main sources of senior staff. Career in the minerals 
industry offers opportunity, responsibility, work of tremendous interest and a good salary. </p>
<p>Matriculants can be engaged as learner officials in different engineering disciplines and may embark on structured training 
programmes lasting from three to six years. During this period, learner officials work approximately six months on a mine as 
part of the initial practical training. This completed, the learner officials have the option, according to their abilities, of following 
one of three routes: </p>
<ul>
<li>Promising students whose performance and ability indicate that they are capable of completing the university course in 
mining or metallurgy can apply for a bursary for full-time study </li>
<li>Subject to satisfactory performance, the learner official can enrol for the technikon Higher National Diploma course, 
comprising five months full-time study a year, for four years. The remainder of each of the years is spent gaining 
practical experience on mines </li>
<li>Those who do not like intensive study, but who are more practically orientated, can do the two year practical mining 
course to become shift bosses </li>
</ul>
<p>Learner officials are paid good salaries whilst they study. The company that employees them also pays any course fees and 
makes a contribution to the cost of prescribed books. </p>
<p>All technikon students in mining disciplines engaged by mining companies, members of the Chamber of Mines, have a 
structured training programme and are guaranteed the period of employment which is a prerequisite for the completion of their 
diploma. Many mining students who are at university receive a bursary which pays for tuition, residence fees and text books 
and in certain cases they also enjoy company benefits and receive a portion of their salary. Makes you think - doesn't it? </p>
<p>Another advantage of taking a mining related degree or diploma is that the student is prepared for the mine manager's 
Certificate of Competency and the other necessary government certificates or qualifications. In addition, from the day that a 
learner official is accepted as a trainee he receives all the benefits to which other mine employees are entitled. Some of these 
benefits include : </p>
<ul>
<li>Attractive training courses which provide low-cost, single quarter accommodation and meals </li>
<li>Subsidised accommodation for married employees </li>
<li>Generous leave allocations </li>
<li>Insurance, pension, medical and provident benefits </li>
</ul>
<p>For a more detailed description of what a career entails in mining engineering and metallurgy, we suggest you make an 
appointment with the lecturing staff at the university's and/or technikon's mining or metallurgy departments to find out more 
about the subject content of degree and diploma courses. You could also contact the Manpower and Education Department 
of the Chamber of Mines for career information. </p>
<p>Technikon entrance requirements are as follows for learner official courses: </p>
<p><b>Diploma courses in mining</b> </p>
<p>A Senior Certificate with an E symbol for mathematics on the higher grade or a D symbol on the standard grade. </p>
<p><b>Diploma courses in surveying, economic geology, extractive metallurgy and assaying</b> </p>
<p>A Senior Certificate with an E symbol for mathematics and physical science on the higher grade or D symbols on the standard 
grade. </p>
<p><a name="GEOLOGY"><b>GEOLOGY</b></a> </p>
<p>The general public often pictures the geologist as a romantic individual who spends his time driving around in a 
four-wheel-drive vehicle and prospecting, hammer in hand, in the veld. This is the picturesque side to geology, and although it 
still exists today, most exploration or field geologists are equipped with modern scientific instruments to assist in the search for 
new mineral deposits. </p>
<p>Most minerals occur in specific settings and it is the geologist's task to identify and find these deposits. The geologist's trained 
eye draws a wealth of conclusions from borehole core samples obtained from the earth's crust. </p>
<p>Although there are a number of economically important minerals contained in the soil and rocks in your garden at home, one of 
the reasons that they are not mined is that they are not present in sufficiently adequate concentrations to be extracted 
profitably. The geologist concerns himself with minerals that have been sufficiently concentrated by geological processes to be 
mined economically. </p>
<p><b>What do geologists do?</b> </p>
<p>Geologists use the following techniques to locate new mineral deposits: </p>
<ul>
<li>Remote sensing, photogeology and geological mapping </li>
<li>Geophysics - magnetic, radiometric, electrical, seismic and gravity surveys </li>
<li>Geochemisty. </li>
</ul>
<p>Once a mineral deposit is located, borehole drilling and logging take place in order to define and quantify the grade and size of 
the deposit. In this way, it is established whether or not mining of the orebody is possible. </p>
<p>In the mining industry, geologists fall into two broad categories: </p>
<ul>
<li>EXPLORATION GEOLOGISTS - who are involved in the search for and evaluation of new ore deposits, using one 
or more of the above techniques </li>
<li>MINING GEOLOGISTS - who are involved with the daily duties of manning geological departments on mines. The 
work, which is concerned with establishing the basic geological and structural properties of the orebody at the mine, 
involves surface and underground mapping in conjunction with logging and sample analysis. </li>
</ul>
<p><b>What educational qualifications do you need?</b> </p>
<p>Although there is at present no statutory training period geologists after university, experience gained on the job in early 
working years develops a geologist's skills. Some companies do have a formal training period for mining geologists. A 
BSc(Hons) degree or equivalent in geology, with good academic and practical training, entitles graduates to register as 
professional geologists with the South African Council for Natural Scientists. </p>
<p>Promotion is based on merit and experience, and the ability to do the job well allows individuals to rise to senior positions on 
mines and head offices of the mining finance houses. </p>
<p>Some mining houses offer a learner official course in geology which includes technikon study. </p>
<p><a name="APPRENTICES"><b>APPRENTICES</b></a><b>/LEARNER MINERS</b> </p>
<p>The mining industry offers apprentice training in all popular trades: fitting and turning, mechanical, electrical, plating, rigging and 
others. Apprentice training centres on the mines are equipped with the most modern training facilities to ensure that the 
specialists that they turnout are a credit to the industry. </p>
<p>Many apprentices start off with a standard eight education, but higher qualifications provide greater opportunities. There is no 
reason why an apprentice should not become a junior engineer through further study. </p>
<p>The duration of an apprenticeship depends on the trade chose, educational standard and the person's ability to pass a trade 
test (with the aid of classes at technical colleges). An apprentice who has an N2 can complete a four year apprenticeship in 
two and a half years, or a three year apprenticeship in on and a half years. No apprenticeship takes longer than four years. </p>
<p>Inexpensive accommodation and recreational facilities are provided. </p>
<p><b>What do apprentices do?</b> </p>
<p>Fitters are responsible for the maintenance of all mining machinery, including the assembling and fitting of new components. </p>
<p>Fitter and turners do all of the above and, in addition, use a wide variety of power operated tools such as lathes and milling, 
drilling and shaping machines. </p>
<p>Electricians inspect and maintain all the electrical equipment on mining machinery and in plants. They also lay cables and install 
transformers. </p>
<p>Platers are responsible for cutting, welding and fashioning steel into parts for mining machinery, conveyor systems and 
underground and surface vehicles. They also carry out pipe and construction work on surface and underground. </p>
<p>Diesel mechanics maintain diesel vehicles, including the heavy earth-moving equipment found on open cast mines. </p>
<p><b>What does a miner do?</b> </p>
<p>A miner is in charge of a working section using, at times, a number of sophisticated mining machines. He also has between 30 - 
100 assistants under his supervision. As mining becomes more mechanised, so the challenges become greater. The miner is 
responsible for safety and productivity in his work section and for conveying management's objectives to all employees under 
him. </p>
<p>The mineral that is being mined must generally be blasted and removed using machinery such as scraper winches and 
mechanical loaders. Underground support systems must be installed in carefully calculated patters before clearing and the next 
phase of mining operations takes place. </p>
<p>Learner miners are trained at fully-equipped training centres in both the practical and theoretical aspects of mining. The 
Chamber of Mines operates 10 training colleges for learner gold miners and two training colleges for learner coal miners. </p>
<p><b>What do you need to become a learner miner?</b> </p>
<p>If you are a male between the ages of 18 - 30 years, physically healthy with a minimum standard eight qualification, you could 
make a success of mining. Regardless of qualifications, all candidates must pass an aptitude test and undergo an interview. </p>
<p>To become a miner, it takes approximately 12 to 15 months of training to work the necessary number of shifts and to acquire 
the mandatory blasting certificate. Most of the training is practical, on-the-job training. Opportunities do exist for promotion to 
shift boss and mine overseer on the basis of merit and the necessary certification as laid down in mining legislation. </p>
<p><b>What are the benefits?</b> </p>
<ul>
<li>You are paid a salary while you learn </li>
<li>Learner miners enjoy pleasant, inexpensive accommodation and meals at all of the Chamber of Mines training colleges </li>
<li>Miners who are prepared to continue with further study can reach managerial positions </li>
<li>Married employees are provided with accommodation. </li>
</ul>
<p><a name="ENVIRONMENTAL"><b>ENVIRONMENTAL</b></a><b> ENGINEERING</b> </p>
<p>The improvement of safety and working conditions in South African mines has always been a priority of the mining industry. 
The environmental engineering department on a mine advices mine management on all aspects of airflow, heat, humidity and 
dust control. Ventilation and refrigeration are two of the most vital processes that fall under this department's responsibility. </p>
<p>Ventilation in deep-level mining involves forcing immense volumes of air through a network of underground shafts and tunnels. 
The process requires gigantic fans, huge electric motors and underground refrigeration plants. All large gold, coal and base 
metal mines have ventilation departments and the specialist staff employed in these departments measure and report on 
environmental conditions. They are also involved in the planning and design of ventilation and refrigeration systems. The use of 
ice as a means of cooling deep mines was established in 1986, after tests demonstrated that ice can be pneumatically 
conveyed over long distances. Another advantage of ice is that freezing desalinates mine water and thus provides clean water. 
A dense ice slurry can be sent underground and melted to yield clean, cold water at temperatures just above 0&#186;C. Two mines 
have already started to introduce the large-scale use of ice and the ERPM gold mine has a refrigeration plant that will 
eventually make 6 000 tons of ice per day. </p>
<p>The Chamber of Mines operates environmental training courses for new employees and experienced officials. After a period of 
about one year, the trainees should obtain their Elementary and Practical Mine Environmental Control Certificates. After a 
further two or three years study, they should be able to obtain the Advanced Certificate of Mine Environmental Control. 
Training does not stop here and additional in-house training is given to keep abreast of technological developments in 
computer applications, heat transfer theory, thermodynamics, refrigeration and airflow. The University of the Witwatersrand 
offers a Msc degree course in environmental engineering. Post-graduate study is also available in rock mechanics. </p>
<p><b>SURVEYING</b> </p>
<p>&#147;Surveying is the art of making such measurements and observations as are necessary to determine the position of areas and 
volumes of natural and man-made features on the earth's surface as well as underground, and representing the results on plans 
or maps drawn to a suitable scale&#148;. </p>
<p>The mine surveyor carries out routine practical survey duties in the mornings so that he can prepare and update all statutory 
surface and underground mine plans. He determines directions underground and measures up the areas and volumes of rock 
blasted by production crews. In addition he takes regular samples of all the reef or orebody exposed in the underground 
excavations in order to determine which areas are payable. In the afternoons, back in the office, the surveyor calculates and 
computer processes the survey data acquired during the morning and every month, measures the quantity of work done by the 
mining contractors underground and calculates their contract earnings. During his initial training the surveyor becomes 
competent in all aspects of practical surveying including the use of calculators, computers and surveying equipment. He is also 
training through the whole spectrum of mine valuation, from sampling to ore reserve computations and viability studies. </p>
<p>Those men wishing to enter this challenging career must be matriculated or have an equivalent certificate with a pass in 
mathematics. Promotion is dependent upon merit and the attainment of the required qualifications or Certificate of 
Competency. The University of the Witwatersrand offers a degree course in mine surveying. </p>
<p><b>SAMPLING AND ASSAYING</b> </p>
<p>In any type of mining operation it is important to know, on a regular basis, how much of a mineral or metal is being recovered. 
This enables management to determine whether the recovery process is efficient and where losses are occurring. Sampling and 
assaying is the process whereby ore samples are used to ascertain the value of an ore deposit. The assayer is responsible for 
the labority analysis of samples. This must be done quickly and accurately, using modern equipment and sophisticated 
techniques. </p>
<p>Potential candidates should be matriculated with average passes in mathematics and physical science and have an interest in 
chemistry. Further study towards a diploma or degree in chemistry will be encouraged. Samplers collect the ore from 
underground for assaying and, although a school leaving certificate is recommended, persons with lower qualifications would 
be considered. </p>
<p><a name="ADMINISTRATION"><b>ADMINISTRATION</b></a><b> AND MEDICAL SERVICES</b> </p>
<p>Modern mines run on up-to-date business lines. This means that the mining industry offers the applicant a wide variety of 
commercial positions. If you are interested in a career in the business world you should select the one that best fits your 
knowledge and skills. To do this, you must find out as much as possible about each of the careers available, before making a 
final decision. You will need some of the following attributes to be successful in the commercial sector: </p>
<ul>
<li>The ability to understand and interpret figures </li>
<li>Good communication skills </li>
<li>The capacity to work with and manage people </li>
<li>Initiative, conscientiousness and determination </li>
</ul>
<p><b>Accountancy and Commerce</b> </p>
<p>The two branches of accountancy most in demand are : </p>
<ul>
<li>Chartered accountancy </li>
<li>Cost and management accountancy </li>
</ul>
<p>Either of these branches of accounting requires a period of part-time study after attaining a commerce degree. Persons with a 
broad based B Com degree are often in demand by mining companies. </p>
<p><b>Personnel Management</b> </p>
<p>Personnel work includes the following : </p>
<ul>
<li>Manpower planning </li>
<li>Recruitment and selection of staff </li>
<li>Establishment and operation of medical and pension schemes </li>
<li>Monitoring and evaluation of employee efficiency </li>
<li>Attention to employees' welfare needs </li>
</ul>
<p><b>Training</b> </p>
<p>Training is an ongoing process; its function is to improve employees' job performances by improving skills. Training staff liaise 
with managers to establish in which areas skills can be improved and implement courses to achieve this objective. Training staff 
also have to supervise the training and development of human resources on the mine. </p>
<p><b>Industrial Relations</b> </p>
<p>Industrial relations personnel are concerned with the establishment and maintenance of systems of negotiations, consultation 
and communication aimed at promoting healthy relationships between management and employees. </p>
<p>Their work involves : </p>
<ul>
<li>Negotiating agreements with trade union representatives on procedures and conditions of employment </li>
<li>Devising and implementing disciplinary and grievance procedures </li>
<li>The interpretation and implementation of agreements and labour legislation </li>
</ul>
<p><b>Medical Services</b> </p>
<p>The mining industry, which pioneered employee compensation in South Africa, continues to be a leader in the field of insurance 
cover for employees and their dependants through the Rand Mutual Assurance Company, an affiliate of the Chamber of 
Mines. </p>
<p>The mining houses run many well-equipped hospitals for mine employees throughout South Africa. In addition to the normal 
treatment of disease and injuries, mine hospitals actively promote public health and preventative medicine and thus offer good 
all-round training to young medical personnel. To encourage further training amongst mine medical officials (doctors), a number 
of fellowships are awarded every year for post-graduate training in South Africa and overseas. </p>
<p><a name="BENEFITS "><b>BENEFITS</b></a></p>
<p><b>Training and Career Advancement</b> </p>
<p>Many millions of rands are spent annually on training which is carried out by individual mines, by mining groups at centralised 
training centres, at training colleges and universities. Training in the mining industry is both practical and theoretical and all 
employees are encouraged to develop their full potential in all job categories. Most careers in the minerals industry offer scope 
for career advancement and the development of leadership abilities coupled with responsibility and security. </p>
<p><b>Salaries, Leave and Other Benefits</b> </p>
<p>Salaries and wages in the mining industry compare well with those in other industries and the mining industry offers many 
advantages that other employers would find difficult to match. </p>
<p>All skilled employees get a minimum of 21 calendar days holiday leave a year which can rise substantially depending on 
circumstances. Officials and union men receive a holiday leave allowance and this means a double salary cheque. Sick leave is 
also very generous and can be extended at the discretion of mine management. In general, sick leave benefits are far superior 
to all other sections of commerce and industry. </p>
<p>Mine medical benefit societies provide excellent hospital and medical facilities. Pension and provident fund benefits are 
comprehensive and afford high security for mining industry employees who retire or take early retirement due to ill health or for 
the dependants of deceased employees. </p>
<p><a name="SAFETY"><b>SAFETY</b></a> </p>
<p>The Mine Safety Division of the Chamber of Mines spearheads one of the longest-running mine safety campaigns in the world. 
The campaign aims to establish and maintain a climate and attitude conducive to the elimination of mine accidents. </p>
<p>Safety is the industry's top priority and during the past decade the industry has been rewarded by a sharp fall in casualty rates. </p>
<p>To assist mine managements in improving the implementation of safety measures on mines, the Mine Safety Division operates 
the Mine Safety Management System, which caters for the often unique conditions found in South African mines. The extent to 
which a mine implements this system is assessed regularly and the mine is rated accordingly. </p>
<p>Since deep-level mining on the scale now common in South African gold mines is not practised in other countries, safety 
comparisons with mining elsewhere can be misleading. But our coal mining industry's safety record has compared favourably 
with other countries. </p>
<p>The safety competitions organised by the Mine Safety Division are an effective method of promoting safety consciousness 
because of the competitive spirit they engender. Amongst the most sought after of the safety awards is the &#147;Millionaire Shield&#148; 
which is presented to mines achieving a million consecutive fatality-free man-shifts. </p>
<p>Twenty-two South African gold, coal and other mines that are members of the Chamber of Mines achieved a million 
consecutive fatality-free man-shifts in 1995. One gold mine gained this distinction twice in the year, resulting in a total of 24 
millionaire achievements in the year. </p>
<p><b>ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL AND REHABILITATION</b> </p>
<p>Mining nearly always produces large quantities of was, both from open pit and underground mining operations. Added to this 
is the fact that many minerals processing operations have waste sands and slimes as by-products of the extraction process. </p>
<p>The industry counteracts these negative aspects in several ways. In some mining operations, waste material can be channelled 
back into the earth, which is called `backfilling'. The pollution problems created by wind and rain erosion of mine dumps are 
solved by the Chamber of Mines' vegetation unit which undertakes the planting of grass and other vegetation on these dumps 
and also on slimes dams. The process also improves the appearance of these man-made features! </p>
<p>In the case of open cast mining, before any operation can begin, an environmental inventory must be compiled along with a 
rehabilitation plan - both of which must satisfy the Government Mining Engineer. Some large open pit base metal mines may 
remove up to 350 000 tons of rock per day, of which a large percentage is waste. This process, repeated for many years, 
leaves a large hole in the ground. In some circumstances, open pit mines are filled with fresh water and turned into recreational 
amenities. In all cases, however, large-scale land rehabilitation takes place and it may cost many thousands to rehabilitate one 
hectare of land. </p>
<p>Environmental protection is an integral part of the mining process. Every year, the South African mining industry spends 
millions of rands on environmental control and rehabilitation and researches more efficient ways of ensuring that mining does 
not cause unnecessary environmental degradation. </p>
<p><a name="BURSARIES"><b>BURSARIES</b></a><b> IN THE MINING INDUSTRY</b> </p>
<p><b>The Mining Houses</b> </p>
<p>The mining houses make available generous bursaries and scholarships to employees, matriculants and students. The emphasis 
for bursaries is on the professions which are most essential to the industry : mining engineering, metallurgical engineering, 
chemical engineering, mechanical engineering, electrical engineering and mining geology. </p>
<p>Applications for bursaries should be made direct to the bursary department of the following mining houses : &#160;</p>
<div align=center><center>
<table border=2 width=100%>
