<p align=center><font color="#FF0000"><strong><tt>Please note that only the contents of the Appendix are available<br>
in HTML format. The full file can be downloaded from this page.</tt></strong></font></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wd1.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=31><br>
<img src="../images/linegr.gif" align=bottom width=402 height=5><br>
</p>
<p><a name="MainIntro"><strong>1. INTRODUCTION </strong></a></p>
<p>South Africa is settling down to its acceptance internationally, and to majority government. The withdrawal of the National 
Party from the government of national unity has meant that the country is now a conventional democracy. Greater coherence is 
being seen in policy development as a result. The transformation that has been taking place in all sectors of society is still 
occurring, but at a less frenetic pace. Contrary to the expectations of many, the government has embarked on a reasonably 
business-oriented economic policy, which has seen inflation fall to its lowest levels in many years. However, the high level of 
crime has had a marked impact on economic growth.<br>
</p>
<p>The coal mining industry has continued to grow, buoyed by a strong international steam coal market. The findings of the 
Commission of Inquiry into safety and health in the mining industry, which were released in April 1995, are gradually being 
implemented, though it is too early to assess their effects. A new Mine Health and Safety Act was promulgated in June 1996, 
but it has not been implemented yet. The coal mining and combustion industries are increasingly perceived as dangerous and 
polluting, and have much to do to repair their images.<br>
</p>
<p>The Department of Minerals and Energy (DME) released a Green Paper on energy during the year, and the White Paper is 
expected in shortly. A feature of government's energy policy is that its policy towards the coal industry is unchanged, with the 
industry continuing to operate according to market constraints.<br>
</p>
<p>A matter of great concern is that many government departments, including those relevant to the coal mining and combustion 
industries, have lost, and continue to lose, qualified staff owing to pressure on departments to cut costs, fears related to the 
implementation of affirmative action programmes, and sustained emigration of professionals because of high crime levels.<br>
</p>
<p><a name="MR_D"><b>2. COAL RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT </b></a></p>
<p>As part of the lead up to preparation of this report, and in order to assess the support for a move to better co-ordinate coal 
research being carried out in South Africa, a meeting was held, involving a wide variety of companies and organisations with an 
interest in the matter. Limited initial interest was shown in co-ordinated research, and the necessity for such a meeting will be 
continually evaluated. Owing to the many similarities in the interests of the South African and Australian coal producers, efforts 
have been made during the year to forge links between research organisations in the two countries. Discussions are still at a 
preliminary stage. <br>
</p>
<p>Unlike the conditions prevailing in the country's precious metal mines, many techniques and much equipment developed 
elsewhere can be adapted for use in South African coal mines. The mining industry's R&amp;D thus tends to be focussed on 
adaptation, rather than on development of new equipment. The R&amp;D generally falls into two categories, as follows: </p>
<ul>
<li>A Safety in Mines Research Advisory Committee (SIMRAC) programme, carried out under the aegis of the DME and 
funded by a levy on the mines; this programme concentrates on work aimed at addressing the health and safety issues of 
the industry. </li>
<li>Work which mining houses arrange to have carried out in-house, using external agencies as necessary, as part of their 
own internal programmes of research. </li>
</ul>
<p>A programme of elective, cost-shared research, whereby the Chamber of Mines arranged, on behalf of its mining company 
members, for projects to be undertaken by external agencies has recently come to an end. The mining companies now arrange 
directly for their research needs to be met.<br>
</p>
<p>The government no longer supports coal research directly with funds from the fiscus. It provides funding for the universities for 
the whole spectrum of research, and provides funds to the Council for Scientific and Industrial Research (CSIR) for strategic, 
exploratory R&amp;D, and for capacity building purposes. The DME commissions research on policy issues. Other government 
departments sponsor environmental projects, mainly to do with the rehabilitation of abandoned mine sites where responsibility 
for cleanup cannot be assigned to specific companies.<br>
</p>
<p>The mining industry and the statutory Water Research Commission co-operate through the Co-ordinating Committee for 
Mining-Related Water Research in carrying out several projects of an environmental nature, some of which relate to coal.<br>
</p>
<p>As there is only one major electricity generating utility (small amounts of electricity are generated by some of the larger cities), 
this utility, Eskom is really the only organisation that undertakes large-scale combustion-related research.<br>
</p>
<p>South African coal-related research is summarised on the pages that follow. An appendix describes each research project in 
greater detail, with an indication being given of the potential for collaboration. Owing to the proprietary nature of much of the 
research carried out directly by individual companies, only limited information from such projects has been included within this 
report.<br>
</p>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="MS_H"><b>2.1. Safety and Health</b></a> </p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="ME_f_d">2.1.1 <u>Explosions, fires and dust </u></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>While South African collieries are generally not very gassy, methane explosions do occur infrequently, and are often associated 
with a high loss of life and damage to the mine. A recent analysis identified friction generated by cutting picks as the major 
ignition source in the South African coal mining industry, accounting for 68% of the known causes of ignitions of methane. The 
steady increase in frictional ignitions has followed the introduction of continuous miners in the early 1970s and has more than 
balanced the equally noticeable decrease in the percentage of incidents caused by blasting. Consequently, there have been 
several projects aimed at reducing the methane hazard, and fire and explosion risks. Dust is not only a potential cause of 
explosions, but also a significant health hazard, and methods for improved dust suppression are thus under investigation.<br>
</p>
<p>A short project reviewed methane prediction techniques, and commented on their applicability in South Africa. The conclusion 
was drawn that complex prediction tools are not required under normal conditions in South African collieries. Training 
guidelines are being prepared to enable supervisory and maintenance staff to use electricity more safely underground. More 
than two thirds of methane ignitions are caused by the friction generated by cutting picks in continuous miners, and a project 
aimed at reducing the risk of frictional ignitions made recommendations regarding a training and information kit, a 
machine-mounted active suppression system and the need for an effective wet-head. Another project seeks to improve the 
ventilation of continuous miner headings, which, if successful, will reduce explosion risks and benefit the health of underground 
mine workers. A face ventilation effectiveness system has already been developed. Scrubber designs are being upgraded to 
improve their effectiveness in capturing the dust generated by mechanical miners. A further project is aimed at improved 
methods for ventilation of mined-out areas. A less frequent, though potential, cause of methane explosions is the battery of 
safety cap lamps. A prototype has been designed that is intrinsically safe. A current project is aimed at suppressing explosions 
when they do occur, with encouraging preliminary results. Both a machine-mounted active suppression system, and a 
dispersed barrier system are being designed.<br>
</p>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="MT_m">2.1.2 <u>Transport and machinery</u> </a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Transport and machinery accidents account for a third of all fatalities and injuries on South African coal mines. In order to 
reduce worker exposure to the risk of explosions and rockfalls, a project is aimed at fitting remote control systems to 
continuous mining machines presently in operation. Another project will provide guidelines for the development of training 
manuals for the safe use of high-risk underground machinery.<br>
</p>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="MSupport">2.1.3 <u>Support </u></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Falls of ground are a significant cause of accidents underground, and accounted for over 80% of fatalities there in 1995 (24% 
in 1994). Thus the underlying reasons for unsafe acts or neglect that lead to roof falls or sidewall accidents are under 
investigation, with the intention of developing training programmes and improving communication procedures. The Salamon 
formula for the design of coal pillars has been found to be inadequate when applied to coal seams outside of the original 
geographical range. Collapsed pillars are being investigated with a view to improved pillar design. Another aspect of this 
project concerns the effect of discontinuities on coal pillar strength, so as to allow pillar layouts to take account of 
discontinuities. Different roof support methodologies from South Africa and elsewhere are being reviewed so as to improve the 
safety of roof support, particularly in the face area.<br>
</p>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="MCommcn">2.1.4 <u>Communication </u></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Fatal and other injuries related to an underground explosion are not always the direct result of the explosion, but are also 
caused by disorientation of the initial survivors, particularly if communication and lighting equipment are damaged in the blast, 
and visibility is poor. Several explosion-resistant systems are being designed that should also enhance communication under 
normal operating conditions.<br>
</p>
<p>Paging and expert systems are being used to enable personnel and equipment identification. An emergency speech 
communication system on escape routes is also under investigation. Another project aims at enabling mineworkers to locate 
refuge bays using radio frequency transmitters located in refuge bays and on roadways. Theoretical investigations indicate that 
a single transmitter per section, located in the refuge bay will be sufficient, and experimental work underground has shown that 
propagation of radio waves through a radius of 500 m is possible, with greater distances feasible where there are no 
obstructions. The ability to communicate and log data remotely from equipment sited in hazardous areas is also the subject of a 
research project.<br>
</p>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="MProd"><b>2.2. Productivity</b></a> </p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="MMining">2.2.1 <u>Mining </u></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Explosives are used to break large quantities of coal, especially in opencast mines. The production of fine particles (fines) by 
blasting reduces the yield of usable coal. Two projects are aimed at developing blasting techniques that minimise the quantity of 
fines produced. An empirical model has been developed for the evaluation of the sources of fines and the most sensitive 
parameters in their generation. It is currently being tested in the field. A means of visual evaluation of the effects of changing 
blasting parameters has been used successfully under both laboratory and field conditions. One of the mining companies has, in 
collaboration with a manufacturer, developed an explosive that is less prone to misfiring, although some explosive energy has 
had to be sacrificed. It had earlier been found that a high-strength detonator was ineffective in preventing misfiring.<br>
</p>
<p>Hard intrusions, such as dykes and sandstone, reduce the effectiveness and life span of continuous miners and longwall 
shearers. Projects are in progress to activate the cutters on these machines to enable them to cut through hard coals more 
economically and also through intrusions. A system is being developed to monitor the activity of shuttle cars and continuous 
miners in a production section. A number of trials are being conducted on continuous haulages. <br>
</p>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="MP_m">2.2.2 <u>Processing and metallurgy </u></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Projects are being undertaken in the fields of coal fines recovery, processing and transportation methods, metallurgy and the 
production of chemical feedstocks.<br>
</p>
<p>In addition to the projects described above that are seeking to reduce the production of coal fines, some possibilities are being 
investigated for recovery of the fines that are produced, in order to provide saleable coal and to reprocess the dumps that have 
already accumulated. In one case, a free jet co-current feed aeration mechanism to a flotation process has been implemented 
effectively. A model of the overall process is being developed so that new designs can be optimised and appropriate control 
systems can be developed. Another project aims to settle out coal slurry solids in drying beds, and removing the solids thus 
dewatered as saleable coal.<br>
</p>
<p>The amenability of various coals to separation by jigging is being investigated on a pilot-scale pneumatic jig. Coal softening 
technology has been looked at as a possible means of improving extraction productivity. The uniaxial compression strength of 
coal was reduced by 50 per cent. Research is being conducted into the hydraulic transportation and hoisting of coarse coal 
over long distances. The research is somewhat novel in that coarse, rather than fine, coal is the subject of the investigations, 
and that water is the only transport medium under consideration.<br>
</p>
<p>Coal is used as a char or coke as a reductant and energy source in several metallurgical processes. Owing to a deficiency in 
high-grade coking coals in South Africa, chars are increasingly being used instead. A wide range of Southern African coals 
have been characterised on the basis of their reactivity as chars using thermogravimetric analysis. The reasons for the 
differences in their reactivity are being investigated, with one aim being to form a basis for predicting the reactivity of untested 
material. A related project is concerned with the determination of what properties of a char are responsible for its reactivity in 
the smelting of ferrochrome. One of the country's steel producers has ongoing projects to characterise and evaluate the coking 
and non-coking coals it uses, and to evaluate and optimise the quality of coke it produces.<br>
</p>
<p>The South African chemical industry has no natural sources of aromatic compounds, and thus feedstocks have to be imported. 
It has been found possible to achieve very high conversion rates for the direct liquefaction of a volatile coal from the Northern 
Province of South Africa in the preparation of a stream rich in aromatic feedstocks. Attempts are being made to find backers 
for a feasibility study for a commercial scale plant.<br>
</p>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="MEnergy">2.2.3 <u>Energy </u></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Since coal accounts for more than 90% of South African electricity production, thermal efficiency of coal-fired power stations 
is vital to the national power generation utility, Eskom, and the nation. As part of its ongoing updating of its database of coal 
combustion characteristics, Eskom is seeking to optimise its combustion of coal, and to predict future problems. The database 
now allows the diagnosis of existing combustion-related problems on Eskom's plant, and allows predictions of problems on the 
basis of laboratory tests. Coals from other Southern African countries and elsewhere are now accommodated as well, thus 
enabling correlation with other power utilities. The government Department of Minerals and Energy (DME) funds the 
publication of an annual bulletin which gives certain physical and chemical properties of commercial products from producing 
South African collieries. An ongoing project at the University of the Witwatersrand is characterising Southern African coals in 
order to optimise production, utilisation, storage and environmental protection.<br>
</p>
<p>In order to enhance its coal combustion research, Eskom is developing a pilot-scale combustion research plant. The scope of 
its three-dimensional modelling facility is being expanded in order to enhance the evaluation of coal feedstocks, optimise 
furnace operation and minimise environmental emissions. It is also researching the applicability of fluidised bed combustion and 
coal gasification technology to low-grade South African coals. The DME sponsored a project in which 14 coal-fired industrial 
boilers of various types were tested to ascertain their operating efficiency. It was found that they seldom operate at their 
designed efficiency, and several recommendations were made to improve efficiencies. An Eskom project is concerned with the 
impacts of ash on all aspects of a coal-fired electricity generating facility.<br>
</p>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="MEnvment"><b>2.3 Environment </b></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Environmental impacts from coal-related industries in South Africa are caused by opencast mining pits, subsidence of 
underground workings, combustion of and water drainage from coal and discard heaps, emissions from coal combustion by 
both electricity generation plants and household users, transportation of coal, and the chemicals industry that uses coal as a 
raw material. There are a few projects concerned with reusing discard coals, and a shift towards regarding them as an asset 
for potential future use. Household users of coal account for only 4% of South African coal consumption, but about 20 - 25% 
of particulate emissions. In order to reduce pollution by these small users, the DME has instituted a low-smoke coal 
programme.<br>
</p>
<p>Eskom is using a waste management programme to characterise the source distribution and trace chemicals in its power plants. 
A database and probabilistic distribution model will be developed in order to minimise and manage the environmental impacts 
of the chemical species in airborne, aqueous and solid discharges.<br>
</p>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="MSurface">2.3.1 <u>Surface </u></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Spontaneous combustion of coal and carbonaceous waste affects mining, storage and transportation. Research has been 
carried out using various methods to model the processes occurring in coal heaps in order to improve the design of coal 
stockpiles and dumps, thus minimising environmental impacts and meeting the relevant legal requirements. In one case, the 
research has reached the stage of transferring the developed expertise to industry.<br>
</p>
<p>Water-related environmental research receives a great deal of attention, not least because water is a scarce resource in South 
Africa. A study is being undertaken to examine the feasibility of diverting a river over a backfilled opencast mine. Covers 
constructed from coal discards, clay and topsoil in layers of various thicknesses and with varying gradients are being evaluated 
for used in the rehabilitation of abandoned opencast mines and waste dumps. There are projects concerned with the 
monitoring of groundwater pollution from the leaching of coal stockpiles and ash dams to determine the long-term pollution 
risks of stockpiling and control the discharge of heavy metals into the environment. Leaching has been found to vary markedly 
between the stockpiles at different power stations. The use of a particular natural wetland for assimilating acid mine drainage 
was investigated. It was found that the system was overloaded in terms of volume flow rate and chemical loading, but that the 
implementation of certain changes to the chemical treatment plant upstream would allow the wetland to function well. An 
artificial wetland is being used at an old colliery to ameliorate acid mine drainage with a view to using the system at abandoned 
mines. A passive water treatment system is being designed to remove acids and to use naturally occurring carbon sources to 
reduce sulphates. Significant sulphate reduction has already been observed. An attempt is being made to utilise gypsiferous 
mine water to irrigate croplands. A computer model and small-scale field trials have already been carried out.<br>
</p>
<p>The use of power station fly ash is being investigated as a potential fertiliser for the forestry industry. If successful, it will put a 
source of pollution to good use. An envisaged project is aimed at demonstrating the use of fly ash to backfill both opencast 
and underground mines so as to provide cost-effective, reduced pollution discharge from power stations closely tied to coal 
mines. The pozzolanic (cement-producing) characteristics and rain water infiltration into a particular fly ash dump are being 
investigated in order to better manage ash dams using the dry ash disposal method.<br>
</p>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="MAtmos">2.3.2 <u>Atmosphere </u></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>The burning of coal to generate electricity is responsible for a large proportion of the atmospheric pollutants emitted in South 
Africa. Thus Eskom has several projects under way to monitor the amounts and nature of the gases and solids released, as 
well as to reduce the impacts on the environment that these pollutants cause. Most of Eskom's power stations use electrostatic 
precipitators (ESPs) to filter dust from the flue gases. As a number of the ESPs will need to be upgraded in order to meet 
envisaged future emission requirements, several projects concern this equipment. Furthermore, the use of bag filters as an 
alternative is under investigation.<br>
</p>
<p>As part of its strategic planning initiatives, Eskom has an ongoing programme to monitor the ambient air pollution and its effect 
on air quality at a range of distances from its power stations, and to compare the power stations with other sources of 
pollution. The meteorology around several of the utility's power stations in Mpumalanga province is measured in order to 
model dispersion of emissions. A database for boundary level climatology has been established in conjunction with the Council 
for Scientific and Industrial Research (CSIR). Atmospheric chemical processes, in the context not only of coal-fired electricity 
generation, but also natural processes and biomass burning, are being investigated in the same region in order to model and 
predict environmental impacts, such as acid rain. Computational fluid dynamics is being used to model two-phase flow within 
various fluid streams in order to optimise plant design. A scanning project is aimed at identifying appropriate technologies for 
gaseous detoxification. Thus far, the project has been limited to cost estimation and the examination of various technical issues, 
as legislation does not currently require the technology. Porous acrylic bag filters are being studied in order to develop a 
cost-effective technology to remove 99.99% of particulates and toxic gases from flue gas. A pilot plant has been erected and 
commissioned.<br>
</p>
<p>A small project is concerned with identifying potential technologies to upgrade the existing ESPs. Compact hybrid particulate 
collectors, wet ESP and electrostatically enhanced core separators have been identified as having potential. Another project is 
investigating the optimisation of vibrating (rapping) ESPs in order to remove the collected ash, thus enhancing ESP efficiency. 
It has been found that, if the flow within ESPs is skewed, particulate emissions may be cut significantly. The applicability of this 
concept is currently under investigation.<br>
</p>
<p>Projects concerned with the impact on water supplies of ash dumps were discussed in the preceding section. These dumps are 
also a source of dust pollution, and research is being carried out to evaluate windblown ash models in order to monitor and 
minimise ash dispersion. Initial results are promising.<br>
</p>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="MLSF">2.3.1 <u>Low-Smoke Fuel</u></a> </p>
</blockquote>
<p>The low-smoke coal programme encompasses investigations into overall energy scenarios, development of low-smoke coal, 
and technical and sociological aspects of implementing the programme. The main aim of the programme is to replace smoky 
household coal with suitable low-smoke fuels.<br>
</p>
<p>While indirect apportionment studies have established that the dominant sources of atmospheric particulates in areas where 
household use of coal is high are coal smoke and road dust, a direct, receptor-based study is being carried out over a 
two-year period. The DME is developing an integrated energy decision support model to design a computerised simulation 
package to predict the impacts of any of the variables that affect health risks associated with household coal use. A 
specification for a low-smoke fuel, which describes physical, chemical and performance characteristics and maximum emission 
levels is being drafted. A system to sample particulate and gas emissions from stoves and braziers has been designed, and is 
being used to characterise emissions from potential low-smoke fuels. Studies are being carried out of potential low-smoke coal 
producers and distributors to determine their ability to produce fuel that meets the specification, sustain production in sufficient 
volumes, and distribute the fuel satisfactorily. Established companies have been assessed and businesses without a track 
record are in the process of being assessed. It has been found that the manufacturing capability exists to produce sufficient 
low-smoke coal, but that distribution of the new fuel will be a critical problem. Low-smoke fuels based on other raw materials, 
however, are unlikely to gain more than niche shares of the market. Nine low-smoke fuels were subjected to field tests in 
order to determine their acceptability to consumers. Those fuels that are acceptable, meet safety standards and can be 
manufactured in sufficient quantities and at competitive prices, will be subjected to a macro-scale field test in 1997. <br>
</p>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="MGeol"><b>2.4 Geology </b></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>The statutory Council for Geoscience is carrying out several projects to expand the knowledge of South Africa's coal 
resources and reserves. These projects are concerned with: formulating an internationally acceptable methodology for 
calculating the country's coal resources and reserves, and documenting the peat deposits and unexploited coalfields of 
KwaZulu-Natal province. The Council for Geoscience is also mapping the commercial energy resources, reserves and current 
production of each African country, together with infrastructural information.<br>
</p>
<p><a name="S_H"><b>3. SAFETY AND HEALTH </b></a></p>
<p>One of the results of the Commission of Inquiry into health and safety in the mining industry that completed its work during 
1995 was a new Mine Health and Safety Act, which was promulgated in June 1996. It has not yet come into force, owing to 
bureaucratic delays, capacity deficiencies in the government department charged with implementing it, and some disputed 
provisions that allow for the mine manager to be presumed guilty of negligence in the case of an accident unless he can prove 
otherwise. Regulations under the Act are presently in the process of being drafted.<br>
</p>
<p>Safety statistics for 1994 and 1995 are given in Table 1 below. While there have been increases in the rates of some of the 
individual categories, overall fatality and injury rates have dropped at both surface and underground operations. It must be 
noted however that the fatality rates, in particular, are subject to sharp swings from year to year.<br>
</p>
<p align=center><font color="#008040"><font size=4><em><b>Table 1:</b></em><em> <br>
