<p><font size=1>Sources: Government Mining Engineer and X Prevost, Department of Minerals and Energy<br>
</font></p>
<p><b>4. COAL AND THE ENVIRONMENT</b><font size=4><b> </b></font></p>
<p>The Framework Convention on Climate Change (FCCC), which was signed by South Africa in 1993, has been identified as 
having the potential to impact significantly on the South African coal mining and combustion industries. In line with its concern 
for the country's already limited water resources, and bearing in mind the energy needs of the country's many poor people, it is 
expected that the national government will ratify the Convention in early 1997, as a developing country. The reasons for 
ratifying the FCCC as a developing country are that this will enable South Africa to benefit from the favourable aspects of the 
convention, thus reducing the cost of ratification and providing the country's researchers access to the Global Environmental 
Facility. All stakeholders in the issue, including environmental pressure groups, have agreed that a national process for 
developing a policy on climate change must be commenced as soon as possible. An inventory of greenhouse gases in the 
country has already been compiled and preliminary work on mitigation options has been done. Pledges have been received 
from donor agencies for the determination of mitigation options, and related issues.<br>
</p>
<p>An environmental issue of wider importance locally is the consultative national environmental policy (CONNEP) process, 
which has involved extensive consultations with all stakeholders at national, provincial and sub-provincial levels. A Green 
Paper is in the process of being drafted at the time of writing.<br>
</p>
<p>The coal mining companies are very concerned that the direction of environmental legislation and policy, particularly water 
legislation and policy, could have a major effect on the economics of mining and on the likelihood of the development of new 
mines. This matter is being addressed with the government, but the issue is a very complex one owing to the scarcity of water 
in the country and the rapidly growing population.<br>
</p>
<p><a name="CCT">4.1 <u>Clean Coal Technology</u></a> </p>
<p>Coal will remain South Africa's major source of energy for the foreseeable future. Despite the abundant present capacity, the 
potential to import hydroelectric power from other Southern African countries and the possibility of generating electricity from 
gas, Eskom will have to consider building a new power station early in the 21st century. In the shorter term, coal consumption 
is expected to increase as power stations are operated more efficiently and using new technologies.<br>
</p>
<p>Although South Africa is fortunate to have low sulphur content coals for utility power generation, it is envisaged that future 
coal-fired power stations will be fitted with sulphur dioxide and nitrogen oxide (NO<sub>x</sub>) controlling technologies. Further to the 
ratification by South Africa of the FCCC, will be the responsibility of investigating mitigation options for greenhouse gases 
which, for South Africa specifically, has to include potential clean coal technologies. New technologies, such as pressurised 
fluidised bed combustion (PFBC), integrated gasification combined cycle (IGCC) and coal fired gas turbines (CFGTs), are 
under development worldwide, which have the potential both to reduce atmospheric emissions significantly and increase 
thermal efficiencies. Government's involvement is to the extent of monitoring, evaluation/ demonstration and facilitation, where 
applicable, as these and other technologies become known and determining the potential impact they might have on energy 
policy for the country. <br>
</p>
<p>Eskom's coal research programme has been focussing on minimising the environmental impact of its present pulverised fuel 
combustion technology by optimising the combustion process and quantifying the gaseous and particulate pollutants. Research 
priority is now being given to the modelling of nitrogen oxide formation during combustion so as to understand and influence 
the formation of this pollutant. The quantification of trace elements emitted from Eskom plant has also been initiated, as part of 
a joint development with the Electric Power Research Institute in the USA. These programmes are complemented by studies 
into the feasibility and cost of plant that can remove gaseous pollutants such as SO<sub>2</sub> and NO<sub>x</sub>.<br>
</p>
<p>Newer and inherently cleaner power generating technologies are also being researched as part of a desktop study at present, 
but laboratory work will commence during 1997 to research the suitability of low-grade South African coals for fluidised bed 
combustion and coal gasification. The focus of the fluidised bed combustion research will be on assessing the fundamental 
reactivity of South African coal, limestone and dolomite resources with the latest power generating options this technology 
offers. A similar approach will be adopted with the gasification research. Research partners are being sought nationally and 
internationally.<br>
</p>
<p>A further clean coal technology initiative involves the electrification of South Africa's urban communities, so as to provide them 
with an alternative to coal as a primary energy source. The use of electricity in these communities will reduce low-level gaseous 
and particulate emissions, which pose a serious health risk. It must be noted however that the use of low-smoke fuels will 
result in the production of greater quantities of carbon dioxide as a result of the energy required to manufacture them. <br>
</p>
<p>In order to quantify rain quality trends, it is necessary to assume that increases in emissions from Mpumalanga province are not 
offset by decreases in Gauteng province, an extremely conservative assumption given that rainfall is a regional phenomenon. 
Studies to date reveal that full electrification will result in small increases in hydrogen ion concentrations. However the changes 
in pH will only be seen in the second decimal place.<br>
</p>
<p>In classifying local impacts of electrification, indoor air quality is of vital importance, especially if its significance for human 
health is considered. Results obtained thus far indicate that children living in partially electrified areas had a 130% higher risk of 
developing respiratory infection than those living in completely electrified areas, while children living in non-electrified areas had 
a 190% higher risk of developing respiratory infection compared to the same age group in electrified areas.<br>
</p>
<p>The net emission reduction for full electrification calculated by the year 1998 will be in the order of 1.5 Mt of carbon dioxide, 
14 kt of sulphur dioxide and 250 kt of particulates. Thus it can readily be concluded that electrification will result in net 
reductions of total emissions and in addition will substantially improve the quality of life of many individuals. It should be noted 
that partial electrification is not expected to have a substantial effect on emissions.<br>
</p>
<p><a name="CEcon"><b>5. COAL ECONOMICS</b></a> </p>
<p>Coal production continued to increase during 1995, being buoyed by strong growth in international demand for steam coal. 
Saleable coal production amounted to 206.2 Mt, an increase of 5% over 1994, while run of mine production was 258.7 Mt, 
an increase of 6%.<a name="_Ref366472180"> </a>Domestic consumption increased by 5%, and exports by 9% (see Table 2 below). South Africa is the 
world's fourth largest hard coal producer.1 More than half of the country's domestic coal production is consumed by Eskom, 
the national electricity generating utility, which sold more than 160 TWh during 1995, about 92% of which was generated from 
coal.2 Most of the rest of the locally consumed coal was used by Sasol in the production of liquid fuels, plastics and other 
chemicals. South Africa is poorly endowed with high-quality coals, and a certain amount of beneficiation is required to 
produce them. Of exported coal, 54% went to Europe, and 35% to the Far East. More than 96% of exports were through 
Richards Bay Coal Terminal. Coal continues to be produced in almost equal quantities by underground (51%) and opencast 
(49%) mining.1<br>
</p>
<p>The stabilisation in the coal mining producer price index that was reported last year has unfortunately not been sustained. It 
increased by 22% between July 1995 and June 1996, compared with a 7% increase in the overall producer price index. 
However, productivity in terms of tons of coal produced per employee has continued to increase, though the industry still lags 
far behind its major competitors, the USA and Australia.4 The rise in production has led to a slight increase in employment 
levels, by 2% to 59&#160;000 in 1995.<font size=2><br>
</font></p>
<p align=center><font color="#008040"><font size=4><b><i>Table 2:</i></b><i> <br>
</i></font><font size=3><strong><u>Domestic coal sales by sector and exports (million tons)</u></strong></font><font size=4><strong><u> </u></strong></font></font></p>
<div align=center><center>
<table border=1>
<tr><td width=216><strong>Sector</strong></td><td align=center width=79><strong>1991 </strong></td><td align=center width=79><strong>1992</strong></td><td align=center width=79><strong>1993 </strong></td><td align=center width=79><strong>1994</strong></td><td align=center width=79><strong>1995 </strong></td></tr>
<tr><td width=216><strong>Exports</strong></td><td align=right width=79>49.3</td><td align=right width=79>50.3 </td><td align=right width=79>53.5</td><td align=right width=79>55.5</td><td align=right width=79>60.3 </td></tr>
<tr><td width=216><strong>Electricity</strong></td><td align=right width=79>71.3</td><td align=right width=79>67.8 </td><td align=right width=79>73.6</td><td align=right width=79>76.9</td><td align=right width=79>82.6 </td></tr>
<tr><td width=216><strong>Industry (including Sasol)</strong></td><td align=right width=79>45.2 </td><td align=right width=79>44.6</td><td align=right width=79>45.8</td><td align=right width=79>46.9 </td><td align=right width=79>49.2</td></tr>
<tr><td width=216><strong>Metallurgy</strong></td><td align=right width=79>8.3</td><td align=right width=79>7.1 </td><td align=right width=79>7.1</td><td align=right width=79>7.4</td><td align=right width=79>7.4 </td></tr>
