<tr><td width=216><strong>TOTAL</strong></td><td align=right width=79><strong>181.6</strong></td><td align=right width=79><strong>176.8 </strong></td><td align=right width=79><strong>185.4</strong></td><td align=right width=79><strong>194.3</strong></td><td align=right width=79><strong>206.3 </strong></td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<blockquote>
<p><font size=1>Sources: X Prevost, Minerals Bureau, Department of Minerals and Energy and South African Coal Report<br>
</font><font size=2><i>Note: </i>Differences between figures for saleable coal production and coal sales are due to the sale of coal from stockpiles and 
imports.<br>
</font></p>
</blockquote>
<p><a name="Concl"><b>6. CONCLUSION </b></a></p>
<p>South African coal research and development continues to cover a wide spectrum of interests, from mining, to processing and 
metallurgy, to combustion and other types of coal burning. It is hoped that, in next year's report, details can be given of the 
oil-from-coal industry. The extensive R&amp;D that is reported here has been carried out despite relatively limited funding and the 
loss of much expertise in recent years. The reader's attention is directed to the appendix for further detail regarding each 
project, and particularly the potential for collaboration. <br>
</p>
<p>Coal will remain the country's primary energy source for many years to come. However, the mining and utilisation industries 
are facing an ever stricter regulatory framework as pressures mount for greater protection of safety and health and the 
environment. Already these two issues dominate the research being carried out nationally. As pressure to reduce research 
funds mounts, there is likely to be an increasing need to explore the possibility of co-operative research both intra- and 
internationally. In such a scenario, the need for bodies such as the ICCR is very apparent. <br>
<br>
</p>
<p>10 September, 1996</p>
<hr noshade width=80%>
