<HEAD>
<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Rescue Drilling Unit for South African Collieries</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF TEXT=#0000A0 LINK=#006030 VLINK=#FF8040 ALINK=#C0C0C0>
<center><b><h1><b>Chamber of Mines of South Africa </b></h1></b><p>
<IMG SRC="/images/LOGO1.gif"><p>

<FONT SIZE=4 COLOR=800080><B>ADVANCED RESCUE DRILLING UNIT<br>
FOR SOUTH AFRICAN COLLIERIES</B></FONT><P>

<I><B>20 February 1996</B></I><p>

<IMG SRC="/images/line3.gif"><p>

<FONT SIZE=4 COLOR=008000><B>CONTENTS</B></FONT></center>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<ul>
<B><li><A HREF="#intro">INTRODUCTION</A>
<li><A HREF="#geology">GEOLOGY OF SOUTH AFRICAN COALFIELDS</A>
<li><A HREF="#rescue">RESCUE DRILLING IN THE PERIOD 1967 - I977</A>
<li><A HREF="#present">THE PRESENT RESCUE DRILLING UNIT</A>
<ul>
<li><A HREF="#equipment">Equipment for rescue hole drilling</A>
<li><A HREF="#probe">Probe hole drilling</A>
<li><A HREF="#ancillary">Ancillary equipment</A>
</ul>
<li><A HREF="#management">MANAGEMENT AND OPERATION OF THE RESCUE DRILLING UNIT</A>
<ul>
<li><A HREF="#location">Location</A>
<li><A HREF="#unit">Management of the unit</A>
<li><A HREF="#training">Training</A>
</ul>

<li><A HREF="#operation">RESCUE OPERATION</A>

<li><A HREF="#innovations">INNOVATIONS</A>
<ul>
<li><A HREF="#overburden">Overburden drilling</A>
<li><A HREF="#removal">Removal of drill cuttings from hole collar</A>
<li><A HREF="#flexible">Flexible casings</A></B>
</ul>
</ul></BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
<Center><IMG SRC="/images/line3.gif"><p></Center><br><p>

<A NAME="intro"></A>
<B>INTRODUCTION</B><br>
In 1960 South Africa suffered the tragedy of the Coalbrook disaster when a large section of a handgot mine near Sasolburg in the Free State collapsed, leading to the loss of more than 400 lives. No machine capable of drilling holes large enough through which to rescue people was available anywhere in the country. Following this incident, and particularly after the successful rescue at Lengede in Germany, the Chamber of Mines decided to purchase a suitable drill which would make it possible to reach men trapped underground in South African coal mines.<p>

<A name="geology"></A>
<B>GEOLOGY OF SOUTH AFRICAN COALFIELDS</B><br>
The economic coal seams are contained at depths ranging from a few to about 300 metres in the largely horizontal Ecca Series of the Karoo Geological System, which consist mainly of reasonably soft sandstone, shale and mudstone. Intruded in these coal measures and overlying most South African collieries, are dolerite sills of varying thickness from a few to more than a hundred metres. The dolerite intrusions are related to the outpouring of the Drakensberg volcanics and belong to the gabbro family. The characteristic Karoo dolerite generally consists of a dark medium-grained rock made up of augite and plagioclase-felspar. Olivine is often present or the rock may occasionally be more acid resulting in quartz dolerites.<p>

The following ranges of uniaxial compressive strengths have been recorded for South African coal measures:<br>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=2 CELLSPACING=2>
<TR><TD>Sandstone</TD><TD>48-100MPa</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Shale</TD><TD>70-80Mpa</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Dolerite	</TD><TD>250-390Mpa</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
	
<p>	
<A NAME="rescue"></A>
<B>RESCUE DRILLING IN THE PERIOD 1967 - 1977</B><br>
In 1967, after a worldwide investigation of the available mobile drilling equipment, the Chamber of Mines bought a Wirth L10 drill rig similar to the Wirth L4 in use by the National Coal Board at the time. It was a conventional rotary drill, equipped to drill small diameter holes by air-flush methods and large diameter holes by reverse flush water circulation.<p>

The drill was able to penetrate ordinary coal measures at speeds of some 3 - 4 metres per hour with a large diameter bit, but as soon as dolerite was encountered, penetration rates dropped to less than 0,15 roeires per hour. Modifications to increase these penetration rates had limited success.<p>

The equipment was put into the hands of a commercial drilling company who used the drill, under constraints, for its own contracting work. In this way a trained crew was always available and the equipment kept in operating condition. The company, however, experienced serious :problems, one of which was that it fell on hard times and management was changed some four times in 2½ years. The drilling unit and its ancillary equipment quickly fell into poor condition and disrepair.<p>

<A NAME="present"></A>
<B>THE PRESENT RESCUE DRILLING UNIT</B><p>

<A NAME="equipment"></A>
<B>Equipment for Rescue Hole Drilling</B><br>
Large diameter downhole percussion drills were being developed during the early seventies. Ingersoll-Rand downhole machines were used in piling for the foundations associated with the Alaska pipe:2ne, albeit to relatively shallow depths.<p>

<i>DHD-124. downhole drill</i><br>
On the recommendation of Ingersoll-Rand of the United States, the Chamber of Mines in 1977, purchased their DHD-124 downhole drill on a T-5 Drillmaster mounting, which was capable of drilling a 635 mm (25") or 560 mm (22") hole through which trapped men could be raised. A DHD-130 drill was also purchased for drilling a 760 mm (30") hole, through the overburden so that casings could be installed in the unstable top section of the hole, but it has since been discarded in favour of a borer-type bit. which achieves far higher rates of overburden penetration.<p>

From actual operations it has been established that the DHD-124 drill can penetrate normal coal measures at rates of up to 10 metres per hour and dolerite at up to 3,7 metres per hour, which are far geater than penetration rates achieved by rotary means.<p>

<i>DXL-5000S whisperised compressor</i><br>
The main power-pack is a Spiro-Flo DXL-5000S whisperised mobile compressor capable of delivery 2,4 m3/s of air at 85C kPa (5 000 cfm at 125 psi). The unit consists of two 1,2 m3/s skid-mounted modules connected by a common air discharge manifold. Each module contains an air-end with its own 495 kW, 16 cylinder Detroit diesel engine, receiver, separator, coolers and accessories, and may be run separately. They are housed in a specially constructed acoustic enclosure, mounted on a 12 m long trailer, 3,8 m high and 2,5 m wide.<p>

The T-5 Drillmaster has its own built-in power-pack consisting of a 270 kW, 12 cylinder Detroit diesel engine and compressor capable of delivering a further 0,42 m3/s of air at 1 700 kPa (900 cfrn at 250 psi).<p>

<i>Drill rods</i><br>
The unit is equipped with sufficient drill rods, each 9,1 m (30") long, to reach the deepest present workings of some 270 m. Each rod has a mass of 1,6 tons and diameter of 508 mm (20"). The large diameter of the rods allows for the drill cuttings to be removed from the hole by air-flushing.<p>

Sufficient rod trailers are available to carry the rods.<p>

<i>Mobile crane</i><br>
In order to handle the drill rods of mass 1,6 tons each and the downhole hammer and bit of mass 4 tons, as well as numerous other heavy items, a 15 ton mobile crane with a 15 m collapsible boom forms an integral part of the Rescue Drilling Unit.<p>

<i>Rescue capsule</i><br>
A rescue capsule, known as the Dalbusch Bomb, with 430 mm outside diameter is used to raise trapped men from underground. A parachute-type harness is also available for raising men in situations where the capsule cannot be used, e.g. in very- low seams.<p>

<A NAME="probe"></A>
<b>Probe Hole Drilling</b><br>
Rescue hole drilling is a comparatively slow process and the Chamber of Mines Rescue Drilling Unit was therefore supplemented by a DHD-260 downhole percussion drill on a T--4 Drillmaster mounting, capable of drilling a 165 mm (6V2") diameter hole at rates of 35 - 50 m/hr in soft strata and 10m/hr in dolerite. It is a very mobile, self-contained unit which can get underway quickly, carries 80 metres of rods with it, travels at speeds of up to 80 km/h and sets up in half an hour.<p>

The L4 will drill probe holes to search and locate trapped miners and provide them with air, food, communication and other essential services to sustain them while the rescue hole is being drilled.<p>

The T-5 Drillmaster is also equipped for small diameter probe hole drilling if required. It takes about 3 1/2 to 4 hours to change the machine over from large hole to small hole mode and vice versa.<p>

<A NAME="ancillary"></A>
<B>Ancillary Equipment</B><p>
<I>
Workshop trailer</I><br>
A semi-trailer is rigged out and equipped as a workshop trailer, on which are carried spare parts, tools, welding and cutting equipment and power plant. A section is designed as sleeping quarters and also contains a small refrigerator and cooking equipment for the crew.<p>

The trailer is also equipped with an electric winch fitted with an inverter drive for speed control, to raise and lower the rescue capsule.<p>

<I>Underground surveillance probe</I>
A surveillance probe, fitted with a low-light video camera and on-board lighting as well as a two-way audio communication system, designed to search for and establish contact with survivors trapped underground, forms part of the Rescue Drilling Unit equipment. The unit, which can be lowered down a 150 mm hole. is housed in a mobile caravan. All its functions are operated from a control desk in the caravan. Once the probe is lowered to the required depth, the lower section can be rotated and the lens tilted to scan for personnel up to a distance of 60 m. The audio system, which incorporates a sound signalling device, is sensitive and will pick up sounds 30 m and more away.

<I>Surface communication</I><br>
The Rescue Drilling Unit has long range radio equipment for communicating between the drill site, the base station and Rescue Training Services. Where a network is available, use is made of cellular telephones.<p>

<I>Gas sampling equipment</I><br>
The Unit has equipment to sample the atmosphere in that part of the workings which was drilled into. It is used in conjunction with the Mobile Gas Laboratory (MOGAL) unit of the Collieries Environmental Control Service, which will be summoned to the site. It consists of a bundle of tubes and a sampling head which can be lowered down the probe hole and then coupled to a vacuum pump on surface for taking samples. The samples will be processed and analysed immediately.<p>

<I>Mats for traversing unstable ground</I><br>
During rainy seasons some areas around collieries may become marshy and difficult to traverse with heavy vehicles. The Rescue Drilling Unit acquired 120 metres of heavy-duty epoxy Mo-Mat Panels (15 m lengths) from the United States where it is used by the defence force to traverse beachheads and unstable ground. If soft underfoot conditions are experienced, the panels will be used in leap-frog fashion to reach the drilling site.<p>

<A NAME="management"></A>
<B>MANAGEMENT AND OPERATION OF THE RESCUE DRILLING UNIT
</B><p>

<A NAME="location"></A>
<B>Location</B><br>
The Unit is housed in fire-station fashion in Witbank which is reasonably central to the coalfields, from where it can reach the nearest colliery in less than half an hour and the furthest, some 400 km away, in about 10 hours.<p>

<A NAME="unit"></A>
<B>Management of the Unit</B><br>
The Chamber of Mines has a Collieries: Training College for trainee miners and apprentice artisans in Witbank, which is staffed with mining men, training officers and supervisors with engineering backgrounds and sound knowledge of diesel and hydraulic equipment. The Rescue Drilling Unit was placed under the supervision of the College management as an additional responsibility.<p>

The staff of the College have been trained to operate and maintain the equipment. A core of permanent personnel consisting of the Rescue Drill Supervisor and 6 Operators, was established. The operators are housed on site and informal standby arrangements are maintained over week-ends. Half of the operators are used for general maintenance work at the training centre during normal working hours.<p>

The full-time operating personnel are responsible for the planned maintenance of the equipment.<p>

<A NAME="training"></A>
<B>Training</B><br>

<I>Rescue drilling procedure document</I><br>
A Rescue Drilling Procedure Document, setting out the immediate action that should be taken by various functionaries such as the Mine Manager, the Group Head Office, the Colliery Training College Manager, etc, is circulated to all collieries who are members of the Rescue Drilling Unit. The document also contains a list of telephone numbers of all those persons and organisations who are, or may be involved with the rescue drill or with rescue operations.<p>

This document is updated and recirculated at 6 monthly intervals to ensure that the necessary communications are maintained.<p>

<I>Drilling exercises</I><br>
At least one practice hole is drilled annually to test the equipment and to hone the skills of the operators. These exercises are carried out under simulated emergency conditions, that is, personnel are not pre-warned and call-outs are done at all hours to keep personnel on the alert. Times are recorded through-out the operation in order to improve call-out times and operational efficiencies.<p>
	
Performance criteria established during training<p>
<Center><TABLE border=1 CELLPADDING=3 CELLSPACING=3>
<TR><TD ALIGN=center></TD><TD ALIGN=center><B>T-4 DRILLMASTER<br>(DHD-260)</B></TD><TD ALIGN=center><B>T-5 DRILLMASTER<br>(DHD-124)</B></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=left><B>Penetration Rates</B><br>
Coal measures<br>
Dolerite
</TD>
<TD ALIGN=center>40m/h <br> 10m/h</TD>
<TD ALIGN=center>10m/h <br> 3,7m/h</TD></TR>


<TR><TD ALIGN=left><B>Call-out Time</B><br>
Normal working hours<br>
After hours
</TD>
<TD ALIGN=center>15 min <br> 25 min</TD><TD ALIGN=center>25 min <br>40-60 min</TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=left><B>Travelling Time</B><br>
Nearest colliery (15km)<br> 
Furthest colliery (400km)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN=center>20 min <br>7-8 hrs</TD><TD ALIGN=center>30 min <br> 10-12 hrs</TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=left><B>Setting-up Time</B></TD>
<TD ALIGN=center>½ hr</TD><TD ALIGN=center>1½-2½ hrs</TD></TR>
</TABLE></Center><p><br>

		<A NAME="operation"></A>
<B>RESCUE OPERATION</B><br>
The Rescue Drilling Unit has only once been called upon to rescue persons from underground when 26 miners were trapped 65 m below surface by a major collapse of ground at the Emaswati Colliery in neighbouring Swaziland The collapse, which completely blocked their access, took place at approximately 10:00 on Saturday 9 June 1991. The trapped miners fortunately had access to a safe refuge bay underground. The Unit was alerted and put on standbv at 11:00. It left Witbank at 14: 15, having had to wait for confirmation and international border clearance.<p>

The Unit arrived at Emaswati at 01:45 after a 310 km arduous journey, much of which was in thick mist and rain. The rescue drilling operation proceeded without a hitch and by 12:55 the rescue hole had been completed and the rods, hammer and bit withdrawn for rescue to commence.<p>

Four proto men were lowered to make the area around the base of the rescue hole safe and to assist the miners into the rescue capsule. The 26 miners and four proto members were all brought to safety by 17:10 on Sunday afternoon 10 June 1991, 30 hours 10 minutes after the Unit had first been alerted.<p>

<A NAME="innovations"></A>
<B>INNOVATIONS</B><p>
<A NAME="overburden"></A>
<B>Overburden Drilling</B><br>
A DHD-130 drill and 760 mm (30") diameter bit of total mass 6 tons and special starter rods were part of the original equipment purchased for the purpose of drilling the soft overburden. When soft clay-type overburden was encountered penetration rates fell to as little as 7 m per hour.<p>

The Rescue Drill Supervisor designed a simple borer-type bit by mounting continuous-miner pick-boxes with picks on a flat steel plate in a spiral design and attached this to a cylinder which screws on to an ordinary 508 mm rod. This "drag" bit, as it was named. with mass 250 kg is now used and achieves penetration rates of up to 35 m per hour.<p>

<A NAME="removal"></A>
<B>Removal of Drill Cuttings from Hole Collar</B><br>
A "blooie" device for the removing (blowing away) of cuttings from the hole collar and drill area, which was very cumbersome and took about 4 hours to install between hole collar and footplate of the machine, was incorporated in the original equipment.<p>

This was subsequently replaced by a simplified design, consisting of a pneumatic groundseal mounted at the bottom of a short metal cylinder of sufficient diameter to allow passage of the overburdened drill. The cylinder has a short discharge pipe welded on to it and to which a longer discharge pipe can be fitted for discharging the drill cuttings away from the machine. This part of the "blooie" device is carried on the chassis of the machine below the drilling platform and is hydraulically lowered and pressed to the ground, which is first levelled, to provide an adequate seal.<p>

A pneumatic rod seal, which forms the other part of the device is also attached to a short section of metal cylinder of the same diameter as on the ground seal. The internal diameter of the ground seal snugly accommodates the rod and hammer which has the same diameter, i.e. 508 ram. The rod seal is fitted over the hammer or overburden drill before it is lowered in the hole. Before drilling commences the rod seal is attached to the cylinder of the ground seal by way of a multiple bayonet-type clip-on mechanism and both seals are inflated to provide a seal around the rod and to the ground.<p>

This modified blooie device takes about half an hour to install and together with the improved overburden drilling equipment have resulted in reducing the time it takes from arrival on site to commencement of hardrock drilling from approximately 10 hours to less than 2 hours.<p>

<A NAME="flexible"></A>
<B>Flexible Casings</B><br>
The need for lining a large diameter hole during rescue drilling operations will probably only arise if such large quantities of water is encountered, which the machine cannot handle, or which may pose a danger to men trapped in a confined space. It would then be possible to case and grout the 635 mm hole to seal off the water and continue the drilling operation with the 560 mm bit. Experiments to install rigid casings with large enough inside diameter to allow this were unsuccessful at depths of 30 - 40 m because of the small tolerances and unevenness of the borehole sides.<p>

In order to make a 10 m length of casing flexible, joints are cut in a self-centring dovetail-like pattern at 1 m intervals with a cutting torch. The dovetail joints keep the casing intact and are sealed with vulcanised rubber. The ends of the casings are cut to an exact saw-tooth pattern and covered with vulcanised rubber. Casings are then lowered down the hole one at a ,5me with a special device and the hole cased from the bottom up. The saw-tooth joints are self-centring and the vulcanised rubber provides a good enough seal for grouting.<p>

Casings of 600 mm outside diameter and 588 mm inside diameter were lowered and raised with ease down several holes.<p>
<p>
