</blockquote>
</blockquote>
</blockquote>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p align=left><a name="INTRODUCTION"><font size=4><strong><u>INTRODUCTION</u></strong></font></a><u><br>
</u>Two years ago, at the bottom end of the African continent, a dramatic re-birth took place. South 
Africa, a country whose political leanings had for decades earned it &quot;most despised nation&quot; 
status, emerged from its self-inflicted, apartheid night into a world prepared to accept it once 
more. Archbishop Desmond Tutu appropriately and affectionately dubbed our re-born country 
as the &quot;rainbow nation&quot;.<br>
<br>
The rainbow symbol, as we know, has long been used by pragmatists and dreamers alike as a 
symbol of promise for the future, yet realists - unblinded by the brilliance of the rainbow - 
know that change is necessary for a bright future. In the euphoria surrounding South Africa&#146;s 
re-emergence sight was lost of the fact that as powerful an influence political change may be, 
there are other changes, perhaps even more potent, that have to be brought about to make the 
anticipated bright future work.<br>
<br>
In South Africa, the need for change was seen, fortunately, as fundamental to prosperity. The 
imbalances of the past were not only political, they permeated the very fabric of society: from 
where one was allowed to live, to land ownership rights, to work practices and so forth. And it 
is essential that this distinction be made clear because April 1994 - the date of South Africa&#146;s 
official transition to full democratic rule - does not mark the beginning of change but rather the 
culmination of a nation&#146;s desire to become something very different from what it was before 
and to build upon that departure point. <br>
<br>
Integral to the South African melting pot is a powerful and mature mining industry that itself had 
to cope with pressures of its own. Apart from political imperatives which it knew it would 
have to deal with once a new government came into power, it had been fighting the battle of 
change for itself since the early 1980&#146;s. New ore reserves of any significance had not been 
identified; costs were spiralling out of control; pay limits (particularly in the gold mining 
sector) were ever decreasing; unions were becoming increasingly organised, political, 
demanding and strong; while productivity slumped. &quot;An industry in decline&quot; became a 
catch-phrase in some quarters &#133;&#133;. <br>
<br>
<a name="ENVIRONMENTAL"><font size=4><strong><u>ENVIRONMENTAL</u></strong></font></a><font size=4><strong><u> CHANGES<br>
</u></strong></font>With a new government came a desire to right wrongs. Fortunately the government had been 
quick to reverse its earlier avowed intention of nationalising virtually every major enterprise in 
the country, mining included. However, there was soon a flurry of activity designed to redress a 
whole host of legislation, the result of which was critical examination of issues as diverse as 
mining and minerals policy, health and safety, conditions of employment, industrial relations, 
training and education, and very soon the debate centred on the provision of electricity, water 
rights and the supply of water in a water-poor nation, and the environment. And in 1996 we saw 
the birth of a macro economic model better known as GEAR (Growth, Employment And 
Redistribution plan) which we are confident will bring about the needed six per cent economic 
growth rate per annum if properly implemented.<br>
<br>
At the same time, the mining industry was itself examining ways to - amongst others - cut its 
costs, improve pay limits, up its production, and increase productivity. The whole environment 
in which we had to operate went from one where change was necessary for day-to-day 
survival, to one where change was also thrust upon it from outside of its sphere of influence - 
including the international world of business.<br>
<br>
To cope with these changes and to prevent further declines in the mining sector and to optimise 
on our existing resources, we actively and simultaneously embarked on four major activities.<br>
<br>
<u>Organisational development</u> led us to examine our existing hierarchical structures and we found 
that many of the accusations levelled at us by the unions were well-founded and as a result 
hierarchical levels were reduced from 27 to six. Closed shop agreements were cancelled, 
multi-skilling was introduced, supervisory areas were reduced and teamwork became the name 
of the game!<br>
<br>
The mining industry was in the forefront of eliminating racial inequalities in the workplace by 
having the so-called &quot;scheduled persons&quot; restriction removed from the Mines and Works Act. 
In the simplest terms being &quot;scheduled&quot; meant a person was prevented from holding a blasting 
certificate or a diploma in an engineering discipline, such as electrician, fitter, plater, plumber, 
etc., simply on the basis of skin tone. Since the elimination of this restriction at the end of 1988, 
about 2750 previously scheduled persons have received blasting certificates. In 1995 of the 
610 employees who qualified, the split between races was virtually 50/50 (48,9% non-whites). 
Of course, under the new political dispensation this is no longer an issue of real importance but 
it does emphasise my earlier contention that change - even as far as what was then a sensitive 
issue - had been implemented at the instigation of our industry prior to - in fact about five years 
prior to - the much more publicised political transformation.<br>
<br>
Our <u>support services</u>, a field where we were sure we had everything under control, were also 
put under the microscope. Rationalisation plans were not long in coming forth as a result. For 
example, the age-old separation of the disciplines of engineering and mining has in many cases 
been thrown out the window and has proved to be surprisingly successful. On the gold mining 
side, pay limits have improved, in some cases up to 30 per cent, and face advances have 
improved, even to as high as 150 per cent, with 100 per cent the more general trend. Rivalry 
between the disciplines has been replaced with co-operation. The spin-off has been that costs 
have dropped 30 per cent on project mines, life of mine years on one project mine have 
improved by 50 per cent, while production teams are receiving bonuses at the rate of 100 per 
cent of basic salary with the average standing at 70 per cent. As far as coal is concerned the 
improvements are perhaps even more marked. For instance, on one mine where a pilot project 
has been introduced productivity has leapt from 416 tons per man to 784 and is on track to 
reach a projected target of 915. This has been achieved with a workforce reduced from 231 to 
143 - about 40 per cent - with a cost reduction from about 35 Rand (less than eight US dollars) 
per ton down to 16 (or less than four US dollars), and an overall improvement in production of 
nearly 17 per cent (<em>96000 vs 112200 tons</em>).<br>
<br>
Our employees have not been neglected either as the following illustrate. In the field of <u>human 
resources development</u> great advances have been made in the field of Adult Basic Education 
and Training (ABET), so much so that some employees who until a few years or so ago were 
illiterate and innumerate have already advanced to positions of seniority. Specialisations are 
being eliminated and employees are being armed now with an arsenal of skills which has had 
the value-added benefits of not only widening an individual&#146;s skill&#146;s base, but also of allowing 
the workforce to be rationalised without there being a drop in productivity. Multi-tasking and 
multi-skilling are being introduced as a means of deflating unacceptable working costs, of 
which more than 50 per cent were attributable to the cost of labour on gold mines and 30 to 35 
per cent on coal.<br>
<br>
Perhaps the most important - though most intangible - of the four steps embarked upon was the 
<u>improvement of the quality of life</u> of the workforce. I would hazard a guess that most of you 
attending this presentation have not had to look after the social and basic needs of large 
numbers of workers housed in communal settlements, what we on the mines call &quot;hostels&quot;. The 
whole hostel system is being re-examined right now and I know there is going to be a drastic 
shake-up here in the not too distant future as well.<br>
<br>
The government&#146;s RDP (Reconstruction and Development Plan) has in some instances outside 
of the mining industry not met with the success one would have hoped. Yet, it is alive and well 
and thriving in the mining sector. ABET is a case in point, training of existing workers, the 
re-training of laid-off workers, the construction of rural clinic buildings, upgrading of schools 
and teachers and the provision of running water to households to mention but a few.<br>
<br>
The age-old management versus worker - the &quot;us-and-them&quot; scenario - is also fast becoming a 
thing of the past. While no one disputes the need for a management structure the creation of a 
commonality of interest was seen as imperative if the industry was to march instead of crawl 
into the next century. The traditional &quot;disciplinary hearing&quot; - while still having its place - has 
largely been replaced by some companies by pre-emptive &quot;Fair Treatment Committees&quot; where 
grievances, perceived or real, may be aired. In so doing, cases which in the past would have 
led to wild-cat strikes and their usual accompanying violent behaviour have been amicably 
resolved. Remember that we had a situation on our mines where 90 per cent of skilled and 
supervisory people were white - with far right conservative beliefs - and 90 per cent of the 
workers were far left radicals and yet we expected them to be able to work together! Sharing of 
information and closer communication through all levels is being actively pursued and has 
proved to be very successful indeed.<br>
<br>
In co-operation with employee representatives management is intent on securing the abolition of 
old-fashioned and ludicrous regulations which prohibit the industry from working on Sundays. 
Combined with an excessive number of public holidays (a total of 12), an 11-shift fortnight and 
the inevitable down-time in closing and starting up a mine, a total of some 90 days (three 
months), or a quarter of the working year, are lost to the industry.<br>
<br>
What I am saying here in essence is that with every change in our industry, growth has not been 
far behind. Growth in the sense that while the industry is mature it is not in decline. Growth in 
the sense that we are ready to face the future with confidence in our skills, abilities and vision, 
and more importantly, with confidence in our people as we are unlocking a source of skills, 
knowledge and experience that we had not before recognised.<br>
<br>
For more than a century the mining industry has been the primary catalyst for economic growth 
and development in South Africa. It has every intention of ensuring that it not only maintains - 
but also increases - its capacity to create wealth and provide jobs in the new democratic 
society that is today&#146;s South Africa, rainbow nation of mineral wealth. <br>
<br>
On the other hand, it has been publicly said that if future prosperity is to be ensured in South 
Africa, there is a need to encourage the expansion of more promising industrial sectors, and in 
the process downplaying the role of its premier industry, that of mining. <br>
<br>
Nobody will deny that a broadening of South Africa&#146;s industrial base is a commendable 
objective. What truly makes little sense, however, is to even vaguely consider a scenario where 
the development and extension of mining activity is seen as unimportant while pursuing or 
cultivating alternative enterprises. This thought process - if it can be termed as such - defies 
logic. To attempt to displace mining - which for over a century has been the country&#146;s leading 
business pursuit and principal earner of foreign exchange - with unknown or imagined potential, 
is mind boggling!<br>
<br>
It is a well known fact that South Africa possesses enormous mineral deposits of quite 
phenomenal variety. Turning those deposits to account - including the substantial unmined gold 
reserves - in itself means that mining will continue and will therefore remain in the forefront of 
the country&#146;s national economy for well into the next century.<br>
<br>
In stark contrast to the disheartening forecasts directed at the gold mining industry by some 
domestic and international analysts, there is a new vitality materialising. Innovative thinking 
and structural readjustment are exposing reassuring blue sky potential for the industry and are 
propelling it to what one senior executive describes as &quot;the next wave of its life.&quot;<br>
<br>
The prophets of gloom cited the ever increasing depths at which mining has to take place and 
declining production coupled more recently to political uncertainty which accompanied the 
arrival of a new government in South Africa, as their reasons for pronouncing negatively on the 
state of the mining industry. Since gold mining is seen in many quarters as a criterion against 
which other mining sectors are measured it is essential that both declining production and 
political uncertainty be examined critically because they do indeed have a damaging effect on 
investor sentiment.<br>
<br>
<a name="PRODUCTION"><font size=4><strong><u>PRODUCTION</u></strong></font></a><font size=4><strong><u><br>
</u></strong></font>At its production pinnacle in 1970 South Africa turned out just over 1 000 tons of gold. At the 
time, excluding what was produced by the then Soviet Union, this amounted to a massive 79 per 
cent of world gold production. Since then, with marginal exceptions in some years, South 
Africa&#146;s gold production has shown a consistent decline. The 1995 total was 522 tons, just over 
23 per cent of world production, and this year it is expected that the aggregate will drop by 
about 20 or so tons.<br>
<br>
The primary cause for the substantial reduction in gold output is a considerable drop in grades. 
This is well illustrated by looking again at statistics for 1970 when some 74 million tons of ore 
were milled by Chamber of Mines member gold producers at an average grade of 13,28 grams 
per ton. In 1995 almost 99 million tons were milled by Chamber member mines at 4,87 grams 
per ton. Or to put it in other terms, tons milled increased by about 34 per cent while the grade 
fell by 63 per cent per ton.<br>
<br>
While this vividly illustrates the changed conditions of gold mining in South Africa and 
demonstrates the country&#146;s diminishing production against the increasing volumes of other 
major producers particularly in South America, it nevertheless is a comparison that needs to be 
placed in proper perspective.<br>
<br>
At last year&#146;s production total of 522 tons South Africa remains, by almost 200 tons, the 
world&#146;s biggest single producer. With an estimated 40 per cent of the world&#146;s recoverable ore 
reserves not yet turned to account and the new initiatives that are underway, it is clear that 
South Africa - which is likely to maintain annual production levels in the region of about 500 
tons - will retain and entrench its position as the world&#146;s major producer for many years to 
come.<br>
<br>
In these circumstances it is difficult to understand - because the reasons are certainly not clear - 
why the international market so heavily undervalues South Africa&#146;s gold assets. At the end of 
the second quarter of this year the market capitalisation of South Africa&#146;s unmined gold 
resource was valued by a leading stockbroking company at 192 South African Rand (about 40 
US dollars) per ounce. By comparison, the value placed on Australia&#146;s gold in the ground was 
315 Rand (about 70 US dollars) per ounce. At that price, South Africa&#146;s unmined resource 
represents an exceptional bargain.<br>
<br>
The other mining sectors such as platinum, manganese, chrome and of course, coal, are not 
facing the same pressures as is the gold sector. However, this does not mean that because things 
are relatively easier in these sectors they are by any means being neglected. What I said earlier 
about the energies being expended in the gold mining industry to ensure its longevity applies 
equally, if not more, in the non-gold mining sector. And if what is being done in gold mining can 
be seen as a barometric indicator of potential throughout the industry, mining in South Africa 
certainly has a future well worth investor confidence.<br>
<br>
<a name="GOVERNMENT'S"><font size=4><strong><u>GOVERNMENT'S</u></strong></font></a><font size=4><strong><u> ROLE<br>
</u></strong></font>Critically linked to the private sector&#146;s vigorous endeavours to inject new life into a mature 
gold mining industry is the role that needs to be played by government in making certain that the 
correct and appropriate means are provided in which the industry can operate.<br>
<br>
South Africa&#146;s transition to democracy in April 1994 brought the African National Congress 
(ANC) from being an exiled liberation movement to a political party of national supremacy. As 
was expected after listening to the ANC&#146;s statements in this regard prior to assuming power, 
demands for increased state intervention in private sector activity were not long in coming. The 
despised legislative fabric of the previous regime was subjected to intense scrutiny in a process 
initiated to virtually rewrite the country&#146;s entire book of statutes. <br>
<br>
Because of its centrality to the national economy the mining industry was of course critically 
affected by government&#146;s legislative review. Through the <a href="http://www.bullion.org.za">Chamber of Mines of South Africa</a> - 
an umbrella body which represents about 85 per cent of mining industry interests in South 
Africa - the industry has immediately became an active participant in the national debate that 
has accompanied legislative and regulatory revision in South Africa. <br>
<br>
Without going into great detail, the short version of what is taking place is a tripartite process 
involving the views of government, business and organised labour. We all had our learning 
curves but since learning curves are there to be flattened, I would say that all parties are now 
approaching these forums (for want of a better word) far more open-mindedly and as a result 
are achieving consensus - or at least near consensus - and trust unknown to us in the past.<br>
<br>
The sentiment that government is there to create the environment and the opportunities is central 
to the stance the mining industry has taken on entering the debate on all the issues affecting it. 
Though what is without any shadow of a doubt - certainly from an industry perspective - the 
most significant area of legislative review, the revision to the mining and minerals policy has 
naturally received the brunt of industry&#146;s intense scrutiny. As important as all legislative review 
is to our industry, I would like to focus on the issue of mineral rights in particular since it is of 
singular significance to potential mining investors in our country.<br>
<br>
Initiated shortly after the 1994 election, the minerals policy deliberations have focused 
predominantly on the controversial issue of mineral rights. South Africa - like the United States 
- has a mixed system of mineral rights ownership. The most common estimates for South Africa 
suggest that about half of the country&#146;s mineral rights already reside in the hands of the state, 
while 20 per cent belong to mining companies and the remaining 30 or so per cent belong to 
tribes, landowners and private individuals.<br>
<br>
The system in place at present has been attacked by critics who express the view that mineral 
deposits are an essential part of a nation&#146;s heritage and should revert to state ownership. The 
mining industry has adopted a contrary position. Although it has no objection to the principle of 
state ownership, it contends that to attempt at this late stage to unscramble the existing regime is 
certain to cause confusion and a substantial erosion of confidence that would clearly be harmful 
to the best interests of the mining industry.<br>
<br>
Condemnation is also directed at the prevailing system on the basis that it locks out small 
mining entrepreneurs who are unable to gain access to mineral rights. This is seen by the critics 
as an obstacle to small business development. The small to medium business sector is touted in 
some quarters as a major potential contributor to South Africa&#146;s economic growth. The large 
industrial sector, including the mining industry, has no quibble with its potential for economic 
growth and would be delighted should that potential be realised. What is happening at this time 
is that major mining companies are examining their portfolios with the intention of making 
available to small operators those rights that are either too small or otherwise inappropriate to 
be mined by themselves.<br>
<br>
This is a but one aspect of the much larger and exciting process of empowerment that is taking 
place in contemporary South Africa. Before spending some time outlining some of the 
significant empowerment initiatives I would like to express the view that South Africa&#146;s dual 
system of mineral rights ownership is unlikely to be radically changed.<br>
<br>
<a name="EMPOWERMENT"><font size=4><strong><u>EMPOWERMENT</u></strong></font></a><font size=4><strong><u><br>
</u></strong></font>As important as criticism of the mineral rights system, perhaps considerably more important, 
have been the accusations levelled at the mining industry that it is unrepresentative of South 
Africa&#146;s majority black population. The policies of racial segregation which were the dominant 
features of an apartheid government distinctly disadvantaged citizens who were not white and 
effectively guaranteed that both political and economic power were firmly entrenched in white 
hands.<br>
<br>
Conscious of the need to temper white domination of South African business, the country&#146;s 
biggest mining house, <a href="http://www.edata.co.za/Anglo/anglostart.html">Anglo American Corporation</a>, structured a deal to facilitate black 
acquisition of a substantial industrial holding lodged in another of South Africa&#146;s major mining 
houses.<br>
<br>
Johannesburg Consolidated Investments, a well established mining house controlled by the 
Anglo American Corporation, was unbundled into three parts. Its platinum interests were 
placed in a company named Amplats; its gold, coal and base metals mining interests in <a href="http://www.bullion.org.za/organisation/members.htm#JCI">JCI</a>; and 
its powerful industrial holdings were assembled in Johnnic. Amplats was absorbed by Anglo 
American, and Johnnic and JCI were placed on the market with the express condition that the 
purchaser must be a black business grouping.<br>
<br>
In what will surely come to be seen as one of South Africa&#146;s business deals of the century, 20 
per cent of Johnnic was bought recently by the National Empowerment Consortium - a group of 
more than 50 black organisations - for more than 1,5 billion Rand (or US$325 million). The 
consortium has been given an 18 month option to buy an additional 15 per cent of Johnnic 
whose tentacles by the way extend into property, newspapers, motor vehicle manufacturing, 
brewing and pharmaceuticals.<br>
<br>
The central figure in the national economic consortium&#146;s bid for Johnnic was Cyril Ramaphosa, 
former secretary general of the ANC and principle architect of South Africa&#146;s new constitution.<br>
<br>
Anglo American, on 26 November, announced that Capital Alliance, another major black 
owned consortium, had purchased 34.9 per cent of JCI for 2.8 billion Rand (US$610 million). 
The mining industry, by finalising these two deals together with other though less headline 
grabbing but equally pertinent deals, broadcast a clear message to the industry&#146;s critics that it is 
in fact serious about and committed to the establishment of a significant black presence at the 
highest level of management in the South African mining industry. Certainly more will follow 
now that the precedent has been set.<br>
<br>
<a name="NEW"><font size=4><strong><u>NEW</u></strong></font></a><font size=4><strong><u> ENERGY<br>
</u></strong></font>Looking at new business, the compulsory revitalisation of an industry that several years ago 
was beginning to show signs of premature fatigue is being additionally animated by the 
optimistic prospect of a variety of new mega-ventures. Conservative estimates suggest that 
these will absorb more than 20 billion Rand (US$4.4 billion) in capital investment.<br>
<br>
One mining house, for instance, is engaged in the expansion and development of one of their 
gold mines which will produce more than 60 million ounces of gold. It is the single largest ore 
body actually or prospectively being worked in the world and, when it comes fully on stream 
just after the turn of the century, will have a life of at least 60 years.<br>
<br>
In the same area on the Far West Rand another mining corporation is investigating the 
possibility of developing at least two major shaft systems within the western ultra deep levels 
lease area. <br>
<br>
Another project with an estimated gold resource approaching 40 million ounces has been 
identified. A decision is imminent on whether to proceed with a 3 billion Rand (over US$650 
million) capital investment for shaft sinking and ancillary infrastructure.<br>
<br>
Now that political constraints have been removed, South Africa&#146;s mining companies with their 
considerable technological and intellectual resources are moving north into the African 
continent as well as throughout the rest of the world. Gencor acquired Billiton from Shell which 
elevated it into the premier league of international mining companies. The Anglo American 
corporation with business interests in Europe, North and South America and the Far East has 
long been a major global player. Other South African mining companies are pursuing 
opportunities in countries as diverse as Australia, Venezuela, India, Indonesia and Spain.<br>
<br>
<a name="CONCLUSION"><font size=4><strong><u>CONCLUSION</u></strong></font></a><font size=4><strong><u><br>
</u></strong></font>Ladies and gentlemen my presentation today has to a very large extent been focused on the 
South African gold mining industry. That is because gold is the metal most commonly and 
justifiably associated with South Africa. Coal, platinum, diamonds and an extensive range of 
other metals and minerals are found in almost embarrassing abundance in South African soil.<br>
<br>
Last year total mineral sales amounted to nearly 57 billion Rand or US$12 billion. The value of 
mineral exports in 1995 was 44 billion Rand (some US$10 billion) which represented close to 
42 per cent of the country&#146;s annual merchandise exports and if the value of beneficiated mineral 
products is also taken into account the exports exceed 60 per cent, which figures in themselves 
are hardly indicators of an industry in decline.<br>
<br>
Political uncertainty has now effectively been erased by a government that is giving serious 
attention to erasing the scourge of serious crime - probably one of the greatest deterrents to 
investment in contemporary South Africa.<br>
<br>
We are confident that the South African mining industry is moving into the next wave of its life. 
As it does so it will provide a profusion of profitable opportunities, not only for the people of 
South Africa, but also for the international community. Sure, there is risk involved in 
speculation, but I would venture that South Africa as a destination for speculative capital 
certainly is far less risky than other, perhaps more exotic, localities! Furthermore, South Africa 
has a burning need for foreign investment. While my country has a track record of providing 
more than fair returns to its investors, its populace also needs to get to work again. While the 
resources presently at our disposal are being used to their fullest, it is investment by outsiders 
which will eventually turn the tide and allow the country itself to progress to &quot;the next wave of 
<em><u>its</u></em> life.&quot; <br>
<br>
&#160;</p>
