<p align=center><font color="#FF0000"><font size=5><strong>GOLD AS A HEDGE WITHIN<br clear=all>
RISK DIVERSIFICATION</strong></font></font></p>
<p align=center><img src="/images/linegr.gif" align=middle><br>
</p>
<p align=center><font color="#800040"><font size=4><b>CONTENTS</b></font></font> </p>
<blockquote>
<blockquote>
<p><a href="#Introduction"><strong>INTRODUCTION</strong></a><strong><br>
</strong><a href="#today"><strong>THE GOLD MINING INDUSTRY IN SOUTH AFRICA TODAY<br>
</strong></a><a href="#trends"><strong>RECENT PRICE AND PRODUCTION TRENDS	<br>
</strong></a><a href="#approach"><strong>THE APPROACH TO HEDGING BY SOUTH AFRICAN PRODUCERS	<br>
</strong></a><a href="#perceptions"><em>Pricing perceptions	<br>
</em></a><a href="#Reasons"><em>Reasons for hedging	<br>
</em></a><a href="#Assessing"><em>Assessing risk	<br>
</em></a><a href="#examples"><em>South African examples	</em><br>
</a><a href="#impact"><strong>THE IMPACT OF HEDGING ON THE GOLD MARKET	<br>
</strong></a><a href="#Conclusion"><strong>CONCLUSION	</strong></a></p>
<p align=center><img src="/images/linegr.gif" align=middle><br>
<br>
</p>
</blockquote>
</blockquote>
<p><a name="Introduction"><b>Introduction</b></a> <br clear=all>
It is indeed a privilege for me to be present at this conference and to address you on the impact of mine producer hedging on 
the world gold market, particularly from a South African perspective. I will briefly talk about recent price and production 
trends, the pricing and marketing issues that impact on hedging strategies for gold producers, and finally, the impact of hedging 
on the world gold market. Given the prevailing difficult circumstances of gold mining in South Africa, hedging has become an 
important component of the producer's marketing mix. </p>
<p>Prior to grappling with the topic in detail, I would like to take this opportunity to inform you about recent developments in 
South Africa. We just wish that the pessimism about South Africa in some quarters would push bullion to better price levels! </p>
<p>Following our welcome political transition to democracy, it is now apparent that a more sobering reality is upon South Africa. 
The so-called `Mandela dividend' has begun to wane as the country comes to grips with the demands of international 
integration and the reality of President Mandela's imminent retirement. Whilst the transition will remain an enduring symbol for 
democracy and conflict resolution, the next phase of democratic consolidation requires addressing the imperatives of 
sustainable growth and development by setting priorities that can realistically be achieved. South Africa's future will, almost 
exclusively, be determined by its success in aligning itself with global and regional social, political and economic dynamics. </p>
<p>Whilst we cannot profess to be entirely satisfied with developments in every area, we remain optimistic that the government 
will continue the trend toward international alignment and integration. We are encouraged by the market orientation of the 
government which seemed improbable some years ago. Indeed, it is sobering to witness the power of globalisation and the 
doctrine of the market at first hand. </p>
<p>Government's recently published <i>Macroeconomic Strategy for Growth and Development</i> is welcome confirmation of the 
direction in which South Africa must move. As the new government continues to develop the required confidence and 
competency, we will see this trend accelerating, and we have no doubt that South Africa will emerge as a strong contender in 
the race for honours amongst the developing countries. We acknowledge that it will be a difficult process, characterised by a 
lack of policy latitude in respect of national interest goals. It is certainly not a challenge that we will shy away from. </p>
<p><b>The gold mining industry in South Africa </b><a name="today"><b>today</b></a> <br>
It is now a common theme amongst many analysts and pundits that the South African gold mining industry is in a terminal state, 
kept alive merely by the good fortune of a depreciating currency. Whilst it is true that the gold mining industry, undisputedly 
South Africa's economic bedrock, is facing significant challenges, it is certainly not terminal or even short of breath. </p>
<p>It remains robust, energetic and exceptionally innovative. Indeed, if there is a defining feature of South African gold mining, it is 
its inherent resilience and capacity for adaptation. The formal mining industry will remain a reliable wealth generator for the 
sub-continent well into the next century, as it has done for over 110 years through seemingly insurmountable problems and 
periodic turmoil. In terms of the world gold market, South Africa will continue contributing the dominant share of world gold 
production for many years to come, although we recognise the increasing contribution from other areas. </p>
<p>Descriptions of a crisis in the industry are certainly exaggerated. There are serious concerns about the continuing decline in 
profitability in the face of high working costs and a relatively stagnant dollar gold price. However, the industry has responded 
to the challenges and we are seeing exciting progress where problems have been addressed creatively. This creativity is 
generating new production and revenue axioms, based principally on profit maximisation as opposed to the previous focus on 
cost management. </p>
<p>Any analysis of the conditions facing South African producers must be tempered by a thorough appreciation of the seven 
fundamental pillars that form an interactive system that makes mining our unique gold ore bodies possible: namely geology, 
grades, depth, human capital, the regulatory environment, revenues and costs, and technology. At any moment, these seven 
issues are impeding or accelerating improvements in the gold mining industry - it is the task of our miners to apply their 
considerable expertise to harmonising each element in the pursuit of greater rewards. It is notable that nowhere else in the 
world have these fundamentals been managed to mine complex orebodies similar to those of South Africa - it is a fine 
testimony to the gold mining industry's achievements. </p>
<p><b>Recent price and production </b><a name="trends"><b>trends</b></a> <br>
South African gold producers have to benchmark their performances internationally and locally, and this is achieved by 
examining production data in a number of ways. The most useful analytical method is the concept of the mill pay limit. The mill 
pay limit is the minimum amount of gold that needs to be recovered from every ton of ore milled in order to break-even on 
costs - given a certain gold price and cost per ton milled. The two important variants are the Rand gold price and working 
costs per ton. </p>
<p>The nature of the South African gold mine tax formula has encouraged the mining of grades as close to the mill pay limit as 
possible, to ensure that as many low grade ore bodies are brought to account as is feasible. Graph 1 illustrates South Africa's 
mill pay limit and average recovery grade for the period 1961 to 1996. </p>
<p>The difference between the lines reflects the average grade recovered in excess of the pay limit (i.e. the working profit). In the 
period 1961 to 1971 the gold price was constant at US$35/ounce, but costs were rising rapidly, resulting in an increasing pay 
limit and an associated rise in average grade to maintain profits. With tons of ore milled increasing, and the pay limit and 
average grade peaking in 1970, production also peaked in 1970 at about 1 000 tons as shown in Graph 2: (all indicators base 
indexed to 1961). </p>
<p>The liberalisation of the gold market in 1968, and more importantly, the United States' decision to break the link between gold 
and the dollar on 15 August 1971, provided the spark that pushed the gold price up to a new peak in 1974. </p>
<p>Graph 3 shows working revenue per kilogram in 1995 Rand terms, from 1961 to 1995. The sudden rise in the gold price, and 
the slower rise in working costs, meant a fall in the mill pay limit from 8,8g/ton in 1970 to 3,8g/ton by 1974. Average grades 
followed suit, declining from 13,5g/ton in 1970 to 10,2g/ton in 1974. </p>
<p>The mid 1990s have, in many respects, been aberration years. Lower levels of productivity, from both capital and labour, 
resulted in rapidly rising costs which raised the mill pay limit. The decline in ore mined from underground forced the use of low 
grade surface material to supplement volumes of ore through the mills. Consequently, average grades declined placing 
substantial downward pressure on profitability. Gold production in 1995 fell to 522 tons, a 12 per cent decline on the previous 
year. We expect the figure in 1996 to decline further to around 500 tons. </p>
<p>The decline in the level of productivity, rapidly increasing costs and constant, or at least relatively stable gold prices, have 
increased pressure on the high cost, older marginal mines. These mines have limited grade flexibility and are most vulnerable to 
closure. The development of new marketing and pricing strategies has become more important for South African gold 
producers if they are to maximise profits in the current environment. </p>
<p><b>The </b><a name="approach"><b>approach</b></a><b> to hedging by South African producers</b> <br>
Previous trends and perpetually bullish sentiment has seen most South African producers follow a passive pricing doctrine, 
relying on the cushion of substantial profit to revenue ratios rather than risk losing upside gains, which tend to be highly 
leveraged for South African producers. That cushion has been diminishing for some time now, noticeable by the fact that South 
Africa is now the highest cost gold producer in the world (Graph 4). </p>
<p>The widely publicised hedging programmes recently undertaken by some South Africa mines should not be interpreted as a 
panic response to a crisis. The re-evaluation is essentially a need to revisit perceptions of the market to determine whether the 
mix of fundamentals on which South African producers relied previously, are less important. Increased South African hedging 
is a welcome adaptation to globalisation and the need to maximise opportunities. </p>
<p><a name="Why"><em><u>Why</u></em></a><em><u> hedge? <br>
</u></em>The objective of gold producer hedging is generally to achieve an appropriate balance between risk and expected return by 
actively managing commodity price risk, to which gold producers are especially vulnerable given that they are price-takers 
rather than price-makers. Notably, most, if not all, South African producers take a strong stance against speculative hedging 
transactions. </p>
<p>By engaging in hedging, producers are able to lock in a required price for a percentage of production, assuring them of a 
steady stream of revenue that might be required to sustain a marginal mine or pay for major capital development projects. </p>
<p>Hedging decisions are generally informed by the competition for scarce and expensive capital, limited cash reserves, the 
savings that can be effected on operating costs and the tax structure to which gold mines are subject. </p>
<p>In essence, it is a reduction of uncertainty in a risk environment of exceptionally scarce resources that have to be allocated 
strategically as well as optimally. Hedging has become an important alternative price insurance device for South African gold 
producers in an era of declining production and rapidly increasing costs. </p>
<p>Historically, the North Americans and Australians led the way in gold hedging. In the latter case, hedging was essentially a 
by-product of the use of gold-loan financing that enabled the Australian boom of the late 1980s - encouraged by the bullion 
banks to reduce their risk exposure and at a time when financing expansion through the share market, following its collapse in 
October 1987, was no longer possible, and the cost of debt financing was exorbitant. </p>
<p><em><u>Pricing </u></em><a name="perceptions"><em><u>perceptions</u></em></a><em><u> <br clear=all>
</u></em>For the South Africans, there are two factors that affect producers' perceptions of how gold is `priced' - its production cost 
and its currency cost (converting US$ to Rands). First, the production cost impacts on the mill pay limit which determines the 
efficiency of extraction (the ideal is not to leave any gold in the ground, hence a demand for the lowest possible pay limit). </p>
<p>Secondly, the price of the South African Rand in relation to the US Dollar is of special significance. For example, the 
depreciation of the Rand against the US Dollar has for many years cushioned, to some extent, the effects of the flat gold price. </p>
<p>Notably, my Australian colleagues believe that hedging has been far more successful in that country because of the relative 
stability of the Australian Dollar against the US Dollar. Compare this to the Rand, which depreciated unexpectedly by over 20 
per cent against the US Dollar in the first quarter of 1996. In such a volatile environment, it is exceptionally difficult to develop 
forecasts with sufficient confidence, hence the reliance on flexible strategies that allow hedges to be unwound or rolled over on 
demand. </p>
<p>It is also useful to consider pricing conditions governing some other metals, especially the platinum group metals. These metals 
are commonly sold on a contract basis and enjoy a high degree of certainty and security in terms of medium to long-term price 
commitment and therefore, the anticipated revenue is more easily established. On the other hand, gold is rather unique in that, 
traditionally, a relatively small proportion of its production was sold forward for an agreed price. </p>
<p>In other metal and commodity transactions, the producer and consumer are generally known to each other and conduct their 
business bilaterally. As such, the seller and buyer are clearly identified, which is unusual in the case of gold. With gold, price 
can determine the character of the holder as a buyer or seller - the boundaries between the two are entirely fluid and, 
therefore, unpredictable. The widespread parallel markets for gold further complicate the equation. </p>
<p>Of course, the other central issue, perhaps more favoured by South Africans for obvious reasons, is that gold remains a form 
of money, despite attempts to deprecate its status to a mere commodity. In this sense, the usual loop between supply and 
demand cannot be seen as complete. The holding and disposal of gold carries significant consequences, usually in the form of 
opportunity costs. Essentially, very little gold is actually `consumed' in the way that other metals are. Much of the world's gold 
remains accessible and, therefore, tradable. Similarly, the much described supply `gap' must be viewed circumspectly - we 
have seen how vast volumes of metal can flow into the market at certain price levels and we have very little inkling of illegal 
gold production and trade. </p>
<p>South African gold producers certainly cannot be regarded as neutral pricing strategists anymore. By virtue of the massive 
capital investment required to bring an orebody to account, and the subsequent burden of operating costs, producers are by 
nature long gold. This is a weight that should not be underestimated. Hedging is not a sign of pessimism, but an alternative 
method for managing risk at any time - both good and bad. Consequently, satisfactory producer pricing of gold is a difficult 
business; if not a fine art! </p>
<p><a name="Reasons"><em><u>Reasons</u></em></a><em><u> for hedging <br clear=all>
</u></em>To some extent, hedging by South African gold producers might be regarded as an inverse barometer of price and revenue 
expectations - a pessimistic position. However, this is moderated by a common thread that governs any business - the demand 
for a degree of price certainty to enable meaningful strategic planning to take place in what is inherently a risky environment. 
Hedging is one way to achieve this and the management philosophy and corporate culture guiding its employment are 
important considerations. </p>
<p>In the first instance, producers must be distinguished from speculators. The speculative use of hedging has, somewhat unfairly, 
tainted it in certain quarters as a high risk boom and bust option that responsible companies should avoid. This is especially 
true where exotic derivatives have been employed with disastrous consequences. Fundamentally, the hedging objectives for 
any producer are these: to maximise returns over the long-term, to prolong the profitable production life of a mine and to lock 
in a gold price that is adequate to cover the costs of a particular development - such as a new shaft. </p>
<p>Any hedging programme will be founded on an assessment of all the risk factors, building in a degree of flexibility to allow 
measured responses to unfavourable conditions. This is fundamental to South African conditions where the operational 
circumstances and philosophies vary so significantly from one mine to another, and indeed, within the mining finance houses 
themselves. </p>
<p><a name="Assessing"><em><u>Assessing</u></em></a><em><u> risk<br clear=all>
</u></em>For producers, hedging is a component of the total risk package, the objective being to minimise each component's risk. 
Critically, the risk package cannot be easily unbundled for a pricing strategy. A producer can cut costs without too much 
regard for price - the point of reference is the international cost curve. However, the pricing strategy is as dependent on the 
cost component as it is on all the other factors. A producer's position on the cost curve will influence his capacity for exposure, 
both upside and downside, and determine the extent of fixed price sales. Consequently, in South Africa, we have seen more 
marginal mines using hedging as a precaution against downside trends and volatility. </p>
<p>There are five important risk factors that will drive the South African producer's pricing strategy: </p>
<ul>
<li>gold spot price; </li>
<li>local interest rates; </li>
<li>gold price volatility; </li>
<li>gold lease rates; and </li>
<li>exchange rate fluctuations. </li>
</ul>
<p>South African producers have attached little significance to gold lease rates in the past because of the primary reliance on 
equity financing. However, they are critical to a hedging strategy that is being used for financing purposes because they form an 
important component of the gold price contango. </p>
<p>Indeed, the closing months of 1995 saw gold lease rates soar unexpectedly which had a significant impact on hedging 
programmes across the world as the market went into backwardation for a while. What that period did demonstrate to many 
analysts, was the flexibility of hedging programmes. There was evidence that the lease rates were reversed by increased 
liquidity derived from producers using the opportunity to make profits on their production that was hedged at higher 
contangos. </p>
<p><em><u>South African </u></em><a name="examples"><em><u>examples</u></em></a><em><u> </u></em><br clear=all>
It is worthwhile noting that South African producers have altered their hedging disclosure policies in recent years to conform to 
international best practice. This is a welcome development, especially for the many analysts who make a living in this field! It 
will certainly assist in evaluating more accurately the impact of hedging on the international gold market. </p>
<p>In addition to the key risks, there are other considerations that are intrinsically related to a producer's circumstances, which are 
by no means uniform: </p>
<ul>
<li>production prospects in terms of cost inflation, capital and labour productivity, tax obligations and capital expenditure; </li>
<li>a producer's capacity for downside endurance or, conversely, the tolerance for losing the gains of an upward price 
movement; </li>
<li>the medium to long-term view of market trends, especially in terms of contangos or potential for backwardation; </li>
<li>the macro social, political and economic risks attached to the location of production; </li>
<li>the capacity to adequately benchmark returns on particular instruments; and </li>
<li>the availability of willing counterparties in a scenario of a persistent gold price contango. </li>
</ul>
<p>South African producers traditionally refrained from active hedging for a number of reasons, the most important of which are 
the gold sales arrangements with the South African Reserve Bank and the cushion of a depreciating currency which has 
allowed steadily increasing Rand prices to be achieved against a static dollar price for gold. </p>
<p>The underlying management perspective on hedging is a concern that the future dollar gold price will continue to move 
sideways, decline or rise less than the prevailing contango rate. Hedging is made more attractive by the ability to lock in prices 
with some upside potential using structured hedges that combine commonly used spot-deferred contracts with gold and 
currency call options. </p>
<p>An example of this was JCI Limited's use of Rand/gold call options on 55 per cent of Western Areas' production to allow the 
group to benefit from increases in the gold price. On the other hand, Rand/Dollar call options on the remaining percentage 
provides protection against a depreciating Rand. The programme was flexible enough to allow JCI to exercise the option on 
the Rand/gold call options, whilst rolling forward the currency options which allowed it to sell all production into the spot 
market at the higher prices that prevailed earlier this year. </p>
<p>Each of the mining finance houses adopts a different approach to hedging - as a group and for the individual mines that they 
manage. It is essential for us to recognise that each South African gold mine is unique and consequently has unique financing, 
production, sales and administrative needs. These cannot be met by an inflexible pricing and marketing arrangement, and as a 
result there is no single hedging doctrine to speak of save that the results should be profitable! </p>
<p>To illustrate this, Anglo American is a relatively aggressive hedger whilst Gold Fields of South Africa does not hedge at all. </p>
<p>Anglo American sold forward 20 per cent of production in 1995 and this has been increased to 44 per cent in 1996. 
Anglovaal has sold forward an estimated 19 per cent of its production, up by 5 per cent on 1995. Gengold has hedged 
production at Beatrix Gold Mine in order to secure the development of a new shaft system. The hedge covers total production 
for 5 years. Notably, Gengold only hedges on a project specific basis. </p>
<p>JCI Limited has routinely sold forward 10 to 15 per cent of production. The most recent contract was for Western Areas 
Gold Mine, in which 7,3 million ounces were hedged in order to develop the South Deep project. The group's H.J. Joel Gold 
Mine is also considering selling forward its entire gold output in order to finance its capital expansion phase, to be implemented 
by 2001. Randgold recently unwound many of its hedges and has replaced them with flat currency forwards in both Rands and 
Dollars. </p>
<p>Flexibility is the key requirement - producers want exposure built into options or the ability to roll positions. When recent 
interest rate increases in South Africa were anticipated, producers avoided locking in higher Rand gold prices in order to take 
advantage of a more attractive contango. There must be the ability to survive periods of crisis such as the recent rapid 
depreciation of the currency where South African producers were able to roll-over their existing positions. However, most 
producers, if not all, certainly ceased hedging during the extreme period of currency volatility, because it made forward sales 
protection via Rand/Dollar call options very expensive. </p>
<p>In future, producers will have to watch the declining net contango very closely to ensure that their hedging strategies are 
optimising price opportunities. Indeed, we have seen a number of Australian and North American producers closing out their 
positions because of the contango, which is at its lowest level in many years. </p>
<p><b>The </b><a name="impact"><b>impact</b></a><b> of hedging on the gold market</b> <br clear=all>
Hedging has by no means been without controversy. In retrospect, the increased volume of hedging in the 1980s and 1990s 
can almost certainly be seen as partly responsible for capping the gold price and tranquilising its traditional volatility which 
attracted so many investors. Other factors have included, of course, central bank sales and profit-taking by hedge and 
commodity funds. Similarly, the debate surrounding the possible sale of 5 million ounces from the International Monetary Fund 
(imf) gold stocks, and uncertainty about the use of gold in reserves by the proposed European Central Bank, will continue to 
occupy the minds of analysts and commentators. </p>
<p>Important in considering the effect of hedging, is the distinction between long-term and short-term trends. In the short-term, the 
gold price is definitely constrained, but in the longer-term, it offers a more stable risk environment that allows more reliable 
forecasting by the gold producer. </p>
<p>However, the school opposing hedging is quite forceful. Prominent fund managers have made strong appeals to producers to 
halt forward sales to remove the cap on the gold price. We should understand the situation from a traditional management 
perspective though. Producers cannot optimise resources without planning; which requires a measure of certainty. Competitive 
conditions are such that extreme volatility could sink many operations instantly. It is therefore a trade-off between the 
spectacular and the mundane but predictable - most managers would choose the safety of the latter. </p>
<p>Critics bemoan the capping effect of hedging, but I believe that we need to accept this as a market condition rather than an 
unwelcome aberration or artificial distortion. We have no way of objectively determining what the gold price would have been 
without hedging although many would maintain a slight price bias against hedging. Once again though, I would remind you of 
the significant changes in the international political economy, especially in terms of official attitudes toward gold as money. </p>
<p>Hedging most certainly has impacted on price trends, but producers cannot make normative statements about the benefits, or 
lack thereof, of hedging. All participants are subject to the vagaries of the gold market and that is, arguably, its attractiveness. 
Otherwise we could make a case for some sort of systemic intervention since surely every impact on the price could be 
construed as a distortion rather than a fact of life. </p>
<p><a name="Conclusion"><b>Conclusion</b></a> <br clear=all>
The South African mining industry as a whole is vigorously addressing the most pressing issues facing it, some of which I have 
outlined for you today. I can emphatically refute the view that the South African gold mining industry is about to be laid to rest. 
We should not forget that gold has been mined commercially in South Africa for over 500 years, and scientifically for over 120 
years. Throughout the latter period, the industry has faced numerous crises; from war to labour shortages. </p>
<p>Most importantly, South Africa has nearly 40 per cent of the world's known gold reserves. If cost and revenue constraints 
improve as they have done previously, there is every possibility that gold mining will enjoy a renaissance in South Africa. </p>
<p>To conclude, the mining industry is central to the successful socio-economic development and welfare of the country. In return, 
it requires an enabling operational environment characterised by stable political and economic fundamentals. If there is one 
abiding impression of South African gold mining, it is one of positive pragmatism - an unsentimental understanding of the 
threats tempered with in-depth knowledge of the current realities and a vision based on sound and meticulous strategic 
planning. </p>
<p>Thank you. </p>
<p align=center><a href="/org1.htm"><img src="/images/tb101.gif" alt="organisation" align=bottom border=0></a> <a href="/res1.htm"><img src="/images/tb102.gif" alt="Resources" align=bottom border=0></a> <a href="/kruger.htm"><img src="/images/tb104.gif" alt="Krugerrand" align=bottom border=0></a> <a href="/new.htm"><img src="/images/tb105.gif" alt="What's New?" align=bottom border=0></a> <a href="/info.htm"><img src="/images/tb106.gif" alt="Contacting us" align=bottom border=0></a> <br>
</p>
