<html>

<head>
<title>Internet in the Mining Industry</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#0000A0">
<p align=center><font FACE="Arial Narrow"></font><font color="#0080FF"><font size=5><strong>INTERNET IN THE MINING INDUSTRY</strong></font></font></p>
<p align=center><font color="#400040"><em><strong>SEMINAR<br>
</strong></em></font><font color="#008040"><strong>The South African Institute of Mining and Metallurgy <br>
</strong></font><a href="http://www.infodoor.co.za/ema/"><font color="#008040"><strong>Electra Mining Exhibition</strong></font></a><font color="#008040"><strong>, Nasrec, Johannesburg 2 October 1996</strong></font><strong> </strong></p>
<hr noshade width=70%>
<p align=center><a href="mailto:twood@bullion.org.za"><font size=2><b>TIMOTHY WOOD</b></font></a> <br>
<font size=2><b>CHAMBER OF MINES OF SOUTH AFRICA</b></font> </p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/logo2.gif" align=bottom width=102 height=64><br>
</p>
<p><b><u>Introduction</u></b> <br>
The Chamber began investigating the application of Internet technology in 1994 and we implemented a comprehensive service 
package for the core business units in early 1995.<br>
</p>
<p><b><u>Implementation</u></b> <br>
The reasons for implementing Internet services were a little different to those already dealt with today, primarily because the 
Chamber is a non-profit organisation representing private sector mining employers in South Africa. As such, our point of 
departure was to critically evaluate the range of services and simulate applications for them in terms of the day-to-day service 
operations of our organisation, carefully examining the internal and external implications of its employment.</p>
<p>The results of the simulations were mixed, largely because the technology was so unfamiliar and because of scepticism about 
the 'business value' of the net. At that point in time it was still seen as a 'nice-to-have' that would damage productivity and 
corrupt corporate morals!</p>
<p>To overcome existing and potential resistance to the technology, we evaluated its potential using very distant time horizons. We 
recognised that with innovations increasingly being directed toward Internet applications; a diffusion of technology would occur 
that would revolutionise access to, and use of, information and knowledge, which is our core competency. It was an 
opportunity that we could not afford to ignore.</p>
<p>The evaluation phase also indicated that the technology was in such a state of flux that a formal policy governing standards 
would have to be delayed until more stability emerged. Initially, the sole objective was to explore and understand the 
technology and begin moulding it to our requirements as a knowledge organisation without disregarding new developments. </p>
<p>By adopting an incremental approach, we were able to develop a comprehensive and reliable package of Internet services for 
our employees that encouraged them to utilise its potential in a creative manner geared toward maximising the Chamber's 
return on its investment and spreading information about Internet resources that were particularly valuable. <br>
</p>
<p><b><u>Application</u></b> <br>
E-mail and USENet were an immediate success, particularly because of the nature of the Chamber's work as an advocacy 
organisation which requires extensive collective and personal networking; and the collation and distribution of knowledge as a 
value-added product. </p>
<p>Our approach to the world wide web was a little more difficult to conceptualise, largely because we didn't appreciate it's 
potential for non-profit organisations. However, I must admit that once we had decided on a formula, it appeared as if the 
medium had been designed specifically for us. </p>
<p>The use of the web as a credible information resource was very limited in late 1994 and early 1995. However, we recognised 
that the Internet was a public good in the sense that it encouraged knowledge sharing and distribution - it was only a matter of 
time before the biographies of pets would be replaced by decision-making information. We had to ask ourselves what we 
could do for the Internet. </p>
<p>We felt that by developing a benchmark product, we would stimulate the growth of other sites committed to providing quality 
information that we would find valuable in a reciprocal manner. We are immodest enough to believe that our contribution has 
helped to bring a number of other mining and minerals related sites online in South Africa and throughout the world in the last 
18 months.</p>
<p>We decided to appeal to the broadest possible market, from schoolchildren to mining industry analysts. The Chamber web site 
is therefore both an educational project as well as a service to our members and local and international mining industry 
stakeholders. </p>
<p>As an educational tool, it has been impressively successful in imparting knowledge about the benefits of responsible mining 
enterprise. As a service, it has given our members and stakeholders a far better insight into the organisation that represents 
their interests at the highest level. It is now an essential component of the Chamber's advocacy strategy that is complemented 
by the depth and breadth of information being supplied by other mining and minerals related sites.<br>
</p>
<p><b><u>Content</u></b> <br>
We have consciously allowed the web site to evolve according to internal and external requirements, and those of you who are 
familiar with it, will know that it is in its seventh outgrowth. </p>
<p>We have concentrated on making who we are and what we do transparent - to the browsing public and especially our 
members. To achieve this we had to adopt the perspective of someone who is unfamiliar with the Chamber and the mining 
industry. Navigation links have to be devoid of jargon, and the structure must facilitate finding what you require easily and 
quickly.</p>
<p>We believe the single biggest success driver for the Chamber web site is its simplicity - the points of entry and layers of 
information are minimalistic, as is the use of graphics. In effect, everything of substance is accessed through a single area.</p>
<p>The second important driver is substance - we have made very effort to ascertain what our stakeholders consider to be 
required information and combined that with specific information that we would like browsers to digest. </p>
<p>Thirdly, we are fortunate to have high-demand information that can be updated regularly. Having recognised the power of 
regularly updated material, we also introduced a daily news and economic indicators service that has proved extraordinarily 
popular. However, considerable effort is also put into finding new material for publication on the web and we have a fairly 
good monthly production. </p>
<p><b><u>Assessment</u></b> <br>
Activity on our site has a pattern consistent with business users who log in once every week, usually on a Monday morning. 
We therefore ensure that new material is posted on the site by close of business on Friday to make sure that repeat browsers 
will not be disappointed. </p>
<p>We have approximately 12&#160;000 - 15&#160;000 hits per month, excluding graphics and Chamber staff activity, the highest numbers 
coming from the United States, South Africa and Canada. We believe that that is confirmation of the appeal of the site across 
a broad target market. </p>
<p><b><u>Conclusion</u></b> <br>
The future of the Internet for the Chamber lies beyond its origins - in the application of its technology to secure electronic data 
interchange between ourselves and our members. We are looking at Intranet technologies and the way that we can integrate 
our existing information systems with browser front-ends. The result will be far cheaper and more efficient client-server 
solutions than we envisaged just one year ago that will help to reduce the paper mountain we produce each year.</p>
<p>Thank you. </p>
<p align=center><a href="/org1.htm"><font size=3><img src="/images/tb101.gif" alt="organisation" align=bottom border=0 width=101 height=17></font></a><font size=3> </font><a href="/res1.htm"><font size=3><img src="/images/tb102.gif" alt="Resources" align=bottom border=0 width=101 height=17></font></a><font size=3> </font><a href="/kruger.htm"><font size=3><img src="/images/tb104.gif" alt="Krugerrand" align=bottom border=0 width=101 height=17></font></a><font size=3> </font><a href="/new.htm"><font size=3><img src="/images/tb105.gif" alt="What's New?" align=bottom border=0 width=101 height=17></font></a><font size=3> </font><a href="/info.htm"><font size=3><img src="/images/tb106.gif" alt="Contacting us" align=bottom border=0 width=101 height=17></font></a><font size=3> </font></p>
<hr size=3 width=70%>
<address><font size=2>&#169; 1996 Chamber of Mines of South Africa<br>
HTML Coding by Timothy Wood : </font><a href="mailto:twood@bullion.org.za"><font size=2>twood@bullion.org.za</font></a><font size=2> </font></address>
