<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>1996 Wage Agreement Speech</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#0000A0">

<p align="center"><img
src="http://www.bullion.org.za/images/wd1.gif" align="middle"
width="32" height="31"></p>

<p align="center"><font color="#0000A0" size="4"><b>ADDRESS</b></font><font
size="2"><br>
</font>by the<br>
<font color="#008040" size="4"><b>PRESIDENT OF THE CHAMBER OF
MINES OF SOUTH AFRICA,<br>
MR A.J. &quot;AT&quot; DU PLESSIS</b></font><font color="#008040"><br>
</font>at the <br>
<font size="4"><strong>Signing of the 1996/97 Wages and
Conditions of Employment Agreement</strong></font><br>
between<br>
<font size="4"><strong>The Chamber of Mines of South Africa and
the National Union of Mineworkers</strong></font></p>

<p align="center"><font color="#0080FF" size="4"><b><tt>WEDNESDAY,
11 SEPTEMBER 1996</tt></b></font></p>

<p align="center"><img
src="http://www.bullion.org.za/images/line3.gif" align="middle"
width="590" height="2"><br>
</p>

<p>An outsider looking at the industrial and labour relations
climate in South Africa at present could not be blamed for
reaching the conclusion that things might not all be well on that
front. He would note the high level of acrimony evident at times between
business and labour, and several incidents of industrial action.</p>

<p>Whether correct or not, such perceptions colour the backdrop
against which this signing ceremony today is seen, and make it so
much greater a moment of pride to be able to sign the <a
href="/agreements/wage96.htm">1996/97 WAGES &amp; CONDITIONS OF
EMPLOYMENT AGREEMENT</a> between the National Union of Mineworkers
[representing some 194 000 employees on Chamber member mines] and
the Chamber of Mines [representing the bulk of South
Africa&#146;s private-sector mining interests] today.</p>

<p>It is an indication that, however great the differences
between us might be, enough commitment, dedication and
perseverance can and do deliver results in the form of an
agreement.</p>

<p>There were fewer items on the negotiating table this year, but
the negotiations proved to be protracted and difficult. This is not
only an indication that the parties faced some particularly complex
issues such as the restructuring of the Mineworkers&#146; Provident
Fund and the Mineworkers&#146; Assurance and Benefits Scheme, but
also that the parties have different perceptions about the economic
position of the industry. </p>

<p>In these circumstances it is particularly gratifying that the
parties once again were able to find each other and reach
agreement.</p>

<p>Mention should be made of the agreement regarding industrial
relations-related education and training in terms of which the mines
- at either Group or mine level -and the union will jointly develop courses
to equip shop stewards for the challenges presented by the new
industrial relations environment as envisaged within the new
Labour Relations Act and the concept of workplace forums among
others. These courses will then be financed by employers.</p>

<p>Secondly, there is the agreement that elected union
representatives serving on various tripartite forums will receive
paid leave to allow for meaningful representation of the union on
such new structures, particularly those set up under the new Mine Health
and Safety Act.</p>

<p>Several other issues were referred to working parties outside
of the wage review, and these will be pursued separately. They include:<br>
· the implementation of the agreement on restructuring the
Provident Fund and the Mineworkers&#146; Assurance <br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;and Benefits Scheme,<br>
· the institution of a statutory bargaining forum for Chamber
members,<br>
· the possibility of a two-year wage review cycle, and<br>
· the review of the job-grading systems in the industry -
something which was agreed to last year and which the <br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;parties this year have agreed should continue.</p>

<p>Productivity was a recurrent theme of the wage review, and
numerous sessions were dedicated to this matter. It is an issue which
will be pursued at either Group or mine level outside the wage review.
It is vital to the long-term viability of the industry as a
whole. During the course of the negotiations the NUM indicated
that it stood ready at all times to meet with Groups and individual mines
to discuss these and related issues.</p>

<p>The Chamber of Mines and its members pay tribute to the
negotiating team and to the representatives of the NUM in their deliberations
this year and congratulate all on reaching agreement. This
year&#146;s agreement once again underscores the impressive
levels of sophistication and maturity that characterise the
industrial relations climate within the South African mining industry
- and which, in fact, set it apart from most industry sectors in
this country.<br>
</p>

<p align="center"><br>
<a href="/org1.htm"><img src="/tb101.gif" alt="organisation"
border="0" width="101" height="17"></a><a href="/ess1.htm"><img
src="/tb103.gif" alt="Essentials" border="0" width="101"
height="17"></a><a href="/kruger.htm"><img src="/tb104.gif"
alt="Krugerrand" border="0" width="101" height="17"></a><a
href="/new.htm"><img src="/tb105.gif" alt="What's New?"
border="0" width="101" height="17"></a><a href="/info.htm"><img
src="/tb106.gif" alt="Contacting us" border="0" width="101"
height="17"></a> <br>
</p>

