<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Chamber of Mines Speeches</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000080">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/wd1.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><br>
<h3>Address by MrA.J. ('At') du Plessis,<br>President, Chamber of Mines of S.A.,<br>on 16 August 1996,<br> at the Kloof Mine Recreation Club<br> to the<br></h3><h2>1996 ANNUAL GENERAL MEETING<BR> of the<br> ASSOCIATION OF MINE HUMAN RESOURCE PRACTITIONERS.<br></b></h2>
<IMG SRC="/line3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><br><p></center>

<b>SUMMARY</b><br>
The Chamber's President, Mr At du Plessis, himself a Human Resource Practitioner (Chief Executive, Management Resources) at Gencor, equates Human Resource management to being in a "cauldron"and comments to members of the Association on the following:
<ol>
<li><I>labour unrest and impatience,</I>
<li><I>hardening of bargaining stances,</I> 
<li><I>new legislation, and</I>
<li><I>empowerment,equality and participation in the work place.</I>
</ol><br><p>
<center>
<IMG SRC="/line3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><br><p></center>

After making the usual introductory comments and welcoming various guests and VIPs, Mr du Plessis said:<BR><P>
It is always a pleasure to be given the opportunity to address one of the mining industrys important professional associations.  However, that pleasure is doubled when I am able to speak to a group of people who are all in exactly the same line of business in the mining industry as I am.  So therefore,  Mr President, an especially warm thank you for inviting me to attend todays proceedings.<BR><P>
Friederich Nietzsche, in one of his more lucid moments wrote: "Is not life a hundred times too short for us to bore ourselves?"  Well, ladies and gentlemen, if there is one field of endeavour in our industry which is constantly subject to change - particularly in the post democratic election period in this country - it is the field of human resource management.  Time in which to bore yourselves as H. R. practitioners is certainly a scarce commodity these days.<BR><P>
<B>LABOUR UNREST AND IMPATIENCE</B><BR>
While there are also changes taking place as far as engineering methodologies, mining techniques, survey methods, ventilation and refrigeration systems, and so forth are concerned, I would think these changes are taking place definitely not as rapidly, nor accompanied with as much violence, as in our specialised discipline.  The spate of injuries and tragic deaths during unrest at East Driefontein, or even more recently at Rustenburg and Impala Platinum for instance, were neither the result of a rock burst nor the result of a runaway locomotive - they were caused by humans to humans who were emotionally involved in human resource issues.<BR><P>
Our labour force seems increasingly to be showing signs of impatience.  It is coming across as trying its best to drive through issues that it feels its leaders in the union movement are not addressing to their satisfaction.  Due largely to misdirection and disinformation certain employees -- in fact, about 28000 employees at AMPLATS in Rustenburg -- succeeded through their actions not so long ago in undoing much of the good work their leadership had in the past fought so hard to win for them.  Despite the disadvantageous results to the employees at AMPLATS, Impala Platinum employees thereafter also embarked on a five day strike, losing in the process some 11 million Rand in wages.<BR><P>
<B>HARDENING OF BARGAINING STANCES</B><BR>
And on a macro level, it appears that harder stances are being adopted by the unions, the NUM in particular, in their annual negotiations in the Chamber of Mines.  Though, the same hardening of stances can also be said - I might add - of mine management in certain instances.  Declarations of disputes, conciliation boards and mediation seem to characterise bargaining these days and are becoming increasingly commonplace.  Most of us might say that a more level headed approach would be more in order, especially in regard to bargaining in 1996.  The question raised however is this - do we as management indeed have a more level headed approach?  And to what extent does <I>our </I>attitude contribute towards the creation of <I>their </I>attitude?<BR><P> 
Todays human resource practitioners find themselves in a position similar to the witches in Shakespeares Macbeth.  The three witches are to be found opening act four of the play chanting the following famous words around their huge cooking pot: "Double  double toil and trouble; fire burn and cauldron bubble!"  And it is right inside this cauldron, this human resource melting pot, that todays H. R. practitioners finds themselves.  Not always a comfortable place to be, but bearing in mind the rapidly changing environment around us, certainly a stimulating, if not exciting one.<BR><P>
<B>CORRECTIVE ACTION THE SALVATION OF THE INDUSTRY</B><BR>
With so much that is changing around us in the mining industry we tend to forget that these changes are not only the result of the altered political arena in our country.  Our industry has had in the past decade to take a critical look at itself.  In many ways it found itself wanting.  Fortunately it was recognised early on that the way we had done things in the past no longer applied, and if we continued along the same path our industry was doomed to failure.  The situation was critical - for the gold mining sector in particular - but signals were just as loudly being broadcast to coal, platinum, chrome, and others.  That we are all here today at this function is proof positive that we were alert to the changes and heeded the signals in time, and our corrective measures did indeed work.  That does not mean however we are off the hook yet.  Not by a long chalk!<BR><P>
<B>NEW LEGISLATION</B><BR>
In just less than three and a half years from now, we enter the 21st century.  And I would like to state quite categorically that you are going to enter this brave new century doing much of what you did last year, or are doing this year,<U> very much differently indeed</U>.<BR><P>
New legislation, such as the "Labour Relations Act" and the legislation replacing the old Basic Conditions of Employment Act, the pending "Employment Standards Act", and the Labour Market Commission Report are three cases in point which highlight what I am getting at.  Largely because of just these documents, human resource practitioners are certainly going to have their work changed for them, so I am particularly glad at this time to have been given the opportunity of speaking to you.<BR><P>
<B>'GOLDEN THREADS' </B><BR>
Today is not the appropriate time to go into the detail of the documents I mentioned a moment ago, because I would expect most of you would be familiar with at least some of their aspects and implications.  However, when I read through the documents, it became very clear to me that there are three basic concepts running like a golden thread through them all.  And the sooner we can get to grips with these concepts, the better for all concerned.  Each of the documents - though of course not spelt out in as many words - contain the common elements of: Empowerment, Equality and Participation.<BR><P>
I would say that most of you here today find these concepts alien to the way we went about our business in the past.  I know I did!  After all, we are in the mining industry and what mining management says is law and heaven help the poor soul who tries to break that law!  Just the mere idea of allowing employees any small degree of participation, never mind any sort of equality is enough to send shudders down ones spine!<BR><P>
But, whether we like it or not, dramatic change in the H. R. arena is upon us all.  The way in which we did things in the past has turned around significantly and where we once could choose to be either democratic or autocratic in our management styles, that choice has been taken away from us.<BR><P>
The new way of doing things is not a choice, it is legislation and, simply put, if you do not do it the way it has to be done, you are looking for serious trouble, resulting most likely in substantial penalties.<BR><P>
However, one choice still resides with you.  And that is the choice of whether to go with the flow or to resist the legislation changes every step of the way.  Actually, any reasonable person will see that there is not any real choice here either - unless, of course, if you want to make your lives unbearably difficult.<BR><P> 
<B>THE GOLDEN THREAD OF 'EMPOWERMENT'</B><BR>
Of the three concepts of "Empowerment, Equality and Participation", perhaps the most contentious of them is the first, namely "Empowerment."  Simply put it means that it is managements responsibility to see to it that your new management partners (for want of a better term) are real partners in decision making and not just some appointments made out of tokenism.  And if you do not have the properly qualified personnel to fill those roles, you have the responsibility to see to it that you indeed do find the right people.  This means you will most likely have to select and train the appropriate personnel if you hope to succeed.<BR><P>
Careful selection  - and I am not suggesting that you select a bunch of yes-men either - combined with the proper training will ultimately be to your benefit if you go about it in the right way.  Or to put it a little less diplomatically, screw up now and your lives will be made a misery.<BR><P>
<B>THE GOLDEN THREAD OF 'EQUALITY'</B><BR>
The next concept, namely, "Equality", in regard to the new legislation does not mean that, say, a shop steward is equal to his mine manager.   What it means is that, for example, in "workplace forums" every recognised member has equal status and an equal right to be heard and to put across their point of view.  This holds true for management as much as it does for labour and government.  Be  aware of falling into the trap of thinking along the lines suggested by the ruling powers in George Orwells famous allegory, "Animal Farm" that: "All animals are equal, but some are more equal than others." <BR><P>
<B>THE GOLDEN THREAD OF 'PARTICIPATION'</B><BR>
The final concept, that of "Participation" is, I think, self-explanatory.  Labour has for many years been griping about the lack of participation in the affairs of the mine.  They have felt excluded and have, rightfully I might add, felt extremely frustrated at their exclusion.  Now is the time to redress the situation.  In the long run, a better informed, more involved work-force will result in a smoother mining operation.  One of the positive side effects could perhaps be the diminishing of the industrial unrest that has been bedevilling our industry of late  only time will tell.<BR><P>
The role to be played in the new order of things by human resource practitioners is enormous ladies and gentlemen.  But you know this better than anyone else.  You, as members of this association, are in the firing-line of some heavy-weight legislation but I know you will face the challenges ahead of you with skill, aptitude and professionalism.<BR><P>
<B>CONGRATULATIONS TO THE ASSOCIATION'S NEW PRESIDENT</B><BR>
Mr President, congratulations on your election as president of this fine association.  I wish you good luck in your year of presidency.  Furthermore I extend to all the associations members the very best and pray that God grant you strength for the times ahead.<BR><P>
<B>CONCLUSION</B><BR>
The times before you are going to be interesting to say the least.  Frustrations will certainly abound, but there will also be dizzying successes.  Many downs will be counterbalanced by just as many, if not more, ups.  On the other hand, we should again remind ourselves of Nietzsches words: "Is not life a hundred times too short for us to bore ourselves?"  Well, if these days any H. R. practitioners worth their salt have the time in which to bore themselves, I heartily congratulate you and humbly ask that you pass your secret on to me!<BR><P>
Thank you.<BR><P>

<center><img src="/linegr.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><br><p>
