<head>
<title>The Chamber of Mines Speeches</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000080">
<p align=center><font size=2><strong>Chamber of Mines of South Africa</strong></font></p>
<p align=center><img src="/wd1.gif" align=middle width=32 height=31></p>
<p align=center><font color="#0080FF"><font size=4><strong>Address made by Mr E. P. Gush,<br>
Deputy Chairman, Anglo American Corporation, <br>
</strong></font></font><br>
on 10 August 1996,<br>
<br>
when toasting the<br>
<br>
<a href="http://www-eng.wits.ac.za/min/min_home.html"><strong>DEPARTMENT OF MINING ENGINEERING</strong></a><strong><br>
</strong><b>of the<br>
</b><a href="http://sunsite.wits.ac.za/wits/wits1.html"><b>UNIVERSITY OF THE WITWATERSRAND</b></a><b> (Johannesburg)<br>
</b><br>
on the occasion of its<br>
<br>
<a href="/publications/centenary.htm"><b>CENTENARY</b></a><b><br>
</b></p>
<p align=center><img src="/line3.gif" align=middle width=590 height=2><br>
</p>
<p align=center><font color="#800040"><b>SUMMARY</b><br>
</font>Mr E. P. (Peter) Gush, Deputy Chairman of one of South Africa's leading mining houses, in proposing the toast to the 
Department of Mining Engineering of the University of the Witwatersrand on the occasion of its centenary celebrations, 
mentioned: </p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li><a href="#DISCOVERY">the discovery of 'world class mineral deposits</a>', </li>
<li><a href="#SYNDICATES">the development of syndicates in the early days and the evolution of the Chamber of Mines of S.A</a>., </li>
<li><a href="#WATER">the supply of water to the Reef</a>, </li>
<li><a href="#VISIONARIES">the young visionaries or pioneers who exploited the mineral wealth</a>, </li>
<li><a href="#TECHNOLOGY">how S.A. leads in mining technology</a>, </li>
<li><a href="#HOUSE">the evolution of the 'Mining House' system</a>, </li>
<li><a href="#ROLE">the role of trade unions in mining and the political changes in the country</a>, and </li>
<li><a href="#OUTLOOK">briefly touched on what the future holds in store</a>. </li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<p>He concluded his address with a toast to the Department. <br>
</p>
<p align=center><img src="/line3.gif" align=middle width=590 height=2><br>
</p>
<p align=left><b>INTRODUCTION</b><br>
South Africa is mining country - no doubt about that. From 120 years ago when Cecil John Rhodes wheeled and dealed in the 
fastest growing town on the African continent - Kimberley - to today when mining takes place four kilometres below the 
ground.<br>
</p>
<p>Most people in this room have been involved with mining over their lives in one form or another. A lot of you have moved 
around the country with your families building these mines. In doing so, you have created, I believe, one of the best, if not the 
best, mining communities in the world. And I would think most would have found it an exciting, challenging even exhilarating 
career. Indeed, it is only when one stands back from the humdrum existence of everyday issues that one sees the greatness of 
our mining industry, the wealth of our deposits, their immense size, their variety and their position in the global scene. The 
words &quot;world class deposits&quot; were coined here.<br>
</p>
<p><a name="DISCOVERY"><b>DISCOVERY</b></a><b> OF 'WORLD CLASS MINERAL DEPOSITS'</b><br>
The stories of the discoveries are well-known. The strange stone picked up on the Orange River which led to the rush of 
diggers firstly to the rich alluvial deposits on the banks of the Vaal and then to the mother lodes at Colesberg Kopje and 
elsewhere. The diggers went in in their thousands, the pits were being worked faster by the syndicates and much less so by the 
individuals, resulting in the pictures we all know so well of differing heights of claims in an ever deepening hole with spider 
webs of wires fanning and criss-crossing the hole. A chaotic and indeed fragile industry.<br>
</p>
<p>After diamonds the hunt for gold was on, spurred by rumours of discoveries at Pilgrims Rest, the Blyde River and Barberton. 
As Cartwright says: &quot;Watching the events was like watching an exciting film being run through in slow motion.&quot; Early 
prospectors bumbled and stumbled around the Witwatersrand as though blindfolded, following false trails, pausing in the 
wrong places and crushing samples of the wrong rocks. In the end it fell to an Australian, George Harrison, to discover the 
Main Reef Series. And what a discovery!<br>
</p>
<p>Samples were sent to Kimberley and crushed and panned publicly, no doubt with considerable showmanship. The results 
created a sensation. Cartwright&#146;s film had been switched to &quot;fast forward.&quot; Syndicates were formed by all the famous names, 
Beit, Robinson, Rhodes, Sauer. The rush to the Rand was on - and what a rush.<br>
</p>
<p>Diamonds in Kimberley were not enough. They were discovered strewn over the desert at Luderitz by Stauch and then later, 
intermingled with oyster shells, at Oranjemund by Hans Merensky - one of the great names of mineral discoveries in South 
Africa. Wealth of untold proportions in the harshest of climates and environments - an extraordinary tale of mineral discovery.<br>
</p>
<p>Platinum - again by Merensky - in that great geological formation known as the Bushveld igneous complex - followed by 
chrome. The platinum deposits overwhelmed anything found before and after - and because of their very size have not been 
developed to anywhere like their full potential.<br>
</p>
<p>Coal had been found as early as 1880 on the farms Leeuwkuil, Rietfontein and Maccauvlei, near Vereeniging. Until then most 
coal had been imported, and it goes without saying, at considerable cost. Sammy Marks quickly grasped the significance of 
the find on the banks of the Vaal river and invested heavily in the coal mines. Marks, never short of grandiose schemes, 
planned to float loaded barges of coal down the Vaal to Kimberley. Two steel barges were built, and in typical fashion, <i>only 
once they had been built</i> was the river surveyed. The Vaal of course proved unnavigable. Ox wagons were resorted to to 
transport the coal to Kimberley.<br>
</p>
<p>Manganese, vanadium, titanium, iron - the list of the wealth bestowed on this land seems endless.<br>
</p>
<p><b>EARLY </b><a name="SYNDICATES"><b>SYNDICATES</b></a><b>/EVOLUTION OF THE CHAMBER OF MINES OF S.A.</b><br>
To exploit all this required special solutions. Each discovery brought with it immense, almost insoluble, problems. In 
Kimberley the dangerous and impossible situation of hugely differing levels of claim blocks required a drastic solution. This 
came in the form of Barnato and Rhodes and De Beers Consolidated Mines. It was the first small step towards an integrated 
mining company. Kimberley was followed by the Witwatersrand - where it soon became clear that this was no poor man&#146;s 
diggings, like California.<br>
</p>
<p>The remarkable feature here was not so much the richness of the ore but the vast extent and uniformity of the deposits. There 
was still bonanza ground about, certainly, but the average grade overall was not high. It was the continuity that made possible 
the large scale employment of machinery. Indeed the reefs could not be mined on an economic scale without this. Nor could 
such enormous expenditure be justified on a single, or even small group of claims. As a result, syndicates were quickly formed 
to acquire groups of claims. The syndicates were themselves the forerunners of today&#146;s mining finance houses, or &quot;Groups&quot;. 
The potential of the gold-field had been proved but the financing and technological problems associated with the mines were 
only beginning.<br>
</p>
<p>Part of this structural and organising process involved the formation of the Chamber of Mines of South Africa. An important 
motivation for the founding of the Chamber was the need for authoritative information about the output of the new gold field. It 
is forgotten today that the published yields of the diamond fields of Kimberley and of the Witwatersrand gold-field were 
regarded at first with scepticism because mining &#145;experts&#146; had rejected on geological grounds the possibility of major deposits 
in South Africa. The climate of opinion was also not improved by over-speculation and bogus promotion.<br>
</p>
<p>Be that as it may. After a false - though very impressive - start in 1887, a Chamber of Mines was formed - and then closed 
18 months later. Then, barely three years after the first proclamation of gold on the Rand, The Witwatersrand Chamber of 
Mines was launched. Like today&#146;s Department of Mining Engineering it too went through a number of name changes and 
added many functions as it grew. After attracting members from outside the Transvaal it eventually settled on the name it 
enjoys today.<br>
</p>
<p><b>SUPPLY OF </b><a name="WATER"><b>WATER</b></a><b> TO THE REEF</b><br>
Water, another vital commodity for the mines, was available in abundance from the Vaal river though supply was erratic. In 
1901 Lord Milner appointed a commission to &quot;prepare a scheme for the creation of an unfailing water supply to the Rand and 
the mines&quot; which led to the establishment of an enduring institution, the Rand Water Board, charged with supplying potable 
water from Randfontein to Springs.<br>
</p>
<p><b>YOUNG </b><a name="VISIONARIES"><b>VISIONARIES</b></a><b>/PIONEERS</b><br>
As rich as all these mineral deposits and reefs were, there were major riches to emerge in the people front. The pioneering 
spirit, the seemingly limitless opportunities and the need for consolidation in diamonds and gold resulted in co-operation first, 
then the formation of syndicates and finally the mining finance house system, which has served this country so well.<br>
</p>
<p>The history of the diamond rush is peppered with the names of many entrepreneurs familiar to you. Young, dynamic people 
like Rhodes who began his career there at the age of 18, while Alfred Beit, Julius Werner, Sammy Marks, George Albu, John 
Merriman, Leander Starr Jameson, Lionel Phillips and Barney Barnato were all 22 or younger. These young entrepreneurs 
who emerged at Kimberley brought with them to the Witwatersrand a gift for getting things done in the face of seemingly 
insurmountable difficulty. Not surprisingly, perhaps, they were sometimes short on patience, and sometimes short on wisdom. 
But they were rich in faith in the future greatness of South Africa. A future greatness firmly rooted in the world&#146;s single biggest 
gold field.<br>
</p>
<p>These were the visionaries who made the mines work. Certainly they rank with the greats of mining elsewhere and what they 
created stands today as a monument to their efforts. Subsequent generations have continued with this tradition.<br>
</p>
<p><b>S.A. LEADS IN MINING </b><a name="TECHNOLOGY"><b>TECHNOLOGY</b></a><br>
When difficulties were encountered people came up with solutions. Deep level mining with all its problems of shafts and shaft 
sinking, of mining and support systems, of seismic problems and breakthroughs in seismic research; heat problems overcome 
by ventilation systems and ice cooling; metallurgical breakthroughs such as CIL and CIP which kept our name high in the 
international world of mining; and geophysics and the magnetometer which had its first great success here.<br>
</p>
<p>A great deal of the strength of this great industry has been the army of people who have laboured and toiled over many years 
in the mines, the plants and the offices. These are the people who shaped the country in many ways, who made things happen 
and who developed the technology that made this industry great.<br>
</p>
<p><a name="GROWTH"><b>GROWTH</b></a><b> OF DEPARTMENT OF MINING ENGINEERING FROM HUMBLE BEGINNINGS</b><br>
This is where this great institution - Wits - comes into its own. None of this would have been possible without the really 
excellent tertiary education institutions in South Africa. Of particular importance was and remains Wits - for historical reasons, 
its proximity and also because of the quality of its graduates.<br>
</p>
<p>The dominant city in South Africa in 1890 was, of course, Cape Town which already had a fairly well-established university, 
the University of the Cape of Good Hope and also the home of the South African College, the leading teaching institution. The 
Council of the College proposed in 1890 to establish a school of mines in Cape Town, which proposal was opposed, wisely 
as it transpired, by Rhodes, who - by the way - became Prime Minister of the Cape in July that year. Not that he was against 
the idea of a school of mines. He believed Kimberley - where, after all, the country&#146;s mining activities were then centred - 
would be the more appropriate seat.<br>
</p>
<p>Unsurprisingly, the proposal was shelved - but four years later, in 1894, it was resurrected. This time with the co-operation of 
the Cape government and De Beers, but unfortunately in a flawed form:- two years of theoretical training in Cape Town, 
followed by a year of practical training in Kimberly and a further year in Johannesburg during which students would be placed 
under the care of various mine managers. After much wrangling - in the middle of which the ill-fated Jameson Raid on the 
Transvaal Republic took place which - shall we say - didn&#146;t help matters in any way - the South African School of Mines 
opened its doors in Kimberley in August 1896 to an initial student body of five intrepid youths.<br>
</p>
<p>Obviously the system of fragmented study was neither viable nor practical and the Kimberley School of Mines was, to put it 
mildly, rather unsuccessful. It was &quot;started on the worst possible basis and with the least amount of money that any school 
ever started.&quot; Throughout, the school was short of finance, staff, and students. It closed temporarily in 1899 with the outbreak 
of the Anglo-Boer war and the ensuing siege of Kimberley. But the defeat of the Boer republics provided the death knell to 
the school because, with the Boer republics now reduced to colonial status, the political incentive for maintaining a school of 
mines in the Cape collapsed.<br>
</p>
<p>With the ink on the Treaty of Vereeniging hardly dry, Lord Milner established Johannesburg as the centre for mining and 
technical education in South Africa - largely for imperial reasons. It was hoped that a university would, amongst other ideals, 
stabilise the local British population and promote the assimilation of the Afrikaner. After winning the war it seemed a good 
idea at the time, but was doomed to failure as a system of secondary education in the Transvaal capable of sustaining anything 
approaching a university was simply not there. Furthermore, there were grave doubts as to the appropriateness of 
Johannesburg as the seat of higher learning. In those days it was the haven of pimps and prostitutes, speculators and sharp 
dealers, liquor and violence.<br>
</p>
<p>Nevertheless, on the recommendation of a special commission the School of Mines in Kimberley transferred to Johannesburg 
as the Transvaal Technical Institute in 1902. Its first professors were appointed in typical technical disciplines such as 
engineering, mining, metallurgy, chemistry, and geology. Interestingly enough, only the Department of Geology has survived in 
its original form.<br>
</p>
<p>Jan Smuts, who was the then Minister of Education, thought that Johannesburg was far too decadent a place for a university 
and he moved the seat of the Transvaal University College to Pretoria, later to become Tukkies. The Institute in Johannesburg 
in turn became the Applied Science Department of the Transvaal University College, which in turn became the South African 
School of Mines and Technology in 1910. All very complicated and I suppose somewhat unnecessary, but nevertheless, from 
this, somehow, a university of stature was born and was officially inaugurated as the University of the Witwatersrand in 1922.<br>
</p>
<p>Looking at how our industry has grown an prospered there is no doubt that we have been well-served by Wits in general and 
the Mining Department in particular. There have been ebbs and flows. However, the number and competence of Wits mining 
graduates - and their status in the world of mining - is testimony to this department. I know you will also agree with me that 
under Huw Phillips it has certainly regained its pre-eminent position amongst the mining schools of the world.<br>
</p>
<p><b>DEVELOPMENT OF THE 'MINING </b><a name="HOUSE"><b>HOUSE</b></a><b>' SYSTEM</b><br>
A feature of South African mining has been the development of the mining house system. Being in Africa the mining industry 
faced two critical shortages - money and skills. The mining house system made best use of both those scarce resources - by 
equity leverage and public listings on the one hand, and by enabling top technical and financial people to spread themselves 
over many mines and without losing their entrepreneurial touch.<br>
</p>
<p>The founders of these houses are legend, as are those who succeeded them over the years. While some of the mining houses 
have fallen by the way, we still have some of the largest and most successful in the world. Being forced to struggle through 40 
years of isolation and almost as long a time of exchange control has seriously limited our ability to become truly global players. 
The isolation, however, did protect us from incursions and takeovers, but this is now changing and the harsh winds are 
blowing. Nevertheless, these winds have also brought many opportunities which the houses of today are running with strongly.<br>
</p>
<p>Most of the houses still exist - but where they had a common basis for their creation, circumstances now are much more 
varied and many have already moved in diverging directions. More divergencies are likely as the debate about bundling or 
unbundling, pooling of management skills or decentralising them, national or international focus - continues. One thing is for 
sure though - South African mining houses will be around for some time yet.<br>
</p>
<p><a name="ROLE"><b>ROLE</b></a><b> OF TRADE UNIONS</b><br>
Trade unions have played a major role - not just in the industry but in shaping the country. The early white unions took on the 
big companies and forced them to make room for them. The black trade unions did much more. They mobilised their 
members in the workplace - but, more importantly, provided a political outlet - a safety valve. With hindsight we could have - 
should have - done things differently, but the mining industry was a pawn in a much greater political game. The 1970&#146;s and the 
1980&#146;s were rough years. But it may well just be that the constant - even though acrimonious - negotiations pushed the 
country politically into the realisation that there was really only one solution - negotiation for a common destiny. Thereafter the 
black trade unions provided the new government with much of its leadership. It now remains to address the labour related 
issues.<br>
</p>
<p><a name="OUTLOOK"><b>OUTLOOK</b></a><b> FOR THE FUTURE</b><br>
But what about the future? There are many challenges and serious problems facing us. To look only through rose coloured 
spectacles would be wrong. Equally, the prophets of doom and gloom will also be confounded. It is worth reflecting for a 
moment on the rich history of the mining industry, on the daunting problems faced 100 - or even 50 years ago. These have 
been overcome. We need only look back five years to see how far we have come - from such a low road. In five years time 
we will look back equally incredulously to see how far we have progressed on the high road.<br>
</p>
<p>One last thing to the students here tonight - never forget how much people like Rhodes, Barnato and Marks achieved, and 
never forget how very young they were.<br>
</p>
<p>A toast to the Department of Mining Engineering of the University of the Witwatersrand.<br>
</p>
<p align=center><img src="/linegr.gif" align=middle width=402 height=5><br>
<br>
<font color="#FF0000"><strong>Please Note</strong></font><br>
Copyright subsists in this work. Any unauthorised reproduction, adaptation, distribution <br>
or commercial exploitation of the work is an act of copyright infringement.<br>
</p>
