<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Chamber of Mines Speeches</TITLE><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000080">
<center><IMG SRC="/wd1.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><br>

<h3><B><FONT SIZE=5>MANAGEMENT, LABOUR & PRODUCTIVITY</FONT></B><BR>
by the<BR> 
<B><FONT SIZE=4>C.E.O. OF THE CHAMBER OF MINES OF SOUTH AFRICA,<BR> MR T.R.N. (TOM) MAIN</FONT></B><BR>
at the <BR>
1996 SUB-SAHARAN OIL & MINERALS CONFERENCE<BR>
Johannesburg, 11 June 1996<BR></h3>



<IMG SRC="/line3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><br><p></center>


<Center></Center>



<FONT SIZE=4><B>KEY POINTS:</B></FONT><BR>
<B>*	"OPERATIONAL TRIPARTISM"<BR>
*	THE NEED FOR AN ENABLING & FAVOURABLE ENVIRONMENT<BR>
*	THE NEED TO BETTER UTILISE WORKING TIME<BR>
*	OPTIMAL UTILISATION OF HUMAN RESOURCES<BR>
*	CONCLUSION</B><BR><P><P>
If one over-riding message is to emerge from this, the 1996 Sub-Saharan Oil & Minerals Conference, it should be that mining in Sub-Saharan Africa in general - and in South Africa in particular - is very much alive and brimming with promise. <BR><P>
This is not a naïve denial of the reality or gravity of the challenges facing all of us. Rather it is a powerful reaffirmation of the dogged resilience of mining men and women, their consistent creativity in the face of change and their preparedness to confront all the issues of the day (no matter how unpleasant they may be). <BR><P>
In short - we are seeing today the same powerful and pervasive optimism that has characterised miners since first they gouged wealth from the earth.<BR><P>
One of the critical challenges facing the industry in South Africa today is that of implementing a new form of tripartism. This time not so much in terms of a co-operative relationship as in that between employers, employees and government - although this facet remains vitally important.   Rather it relates to the title of my presentation today - MANAGEMENT, LABOUR AND PRODUCTIVITY; a kind of <B>OPERATIONAL TRIPARTISM</B>.<BR><P>
The English writer and one-time chaplain to the king, Thomas Fuller, once remarked that "A mariner must have his eye upon rocks and sand as well as upon the North Star". The same applies metaphorically to a miner - who has to deal with the here-and-now practicalities of wresting mineral wealth from the rocks and sand that hold them,  but equally his eye must remain fixed upon the guiding objective of  long-term viability and prosperity, both for the industry and for the greater social well-being.<BR><P>
But, in this process, we need to identify and campaign for the establishment of those conditions which, like fair winds and weather were to the mariners of Fullers time, are indispensable for mining to survive and thrive. Here I am referring to the <B>ENABLING AND FAVOURABLE ENVIRONMENT</B> for both mining and mining investment. <BR><P>
While it is patently obvious that management and labour urgently need to find ways and means of pooling their resources in this campaign, the realities within the nascent and fluid democracy in South Africa are quite different. <BR><P>
It is acknowledged that managements across the board need to move away from some of the historical hierarchical structures which have served them well in, and change their philosophies, attitudes, measurements and methods for more effective approaches in todays world of work. By the same token, labour at all levels needs to jettison outdated and inappropriate ideologies, inject serious effort into productivity drives and reprioritise their agenda to reflect the complex demands of society on the threshold of the millennium.<BR><P>
At the same time as looking to what management and labour can and should be doing, we need to identify what government, the formulators and implementers of law, is doing. As far as mining is concerned, there are both heartening and dispiriting signals.<BR><P>
The new Mine Health and Safety Act holds great potential for bringing about safer and more healthy conditions on our mines.  As the<A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/speeches/atsubsa.htm"> President of the Chamber of Mines, Mr At du Plessis, said yesterday</A>, this Act, the result of  compromise, could well be recognised as "the most constructive legislative enactment in (our) industrys history". This point is very important, for it also helps locate other legislative developments within the greater context of the sweeping and comprehensive statutory review upon which the government has clearly embarked. Of key interest in this context will be the formulation of the Mining and Minerals Policy now in progress.<BR><P>
New bills and the regulatory environment they generate not only have direct impact on our industry, but send critical messages across the globe affecting investment decisions and colouring international perceptions about our country. No one piece of legislation can be viewed in grand isolation: the Mine Health and Safety Act and the emerging minerals policy need to be seen together with the Labour Relations Act (LRA), the Employment Standards Act (ESA) and several other possible regulatory changes.<BR><P>
In this context too it is heartening to see the steps currently being undertaken within the Department of Mineral and Energy Affairs - and especially in the Government Mining Engineers division. Building on the recommendations of the Leon Commission of Enquiry into Mine Health and Safety, many of which have been entrenched in the new Act, the entire mining industry will be looking to the men and women of this division for effective regulation and implementation of requirements and standards embodied in the Act.<BR><P>
Our industry has also seen, in rapid succession, the appointment of not only a new Deputy Minister, but a new Minister of Mineral and Energy Affairs to whom management and labour will be looking for clear guidance and sound judgement in the creation and development of a new dispensation for mining in SA.<BR><P>
Simultaneously, however, the ambit of the favourable enabling environment mentioned earlier has to be cast wider since we all live and work in a greater social framework. This means crime, housing, migrancy, the general economic environment, certainty regarding taxation and discipline in monetary and fiscal policies need to be factored in as well.<BR><P>
We are encouraged by the many positive signals emerging from both national and provincial governments in this regard. Comprehensive programmes to seriously cut the unacceptably high crime rates, recent initiatives to deliver on housing promises, early signs that augur possible economic improvements, recent steps by the Katz committee on taxation to look into the vexed question of  ring-fencing, and what appear to be serious efforts by government to bring about greater monetary and fiscal discipline - are all heartening to the SA mining industry.<BR><P>
However, we need to contextualise these factors within the ambit of this presentation - the operating relationship between management, labour and productivity.<BR><P>
As we stand at the start of the annual wages and conditions of employment negotiations between the Chamber of Mines and the various unions and associations, it is valuable briefly to examine some of the pivotal issues colouring this years discussions.<BR><P>
<B><Center>THE NEED TO BETTER UTILISE WORKING TIME</Center></B><BR><P>
The groundwork was laid during last years negotiations for the establishment of methods to optimise available working time - a fundamental facet of improving productivity levels. The SA mining industry is highly capital intensive and needs to address the demands of reducing pay limits. To this end it is important that every day be utilised to its utmost, without entailing a necessity that employees work more hours than at present.<BR><P>
Central to this endeavour are the twin issues of Full Calendar Operations (or Fulco) and dealing with the not-insignificant jump in the number of public holidays with which the mining industry has had to deal in the past 18 months. By Fulco we mean the opportunity to utilise every day of the year to maintain production on mines - an opportunity which is currently denied us through the statutory prohibition of blasting or working on Sundays contained in Section 9 of the Mines and Works Act. Mines which have been able to negotiate with employees to gain their support for Fulco, have had to apply to the Minister of Mineral and Energy Affairs for exemption from this prohibition. Mines which have succeeded in this have met largely with highly favourable results. <BR><P>
The central issue for the industry, however, is our belief that this restriction is wholly inappropriate for our times, not to mention the specific and serious circumstances facing especially the gold mining industry.<BR><P>
These straits are further compounded by the fact that we have to cope with no fewer than 12 statutory paid public holidays in terms of the new Public Holidays Act.  This has placed an inordinate burden on mining, which, prior to January 1 last year, only had to cope with four holidays. The situation also has an added barb in that the act stipulates that, where a public holiday falls on  a Sunday, the Monday immediately following shall be a holiday - as will be the case this coming weekend!<BR><P>
It has, therefore, become increasingly vital that management and labour co-operate with due haste to find mutually acceptable means of ensuring that each day is utilised to the fullest degree - and then to approach government to remove counter-productive and outmoded restrictions. As the Chamber of Mines, we are highly optimistic this can be achieved, and the indications from mine-level would seem to support our optimism. The agreement reached with the NUM (National Union of Mineworkers) last year regarding two-tier bargaining - and possibly substantiated by the bargaining councils envisaged in the LRA - holds great promise in support of this view.<BR><P>
<B><Center>OPTIMAL UTILISATION OF HUMAN RESOURCES</Center></B><BR><P>
Mining in SA - especially gold mining - will remain labour intensive, and we have to develop our human resources if we are to increase productivity. This is a sine qua non. It is wholly unrealistic to expect labour to achieve its side of the tripartite equation without providing each employee with every opportunity to maximise his or her potential.<BR><P>
Already, widespread and meaningful mine-level initiatives and educational programmes are being implemented to provide a wide range of skills. These efforts have been supported by industry framework agreements signed between the Chamber and NUM on Adult Basic Education and Training (ABET) last year, and Paid Education and Training Leave (PETL) this year. These programmes provide vital skills ranging from adult basic education, through career development, supervisory and technical skills training to multi-tasking and training aimed at equipping mineworkers for life outside mining in the event of retrenchment. <BR><P>
Attendant issues with human resource optimisation include the appropriate and effective implementation of  affirmative action programmes, the hands-on implementation of the provisions of the Mine Health and Safety Act (MHSA) and the development of the Mining Qualifications Authority (MQA) in the context of the larger National Qualifications Framework (NQF).<BR><P>
Of particular significance to management is the maturity and sophistication of the relationships which have been built between management and labour in our industry. We have been able to forge some of the most sophisticated agreements in the world thanks to this fact. As we face this years round of negotiations, tough though they undoubtedly will be, we can rest assured that what will emerge will be as much a benchmark agreement as were those which preceded it.<BR><P>

<B><Center>CONCLUSION.</Center></B><BR><P>
In his budget speech to the Senate last month, outgoing Minister of Mineral and Energy Affairs, Pik Botha, stated the following: "South Africas gold mining sector, for long the backbone of the mineral industry and the economy, is facing major challenges. It has become a mature industry, increasingly forced to mine lower grades at greater depths and greater distances from the shafts. South African gold industry costs have consequently become the highest anywhere.<BR><P>
"Minings contribution to the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) declined from 15,4% in 1986 to 7,7% in 1995. The contribution of mining to total merchandise exports likewise declined from 60% in 1986 to 43,5% in 1995. Average employment in the mining industry fell from 828 000 to 596 000 during the same period."<BR><P>
But then he went on to say - and I venture to extend his words beyond gold mining to other sectors of the industry as well - Minister Botha told the Senate: "The gold mining industry has faced and weathered difficult conditions before. With government, management and labour pulling together, the necessary adjustments can be achieved." - and this is the point I wish to communicate today.<BR><P>
With co-operation and commitment by all three stakeholders and the joint efforts of management and labour, especially at mine level, this industry can rise to a position of even greater economic, social and internationally competitive pre-eminence in South Africa - and indeed in Sub-Saharan Africa.<BR><P> 


<P>
<a href="main.htm"> <img src="/nb1.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Main Menu" hspace=20></a>
