HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 17-Feb-97 03:35:27 GMT
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>The Chamber of Mines Speeches</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000080">
<p align=center><img src="/wd1.gif" align=middle width=32 height=31><br>
</p>
<h3 align=center><font size=5><b>PEOPLE AND PROFITS: SAFETY AND QUALITY.</b></font><br>
by the<br>
<font size=4><b>PRESIDENT OF THE CHAMBER OF MINES OF SOUTH AFRICA,<br>
MR A.J. &quot;AT&quot; DU PLESSIS</b></font><br>
at the <br>
1996 SUB-SAHARAN OIL &amp; MINERALS CONFERENCE<br>
Johannesburg, 10 June 1996<br>
</h3>
<p align=center><img src="/line3.gif" align=middle width=590 height=2><br>
</p>
<p align=left>Given that there remains an abundance and wide variety of unmined mineral deposits in South African soil, the single most 
important imperative for their successful and profitable future extraction will be the availability of suitably equipped people. 
That they be suitably equipped is a critical criterion because the business of mining demands a unique set of qualities and 
talents that are not the natural possession of all individuals.</p>
<p>Mining in South Africa - and particularly gold mining which will more than likely remain the country&#146;s major earner of foreign 
exchange for many years to come - is most commonly conducted in arduous conditions thousands of metres below ground. It 
has always been labour intensive and in spite of impressive capital intensive technological innovations that have been 
productively introduced over the years, there is no compelling evidence to suggest that the operational profile of south african 
mining is about to be radically changed.</p>
<p>People will continue to be the industry&#146;s pre-eminent asset.</p>
<p>That much accepted, the fundamental challenge that confronts industry leadership - if continuing viability is to be ensured - is 
to forge flexible and constructive partnerships with employees which are designed to optimise performance in a working 
environment that is both acceptable and beneficial to all industry stakeholders.</p>
<p>Much progress in achieving this objective has already been made. However, it is a broad-based, multifaceted process that 
demands ongoing attention. It will almost certainly result in considerable revision of existing work-place practices as well as 
changes to remuneration policies that traditionally have been followed.</p>
<p>The consequences of failure to co-operatively re-engineer outdated work practices and conditions are unappealing. They 
include premature mine closures and substantial job losses. But contrary to what is believed by some people, the mining 
industry&#146;s objective is to refrain from putting even one employee on the street if it can be prevented. Finding the means to 
prevent job losses will require the co-operation and participation of all role players.</p>
<p>Positive advances that have previously been effected in the endeavour to enhance the productive capacity of the mining 
industry&#146;s human resource constituent, have been the outcome of the sophisticated collective bargaining structure that has 
evolved over a period extending back to the discovery of gold on the Witwatersrand more than 100 years ago. For some time 
- specifically during the 1980s - the relationship between employers and employees was diluted by the understandable 
introduction by the National Union of Mineworkers of a political dimension to the negotiation process. Political demands 
brought to the table fell outside the competence of employers to deliver. They were nevertheless regarded as an essential 
component of the process by NUM representatives who assumed the dual responsibility of articulating the political objectives 
of their disenfranchised constituents as well as their work-related demands.</p>
<p>The reason for this adulteration of the classic labour/capital relationship is well known. Apartheid era unions were the only 
legitimate institutions for the expression of a much wider range of social and political aspirations. The political intrusion was 
significant. It brought to the process - most certainly in the mining industry - a robustness and vigour which sharpened 
negotiation skills and propelled the bilateral relationship to a level of maturity that would otherwise have taken much longer to 
accomplish.</p>
<p>It is on that foundation that the existing association between mining industry employers and the NUM, by far the biggest of 
several industry unions, was constructed. With the advent of democracy in our country the political heat has been removed 
from the equation. Today&#146;s priority rests firmly in the domain of agreeing the work-related fundamentals to ensure that the 
industry continues to provide jobs for hundreds of thousands of people while simultaneously maintaining its role as a national 
creator of wealth.</p>
<p>The additional participant in determining the success of this endeavour is government.</p>
<p>While employers and employees may well negotiate mutually beneficial conditions and agreements, their practical efficacy 
could easily be inhibited by unfriendly statutory decree. South Africa&#146;s new democratic government is currently engaged in a 
comprehensive statutory review. Because it is a microcosm of South African society, there is very little legislation which does 
not impact, directly or indirectly, on the mining industry. The present review process provides useful opportunity for the 
amendment of laws which detrimentally affect the mining industry&#146;s capacity to operate at its most effective level. There are 
several such enactments and they are receiving attention in various tripartite forums.</p>
<p>The most recent and by far the most significant product of tripartite deliberations insofar as mining is concerned, is without 
doubt the new draft Mine Health and Safety Act. Predictably, because it is the creation of the characteristic give-and-take 
activity of a negotiation exercise, the proposed act does not enjoy the unconditional acceptance of all parties. It contains some 
elements clearly forged in a spirit of compromise.</p>
<p>All things considered, however, there is a belief that the provisions of the new Act - once promulgated and introduced - have 
the potential to deliver a safer working environment for mining industry employees. There is nothing more important for 
although mining - wherever it is pursued - is a potentially hazardous business, the sanctity of human life must always take 
precedence over all other objectives. If the new safety provisions significantly reduce the South African mining industry&#146;s 
fatality and injury rates - figures which it is conceded are unacceptably high - then they will most certainly earn the 
well-deserved recognition of being probably the most constructive legislative enactments in the industry&#146;s history.</p>
<p>Time will be the judge of the new Act&#146;s effectiveness.</p>
<p>Whether it works or not will also be determined to some considerable extent by the degree to which management and 
employees are prepared to commit themselves to the spirit of the Act. The new provisions give employees considerably more 
authority and say than they have had in the past to exercise a judgment on the safety of the working environment. They also - 
in their existing composition - place awesome emphasis on management&#146;s responsibility to ensure that working conditions, 
particularly underground, are not life-threatening.<br>
</p>
<p>What is clearly required to underwrite the successful implementation of the new Act is the kind of constructive partnership, or 
compact, between management and employees which I referred to earlier. There can be no doubt that democratisation of the 
workplace is the logical attendant of the democratic transition that has transformed wider South African society. Employees 
must - indeed will - become a far greater participative component in the determination of business imperatives.</p>
<p>There is, however, a <i>quid pro quo</i>.</p>
<p>In the same way that democratic society grants rights but imposes obligations, workplace democracy requires 
co-responsibility in exchange for participation. This concept - although it has extensive application potential - is particularly 
significant in the areas of safety and productivity in the underground working environment. It is imperative that employees 
exercising their right to help compose the rules governing safe work practices, be correspondingly obliged to accept 
responsibility for ensuring their own and their colleagues&#146; adherence to those rules.</p>
<p>Furthermore, it is necessary for labour and employers to adopt a fully co-operative approach to improve productivity. The 
time has come, not only to reconstruct and develop our country, but through the development of people and adherence to 
their need for houses and other social infrastructure, also to reconstruct and reorganise business operations aimed at insuring 
maximum employment and optimal utilisation of ore reserves to compete internationally and create wealth for every individual 
involved in the business of mining.</p>
<p>Minimising the threat to life and reducing injuries through the creation of a safer working domain in the mining industry can 
contribute to the realisation of these objectives. Experience demonstrates that a safe working environment is more often than 
not far more productive than one perceived to be dangerous. As a result productivity profiles on mines with low accident rates 
are consistently superior to those of mines with a higher incidence of casualties.</p>
<p>What this clearly implies is that there is an association between safety, productivity and ultimately, profit. It is, therefore, in the 
interests of all mining industry stakeholders to promote the improvement of safety standards.</p>
<p>In South Africa, as well as other third-world countries on the African continent, the task of enhancing safety - and hence the 
profitability of an enterprise - is an exercise far removed from approaches adopted in first-world economies. Most mining 
industry employees in South Africa and neighbouring countries are drawn from disadvantaged communities. They have not 
been the beneficiaries of well-structured primary and secondary educational facilities. The few that have been exposed to a 
reasonable level of scholastic instruction were - in many instances - prevented from developing to their full potential by 
apartheid laws which compelled employers to retard their progress to a comparatively menial level on the hierarchical ladder. 
Senior positions were reserved for people with white skins.</p>
<p>The mining industry consistently opposed the statutes that inhibited human resource development during the previous era. They 
are now, thankfully, dispatched to the annals of history. But they have left our country - and indeed the mining industry - with 
an unfortunate legacy. There now exists in South Africa a considerable number of people - many of them working in the 
mining industry - with abundant productive potential but deprived of the developmental progression to perform at optimal 
capacity.<br>
</p>
<p>This is a condition that the mining industry will not condone. It acknowledges its responsibility to develop to their maximum 
possible potential both the educational and the operational capabilities of its employees. This is done in the knowledge that 
there is no other way to improve the quality of the lives of our employees and their dependants and to maximise the generation 
of profits for our shareholders and other stakeholders including the fiscus.</p>
<p align=center><a href="main.htm"><img src="/nb1.gif" alt="Main Menu" align=middle border=0 hspace=20 width=60 height=17></a> <a href="#top"><img src="/nb2.gif" alt="Top of Page" align=middle border=0 hspace=20 width=60 height=17></a> <a href="#toolbar"><img src="/nb3.gif" alt="Toolbar" align=middle border=0 hspace=20 width=80 height=17></a> <br>
<br>
<br>
<a href="/org1.htm"><img src="/tb101.gif" alt="organisation" align=bottom border=0 width=101 height=17></a> <a href="/res1.htm"><img src="/tb102.gif" alt="Resources" align=bottom border=0 width=101 height=17></a> <a href="/kruger.htm"><img src="/tb104.gif" alt="Krugerrand" align=bottom border=0 width=101 height=17></a> <a href="/new.htm"><img src="/tb105.gif" alt="What's New?" align=bottom border=0 width=101 height=17></a> <a href="/info.htm"><img src="/tb106.gif" alt="Contacting us" align=bottom border=0 width=101 height=17></a> <br>
</p>
<hr>
