HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 17-Feb-97 03:36:18 GMT
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Chamber of Mines Speeches</TITLE><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000080">
<center><IMG SRC="/wd1.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><br>

<h3><B><FONT SIZE=5>BUDGET SPEECH</FONT></B><BR>
by the<BR> 
<B><FONT SIZE=4>MINISTER OF MINERAL AND ENERGY AFFAIRS<BR>
Mr. R F (PIK) BOTHA</FONT></B><BR>
in<BR>
The Senate<BR>
Tuesday 14 May 1996<BR></h3>



<IMG SRC="/line3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><br><p></center>


<Center></Center>

The new South Africa recently celebrated its second birthday on 27 April 1996.  We call the birthday of our now-democratic state, Freedom Day.  And so it should be.  South Africa has achieved freedom:  freedom from discrimination, freedom for all to play their part in selecting who shall govern over them, and freedom for anyone to participate in that government.<BR><P>
But there are other freedoms still to be achieved.  Freedom from poverty, hunger and fear.  Freedom from the violence of crime.  Freedom from ignorance and disease.  Freedom from the hostilities, divisions and wounds of the past.<BR><P>
The mining, minerals and energy industries in South Africa have an essential role to play in increasing and expanding these freedoms.  Whatever their defects may have been, these sectors form the foundation of our economy.<BR><P>
Imagine where South Africa would be had there been no minerals, no entrepreneurs to develop them or no miners to mine them.  Imagine a South Africa without our electricity infrastructure.<BR><P>
In 1996 we will be completing South Africas minerals and mining policy process as well as our energy policy process.  As regards the mining policy process, a trilateral Steering Committee of government, the mining industry and organised labour, is managing a transparent and inclusive mining policy review.  The Committee has drawn up and distributed a discussion document on minerals and mining policy.  Later this year a first draft will be published and then a final policy position paper.<BR><P>
The position with energy is similar.  There too a discussion document has been drawn up and we are expecting a draft and then a final white paper.<BR><P>
The process is intended to provide policies in each sector that will demonstrate excellence due to the widespread sources of the inputs as well as a high degree of credibility and acceptance.<BR><P>
Major issues dealt with in the policy process include making our business and investment terms even more internationally competitive.  This will provide the resources we need to improve education, health services, combat crime and reduce unemployment.  For the same reasons we need to promote greater access to the mining industry while at the same time guaranteeing security of tenure.<BR><P>
There are many who have it as their ambition to establish small-scale mining operations.  Some of our major mining houses have taken this seriously.  They have looked through their portfolios and are prepared to identify and make available resources which lend themselves to smaller scale operations.  Others should follow their example.<BR><P>
There is in some quarters a concern that small miners will not have the capacity to comply with the prescribed mine health and safety measures or with environmental requirements.  They often lack the financial resources or the expertise to fulfil what is required.  But the basic point still remains stubbornly valid:  we need to create opportunities for as many of the smaller operators as are prepared to take them up.  We can find ways and means of ensuring acceptable standards of health, safety, environmental protection and competence.<BR><P>
Our other ambition is to provide an effective service to those from South Africa or abroad who seek to pioneer or run a substantial mining venture.  The state owes them an administrative system that speedily and effectively supplies them with what they need.  Mine promoters and managers deserve prompt and accurate advice and information from the Department of Mineral and Energy Affairs and its associated organisations.<BR><P>
South Africas mineral industry will also have to consolidate initiatives to improve working conditions as well as considering workers, their families and the communities in which it operates.  Housing, training, recreation, health services - in short the improvement of the quality of life - have all been improving in recent years.  This parliament is busy enacting a Mine Health and Safety Bill that is in line with the latest international developments.  The Bill has already passed its second reading in the other place and it will be debated here next week.  Our health and accident statistics will hopefully show that the new law and the new Inspectorate are having an effect.  It is essential that Inspectorate salaries are commensurate with those in the private sector.  We can have the best laws in the world, but unless those that police them are vigilant and effective and rewarded as such, we will remain with sterile words on a statute book.<BR><P>
South Africas gold mining sector, for long the backbone of the mineral industry and the economy, is facing major challenges.  It has become a mature industry, increasingly forced to mine lower grades at greater depths and greater distances from the shafts.  South African gold industry costs have consequently become the highest anywhere.<BR><P>
Minings contribution to the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) declined from 15,4% in 1986 to 7,7% in 1995.  The contribution of mining to total merchandise exports likewise declined from 60% in 1986 to 43,5% in 1995.  Average employment in the mining industry fell from 828 000 to 596 000 during the same period.<BR><P>
The gold mining industry has faced and weathered difficult conditions before.  With government, management and labour pulling together, the necessary adjustments can be achieved.  Improvements in technology may yet play a greater role than we anticipate.<BR><P>
In addition there are other imperfections in our mining and elsewhere.  Although the country commands good technology and skills, the base is too narrow, leading to a shortage of skilled manpower with a large supply of unskilled labour.  South Africas expenditure on research and development falls short of what is required to keep the country competitive internationally.  The high cost of capital limits development of large mechanised mines and beneficiation plants, required to achieve economies of scale and international competitiveness.<BR><P>
The mineral industrys high concentration of economic power makes it difficult for foreigners to gain meaningful access.  However, recent Japanese investments in South Africas ferroalloys industry show that joint ventures can be successful.  The limited and fragmented availability of information about South Africas mining and regulatory structure is also cited as a weak point.  This is in the process of being rectified by implementing the recently approved new structure of my Department.<BR><P>
Unrealistic demands in respect of the environment and social commitment in some cases threaten to impose financial burdens on the mineral industry in excess of those applicable to our competitors.  A balanced and pragmatic approach needs to be adopted.  Of course we need to protect the environment and provide economic and other encouragement for those who need it.  But we must be realistic enough not to destroy the source which enables us to protect our environment and care for our less privileged.  In that case our last state will be worse than our first.<BR><P>
Due to the vastness of some of our resources - manganese, the platinum-group metals, chromium, vanadium - South Africas production is not related to its reserves.  This leads some to charge that reserves are being sterilised.  But companies take these decisions on the basis of what they can sell.  Forcing companies to bring reserves to account would lead to destructive internal competition, as chrome once showed.  International markets for these minerals are generally small in relation to our resources.  Even small supply increases can destroy prices.  The whole country would lose.<BR><P>
From the above, it might seem that the industry is not doing that well.  This is an oversimplification.  South Africa remains a major producer, in world terms, of many minerals.  She dominates the worlds treasure chest in andalusite, chromium, gold, manganese, the platinum-group metals and vanadium.  The country is in the worlds top five for antimony, asbestos, coal, diamonds, fluorspar, nickel, phosphate rock, titanium, vermiculite, zinc and zirconium, with significant reserves of copper, iron, lead and uranium.  The only mineral imports of note apart from crude oil are alumina, coking coal, magnesite, potash, soda ash, sulphur and tin.<BR><P>
There are several reasons why the South African mineral sectors apparent decline is not what it may seem:<BR>
<B>Firstly, </B>77% of South Africas total mineral revenue by value comes from exports.  Even though many mineral commodity prices have recovered during the last few years, most prices have shown a long term downward trend.  Minings shrinking share of the GDP also reflects lower international prices.<BR><P>
<B>Secondly, </B>the misfortunes of the gold sector - gold production fell from 619 tons in 1993 to 522 tons in 1995 - mask the fortunes of the rest of the industry.  The contribution of gold sales to total mineral sales may have declined from 69% in 1986 to 53% in 1995, but coal production increased from 176,7-million tons in 1986 to 204,3-million tons in 1995 and its exports increased from 46,9-million tons to 59,7-million tons.<BR><P>
<B>Thirdly, </B>the decrease in employment is also a reflection of improved efficiencies.  Employment opportunities have been lost by right sizing, productivity improvements and mechanisation.  In the gold mining sector, tons of ore milled per employee increased from 202 in 1986 to 262 in 1995.  In the coal sector, tons mined per employee increased from 1 827 in 1986 to 4 128 in 1995.<BR><P>
<B>Fourthly, </B>South Africas mineral industry has been undergoing a process of adjustment.  The important question for a successful economy is how to remain a winning nation after an original competitive advantage - mining in this case - has lessened.  Much of South Africas physical and financial infrastructure and its secondary industries were developed on the back of mining.  The Physical infrastructure - roads, railways, electricity and telecommunications - is extensive and of a good standard.  The financial infrastructure, required for the development of capital-intensive mineral-related industries, is world class.<BR><P>
South Africas energy costs, due to its coal, are of the lowest in the world.  This favours energy-intensive mineral beneficiation projects.  South Africa also boasts world-calibre mineral-related research institutions - Mintek, the Council for Geoscience, the AEC and the CSIRs Miningtek.  South African minerals graduates have proven themselves all over the world.  South Africa is an international leader in mining and mineral beneficiation, as well as developing competitive related industries like mining machinery and mineral processing plants.<BR><P>
Economic competitiveness is being built increasingly on technological and skills advantages.  For decades now, the terms of trade have been in favour of producers of manufactured products rather than of raw materials.  This underlines the importance of technology development, and South and southern Africa are no exceptions.<BR><P>
Whereas the contribution of the mining industry since the 1950s has been declining, that of manufacturing has been increasing.  Much of this growth in manufacturing has been mineral-based, consisting of value-adding activities.<BR><P>
This throws a different light on the role of mining and minerals in the GDP, foreign exchange and employment.<BR><P>
As countries develop industrially, the products required change to those requiring less traditional metals and minerals.  The need for environment-friendliness and the willingness to pay a higher price for longer-lasting products has changed metal and mineral requirements.  The use of traditional metals and minerals has lessened, leading to overproduction and increased competition on world markets.  This, in turn, has caused the long-term weakening of real mineral prices.  Technology came to the rescue of mineral producers, allowing them to keep on operating profitably.  These trends are expected to continue, balanced to an extent by accelerated growth in the developing economies.<BR><P>
Current and planned investment projects in South Africa show a preponderance of mining and mineral-based undertakings.  Of these, primary mining projects amount to R15,5-billion and mineral processing projects to R22,3-billion.  Potential projects amount to another R4,9-billion and R12,2-billion, respectively.  Gold, coal and platinum mine expansions form the bulk of the primary developments, except for the Namakwa Sands and recently announced Nkomati nickel and Palabora underground copper projects.  Mineral processing projects include Columbus Stainless, Iscor Stainless, Alusaf, Hulett Aluminium, Saldanha Steel, various ferroalloy plants and the downstream processing of Sasol products.  Some exciting projects possibly on the horizon include zinc smelters, an aluminium smelter in Mocambique, offshore natural gas and oil deposits, the Gamsberg zinc deposit in the Northern Cape and various developments at Phalaborwa.<BR><P>
In the light of this and the imminent implementation of investment friendly and efficient minerals and mining policies and legislation, South  Africas mineral industry will continue to play a major role.  It will be vital in the earning of foreign exchange, the creation of employment and as a base for further industrial development.<BR><P>
This is true not only for South Africa, but for the whole of the subcontinent.  Many of the new projects announced for neighbouring and other African states also involve mineral-related developments, often with South African participation.  The synergies between us and our neighbours will lead to economic growth in the whole region.<BR><P>
Energy services are necessary to fulfil basic needs such as cooking, warmth and light, and as an input to productive economic sectors such as industry, mining, commerce, agriculture and transport.  South Africa has a modern, well-developed and intensive energy sector, employing about 250 000 people.  It is to a large extent coal-based and only 15% of energy in the form of crude oil is imported.  These imports represent nearly 10% of the value of total imports.<BR><P>
Many of our citizens still do not understand how the monthly adjustments in fuel prices are effected.  The petrol price goes up when its international price goes up - in other words when there is a greater demand for it than can be supplied.  It also goes up when our rand goes down against the dollar, because we pay for our crude oil in dollars.  So the extra money goes to those who sell the oil and the dollars to us, not to the government.<BR><P>
We can be thankful that we have a Sasol that produces about a third of our liquid fuels inside the country.  We can also be thankful that we have oil companies here who refine oil inside the country.  If this were not so, all the money we spend on liquid fuels would be sent overseas.<BR><P>
From some perspectives, the mid-1990s are a dark time for the world energy system.  Oil consumption is approaching the record levels of the late 1970s, with demand in some countries growing at rates as high as 10% per year.  Even the use of coal is still expanding in many nations, pushing emissions of carbon dioxide, the leading greenhouse gas, to more than 6-billion tons per year.  Emissions are growing particularly rapidly in China and India, but even the United States and Canada are failing to hold carbon dioxide emissions steady as they are supposed to under the Rio Climate Convention.<BR><P>
Although most energy analysts view such trends as convincing evidence that the world energy system wont change anytime soon, the reverse may be true.  Today, three major forces of change are bearing down on the world energy economy - new technologies, industry restructuring, and tougher environmental policies - all of which are likely to be intensified by the danger of climate change.<BR><P>
We are in for an interesting time as far as our national energy scene is concerned.  There is a new energy policy process which will probably result in a new Energy Act by next year, there is a restructuring of the electricity distribution sector and in a few years time there will probably be competing suppliers of electricity;  the liquid fuels sector is eagerly awaiting the report of the Lambrechts Committee on the sectors restructuring and we have to be ever-mindful of renewable energy sources.<BR><P>
<P>
