<title>The Chamber of Mines Speeches: UNCTAD / Africa Connect Conference</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000080">

<p align="center"><font color="#800040" size="5"><b>UNCTAD /
AFRICA CONNECT CONFERENCE</b></font></p>

<p align="center"><br>
<font color="#006231" size="4"><b><i>JOHANNESBURG, 2-4 MAY 1996</i></b><br>
<b>OFFICIAL OPENING</b><br>
</font></p>

<p align="center"><font color="#0000A0" size="4"><b>ADDRESS BY </b></font><a
href="/cvs/main.htm"><font color="#0000A0" size="4"><b>MR TRN
MAIN</b></font></a><font color="#0000A0" size="4"><b> <br>
CHAIRMAN, ICC-SOUTH AFRICA</b></font> </p>

<p align="center"><br>
</p>

<hr size="4" noshade width="90%">

<p><br>
</p>

<p>Mr Chairman, Madam Minister, Ladies and Gentlemen,</p>

<p>On behalf of the South African Council of the International
Chamber of Commerce, I would like to welcome the UNCTAD and
Africa Connect participants to our country. It is indeed an
honour for us to co-host such a prestigious event and I would urge
all of you to make the most of your visit to South Africa - in
terms of absorbing the spirit of change in the country and contributing
to our growth and prosperity by parting with large sums of money!</p>

<p>It is appropriate that this conference should be convened at
such a critical moment in South Africa&#146;s transition. We have undergone
one of history&#146;s most remarkable political transformations
that has become a global icon for democracy and conflict
resolution. The welcome political reforms have thrust South
Africa firmly into the next phase of democratic consolidation as
it begins to address the imperatives of sustainable growth and
development.</p>

<p>This phase will be characterised by South Africa&#146;s full
readmission to the international political economy and the
country&#146;s efforts to deal with the pace, depth and breadth
of change that is sweeping the globe, especially in the area of
international trade. South Africa&#146;s future will, to a great extent,
be determined by its success in re-integrating with the global
economy. However, we need to recognise that South Africa forms
part of a community, and as such, requires the assistance of a
wide range of global partners, including international
organisations and national governments. </p>

<p>Imperative for Africa, including South Africa, is the
confidence that international trade policy is being pursued in
terms of both growth and development objectives to ensure that
the trade conditions in the early part of the century are not
repeated. Indeed, it is our firm conviction that an equitable and sensible
world trade regime will contribute immeasurably to alleviating global
poverty and dissolving the artificial and harmful North-South
polarisation.</p>

<p>The liberalisation of trade and investment requires - apart
from significant tariff cuts and a reduction or elimination of quantitative
restrictions - a period of strong growth and low inflation which
should have a positive impact on external debt.</p>

<p>The WTO and UNCTAD have committed themselves to jointly
increasing technical assistance efforts. The overall objective of
this approach is collaboration between trade policy and trade promotion
experts to assist developing countries - and especially the least
advantaged amongst them - to integrate themselves effectively
into the multilateral trading system in a meaningful way.</p>

<p>The International Chamber of Commerce is committed to serving
world business by promoting trade and investment in an open
international political economy sustained by entrepreneurial
private enterprise, self regulation and the free movement of goods,
services, capital and labour. </p>

<p>The ICC was founded in 1919 and represents thousands of
companies and business associations in 139 countries. National Committees
throughout the world convey ICC views to their respective governments
and co-ordinate policy issues with ICC headquarters in Paris. The
ICC maintains close relations with international organisations,
intergovernmental and non-governmental bodies and has permanent
representatives to the UN in New York and Geneva to monitor
developments affecting business.</p>

<p>The South African Council was constituted in 1958 and
represents employer organisations as well as independent
companies. As we re-enter the global economy and grapple with the
demands of uncompromising international competition, the South African
Council will provide a vital facility for exchanging views and
addressing concerns. Most importantly, ICC-South Africa will
encourage South African business to remain sensitive to the
demands and trends of the global economy.</p>

<p>I would briefly like to touch on developments in the South
African economy and the most important issues facing Africa from a
business perspective.</p>

<p>South Africa is undertaking a comprehensive review of its
policies covering almost every aspect of commercial activity. The review
is, to a considerable extent, a consequence of the rigidities and inefficiencies
induced by Apartheid. In addition, South Africa has returned to a
markedly different global economy to the one it isolated itself
from so many years ago. As if this is insufficient, those responsible
for reforms need to mould them in a manner that gives constant
cognisance to the legacy of underdevelopment in South Africa.</p>

<p>Consequently, the task of reform is being driven by two
imperatives - the need to comply with the provisions of the Marrakech
Agreement and the need to achieve sustainable growth and development.
The world we have re-entered has reduced national policy options
amid greater demands for international compliance, especially in
terms of the global trade regime. Consequently, South Africa will
have to manage its reconstruction and development in a context of
diminished national sovereignty.</p>

<p>However, this is not a condition to be feared. Indeed, we
welcome the challenges thrust upon us. However, it is critical
that the correct decisions are taken to ensure that
reconstruction and development is meaningful and sustainable -
the margin for error in policy-making has been reduced dramatically
in the last two decades. Given this reality, we are cautiously
optimistic that the government is pursuing enlightened policy
reforms that will assist South Africa to develop into a truly world-class player,
for that should be our sole objective in the new world order.</p>

<p>South Africa&#146;s trade relations with the rest of Africa
have developed spectacularly although we should be concerned that
the direction of flows has been somewhat singular. While this is
a function of the market rather than South African hegemony, we are
acutely aware of the need to develop strong reciprocal trade
flows throughout Africa and we look forward to mutually beneficial continental
growth and development.</p>

<p>Unfortunately, the current national and international
environments are not entirely conducive to that end. It is
imperative that African countries integrate themselves more
effectively into the global economy by pursuing policies that are
aligned with international trends. Similarly, Africa needs access to
new markets and improved access to existing markets. The
increasing use of informal protectionist trade measures must be
strongly condemned because of the multiple impacts on developing countries.
The world&#146;s future is a common one and the benefits that
arise from a unitary perspective will be delayed by parochial
national and regional interests.</p>

<p>It is worth reflecting for a moment on the major issues
confronting Africa which include:<br>
</p>

<ul>
    <li>poverty alleviation; </li>
    <li>commodity dependence; </li>
    <li>technology transfer; </li>
    <li>implementation of the Uruguay Round Agreements, including
        mitigation of the adverse effects and benefiting from trading
        opportunities; </li>
    <li>dealing with future trade negotiations and new issues; </li>
    <li>attracting foreign direct investment and promoting
        enterprise development - FDI can be viewed as the primary
        motor of globalisation. Trade and investment are not
        merely complementary but also increasingly inseparable as
        two sides of the same coin in the process of
        globalisation; </li>
    <li>policy issues relating to debt and its management; </li>
    <li>capacity-building, including trade efficiency; </li>
    <li>economic co-operation among developing nations; and </li>
    <li>development of the service sector. </li>
</ul>

<p>The Marrakech Agreement launched wide-ranging trade reform and
will thus expose previously protected manufacturing and service
sectors to the rigours of competition.</p>

<p>UNCTAD IX provides an exceptional opportunity to pursue the
dialogue on development and international co-operation in the
spirit of genuine partnership between the relevant organisations, including
the WTO, UNCTAD, ECA and OAU to promote and facilitate the
integration of African countries in the new global economy.</p>

<p>This parallel event, &quot;Africa Connect&quot;, provides an
excellent opportunity to move the debate forward through
multilateral co-operation and first-hand participation by the
business community.</p>

<p>Global economic integration and the liberalisation of trade
affect opportunities for all countries. Technological advances,
the increased mobility of production factors, as well as the
enlargement of economic areas, following the successful
conclusion of the GATT Uruguay Round, set the basis to develop
prospects of unprecedented gains of wealth creation.</p>

<p>We trust that both the UNCTAD and Africa Connect proceedings
will be fruitful and ground-breaking. We wish you every success
in your endeavours and trust that South Africa will forever
retain a special place in your hearts.</p>

<p>Thank you.</p>

<p align="center"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="1">TRN5_96-Africa
Connect.doc<br>
Wednesday 24 April 1996<br>
Timothy Wood</font><br>
