<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Chamber of Mines Speeches</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000080">
<center><IMG SRC="/images/save.gif"> <L1><A HREF="FinProj.pdf">Download</A> Keynote Address by Mr TRN Main (PDF 95k) <IMG SRC="/images/save.gif"> <br><p>
<IMG SRC="/images/wd1.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><br>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=800040><b>KEYNOTE ADDRESS</b></FONT><P>
by <P>
<FONT SIZE=4><a href="/cvs/main.htm">Mr TRN Main,</a> Chief Executive of the Chamber of Mines of South Africa</font>, <br>
<p>at the Financial Times Gold Conference, Marriott Hotel, London.<br>
<i>Tuesday, 25 April 1995</i><p><br>
<img src="/images/linegr.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><p>

<FONT SIZE=4 COLOR=006262>FINANCING MINING PROJECTS IN THE EMERGING MARKETS<br>
WITH SPECIAL REFERENCE TO MINING OPPORTUNITIES<br>
IN SOUTH AND SOUTHERN AFRICA
</FONT><p>

<img src="/images/linegr.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><br><p>

<FONT SIZE=4 COLOR=800040><B>CONTENTS</B></FONT></CENTER></center>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#INTRO">Introduction</A>
<li><A HREF="#NEW">New Mining Projects</A>
<ul>
<li><A HREF="#CENTRAL">Central Questions</A>
<li><A HREF="#RISK">Risk Considerations</A>
</ul>
<li><A HREF="#FINANCING">Financing Mechanisms</A>
<ul>
<li><A HREF="#HOUSES">Mining Finance Houses</A>
<li><A HREF="#SMALL">Small Mines</A>
<li><A HREF="#GROUP">The Group System</A>
<li><A HREF="#GOLD">Gold Loans and Hedging</A>
<li><A HREF="#JOINT">Joint Ventures</A>
</ul>
<li><A HREF="#OPPORT">Mining Opportunities in South Africa</A>
<li><A HREF="#CAPITAL">Capital Expenditure</A>
<li><A HREF="#STATE">State of the South African Mining Industry</A>
<li><A HREF="#CONCLUSION">Conclusion</A>
</ul>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
Mr Chairman, Ladies and Gentlemen,<p>

<A NAME="INTRO"></A>
<B>INTRODUCTION</B><br>

It is indeed a pleasure to have been invited to address such an important conference on a subject that is very pertinent to the South African mining industry and to South Africa today.  You are no doubt all aware of South Africas recent history and its transformation into a new democracy.<p>

The emergence of South Africa's new order has been miraculous for a number of reasons.  Most notable, is that it was accomplished in the space of four years, a relatively short time if one considers the widely differing political stances that had to be harmonised to reach consensus.<p>

The net result has been promising. The new political management appears to be on the right track and obstacles are slowly being overcome.  The mining industry believes that its own wide-ranging expertise, especially in the fields of housing, health care, education and training will be of great benefit to our Reconstruction and Development Programme (RDP), the chief objective of which is to meet basic human needs.<p>

Mr Chairman, in addressing the subject at hand, I shall present a potted overview of our experiences in financing new ventures on a large scale and some other financing methods pioneered outside of South Africa which could well become more important in the coming years.  Integrated into my summary will be some indication of the prospects for mining in the Southern part of the continent.<p>

But before I do so, let me say that for more than a century the mining industry has been the foundation of the South African economy - and will be so well into the next century.  Today, the industry, despite many serious challenges, remains robust, energetic, more innovative than ever and, despite its age and maturity, still possesses the capacity to be a reliable economic generator and wealth creator for the country and many of its neighbouring states, such as Lesotho, Mozambique and Swaziland.  Last year, for instance, the mining industry generated over 60% of South Africas foreign exchange earnings, through exports of primary and beneficiated mineral products.  We play an important role in the Johannesburg Stock Exchange (JSE) and indeed, although South Africa is now classified as an emerging market, a much more accurate description would be a re-emerging market.<p>


<A NAME="NEW"></A>
<B>NEW MINING PROJECTS: PRELIMINARY CONSIDERATIONS</B><br>

<A NAME="CENTRAL"></A>

<B>Central Questions</B><br>
Since the termination of the cold war, financing mining projects in the emerging markets has become intensely objective.  Historical bi-polar political constraints have largely been excised from investment decisions and tough market forces are now driving the new wave of mining projects.  Nowhere is this more apparent than in the emerging markets, including Sub-Saharan Africa, where there have been astounding mineral code revisions in recent years in response to market pressures and the realisation that socialist policies have been a dismal failure.<p>

These revisions reflect a truism that I believe now governs mining investment, namely, the need for an adequate risk-return relationship in a market economy.  Quite simply, new mining investment is moving to those areas where the return is greater than the perceived risk.  The most successful emerging markets, in new mining investment terms, are those that have positively addressed their risk profiles.<p>

This mining investment truism might be more precisely defined by four critical questions:
<ol>
<li>Is the mineral rights policy conducive to entrepreneurial activity?
<li>Is there a secure transition from exploration to development?
<li>What is the projects comparative advantage that makes it especially attractive?
<li>Will the return on investment compensate for the risks?
</ol><p>

<A NAME="RISK"></A>
<B>Risk considerations</B><br>
The above questions will be answered by a consideration of risk.  Mining projects are perhaps unique in that they avoid trying to manage risk after the initiation of the project.  Instead, an attempt is made to reduce the apparent initial risks as far as possible.  This is rare in the sense that mining investors demand the best environment before a project can commence.  <p>

A countrys risk profile will equate to an evaluation of certain preconditions that dictate new investment decisions.  I believe we can broadly categorise mining investment risk into three distinct but interdependent aspects, namely:
<ul>
<li>socio-political risk;
<li>marketing risk; and
<li>financial risk.
</ul>

<I>Socio-political risk</I><br>
Socio-political risk is largely intangible but nevertheless central to any new project consideration.  In the past, certain countries in Southern Africa have exemplified volatile socio-political risks that have inhibited new mining investment and affected the competitiveness of the mining industry as a whole.<p>

A stable political and social order does not imply a preference for authoritarianism but rather, good governance.  Good governance will be reflected in a countrys ability to create wealth through economic growth, particularly where it attracts new foreign investment.  This will be more pronounced in the emerging markets where development backlogs must be overcome.  <p>

Indeed, the distributive prosperity of sustainable growth has become the key feature in the reduction of socio-political risk in any country.  The ability to achieve prosperity through growth depends largely on an holistic treatment of risk.<p>

<I>Marketing risk</I><br>
Marketing risk is predominantly a consideration of a countrys openness to international markets and willingness to engage in commercial exchanges.  <p>

Mining investors take cognisance of leverage abilities brought about by economies of scale.  To this end, marketing risk will examine a countrys degree of outward-oriented trade, focusing on the exchange rate and level of protection.<p>

Domestic access to international markets magnifies economies of scale and reduces input cost structures, a central consideration in any mining project.  Similarly, resource allocation and the cost of capital, labour and production is forced to respond to the stimulus of international competition in order to survive and become attractive to new investment.  There are also marked knowledge transfers in favour of developing countries.<p>

These competitive responses reduce the investors risk exposure by making product deliveries timeous and cost competitive.  A reduction in marketing risk is also likely to enhance downstream beneficiation prospects, allowing specific mining ventures to expand into value-added clusters at source.  The development and growth implications of reducing marketing risk to both emerging markets and mining investors cannot therefore be ignored.<p>

<I>Financial risk</I><br>
Financial risk is the most important determinant of the three risk areas because the other areas are dependent on its soundness and effectiveness.  Indeed, financial risk reflects the most stringent preconditions for investment generally but more especially for capital intensive mining projects.<p>

Financial risk measures macroeconomic stability from the point of view of its impact on capital costs and production efficiency.  Quoting an IMF model, "a stable macroeconomic environment is one where inflation is low and predictable, the exchange rate is near its equilibrium level, the government budget is well managed, the deficit relative to GDP is at a reasonable level and consistent with a non-increasing ratio of public debt to GDP, and the use of central bank credit to finance the deficit is kept at a minimal level" .<p>

These are not arbitrary performance measures but are significant risk indicators that impact on an investors long-term planning capacity which is imperative for capital intensive mining ventures.  As South Africa takes its place in the international community again, the Reserve Bank, in response to macro-imperatives, has shifted its emphasis from dampening cyclical upswings to maintaining domestic price stability.  This has considerably reduced planning risks in the consideration of new mining projects.<p>

Increasingly, emerging markets are conforming to the international macroeconomic standards quoted above and this is stimulating global mining investment, not least in Africa.  South African mining finance houses have expanded exploration activity in Africa substantially because of macroeconomic stability rather than just an end to sanctions.  For example, just last week one of our gold mining groups announced exploration projects underway in Burkina Faso, Mali, the Ivory Coast, Ghana and Senegal , consolidating the rapid internationalisation of our mining operations.<p>

This reiterates my observation that mining investment has shed any reliance on non-market incentives and that new projects reflect rigorous analysis and approval of a countrys risk profile.  A staggering number of emerging market countries have revised their mineral codes in the last 5 years and the benefits of doing so are abundant.  South Africa is also in the process of revisiting its minerals policy, hopefully to ensure an attractive environment to encourage new mining investment, somewhat belatedly I might add in view of the progress made by our African neighbours.<p>


<A NAME="FINANCING"></A>

<B> FINANCING MECHANISMS</B><br>

Clearly, there is no single best method of financing mining projects.  Experience shows that ventures are financed according to a broad range of factors and very often there is an amalgam of methods to produce the desired result which is to bring an orebody to profitable account.<p>


<A NAME="HOUSES"></A>

<B>Mining Finance Houses</B><br>

Financing mining projects in emerging markets is of course a problem that pertained to the South African mining industry almost from inception in 1852 when the first systematic attempts were made to recover copper in the Namaqualand region of the old Cape Colony.  The discovery of large scale deposits of alluvial diamonds along the Vaal, Harts and Orange Rivers some 15 years later added further impetus to the establishment of a stock exchange and the first rudimentary mining houses.  The mining houses developed out of sheer necessity, especially during the late 1880s and the early 1890s.  They remain in many ways peculiar to South Africa, although similar transnational institutions have and are emerging in other countries.

<p>
The mining finance houses emerged to bridge the immense problems associated with deep-level mining.  Mines and companies formed partnerships to overcome poor communications and rudimentary physical infrastructure, consolidate financial resources and make the ventures attractive to cautious foreign investors.<p>

These early partnerships and companies were the precursors of the Group System or "mining houses" as they are known today.  They continue to provide capital and expertise for the development of new mines and for the expansion, development and management of their member mines.<p>

The mining finance house flourished in South Africa largely because of our system of mineral rights.  Unlike most other countries, South African mines operate within fixed lease areas and do not enjoy blue-sky potential.  This means that each mine has finite reserves and usually cannot undertake new projects of its own accord.  Thus the mining houses play a crucial role in establishing new mining opportunities.<p>

In time, the role of the mining house has increased in importance.  Because mining is a high-risk, capital-intensive industry, mining houses have found two dependable sources of finance to open new mines - foreign capital and the re-investment of retained profits.  Local banking was, and still is, incapable alone of sustaining the industrys financial needs to any degree, the risks attached to deep level mining being too extensive.  As a consequence, large-scale mining ventures in South Africa have been equity reliant rather than debt based.<p>

The mining houses operate by absorbing all risk associated with a project in the initial stages of exploration, feasibility studies and shaft sinking.  This has the effect of minimising the risks for both individual and institutional investors.  It also serves to re-assure investors that the venture has the backing of a reputable organisation.  To this end, the houses function as their own bankers, making prospective public fund raising very attractive indeed.<p>

Once a project nears production, public funds are raised progressively to provide the additional capital required for the project.  Funds raised are usually in the form of equity finance, either directly by way of shareholders capital or by way of shareholders loans.  This is usually accompanied by a subsequent rights issue to enable completion of the project.  During the mines lifetime, the mining house reduces its share in the mining company in order to realise its original risk capital and secure profits for new ventures.<p>

Though the primary motivating force for establishing mining houses was to muster financial resources, a secondary but equally important consideration was to provide scarce managerial and technical skills.  Small mining companies simply could not afford to employ highly qualified mining engineers and other experts with specialist skills to manage the risks involved over the long lead times to production and as the gold mines became deeper and deeper, with all the inherent problems resulting from such circumstances.  <p>

Instead mining houses started using a streamlined system whereby various managerial and technical services were provided to member mines by a limited number of consultants employed by a mining house.  Even today the link between the mining company and the mining house is by way of the number of shares the latter owns and a contract to provide managerial, buying, taxation, secretarial, technical and other services; services an individual mine may well not be able to afford or would not wish to fund where such visible economies of scale are available through the mining house.<p>

The system has proved highly cost effective and efficient, as some other mining countries have found.  Many more of our marginal mines would have closed down long ago - or much sooner than they did - had it not been for the backing and expert guidance they received from a mining house.  The management contract system principally enables mining houses to buffer individual mines against unexpected external shocks which might otherwise destroy them.  The implications for a country with a vast reservoir of unskilled labour, such as South Africa, are fairly obvious.<p>

It was inevitable that mining houses, as they grew, would contribute to the creation of South Africas infrastructure on a massive scale.  Besides spawning major cities and towns in remote and often desolate parts of the country, South Africas railway system, power supplies, explosive and timber industries and its burgeoning coal mining industry can all find their roots in the demands and requirements of the gold mining industry, as can the sophisticated legal and financial institutions.  <p>

It was, I suppose, inevitable that surplus resources would be re-invested by mining houses in secondary and tertiary industries and, indeed, in major industrial undertakings.  Even in the field of health and medical care the industry has done more than its share, administering scores of hospitals, as well as innumerable clinics, first-aid posts and rescue stations strategically located on gold, coal and other mineral mines.  The Rand Mutual Hospital, an associated company of the Chamber of Mines, is counted among the best trauma hospitals in the world.  Mining houses are therefore unique South African institutions which can bridge the gap between the mature and established part of our economy, and that part of our economy which remains underdeveloped.<p>

Essentially, mining houses are no different from large companies that have characteristics related to the particular field in which they operate.  Their characteristics include:
<ol>
<li> The availability of large financial resources,
<li> A preference for large projects when making new investments,
<li>The control of investments on a centralised basis from their head offices, and
<li>The vertical integration of the operations when new investments are made, as is the interaction between the operations.
</ol>

<A NAME="SMALL"></A>

<B>Small Mines</B><br>
Equity based financing is not confined to large projects although the complexity of South African mining conditions generally mitigates against viable small mines. Historically, as Dr Willo Steer, a South African geological consultant, has pointed out, junior mining companies, by virtue of their entrepreneurial character, have an impressive international record of finding and initiating new mines. Major mining corporations, with their substantial financial and technical resources, have often been an important source of development capital for these small ventures - but usually at the expense of a large equity dilution and the loss of control by the discoverer.<p>

In South Africa, small mining companies and entrepreneurs have not enjoyed the same confidence among investors as do the large groups.  Financial institutions have been reluctant to fund smaller companies, mainly because they do not have the mechanisms to monitor such ventures.  The relatively small investments involved often also do not yield a growth rate which is attractive to interest-performance driven portfolio managers.<p>

An example of a small, independent mining venture making use of equity financing is the Amalia Gold Mine to be listed on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange in June 1995.  Amalia is situated in South Africas Northwest Province and is exploiting a shallow orebody.  This has allowed a very favourable ratio between projected working costs and profit, making the mine a viable and attractive investment.  To illustrate the scale of operation in comparison to a typical mining house project, which requires almost £170 million  to initial production and £1 billion over a normal lifetime, Amalia will be developed from an equity issue of just £2,1 million.<p>

Such small ventures up to the present have, however, been the exception.  The available orebodies for such projects currently appear to be relatively limited in South Africa although there are inevitably exciting opportunities for entrepreneurs.  The mining houses are reassessing their mineral rights holdings in an endeavour to create viable small mine opportunities where feasible.  The state of course holds extensive mineral rights and will need to do the same.  <p>

Also, the cost of a listing is disproportionately high for small share issues and the domestic market may not have sufficient liquidity or risk capacity to support numerous small-scale ventures.  One must also take into account the exposure of small mines to external shocks from which they may not be able to rescue themselves.  The ability of small mines to generate substantial capital for exploration and development, especially simultaneous regional or international exploration, is also limited and negates self-regeneration.<p>

Another negative consequence of small-scale mining is that entrepreneurial operations may only function to extract the best ore grades, resulting in considerable waste and an unnecessary reduction in a mines ore reserves.  Mining finance houses are able to overcome this pecking out the eyes syndrome through large-scale projects that enjoy some pay-limit flexibility.<p>

<A NAME="GROUP"></A>

<B>The Group System</B><br>

In South Africa, more than 100 mines are closely linked financially and administratively to one or other of the major mining houses.  They are further linked through membership of the Chamber of Mines, a private enterprise voluntary employers organisation and the industrys central co-ordinating body.  The Chamber provides a valuable and convenient vehicle for its members to act in concert when and where they deem it both prudent and desirable.  The Chamber provides services to the mines and the mining houses but is not involved in prospecting, financing or managing mines in any way.  <p>

It formulates industry policy on matters of general concern assigned to it by its members and it serves as the advocate of that policy to the general public and at the interface with government and organised labour.  The Chamber is playing an important role in the new South Africa trying to secure for the mining industry a supportive political, economic and social environment so that it can operate efficiently and effectively.<p>

From what I have said it is clear that South Africas mining houses are well placed to assist in developing mineral resources in South Africa itself, in neighbouring states and, indeed, in the rest of Sub-Saharan Africa.  They have the technical and financial expertise, know-how and experience to operate under Africas unique conditions.  They also have the financial muscle, although much of the capital needs for these developments will need to be drawn from the countries themselves, the International Finance Corporation and other international capital markets and sources.<p>

Countries in which South African mining houses are already involved include Zambia, Mozambique, Zimbabwe, Angola, Tanzania, Congo, Zaire, Kenya and in West Africa, in particular Ghana and the Ivory Coast.  Much of the basic exploration has already been done, or is being done, with South African-based companies well to the fore and international investors are bound to take this into account when expanding their investment portfolios into Africa.<p>

<A NAME="GOLD"></A>

<B>Gold loans and hedging</B><br>

Australian banks pioneered the shift away from equity based finance to gold loan finance in the 1980s.  This was as a result of the then high cost of capital.  Typically, real interest rates in this period exceeded 10 per cent whereas gold could be borrowed at below 5 per cent.  Gold loan financing was dramatically encouraged by the collapse of the stock markets in 1987 and the inability thereafter for some time to raise large sums of equity finance.  This came at a time, too, when Central Banks were seeking opportunities to obtain some income from their extensive gold reserves.<p>

Gold loan financing is categorised by two typical processes: physical gold loaned is sold at spot prices to finance immediate exploration and development costs while future production is sold forward to underwrite the cost of the loan and the interest attracted.  Im sure that the analogy to a share and rights issue will not escape you.  Gold loans reached their apogee in 1988 when former RTZ analyst Jessica Jacks estimated that almost 4.8 million ounces of gold were loaned .  To date, it is estimated that 260 contracts involving 12.9 million ounces have been brokered.  <p>

The advent of gold loans provided a window of opportunity for the banks involved and many of them became de facto mining finance houses providing almost identical services to such companies.  This was extremely beneficial to entrepreneurial mining ventures who were able to access tailored, off-the-shelf packages.  In some cases, Australian open pit gold mines were in production within six months.  A massive boom in gold loan financed mining ensued in Australia and the United States although this was tempered by the availability of cheaper capital in the early 1990s and a decline in interest rates.<p>

The most interesting derivative, if you will forgive the pun, of gold loan financing was the formalised use of hedging which the bullion banks insisted on to reduce their risk exposure.  The effect of hedging forward sales from gold loans was initially to depress prices in the physical gold market as companies sought to counter their exposure to possible lower prices over the long term.  Hedging, in its many forms, has helped certain companies to realise higher returns than the prevailing average prices.<p>

Today, there are few world-class mining companies without a hedging programme in their treasuries.  Although critics regard the paper gold market to be partially responsible for the sideways movement in the gold price in recent years, hedging has provided the means for certain ore bodies to be brought to profitable account and to sustain marginal mines through low-price and high-cost cycles.<p>

<A NAME="JOINT"></A>

<B>Joint Ventures</B><br>

Newly revised mining codes have paved the way for state-owned mines to be privatised.  This is taking place all across Africa and Latin America with considerable success.  Usually, projects are existing mines that were nationalised after independence or initiated by the state under the tutelage of foreign advisors.  Invariably the ventures became unproductive and were sustained through subsidisation in the form of grants or aid.<p>

Privatisation typically involves the sale of a state-owned project, or portion thereof, to a private interest.  Financing is then raised using a combination of methods.  An interesting approach has been a combination of debt and equity financing which is used to rejuvenate the mine and return it to profitability.  In terms of debt financing, a low-interest loan was secured from the International Finance Corporation and the State was also persuaded to put up some of the required funds.  Equity financing was achieved by an international share offer to investors.  The net result has been unusual co-operation between private sector interests, the State and international organisations such as the IFC.<p>


<A NAME="OPPORT"></A>

<B>MINING OPPORTUNITIES IN SOUTH AFRICA</B><br>

South Africas mineral reserves, other than gold, are enormous.  To name but a few:
<ul>
<li>Almost 59 000 metric tons or 88% of the worlds platinum group metals,
<li>Almost four billion tons or 83% of manganese deposits,
<li>Over three billion tons or 72% of chrome ore,
<li> Over 12 million tons or 44 % of vanadium,
<li> Still 44% of the worlds recoverable gold,
<li> Almost 51 million tons or 37% of alumino-silicates,
<li>Some 80 million tons or 40% of vermiculite, and
<li>Over 15 million tons or 26% of zirconium minerals.
</ul>

And these figures do not include our recoverable coal deposits of 55 billion tons - enough to meet our domestic needs for 300 years!  Or our five million tons of lead, almost six billion tons of iron ore and 13 million tons of copper.<p>

Coming back to gold, according to geological estimates there is an equivalent amount of gold left in South African soil as has been mined to date - about 44 000 tons.  Subject to the market price, the most conservative projections suggest that at least 18 000 tons of refined gold can still be viably recovered at present, unless, of course, new and more cost effective systems are developed.  A number of new gold mines - estimates of up to 15 have been mentioned - in excess of 4 000 metres deep with estimated 30 year life spans, have been identified for development if circumstances are advantageous.<p>

<A NAME="CAPITAL"></A>

<B>CAPITAL EXPENDITURE</B><br>


Business confidence has, not unexpectedly, soared since South Africas return to the "real" world.  Investor confidence is reflected in the recovery of Gross Domestic Fixed Investment, dominated by investment in new capacity for exports, and in the strength of the Johannesburg Stock Exchange.  A secondary tax on companies, intended to encourage re-investment of corporate profits, has also promoted the fixed investment cycle.<p>

Projects valued at some R95 billion (£16,4 billion) have been identified for expenditure by the end of 1996.  No doubt there are many more. Some 22 per cent or R20 billion (£3,4 billion) - R11,8 billion (£2,0 billion) already announced and another R8,6 billion (£1,5 billion) on possible projects - has been earmarked for mining projects.  Of this, R12 billion (£2,1 billion) has been directed at gold mines, R2,3 billion (£396 million) at platinum mines and R6,2 billion (£1,1 billion) at "other" mining ventures, such as coal, mineral sands and vanadium, among others.<p>

The gold mining industry has projects already underway totalling some R7,6 billion (£1,3 billion).  With one exception, these projects involve expansion programmes on existing mines, although in the case of Vaal Reefs gold mines Moab expansion, an entirely new mining lease area is being developed.  Gencors Oryx gold mine, which started in 1988, is the only "new" gold mine and has already absorbed some R1,3 billion (£224 million) in capital expenditure.<p>

Most of the R2,3 billion (£396 million) earmarked for platinum mining is regarded as replacement spending.  The announcement recently of a new platinum-based catalyst for controlling vehicle exhaust emissions will no doubt be a tremendous boost for the industry.  The effect has already been felt on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange.<p>

Of the R2,2 billion (£379 million) to be spent on "other" mining, R560 million (£96,5 million) has been earmarked for expansion of Khutala Colliery, a major domestic utility supplier and exporter, R110 million (£18,9 million) in a phlogopite plant, a form of mica rich in magnesium, and R1,4 billion (£241 million) for the development of the Namakwa Sands project mining zircon, ilmenite and rutile.<p>

<A NAME="STATE"></A>

<B>STATE OF THE SOUTH AFRICAN MINING INDUSTRY
</B><br>
Public policy is currently a central issue which is being vigorously addressed by the Chamber of Mines.  The Chambers main purpose is to engage influential organisations and individuals, particularly from the executive and legislative arms of government, in debate to emphasise the mining industrys role in the national economy and its capacity to create wealth.  In our view, the industry should be as free and unfettered as possible to deliver the assets that will help enrich the whole country and all its people.<p>

We are sure of a reasonable degree of success, especially as the advantages of a free market become more apparent - and appreciated. In fact, we are extremely encouraged by the way the Government of National Unity is using modern business methods to carry out its Reconstruction and Development Programme.  In the end, economic prosperity, unlike economic ruin, cannot be achieved through legislation; social progress, unlike social decline, cannot be created by regulation.<p>

The mining industrys requirements are simple: a sound, market-based economic system, a stable political environment, meaningful efforts to combat crime and lawlessness, a steady and predictable system of taxation which reflects the fact that we turn to account non-renewable assets, incentives to advance technology and a sufficient portion of distributable profits to be returned to shareholders.  We think these are eminently reasonable requirements.<p>

There are now sufficient signs that we are well on our way to achieving these needs.  As far as the central government process is concerned, there have been important improvements, especially in regard to the transparency of, the accountability by, and the accessibility to, those who govern.  Parliamentary Portfolio Committees now sit in public and have commenced their efforts with wide interpretations of their briefs and have created a dynamic policy-making environment in which there are seemingly no holy cows.<p>

The new political management is, in my view, on the right track and the obstacles are being overcome.  We are able to engage policy-makers meaningfully and we are delighted at the degree to which stakeholders, such as business, labour and others, are encouraged to participate in shaping policy.  Participative management has become the central theme of our Government of National Unity.<p>


<A NAME="CONCLUSION"></A>

<B>CONCLUSION</B><br>

Mr Chairman, Ladies and Gentlemen, I trust that I have sufficiently whetted your appetites for the detailed perspectives to be given by my fellow speakers whom I have no doubt will provide not only critical but fascinating insights into their specialist fields.<p>

I also hope that I have conveyed to you my sense of optimism about South Africa generally and our mining industry particularly.  South Africans have demonstrated a remarkable resilience and determination to resolve problems throughout our current and past history.  No other country has achieved what we have and I believe that we will remain a unique global icon for democratic transformation.<p>

This same resilience and persistence is apparent in our mining industry.  Although we face significant challenges in the years ahead, none are insurmountable or unresolvable.  We believe that mining is the flywheel of South Africas Reconstruction and Development Programme and we are committed to eradicating the distortions and inefficiencies that plagued us in the past.  Indeed, South Africa has responded vigorously to its new international status and we are in the process of a comprehensive review of our competitive standing in the world.  Potential investors can be assured that South Africa is fast becoming a choice location with an ever improving risk profile.<p>

Thank you.<p>

