<h3>Address by Mr At du Plessis,<br>President of the Chamber of Mines of South Africa and <br>Chairman of the Collieries Committee<br>on 15 March 1996, at Kriel Colliery<br> to the<br></h3>
<h2><b>1996 Coal Safety and Health Seminar<br></b></h2>
<IMG SRC="/line3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><br><p></center>



<U><B>SUMMARY</B></U><BR><P>

<A HREF="#over">BRIEF OVERVIEW OF THE SA COAL MINING</A><BR> 
<A HREF="#prod">PRODUCTIVITY</A><BR>
<A HREF="#gaz">SOME CRYSTAL BALL GAZING</A><BR>
<A HREF="#trust">TRIPARTISM AND TRUST TEMPERED BY REASONABLY PRACTICAL MEASURES
OTHER ISSUES</A><BR>
<A HREF="#red">REDUCTION OF CASUALTY RATES</A><p><p>


<A NAME="over"></A>
BRIEF OVERVIEW OF THE SA COAL MINING SITUATION<BR>
Henry Ford, as we know, was famous for introducing the motor vehicle production-line from which initially rolled many thousands of the now legendary Model-T automobile.  He was also famous for rolling off his tongue certain sayings, with perhaps the most famous of them being: "History is more or less bunk!"<BR><P>

History, whether "bunk" or not, is not always pleasant.  There are notable exceptions however, such as the complete turn-around of an industry like ours in the short space of 18 months.  It is particularly pleasant  when one is able to stand in front of a group of delegates such as yourselves and report that the positive historical trend has continued, and moreover, continues to exceed predictions.<BR><P>

Despite fierce competition on the international market, South African coal exports grew to a record level of some 60 million tons in 1995.  Contract and spot prices levelled after the initial strong 63 per cent growth in spot prices.  Our exports last year realised over 6 billion Rand in foreign exchange.  Coal, after gold and the platinum group metals, remains South Africas largest export.  South Africa was the second largest exporter of seaborne steam coal in 1995 after Australia with us continuing to supply our traditional markets in Europe and the Far East.  Of concern however is that though for 1995 our contract prices were negotiated up by 23 per cent on 1994 levels in US dollar terms, in real Rand terms the contract price for 1995 remained lower than 1992 levels.   (These contract price figures are historically based on the benchmark contract prices paid by ENEL, the giant Italian power utility.)  Spot prices in the Amsterdam-Rotterdam-Antwerp market were the highest they have ever been since 1990.<BR><P>

<A NAME="prod"></A>
PRODUCTIVITY<BR>
On the other hand, in 1995 the industry was hard-pressed to improve productivity and I believe that there still remains considerable potential for productivity improvements in our industry when you consider that productivity, based on tons mined per employee per annum.  Other countries, like Australia and the USA are leading the way.<BR><P>

<A NAME="gaz"></A>
SOME CRYSTAL BALL GAZING<BR>
Mr Ford did however not let his indictment of history stand on its own ... he expanded somewhat on his theme.  The full text of what he said reads as follows: History is more or less bunk.  Its tradition.  We dont want tradition.  We want to live in the present and the only history that is worth a tinkers damn is the history we make today.  I agree with Henry Ford ... we dont want tradition, we want change - but not change for the sake of change but to improve!  I would go so far as to say that what matters even more than the history we make today is where we are going in the future.  And we are to a degree fortunate in having a pretty good idea of what lies ahead of us, at least in the short- term and I would like to expand on this right now.  I will however not deal with prices and markets as you have your ideas about the future.<BR><P>

The government  views coal mining as being very important to South Africa and this was emphasised in no uncertain terms by government in the last four weeks when, as President of the Chamber of Mines, I met with senior parliamentary personalities, particularly the Minister of Mineral and Energy Affairs, Minister 'Pik' Botha, and vice-president Thabo Mbeki.  We laid our cards on the table and they were equally frank with us and in discussion certain issues were identified as being critical to mining in the years to come.<BR><P>

Prime amongst these was the issue of a revised minerals policy.  Though it would be dangerous to predict its outcome, what we do know is that there is certainly lots of sympathy at present for the small mining concept.  Of particular significance was governments desire to attract black investors to this sector and also its aim of encouraging greater black investment into the existing sector.<BR><P>

What we however fight against is not the concept of small mines but the idea expressed in some circles to ease environment and safety regulations for the small miner.  The security of mineral rights and prevention of the implementation of a minerals right tax were also high on our list.<BR><P>

Increased exports are seen as being critical and government is fully aware that our existing export facilities are already under pressure.  These facilities will have to expand and there is a distinct possibility that this will take place with the probable assistance of overseas investment.  Here again Minister Pik Botha indicated to us on Monday that he is busy with discussions on this issue.<BR><P>

Significant decreases in job opportunities and foreign income capacity will also lead to the interference of government in our business in future.<BR><P>

<A NAME="trust"></A>
TRIPARTISM AND TRUST<BR>
Of greater significance to you all at todays conference however is governments increasing emphasis on health and safety issues in the mining industry.  It was made abundantly clear to me during my visit to parliament, that if we want to get it right we have to include all role players, which in mining terms means, government, management and labour.  Or in other words, tripartism.  Some Ministers are even making noises that they are not willing to see employers alone (for example, through the Chamber of Mines), but only to agree to meetings where employers and employees are together.<BR><P>

For tripartism to work properly though, it has to rest firmly on four pillars, namely trust, participation, reason and compromise.  If one of these pillars is shaky, tripartism itself will wobble and eventually fail. This brings me back to what I said when I opened the Mine Safety and Health Congress at the end of November last year.  I stated then that it was of the utmost importance that parties do not adopt fixed and immovable positions.  The tripartism pillar of compromise should not be threatened.  However I am glad to say that there have been positive moves already in this direction as we have heard today.  By the same token, parties that publicly and destructively attack each other during tri-partheid discussions will break down trust.  Trust is, I contend, perhaps the most important of the tripartism pillars.  I heard Anthony Gill of the Mine Safety Division saying something similar earlier.<BR><P>

I make specific reference to a rather contentious clause in the Mines Health and Safety Bill.  This clause we argue conflicts not only with the recommendations of the Leon Commission but also with the basis of our legal system, and may even be deemed unconstitutional. Essentially, it deals with the reversal of onus - or being assumed guilty until proved innocent.  When this issue was first raised it was made very clear to me that if something went wrong on a mine the responsible people would have to face the consequences, and added to this was the rider that "if the unions dont get you, government will."  What worth tripartism if this is the level of trust?<BR><P>

REASONABLY PRACTICAL MEASURES<BR>
Let me hasten to add that mine management has however not been altogether unfairly treated in this regard.  It falls squarely on your shoulders to make sure that you have taken all reasonably practical measures - and the Bill refers specifically to measures having to be adjudged reasonably practical - to protect the health and safety of your employees.  Negligence, if it is proved that you did not take reasonably practical steps to prevent a negative occurrence, will - as it should - be dealt with severely.<BR><P>

<A NAME="other"></A>
OTHER ISSUES<BR>
There are of course other issues facing the industry, such as the new Labour Standards Act which replaces the Basic Conditions of Employment Act, and the introduction of full-time safety stewards.  The mining industry will have to deal with these and many more issues in the near future.  The introduction of these proposed changes if contained in the new Acts will definitely lead to an increase in costs.<BR><P>

<A NAME="red"></A>
REDUCTION OF CASUALTY RATES<BR>
As already said, mining remains the mainstay of South Africas economy and therefore whatever we do - or dont do for that matter - will come under the spotlight.  We cannot afford to be anything but squeaky clean in whatever we do. The fact remains that our casualty rates, rather than the measures being taken to bring them to zero, receive prominence.  The media takes pleasure in publicising our less than flattering safety record, and the only way we can prevent being caned like this is by dramatically improving our safety record.<BR><P> 

However, you have already begun taking the right steps, adopting the right attitude and what you have learned today I am sure will result in further improvement.  You have set as your goal "Zero Fatalities".  After all, if you hope to achieve something worthwhile there is no point in taking a half-hearted stab at getting there ..... you have to go all out, to go for broke, in that way making your chances of getting there so much better!  Or, as your newly adopted slogan puts it so neatly, "Go for Goal."<BR><P>

Attaining that magical, but so elusive, zero fatality rate - is a goal certainly worth getting.  I am confident that just as on the football field your chances of scoring are increased the more often you shoot at the posts, or you Go for Goal, the more often you shoot for a zero fatality target, the better your chances are of hitting it.  If last year 31 coal mines managed to achieve zero fatalities, I see no reason why the rest of the 44 collieries that participate in the Chamber of Mines safety competitions cannot follow their example.<BR><P>


