<p align=center><b><u>ANNEXURES<br>
</u></b></p>
<ol>
<li><a href="#ANNEXUREA">ANNEXURE A : CONTRIBUTIONS IN RESPECT OF THE MPF AND MABS FOR 1996/97</a></li>
<li><a href="#ANNEXUREB1">ANNEXURE B1 : AGREEMENT IN RESPECT OF BLYVOORUITZICHT GOLD MINING COMPANY LTD </a></li>
<li><a href="#ANNEXUREB2">ANNEXURE B2 : AGREEMENT IN RESPECT OF EAST RAND PROPRIETARY MINES LIMITED</a></li>
<li><a href="#ANNEXUREB3">ANNEXURE B3 : AGREEMENT IN RESPECT OF HARMONY GOLD MINING COMPANY LTD</a></li>
<li><a href="#ANNEXUREB4">ANNEXURE B4 : AGREEMENT IN RESPECT OF DURBAN ROODEPOORT DEEP LIMITED</a></li>
<li><a href="#ANNEXUREB5">ANNEXURE B5 : AGREEMENT IN RESPECT OF DOUGLAS COLLIERY</a></li>
<li><a href="#ANNEXUREB6">ANNEXURE B6 : AGREEMENT IN RESPECT OF GOLD MINES ADMINISTERED BY JCI LIMITED</a></li>
</ol>
<p align=center><a name="OLE_LINK1"><font size=4><b><img src="../images/linegr.gif" align=bottom width=402 height=5></b></font></a> </p>
<p><a name="PREAMBLE"><b><u>PREAMBLE</u></b></a><b><u><br>
</u></b>WHEREAS the NUM sent to the Chamber a letter dated 2 May 1996 containing the NUM's proposals for the 1996 review 
of wages and other conditions of employment for members of the NUM employed in recognition units for which the NUM is 
recognised by gold mines and collieries that are members of the Chamber (&quot;the 1996 review&quot;); and<br>
</p>
<p>WHEREAS meetings have subsequently taken place between representatives of the NUM and the Chamber and the parties 
have reached agreement on the 1996 review<br>
</p>
<p><b>THE PARTIES THEREFORE AGREE AS FOLLOWS:<br>
</b></p>
<p>1. <a name="APPLICATION"><b><u>APPLICATION</u></b></a><b><u> OF AGREEMENT<br>
</u></b>1.1 Subject to 1.2, this Agreement shall apply to all members of the NUM employed in recognition units for which the NUM 
is recognised by gold mines and collieries that are members of the Chamber. <br>
</p>
<p>1.2 Annexure B4 hereto shall apply to Durban Roodepoort Deep Limited. <br>
</p>
<p>2. <b><u>RESTRUCTURING THE MINEWORKERS PROVIDENT FUND (</u></b><a name="MPF"><b><u>MPF</u></b></a><b><u>) AND THE MINEWORKERS 
ASSURANCE AND BENEFITS SCHEME (MABS)<br>
</u></b></p>
<p>2.1 <b><u>Preamble<br>
</u></b>The parties acknowledge and recognise that there are historical disparities in the provision of retirement, death and funeral 
benefits within the mining industry. Retirement funds for the majority of white miners have long been established with 
membership of such funds restricted in terms of the job reservation policies of the day. The closed shop enjoyed by the former 
whites-only unions also resulted in exclusions. Racial inequalities have been and are being addressed. These inequalities cannot 
be addressed without the implementation of practical steps to correct the past by changing the future.<br>
</p>
<p>2.2 <b><u>Equity<br>
</u></b>The parties recognise and acknowledge the need to restructure all existing industry retirement funds (Mine Officials Pension 
Fund, Mine Employees Pension Fund, Mineworkers Provident Fund). In the context of the restructuring of the MPF and 
MABS, the parties agree to the following principles of equity which should be worked towards: <br>
</p>
<p>2.2.1 Contribution levels for the various restructured defined contribution funds within the mining industry should be on parity. <br>
</p>
<p>2.2.2 Equity should prevail with regard to the basis of calculation of contributions to the restructured retirement funds in the 
industry. <br>
</p>
<p>2.2.3 The restructured MPF/MABS fund should be opened to all permanent workers of participating employers of the Fund.<br>
</p>
<p>2.2.4 Membership of the Chamber should not be a pre-condition of the restructured MPF/MABS fund. The trustees of the 
Fund will consider each application on a case by case basis in order to protect their fiduciary responsibilities.<br>
</p>
<p>The parties further agree that they will endeavour to achieve 2.2.3 and 2.2.4 above by July 1997.<br>
</p>
<p>2.3 <b><u>Restructuring of MPF/MABS</u></b></p>
<p>The MPF and MABS require urgent restructuring and consequently the parties agree as follows:<br>
</p>
<p>2.3.1 MPF and MABS will be merged by 1 July 1997, with the longer term objective of minimising the cost of death and 
funeral benefits, and enhancing retirement benefits. Hence the contribution allocation for retirement benefits will be a minimum 
of 75% of each of the total employer and total employee contributions respectively. <br>
</p>
<p>2.3.2 The merged Fund will be a defined contribution fund for retirement, death and funeral benefits. The trustees of the Fund 
will restructure the benefits accordingly.<br>
</p>
<p>2.3.3 The combined contribution level to the merged fund should be 20% calculated on the current basis applicable to MPF 
at the date of this agreement. This will not apply in cases where an agreement on higher contribution levels is in existence at the 
date of this agreement or where additional voluntary contributions are made by employees.<br>
</p>
<p>2.3.4 The parties accept that in the interim, the increase of 0,610% in contributions to MABS on 1 August 1996 will be paid 
for as set out in Annexure A.<br>
</p>
<p>2.3.5 The contribution levels for 1996 and 1997 are set out in the schedule attached as Annexure A.<br>
<br>
</p>
<p><b>3. </b><b><u>FRAMEWORK AGREEMENT ON INDUSTRIAL RELATIONS RELATED EDUCATION AND 
</u></b><a name="TRAINING"><b><u>TRAINING</u></b></a><b><u><br>
</u></b>3.1 The parties agree in principle to the joint development at Group or mine level, or in the case of Gold Fields, mines at a 
Group co-ordinated level, of industrial relations training relating to the new Labour Relations Act, health and safety legislation, 
workplace efficiency and mine level industrial relations procedures. The target population for such education and training 
should be formally elected union representatives. Such education and training should be jointly reviewed.<br>
</p>
<p>3.2 The parties agree that the development, presentation and running costs of the jointly agreed Education and Training 
Programmes will be financed by individual employers. It is the intention of Anglo American (Gold Division) to utilise the 1987 
Strike Settlement Fund for this purpose.<br>
</p>
<p>3.3 The modules of the education and training should as far as possible be accredited.<br>
</p>
<p>3.4 All information relevant to the discussions between the parties on the development and presentation of courses will be 
disclosed between the parties.<br>
<br>
</p>
<p>4. <a name="PATERNITY"><b><u>PATERNITY</u></b></a><b><u> LEAVE<br>
</u></b>In regard to paternity leave, the parties agree that the number of days of unpaid leave to which employees are entitled shall be 
increased from three days per annum to seven days per annum. All other conditions relating to paternity leave as agreed upon 
in the 1994 Wage Review shall remain unchanged. </p>
<p>5. <b><u>PAID LEAVE FOR REPRESENTATIVES ON </u></b><a name="TRIPARTITE"><b><u>TRIPARTITE</u></b></a><b><u> FORUMS<br>
</u></b>5.1 The parties agree in principle that duly appointed principal representatives on the tripartite bodies enumerated in clause 
5.2 should be granted paid leave for the purpose of attendance at meetings of those bodies, provided that:<br>
</p>
<p>5.1.1 the NUM undertakes that its representation on the bodies referred to will be such that no undue burden for the 
provision of leave to representatives will be placed on any one mine;<br>
</p>
<p>5.1.2 application for leave shall be made to management in respect of each specific meeting to be attended and approval shall 
be granted subject to operational requirements; and<br>
</p>
<p>5.1.3 the implementation of this agreement shall be subject to existing arrangements at the applicable level.<br>
</p>
<p>5.2 The bodies referred to in paragraph 5.1 are the following: <br>
</p>
<p>5.2.1 Mine Health and Safety Council.<br>
</p>
<p>5.2.2 Mining Regulation Advisory Committee (MRAC).<br>
</p>
<p>5.2.3 Safety in Mines Research Advisory Committee (SIMRAC).<br>
</p>
<p>5.2.4 Mining Occupational Health and Safety Committee (MOHAC). <br>
</p>
<p>5.2.5 Mining Qualifications Authority (MQA).<br>
</p>
<p>5.2.6 Minerals Policy Steering Committee.<br>
</p>
<p>5.2.7 Mining Industry Engineering Trades Training Board (MIETTB). <br>
</p>
<p>6. <a name="SICK"><b><u>SICK</u></b></a><b><u> LEAVE<br>
</u></b>The parties confirm the agreement relating to sick leave concluded by them in 1995. The NUM undertakes to inform its 
members of the importance of not abusing sick leave entitlements. The parties agree that management may require assistance 
from the NUM's mine level structures to address possible abuse of sick leave entitlements, in which case the NUM's 
structures will take all reasonable steps to rectify the problem in line with employees' obligations in this regard.<br>
<br>
</p>
<p>7. <b><u>COMPENSATION FOR PRE-</u></b><a name="1977"><b><u>1977</u></b></a><b><u> INCAPACITATED WORKERS<br>
</u></b>The parties agree to address in writing a joint request to the Board of Directors of the Rand Mutual Assurance Company 
Limited that it give favourable consideration to the provision of further benefits to ex-employees of member mines who before 
1977 were permanently incapacitated with less than 100% incapacity, provided that relevant surpluses be utilised for this 
purpose.<br>
<br>
</p>
<p>8. <a name="LUMP"><b><u>LUMP</u></b></a><b><u> SUM BENEFIT APPLICABLE TO EMPLOYEES WITH STATUTORY OCCUPATIONAL 
DISEASES AND INJURIES SUSTAINED ON DUTY</u></b><u> <br>
</u></p>
<p>8.1 <b><u>All Groups except JCI Ltd Gold mines and mines currently associated with Randgold<br>
</u></b>All employees whose services are terminated due to occupational injuries and diseases in accordance with the terms of the 
1992 Agreement on the Principles and Values Applicable to Employees with Statutory Occupational Diseases and Injuries 
Sustained on Duty, shall receive a lump sum benefit calculated at 5% of the medically incapacitated employee's basic pay 
earned during the period of Group service prior to 1 July 1989.<br>
</p>
<p>This lump sum is separate from and in addition to the Chamber of Mines Long Service Award Scheme.<br>
</p>
<p>8.2 <b><u>JCI Ltd Gold mines<br>
</u></b>Lump sum benefits will be provided in terms of the Gold division agreement between the parties signed on 25 June 1996.<br>
</p>
<p>8.3 <b><u>All groups except mines currently associated with Randgold <br>
</u></b>In respect of employees who started employment on or after 1&#160;July 1989, the parties agree that the existing working party 
which is charged with the restructuring of the MPF/MABS should look into providing a lump sum benefit in the restructured 
fund as a supplement for such employees, in order to address the union's concerns about their position.<br>
</p>
<p>8.4 <b><u>Mines currently associated with Randgold<br>
</u></b>East Rand Proprietary Mines Limited, Blyvooruitzicht Gold Mining Company Limited and Harmony Gold Mining Company 
Limited already have mine level agreements in place dealing with this issue.<br>
</p>
<p>Buffelsfontein Gold Mining Company Limited and Grootvlei Proprietary Mines Limited are prepared to explore this issue at 
mine level. <br>
</p>
<p>8.5 <b><u>All Groups<br>
</u></b>The parties agree to amend the 1992 Agreement on the Principles and Values Applicable to Employees with Statutory 
Occupational Diseases and Injuries Sustained on Duty appropriately.<br>
<br>
</p>
<p>9. <b><u>SUB-</u></b><a name="CONTRACTING"><b><u>CONTRACTING</u></b></a><b><u><br>
</u></b>9.1 The parties agree upon the need for effective implementation of the 1995 agreement on sub-contracting regarding, 
amongst other matters, advice to the NUM's mine level structures of new sub-contracting plans and disclosure to the NUM 
on a regular basis of information relevant to sub-contracting.<br>
</p>
<p>9.2 The Chamber undertakes to bring to the attention of its gold and coal members which recognise the NUM the need to 
fulfil their obligations under the terms of the 1995 sub-contracting agreement. <br>
</p>
<p>10. <a name="RIOT"><b><u>RIOT</u></b></a><b><u> AND MINES AUXILIARY FORCES POLICY<br>
</u></b>10.1 The parties note the existence of a &quot;Riot and Mines Auxiliary Forces Policy&quot;, which is an insurance policy offered by the 
Rand Mutual Assurance Company Limited to its members.<br>
</p>
<p>10.2 The Chamber undertakes to make known to its gold mine and collieries members which recognise the Union the 
existence, provisions and terms of the above-mentioned policy.<br>
<br>
</p>
<p>11. <b><u>INSTITUTION OF A STATUTORY </u></b><a name="BARGAINING"><b><u>BARGAINING</u></b></a><b><u> FORUM<br>
</u></b>11.1 The parties are in agreement on the principle that it is desirable for a statutory bargaining forum to be instituted by the 
Chamber and its collective bargaining partners.<br>
</p>
<p>11.2 The parties agree to the establishment of a working party to consider and make recommendations to the parties on the 
manner in which the agreement recorded in clause 11.1 should be given effect.<br>
</p>
<p>11.3 It is agreed that all trade unions and employee associations which are recognised by the Chamber for the purposes of 
collective bargaining should be invited to be represented on the working party referred to in clause 11.2.<br>
</p>
<p>11.4 The parties agree that the terms of reference of the working party referred to in clause 11.2 should include consideration 
of the NUM's proposal relating to representation rights, with a view to the making of recommendations to the Chamber and 
the NUM.<br>
<br>
</p>
<p>12. <b><u>WORKING PARTY ON A</u></b><u> </u><a name="TWO"><b><u>TWO</u></b></a><b><u>-YEAR WAGE REVIEW CYCLE <br>
</u></b>12.1 The parties note the NUM's proposal that an agreement be negotiated for a two-year wage review cycle which cycle 
would operate until 30 June 1998.<br>
</p>
<p>12.2 Noting that the NUM's proposal has been under consideration in a working party of the wage review, the parties agree 
that the working party should continue with its deliberations with a view to submitting recommendations to the parties.<br>
<br>
</p>
<p>13. <b><u>MINE </u></b><a name="SPECIFIC"><b><u>SPECIFIC</u></b></a><b><u> AGREEMENTS<br>
</u></b>Agreements, as recorded in Annexures B1 to B6 hereto, have been reached between the mines listed below and the NUM, 
viz.:<br>
</p>
<p>13.1 Agreement in respect of Blyvooruitzicht Gold Mining Company Limited (Annexure B1);<br>
</p>
<p>13.2 Agreement in respect of East Rand Proprietary Mines Limited (Annexure B2);<br>
</p>
<p>13.3 Agreement in respect of Harmony Gold Mining Company Limited (Annexure B3);<br>
</p>
<p>13.4 Agreement in respect of Durban Roodepoort Deep Limited (Annexure B4);<br>
</p>
<p>13.5 Agreement in respect of Douglas Colliery (Annexure B5); and <br>
</p>
<p>13.6 Agreement in respect of gold mines administered by JCI Limited (Annexure B6).<br>
<br>
</p>
<p>14. <b><u>WORKPLACE AND ORGANISATIONAL </u></b><a name="RESTRUCTURING"><b><u>RESTRUCTURING</u></b></a><b><u><br>
</u></b>14.1 Recognising that changes in the workplace and in the organisation of work require that attention be given to job grading 
systems, the parties agreed during the 1995 Wage Review to a review of job grading systems applicable on mines to be 
undertaken by a committee set up for that purpose. The review must take account of restructuring and re-organisation taking 
place on mines, as well as progress already made on several member mines.<br>
</p>
<p>14.2 Noting that the committee was unable to meet the objective of submitting its report to the parties by December 1995, the 
parties agree that the committee should continue with its deliberations and should complete its mandate of submitting 
recommendations to the parties as to how current job grading systems on mines might be improved to meet current and future 
needs.<br>
<br>
</p>
<p>15. <a name="BROADBANDING"><b><u>BROADBANDING</u></b></a><b><u><br>
</u></b>15.1 The parties agree that the issue of broadbanding is being addressed as part of the job grading committee referred to in 
Clause 14.1 above.<br>
</p>
<p>15.2 <b><u>Mines in the Gold Fields Group<br>
</u></b>15.2.1 New Employees and Sheltered Employment Posts<br>
</p>
<p>15.2.1.1 Employees in sheltered employment posts and, for an initial training period of three months, new employees who do 
not possess the requisite skills and experience will be paid at a rate of 87,5% of the Category 2 minimum rate. The provisions 
for service increment will apply.<br>
</p>
<p>15.2.1.2 With regard to sheltered employment posts, the parties agree that this provision will not derogate from the terms of 
the Income Security Agreement and the 1992 Medical Separation Framework Agreement (&quot;The Principles and Values 
Applicable to Employees with Statutory Occupational Diseases and Injuries Sustained on Duty&quot;).<br>
</p>
<p>A sheltered employment post is a post requiring very limited skills which, where available, an employee with very limited 
ability can choose to take up and thus continue in employment.<br>
</p>
<p><u>Note:<br>
</u>Employees who are disabled at work are, as part of rehabilitation, trained to the level of their ability. When employed 
following training, they are employed in and paid at the level of the job. Mines in the Gold Fields Group have always been and 
remain committed to such rehabilitation and training.<br>
</p>
<p>15.2.2 All Category 1 employees who do not fall into the above and who have completed 3 months' employment in that job 
will be paid at the Category 2 minimum rate.<br>
<br>
</p>
<p>16. <a name="MINIMUM"><b><u>MINIMUM</u></b></a><b><u> WAGES<br>
</u></b>The increases in minimum wages that have been agreed to between the Chamber and the NUM in respect of staff and 
non-staff members of the NUM in recognised bargaining units are reflected in Annexure C (gold mines), Annexure D 
(Randgold Associated mines) and Annexure E (collieries) to this Agreement.<br>
</p>
<p>17. <a name="BASIC"><b><u>BASIC</u></b></a><b><u> CONDITIONS OF EMPLOYMENT ACT<br>
</u></b>The NUM undertakes to inform the Department of Labour by letter of the NUM's support for the exemption of gold mines 
and collieries, members of the Chamber, from sections 7, 9, 10 and 12 up to and including 16 and 19 of the Basic Conditions 
of Employment Act, or similar provisions in any legislation which might replace that Act, for the period 1 October 1996 to 30 
September 1997. The NUM shall send a copy of the letter to the Chamber for its records. <br>
</p>
<p>18. <b><u>FULL AND FINAL </u></b><a name="SETTLEMENT"><b><u>SETTLEMENT</u></b></a><b><u><br>
</u></b>18.1 This Agreement constitutes full and final settlement of all proposals made by the NUM and the Chamber in the 1996 
review of wages and other conditions of employment for all members of the NUM in recognised bargaining units on gold 
mines and collieries, members of the Chamber.<br>
</p>
<p>18.2 The parties agree that any dispute that may arise from the implementation of Clauses 1.2, 2.3, 3.2, 8.3, 8.4, 11 and 12 
of this agreement or the implementation of the agreements recorded in Annexure B hereto shall not detract in any way from 
this agreement and should any dispute arise in respect of <br>
</p>
<p>18.2.1 Clause 2.3, 8.3, 11 or 12 hereof it shall be between the NUM and the Chamber and<br>
</p>
<p>18.2.2 Clause 1.2, 3.2 or 8.4 or Annexure B it shall be between the NUM and the individual mining company concerned.<br>
</p>
<p>18.3 This agreement shall amend the terms and conditions of employment of the employees concerned and no demand with 
cost implications for the employer shall be made before the next wage review.<br>
</p>
<p>19. <a name="IMPLEMENTATION"><b><u>IMPLEMENTATION</u></b></a><b><u> DATE<br>
</u></b>Unless otherwise stated, the wage increases and other changes in conditions of employment referred to in this Agreement and 
the Annexures hereto shall be implemented with effect from 1 July 1996.<br>
<br>
<br>
</p>
<p>SIGNED AT JOHANNESBURG ON THE 11TH DAY OF SEPTEMBER 1996<br>
<br>
</p>
<p>FOR AND ON BEHALF OF THE NATIONAL UNION OF MINEWORKERS<br>
<br>
</p>
