<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../images/linegr.gif"><BR>
<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<A NAME="preamble"><U><B>PREAMBLE<BR>
</B></U>WHEREAS the NUM sent to the Chamber a letter dated 24
April 1995 containing the NUM's proposals for the 1995 review
of wages and other conditions of employment for members of the
NUM employed in recognition units for which the NUM is recognised
by gold mines and collieries that are members of the Chamber ('the
1995 review'); and<BR>
</A>
<P>
WHEREAS meetings have subsequently taken place between representatives
of the NUM and the Chamber and the parties have reached agreement
on the 1995 review; and<BR>

<P>
WHEREAS during the course of the 1995 review the parties have
considered certain arrangements with regard to restructuring the
mining industry towards productivity improvements on gold and
coal mines;<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>THE PARTIES THEREFORE AGREE AS FOLLOWS :<BR>
<BR>
</B>
<P>
<A NAME="applic"><B>1. <U>APPLICATION OF AGREEMENT<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
1.1 This Agreement shall apply to all members of the NUM employed
in recognition units for which the NUM is recognised by gold mines
and collieries that are members of the Chamber. <BR>

<P>
1.2 It is recorded that negotiations have taken place separately
between the NUM and Harmony Gold Mine, Blyvooruitzicht Gold Mine
and ERPM. A separate agreement on the 1995 review, annexed hereto
as Annexure F, has been concluded between the NUM and these mines.
Each of the mines concerned shall be subject to all the provisions
of this agreement except where a provision of the agreement between
the NUM and a mine deals with a particular matter in which case
the provision of the latter agreement shall apply and not the
relevant provision of this agreement.<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="broadbanding"><B>2. <U>BROADBANDING<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
2.1 The mines that are members of the Chamber undertake to implement
initiatives set out in Annexure A.<BR>

<P>
2.2 Clause 2.1 does not apply to Gold Fields. The NUM reserves
the right to pursue Gold Field's exclusion from Clause 2.1 after
conclusion of this agreement.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="restructuring"><B>3. <U>WORKPLACE AND ORGANISATIONAL
RESTRUCTURING <BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
3.1 The parties agree that, in the interest of the long term viability
of the mining industry there needs to be ongoing workplace and
organisational restructuring, which must occur in collaboration
with individual employees and their unions at mine level.<BR>

<P>
3.2 Critical issues in this regard relate to job design towards
the optimal utilisation of human and capital resources. <BR>

<P>
3.3. Changes in the workplace and in the organisation of work
on mines require that attention be given to job grading systems.
The parties agree to a review of job grading systems applicable
on mines. This review will be undertaken by a committee which
has equal representation of both parties. It will be chaired by
an independent person to be agreed by the parties, and assisted
by two assessors who may be experts. Each party will bear its
own costs, and any common costs will be shared equally, unless
otherwise agreed between the parties.<BR>

<P>
3.3.1 The committee would be mandated to review the current job
grading systems on mines that are members of the Chamber, to receive
representation from parties and to make recommendations as to
how systems might be improved to meet current and future needs.
The review must take account of restructuring and re-organisation
taking place on mines, as well as progress already made on several
member mines.<BR>

<P>
3.3.2 The committee must endeavour to submit its report to the
parties by December&nbsp;1995. The recommendations of the committee
could be the subject of discussions between the parties in 1996
and be used to supplement<B> </B>progress in terms of the 1994
agreement.<BR>

<P>
3.3.3 Mines undertake to deal, in terms of mine level procedures,
with problems currently experienced with certain individual occupations.
These problems will therefore not form part of the committee's
brief.<BR>

<P>
3.4 Workplace redesign at mine level should take cognisance of
the need for effective and efficient supervision structures in
order to enhance productivity and safety performance. <BR>

<P>
3.5 To the extent that mine level investigations result in general
industry consensus regarding the need for legislative changes
for more effective supervisory structures, the parties will discuss
such changes centrally in order to develop joint approaches to
the relevant authorities.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="subcontracting"><B>4. <U>SUB-CONTRACTING<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
4.1 The parties acknowledge that it is custom and practice in
the mining industry throughout the world that aspects of the mining
process and other matters associated with the operating of mines
are sourced out or contracted out by mining companies to other
persons. Whilst this practice of out-sourcing or subcontracting
offers various advantages to mining companies and supports the
development of small business enterprise, it might contain threats
for employees and members of trade unions operating in the mining
industry.<BR>

<P>
4.2 Therefore, the parties agree that when considering subcontracting,
the company shall adhere to the following principles and procedures
and have due regard to the factors contained in this agreement.
The provisions of this agreement shall not apply to tasks which
require special skills, equipment and/or resources and for which
tasks mines do not ordinarily employ category 1 - 8 employees,
provided that from time to time, the NUM will be informed of the
type of tasks which are outsourced on this basis. <BR>

<P>
4.2.1 Within thirty days of signing this agreement, the NUM shall
be advised of existing subcontracting agreements. <BR>

<P>
4.2.2 Mines undertake:<BR>

<P>
4.2.2.1 to advise the NUM's mine level structures of new sub-contracting
plans;<BR>

<P>
4.2.2.2 to disclose to the NUM on a regular basis information
relevant to subcontracting, subject to the law and applicable
agreements; and<BR>

<P>
4.2.2.3 where the employment of subcontractors might lead to the
retrenchment or downgrading of an existing employee, the NUM's
representatives will be involved in discussions in respect of
such retrenchment or downgrading.<BR>

<P>
4.3 To facilitate the implementation of this agreement the question
of contracting out will be a subject for discussion in management/NUM
meetings.<BR>

<P>
4.4 The parties agree that the purpose of this agreement is to
promote harmonious relationships and in this regard commit themselves
that where incidents of conflict arise between mine employees
and employees of contractors, all parties will become involved
to defuse the situation.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
4.5 A subcontractor is required to comply with applicable legislation,
including the Aliens Act, Labour Relations Act, Basic Conditions
of Employment Act, Minerals Act, Unemployment Insurance Act and
the Compensation for Occupational Injuries and Diseases Act.<BR>

<P>
4.6 It is acknowledged that mine management cannot interfere with
the contractual relationship between the contractor and his employees,
but good practice dictates that there should be sound employment
practices.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="fulco"><B>5. <U>FULL-CALENDAR OPERATIONS<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
5.1 The parties agree that Section 9 of the Mines and Works Act
imposes a restriction on the better utilisation of labour and
capital resources, that this restriction needs to be addressed
urgently and that they will enter into negotiations at industry
level on the review of this law to facilitate the introduction
of full calendar operations (FULCO).<BR>

<P>
5.1.1 The parties agree that such negotiations should take place
in a working party and that they will invite all other recognised
unions and mining companies not members of the Chamber to participate
fully in this working party. The parties shall endeavour to conclude
such negotiations by December&nbsp;1995. The parties agree further
that arising from these negotiations they will enter into an agreement
for the amendment of Section 9.<BR>

<P>
5.2 Pending the amendment of the relevant section of the legislation
and the outcome of the negotiations in the working party, the
parties undertake to negotiate in good faith and without delay
at mine level on such mines that may wish to work FULCO, the details
of shift and other arrangements regarding FULCO;<BR>

<P>
5.2.1 The parties agree that:<BR>

<P>
(a) there is the need for the better utilisation of human and
capital resources;<BR>

<P>
(b) it is the intention that both the company and the employees
benefit from FULCO and to this end mutually acceptable arrangements
for FULCO will be negotiated at mine level;<BR>

<P>
(c) applications for exemptions from Section 9 should have the
support of those unions and/or associations representing the majority
of employees at the mine;<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
(d) there will be disclosure of relevant information to the NUM
on FULCO, subject to the law and applicable agreements; <BR>

<P>
(e) mechanisms to monitor the effect of FULCO will be developed
at mine level; and<BR>

<P>
(f) any arrangements made should strike an appropriate balance
between the rights and interests of employers, employees and those
of the NUM.<BR>

<P>
5.2.2 Subject to agreement being reached on the items in 5.2,
the NUM agrees to support applications to the Minister to grant
exemptions to individual mines where agreement has been reached,
and such applications will be jointly made, by the NUM and the
mine. <BR>

<P>
5.3 For purposes of this agreement full calendar operations shall
mean that normal operations on a mine may be conducted on 7 days
a week, and that each day of the week shall be regarded as an
ordinary working day. This definition will be subject to the provisions
of the Public Holidays Act, 1994.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="tiers"><B>6. <U>TWO-TIER BARGAINING<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
6.1 The parties agree that they require a single, co-ordinated
and orderly collective bargaining system, and to this end agree
on the following:<BR>

<P>
6.1.1 that bargaining on basic wages and conditions of employment
shall take place at Chamber level, provided that by mutual agreement
between the parties special circumstances may necessitate negotiations
on these issues to take place at mine or Group level;<BR>

<P>
6.1.2 that bargaining on organisational, operational and workplace
issues, shall be at the level of the mine or company, provided
that this does not preclude matters of industry concern being
raised at Chamber level, in which event negotiations at mine or
company level will take place within any applicable framework
agreed to at Chamber level;<BR>

<P>
6.1.3 that issues which are bargained at Chamber level not be
bargained again at mine or company level, unless a framework agreement
has been concluded at Chamber level which specifies that the details
are to be negotiated at the appropriate level; and<BR>

<P>
6.1.4 that the levels of bargaining need to be co-ordinated within
an industrial relations framework that is orderly but capable
of change to meet new circumstances by agreement between the parties.
<BR>

<P>
6.2 The parties affirm their commitment to enter into Chamber
and mine or company level bargaining in terms of these principles
and objectives in good faith.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="capacity"><B>7. <U>CAPACITY BUILDING<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
7.1 The parties acknowledge that the building of union capacity
is important for the functioning of the NUM. In this regard arrangements
have been agreed to with regard to the release of recognised shaft
stewards and some branch committee office-bearers on full pay
for training purposes.<BR>

<P>
7.2 The parties acknowledge that in addition to the above, it
may be necessary to develop capacity at mine level, in order to
facilitate meaningful engagement on specialised topics. On occasions
when such topics are under discussion management will consider
releasing certain shaft stewards for additional specialised training
in such topics. The nature, content and duration of such training,
together with the number of people, will be agreed at mine level.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="housing"><B>8. <U>HOUSING AND ACCOMMODATION<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
8.1 Recognising that policy development in the field of housing
and accommodation should take place in consultation with stakeholders,
the parties agreed in 1994 on a Framework of Principles on Housing
Forums and Hostels (attached as Annexure B).<BR>

<P>
8.2 The 1994 Agreement set up the structure for Housing Forums,
which would be located at mine or company level so that regard
could be had to the specific circumstances or philosophy of the
individual mine or company, including operational circumstances.
It was envisaged that the primary function of such bodies would
be to discuss the broad parameters, or framework, of the mine
or company's policy or approach to housing, including the issue
of hostels and the improvement of living conditions.<BR>

<P>
8.3 It is recorded that even though discussions within the framework
set up by the 1994 Agreement have been initiated in respect of
the mines of certain mining houses, they have not yet commenced
in respect of all mines.<BR>

<P>
8.4 The parties agree to amend the 1994 Framework of Principles
on Housing Forums and Hostels and replace the second sentence
of clause 2.4 with the words:<BR>

<P>
&quot;While recognising that the fundamental responsibility for
the running of and maintenance of good order in the hostels rests
with management, the parties <BR>

<P>
agree that it is desirable that there be joint decision making
on issues agreed to between the parties at the appropriate level&quot;.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="safety"><B>9. <U>SAFETY REPRESENTATIVES<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
9.1 Mines that are members of the Chamber agree in principle to
full time safety representatives subject to discussions at mine
or Group level, or in the case of Gold Fields, Group co-ordinated
level with all unions and associations on a comprehensive agreement,
which will include the number and duties of such representatives.
The effectiveness of such representatives is to be reviewed from
time to time.<BR>

<P>
9.2 Clause 9.1 does not apply to Duiker. The NUM reserves the
right to pursue Duiker's exclusion from Clause 9.1 after conclusion
of this agreement.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="discrimination"><B>10. <U>NON-DISCRIMINATORY EMPLOYMENT
PRACTICES <BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
10.1 The parties agree to the following:<BR>

<P>
10.1.1 Regardless of citizenship status and country of domicile
the industry enters into permanent employment relationships with
its employees, and whilst employees are on leave their employment
status remains intact;<BR>

<P>
10.1.2 Employees in the category 1 to 8 bargaining unit from foreign
countries shall not have different conditions of employment from
local counterparts with regard to absence on unpaid leave;<BR>

<P>
10.1.3 Where employees perform identical jobs on the same mines,
the rates of pay should be aligned;<BR>

<P>
10.1.4 Industrial relations procedures should not be discriminatory;
<BR>

<P>
10.1.5 The parties agree in principle on the incorporation of
correct information on personal records. To the extent that proof
is available, records will be amended; and<BR>

<P>
10.1.6 The parties agree to a joint process of identifying alleged
unfair racial discriminatory practices by establishing joint management/union
committees at mining house level, or, in the case of Gold Fields
and Anglovaal, at Group co-ordinated level to undertake such identification.
Where appropriate, this can be extended to mine or company level.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="holidays"><B>11. <U>HOLIDAY LEAVE ALLOWANCE<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
11.1 In respect of mines administered by Gold Fields and in respect
of East Rand Proprietary Mines Limited the holiday leave allowance
of members of the NUM in recognition units for which the NUM is
recognised shall be increased to 100% of basic rate of pay with
effect from 1&nbsp;July&nbsp;1995.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="sick"><B>12. <U>SICK LEAVE<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
12.1 The parties agree that where satisfactory evidence of sickness
from a registered medical practitioner is produced, payment for
sick leave shall be from the first day of absence. <BR>

<P>
12.2 If management is not satisfied with the evidence of sickness
produced by the employee, it can refuse to condone the absence.
The employer will in such a case provide the employee concerned
with the reasons for its decision. The employee has the right
to appeal against the decision.<BR>

<P>
12.3 The employer may waive the requirement that evidence from
a registered medical practitioner be provided where it is satisfied
that other evidence of sickness exists.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="mpf"><B>13. <U>MINEWORKERS PROVIDENT FUND (MPF) AND HOUSING
LOANS<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
13.1 The parties note that the NUM's demand that each mine agree
to facilitate the implementation of arrangements made by the Mineworkers
Provident Fund to permit members' withdrawal benefits to serve
as collateral security for housing loans, was resolved at an MPF
Trustees meeting on 19&nbsp;May&nbsp;1995. <BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="aa"><B>14. <U>AFFIRMATIVE ACTION<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
14.1 The parties concluded a framework agreement in the 1994 review
(attached as Annexure C) and re-affirm the validity of that framework.
Discussions at the relevant mine/company level in terms of that
Agreement should be commenced or continued. All parties reconfirm
their commitment to the 1994 agreement to discuss this issue at
the relevant mine/company level.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="income"><B>15. <U>INCOME SECURITY<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
15.1 The period applicable in terms of the initial Income Security
Agreement of 1987 shall be extended from 9 months to 12 months.
<BR>

<P>
15.2 Mines will make every reasonable endeavour to train an employee
who is incapacitated through a medical condition arising out of
and in the course of his employment so that the employee need
not suffer a reduction in wages on account of his incapacity.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="mpfcontributions"><B>16. <U>MINEWORKERS PROVIDENT FUND
CONTRIBUTIONS <BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
16.1 The employer's and the employee's contributions to the Mineworkers
Provident Fund (MPF) will each be increased by 0,5% of wages,
as defined in the rules of the MPF.<BR>

<P>
16.2 The parties agree that the annual negotiations regarding
this issue are unacceptable. The parties therefore agree to a
working party to consider:<BR>

<UL>
<LI>The ideal level of contributions;
<LI>The ideal level of benefits; and
<LI>Methods of marrying the two objectives in the best possible
manner.<FONT SIZE=2> </FONT>
</UL>

<P>
16.3 The parties acknowledge that differences exist between the
employer's contributions to the MEPF and the MPF. These differences
should be addressed as part of the task of the working party review
into provident funding.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="assurance"><B>17. <U>MINEWORKERS ASSURANCE AND BENEFITS
SCHEME (MABS)<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
17.1 It is recorded that the contributions payable under the MABS
were increased from R2,10 to R2,89 per hundred rand of earnings
with effect from 1&nbsp;August&nbsp;1995.<BR>

<P>
17.2 It is agreed that with effect from 1&nbsp;August&nbsp;1995
employers will bear the cost of contributions in respect of MABS
in the proportion of 70% and employees will bear the cost of contributions
in the proportion of 30%.<BR>

<P>
17.3 The working group on MABS will continue its deliberations
in order to address the structural funding problems experienced
by the scheme.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="wages"><B>18. <U>WAGES<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
18.1 The increases in wages for staff and non-staff employees
agreed between the Chamber and the NUM are set out fully in Annexures
D and E to this Agreement in respect of gold mines and collieries,
respectively.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
18.2 In respect of JCI Gold, the increase on basic wages will
be made up of 10,5% plus an additional 1% payable on conclusion
of mine level agreements with the NUM on FULCO. The 1% increase
shall be backdated to 1&nbsp;July&nbsp;1995 if mine level FULCO
agreements are concluded within three months of settlement of
the COM/NUM agreement.<BR>

<P>
H J Joel shall be included in this arrangement and, therefore,
a revision of the existing FULCO agreement applicable on the mine
is implied.<BR>

<P>
18.3 Gengold and the NUM agreed to jointly develop an appropriate
bonus scheme before 31&nbsp;October&nbsp;1995, which will:<BR>

<P>
18.3.1 Reward employees for production increases. <BR>

<P>
18.3.2 Replace the plethora of bonus schemes in use at the mines
at present.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="bcea"><B>19. <U>BASIC CONDITIONS OF EMPLOYMENT ACT<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
19.1 The NUM undertakes to inform the Department of Labour by
letter of the NUM's support for the exemption of gold mines and
collieries, members of the Chamber, from sections 7, 9 to 16 and
19 of the Basic Conditions of Employment Act for the period 1&nbsp;October
1995 to 30 September 1996. The NUM shall send a copy of the letter
to the Chamber for its records. <BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="full"><B>20. <U>FULL AND FINAL SETTLEMENT<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
20.1 This Agreement constitutes full and final settlement of all
proposals made by the NUM and the Chamber in the 1995 review of
wages and other conditions of employment for all members of the
NUM in recognised bargaining units on gold mines and collieries,
members of the Chamber.<BR>

<P>
20.2 The parties agree that any dispute that may arise from the
implementation of Clause 2, 3.3, 4, 5.1.1, 7, 8, 9, 10.1.6, 14,
16 or 17.3 of this agreement shall not detract in any way from
this agreement and should any dispute arise in respect of<BR>

<P>
20.2.1 Clause 3.3, 5.1.1, 16 or 17.3 hereof it shall be between
the NUM and the Chamber and<BR>

<P>
20.2.2 Clause 2, 4, 5.2, 7, 8, 9, 10.1.6, 12 or 14 it shall be
between the NUM and the individual mining company concerned.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="implementation"><B>21. <U>IMPLEMENTATION<BR>
</U></B></A>
<P>
21.1 Unless otherwise stated, the wages increases and other improvements
in conditions of employment referred to in this Agreement and
the Annexures hereto shall be implemented with effect from 1&nbsp;July&nbsp;1995.
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<CENTER><I><B>SIGNED AT JOHANNESBURG ON THE 5<SUP>TH</SUP> DAY
OF SEPTEMBER 1995.<BR>
<BR>
</B></I></CENTER>
<P>
<A NAME="annexa"><U><B>ANNEXURE A<BR>
<BR>
</B></U></A>
<P>
<CENTER><U><B>BROADBANDING<BR>
<BR>
</B></U></CENTER>
<P>
<U><B>Anglo Gold Division<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
All category 2 jobs will be reviewed and upgraded to category
3 through a process of job enrichment and multi-skilling. This
process will be completed within six months of the date of signature
of this agreement by both parties. However, where new employees
who do not possess the requisite skills are employed they will
be employed at a training rate which is determined at 85% of the
category&nbsp;3 minimum until their training has been completed.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Amcoal<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
Employees presently graded at the category 2 level will have their
jobs reviewed and expanded and upgraded to category 3 by the end
of December&nbsp;1995. On being upgraded, such employees will
be credited with their service increments in respect of past service.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Gengold<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
Gengold will upgrade all category&nbsp;1 employees to category&nbsp;2
on the day following the date on which agreement is reached on
the Gengold multi-skilling proposals in the Gengold/NUM working
group on Job Grading, Broadbanding and Multi-skilling. <BR>

<P>
It is recorded that this working group has committed itself to
reach agreement by 30&nbsp;August&nbsp;1995.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>JCI Gold<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
JCI Gold Division undertakes that as a consequence of the current
job redesign program Category A1 substantive positions will be
consolidated into Category&nbsp;2 by the end of December&nbsp;1995.
Service increments will not be carried forward.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>JCI Coal<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
JCI Limited Coal Division and the NUM undertake to enter into
discussion on restructuring as a result of the current productivity
improvement exercise.<BR>

<P>
Broadbanding shall constitute an element of such restructuring,
and in this regard it is agreed that the current category&nbsp;1
substantive occupations shall be incorporated into at least the
current category&nbsp;2 within three months of the date of signature
of this agreement by both parties. Service increments will not
be carried forward.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Ingwe<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
Ingwe Coal Corporation undertakes to combine categories 1 and
2 into a single category with wage rates and grade defined benefits
set at the level of category&nbsp;2.<BR>

<P>
The organisational change process embarked upon with the co-operation
and participation of all unions and associations will proceed.
This process addresses the Union's concerns about job levels and
minimum wages.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Anglovaal<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
Anglovaal is prepared to upgrade all existing employees in Category
1 to Category 2. The basic wage of all existing employees in Category
1 will be increased to the minimum of Category&nbsp;2. <BR>

<P>
For the purposes of service increments for employees who are upgraded
from category&nbsp;1 to category&nbsp;2, service will commence
from the date of the implementation of the agreement on the 1995
wage review.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Duiker<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
All category&nbsp;1 jobs will be reviewed and upgraded to category
2. However, where new employees who do not possess the requisite
skills are employed, they will be employed at a training rate
which is determined at 87% of the category&nbsp;2 minimum until
their training has been completed.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Kangra<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
Employees presently graded at the category&nbsp;1 level will have
their jobs reviewed and expanded and upgraded to category&nbsp;2
by the end of December&nbsp;1995.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>ERPM, Harmony Gold Mine and Blyvooruitzicht Gold Mine<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
As part of a general process of job enrichment, which includes
job redesign, additional training and multi-skilling, the mines
referred to are prepared to combine categories 1, 2 and 3 by no
later than June&nbsp;1996. Consequently the minimum basic wage
of all employees in category 1 and 2 will be increased to the
minimum of category&nbsp;3 by no later than 30&nbsp;June&nbsp;1996.
<BR>

<P>
For the purposes of service increments for these employees, service
will commence from the date of the implementation of the agreement
on the 1995 wage review.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="annexb"><U><B>ANNEXURE B<BR>
<BR>
</B></U></A>
<P>
<CENTER><U><B>FRAMEWORK OF PRINCIPLES ON HOUSING FORUMS AND HOSTELS
<BR>
</B></U></CENTER>
<P>
<U><B>Preamble<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
The Chamber of Mines and the National Union of Mineworkers, (hereinafter
referred to as &quot;the parties&quot;) have reached agreement
on the following framework of principles and guidelines with regard
to housing and hostels<B> </B>in respect of members of the National
Union of Mineworkers in recognised bargaining units on gold mines
and collieries subject to the agreement between the parties on
the 1994 review of wages and other conditions of employment<B>.
<BR>
</B>
<P>
In the knowledge that hostels and accommodation are important
to employers and employees, this framework has as an objective
the establishment of housing forums at mine or company level in
order to discuss the approach to housing and hostels.<BR>

<P>
1. <U><B>Housing Forums<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
1.1 The parties agree to the establishment of Housing Forums at
mine or company level.<BR>

<P>
1.2 Housing Forums will serve to discuss the broad parameters,
or framework, of the mine or company's policy or approach to housing
which could lead to agreements on housing policy having regard
to the individual circumstances or philosophies of individual
mines or companies with regard to a variety of factors including
operational circumstances.<BR>

<P>
1.3 The functions and specific role and activities of Housing
Forums will be discussed at the level set out in clause 4 below
and could inter alia include surveys, liaison with housing regulatory
authorities where necessary, and discussion on housing arrangements
and the possibilities of improving living conditions.<BR>

<P>
The parties acknowledge that those persons serving on the Housing
Forums should be knowledgeable and properly informed so as to
facilitate the proper functioning of the Housing Forums.<BR>

<P>
1.4 Recognising that this framework agreement is between the Chamber
of Mines and the National Union of Mineworkers, each Housing Forum
will be inclusive of all parties affected.<BR>

<P>
2. <U><B>Hostel principles<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
2.1 Private sector hostels are best regulated between employers
and employees in the interests of constructive employer/employee
relationships. However, consideration could be given to accessing
state resources for marginal mines.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
2.2 The policy approach by mines or companies to the issue of
hostels and the improvement of living conditions will be addressed
in Housing Forums to be established at each mine or company.<BR>

<P>
2.3 Hostel residents, together with representatives as agreed
to by each Housing Forum, will be involved in the consideration
of improvements in living conditions in hostels.<BR>

<P>
2.4 The parties agree that it is desirable that residents in hostels
should participate in decision making processes in hostel affairs.
However, the fundamental responsibility for the running of and
maintenance of good order in the hostels rests with management.
Participation should take place in accordance with the following
guidelines:<BR>

<P>
The system for participation will be agreed at mine level;<BR>

<P>
The agreed system should not discriminate against residents on
the basis of their ethnic origin, language, national origin, creed
or union affiliation or political affiliation;<BR>

<P>
The system should secure equity, justice and the protection of
the human dignity of all residents;<BR>

<P>
The system should strive for just, acceptable and decent living
conditions for all residents;<BR>

<P>
The system should strive to enhance the social welfare and health
and safety of all residents;<BR>

<P>
The system should strive for peace and harmony;<BR>

<P>
Residents should regularly elect their representatives independently,
democratically and without interference;<BR>

<P>
Clear functions, powers and resources for elected representatives,
should be agreed to.<BR>

<P>
2.5<I> </I>The physical circumstances of hostels will necessarily
vary from one company to the next, with regard to a variety of
factors including operational circumstances.<BR>

<P>
3. <U><B>Implementation<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
3.1 This framework forms part of any settlement on the 1994 review
of wages and other conditions of employment. Discussions at the
level referred to in clause 4 will commence within 3 months of
the conclusion of such a settlement.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
4. <U><B>Mine or Company Level<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
The level at which the discussions referred to in paragraph 1.3
should take place, will be as follows:<BR>

<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>AAC </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>Initially at a
co-ordinated Gold Division level in order to establish broad policy
parameters. Thereafter, each operating region (Free Gold, Vaal
Reefs, West Rand Region) will establish its own modus operandi
within divisional policy parameters<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>GENGOLD</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> Companies and
Head Office representatives in a co-ordinated Divisional forum
in order to establish broad policy parameters. The policy will
then be passed on to individual mines which will establish their
own Housing Forums operating within the laid down parameters<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>KANGRA</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> Initially the
applicable collieries will meet in a Central forum<I><B> </B>with
Head Office representatives. Thereafter, each colliery will establish
its own Housing Forum where Head Office representation can take
place. <BR>
</I></FONT></I>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>DUIKER, DUIKER COAL, </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>Collieries
will establish individual Housing Forums at <BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>ALPHA ANTHRACITE </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>Mine
level. In the last instance, discussions may be convened with
Head Office representatives where required by an individual Housing
Forum.<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>RANDCOAL</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> Mine level
<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>RANDGOLD</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> Company level
in order to establish broad policy parameters. The policy will
then be passed on to individual mines which will establish their
own housing forums operating within the laid down parameters.
<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>TRANSNATAL </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>Divisional
level, subject to details where appropriate at Mine level forums.
<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>JCI</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> Head office level
at which the policy parameters will be set. The policy will then
be passed on to individual mines who will establish their own
Housing Forums operating within the laid down parameters. <BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>GOLD FIELDS</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> Mines and
representatives from Head Office<I><B> </B>in a Central co-ordinated
forum, subject to details where appropriate at mine level<BR>
</I></FONT></I>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>ANGLOVAAL </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>Mine level
Housing Forums will be established with (Harties) Head Office
involvement.<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>AMCOAL</FONT></B></I><FONT SIZE=2> <I>Head
Office level at which the policy parameters will be set. The policy
will then be passed on to individual colliery managers who will
establish their own Housing Forums operating within the laid down
parameters. <BR>
</I></FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="annexc"><U><B>ANNEXURE C<BR>
</B></U></A>
<P>
<center><U><B>FRAMEWORK OF PRINCIPLES ON AFFIRMATIVE ACTION <BR></center>
<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
<U><B>Preamble<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
The NUM had included in its 1994/95 demands to the Chamber the
issue of Affirmative Action.<BR>

<P>
The Chamber and the NUM have agreed that the implementation of
Affirmative Action at member mines represented at the 1994/95
Wage Negotiations will be informed by the following framework
of principles and concepts.<BR>

<P>
1. <U><B>Principles<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
1.1 This framework agreement forms part of the 1994/95 negotiations
and the implementation process at the relevant mine/company level
will immediately follow the conclusion of these negotiations.
<BR>

<P>
1.2 This framework agreement has as an objective implementation
of an Affirmative Action programme as agreed to and appropriately
monitored at the relevant mine/company level. <BR>

<P>
1.3 For the purposes of this framework agreement Affirmative Action
would mean:<BR>

<P>
&quot;A set of procedures aimed at a progressive human resource
policy which maximises the potential of all employees and pro-actively
addresses the disadvantages experienced by sections of the workforce
in the past. &quot;<BR>

<P>
2. <U><B>A Framework of Concepts<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
It is understood that Affirmative Action will encompass among
others, broadly the following concepts which will serve as points
of reference. It is around these that an Affirmative Action programme
at mine/company level can be agreed upon within its proper context:
<BR>

<P>
2.1 <B>Employee Advancement<BR>
</B>
<P>
It is a programme designed to redress the past disadvantages experienced
by employees, and underpinning the concept is the principle of
merit.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
2.2 <B>Equal Opportunity <BR>
</B>
<P>
Is a concept which surmises that each individual has an equal
opportunity to advance and does not take cognisance of past practices.
<BR>

<P>
2.3 <B>Consultation<BR>
</B>
<P>
The process whereby one party seeks views, feelings and ideas
of another party before it makes a final decision.<BR>

<P>
2.4<B> Negotiation<BR>
</B>
<P>
The process whereby at least two independent parties endeavour
to settle a matter between them in a mutually acceptable manner.
<BR>

<P>
2.5<B> Quotas<BR>
</B>
<P>
A quota is a quantitative value which is either self or statutorially
imposed and relates to the number of placements of specific employees
or groups of employees.<BR>

<P>
2.6 <B>Promotions<BR>
</B>
<P>
Promotions are a form of transfer usually involving a shift to
a higher position in the hierarchy, normally associated with increased
responsibility, wages, status and authority.<BR>

<P>
2.7 <B>Recruitment<BR>
</B>
<P>
Recruitment is concerned with developing a pool of job candidates,
in line with the human resources plan. Candidates are located
through newspapers, professional journal advertisements, employment
agencies, word of mouth and visits to college and university campuses.
Recruitment may also be done within an organisation utilising
the current pool of employees.<BR>

<P>
2.8 <B>Training<BR>
</B>
<P>
The process aims at increasing the ability and skills of individuals
and groups to contribute towards organisational effectiveness.
<BR>

<P>
2.9 <B>Conditions of employment<BR>
</B>
<P>
Basic pay, overtime, annual leave, job category, medical aid,
pension, insurance, working hours, sick leave and other benefits
and conditions associated with employment.<BR>

<P>
2.10 <B>Recognition of prior learning<BR>
</B>
<P>
Is the process of recognising training and experience which has
been derived at the workplace.<BR><p>

<Center><IMG SRC="/images/linegr.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><p></Center><br><p>

