<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining QualificationsForum record of understanding
</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF TEXT=#0000A0 LINK=#008040 VLINK=#808080 ALINK=#C0C0C0>

<P>
<CENTER> <IMG SRC="/images/logo2.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#800000><B>RECORD OF UNDERSTANDING</B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>between</FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE=4 COLOR=008000><B>THE STATE, EMPLOYERS AND LABOUR</B></FONT></B><P>
<FONT SIZE=2>in the</FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=0000A0><B>MINING QUALIFICATIONS FORUM</B></FONT>

<P><p><p>
<IMG SRC="/images/linegr.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><BR></CENTER>
<br><p><br>
<B>It is recorded that at a meeting of the Mining Qualifications
Forum held on 31 July 1995, the undersigned parties agreed that:</B>
<ul>
<li>A Mining Qualifications Authority (&quot;MQA&quot;)
should be established under the new Health and Safety in Mines
Act (&quot;the Act&quot;); and
<li>
A Management Qualifications Board (&quot;MQB&quot;)
and a Vocational Qualifications Board (&quot;VQB&quot;) should
be established under the Regulations to the Act, and
<li>
The document annexed hereto marked &quot;A&quot;
reflects the more detailed understanding of the parties regarding
the MQA, MQB and VQB.<BR><p>
</ul>
<I><Center>Signed at Johannesburg on 31 July 1995<BR><p></I>
<IMG SRC="/images/linegr.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><BR></center>
<p>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">MINING QUALIFICATIONS AUTHORITY
TO BE ESTABLISHED BY STATUTE<BR></font>
</B></U>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Arial"><B>The Mining Qualifications Authority
shall advise the Minister on:</B>
<P>
1.1 the creation of a mining industry framework of qualifications and learning achievements to enhance safety and health standards through quality assurance of training and education;
<br>
1.2 standards and competency setting,
assessment, examinations, quality assur:ance and accreditation
in the mining industry;
<br>
1.3 linking the mining industry qualifications
framework to the national qualifications framework.<BR>
<p>

<B>The Mining Qualifications Authority shall consist of not more than 15 members appointed by the Minister
of whom:</B>
<p>
2.1 five persons shall be in the service
of the Department;
<br>
2.2 five persons shall .be nominated
by a body or bodies which is or are representative of the owners
of mines; and
<br>
2.3 five persons nominated by a body
or bodies which is or are representative of employees employed
at mines.<BR>

<P>
<B>The Mining Qualifications Authority shall, in discharging its advisory objectives, have the following
powers and functions:</B><p>

3.1 seek primary accreditation from
the South African Qualifications Authority;
<br>
3.2 register standards and qualifications
with that Authority;
<br>
3.3 set standards and competencies,
establish competency assessment procedures and accredit assessors;
<br>
3.4 establish examination bodies, appoint
examiners and moderators, monitor and administer examinations
and set examination fees; 
<br>
3.5 accredit providers of .training
and education, and establish quality assurance procedures in this
regard;
<br>
3.6 receive and consider reports and
recommendations from its second tier bodies on the powers and
functions set out in paragraphs 3.3, 3.4 and
3.5 above;
<br>
3.7 appoint committees or subcommittees,
including ad hoc committees, and subject to such conditions as
it may determine, delegate any of its powers to such structures;

<br>
3.8 facilitate the development of learning
pathways and career progression in the mining industry;
<br>
3.9 issue qualifications and keep a
register of them;
<br>
3.10 administer and control its financial
affairs and that of its substructures;
<br>
3.11 provide secretarial and administrative
services;
<br>
3.12 disseminate information and liaise
with the industry and other organisations;
<br>
3.13 do such other things as are necessary
in order to achieve its objectives.<BR>

<P>
Nomination procedures and rules relating
to the appointment of members, conduct at meetings and ancillary
matters pertaining to the functioning of the Mining Qualifications
Authority and any second tier bodies established by it shall,
except as provided for in this Act, be determined by regulation.

<P>
When there is no agreement on any issue
at the Mining Qualifications Authority, the matter shall be referred
to the Minister for resolution.<BR>
<BR></font>

<P>
<U><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">QUALIFICATIONS BOARDS TO BE ESTABLISHED
BY REGULATION</B></U></font>
<P><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Arial">
<B>The Mining Qualifications Authority
shall establish, pursuant to Section 3.7 of the Act, a Management
Qualifications Board and a Vocational Qualifications Board.</B>
<P>
<B>The 'functions of the Management Qualifications
Board shall be to:</B>
<p>
2.1 report and make recommendations
to the Mining Qualifications Authority on:
<br>
2.1.1 the minimum performance competencies
needed for management qualifications in the mining industry and,
if required, the introduction or removal of certificates of competency
for them;
<br>
2.1.2 the establishment and monitoring
of procedures and standards assessment and the accreditation of
assessors; and
<br>
2.1.3 the establishment of examination
bodies, appointment of examiners and moderators and the monitoring
and administration of examinations.
<br>
2.2 perform such other functions delegated
to it by the Mining Qualifications Authority.<BR>

<p>
<B>The Management Qualifications Board
shall comprise of members appointed by the Mining Qualifications
Authority who shall:</B>
<p>
3.1 be nominated by stakeholders represented
on the Mining Qualifications Authority;
<br>
3.2 appoint, on consideration of the
nominations, suitable competent members. In so doing, it will
<br>
3.2.1 seek to provide for an appropriate
spread of all management qualifications in the appointment of
members;
<br>
3.2.2 ensure that a reasonable majority
of members are practising holders of management qualifications
in the South African mining industry;
<br>
3.2.3 use competence as the overriding
selection criteria.Page 2<BR>

<P>
<B>The functions of the Vocational Qualifications
Board shall be to:</B>
<p>
4.1 report and make recommendations
to the Mining Qualifications Authority on:
<BR>

4.1.1 the minimum performance competencies
needed for vocational qualifications in the mining industry and,
if required, the introduction or removal of certificates of competency
for them;
<br>
4.1.2 the establishment and monitoring
of procedures and standards assessment and the accreditation of
assessors; and
<br>
4.1.3 the establishment of examination
bodies, appointment of examiners and moderators and the monitoring
and administration of examinations.
<br>
<B>The Vocational Qualifications Board
shall comprise of members appointed by the Mining Qualifications
Authority who shall:</B>
<p>
5.1 perform such other functions delegated
to it by the Mining Qualifications Authority be nominated by stakeholders
represented on the Mining Qualifications Authority;
<br>
5.2 appoint, on consideration of the
nominations, suitable competent members. In so doing, it will:
&#183;
<br>
5.2.1 seek to provide for an appropriate
spread of all vocational qualifications in the appointment of
members;
<br>
5.2.2 ensure that a reasonable majority
of members are practising holders of vocational qualifications
in the South African mining industry;
<br>
5.2.3 use competence as the overriding selection
criteria.
<P></font><p>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/images/linegr.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><BR>
