<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Chamber of Minesof South Africa: Adult Basic Education and Training</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000080">
<a name="top"></a>
<center>
<IMG SRC="/images/logo2.gif"><p>

<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=800040><B>ADULT BASIC EDUCATION AND TRAINING</B></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>AGREEMENT</B></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3 COLOR=008040>between</FONT><br>
<FONT SIZE=4 COLOR=008040><B>NATIONAL UNION OF MINEWORKERS</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=3 COLOR=008040>and</FONT><br>
<FONT SIZE=4 COLOR=008040><B>CHAMBER OF MINES OF SOUTH AFRICA</B><P></FONT>



<IMG SRC="/images/linegr.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><p>
<IMG SRC="/images/wd1.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><br>


<FONT SIZE=4><B>I N D E X</B></FONT>
</center>
<ul>
<blockquote>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><li><A HREF="#partie">Parties and Scope</a><br>
<li><A HREF="#guide">Guidelines</A><br>
<li><A HREF="#appro">Appropriate Level</A><br></B></FONT>
</blockquote>
<p></UL>

<Center><IMG SRC="/images/linegr.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE><p></Center>


<p>

<A NAME="partie"></A>
<dl>
<dt><B>1. PARTIES AND SCOPE </B><BR>
<dd>
1.1. It is recorded that this framework agreement is entered into by the Chamber on behalf of gold and coal mines, members of the Chamber, which recognises the NUM and by the NUM on behalf of its members employed in recognised bargaining units on such gold and coal mines.<p>

<A NAME="guide"></A>

<dt><B>2.GUIDELINES</B><p>
<dd>
2.1. In consideration of the agreement entered into on 7 October 1994 the parties agreed that joint discussions should take place at the appropriate level identified in 3 below on Adult Basic Education and Training in accordance with the following framework of guidelines: <p>

<dl>
<dd>2.1.1. <b> Definition of Adult Basic Education and Training</b><br>
ABET is the basic education and training phase in the provision of life-long learning which has exit points of equivalence with that of compulsory education and consists of levels along a continuum of learning.  The skills and knowledge acquired in ABET programmes should be assessed as competencies.<p>

<dd>2.1.2. <b> Aims of ABET Programmes </b><br>
ABET programmes for employees should be aimed at the following:<p>

<dl>
<dd> 2.1.2.1. To provide workers with an education and training base for further learning.<p>

<dd> 2.1.2.2. To develope workers' skills and knowledge to participate more actively in the process of change within the mining industry and in the country as a whole.<p>

<dd> 2.1.2.3. To contribute towards removing all discriminatory barriers within the industry particularly racial.</dt><p>

</dl>
<dd> 2.1.3. <b> Principles</b><p>

<dl>

<dd> 2.1.3.1. <i> Legitimacy</i><br>
Have legitimacy for both providers and learners in terms of achieving the agreed aims of ABET programmes.<p>

<dd> 2.1.3.2. <i> Integration</i><br>
Form part of a system of human resources development which provides for the establishment of an integrated approach to education and training.<p>

<dd> 2.1.3.3.<i> Coherence and Flexibility</i><br>
Adhere to principles and frameworks for certification which may be established at national or industry level, but allow the flexibility required to meet the needs of learners and providers.  To this end, both parties are committed to contributing towards the establishment of a national system for ABET.<p>

<dd> 2.1.3.4. <i> Involvement</i> <br>
Provide for the participation of all stakeholders, including Trade Unions, in the planning and provision of access to ABET.<p>
Stakeholders include at least management, learners, unions and providers.<p>

<dd>2.1.3.5.<i> Standards</I><br>
Be based on clearly identified standards expressed as ABET competencies.<p>
(Competence here is used in the broadest sense of the word.  It recognises that  performance is founded in not only skill but also knowledge and udnerstanding.  Furthermore, it accepts that competence involves the ability to perform in different contexts and the capacity to transfer knowledge and skills to new tasks and situations.)<p>

<dd> 2.1.3.6. <i>Access</i><br>
Provide access to ABET for all employees.<p>

<dd> 2.1.3.7. <i> Articulation</i><br>
Provide for learners to move, on successful completion of accredited units of learning, from one component in the certification framework to another.<p>

<dd>2.1.3.8.<i> Portability</i><br>
Provide for successful learners to transfer their ABET credits or qualifications from one provider or user of ABET qualifications to another.<p>

<dd>2.1.3.9.<i> Recognition of prior learning</i><br>
Give recognition to prior learning.<p>

<dd>2.1.3.10.<i> Voluntarism</i><br>
Allow for individuals to undertake learning on a voluntary basis.<p>

<dd>2.1.3.11.<i> Further Opportunities (Progression)</i><br>
Allow for employees to benefit from learning and employment options aligned with the career paths operational in the company/industry.<p>

<dd>2.1.3.12.<i> Relevance</i><br>
Shall address provider needs at industry and enterprise level. and be relevant to national development needs community development needs and individual development needs.<p>

NOTE : No agreement on the proposal on the right to paid educational leave was reached.<br>
</dl><p>

<dd>2.1.4. <b>Framework Guidelines</b><p>
<dl>
<dd>2.1.4.1. <i> Levels</i><br>
There should be 4 levels with the final exit point being equivalent to Level 1 of the National Qualifications Framework (NQF), as per Appendix A.<p>

<dd>2.1.4.2.<i> Subject Areas/Areas of Learning</i><br>
Language and mathematics form the foundation of general education as the basis for communication and problem solving capabilities within a wide range of applications.<br>

ABET should consist of the above subjects/areas of learning, plus further subjects/areas of learning as agreed upon at the appropriate level among stakeholders.<p>

Subjects/areas of learning could be structured for registration on the NQF as unit standards at appropriate levels.<p>

<dd>2.1.4.3.<i> Standards, Competencies and Outcome Statements</i><br>
Unit Standards are expressed in terms of nationally agreed and registered outcome statements (i.e. competency based approach).<p>

The standard setting process will be structured in terms of the NQF Act.<p>

A format acceptance to the South African Qualifications Authority (SAQA) should be used for the purpose of registering standards.<p>

<dd>2.1.4.4.<i> Assessment and Recognition of Prior Learning (RPL)</i><br>
Assessment is a process of collecting and interpreting evidence of competency and may take the form of initial, formative or summative procedures.<p>

RPL means the assessment of what a learner can achieve against the performance criteria described in unit standards and the subsequent recognition of that achievement.<p>

<dd>2.1.4.5.<i> Evaluation of existing ABET in terms of the National Qualificaitons Framework</i><p>

ABET should be aligned with the NQF which focuses on nationally agreed standards, outcomes and competencies.<br>

ABET should be evaluated in terms of the Aims and Principles of the ABET Framework.<p>

<dd>2.1.4.6.<i>Development of Education, Training and Development (ETD) Practitioners within the field of ABET</i><br>
ETD practitioners should be competent, and accredited as such with SAQA on the NQF.<p>

Selection criteria and the procedure for adherence to such criteria should be jointly agreed at the appropriate level.<p>

ETD practitioners should be afforded development apportunities in terms of the Principles of this Agreement.<p>

<dd>2.1.4.7.<i> Guidelines for Governance</i><br>
The Industry will be guided on issues of governance by the NQF Act.<p>

Governence of ABET at the appropriate level should occur in accordance with the Principles notably 2.1.3.4. - (Involvement) of ABET Framework.<p>

<dd>2.1.4.8.<i> Guidelines for an Integrated Approach to Education and Training</i><br>
The proposed structures and principles of the NQF will provide for an itegrated approach to education and training.<p>

<dd>2.1.4.9.<i> Guidelines for Accreditation</i><br>
The South African Qualifications Authority (SAQA) will, in terms of the NQF Act, accredit appropriate industry bodies to ensure that the requirements for registration and accreditation of standards are met.<p>

<dd>2.1.4.10.<i> Guidelines for Career Paths for Learners</i><br>
ABET programmes, learning paths and career paths should be developmed within integrated Human Resource Development (HRD) strategy at the appropriate level.<p>

The relationship between learning paths and career paths should be established in accordance with the Aims and Principles of the ABET Framework.<p>
</dl>

<dt>2.1.5. <b>Delivery Guidelines</b><p>

<dd>2.1.5.1.<i> Management Information Systems</i><p>
Disclosure of all information relevant to ABET should be provided by employers to joint structures to assist decision making.<p>

Key areas of information required should be periodically identified for the purpose of implementation of this agreement.<p>

A record of learning will be kept for each learner.<p>

<dd>2.1.5.2.<i>Infrastructure and Resources</i><p>
The infrastructure and resources supporting ABET such  as employer/union structures, funding facilities, support services and  human resources should be aimed at the efficient and effective use of resources and learning methodologies.<p>

Corporate and/or Mine conditions will determine infrastructure and resources.<p>

<dd>2.1.5.3.<i> Access</i><p>
Access to provision of ABET 1 in workers' languages should be provided.<p>

The physical location of mine ABET classes should be accessible.<p>

Access for disabled employees should be particularly addressed.<p>

Employees have preferential access to ABET programmes.  Family of employees may be provided access to ABET.  This will depend on individual mines' circumstances and must be agreed at the appropriate level.<p></dt></dl>

<A NAME="appro"></A>
<dt>3. <b>APPROPRIATE LEVEL</B><P>

<dd>3.1. The parties agree that the joint discussions referred to in 2.1. will take place between representatives of the NUM, of the one part, and each of the mining companies concerned, of the other part, at the appropriate level which is set out below: 

<B> Anglo American, Anglovaal, Gengold, Ingwe, JCI and Randgold</B> respectively<p>
Each mining company in the mining group concerned in a co-ordinated group forum and thereafter discussions on details with each mine.<p>

<B> Amcoal </b> <p>
Company in central forum<p>

<B> Alpha Anthracite, Duiker, Duiker Coal, Kangra and Gold Fields</b><p>

Mines in each group in a central forum subject to disucssions on details, where appropriate, at mine level.<p>  


 









<p>
<FONT SIZE=4 COLOR=800040><Center><B>Signed by the National Union of Mineworkers and the Chamber of Mines <br>on behalf of recognising mines at Johannesburg on this 13 day of July 1995.</B></Center></FONT>
<p>
