<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 30 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>




GOLD MINES REPORT A PROFITABLE QUARTER <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gold producers had a bumper quarter with the higher gold price received kicking through into better profit across the sector, analysts believe.  But in this quarter, as the precipitous fall in the dollar gold price begins to make its mark, profit will decline.<BR><P>
GENCOR PARTNER FACES TAKEOVER BY CANADIANS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Australian company with which South African group Gencor was jointly developing the Maggie Hays nickel deposit, Forrestania Gold NL, was facing a takeover bid after Vancouver-based Lionore Mining International said it had secured funding for the bid.<BR><P>
JCI TO EXPAND ITS MINING INTERESTS IN AFRICA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
JCI has outlined further plans for mining projects in Africa, including moves to optimise the technical and economic aspects of its R2,5bn hot briquetted iron project planned for Mozambique and Zimbabwe.<BR><P>
ESKOM FACES SUIT FOR COAL POLLUTION <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The Legal Resources Centre is considering bringing a civil suit against Eskom, the state-owned electricity generator, for environmental pollution in Mpumalanga province, a spokesman from the Centre said yesterday.<BR><P>
RAINING ON INGWE'S PARADE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Ingwe Coal was one of the most favoured stocks on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange last year, with many analysts punting for the share to make rapid gains. <BR><P>
HERO'S SEARCH FOR TRAPPED MINERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WELKOM - Rovic diamond mine overseer Kobus Olivier worked all night to rescue trapped miners, one of whom was his best friend, during a mudrush, he said in an interview at the Free State mine yesterday.<BR><P>
GOOD MOVE BY THE RESERVE BANK <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
So the Reserve Bank wants to pull out of the forward foreign exchange market, where it is estimated to have racked up heavy losses for this fiscal year?  No problem.  Enter the Eurorand market, which, according to many bank officials, provides a natural alternative to forward currency cover from the central bank.<BR><P>
STATE STARTS TO RELEASE RDP FUNDS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The government, with an eye on the 1999 elections, was earnestly beginning to release funds for its reconstruction and development programme, Jacques Magliolo, a financial author and investment strategist, said yesterday.<BR><P>
MARKET SIGNALS EASING OF PRESSURE ON RAND <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Foreign exchange inflows, which caused the money market shortage to fall to below R9bn this week, is another signal that pressure on SA's currency and foreign exchange reserves was easing.<BR><P>
GOVT 'IS PLAYING GAMES WITH LABOUR' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government was playing games with labour as state enterprise managers ran roughshod over unions and failed to consult them before starting privatisation initiatives, Mineworkers' Union acting general secretary AC van Wyk said yesterday.<BR><P>
LABOUR ACT CURBS HIRING AND FIRING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The new Labour Relations Act, which provided recourse for job applicants to approach the Labour Court with complaints of discrimination, might cause some employers to yearn for the "good old days" when they could hire and fire at will.<BR><P>
GAUTENG NP IN PUSH FOR PROVINCIAL CONSTITUTION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The opposition National Party in the Gauteng provincial legislature yesterday submitted a proposal to the rules committee, which is due to sit today, for the establishment of a committee to "consider the merits of having a provincial constitution".<BR><P>
WORLD BANK PRESIDENT TO VISIT SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
World Bank president James Wolfensohn is to visit SA next month.  He will arrive on February 15 for meetings with government leaders as well as representatives of the private sector and the labour movement.<BR><P>
NUM SAYS CHROME MINE STRIKE IS OVER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers yesterday said 1 000 workers at the Chromebronne Mining Division and Cashane Plant had ended an eight-day strike after the company agreed to meet demands for an 11%-15% increase.<BR><P>
SWAZILAND ANGRY AT COSATU INTERFERENCE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Swaziland government has lodged a complaint with the South African High Commission in Mbabane over the Congress of South African Trade Unions' (Cosatu) interference in the domestic affairs of the country, which was regarded as direct interference by the South African government.<BR><P>
PRISONERS 'WILL BE RELEASED GRADUALLY ' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Correctional Services Department on Monday confirmed 25% of inmates in SAs jails could soon be released on correctional supervision.<BR><P>
LABOUR PARTY SENDS MEMBERS TO SET UP LOCAL BRANCHES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The British Labour Party is forming branches in SA to mobilise the more than 1-million British citizens living in the country.<BR><P>
</DOC>
