<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 29 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



IMPROVED PERFORMANCE, PROFITABILITY AT AVGOLD <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Avgold turned in a 41% increase in its operating surplus, to R102m, in the December quarter as the Hartebeestfontein and Loraine divisions improved performances and ET Cons returned to profitability.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD LOOKS AT 'BRANDING' GOLD <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Randgold, SA's smallest gold producer, is considering putting its name on its gold products to cash in on international consumers' eagerness to help the country overcome the legacy of apartheid.<BR><P>
CLOSURE OF SHAFT RESULTS IN LOSS OF 640 JOBS AT ERPM <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The closure of a loss-making shaft at Randgold-managed East Rand Proprietary Mines could cut its December quarter operating profit by two-thirds to R6m in the current quarter.<BR><P>
ANGLO RACES FOR BRAZILIAN MINING GROUP <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Anglo American and its foreign minerals division, Minorco, have emerged as the leading contenders in Brazil's plans to sell a controlling interest in Companhia Vale do Rio (CVDR), the country's largest mining company, Brazilian sources said yesterday.<BR><P>
MINER THOUGHT HE WAS GOING TO DIE IN MUD FLOOD <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WELKOM - Berek Losper, the last of 34 miners rescued from the Rovic diamond mine after mud flooded into it from an adjacent open-cast mine in November, told an inquiry yesterday that he had thought he was going to die.<BR><P>
RAND RALLY CONTINUES FOR FIFTH DAY <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The rand continued its relentless march forward yesterday, strengthening for the fifth day in a row to hit R4,5650 in late trade from R4,5840 late on Monday.<BR><P>
INFLATION HELD IN CHECK DESPITE WEAK RAND <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Inflation ticked up to 9,4% in December last year from 9,2% in November - a small increase which encouraged economists to predict that the rate of change in the consumer price index would remain in single digits.<BR><P>
SA CONSUMERS IN FOR TOUGH YEAR, SAYS OLD MUTUAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
South African consumers are in for a tough year, with higher inflation and taxes expected to erode their real spending power, Old Mutual warns in its latest economic monitor.<BR>
<B><I>... and yet ...</I></B><BR>
YEAR OF GROWTH AHEAD <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
While most others forecast a year of decline, Old Mutual chief economist Dave Mohr sees SAs economy consolidating this year before taking off strongly in 1998. In what was described by many as the most optimistic economic growth forecast this year, Mohr predicted a 2,5% growth rate this year.<BR>
<B><I>... and, as if were not sufficiently confused ...</I></B><BR>
SPENDING STILL A PROBLEM <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The government might beat its budget deficit target this fiscal year, but this would not be the result of better fiscal discipline, Dave Mohr, chief economist at Old Mutual, said yesterday.  <BR><P>
DEMAND FOR CREDIT SEEN SLOWING DOWN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Money supply and credit growth fell sharply in December, fuelling bullish sentiment on interest rates and confirming the view in the markets that economic fundamentals were moving in the right direction.<BR><P>
EU WARNS SA ON DELAY IN CLINCHING TRADE DEAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The European Union has accepted SA's intention to grant better market access to its African neighbours, but has warned that such initiatives should not take long, as Pretoria could lose out on the benefits of greater access to the EU.<BR><P>
'MAJORITY OF NEW ACCOUNTANTS LEAVE SA' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Three-quarters of SA's chartered accountants leave the country soon after qualifying and only about a third of them return, research by international auditing firm Deloitte & Touche shows.<BR><P>
COSATU CONTEMPLATES MASS ACTION OVER BILL (BD Pg.3)
Government and business could face mounting pressure from the Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu), the country's largest trade union federation,  to review their respective positions on proposed employment standards legislation as the organisation contemplates a programme of mass action.<BR><P>
MILLIONS PAID TO FUND UNNECESSARILY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Millions of rands in unnecessary premiums were being paid to the Workmen's Compensation Fund, a Johannesburg risk management company claimed yesterday.<BR><P>
RUSSIAN PLATINUM STOCKPILES 'MIGHT SUSTAIN ABNORMAL SALES' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Uncertainty still surrounded the true state of Russian platinum stockpiles and it was probable they could still sustain abnormal sales above production levels for two to three more years, platinum analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
RUSSIAN GOLD INDUSTRY SETS SIGHTS ON EXCHANGE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
LONDON - Russia's cash-strapped gold mining industry hopes to see a gold exchange open in Moscow in coming months, a banker with close ties to the industry said yesterday.<BR><P>
R450M PAYOUT FOR FREEDOM FIGHTERS <I>(Cape Times,Cape Town)</I><BR>
Thousands of former liberation movement members and political activists are to receive pension grants in recognition of years of sacrifice and hardship - a process that will cost the government R450-million this year alone.  The pension pay-outs are projected to run for a 50-year period and will be overseen by a five-member special pensions board that will have sole discretion on who will receive pensions.<BR><P>
MBEKI OFF FOR TALKS WITH WEF LEADERS <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki leaves for Davos, Switzerland, today for the annual; informal gathering of world economic leaders hosted by the World Economic Forum <I>[where] </I>he will lead a discussion on "Globalisation and Development: Win-Win or Winner Take All" on Friday.<BR><P>
CONFIRMATION FOR TRILLION AT KALAHARI GOLD <I>(African Mining Bulletin - 29/1/97)</I><BR>
Trillion Resources (based in Canada) has confirmed and refined previous 
interpretations of the regional geology at its Kalahari Gold Project in 
Botswana (not to be confused with West Rand Consolidated Mine's recently 
commissioned Kalahari Goldridge mine across the border in South Africa), 
having drilled 30 of a planned 60-hole diamond drilling programme.<BR>
<I>[Link to <A HREF="http://www.mining.co.za">AMB </A> or through the "Other Mining News Sources" segment below - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
BURKINA FASO GOLD CONFIRMED <I>(AMB)</I><BR>
BOGORE - Randgold Resources has confirmed gold mineralisation at its Bogore target 
in the Liliga region. After extensive trenching and four boreholes, the 
company reports a minimum strike length of 1,250 m, average width of 20 m 
and down to 130 m deep; estimated grade is 1,5 g/t.<BR><P>
POSSIBLE GOLD LINE AT GHANAIN PROJECT <I>(AMB)</I><BR>
Drilling at Opawica Explorations' Asankrangwa licence has indicated a 
potential gold zone along a 2km strike length where drilling has 
intersected 2m of 35g/t, 2m of 13g/t and 8m of 2,23g/t gold, all 
within 20m from surface. <BR><P>
PROMISING RESULTS IN NIELLE PERMIT IN IVORY COAST <I>(AMB)</I><BR>
A 2400m long mineralised shear zone has been identified by trenching at the 
Tongon target in Randgold Resources'  Nielle permit. Borehole results 
include: 2,8g/t over 37m; 1,1g/t over 12m; 2,6g/t over 26m. The 
permit is one of three new prospecting licences granted to Randgold in the 
Ivory Coast recently; the other two are Tehini West and Tehini East.<BR><P>
NEW DEPOSIT FOR RANDGOLD NEAR LOULO IN MALI <I>(AMB)</I><BR>
Randgold Resources has confirmed a new deposit - Yalea - 6km south of its 
Loulo 0 deposit, after trenching over a strike length of 1 400m returned an 
average grade of 4,2g/t over 20m. <BR><P>
RMB BACKS MANAGEMENT BUY-OUT AT CBR MINING <I>(AMB)</I><BR>
RMB Resources - the mineral resource division of Rand Merchant Bank - last 
month announced it had become a funding partner in the continuing 
development of CBR Mining, a colliery near Newcastle in KwaZulu-Natal 
province.<BR><P>
SINKING AT SOUTH DEEP GOES ON <I>(AMB)</I><BR>
Shaft sinking in the main shaft at South Deep - part of JCI's Western Areas 
Gold Mine - has fully recommenced after the  successful recovery from the 
water inrush.  In addition to the cover drilling and cement grouting 
originally planned, extra drilling and grouting is taking place to minimise 
the possibility of another inrush of water.<BR><P>
DRILLING TO START AT BWANA MKUBWA, ZAMBIA <I>(AMB)</I><BR>
The first stage of exploration is to start at First Quantum Minerals' Bwana 
Mkubwa project in Zambia next month, comprising a 36-hole reverse 
circulation drilling programme to test eastward and westward strike 
extensions to the BM orebody. <BR><P>
AVMIN ALL SET FOR KONKOLA NORTH <I>(AMB)</I><BR>
Anglovaal's minerals division, Avmin, recently won the option to 
acquire a majority interest in Konkola North property, and should sign the 
option agreement this month. <BR><P>
</DOC>
