<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 28 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>




RANDGOLD MINES TURN IN RECORD QUARTERLY RESULTS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The mines managed by Randgold turned in their best quarterly aggregate results yet in the December quarter, boosting taxed profit 69% to R126,6m amid plans to list African exploration arm Randgold Resources in London by next year.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
RANDGOLD PUSHES NET PROFIT UP 179% <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Randgold, the country's sixth-largest gold producer, continued its impressive run of results this quarter after it pushed after-tax profit ahead by 179% to R126,6m.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD RESOURCES DETAILS BASE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Randgold Resources Ltd. on Monday said it had defined a resource base of nine-million ounces in four countries and was evaluating several new discoveries.  The company, which is active in west and central Africa, said this followed the take-over of BHP Minerals Mali, including the Syama Gold Mine, its first gold mine, in October last year.<BR><P>
HARMONY SEEKS TO INCREASE DIRECT GOLD SALES <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Harmony Gold Mining Company will seek permission from SA's Reserve Bank to market more than the current third of its gold directly, managing director Bernard Swanepoel said on Monday.<BR><P>
ROVIC MINE INQUIRY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A preliminary inquiry into the Rovic diamond mine disaster, in which 20 miners died, began in Welkom in the Free State yesterday.<BR><P>
WORLD'S BIGGEST BANK PREDICTS RAND'S REVIVAL <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi, the world's largest bank, has forecast that the rand could trade as low as R4,40 to the dollar in the second half of the is year, Kenji Yoshizawa, the bank's deputy president and head of its foreign division, said last week.<BR><P>
RAND GAINS ON SWISS BANK REPORT <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The rand hit a two-month high against the dollar yesterday, reaching R4,5845 in late trade from R4,6155 late on Friday.  Sentiment over the currency received a large boost in the morning from the release of a currency report by the Union Bank of Switzerland on Friday that said it was undervalued and should fall no further than R4,85 by the end of the year.<BR><P>
FOREIGN INVESTORS SIGNAL CONFIDENCE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The rand pierced the key level of R4,60 to the dollar yesterday as foreign investors signalled that SA had become a buying opportunity after last year's disastrous performance.<BR><P>
RUSTENBURG EXPECTS ADDITIONAL PROFIT <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Rustenburg Platinum Mines could expect an additional R7m profit in the year to June 30 from chrome production at its Union section, officials said.<BR><P>
JOHNNIC TRADE UNIONS NET R9M THROUGH SHARE DEAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Trade unions involved in Johnnic made R9m through a financial arrangement with certain institutions which paid a premium for a portion of Johnnic shares, union sources said.<BR><P>
AMPLATS GEARS UP TO FILL GAP AS RUSSIAN SUPPLIES DECLINE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The world's largest producer of platinum, Anglo American Platinum Corporation, sees Russian supplies declining and is gearing itself to fill some of the gap.<BR><P>
$300M TO BE SPENT ON ZAMBIAN MINE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Cyprus Amax Minerals Co. was expected to spend up to $300m in developing Zambia's Kansanshi copper mine after feasibility studies had been made, Mines Minister Christon Tembo said yesterday.<BR><P>
ANGLO TESTS DUAL FINANCIAL REPORTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Could improved financial reporting raise the ratings of SA's gold shares on international markets?  Anglogold is about to find out.  It hopes to improve overseas investors' understanding of its mines with a move to dual reporting:  it will publish figures which are comparable to those of North American and Australian mining houses, as well as those based on South African accounting methods.<BR><P>
NEW RESERVE BANK DEPUTY GOV. <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Reserve Bank's newest deputy governor, James Cross, would head all foreign exchange and capital markets for the Bank, governor Chris Stals said last night.<BR><P>
SADC TRADE IS BOOSTED 12% BY SA, MAURITIUS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
GABORONE - Intra-regional trade in the Southern African Development Community has increased 12,4% since SA and Mauritius joined, according to a report from the organisation.<BR><P>
AGREEMENTS SETTLING ARMSCOR'S INDICTMENT SIGNED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - Agreements settling Armscor's 1991 embargo-busting indictment have been signed and only await approval by a federal judge in Philadelphia.  Assuming Judge Jan Dubois approves the agreement - which is considered almost certain - and his schedule allows, the long-running irritant in relations between the US and SA should be resolved in time for US Vice-President Al Gore's visit to SA next month for the third meeting of the US-SA Binational Commission.<BR><P>
RELATIONS BETWEEN ILO AND WTO 'COULD IMPROVE' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The International Labour Organisation's relations with the World Trade Organisation could improve now that the inclusion of a social clause in international trade agreements was no longer on the agenda, ILO director-general Michael Hansenne said on his arrival in SA yesterday.<BR><P>
LOMÉ TO BRING SA CLOSER TO FINAL EU DEAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The conclusion of a comprehensive trade deal with the European Union was brought one step closer after SA emerged from weekend talks confident that details of its membership to the Lomé convention could be finalised next month.<BR><P>
SWEDEN WELCOMES MORE SA EXPORTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
STOCKHOLM - The Swedish government was not satisfied with the trade imbalances created by the small amount of exports from SA, outgoing Swedish Trade Minister Bjorn von Sydow said yesterday.<BR><P>
DP TABLES 'VICTIM'S BILL' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Victims of violent crime will have the right to be compensated by the perpetrators, or failing this, by the state - if the Democratic Party has its way.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
CRIME WILL DECLINE IF CRIMINALS FEEL UNSAFE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The experience of the US is that the likelihood of being caught and heavily punished is the greatest deterrent to would-be criminals.<BR><P>
DISABLED WORKERS MAY FINALLY GET THEIR PLACE IN THE SUN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Not only does the new Labour Relations Act prevent employers from discriminating against the disabled, but future legislation is likely to extend these rights by ensuring that employers provide for disabled people in the workplace.<BR><P>
NEW DAILY FOR SA <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Malaysias largest newspaper group will start publishing a newspaper in SA later this year, group MD Mohamed Noor Mutalib said in Kuala Lumpur yesterday. The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Ltd. Is getting a licence and negotiating with potential partners, he said. The newspaper will be a daily, published simultaneously from several cities, but distributed nationwide.<BR><P>
BILL GATES TO VISIT SA <I>(summarised from The Star - Computing, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Americas richest man and most respected executive, Microsoft founder and CEO Bill Gates is expected to visit SA early in March to meet customers, Microsoft SA staff and, possibly, President Nelson Mandela.<BR><P>
