<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 27 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



MINING INDUSTRY HIT BY SECOND TIMBER PRICE HIKE <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The South African mining industry has been hit by the second large timber price rise in two years, a result of the weakening of the rand coupled with increased pulp demand and reduced timber availability.<BR><P>
ISCOR MOVES ON MINE DISPUTE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Iscor has renewed talks with Namibian company PE Minerals, which owns the mineral rights of base metal producer Rosh Pinah, in an attempt to settle a long-standing dispute over the mine. <BR><P>
WEAK PLATINUM PRICE KNOCKS AMPLATS <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SA's platinum industry might be forced to reduce production if the price of the precious metal does not improve, Barry Davison, the managing director of Anglo American Platinum (Amplats), said on Friday.<BR><P>
PRESSURE ON DE BEERS TO MOVE H.O. TO SA <I>(Sake-Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
LONDON - Thousands of job opportunities in the British capitals diamond district are under threat as a result of the commission of enquiry into the diamond industry appointed by President Nelson Mandela. Pressure is mounting on diamond giant De Beers to return its sales offices throughout the world to SA to create job opportunities locally, <I>The Guardian </I>reported yesterday.<BR>
<B><I>... meanwhile ...</I></B><BR>
DE BEERS DENIES DIAMOND CUTTING MOVE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
De Beers Consolidated Mines will not be moving its diamond cutting centre to SA from London, the company said in response to a report in <I>The Guardian</I>, a UK newspaper, that the South African government has set up a commission to investigate bringing the cutting operations to the country.<BR><P>
SA GOLD OUTPUT ON DECLINING TREND <I>(Business Times, with the Sunday Times)</I><BR>
Forecasts from the biggest gold producer of a flat output in 1997 suggest the country as a whole once again may struggle to produce 500 tons this year.  Chamber of Mines economist Roger Baxter said on Thursday he expected final 1996 production to come in around 494 to 495 tons from 522,4 tons in 1995, with output in 1997 likely to be similar.<BR><P>
<B><I>... but ...</I></B><BR>
DON'T PANIC, GOLD WILL SHINE THROUGH THE MURK <I>(Business Times)</I><BR>
Don't panic is the message from Anglogold's marketing director Kelvin Williams on the current weakness in the gold price.  He said Anglo does not see a sea-change in the long-term market for gold.<BR><P>
RESERVE BANK WILL REVISE GOLD EXPORTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Reserve Bank is to revise upwards the figures for net gold exports in the second and third quarters of last year - which means the current account deficit was better and capital flows worse than originally estimated.<BR><P>
US EXPERTS EYE RAND RISKS AMID SA REFORMS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
NEW YORK - Even as SA's valiant struggle to build a prosperous democracy inspires growing confidence, US experts warned that political and speculative risk still pose a material threat to the value of the rand.<BR><P>
SWISS NATIONAL BANK RULES OUT GOLD SALES FOR NOW <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
ZURICH - The Swiss National Bank cannot sell any of its gold reserves until the country's constitution is amended in a reform process that could take years, SNB Chairman Hans Meyer told a Swiss newspaper.<BR><P>
STRONG MOVEMENTS FORECAST IN KEY ECONOMIC INDICATORS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The consumer inflation rate, money supply growth and private-sector credit extension growth, arguably the three most closely watched economic indicators, will be released this week. On Friday, a Reuters poll of economists produced a range of forecasts for the December inflation rate from 9,3 to 9,9%.<BR><P>
NEDCOR SEES GROWTH SLOWING TO 2% <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SAs economic growth was likely to slow down to around 2% of gross domestic product next year from an estimated 3% last year, banking group Nedcor said in an economic review released at the weekend.<BR><P>
DEMOCRACY BRINGS GOOD EXPORT BUSINESS IN AFRICA <I>(Business Times)</I><BR>
The transition to democracy has exposed SAs exporters to new markets north of the Limpopo and they have taken quick advantage of it.<BR><P>
WHAT KIND OF FORCE IS HOLDING UP THE RAND? <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The rand has appreciated against the dollar in the past two weeks because of the Reserve Bank's intervention in the market, and not because of fundamental economic indicators, which remain weak, Charles Jonker, the treasury economist at Absa Bank, said on Friday.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
THE RAND ENDS STRONGER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The rand ended 4c stronger against the dollar on Friday at R4,6080 - its best level in almost two months - after starting the week at R4,6590.<BR><P>
FIVE SA GROUPS RANKED AMONG TOP 500 <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
LONDON - Five SA companies have been ranked among the Financial Times Top 500 global corporations, although well down the list.  They are Anglo American Corporation at 208, De Beers (257), SA Breweries (408), Liberty Life (448) and Sasol (473).<BR><P>
TOUGHER INSIDER TRADING RULES INCLUDE JSE NEWS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Tough new measures are planned to crack down on insider trading, including proposals for more stringent laws and the introduction of a new system at the Johannesburg Stock Exchange to control the release of price sensitive information.<BR><P>
BUSINESS TO HELP PROTECT WITNESSES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
South African businesses would not only provide jobs for people in witness protection programmes, but would also fund the training of those not suitable for employment in the private sector, Business Against Crime MD Eric Tocknell said this weekend.<BR><P>
MP'S FINANCIAL INTERESTS OPEN TO PUBLIC <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
For a fee of R5, and a written undertaking not to use the information for commercial gain, the public will be able to gain access to the newly created public register of MPs' financial interests.<BR><P>
ENVIRONMENT POLICY URGENTLY NEEDED IN SA, SAYS MINISTER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Environmental Affairs and Tourism Minister Pallo Jordan said there was an extreme urgency for government to have a comprehensive environmental policy in place to address problems inherited from the apartheid past.<BR><P>
SA, EU FACE EARLY DEADLINE IN TALKS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Negotiators from SA and the European Union emerged yesterday from the first round of talks determined to intensify efforts to reach agreement next month in Pretoria's accession to the Lomé Convention.<BR><P>


