<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 24 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>


ANGLOGOLD COMMITS ITSELF TO MODERNISING <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The gold mines managed by Anglo American Corporation lifted aggregate available profit 9% to R340,8m in the December quarter due to higher production and a higher price received.<BR><P>
VAAL REEFS NEW CALENDAR <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Vaal Reefs on Thursday said it planned to implement a new working calendar which could add 25 additional shifts to the mine's operational year.<BR><P>
CONS MODDER HIT BY 30KG GOLD THEFT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Consolidated Modderfontien Mines posted profit of R2,5m for the December quarter as profit was hit by the theft of 30kg of gold during the quarter, mine management Golden Dumps said.<BR><P>
MESSINA'S FALL AND RISE <I>(Business Mail, Fridays with the Mail & Guardian)</I><BR>
Foreign investors have given another much-needed capital injection into the economy with the purchase of one of SA's 2 500 diamond mining concerns.  The Canadian-based, but Bahamas-registered, Becksham Corporation recently acquired Messina Investments for R68,52-million.<BR><P>
FREEGOLD PRODUCES ANOTHER STABLE SET OF RESULTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Free State Consolidated Gold Mines (Freegold), one of the five mining companies serviced by Anglo American Corporation's gold division, Anglogold, turned in another stable quarter for the three months ended December.<BR><P>
GOLD DROPS TO LOWEST LEVEL IN 40 MONTHS <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gold fixed in London at $348 an ounce yesterday afternoon, its lowest level in 40 months.<BR><P>
HEALTHY DECEMBER TRADE SURPLUS FOR SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A 23% drop in imports, mainly due to the rand's fall last year, helped SA produce a healthy R2,04bn trade surplus in December compared with November's R378m, Customs and Excise figures released yesterday showed.<BR><P>
AIR FARES RAISED 10% TO OFFSET THE RAND'S WEAKNESS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
South Africans travelling to international destinations will face a 10% increase in air fares from today.<BR><P>
STALS BELIEVES VALUE OF ASSET SWAPS EXCEEDS R15BN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
An estimated R15bn in asset swaps between SA and foreign institutions had already been executed as institutions took advantage of the opportunity to diversify offshore, Reserve Bank governor Chris Stals said yesterday.  Asset swaps were introduced in July 1995 to allow SAs portfolio investors to obtain foreign assets without materially affecting the foreign exchange reserves.<BR><P>
TRADE AND INDUSTRY MOVING AWAY FROM REGULATORY ROLE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Trade and Industry Department is shifting its previous focus from being a regulatory authority to developing a closer partnership with industry, says recently appointed departmental industrial promotion chief director Tony Heher.<BR><P>
WORLD'S BIGGEST HEADS FOR SA <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi, is to sign an agreement next week with Investment SA, the government-funded national investment promotion agency, to help bring more Japanese investment into the county, the bank said yesterday.<BR><P>
MACRO-ECONOMIC PLAN NOT A ONE-MAN SHOW <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel has staked his credibility on meeting his deficit targets and should not lose sight of other aspects of government's macro-economic strategy - Finance Minister Trevor Manuel faces the financial markets' acid test on credibility this year when it comes to implementing the macro-economic strategy.  But Manuel may find that passing muster with the markets, although extremely important, might not be all that is required of him.<BR><P>
SA-EU TRADE DEAL WILL AFFECT THE WHOLE SADC REGION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The negotiations between SA and the European Union over the proposed free trade area, resuming today, are arguably the single most important foreign policy challenge for Pretoria this year.  The deal with the EU cannot be viewed as distinct from the political economy of the Southern African Development Community. <BR><P>
'UK NO LONGER A COMMERCIAL ASYLUM' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Debtors fleeing SA to the UK to seek "commercial asylum" can no longer be assured of safety as a result of SA's return to the Commonwealth and the principle of cross-border recognition of judgements.<BR><P>
GOVT EMPLOYMENT DROPS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Employment at national government level dipped slightly in the third quarter last year after 12 months of rapid expansion, according to Central Statistical Service figures released yesterday.<BR>
<B><I>... and yet ...</I></B><BR>
STILL MORE PUBLIC SERVANTS (<I>Business Report)</I><BR>
Economists criticised the government yesterday for not delivering on its promise to reduce the number of public servants after the Central Statistical Service said the number of staff rose 0,2% in the third quarter of last year.<BR>
<B><I>... meanwhile ...</I></B><BR>
ACCORD ON JOB CREATION 'A KEY PRIORITY' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Labour, government and business would have to begin negotiating an accord within six months on a range of issues aimed at establishing an environment conducive to job creation, Labour Department director-general Sipho Pityana said this week.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
IT'S JOBS, STUPID <I>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
Of all the targets contained in government's Growth, Employment and Redistribution (GEAR) strategy, the employment goals seem the least credible.  Less convincing are the targets for jobs growth - rising to 409 000 jobs, or a 4,3% increase in employment, in 2000.  Indeed latest figures show virtually stagnant employment figures for 1996, as compared with GEAR's projected 126 000 jobs, or 1,3% employment growth.<BR><P>
MANUFACTURING DROPS AGAIN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The manufacturing sector's profitability ratio - net profit as a percentage of turnover - was 4,6% in the third quarter of 1996, 1,2 percentage points lower than a year earlier and the fifth consecutive quarterly decrease, Central Statistical Service said yesterday.<BR><P>
RED TAPE ENTANGLES DEMOCRACY BILL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Despite appearing on a list of legislation due to go to Parliament this year, the Open Democracy Bill, which aims to give citizens more information on public and private institutions, is still caught up in red tape.<BR><P>
BLACKS BEING 'USED TO WIN CONTRACTS' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The insistence by the government that companies bidding for state tenders have black shareholders or be joint ventures was not benefiting black business, a senior official of the National African Chamber of Commerce said yesterday.  A few black individuals were getting rich in return for lending their faces to white firms which used their presence to gain contracts.<BR><P>


