<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 23 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>




WARNING ON AMAZING AIDS CLAIM <I>(The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The University of Pretoria last night warned that a new Aids treatment announced by a team of its researchers yesterday still had to be properly tested. In a late-night statement after a meeting between university authorities and the researchers, the university warned that the promising results from early trials still had to be tested in clinical experiments. But that did not stop the announcement shooting around the world.<BR>
<B><I>... meanwhile ...</I></B><BR>
PRETORIA UNIVERSITY SCIENTISTS PRESENT AIDS DRUG <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The cabinet decided yesterday to consider funding further research into a medicine against AIDS that South African researchers claimed had produced far better results than any other drug.  "We should indeed assist with regard to the encouragement of such research", Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said.  A final decision would be taken later.<BR><P>
SA LABOUR COSTS HIGH, PRODUCTIVITY LOW - LATEST US DATA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The US Commerce Department's Bureau of Economic Affairs (BEA) has just released preliminary country-by-country data on the performance of US companies' foreign operations in 1994.  Some points jump out.  First, there is the one about SA's labour costs.  A South African worker cost his US employer $16 000 in 1994, while generating $6 000 in net income.  A Malaysian cost $9 600 and generated $12 000.<BR><P>
OPTIMISM IN SA DROPS 6% BUT STILL BEATS PESSIMISM <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
South Africans are more pessimistic about the year ahead than they were 12 months ago, according to Markinor International's annual optimism index.  But optimists still constitute the majority and SA is the 13th most optimistic nation out of 49 surveyed.<BR><P>
FIRMS' INERTIA BLAMED FOR LACK OF PRODUCTIVITY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Corporate inertia is the prime cause of the lack of "world class practice" in SA, and also the pervasive international pessimism about the country's ability to compete, says Competitive Strategy MD Laurance Kuper.  Kuper said executives had the choice of either drastically revitalising their companies and repositioning them to learn the way to efficiency fast, or "shoring up comfort zones and securing a low to no profit position right at the tail end of global competitiveness".  He claimed the majority of SAs businesses chose the latter course.<BR><P>
GENCOR RIDES ON ALUMINIUM'S HIGH <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gencor shares moved up smartly over the Christmas holidays and are continuing to ride high on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange.  Even senior Gencor executives are puzzled by the rise, as are most analysts on Diagonal Street.<BR><P>
GOLD PRICE MAY AFFECT TERMS OF JCI DEAL <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The continued weakness in the gold price during the coming weeks could result in Anglo American having to renegotiate the terms of the sale of 34,9% of JCI to the African Mining Group, analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
BLACK MOUNTAIN ON UPWARD TREND <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold Fields of SA's Black Mountain base metal producer could see earnings growth continue if the recent recovery in lead prices continued, following the icy weather which has hit the northern hemisphere over the last few weeks.<BR><P>
MINERS KILLED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Two miners were killed in an underground locomotive accident yesterday at Anglovaal Hartebeestfontein Division near Klerksdorp, southwest of Johannesburg.<BR><P>
EU NEGOTIATORS ARRIVE 'TO LISTEN TO SA' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
European Union negotiators who arrive today for the resumption of co-operation talks with SA tomorrow are hoping to work out a programme of action that will put the stalled discussion firmly on track, sources say.<BR><P>
RAND ON UPWARD MARCH <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The rand's strength continued unchecked yesterday as the currency improved more than 2c against the dollar to reach a seven-and-a-half week high of R4,6325 in late trade, from R4,6545 late on Tuesday.<BR><P>
STALS IN NO HURRY TO CUT MONEY-MARKET SHORTAGE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Chris Stals, governor of the South African Reserve Bank, said yesterday a high money-market shortage helped the authorities keep a rein on bank credit extension and he was in no hurry to see it reduce.<BR><P>
US TO TRADE IN RAND FUTURES (Business Report)<BR><P>
The Chicago Mercantile Exchange has applied for approval to trade futures and options on the rand, it said yesterday.<BR><P>
GOLD SLIDES AS US INFLATION THREAT RECEDES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
US central bank chairman Alan Greenspan's remarks appearing to play down the threat of inflation reverberated around world markets yesterday, depressing the gold price and making the rand and capital markets firm sharply.  The gold price slipped below $350/oz, its lowest level since September 1993.<BR><P>
MANUEL MAY ACHIEVE A RARE FEAT <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
On March 12 Finance Minister Trevor Manuel could achieve a rare feat.  He could table a Budget in parliament which impresses the financial markets and also pleases taxpayers.  The markets may well be impressed that he stuck to his promise to bring the deficit before borrowing down to 4% of gross domestic product (GDP), and there may well be a collective sigh of relief from taxpayers because Manuel managed it without increasing taxes.<BR><P>
1997 MAY SURPRISE ECONOMIC FORECASTERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Optimistic economists got their forecasts wrong in 1996.  Now they are gloomy about 1997 - With a bit of luck, and political ingenuity, 1997 might well display the same perverse pattern as 1996;  notably that of running counter to forecasts by economic soothsayers.  Cast your mind back a year and remember the prosperity predicted, and then remember the bitter pill that characterised our new democracy's mid-term.  Now glance back just a few weeks and recall the doom and gloom that has permeated the latest predictions. Therefore, could it be that 1997 will in fact turn out to be a good year - or at least stabilised enough to provide a foundation for improved prospects?<BR><P>
EASTERN CAPE'S GOVT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Eastern Cape's government is discussing with German consultants an industrial development scheme which would facilitate an injection of up to R28bn into the struggling regional economy.<BR><P>
DEREGULATING LABOUR NOT PATH TO SUCCESS, ILO TOLD <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Deregulated labour markets in some African countries did not necessarily result in successful integration into the global economy, the Southern African Multi-advisory Team director Peter Peet said in Harare yesterday.<BR><P>
'LACK OF LAW, POOR SERVICES HURTING SA' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government must act and stabilise state services whose deterioration, and the insecurity resulting from the lack of law and order, are causing a brain drain that could diminish the country's competitiveness, says Stocks & Stocks chairman Reg Edwards.<BR><P>
US EXPERTS TO ASSIST WITH BORDER CONTROL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A team of US experts on border control arrived in SA yesterday to help bolster the national crime prevention strategy.  Border control was "a critical factor in crime prevention", said Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi yesterday.  His department requested, and will co-ordinate the 10-day visit.<BR><P>
MOVE TO MONITOR FOREIGN BANKS IN SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Registrar of Banks in SA is to begin monitoring the financial position of foreign banks' representative offices from March this year in a move to ensure they do not break the rules when competing with local banks.<BR><P>
GOVT SET TO CLASH WITH UNIONS OVER RETRENCHMENTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government and public service unions are set to clash during negotiations next week over a plan to end a moratorium on forced retrenchments in the public service.<BR><P>
NO QUICK DECISION LIKELY ON SYRIAN ARMS DEAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
No decision would be taken on the controversial R3bn Syrian arms deal until Deputy President Thabo Mbeki had considered a host of issues, including the technology involved and US legislation, cabinet secretary Jakes Gerwel said yesterday.<BR><P>
LIBYAN DIPLOMAT IN SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Libyan Foreign Minister Omar Mustafa Al-Muntasir arrived in SA yesterday for a short visit, including talks with counterpart Alfred Nzo on the pending Organisation of African Unity council of ministers' meeting in Tripoli in February.<BR><P>
BLACKS WARNED ABOUT BOARD TOKENISM <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Black executives should guard against accepting single non-executive directorships offered as a way of elevating their status, key businessmen have cautioned.  National Empowerment Consortium chairman Mashudu Ramano said there was a misconception that the more directorships one held the more importance it added to one's stature.<BR><P>
INVESTMENT AGENCY GETS R5,6M <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Investment SA, the investment promotion agency formed by the Trade and Industry Department, has received R5,6m for its first year of operation to attract foreign investment.  Chief Executive Rafig Bagus said these funds would be used for special development initiatives to attract foreign direct investment (such as the Maputo Corridor) and cluster studies identifying sectors which needed to attract investment.<BR><P>
MOTORISTS PAYING R140M A YEAR EXTRA BECAUSE OF OIL COMPANIES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SAs motorists are paying the domestic off-shore gas exploration group, Mossgas, about R140m a year to make up for the pricing shortfall resulting from the oil industry's refusal to pay Mossgas the prices their members get for their own fuel.<BR><P>
RACISTS WANT TO KICK MANUEL OUT <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
White racists are running a campaign - under the guise of markets - to have Finance Minister Trevor Manuel removed from his position, says ANC economic policy adviser Don Mkhwanazi. "The markets are supposed to be colour blind, but in SA the reverse is true. A white finance minister inspires confidence whereas a black one does not," he said.<BR><P>
DECISION BEFORE END OF YEAR ON LOCATION OF PARLIAMENT <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
A decision on the location of SA's Parliament will be made before the end of this year, National Assembly Speaker Frene Ginwala said yesterday.  The ANCs national executive committee would conduct a study and release a discussion document on the matter in the next few months.  This document would form the basis of a discussion on the subject by the ANCs national conference later this year.  Also in the pipeline is the streamlining of co-ordination between government and Parliament, by dropping the position of Leader of the House and replacing it with the Leader of Government Business. <BR><P>
GREEN GROUP MAY TAKE STATE TO COURT <I>(Cape Times)</I><BR>
The government has been threatened with court action unless it withdraws new environmental law proposals which have been described as "big-business friendly".<BR><P>
</DOC>
