<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 22 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>




JCI GOLD MINES SUSTAIN A POSITIVE TREND <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The gold mines managed by JCI sustained the positive trend experienced so far by SA's main producers as the group reported a 3,6% increase in taxed profit to R132,9m for the December quarter.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
RANDFONTEIN ESTATES IS STAR PERFORMER FOR JCI <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Randfontein Estates was the star performer of three gold mining companies managed by JCI, increasing taxed profit 17% to R43,8m in the December quarter.<BR>
<B><I>... but ...</I></B><BR>
CONSOLIDATED MURCHISON IN THE RED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
JCI's antimony producer Consolidated Murchison slipped into the red in the December quarter as increased world supplies caused metal prices to decline about a third from last year's value.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
NEW PARTNERS SOUGHT FOR DEAL WITH JCI <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
African Mining Group, which bought 34,9% of mining house JCI last year, may be on shaky ground after yesterday's announcement that major player Thebe Investments had pulled out four weeks ahead of the deadline to put up the cash for the deal.<BR><P>
GENGOLD SAYS "JURY STILL OUT" ON BEATRIX HEDGE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - The "jury was still out" on the 2,9-million-ounce gold hedge put in place last year to protect investments of Gencor's gold division, Gengold, in its Beatrix Mine development project, Gengold managing director Tom Dale said on Tuesday. <BR><P>
GENCOR TO GAIN FROM SWAP WITHIN MONTHS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Mining group Gencor could be exploiting some of the mineral rights acquired from Anglo American Corporation in last week's swap within 10 months, officials confirmed.<BR><P>
INVESTMENTS AND ZINCOR LIFT GOLD FIELDS' SIX-MONTH RESULTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold Fields posted a 39% rise in attributable income for the six months to December - to R182m from R131m in the year-earlier period - thanks to sharply higher dividend flows from the group's gold investments in addition to resurgent interest earnings and profit from zinc company, Zincor.<BR><P>
NEW DEAL ON UNCUT GEMS EXPECTED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Russia was expected to sign a new agreement soon with De Beers to resume sales of uncut gems through the South African diamond cartel, the authoritative newsletter Diamantaire reported yesterday.<BR><P>
SA GOLD MINES SEEN REVIEWING HEDGE POLICIES <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Eyeing a weak bullion price and wary of a steadier rand, South African gold producers are caught between a rock and a hard place and are likely to review their hedging policies, analysts said.<BR><P>
CHINA TO OPEN FIRST DIAMOND EXCHANGE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SHANGHAI - China's first diamond exchange is likely to open in Shanghai as part of the city's efforts to attract international business and cater for increasingly sophisticated tastes at home.<BR><P>
DECISION ON FUEL PRICE HIKE PROMISED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Minerals and Energy Minister Penuell Maduna has told the oil industry a decision on the 3c/l "marketing margin" price increase it requested early last year will be made by the end of next month.<BR><P>
DIARY FOR NEW LEGISLATION UNVEILED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Parliament released plans yesterday for legislation likely to be presented this year, which suggests that the long-delayed Open Democracy Bill is likely to be presented to cabinet soon.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
BUSY SESSION FOR PARLIAMENT <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
Apart from the debate on the Budget and the departmental votes, Parliament is scheduled to debate 235 pieces of legislation in this years session, which starts on February 7.  With the introduction of the new Constitution on February 3, and the establishment of the National Council of the Provinces in the place of the Senate, there could be some teething problems.<BR><P>
PRETORIA OPTIMISTIC THAT EU TALKS WILL BEAR FRUIT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA was confident of sealing a co-operation agreement with the European Union, including a trade accord, this year, Pretoria's negotiators said yesterday as they publicly unveiled government's negotiating directives with the EU this week.<BR><P>
ANC SETS DEADLINES FOR IMPLEMENTING MACRO-ECONOMIC STRATEGY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Ministries had been given proper targets and deadlines to implement government's macro-economic strategy this year, reaffirming the ANC's commitment to the policy, the party's economic transformation head Tito Mboweni said yesterday.<BR><P>
HINTS OF CABINET POST OFFER FOR DP LEADER TONY LEON <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The government and the Democratic Party played hide and seek yesterday over strong indications that President Mandela had offered Tony Leon, the leader of the small liberal party, a cabinet post during a weekend meeting.<BR><P>
BAN ON PRE-EMPLOYMENT HIV TESTS LIKELY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Pre-employment testing for HIV could be prohibited by the end of the year, if proposals by an SA Law Commission expert group are accepted.<BR><P>
DIPLOMATS STAY TIGHT-LIPPED ON CAPITAL CITY ISSUE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Foreign diplomats would clearly welcome the relocation of Parliament to Pretoria, but would never press the government on the issue or express this opinion publicly, Potchefstroom University political science lecturer Theo Venter said yesterday.<BR><P>
BIG BUSINESS PAINTS A NO-MIRACLE SCENARIO <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The executives of the top 100 industrial companies listed on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange expect a reduction in the prime overdraft rate to 18% by the end of this year, and a further decline in the rand-dollar exchange rate to an average rate of R5,12 for this year.<BR><P>
WORTH ZERO, BUT THAT'S TOO MUCH FOR THE BANK <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
For those dismayed at the rand's falling purchasing power, help is at hand.  Robert Schormann, a Pretoria entrepreneur who runs a company whimsically entitled Megabucks Marketing, has issued a new "banknote" that is sure not to lose any of its value in these inflationary times.  This is mainly because his brainchild, the zero-rand note, is worth nothing to begin with.  Schormann sought legal advice to ensure the note did not fall foul of the Reserve Bank.  "I modified it to the extent that nobody would be fooled", he said.  "It's got zero on it, it says it's not legal tender and it has a big purple monkey on the front".<BR><P>
'FEWER FIRMS' PLAN TO CUT WORK FORCE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Labour turnover has slowed, emigration is down and the number of companies predicting a decline in the size of their work forces has fallen over the past year, a survey released yesterday shows.<BR><P>
CLINTON GOVT 'SENSITIVE TO SA CONCERNS' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
US Ambassador James Joseph called on SA not to view his country's response to SA's R3bn proposed arms deal with Syria as a threat, but to focus on what both countries had accomplished.<BR><P>
