<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 21 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>





GENCOR MINING FIRMS REIN IN COSTS TO LIFT INCOME <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gencor's three operating mining companies - since the merger of its Evander mines late last year - all lifted distributable income on the back of constrained costs in spite of rising gold production during the December quarter - the groups sixth successive quarterly rise in distributable income.<BR><P>
GOLD FIELDS NAMIBIA MINE CLOSED <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gold Fields Namibia said yesterday that its Kombat mine will only reopen in mid-February after flooding shut down the operation only weeks after it reopened following a lengthy strike.<BR><P>
BOCK INTERESTED IN LONRHO AFRICA <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Dieter Bock, the former chief of British mining and trading firm Lonrho, is interested in buying a stake in its African trading activities following a demerger, the <I>Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung</I> said yesterday.<BR><P>
CONSOLIDATED DIAMOND CORP LOOKING TO SELL TO MINORITY SHAREHOLDERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Consolidated Diamond Corporation said today its holding company was considering making an offer to minority shareholders.  If the offer was made and accepted by more than 90% of the minorities, the company's Johannesburg Stock Exchange listing would be terminated.<BR><P>
JOHNNIC'S EARNINGS GROWTH VITAL TO NEC <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Industrial group Johnnic must achieve compound earnings growth of 12%-14% over the next five years if its black empowerment shareholder, the National Empowerment Consortium, is to retain its controlling stake.<BR><P>
GOVT 'WILL MEET BUDGET DEFICIT TARGET' <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The government will meet its 5,1% budget deficit target set for this year, and has every intention of meeting next year's target of 4%, Deputy Minister of Finance Gill Marcus said last night.<BR><P>
STATE ASKS WORLD BANK FOR $46M <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The Trade and Industry Department will apply for a $46-million loan from the World Bank, $21-million less than originally planned, for the part-financing of a project to improve competitiveness, Judith Edstrom, the head of the bank's local office, said yesterday.<BR><P>
ANC TO LOOK AT ELECTION QUOTA & GREATER ROLE FOR COSATU <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The ANC would investigate setting aside a quota on its election lists for SA's biggest labour federation, the Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu) and strengthening the union federation's representation on the organisation's national executive committee, acting secretary-general Cheryl Carolus announced yesterday. <I>[The ruling party has suffered considerable criticism for what critics have labeled its "kowtowing" to the demands of militant labour unions, with many asking whether the government or its alliance partner, Cosatu, was in power. - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
IFP, DP DISCUSS POLICY ISSUES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
DURBAN - The Inkatha Freedom Party and Democratic Party held talks yesterday aimed at developing a common understanding on policy issues, as moves to create an anti-ANC front in the run-up to the 1999 elections gain momentum.<BR><P>
US WANTS SYRIA TO USE ITS TECHNOLOGY - ANC CLAIMS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A new dimension to the reports about the possible sale of South African arms to Syria was opened yesterday when several ANC and government sources suggested that companies using US technology were bidding for the same contracts.  The suggestion being made by the South Africans was that US protestations over the issue were motivated in part by a desire to ensure that its technology was used by the Syrians rather than that of another country.<BR><P>
LABOUR WORKSHOP EXPLORES JOB CREATION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Representatives from 24 African countries gathered in Pretoria yesterday at the start of a five-day International Labour Organisation (ILO) workshop to explore job creation strategies.<BR><P>
