<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 20 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>




BLACK GROUPS OFFERED ANGLO'S BINDURA STAKE <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
HARARE - The Zimbabwe government's R120m stake in Anglo American subsidiary Bindura Nickel is being offered to black businessmen.<BR><P>
GFSA COMPANIES INCREASE EARNINGS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Three Gold Fields of SA investment companies have declared increased earnings at the interim stage:  New Wits lifted taxed profit to R11,1m from R7m, Gold Fields Property Company to R4,4m from R4m and Vogelstruisbult Metal Holdings to R10,8m from R10,2m.<BR><P>
MINERAL RIGHTS DEAL LIFTS VAAL REEFS <I>(Business Times, with the Sunday Times)</I><BR>
Vaal Reefs shares added R10 to R306,75 on Friday after a mineral rights deal secured ground adjacent to its existing lease areas.  <BR><P>
GEM PROBE COMMISSIONED <I>(Business Times)</I><BR>
The government this week appointed a commission of inquiry into its diamond industry to investigate the report on several aspects of the industry.  These include diamond industry legislation, the role of the SA Diamond Board, and the effectiveness of illegal diamond-buying provisions.<BR><P>
THE RAND/DOLLAR <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The rand ended a volatile week on a firm note on Friday, hardening to R4,6485 to the dollar from Thursday's close of R4,6625.<BR><P>
MONEY SUPPLY FAILS TO FOLLOW PREDICTIONS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The daily money market shortage surprised pundits by sticking resiliently at a relatively high R10bn last week - even though the Christmas shopping spree was over the local currency started firming against the dollar.<BR><P>
STALS SEES PROFIT IN CAUTION AS RAND CLIMBS <I>(Business Times)</I><BR>
Reserve Bank Governor Chris Stals is a cautious man.  This week he predicted economic growth of a mere 2% this year, on the conservative side of forecasts by mainstream economists.<BR><P>
ANC WILL REJECT OLD POLICY OF ALLIANCE WITH ISRAEL: MBEKI <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The African National Congress would not follow the previous government's policy of striking an alliance with Israel and being hostile to its Arab neighbours, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said yesterday.<BR><P>
TAIWAN WARNS OF 'INVESTMENT RISKS IN SA' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
TAIPEI - It would not be surprising if many Taiwan-funded firms - especially money-losing textile companies - closed their operations in SA soon, a deputy director of Taiwan's Economics Ministry said yesterday.<BR><P>
ILO HEAD ARRIVES IN SA NEXT WEEK <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
International Labour Organisation director-general Michel Hansenne arrives in SA for his first official visit next Monday and will address two important conferences focusing on employment creation to eliminate poverty in Africa.<BR><P>
MINISTER'S DESK HAS BECOME BOTTLENECK <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government policy-making on minerals has reached a bottleneck, with a draft green paper still awaiting Minerals and Energy Minister Penuell Maduna's approval three months after landing on his desk, industry sources say.<BR><P>
SQUEEZING A FEW EXTRA DROPS OUT OF AN ARID EU TRADE DEAL <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SA's tireless trade negotiators return to the table this week with the task of convincing their European Union counterparts that the development of southern Africa is a cause worth supporting by offering SA preferential trade terms.<BR><P>
OUTLOOK POOR UNLESS STATE WAKES UP FAST <I>(Business Times)</I><BR>
Leading industrialists predict a gloomy future for the economy and are critical of the government's inability to implement strategic policy changes.  Other disturbing factors are lack of action on the high rate of crime, violence, corruption, and deteriorating education standards.<BR><P>
