<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 17 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>









GOLD FIELDS SEES BETTER INDUSTRIAL RELATIONS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gold Fields' mines were in the process of implementing the Myburgh commission's recommendations to cut mine violence, with indications the industrial relations climate at the mines was improving, gold executive director Alan Munro said yesterday.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
GOLD FIELDS GETS FIVE OUT OF SIX RIGHT IN LAST QUARTER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Five of the six gold mines managed by Gold Fields of SA yesterday announced substantially improved profitability in the December quarter, as aggregate working profit rose 34,5% to R347m.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
GOLD FIELDS NOT IN MINING TALKS WITH NAIL <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Gold Fields said on Thursday that black empowerment business group New Africa Investments Ltd. (NAIL) had been speaking to it but not about taking a stake in the group's mining operations.<BR>
<B><I>... and still with Gold Fields ...</I></B><BR>
GOLD FIELDS NAMIBIA  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold Fields Namibia said yesterday that its Kombat copper mine was still flooding and production remained suspended.  Installation of water sealing plugs was proceeding.<BR><P>
LONRHO'S RESULTS BEAT FORECASTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
LONDON - Lonrho comfortably beat forecasts yesterday by increasing pre-tax profit before exceptional items 13% to £170m in the year to September last year.<BR><P>
ANGLO, GENCOR STRIKE DEAL ON MINERAL RIGHTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American and Gencor have agreed to comprehensive rationalisation of their groups' mineral rights which is expected to result in efficient and early exploitation of reserves in the Klerksdorp, Evander and Free State gold fields.<BR><P>
GOLD THIEVES ARRESTED AT HARMONY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
About 20kg of gold concentrate was seized after three suspects were arrested in connection with the theft from Harmony Gold Mine yesterday.  Police said security guards had spotted six men running from Harmony's Merriespruit plant before dawn.  A guard shot and wounded one of the suspects in the leg.  Two others were arrested later.  Eight bags of gold dust were seized.<BR><P>
GOVT REVENUE RISE BEATS BUDGET EXPECTATIONS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government revenue was up a robust 17% in the first nine months of the fiscal year compared with the same period a year ago - a sign that the economy is still healthy.<BR><P>
ACT WILL STREAMLINE EXTRADITION PROCEDURES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
New legislation to streamline extradition procedures would come into effect today, a Justice Department spokesman said yesterday.<BR><P>
TAIWANESE BUSINESSES LAUNCH PROTEST ACTION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA-based Taiwanese manufacturing businesses began protesting yesterday against the "totally unfair and immoral" decision by SA to switch diplomatic recognition to mainland China.<BR><P>
GOVT SETS UP PROJECTS TO DEVELOP INFRASTRUCTURE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government is to test the concept of public-private sector partnerships in the development of municipal infrastructure by launching up to 20 pilot projects this year, Constitutional Development Minister Valli Moosa announced this week.<BR><P>
NEGOTIATORS IN RACE AGAINST TIME TO FINALISE LOMÉ DEAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA and European Union negotiators will have to race against time when they meet next Friday to pave the way for Pretoria's partial accession to the Lomé convention, sources close to the talks have said.<BR><P>
