<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 16 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>







OVERALL MINING PRODUCTION DROPS  <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Total mining production for the three months to October 31 last year dropped by 3,2% compared with the previous three months, the Central Statistical Service said yesterday.<BR><P>
RUSSIANS SAY THEY ARE CLOSE TO APPROVING DEAL WITH DE BEERS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Russian diamond officials reportedly said they were close to approving a new diamond sales deal with De Beers - although a spokesman for the diamond cartel said yesterday it had not received any official communications from Russia since December.<BR><P>
ANGLO DENIES IT IS SELLING STAKE IN SOUTHERN LIFE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Anglo American yesterday said it had no intention of selling its interest in Southern Life, after reports it had entered discussions over the possible sale of a strategic stake in Southern with Worldwide Africa Investments, a black empowerment consortium.<BR><P>
ONCE ON THE DUMP, JOEL COMES UP TRUMPS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Just a few years ago, JCI's HJ Joel gold mine in the Free State was on the point of closure after a series of bad decisions on exploiting the mine's reserves.  The use of trackless (or mechanised) mining systems and the finding of a narrower gold reef than expected led to increased waste mining and higher costs.  But something quite brave has been done at Joel.  A bold decision to revert to traditional mining methods and develop the reef conventionally has turned the mine around.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD SAYS TO MERGE ERPM AND GROOTVLEI <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Randgold said on Wednesday it was merging the management of its East Rand Proprietary Mines and the Grootvlei Proprietary Mines as a precursor to the proposed rationalisation of its interests on the East Rand.<BR><P>
MINERS WELCOME NEW LAW <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The Mine Health and Safety Act, which tightens regulations governing SA's accident-prone <I>[sic] </I>mining industry, came into effect yesterday.  The celebrations were dampened only by the presence of disabled miners for whom the new law was perhaps too late.<BR><P>
GOLD SLUMPS AS US FUNDS SHIFT TO BONDS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Lower-than-expected US inflation figures jolted SA markets yesterday, reversing bullion's short lived revival and trimming almost 3% off the Johannesburg Stock Exchanges all gold index.<BR><P>
DATE SET FOR DIAMOND INQUIRY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A commission of inquiry appointed by President Mandela to investigate and report on several aspects of the South African diamond industry will begin sitting in Johannesburg on 19 February.<BR><P>
AGENCY RETAINS RETRENCHED MINERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Thousands of people in rural communities affected by the downsizing of the mining industry have become self-employed in recent years through the intervention and assistance of the Mineworkers' Development Agency.<BR><P>
OMAR'S BAIL PLANS AROUSES OPPOSITION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Opposition against the proposal by Justice Minister Dullah Omar to refuse bail to people accused of serious offences mounted yesterday with calls that he immediately withdraw it.<BR><P>
MANDELA REFUSES TO BOW TO US IN SYRIAN ARMS SALE ROW <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
If SA changed its mind on selling arms to Syria it would not be due to objections by the US, but because it would not be in the interests of SA, President Mandela said yesterday.<BR><P>
SA DENIES PLANS TO REJECT EU TRADE OFFER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA and the European Union headed off a potential stand-off in their co-operation talks yesterday, denying reports that Pretoria would reject the EU's offer.<BR><P>
ANC PREPARES FOR JOB CREATION PROGRAMME <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
President Mandela and senior ANC members leave today for a four-day meeting at a secret venue where the party will plan a two-year programme, which will largely focus on job creation.<BR><P>
NEW-LOOK PAC ACCEPTS OFFER TO JOIN UNITY GOVERNMENT <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The Pan Africanist Congress yesterday in principle accepted President Nelson Mandelas offer to join the government of national unity, but it is not clear to what extent the party will be involved in the government.<BR><P>
RAMAPHOSA NOMINATED AS NEW TML CHAIRMAN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Cyril Ramaphosa, non-executive chairman of industrial group Johnnic, had been nominated as Times Media Ltd's new chairman, sources said yesterday.<BR><P>
CREDITORS HOUND DEBT-RIDDEN ANC <I>(Cape Times)</I><BR>
Western Cape ANC officials have had to use public telephones after the partys phone service was cut off because of unpaid bills.  Telecommunicvations giant, Telkom, is just one of many groups owed money by the party, whose debts add up to about R500 000.<BR><P>
NP TO SEEK NEW POLITICAL PARTY <I>(Cape Times)</I><BR>
Steps to set up a new political movement from which a new party might emerge were announced by National Party leader F W de Klerk yesterday.  The party would draw up a new negotiation strategy and action plan before February.<BR><P>

