<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 15 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



<p>NEW MINE SAFETY LAW ENACTED TODAY <i>(Business Report, Jhb.)</i><br>
New legislation to improve safety and training standards on SA's
mines will come into effect today, the National Union of
Mineworkers (NUM) said yesterday.<i> [This originated from a somewhat
distorted NUM statement issued late yesterday - for what purpose
we cannot determine - and which painted a lopsided picture of the
true state of affairs - Ed.]</i><br>
</p>

<p>ERPM TO CLOSE L SHAFT <i>(Business Report)</i><br>
ERPM announced yesterday it was to close the mine's L shaft
complex and access the relevant ore reserves from the FEV shaft
complex. The company said the effect of this decision on L shaft
employees was the subject of continuing negotiations with the
unions, which were expected to be completed &quot;during the
course of February&quot;.<br>
</p>

<p>EVANDER MERGER' MAY HOLD GREAT BENEFITS' <i>(Business Report)</i><br>
The benefits of the Evander Gold Mines merger are so great that
the share price could be revalued upwards of 60% in the next 12
months, according to international research/broking firm, RBC
Dominion Securities.<br>
</p>

<p>BEATRIX MINES TO BE QUOTED ON BELGIAN BOURSE <i>(Business Day,
Jhb.)</i><br>
Beatrix Mines, the owner of SA's 10th biggest gold mine, is to be
quoted on the Brussels stock market from January 20.<br>
</p>

<p>ANGLOGOLD HAPPY WITH REFINER <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Gold mines in the Anglo American stable were content with the
service provided by Rand Refinery in refining and marketing up to
a third of their gold production, Anglogold said yesterday.<br>
</p>

<p>PARTIES EYE ANGLO'S SOUTHERN LIFE STAKE <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Anglo American and Worldwide Africa Investments had entered into discussions
for Worldwide to take a strategic stake in Anglo-controlled assurer
Southern Life, high-level sources confirmed yesterday.<br>
</p>

<p>COMGOLD'S LONDON MARKET LISTING 'WILL TRIGGER EXPANSION' <i>(Business
Day)</i><br>
The listing of South African gold mining group Amalia's
London-based associate, Commonwealth Gold (Comgold), on the
London Offex/AIM market on March 12 would trigger future growth,
the group said today.<br>
</p>

<p>GOLD FIELDS GHANA <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Gold Fields Ghana reported net income of $354 000 ($783 000) in
the six months to December.<br>
</p>

<p>THE ZAMBIA PRIVATISATION AGENCY <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
The Zambia Privatisation Agency said it expected to sell off some
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines' assets, including Konkola North
and Kansanshi mine, by May.<br>
</p>

<p>RISES IN INFLATION, MONEY-MARKET SHORTAGE LIFT RAND <i>(Business
Report)</i><br>
The rand opened robustly and continued to strengthen yesterday,
adding 1c against the dollar. In late trade, it was at R4,6715
from R4,6815 on Monday. Charles Jonker, a foreign exchange economist
at Absa Bank, said last week's announcement that the money-market
shortage had risen to R10,4b, and an expected rise in inflation
after last month's petrol price rise, had strengthened the
currency.<br>
</p>

<p>ANALYSTS TEND TO LOWER GOLD PRICE FORECASTS - POLL <i>(Reuters)</i><br>
LONDON - A drop in the gold price of 3,25% at the start of 1997
and the spectre of new bullion sales by central banks have led
several analysts to revise down predictions for the value of the
metal.<br>
</p>

<p>FIRST SECURE END-TO-END INTERNET TRANSACTION <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
IBM, Mastercard and Danish Payment Systems have announced the
first end-to-end secure Internet transaction using the Secure
Electronic Transaction protocol, an industry standard for securing
on-line transactions.<br>
</p>

<p>MEXICO DETAILS 12 MINE PROPERTIES FOR AUCTION <i>(Reuters)</i><br>
PUERTO VALLARTA, MEXICO, - Mexico gave details late on Monday of 12
mine properties it will soon auction off in its new bid to boost mining activity
in the country by releasing federal lands for detailed exploration rights.<br>
</p>

<p>VIRGIN WILL BID FOR AS MUCH OF SUN AIR AS STATE WILL SELL <i>(Business
Report)</i><br>
Virgin Atlantic Airways, which is pursuing a 35% stake in the state-owned domestic
airline Sun Air, would settle for 10% less should the government stick
to its decision to sell no more than 25% to a foreign shareholder, David
James, Virgin's general manager for southern Africa, said
yesterday.<br>
</p>

<p>SA GOVT BACK-PEDALS OVER SYRIAN ARMS DEAL <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Government back-pedalled yesterday from the proposed R3bn sale of defence
equipment to Syria, saying any tender for the sale would be
issued after 1999 and a final decision need only be made then.<br>
</p>

<p>SOUTHERN AFRICAN AIR CARGO GROWTH OUTSTRIPS GLOBAL AVERAGE <i>(Business
Day)</i><br>
The growth in import and export air cargo volumes from southern
Africa continues to outstrip the global average, with some major
international carriers reporting an increase of about 40% last
year.<br>
</p>

<p>SA TOPS LIST OF 'REPORTED' RAPES <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
The recent spate of gang rapes which shocked the Gauteng
community have highlighted the increase of reported rapes in SA,
with a 1994 Interpol survey naming the country as having the highest
incidence of reported rape in the world.<br>
</p>

<p>RIGHTS ACTIVISTS REJECT OMAR&#146;S NO-BAIL PLAN <i>(Cape
Times, Cape Town)</i><br>
The way in which magistrates apply legislation governing bail -
and not the law itself - has come under fire as the row over easy
and cheap bail escalates. This emerged after Justice Minister
Dullah Omar yesterday said he intended lobbying political parties
for support on drastic legislation to compel courts to refuse
bail in all serious crime cases. The proposed new law would
require a change to the Bill of Rights.<br>
<b><i>... and ...</i></b><br>
PRESUMED INNOCENT <i>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</i><br>
Justice Minister Dullah Omar has been overhasty in promising to
change the law so that bail will be refused for people accused of
serious crimes. In an emotional response to two particularly
distressing double rapes in Johannesburg, he said he would get
the law tightened up even if this meant changing the bill of
rights in the new constitution. Omar seems to have overlooked the
consequences of such an action on the law's essential function in
protecting the innocent, whether this refers to a possible victim or
a falsely accused person. The right to bail is entrenched in the
new constitution, and there is now a stronger onus on the police
to show why bail should be denied, and this is as it should be.<br>
</p>

<p>BLACK-OWNED FIRMS GROWING <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
The small band of black-owned South African companies was growing
in stature and respect in the post-apartheid era after succeeding
in winning significant control of listed companies last year,
market analysts said yesterday.<br>
</p>

<p>PROJECT LACKS GOVT SUPPORT <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
A small business development project initiated by the United
Nations Conference on Trade and Development (Unctad), which was
being scrapped, did not have the support of government, a Trade
and Industry Department official said yesterday.<br>
</p>

<p>BORROWING CUT $1,2BN TO $14,8BN <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
LONDON - The South African public and private sector reduced
foreign bank borrowings by $1,2bn to $14,8bn in the first half of
last year, according to the figures released by the Bank for International
Settlements (BIS), the central banks' central bank.<br>
</p>

<p>INVESTMENT PAYS OFF FOR FOREIGN FIRMS <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Foreign companies operating in SA in the past two or three years
have exceeded their growth projections and are planning to
expand, key new investors say.<br>
</p>
</DOC>
