<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 14 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



GOLD RALLIES ON DUTCH BANK SALES <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
LONDON - The gold price rallied further yesterday on an announcement that the Central Bank of Netherlands had sold 300 tons of gold worth 6,4-billion Dutch florins - $3,6bn at present exchange rates - during 1996.<BR><P>
U.S. GOLD MINING COMPANIES SCRAMBLE FOR NEW RESERVES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold is at its lowest price for years and gold mining shares are out of fashion - the<I> Financial Times</I> gold mines index ended last year at it lowest for the year.<BR><P>
"NEUTRAL" COMPUTER PROGRAM DIGS UP METAL DEPOSITS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - A self-teaching computer program has been launched which trawls through reams of data to spot metal deposits in days where it would take a team of mining geologists months, its developers said on Monday.<BR><P>
CLAIMS 'SHED PARTIAL LIGHT' ON NAZI GOLD DEALS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
GENEVA - The Swiss National Bank has admitted charges by a leading US senator and the World Jewish Congress that Switzerland served Nazi interests during the war by reselling looted gold to Spain and Portugal, but insisted the facts were already known.<BR><P>
MINES EXPECTED TO SHOW IMPROVEMENT  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The South African gold mining industry is expected to report an overall rise in operating profit for the December quarter, with analysts predicting a small jump in gold production coupled with a slightly firmer rand gold price received in the absence of any major cost increases.<BR><P>
LONRHO DEMERGER PLAN OVERSHADOWS ITS RESULTS <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
LONDON - Lonrho, which had been working for the last year on splitting itself up, was set to report a modest full-year profit rise on Thursday, analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
US THREATENS TO SUSPEND AID TO SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - In the toughest warning it has issued to President Mandela's government, the Clinton administration said yesterday it was "deeply concerned" by cabinet's provisional approval of a R3bn arms sale to Syria, and might be obliged under US law to suspend aid to SA.<BR><P>
MANUEL PREPARES TO WOO MARKET PLAYERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel is to launch a "charm offensive" next month to gain the confidence of local market players who might still be sceptical about his ability to deliver on his ambitious macro-economic strategy.<BR><P>
TAX VIEW OF EXCHANGE CONTROLS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Katz commission is to report later this month on the income tax implications of scrapping exchange controls, including the consequences of moving from the current source or geographically based system to one which is residence-based, tax experts say.<BR><P>
FUND COMMISSIONERS INVEST R84M IN MOVE TO DIVERSIFY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Public Investment Commissioners (PIC)- <I>[a body]</I> which manages the investments of government's R110bn pension funds - has invested almost R84m in Real Africa Investments Limited as part of a move to diversify its portfolio.<BR><P>
LABOUR CONSULTANTS WARN OF TENSIONS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Economists and labour consultants have warned of heightened tension between unions and employers as workers demand double-digit increases in line with current inflationary trends to make up for last year's lower increases.<BR><P>
BUSINESS TO BE ASKED TO SET ASIDE JOBS FOR WITNESS PROTECTION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Big business will be asked to allocate a percentage of its vacant  jobs to accommodate state witnesses each year as part of an integrated and effective witness protection programme.<BR><P>
BUSINESS REPORT LOOKS AHEAD TO 21ST CENTURY <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
James Lamont (28), the former industrial editor of Business Report, was appointed journals new editor yesterday. <BR><P>
NONRESIDNETS STILL BUYING SA EQUITIES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Nonresidents had purchased a net R203,4m of South African equities last week, the Johannesburg Stock Exchange reported yesterday. Foreigners had purchased R105bn against sales of R846,6m.<BR><P>
R12,6m BOND MARKET OUTFLOW <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Foreign outflows from the SA bond market had totalled R12,65m in the week ended 10 January, the bond exchange reported yesterday. Nonresidents purchased R4,444bn worth of bonds against sales of R4,456bn.<BR><P>
NEW GOLD FIND NEEDS INFRASTRUCTURE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The site of a major gold find on the Indonesian island of Kalimantan required about $1,3bn worth of infrastructure, the islands regent said.<BR><P>
BAIL SHOULD BE REFUSED ON SERIOUS CASES, SAYS OMAR <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Justice Minister Dullah Omar has vowed to change the law so that bail will be refused by the courts for serious crimes, even if this means making changes to the new constitution's bill of rights.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
POLICE 'CARRYING OUT ALL DUTIES' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi yesterday denied reports that SA Police Services operations or essential services were suspended due to a shortage of funds.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
SA SAFER THAN NEW YORK - POLL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA is on a list of the world's 10 most dangerous holiday destinations, but is seen as being not as bad as some US cities.<BR><P>
SADC SEEKING WAYS TO END TENSIONS WITH RIVAL BLOC <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Southern African Development Community plans to continue searching for ways of resolving tensions with the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (Comesa), despite the increasing number of Comesa members which are relinquishing dual membership.<BR><P>
COSATU KEEN TO ASSIST SOUTH KOREAN STRIKERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu) extended its support to South Korean workers yesterday, three weeks after they began strike and protest action, and said it would approach the SA Labour Ministry to discuss ways of influencing the outcome of the situation in Korea.<BR><P>

