<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 13 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>





SA GOLD MINES' RICH 4TH QUARTER NOW HISTORY <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
South African gold mines should report December quarter earnings up 9% to 13% on the previous quarter, benefiting from fewer holidays and a richer rand gold price.  But the outlook for 1997 is grim with reserves in the March quarter likely to be hit hard by bullion's meltdown and production pressured by four public holidays.<BR><P>
RAND REFINERY ALREADY SELLING GOLD DIRECT <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SA's Rand Refinery said on Friday it was already marketing gold directly on behalf of producers and had sold and exported 140 tonnes direct in 1996.<BR><P> 
TRADERS ATTRIBUTE GOLD'S $4 LEAP TO SHORT COVERING <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The gold price recovered a whopping $4 an ounce on Friday in what traders and analysts attributed to short covering after weeks of declining prices.<BR><P>
RAND/DOLLAR <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The rand ended at R4,6770 to the dollar on Friday after a volatile week.<BR><P>
GOLD FIELDS' CLAIMS DOUBTED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
LONDON - The World Gold Council is sceptical about Gold Fields Mineral Services' claims that central bank bullion sales soared in the second half of last year, pointing out that none of the banks were <I>[sic] </I>identified.<BR><P>
FREEGOLD AND HARMONY DISCUSS SALE <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Free State Consolidated Gold Mines (Freegold) and Harmony are in talks over the sale of Freegold's Free State Saaiplaas number three shaft to Harmony, the companies said yesterday.<BR><P>
RUSSIAN DIAMOND PRODUCER THINKS DE BEERS DEAL ON THE CARDS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
MOSCOW - Almazy Rossii-Sakha, Russia's largest diamond producer, believes Russia could approve a long-delayed export deal with De Beers this month, Vyacheslav Shtyrov, the president, said on Saturday.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD TO CONSOLIDATE ITS SHARE INTERESTS IN HARMONY <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The Harmony offer to acquire Lydex's shareholders shares in consideration for a cash payment of R10 for every 100 Lydex share held together with 45 Harmony options for every 100 Lydex shares held closes this Friday.<BR><P>
AMALIA GOLD MINING & EXPLORATION COMPANY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Amalia Gold Mining Company was the best performing share in the mining sector on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange last year, the company said today.<BR><P>
NUM IN BID TO OPPOSE ALEXKOR PRIVATISATION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The state-owned Alexkor diamond mine in the Northern Cape played a crucial role in sustaining the depressed regional economy which relied heavily on the mine and it should therefore not be privatised, the National Union of Mineworkers said yesterday.<BR><P>
EURORAND BOND ISSUES ARE BOOMING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Eurorand bond issues are booming, with foreign investors buying about R850m worth of bonds since the start of the year to cash in on SA's high interest rates.<BR><P>
SA REACHES TARGETS ON DIPLOMATIC FRONT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA had established diplomatic relations with 63 countries and upgraded its relations with a further 20 since the 1994 elections, effectively bringing to an end SA's drive for international representation.<BR><P>
TAIWAN'S FOREIGN MINISTER TO VISIT SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Taiwanese Foreign Minister John Chang is reportedly to meet President Mandela again on January 19, during a visit to Taiwan's few remaining allies in Africa.<BR><P>
SA MUST GEAR ITSELF FOR WINDS OF CHANCE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The amber lights are flashing for government's macro-economic strategy.  Fairly or otherwise, the markets continue to reflect scepticism which, to some extent, is echoed by the local business community.  The fact that it was necessary to raise the Bank rate again at the tail end of the economic upturn speaks volumes about the negative perceptions of financial markets about implementation of the Growth, Employment and Redistribution strategy and macro-economic policy generally.<BR><P>
MANUEL PROMISES BETTER TAX COLLECTION AND SPENDING CUTS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The government's Budget deficit target for 4% of Gross Domestic Product in 1997-98 will be strictly adhered to, Finance Minister Trevor Manuel said in a interview at the weekend.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
MANUEL PUTS HIS FAITH IN ECONOMIC REFORM <I>(Business Times, with the Sunday Times)</I><BR>
It is business as usual for Finance Minister Trevor Manuel.  Dismissing speculation that he is due to be shifted to the Foreign Ministry, Manuel this week outlined plans to speed-up the implementation of government's macro-economic plan.<BR><P>
PRETORIA'S ADVISER BEGINS WORK ON SUN AIR SALE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Sun Air, the government-owned domestic airline, is set to become the flagship of privatisation in SA after the government-appointed adviser on the sale of the airline started work yesterday.<BR><P>
GOVT KEEPS LID ON DEBT COSTS DESPITE RAND'S FALL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government had managed to keep a lid on the extra cost of servicing state debt this fiscal year, despite the rand's sharp depreciation and the unexpected rise in capital market interest rates.<BR><P>
'ONCE-BITTEN' NAIL IS NOT INTERESTED IN GOLD FIELDS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Cyril Ramaphosa, the deputy executive chairman of New Africa Investments Ltd., denied reports yesterday that he was casting his net on Gold Fields of SA, the country's second-largest gold producer.<BR><P>
KWAZULU-NATAL LOOKS AT A STOCK EXCHANGE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
DURBAN - KwaZulu-Natal province could become home to SA's first provincial stock exchange, giving a crucial leg-up for small businesses.<BR><P>
MANDELA TAKES ANC TO TASK OVER 'CAREERISM, PETTY RIVALRY' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
BOTSHABELO - President Mandela read ANC members the riot act yesterday, telling them to set aside "individualism, mindless careerism and petty rivalries" and to make sure that "the people come first".<BR><P>
TALKS ON EU DEAL SET TO RESUME <I>(Business Times)</I><BR>
Stalled trade talks between SA and the European Union could resume in Pretoria within 10 days, a government source said on Friday.<BR><P>
1997 THE YEAR TO BITE THE BULLET <I>(F&T Weekly, 10 Jan. 1997)</I><BR>
It seems that employers and unionists alike would be well advised to make the most of the festive season. The 1997 return-to-work may herald one of the toughest years they will face since the chaotic mid-Eighties. Employment levels in the formal sector have declined for six successive years and - in the face of an<I> <B>accelerating </B>economic <B>slowdown </B>[my italics!! - Ed.]</I>, rising inflation and wage costs, punitive interest rates and a weak currency - the level of employment is bound to decline at an even faster rate in 1997. This, in turn, is likely to make retrenchment issues a key focus of the collective bargaining debate in many companies this year, a topic unlikely to dilute the adversarial nature of industrial relations interaction.<BR><P>
PESSIMISM ON SAS ECONOMIC GROWTH RATE <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The nominal economic growth experienced at the end of 1995 and the beginning of 1996 is unlikely to be repeated this year, economists agree. Contrary to what they predicted at the beginning of 1996 - real growth rates of four to five percent for 1996, a fall in interest rates and a strong currency - economists are pessimistic about prospects in 1997.<BR><P>
SA WARNED OF PITFALLS <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
If SA wants to improve its economy and realise its social upliftment programmes, free enterprise is the answer. This is the advice of former German federal minister of economics, Count Otto Lambsdorff. Lambsdorff said an economic system based on a social partnership between government, labour and business would not only be detrimental to the economy, but to the unemployed as well. Lambsdorff said the idea of a social partnership was good in principle, but was full of problems in reality. "The idea of underlying conditions set by the state for the process of negotiating wages is full of snags," he told a business breakfast in Johannesburg last week.<BR><P>
EDUCATION APPOINTMENTS: QUALIFICATIONS COUNT LITTLE <I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Qualifications are going to count for less and less in appointments in the Department of Education. This is as a result of concept policy for a more representative personnel corps which, in practice, will make it impossible for whites to be appointed in the Department in the coming two years. They will also not be promoted easily.<BR><P>
GROWTH RATE OF 2,19% EXPECTED <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Economists taking part in <I>Beelds </I>Economist of the Year competition agree in their consensus projections that SA achieved a 3% growth rate last year. The actual growth rate will only be announced later this year. A growth rate of 3% would be considerably better than the slightly more than 2% economists expect for this year.<BR><P>
JORDAN UNDER FIRE FOR STATEMENT <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
CAPE TOWN - The racist remarks about white investors made by Pallo Jordan, Minister of Environmental Affairs and Tourism, were strongly rejected by chambers of commerce on Friday. According to an SABC radio report Jordan said during the ANCs 85th anniversary that most investors were white and unwilling to support the government with projects to create employment. <BR><P>
</DOC>
