<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 10 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>




MINISTER TAKES PLUNGE TO LAUNCH MINE SAFETY ACT <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Minerals and Energy Minister Penuell Maduna will officially launch the long-awaited new Mine Health and Safety Act thousands of metres underground next week.<I> [This report arises from yesterdays joint media conference between the Chamber and NUM - see our website at<A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/releases/comnum97.htm"> http://www.bullion.org.za/releases/comnum97.htm</A>. Television and radio carried extensive reports last night and The Star & Citizen this morning also reported on the signing of the agreement between us and NUM regarding administrative penalties instead of Sections 86(2) & (3) and the scheduled signing into force of the Act next week - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
HARMONY TO MARKET SOME OF ITS OWN GOLD <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government has taken another small step towards easing foreign exchange regulations by allowing Randgolds Harmony Gold Mining Company to market a third of its own gold production on international markets.<I> [Most local media carried this item this morning - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
GOLD SEEN SET FOR FURTHER PUNISHMENT AFTER SLIDE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Gold seems set for further punishment in 1997 after a price slide of 3,3% in the first few trading days, bullion analysts say.  Investors and consumers dont want to touch it.  Producers are panicking about getting a decent return on it.  And speculators are selling gold which they dont own in the hope of buying it back cheaper later.<BR><P>
BOBBY ON THE GOLD BEAT <I>(Business Mail, Fridays with the Mail & Guardian)</I><BR>
At a time when negative sentiment is ruling the market, there is a strange, yet welcome sense of optimism at Anglo Americans gold and uranium division in its Main Street headquarters in Johannesburg.  Gold might be hitting three-year lows, at one stage trading at $358 this week - its lowest level since October 1993 - but says Anglogold chair Bobby Godsell with a laugh, his tenure of 18 months has been fun. <BR><P> 
WORLD GOLD DEMAND IS STEADY <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Worldwide demand for gold remains strong as the slide in gold prices in recent months continued into the new year, George Milling-Stanley, the manager of market analysis at the World Gold Council said yesterday.  <BR><P> 
BANK OF PORTUGAL DENIES IT SOLD GOLD <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LISBON - The Portuguese central bank denied that it had sold gold from its reserves after an authoritative research group said gold sales from the official sector had accelerated in the second half of 1996. <BR><P>
ZIMBABWES 1996 GOLD OUTPUT DOWN ON 1995 <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
HARARE - Zimbabwes gold output slipped to 23,7 tonnes in 1996 from 24,3 tonnes the previous year, largely due to production problems at the countrys major gold mines, an industry official said on Thursday.<BR><P>
CHINAS 1996 GOLD OUTPUT AT 120,6 TONNES <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BEIJING - Chinas gold output totalled 120,6 tonnes last year, the official Xinhua news agency said.  China produced 108 tonnes of gold in 1995.<BR><P>
BRAZILIAN EXPLORATION RIGHTS DRAW GENCORS INTEREST <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Three major international firms had shown interest in the exploration rights of a possible gold reserve in Brazils northern Rondonia state, a spokesman at the Mineral Resources Survey Company (CPRM) said on Wednesday.<BR><P>
MINORCO JOINT VENTURE SETS ITS GOLD AND SILVER TARGET <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
BUENOS AIRES - Cerro Vanguardia, the $230m gold project approved in Patagonia by Minorco SA and Argentinas Perez Companc, should produce its first dore bars, containing 90% silver and 10% gold, by the middle of next year, the company said yesterday.<BR><P>
DIAMONDS MINED IN SA WATERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Moonstone Diamond Corp. NL said yesterday it had begun trial mining of diamonds from the sea floor on the west coast of SA using a specially fitted vessel.  <BR><P>
DUIKERS DIRECTORS OPT TO SELL MOST OF THEIR SHARES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Directors of Duiker Mining sold just more than two-thirds of their shares in the firm last year, the latest annual report discloses.   <BR><P>
POWER SUPPLY BLOW FOR 100 MUNICIPALITIES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
More than 100 of the estimated 400 South African municipalities stand to lose their licences to supply electricity following a decision by the national electricity regulator to take action against non-performing electricity distributors.<BR><P>
FOREIGN INVESTORS WARM TO SA BONDS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Foreign investors are showing signs of liking SA again, helping the rand to consolidate at stronger levels and underpinning bullish sentiment in the gilts market.<BR><P>
FOREIGN AFFAIRS MAY MERGE MISSIONS WITH OTHER SADC STATES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Foreign Affairs Department has been holding discussions with other Southern African Development Community (SADC) countries on the possibility of merging overseas missions to reduce costs, SADC sources have confirmed. <BR><P>
MOZAMBICAN DECISION A FILLIP FOR SADC <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Southern African Development Community (SADC) scored a diplomatic coup this week when Mozambique signalled its intention to leave the rival Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (Comesa) and to remain within the SADC.<BR><P>
ANGOLAS REJECTION OF SA ROLE A MISUNDERSTANDING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The rejection by Angolas ruling party of a greater South African role in the creation of a lasting peace there had been "based on a misunderstanding," presidential spokesman Parks Mankahlana said yesterday.<BR><P>
TRADE TALKS ON TRACK <I>(Business Mail)</I><BR>
After frequent setbacks, the next round of talks between South Africa and the European Union over a trade deal will kick off on January 22.  This time, the departments of Foreign Affairs and Trade and Industry, jointly leading the negotiations, will put regional development issues top of the agenda.  <BR>
<B><I>... but ...</I></B><BR>
SA HAS YET TO ASSEMBLE EU NEGOTIATING TEAM <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government, which is seeking better market access to the European Union (EU), has yet to assemble a team of negotiators ahead of the planned talks with the EU later this month. <BR><P>
SA WARNED ABOUT ITS ECONOMY <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SAs economy will deteriorate further if the government continues to pursue an economic policy based on a social partnership. This warning came from former German federal minister of economics, Count Otto Lambsdorff at a business breakfast organised by the Institute of Race Relations in Johannesburg yesterday. <BR><P>
BLACK BUSINESS GROUPS PLAN TO FORGE CLOSER TIES THIS YEAR <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Local black business organisations plan to forge closer ties this year to ensure greater success of black empowerment transactions.<BR><P>
BRIGHT SECOND HALF FOR THE JSE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The Johannesburg Stock Exchange is in for a tough first half this year, but share prices should start looking up in the second half, Adrian Allardice, Old Mutual Unit Trusts senior portfolio manager, said yesterday.<BR><P>
IMF PULLS THE PLUG ON MOZAMBIQUE <I>(Business Mail)</I><BR>
Peace has not brought prosperity to Mozambique.  Four years after the end of the civil war, the poorest country in the world is growing poorer.  The reason is that the International Monetary Fund has ruled that annual inflation must be brought below 15% before there can be significant post-war reconstruction.<BR><P>

