<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 9 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



GOLD MELTDOWN BAD NEWS FOR SA EXPORTS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Gold's New Year meltdown could deliver a fresh blow to SA's economy, hurting a hoped-for export recover in 1997, threatening job losses in mines and hitting reserves, economists said on Wednesday.<BR><P>
DIAMONDS ARE TRADERS' NEW BEST FRIENDS <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
While gold shares continued their meltdown on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange yesterday, commodity inclined investors turned hot for marine diamond mining stocks, with Ocean Diamond Mining Holdings and Benguela Concessions racing to new highs.<BR><P>
PANIC SELLING DISTORTS PRICES <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Diagonal Street's gold share bloodbath of the past 10 days has been indiscriminate, with sellers unaccountably hitting the high graders as hard as the marginals.  The catalyst for the fall has been the steep decline in the dollar gold price which slumped from $370 on December 30 to $359 on December 7 <I>[sic - presumably January]</I>, a drop of 3%.<BR><P>
MONEY MARKET RATES EDGE DOWN <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Signs of light at the end of SA's tunnel of high interest rates appeared yesterday, as rates in the money market edged down.<BR><P>
ERPM MINERS FACE THREAT OF RETRENCHMENT <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The fate of 1 000 workers at Randgold's ERPM mine near Boksburg will hang in the balance until a decision is taken later this month on whether closure of a shaft will result in their retrenchment.<BR><P>
LONRHO TO SELL MOZAMBIQUE MINE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
British multinational corporation Lonrho is selling its alluvial gold mining operation in Mozambique to SA mining company Benicon, a Benicon official said yesterday.<BR><P>
GENCOR INCREASES STAKE IN GENBIQUE TO 100% <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
SA mining house Gencor announced yesterday that it had increased its stake in the exploration licence holding company, Genbique, to 100%<BR><P>
MINING SHARES AMONG TOP PERFORMERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Mining, commodities, technology and investment trust shares were the JSE's top performers last year, with the building and construction, clothing, footwear and textiles, stores and property sectors the worst.<BR><P>
POOR RESERVES MAY PRESAGE BETTER DAYS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA Reserve Bank's gold and foreign exchange reserves ended last year on a dismal note, dropping more than R629m in December to R10,3bn in a final reminder that SA was the blacksheep of emerging market economies last year.<BR><P>
THE WORLD BANK TO INVEST IN SA CHEM PLANT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The World Bank's private investment arm, the International Finance Corporation, is set to invest in a new chemical plant in SA and to back three other ventures.<BR><P>
EARLY SUCCESS FOR NEW DISPUTE RESOLUTION BODY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Commission for Conciliation, Mediation and Arbitration, established in terms of the new Labour Relations Act, has achieved a 77% success rate in resolving disputes in the first seven weeks since its inception.<BR><P>
PARTIAL DISCLOSURE PLAN FOR NOMINEEES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government's standing advisory committee on company law is likely to recommend that nominee companies - which control more than a third of the JSE's market capitalisation - should be forced to name shareholders holding a significant stake in the company, sources say.<BR><P>
ANC TURNS TO TRADITION TO REVITALISE PARTY'S SPIRITS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
President Mandela will call on African National Congress cadres this weekend to rededicate themselves to "consolidating the national democratic revolution" to revitalise the party.<BR><P>
DIALECTICAL MATERIALISM <I>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
There are obvious ironies in the flood of union money into the acquisition of some very large South African corporations.  But it is also giving rise to a debate which unions and the business world will have to take increasingly seriously.  Trade unions are now able to influence pension fund investments and other assets valued at many billions of rands. <BR><P>
SA EAGER TO RESUME EU TRADE TALKS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
SA wants a speedy resumption of stalled trade talks with the European Union after it broke an impasse last month by outlining its negotiating mandate to the EU, a government official said yesterday.<BR><P>
