<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 8 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



MORE SA MINES TURN MARGINAL AS GOLD SLUMPS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Bullion's tumble to three-and-a-quarter year lows has increased the number of marginal mines operating in SA and dampened the outlook for gold shares this year, industry analysts said on Tuesday.  But, although the gold price was seen sliding further, most mines were not expected to trim production in 1997 as a weak rand was cushioning them from the full effect of the slump in dollar terms.  Roger Baxter, senior economist at the Chamber of Mines, said marginal mines, those with a working profit to working revenue ratio of less than 7%, had risen to nine from six during the third quarter.<BR><P>
SA MINERALS BUREAU SEES GOLD AT $415 IN 2001 <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
The dollar gold price is expected to rise gradually to reach $415 an ounce by 2001, SA's Minerals Bureau said in its annual review. The Bureau reports further that the decline in gold output is expected to bottom out with production in the medium term holding around 500 tonnes a year.<BR><P>
OFFICIAL SALES, DISINVESTMENT HURT GOLD PRICE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON  - A rise in official sector sales was the chief cause of weakness in the gold price in the second half of 1996, Gold Fields Mineral Services said in a report.<BR><P>
ASSAULT ON RAND LIKELY TO CONTINUE <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
More than 100 domestic and foreign fund managers with investments in SA expect renewed attacks on the fragile rand.<BR><P>
FOREIGN INTEREST IN BONDS LIFTS CURRENCY <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The rand got a more than 3c jolt of strength yesterday, reaching R4,6650 in late trade, as a spurt of foreign interest in SA government bonds helped bring in rand buyers from offshore.<BR><P>
MINE WORKERS RESCUED <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Four mine workers trapped behind 280 tons of mud and rock since Monday were rescued yesterday after an emergency operation at Randgold's Harmony mine in the Free State.<BR><P>
LONRHO MINERS TO PROTEST AGAINST BOMBINGS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Union members at Lonrho platinum mines will stage a mass meeting tomorrow to protest against the alleged involvement of white miners in a series of recent bombings, the National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) said yesterday.<BR><P>
ZCCM LIFTS COPPER PRODUCTION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines' copper production lifted in November to 22 052 tons from October's low of 18 338 tons, central bank statistics showed yesterday.<BR><P>
DUIKER SEES STRONG COAL DEMAND IN PACIFIC RIM <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
South African bituminous coal is expected to be in strong demand from the Pacific Rim countries for the foreseeable future, "with SAs supplies to India, Korea and Japan rising steadily", according to Duiker Mining's latest annual report.<BR><P>
CRUDE IS REASON FOR PPI DROP <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Producer Inflation rose only modestly from 8,3% in October to 8,5% in November last year, thanks to a 6,6% decline in the price of imported crude petroleum, the Central Statistical Service announced yesterday.<BR><P>
SOCIALISM 'SIDELINED BY BLUE-COLLAR BOSSES'  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA's labour movement is raising a few eyebrows with its swift move away from its adherence to socialism by spending almost as much time buying into business as it is trying to curb it, says IR Data, published by Andrew Levy & Associates.<BR><P>
UNIONS UPSET THAT OFFICIALS MAY QUIT PARLIAMENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The 20 former Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu) officials who are MPs were chosen by the federation to represent workers' interests in Parliament and should fulfil this mandate for the full term of office, a key unionist <I>[NUM general secretary Kgalema Motlanthe]</I> said yesterday.<BR><P>
'ROAD COURTS' IN STRICT GOVT STRATEGY TO CURB ABUSES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A road traffic management strategy, which proposes on-the-road courts, a points demerit system for repeat offenders, improved breathalyser tests and the issuing of traffic safety aids was released by Transport Minister Mac Maharaj in Pretoria yesterday.<BR><P>
FURTHER DROPS IN GOLD PRICE COULD PUT SHARES UNDER PRESSURE <I>(Sake-Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Most South African gold mines are still profitable against the current lower gold price because, despite the lower gold price, they still earn a reasonable rand-price for their gold, but the industry is faced with serious difficulties should the gold price experience further drops. Analysts say this means the price of gold shares could come under increased pressure if the gold price does not stabilise soon.<BR><P>
TOWNSHIP GROUPS HIT BACK AT CRIME <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
Vigilante South African street committees are turning away from taking the law into their own hands - and have formed neighbourhood watches that conduct special crime-prevention operations with police.  This is in stark contrast to the often-hostile attitude displayed toward the police during the politically turbulent 1980s.<BR><P>
KNIVES OUT FOR SOURCE OF CABINET RESHUFFLE LEAK <I>(Cape Times)</I><BR>
The knives are out for the person who leaked details of an alleged cabinet reshuffle to the media, with ANC sources indicating yesterday that a senior cabinet minister was suspected of trying to foster his career. <I> [Rumours are rife at present that Finance Minister Trevor Manuel is to be shifted to Foreign Affairs to take over from the aging Alfred Nzo, and that Manuel's position would be taken over by Trade and Industry Minister Alec Irwin, whose portfolio would, in turn, be taken over by current Deputy Finance Minister Gill Marcus. Manuel raised eyebrows last year with statements - which commentators described as "naive" - about international markets, and which lead to questions being raised about his competence to occupy the post. - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
