<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 7 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>




DELAYS END FOR MINE HEALTH, SAFETY ACT <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The new Mine Health and Safety Act passed by parliament in June last year will finally come into operation later this month, after months of delay. <BR><P>
RESERVE BANK PROPS UP RAND <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The rand was barely changed at R4,6995 in late trade yesterday, after intervention from the Reserve Bank helped the currency retrace an intraday<I>[sic]</I> slip of nearly 2c to R4,7190, dealers said.<BR><P>
BAD CHEQUES POINT TO ECONOMIC SLUMP <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
SA's economic downturn is sharper than perceived, judging from the significant rise in dishonoured cheques.<BR><P>
TALK OF ERWIN REPLACING MANUEL DISMISSED AS RACIST<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
Reports of (white) Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin replacing (black) Finance Minister Trevor Manuel were 'racist' and 'nonsensical', Erwin's spokesman said yesterday.<BR><P>
GOLD'S SLIDE MAY HAMPER JCI SALE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The slide in the gold price in recent weeks could put pressure on the African Mining Consortium which bought 34,9% of mining group JCI from Anglo American in November, as it seeks capital to fund the R2,8bn deal, industry sources say.<BR><P>
GOLD LOSING APPEAL AFTER TWO DECADES OF FALLING REAL PRICE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold was becoming less attractive as a medium for investment, with its real price falling steadily for almost two decades and the increasing availability of alternative instruments, analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
SWISS ACCUSED OF TRYING TO CAMOUFLAGE NAZI GOLD <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
NEW YORK - Switzerland, fearing that looted gold ingots it received from Nazi Germany could be seized for war damage settlements, had Germany stamp them as made before the start of World War II, according to a U.S. intelligence document released on Monday.<BR><P>
COPPER OUTPUT <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SEOUL - LG Metals Corporation, said on Monday its copper production was expected to rise 6,3% to 260 000 tonnes in 1997 from 244 500 tonnes in 1996.<BR><P>
DURBAN DEEP PLANS FURTHER GROWTH <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Durban Roodepoort Deep, one of SA's oldest gold mines, is poised for further growth through expanded underground operations and the longer-term possibility of additional mergers with neighbouring gold mines, according to a recent report from stockbrokerage EW Balderson.<BR><P>
SADIOLA MINE POURS FIRST GOLD <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American Corporation said yesterday its Sadiola Hill gold mine in the West African country of Mali completed its first gold pour on December 20.<BR><P>
DOUBLE FIGURE WAGE INCREASES EXPECTED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Wage increases this year could rise to double figures and exceed last year's overall average increase of 9,9%, Andrew Levy & Associates said yesterday.<BR><P>
BIG SPENDING CUT LIKELY TO CURB DEFICIT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government was considering cancelling about R5bn in spending from its huge rollovers from previous fiscal years as a means of keeping a lid on the deficit, a source said yesterday.<BR><P>
CHRISTMAS BONUS BOOM COULD LIE AHEAD FOR BANKERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
South African investment and merchant bankers could look forward to a Christmas bonus boom this year, with an expected surge in black empowerment deals and merger and acquisition fees likely to boost earnings packages, sources said yesterday.<BR><P>
ROBBEN ISLAND RAKING IN R20 000 A DAY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Visitors to Robben Island have been queuing at the Victoria & Alfred Waterfront booking office from 4am to get tickets, which, on most days, have sold out by 8:30am.<BR><P>
