<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 6 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



INVESTORS WARY AS GOLD KEEPS SINKING <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gold slumped to its lowest level in more than three years, closing at $360,80/oz in New York on Friday and recovering only marginally to just more than $361 in Hong Kong on Saturday, as investors took a negative view of the metal in a thin market.<BR><P>
ANALYSTS EXPECT SLIGHT RISE IN PRODUCER INFLATION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Economists polled at the weekend ahead of this week's release of economic data are expecting the November producer price index (PPI) to be slightly higher at between 8,3% and 9,3% compared to the October figure of 8,3%.<BR><P>
DEFICIT FINANCING PLANS ON TRACK AFTER 9 MONTHS <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Nine months into the present financial year the government's deficit financing programme is still dead on track with R33,3bn of the required R45,1bn having been borrowed.<BR><P>
CENTRAL GOVT GETS R1,6BN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Central government had obtained R1,636bn in government bonds and debentures in December, while short-term loans decreased by R1,18bn, resulting in a total financing figure of R456,1m for the month, the Finance Department reported on Friday.<BR><P>
IT HAS BEEN A PROSPEROUS YEAR FOR NEW HI-TECH JSE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The Johannesburg Stock Exchange achieved several significant milestones last year, not least of which was a dramatic improvement in liquidity from 7% in 1995 to 11%.<BR><P>
THREAT OF JSE SUSPENSION FOR CONSOLIDATED DIAMOND <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The JSE said at the weekend that Consolidated Diamond Corporation was under threat of suspension and possible delisting after failing to submit its annual financial statements.<BR><P>
DE BEERS NUDGES RUSSIA TO NEW DEAL <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Diamond giant De Beers is actively buying Russian diamonds on the open market after the expiry of its marketing agreement with Russia on New Year's Eve, a company spokesman said last week.<BR><P>
JOHNNIC'S NEW OWNERS SET TO DISCUSS STRATEGY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The steering committee of the National Empowerment Consortium (NEC), which in August bought control of industrial group Johnnic for R2,7bn, will meet for three days next week on a farm near Cape Town to discuss the group's strategy.<BR><P>
'BETTER TIMES AHEAD FOR MANUFACTURING' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Overall performance in the manufacturing sector might stabilise next year with strong prospects for a bottoming-out of the unfavourable conditions experienced in the past few months, Stellenbosch University's Bureau for Economic Research projects in its December survey.<BR><P>
ROAD DEATHS COSTLY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The financial cost of road collision fatalities to SA's economy since December 3 is almost R200m, says National Traffic Information Centre spokesman Marleen Leita.<BR><P>
IFP WELCOMES 'PEACE PACKAGE' PLAN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Inkatha Freedom Party yesterday welcomed proposals for a "peace package" for KwaZulu-Natal province if it led to lasting peace, amid concern from other political parties that elements within the ruling African Nationalist Congress might not be supportive of this package if it included a special amnesty deal.<BR>
<B><I>... meanwhile ...</I></B><BR>
MOST SOUTH AFRICANS NOW WORSE OFF <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
INKANDALA - Inkatha Freedom Party leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi said on Saturday that many of the hopes ushered in by the first all-race elections in 1994 are disappearing under magnitude of the countrys unresolved problems. "Today most South Africans are much worse off then they were two years ago and the horizon of our future is clouded by unemployment, seemingly uncontrollable criminality and the disintegration of social and moral values," Buthelezi said. <BR><P>
