<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 3 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>




RAND PLUNGES AGAINST MAJOR CURRENCIES <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The rand started off the new year on an uneasy note, reaching another historic low of R8,0178 against the British pound and shedding 1,2c against the dollar, as it was caught in a crossfire between the stronger major currencies. Against the US dollar, the rand slid to a low of R4,6995 to the dollar before reaching R4,6925 at 5.30pm.<BR><P>
GROWTH IN MONEY SUPPLY, CREDIT EASES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Money supply and private credit extension growth dropped in November to levels below what many economists had predicted, signalling that a slowdown could be underway in response to high interest rates.<BR><P>
MOZAMBIQUE GRANTS JCI OPTION ON COAL PROJECT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Mozambique government has granted mining house JCI a 120-day option to lead manage the development of a $1,5bn coking coal project in Moatize in central Mozambique.<BR><P>
RETAIL TRADE SALES GROW MODESTLY IN OCTOBER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Retail trade sales in October grew 1,1% on a seasonally adjusted basis to R11,3bn compared with September, representing a real increase of 0,8%, Central Statistical Services figures showed. <BR><P>
DEATH TOLL TOPS 1000 <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The death toll on South Africa's roads since the start of the holiday season on 3 Decmber last year reached a record
1 016 yesterday afternoon, with traffic on major routes increasing as holiday-makers returned home, the National Traffic Information Centre said.<BR><P>
PLANT INTACT AFTER MAJOR ZAIREAN GOLD MINE LOOTED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Zairean soldiers looted a major gold mine north of the eastern town of Bunia, but the processing plant was believed to be still intact, a former Zairean official said yesterday.<BR><P>
EU SAYS IT WILL NOT DITCH THE LOMÉ CONVENTION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The European Union (EU), which recently published a policy paper suggesting far-reaching changes to its relationship with African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) nations, is not about to ditch the Lomé Convention, the union has said.<BR><P>
BLACKS SUPPORT AFFIRMATIVE ACTION - SURVEY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Blacks are strongly in favour of affirmative action as a policy for SA, coloureds have their doubts, and whites and Indians oppose it, according to an opinion poll conducted for Business Day by Market Research Africa (MRA).<BR><P>
PROVING SCEPTICS WRONG <I>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
If 1996 was the year the honeymoon ended and market cynicism sent the currency crashing, forcing government to take the tough policy choices required to restructure the economy, 1997 must be the year of consolidation and implementation. Those sceptical of government's will to implement its policy pronouncements will have to be proved wrong if the economy is to reach a higher plane. <BR><P>
INDIAN TENDER REVERSAL A SETBACK TO DE BEERS' PLANS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
De Beers has suffered a setback in its plans to prospect for diamonds in Madhya Pradesh province of India, after the provincial government backtracked on a decision to allocate the company a lease for the region.<BR><P>
SA MAY HOST NON-ALIGNED MOVEMENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA has offered to host the next heads of government summit of the Non-Aligned Movement in 1999, Foreign Affairs spokesman Marco Boni said.<BR><P>
1997 LIKELY TO PROVE WATERSHED YEAR FOR ECONOMY <I>(The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Much scope for debate exists as to whether or not SAs economic transformation has kept pace with the countrys political transformation. The trends of the two cornerstones destined to determine the nations future are evolving rapidly (though some say not rapidly enough), with 1997 slated to be a watershed year for development of the economic front. Looming crucial issues, hopefully capable of resolution during the course of the year, are the abolition of foreign exchange controls, significant moves in the privatisation arena, a national Budget which signals real (inflation-adjusted) cuts in government spending and $2-billion loan from the International Monetary Fund. Even should all this materialise, economic growth seems unlikely to match the 3% expected for 1996, in spite of predictions of a stronger intentional economy. Consumers face a tough 12 months as the economy stalls in the face of high interest rates, a chronically weak currency, rising inflation, foreign competition, intransigent labour, a manufacturing sector which has not followed through on 1995' buoyancy and the continuing inadequacy of RDP (Reconstruction and Development Programme) delivery.<BR><P>
ERWIN TIPPED AS NEW FINANCE MINISTER <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin is tipped to become South Africas new Minister of Finance.  He will replace Trevor Manuel, who is to be shifted to the Foreign Affairs Ministry, in a major shake-up of the cabinet to be announced at the opening of Parliament by President Nelson Mandela on February 7, top ANC sources said yesterday.<BR><P>





