<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 2 JANUARY 1997 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



MANDELA PROMISES FASTER RATE OF DEVELOPMENT <I>(The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
President Mandela has expressed satisfaction with progress made by the government since 1994 and has pledged that more emphasis will be put on speeding up implementation of development programmes. In an optimistic New Years message - in stark contrast to that of National Party leader F W de Klerk - Mandela said solid foundations for reconstruction and development had been laid, and hailed the signing in to law of the new constitution and other events as milestones in 1996. However, De Klerk said the ANC/SA Communist Party/Congress of SA Trade Unions alliance had, by "their rejection of a consensus model for the new constitution", assumed the responsibility of governing SA on its own. "The alliance has subsequently failed in all areas. The distressing development with regard to education, the ongoing erosion of health services, the failure of the Reconstruction and Development Programme, the bungling of foreign affaiars and, above all, the surging crime wave are some of the most glaring examples of the failure of the governing party. The impression of a ship drifting downstream, apparently rudderless, is constantly compounded. In short, the ANC displays a lack of vision for the country and for itself, and it is in the grip of an identity7 crisis which is harming the country."<BR><P>
BUSINESS WITH EUROPE IS BOOMING <I>(The Star)</I><BR>
The value <I>[to South Africa]</I> of imports from Europe has doubled over the past four years, while trade with Asia is expected to reach record levels this year. Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo says in a review of his departments activities during 1996 the opening up of relations with Europe has had a direct effect on patterns of trade. Trade with Asia has incraesed 30% and it is now the countrys second largest trading bloc.<BR><P>
A BETTER YEAR FOR ALL <I>(The Star Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
The New Year stretches ahead of SA replete with both danger and opportunity. What are the nations priorities, its resolutions , its hopes and its fears at the start of 1997? Two-and-a-half years into democracy, SA faces much the same tasks as before: to maintain political stability, economic growth and development in the full sense of the word.<BR><P>
THE WEAK SHAL INHERIT BONDAGE<BR>
by Colin Douglas, parliamentary affairs manager of the SA Institute of Race Relations <I>(The Star)</I><BR>
President Nelson Mandelas government might be showing signs of authoritarianism, but it is exercising remarkable restraint, given a society so complacent even Mother Theresa would be tempted to tyranny if she were in charge. SAs main problem is not its government. The problem is civil society that, with few exceptions, is so warty of engaging in open criticism, so devoid of vision and so desperate not to be different that often it may as well roll over and play dead.<BR><P>
GLOBAL TRADE PORTENTS LOOKING GOOD<BR>
by Garth le Pere, executive director of the Foundation for Global Dialogue <I>(The Star)</I><BR>
The conclusion of the Singapore meeting of the World Trade Organisation and its 120 members trade ministers provides an opportune moment to reflect on the challenges of liberalising global trade. There is great optimism about international economic integration through freedom of trade and open markets. Perhaps not for a century have political ideas and economic trends come together in happy coincidence. <BR><P>
