MARKET JOLTED BY RUSSIAN SALE WARNING<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Precious metals markets shuddered yesterday amid warnings by Russia that it planned to dip into its resources - which include gold, platinum, palladium and diamonds to help plug a huge budget shortfall.<BR><P>
INDIA IS WORLDS LARGEST GOLD MARKET<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
BOMBAY - Indias legendary hunger for gold increased 14% to 474 tons last year, making it the worlds largest market, the World Gold Council said in a report released yesterday.<BR><P>
LIFTING OF CONTROLS A GRADUAL PROCESS<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
NEW YORK - SA could expand its prosperity by staying with its gradual course of liberalising domestic capital controls, despite the rands recent slump, US analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
ORYX CONSIDERS OFFERING SHAREHOLDERS A DISCOUNT<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Gengolds free State mine Oryx might offer a 50% discount to tempt shareholders into its R600m rights offer, sources said yesterday.<BR><P>
UZBEKISTAN EXPECTS AVERAGE 1996 GOLD PRICE OF $420<I> (Reuters)</I><BR>
TOKYO - The head of Uzbekistans National Bank for Foreign Economic Activity said he expects the average world gold price in 1996 to be around $420 per ounce.<BR><P>
GOLD SET TO SHINE, SAYS LIBERTYS MCALPINE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
The outlook for an upward break in the gold price was continually improving, Liberty Asset Management chairman Roy McAlpine said.<BR><P>
RUSSIA 1995 ROUGH DIAMOND EXPORTS WORTH $2,979bn <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
