<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 22 FEB. 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>
130 000 MINEWORKERS WILL LOSE JOBS - BOTHA<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
More than 130 000 mineworkers, or 22% of the present 600 000 strong workforce, would lose their jobs before the end of next year, with a major socio-economic impact on the country, Mineral and Energy Affairs Minister Pik Botha said in Parliament yesterday.<BR><P>
<I><FONT SIZE=4>CHAMBER PRESIDENT RESPONDS...<BR>
THE PRESIDENT of the CHAMBER OF MINES, Mr AT du PLESSIS says:<BR>
"The Chamber of Mines does not share the view that more than 130 000 jobs could be lost in the mining industry in the next two years as expressed in parliament yesterday by Mineral and Energy Affairs Minister Pik Botha.<BR>
"While we recognise the unfortunate fact that some jobs could be lost in the face of persistent prevailing negative conditions in the gold mining industry, we do not anticipate they will reach anything near the magnitude Minister Botha gave yesterday.<BR>
"We have discussed the matter with the Minister and will pursue it further with the source from which his information came."<BR><P>
</FONT></I>
