<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b>
<center><b><h1><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 21 FEB. 1996 - at 10H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>

FUNDS APPROVED FOR LEON COMMISSION PROPOSALS <I>(Business Day,Jhb)</I><BR>
The Cabinet has approved the allocation of R29,8m to be included in the Mineral and Energy Affairs Departments 1996/97 budget for the implementation of the Leon Commissions mine health and safety recommendations released in March last year.<BR><P>
ANGLO SEEKING $1BN IN REVOLVING CREDIT<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American and its Luxembourg subsidiary, ARH, are seeking a $1bn revolving credit facility in a move which could signal plans for massive offshore expansion.<BR><P>
GOLD SINKS BELOW KEY $400 AFTER SELLING <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold sank below the key $400 level in New York last night as selling on the US futures exchange, Comex, dented the metal.<BR><P>
ECONOMIC CRISIS LOOMS - EXPERT <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA government had to take radical steps, including far-reaching public sector retrenchments and the privatisation of state assets, to avoid a full-blown economic crisis this decade, insurance giant, Old Mutuals chief economist, Dave Mohr said yesterday.<BR><P>
BUNDESBANK MAY HANG ON TO ITS GOLD<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The Bundesbank had always been sceptical about the IMFs proposals to sell gold, Bundesbank president Hans Tietmeyer said yesterday.<BR><P>
LIFTING OF EXCHANGE CONTROLS IS JUST A MATTER OF TIMING<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
SA was set to lift exchange controls, and all that was left was for government to work out the timing and details, President Mandela said yesterday.<BR><P>
CALL FOR TWO-TIER LABOUR MARKET<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American Industrial Corporation yesterday called for a two-tier labour market to allow new investments at a different and lower wage level without minimum standards and said the unions "should stay out of this sector".<BR><P>
RAND SLIDE SHAKES STOCK MARKET<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
Share prices fell yesterday as sentiment was undermined by the rands crash, a lower gold price, higher long-term interest rates and weaker foreign bourses.<BR><P>
GHANA LEADS NEW AFRICAN GOLD RUSH AS SA DECLINES<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
ABIDJAN - With gold at recent six year highs on international markets and SA still a huge producer, but showing signs of decline, investor interest has turned to the rest of Africa.<BR><P>
GOLD CAN BE USEFUL GUIDE ON INFLATION - GREENSPAN <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan on Tuesday called gold a very useful indicator of inflationary expectations, but shied away from commenting on recent price swings.<BR><P>
DE BEERS TO HOUSE WORKERS OF ALL RACES<I> (Sowetan,Jhb)</I><BR>
The rising tempers over family accommodation for black workers at De Beers Namaqualand mine may soon cool off following managements announcement yesterday that it would purchase land to house employees of all races.<BR><P>
