<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b>
<center><b><h1><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 20 FEB. 1996 - at 12H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></Center><BR><P>
MINE BILL TO USHER IN NEW ERA<I> (Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The new Mine Health and Safety Bill, which was presented yesterday to the parliamentary committee on mineral and energy affairs, will - according to unions and industry -usher in a new safer, more co-operative era in SA mining.<BR><P>
SIX MINE DEATHS COINCIDE WITH TABLING OF SAFETY BILL<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers has reacted strongly to the deaths of six mine workers killed in two accidents at Anglo Americans Vaal Reefs No 2 shaft and Western Deep Levels East Mine yesterday morning.<BR><P>
RESERVE BANK STEPS IN AS RAND IS PUMMELLED<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The Reserve Bank put a parachute on the rands fall yesterday, stopping it from plunging past R3,90 to the dollar in another day of high drama in the foreign exchange market.<BR><P>
MINERALS DEPARTMENT TOLD TO RECRUIT EXPERTS<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The International Energy Agency has questioned the Minerals and Energy Affairs Departments approach to policy making, particularly its outlay on outside consultants, which came to R15,7m this fiscal year.<BR><P>
ECONOMISTS RULE OUT RATE CUT AFTER CURRENCYS DIVE<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The rands dive would halt the decline in inflation only if it remained low for some time, economists said yesterday.  Analysing the effects of the rands collapse on the economy, economists said the units collapse was also likely to postpone a cut in interest rates, as one of the motives for a rate cut would have been to weaken the rand.<BR><P>
ANGLO TO LIFT STAKE IN NICKEL VENTURE<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American South America (Amsa) would increase its stake in Venezuelan nickel project Loma de Niquel to 85% from a current 10% at a net cost of $33,1m, parent Minorco announced yesterday.<BR><P>
NUM/GFSA SIGN EDUCATION PACT<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
The gold and coal mining companies in the Gold Fields group signed an adult basic education and training agreement with the NUM yesterday.<BR><P>
AUSTRALIAN MINERS RATE CHILE/ARGENTINA SAFEST <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SYDNEY - Chile and Argentina have taken the top two slots in a world risk survey to find the countries which Australias 30 leading mining companies see as safe or risky for investment.  The 1996 survey of 30 mining houses, conducted by Australias Mining Monthly and the Export Finance and Insurance Corp, found Chile was seen to be the least risky in a list of 15 resource-rich nations.<BR><P>
GHANA AT FOREFRONT OF AFRICAN GOLD RUSH <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
ABIDJAN - With gold at six-year highs on international markets and SA still a huge producer but showing signs of decline, investor interest has turned to the rest of Africa. Ghana, which revamped its mining code a decade ago, is still at the forefront of a new African gold rush, but other countries are following closely in its wake.  West Africa, where many pre-colonial empires built their might and wealth on gold, has been a prime target.<BR><P>
