<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><center><b><h1><b>
<center><b><h1><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 19 FEB. 1996 - at 12H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center><BR><P></Center>

<FONT SIZE=3>MINISTERS CALL MINING INDABA<I> (Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Labour Minister Tito Mboweni and Mineral and Energy Affairs Minister Pik Botha plan to call SAs mining houses and unions to a series of meetings to discuss the industrys plans to avert major job losses.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD STARTS NEGOTIATIONS WITH GROUP ON HOSTEL MANAGEMENT.<I> (Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Randgold is discussing contracting out the management of its mineworkers hostels to a black business group run by a senior female ANC member of parliament.<BR><P>
ANGLO WINS EXEMPTION FOR SUNDAY SHIFTS<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Mineral and Energy Affairs Minister Pik Botha on Friday granted three Anglo American Freegold shafts exemption to work on Sundays in the wake of an agreement with six mining unions for workers to work 12 days on and have two days off.<BR><P>
TRANSPORT GREEN PAPER CLEARS WAY FOR PRIVATISATION OF NON-KEY ASSETS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The transport Green Paper, released at the weekend, recommends a major shake-up of SAs transport institutions and is intended to clear the way for new investment opportunities, including the outright privatisation of some non-key entities.<BR><P>
MANDELA FACTOR LEAVES RAND A TARGET<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The rands collapse last week showed how vulnerable the currency was to the Mandela factor, Reserve Bank governor Chris Stals said at the weekend.<BR><P>
PROTESTING GHANAIANS SEIZE MINING EQUIPMENT<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
ACCRA - Inhabitants of a town in Ghanas Ashanti region have seized seismic equipment, vehicles, spare parts and other items belonging to three gold-mining companies to protest against their poor treatment by the companies, the Ghana News Agency reported at the weekend.<BR><P>
SA STILL A TOP TARGET FOR US CAPITAL - OFFICIAL <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
South Africa was still one of the top destinations for US capital despite the geographic barriers, a senior US government official said at the weekend.  Oregon-based legislative director Christopher Porter, who is accompanying a 26-firm trade mission to SA led by Congresswoman Elizabeth Furse, said although US firms normally preferred trading with Pacific Rim counterparts, SA was still very attractive.<BR><P>
SAS SOFT-SHOE SHUFFLE FLOPS AT WORLD FORUM<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
Perhaps it was because of our years of isolation, but from a journalists perspective, SA looked amateurish in comparison to other emerging economies at the World Economic Forum held in Davos, Switzerland from February 1 to 6.<BR><P>
SA ECONOMY IS "WEAK RELATIVE TO ITS POTENTIAL"<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
SA is running on only three cylinders.  Its growth rate is only 3% while it should be somewhere between 6% and 8%. <BR><P>
RANDS CRASH DENTS PLANS TO EASE FOREX<I> (Sunday Times, Business Times, Jhb)</I><BR>
Much of governments hard work in phasing out exchange controls was undone on Friday when the rand crashed to an all-time low against the US dollar.  The extent of the currencys fall has taken officials by surprise and could lead to a delay in the timetable for easing remaining foreign exchange restrictions.<BR><P>
GOLD - RECOVERS FOOTING WITH HELP FROM RANDS WOES<I> (Reuters)</I><BR>
NEW YORK - Gold prices recovered their footing this week, despite a worrisome stumble Monday, and got an extra lift Friday from the SA rands tumble to all-time lows against the dollar, traders said.<BR><P>
REFORMS SPUR GUINEAS MINING REVOLUTION <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
CONAKRY - Guinea looks headed for a mining revolution propelled by investment in gold prospecting and production by big industry names, mining sources say.  New laws reinforcing security of investment and cutting costs and red tape have lured mining companies from all corners of the globe to join in the search for minerals ranging from gold and diamonds to nickel and rare earths.<BR><P>
BRAZIL CVRD DENIES GOLD MINE RESERVES 900 TONNES<I> (Reuters)</I><BR>
RIO DE JANEIRO - Brazilian state mining giant Companhia Vale do Rio Doce has denied newspaper reports that a recently-announced gold mine could contain reserves in excess of 900 tonnes, a spokesman said.<BR><P>
POLISH COLLIERS CLINCH DEAL ENDING PAY STRIKE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
WARSAW - Workers and management said they had clinched a deal on Sunday to end a pay strike at eight mines run by state-owned Nadwislanska Spolka Weglowa which has thrown Polands coal industry into turmoil for two weeks.<BR><P>
BUSINESS SECTOR AGAINST MINIMUM WAGES<I> (Beeld,Jhb)</I><BR>
Excessive labour regulations, especially with regard to minimum wages, are one of the major restrictions on the provision of jobs, and the introduction of minimum wages in developing countries like Zimbabwe have led to great losses in job opportunities, says business lobby group,  Business SA.<BR><P>
NEW HOPE NEAR COLLIERY <I> (Beeld,Jhb)</I><BR>
A bright idea by a Sasol employee has led to the beginning of a large-scale agricultural project near a colliery close to Secunda, which is now providing more and more work for entrepreneurs in the region.<BR><P>
EXCHANGE CONTROLS TO BE EASED GRADUALLY<I> (The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Reserve Bank governor Chris Stals said assumptions in the market that foreign exchange controls would be scrapped at a stroke were wrong.<BR><P>
CLASH LOOMS OVER HOLIDAYS<I> (Sowetan, Jhb)</I><BR>
Organised labour and SA's government of national unity are heading for a collision over the planned reduction of public holidays as announced by Home Affairs Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi on Thursday.  Cosatu head of information and technology Charley Lewis said the federation took exception to the fact that only business was consulted.<BR><P>
DE BEERS TO BUY PLOTS<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
De Beers had proposed buying serviced plots in Port Nolloth for acquisition by employees whose wives wished to move to Namaqualand, the company said yesterday.<BR><P>
WHY GOLD CAN RISE FURTHER<I> (Finansies & Tegniek, 16/2/96, Jhb)</I><BR>
Gold and other precious metals have begun a recovery that can go far, partly because there is such a tremendous liquidity building up internationally.  The main source is Japan where low interest rates and stimulation by the State to lift the country from its long recession are gaining momentum.</FONT><BR><P>
