<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 15 FEB. 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center><BR><P>
ELECTRICIAN MAY HAVE CAUSED MINE DISASTER <I>(The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
An inquiry into one of South Africa's worst mine disasters yesterday heard that 104 men were killed last year because an electrician tampered with safety features on an underground train to speed it up.<BR><P>

MINERS AGREE TO HARSH NEW SHIFTS <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
In an attempt to prevent shaft closures, mining unions have signed an undertaking for their members to work 12 days continuously with two days off, instead of a five-day week plus every second Saturday.<BR><P> 

HEAVY RAINS KNOCK INGWES PRODUCTION<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Torrential rainfall had knocked production at some of Ingwes largest coal mines, the group said yesterday.  MD David Murray said production had been affected at the Middelburg Mine Services and Optimum operations because rain had rendered access to some loading faces unsafe.<BR><P>
