<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 14 FEB. 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center><BR><P>
GREEN PAPER PROPOSES SHORTER WORKING WEEK, MORE OVERTIME PAY
<I>(Business Day,Jhb)</I><BR>
A Green Paper on minimum employment standards has proposed more flexible working arrangements, a one-hour reduction in weekly working hours to 45 hours and a higher overtime pay rate.<BR><P>
BID TO ALLAY FEARS OVER COMPETITION<I>(Business Day,Jhb)</I><BR>
CAPE TOWN - Trade and Industry Minister Trevor Manuel moved yesterday to calm the growing storm surrounding competition policy legislation, indicating that no final decisions had been taken and suggesting that the publication of new legislation was not imminent.<BR><P>
DULL PRECIOUS METAL PRICES KNOCK IMPLATS EARNINGS<I>(Business Day,Jhb)</I><BR>
Gencors platinum producer Impala Platinum (Implats) reported a hefty 27% drop in attributable income to R92,7m in the six months to December after dull precious metal prices and a relatively strong exchange rate affected the bottom line.<BR><P>
FINANCE CHIEFS OPTIMISTIC ABOUT EASING FOREX CONTROL<I>(Business Day,Jhb)</I><BR>
Finance Minister Chris Liebenberg and Reserve Bank governor Chris Stals began encouraging the markets yesterday to anticipate relaxation of exchange controls.<BR><P>  
INTEREST RATES EXPECTED TO FALL IN THE SHORT TERM<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
Interest rates look set on a downward trend in the short term and three cuts in the Reserve Bank rate should be forthcoming between now and the end of next year, says Southern Life economist Sandra Gordon.<BR><P>
NEW RULES, GOLD FINDS SET TO SPUR INDONESIA MINING <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
JAKARTA - New rules and a potentially huge gold discovery are expected to trigger a flurry of mining activity in Indonesia, an industry official said on Tuesday.  Ben Wahju, secretary-general of the Indonesian Mining Association, said declining gold output in the former Soviet Union was another likely cause of the mining boom.<BR><P>
GOLD KEY ELEMENT IN SAS SOCIAL OUTLOOK <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Gold was a key variable in SAs social outlook due to its sensitivity to price and employment, Marcel Golding, a spokesman for the ANC told an IBC Conferences Ltd precious metals forum here.  Golding, the chairman of the SA parliaments Mineral and Energy  Portfolio committee, said about 180 000 jobs had been lost in the gold mining industry since the late 1980s.<BR><P>
PERU GOLD OUTPUT SEEN UP TO 60 TONNES IN 96 <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LIMA - Perus total gold production will rise to 60 tonnes this year from 56 tonnes in 1995 and is expected to nearly double to 100 tonnes by the year 2000, industry officials said.<BR><P>
GOLD TESTS $400, BUT BULLMARKET SEEN INTACT <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Gold was flirting with a plunge below the psychological $400 per ounce level on Tuesday as surging US shares diverted speculators attention.  But even if golds spectacular New Years rally has lost some momentum, the metals supply-demand fundamentals and an overheated US stock market still points to firm prices, analysts said.<BR><P>
HIGH GOLD PRICE VOLATILITY UNLIKELY AGAIN - AIG <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Gold would never again attain the high volatility of the late 1970s and early 1980s, Sidney V Gold, managing director of AIG International, told a gold forum here on Wednesday.<BR><P>
COAL DELIVERIES HALTED AT MORE POLISH MINES <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
WARSAW - Miners at about a third of Polands coalmines stopped coal deliveries Tuesday, stepping up a two-week-long pay protest, a Solidarity spokesman said.<BR><P>
WESTERN AREAS ISSUES SHARES<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
Western Areas has issued a total of 540 410 new shares to shareholders who have chosen the company's offer of capitalisation shares rather than an interim dividend.<BR><P>
MESSINA'S EARNINGS RISE<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
Messina has increased its attributable profit for the six months to 31 December from R2,2-million to R3,6-million.<BR><P>
AMGOLD'S SHARE PRICE WEAKENED A GREAT DEAL YESTERDAY<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
Amgold's share price weakened by 1 300c to R380 yesterday because sellers are still disposing of their gold shares.<BR><P>
FIVE MINERS DIE<I> (The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Five mineworkers died yesterday after two rockfalls in succession shook a tunnel 2 400 m below the surface at Vaal Reefs Gold Mine's No. 11 Shaft, near Orkney.<BR><P>
NORWAY PM 'ABUSED' PARLIAMENT SPEECH:  NP<I> (The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Norwegian Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland had abused the opportunity to address the South African Parliament by aligning herself with the ANC, National Party Foreign Affairs spokesman Boy Geldenhuys said yesterday.<BR><P>
NORWAY GAVE R1bn IN HELP<I> (Sowetan, Jhb)</I><BR>
The people of Norway had made financial contributions in the struggle against apartheid to the tune of R1-billion, Norwegian Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland has revealed.<BR><P>
