<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 29 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P><B><I>PRESIDENT NELSON MANDELA YESTERDAY ANNOUNCED HIS FIRST MAJOR CABINET RESHUFFLE WHICH SAW THE RESIGNATION OF FINANCE MINISTER CHRIS LIEBENBERG, HIS REPLACEMENT WITH TRADE & INDUSTRY MINISTER TREVOR MANUEL AND THE SCRAPPING OF THE RECONSTRUCTION & DEVELOPMENT PROGRAME (RDP) DEPARTMENT. HERE FOLLOWS A SUMMARY OF HOW THE MAJOR NEWSPAPERS REPORTED THESE DEVELOPMENTS TODAY ...</I></B><BR><P>
MANUEL TAKES UP FINANCE POST <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Finance Minister Chris Liebenberg resigned yesterday, sparking the scrapping of the Reconstruction and Development Programme department and a host of other changes which will consolidate the African National Congress power in the government of national unity.<BR><P>
MIXED RESPONSE TO CABINET CHANGES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The appointment of a new Finance Minister and the accompanying Cabinet reshuffle drew a mixed reaction from business last night.  Anglo American said it had confidence in Trevor Manuel as Finance Minister and Alec Erwin as Trade and Industry Minister, but the SA Chamber of Business warned that Finance Minister Chris Liebenbergs departure came at an unfortunate time.<BR><P>
SHOCK WAVES OVER LIEBENBERG<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
Pres. Nelson Mandela yesterday caused a surprise with his first far-reaching Cabinet reshuffle, after the unexpected resignation of Finance Minister Chris Liebenberg.  The financial markets fell sharply when the news of Liebenberg's resignation leaked out.  He is being replaced by Trade and Industry Minister Trevor Manuel, the first ANC incumbent of this key position.<BR><P>
FINANCIAL MARKETS RESPOND VERY NEGATIVELY TO MANUEL <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The financial markets responded extremely negatively after the news of Trevor Manuel being appointed Finance Minister leaked out.  Reuters sent out an incorrect report yesterday afternoon that Alec Erwin, not Manuel, had been given the post.  The markets then immediately firmed.  Manuel and Erwin found this amusing when they heard about it at a news conference last night.<BR><P>
LIEBENBERG'S RESIGNATION PUTS PRESSURE ON MARKETS<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The news of Finance Minister Chris Liebenberg's resignation placed financial markets under pressure yesterday, but there were no signs of a large-scale collapse.<BR><P>
BUSINESSMEN REGRET LIEBENBERG'S RETIREMENT<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
It was a pity there had to be a change in the Cabinet's finance portfolio so soon again, SA Foundation president Conrad Strauss said in response to the news of Chris Liebenberg's retirement.  The Foundation felt, however, that Trevor Manuel and Gill Marcus identified themselves fully with the Government's fiscal policy.<BR><P>
THE RIGHT TIME TO LEAVE:  LIEBENBERG<I> (The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
"I believe now is the right time for me to leave," Finance Minister Chris Liebenberg said in his farewell speech delivered to the National Assembly yesterday evening.  "I came in here with the view that it should not be long-term," he said.<BR><P>
DEDICATED ERWIN A GOOD BACK-UP MINISTER<I> (Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
Newly appointed Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin had a long involvement with labour before he became Deputy Finance Minister in May 1994.  Erwin was viewed as a "very good back-up minister" who was completely dedicated to his task, said Ms Jenny Cargill, director of Businessmap SA, a policy information service.<BR><P>
<B><I>... IN OTHER NEWS ...</I></B><BR><P>
INCIDENT-FREE MARCH IN CENTRAL JOBURG <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A massive security force presence, coupled with a deal between authorities and march organisers, disspelled widespread domestic and international fears of bloodshed and led to a largely incident-free march through central Johannesburg yesterday by about 8 000 Zulus commemorating the 1994 Shell House shootings.<BR><P>
GOVT, LABOUR AND BUSINESS TO TALK ABOUT INFRASTRUCTURE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government, labour and the private sector will meet today to thrash out a framework for investment in economic and social infrastructure, a move which could see billions mobilised for infrastructure spending.<BR><P>
SAS BALANCE OF TRADE IN R1,27BN SWING TO BLACK <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
South Africas trade balance swung R1,27bn into the black last month, following heavy diamond exports and a sharp drop in key imports.<BR><P>
MORE WORKING DAYS LOST IN FIRST QUARTER <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
About 175 000 working days were lost in the first quarter of 1996 as a result of strikes, according to labour consultants Andrew Levy & Associates.  This is approximately three times more than in the first quarter of last year.  The National Union of Mineworkers was responsible for 28% of the working days lost.<BR><P>
NUM LASHES OUT OVER LAYOFFS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers has reacted strongly to the retrenchment of 1 800 workers in Gengolds Winkelhaak gold mine near Evander.<BR><P>
STRIKES COST SOUTH AFRICA 1,6-MILLION WORKING HOURS<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
A total of 1,6-million working hours was lost as a result of strikes last year, compared with the average of 3,6-million working hours per year for the previous four years, Labour Minister Tito Mboweni said in reply to a question in the National Assembly.<BR><P>
ANALYSTS SAY JOEL WILL NOT PAY DIVIDENDS UNTIL 2001<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
JCIs gold mine, HJ Joel would withhold dividends until 2001 when the brunt of its capital expenditure programme was over, analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
NEW LEASE ON LIFE <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
The H J Joel gold mine will gain a new lease on life with the implementation of a capital expansion programme aimed at exploiting the mine's remaining ore body, the company says.<BR><P>
GOLD COUNCIL COMMENTS ON FAMILIAR BELGIAN SALE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - There is a "sense of<I> deja vu</I>" about Wednesdays announcement of a 
203-tonne sale of gold from Belgium Central Bank reserves, according to Helen Junz, director the World Gold Councils economic service.<BR><P>
CHINA FINDS GOLD BELT WITH 4,760 T RESERVES -AGENCY <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BEIJING - Chinese prospectors have found a huge gold-rich belt with estimated reserves of 4,760 tonnes in the Qinling area of north-west Chinas Shaanxi province, the Xinhua news agency said on Thursday.<BR><P>
LOSS FOR DIAMOND GROUP <I> (Beeld) </I><BR>
The Consolidated Diamond Corporation has recorded a loss of R352 000 for the six months to 31 December.<BR><P>
UNBUNDLING NO LONGER A DIRTY WORD  <I> (Beeld) </I><BR>
Unbundling, once a politically sensitive subject not taken up lightly in the corridors of monolithic South African corporations, soon abandoned its political mantle as shareholders exerted pressure to loosen the iron grip of a small number of giants.  Among the large mining houses, Gold Fields is the following possible candidate for unbundling.<BR><P>
ASS. MANGANESE DISTRIBUTES INTERIM DIVIDEND OF 250c <I> (Beeld) </I><BR>
Associated Manganese has distributed an interim dividend of 250c per share payable to shareholders registered in the books of the company at the close of business of 12 April.<BR><P>
COSATU TO PROPOSE 4%<I> (Finansies & Tegniek, week 22/3/96)</I><BR>
The Congress of South African Trade Unions (Cosatu) intends proposing that undertakings should be forced to spend 4% of their "profit" on the training of workers.  The proposal will be contained in Cosatu's own growth report, to be issued next week, in reply to the SA Foundation's recent growth proposals.<BR><P>
BE CAUTIOUS OF DIAMONDS AS INVESTMENTS<I> (Finansies & Tegniek)</I><BR>
There is often a great temptation to invest in diamonds or other tangible assets, but these are not investments in the true sense of the word - they should rather be regarded as collector's items, and as such require expert knowledge to ensure a satisfactory return.  One who wishes to invest in a tangible asset would be better advised to put his money into gold.<BR><P>
NO HIGHER PRICES FOR INGWE<I> (Finansies & Tegniek)</I><BR>
The view that the peak of the coal sector's cycle on the stock exchange has passed received confirmation this week by the news that Japanese buyers had refused to increase contract prices, and in fact tried to negotiate lower prices.  Local producers had been hoping for an increase of about 4%.  Ingwe Coal MD David Murray feels, however, that too much should not be read into the group's failure to negotiate higher prices.<BR><P>
</DOC>
