<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 28 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>

SA HOLDS ITS BREATH OVER ZULU MARCH <I>(Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
Tension is mounting both domestically and internationally over the armed march by thousands of Zulus through the streets of Johannesburg today, and cultural weapons can be the spark in the tinder-box as the Police say illegal weapons will be taken away from the marchers.<BR><P>
ZULU MARCH PLACES FINANCIAL MARKETS UNDER PRESSURE<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Foreign investors fear that today's planned march through the streets of Johannesburg by thousands of Zulus to commemorate the Shell House massacre will lead to mass violence, and this placed the South African financial markets under great pressure yesterday.<BR><P>
LIEBENBERG RUMOURED TO BE QUITTING<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Finance Minister Chris Liebenberg did not deny market rumours yesterday that he would be resigning soon, saying only after questioning that he occupied his post "at the pleasure of the president". President Mandela is expected to make an announcement in this regard later today.<BR><P>
TRAPPED WORKER RESCUED FROM MINE AFTER 36 HOURS<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The management of Iscor's Tshikondeni colliery yesterday gave support and assistance with funeral arrangements to the 10 grieving families of rescue workers killed in the mine on Monday afternoon.<BR><P>
MINE TRAGEDY TO BE PROBED<I> (Sowetan, Jhb)</I><BR>
The Mineral and Energy Affairs Department is to investigate the accident at Iscor's Tshikondeni colliery which claimed 10 lives on Monday, the company said yesterday.<BR><P>
BIDVEST ENTERS RACE TO BUY JOHNNIC STAKE<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Bidvest Group has emerged as a player in the National Empowerment Consortiums plans to buy Anglo Americans 48% stake in Johnnic.<BR><P>
MINERS ON STRIKE OVER PAYMENTS <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Demands for the immediate payment of employer and employee contributions to the pension and provident fund was the centre of a three-day strike by about 6 000 workers at Amplats Rustenberg Platinum mines.<BR><P>
WINKELHAAK GOLD MINE CUTS 1 800 JOBS<I> (Business Day & Beeld)</I><BR>
Gengolds second largest gold producer Winkelhaak is to curtail its activities by closing the production area between levels 9 and 16 of No. 2 shaft and axe 1 800 jobs, with a drop in gold production to 650kg a month, the company said yesterday.<BR><P>
NO QUORUM FOR BLYVOOR<I> (Beeld)</I><BR>
The meeting of Blyvooruitzicht shareholders for the purpose of a special resolution over inter alia increasing its share capital had to be adjourned because there was no quorum.<BR><P>
STRUGGLING HJ JOEL LOOKS FORWARD TO NEXT CENTURY<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Struggling gold mine HJ Joel was considering selling forward its entire gold production until 2001 to avoid tapping its shareholders for more cash, owner JCI said yesterday.<BR><P>
COAL UPGRADE HAS MARKET<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
An upgrade of the Richards Bay Coal Terminals capacity to a proposed 69-million tons a year would be supported by growth in the international market, Ingwe Coal Corp MD Dave Murray said yesterday.<BR><P>
GOLD FIELDS PUTS WOMAN AT TOP<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Mining group Gold Fields has given its clearest indication yet that it intends to update company culture with the milestone appointment of a woman to a senior management position.  But new coal, base metal and platinum division GM Barbara Day seems largely unfazed by suggestions that her appointment is a benchmark in the mining industry.<BR><P>
SURVEY JUDGES MANY COMPANIES FATALLY FLAWED<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
A third of the 160 SA companies covered in a recent survey could be extinct within nine years because of neglect of competitiveness, shareholders, customer relations and knowledge of their markets.<BR><P>
WAGES SET TO BEAT INFLATION<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
Workers could expect an inflation-beating average increase of 10,2 percent in this years round of wage negotiations. <BR><P>
SAS MINE HEALTH, SAFETY BILL NEARS COMPLETION <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
The parliamentary committee on mineral and energy affairs will resolve differences between mine managers and workers on a new Mine Health and safety Bill, chairman Marcel Golding said on Wednesday.<BR><P>
SA GOLD MINES INCH TOWARDS SEVEN-DAY MINING WEEK <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
JCI is leading the way on implementing seven-day-a-week mining, but unless more SA gold mines follow suit little reprieve will be offered to the beleaguered industry, analysts said.<BR><P>
BELGIAN SALE MAY BE BULLISH FOR GOLD <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - A sale by the Belgian central bank of 203 tonnes of gold from its reserves to another central bank was fundamentally bullish for the gold market, bullion analysts said shortly after the sale was announced on Wednesday.<BR><P>
DUTCH PLAN NO GOLD DISPOSAL AFTER BELGIAN SALE<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
AMSTERDAM - The Dutch central bank said on Wednesday it did not plan to follow Belgiums lead and make any gold sales whatsoever in the near future.<BR><P>
BULGARIA MAY COLLATERALISE GOLD FOR LOANS<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SOFIA - Bulgaria might win new foreign loans by securing them against part of its gold reserves if it fails to clinch loans this year from international financial institutions, the central bank governor said.<BR><P>
DALLAS GOLD AND SILVER OFFERS INTERNET QUOTES <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
DALLAS - Dallas Gold and Silver Exchange Inc said on Wednesday it launched what it believes is the first live quotation service on the Internet for more than 200 precious metals products.  This activity is now combined with Computer Jewellery Exchange and is located at <A HREF="http://www.dgse.com">http://www.dgse.com</A>, the company said.<BR><P>
THOUSANDS TRAPPED BY PHILLIPPINE MINE SEEPAGE<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
MANILA - More than 3 000 people are stranded in the central Philippines by a torrent of possibly toxic mine waste that has poured into a river running by their villages, officials said Wednesday.<BR><P>
UNISEL STRIKERS BACK <I>(The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Striking employees at the Unisel gold mine have returned to work, a Gengold spokesman said yesterday.<BR><P>
ZCCM's QUARTER LOSSES SOAR <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines said it had posted a net loss of 2,87bn kwacha for the quarter ending 31 December, versus 2,27bn kwacha for the same period in 1994.<BR><P>
ANTWERP HAS OVER HALF WORLD DIAMOND TRADE <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Belgium's diamond trade consolidated its position as the world's biggest with a 14% rise in turnover in 1995, the Diamond High Council says.<BR><P>
US, JAPAN TO MINE INDONESIAN GOLD  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Japan's Sumitomo Corp. and US mining company Newmont Gold will develop a copper and gold mine in Indonesia at a total cost of $1,5bn, a report said yesterday.<BR><P>

