<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 27 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>


MINER BROUGHT TO SAFETY AFTER 10 DIE IN RESCUE ATTEMPT<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
A trapped mineworker was found alive underground and brought to safety yesterday after 10 members of a team trying to save him earlier were killed during a rockfall at Iscors Tshikondeni coal mine in Northern Province on Monday. The rescued miner is in a satisfactory condition.<BR><P>
TRADE WITH SOUTHEAST ASIA IS BOOMING, SAYS MBEKI<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
South Africas economic interaction with Southeast Asia is booming.  Trade with Singapore is more than R1,5bn, and Malaysia and Thailand follow closely with R1bn each. However, trade unions had been pinpointed as a serious deterrent to foreign investment.<BR><P>
STRIKE HALTS PRODUCTION AT UNISEL GOLD MINE<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
About 2 000 mineworkers at Unisel gold mine near Welkom in the Free State province brought production to a halt yesterday when they embarked on a sympathy strike to protest against the dismissal of 259 rock drill operators who went on an unofficial strike earlier.<BR><P>
RUSPLATS WORKERS STRIKE <I>(Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
Rustenburg Platinum is considering legal action against workers taking part in an illegal strike at its Union section.<BR><P>
ECONOMY BREAKING OUT OF CYCLE OF STAGNATION, DECLINE<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Economic growth in SA should address the social ills of high levels of joblessness and widespread poverty in the country, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said yesterday.<BR>
He is also reported as as saying SA was unhappy about the recent European Union trade negotiating mandate, but optimistic of a more generous deal from formal negotiations.<BR><P>
SA PLAN TO ESTABLISH TIES WITH BEIJING<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
BEIJING - In a blow to Taiwan, SA signalled its intention yesterday to open diplomatic relations with Beijing, Taipeis rival. <BR><P>
LABOUR CALLS FOR PENALTIES<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
Labour federations are to finalise proposals this weekend for a social equity contract that, among other things, proposes penalty taxes for companies that do not invest in job creation and the training of workers.<BR><P>
RED TAPE DELAYS MINE TRAINING<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
Bureaucratic delays and a lack of understanding of the reform process by operations managers were hampering the setting up of improved training and qualification systems in the mining industry, Bryan Phillips, human resources manager of Gencor, said on Monday.<BR><P>
GOLD SMELTERS CAUGHT AGAIN AT G HOSTEL<I> (Beeld)</I><BR>
Police have arrested 101 people at the notorious G Hostel near Welkom, and stolen gold dust which could yield pure gold worth as much as R1,8-million was seized.  The hostel is known for the gold washing and smelting activities that take place there. Caches of illegal weapons and marijuana were also seized.<BR><P>
GOLD PRICE BREAKS THROUGH $400 LEVEL<I> (Beeld)</I><BR>
The gold price broke through the $400 per ounce barrier for a while last night.<BR><P>
KINROSS PRODUCTION DISRUPTED<I> (Beeld)</I><BR>
Rock hoisting in the No. 1 shaft at Kinross will be disrupted for the next seven to 14 days after a drum shaft of the dual purpose winch broke down last week.<BR><P>
LTA EXPANDING TO MINING PRODUCTS<I> (Beeld)</I><BR>
LTA has taken over the activities of Boart Longyear SCS near Bronkhorstspruit.  The operation, now to be known as Steeledale SCS, manufactures rock anchors and other mining equipment.<BR><P>
RESEARCH WILL HELP WITH WAGE TALKS <I> (Beeld)</I><BR>
The first comprehensive piece of research on centralised bargaining was published by Nedlac yesterday and will probably play a crucial role in the annual wage negotiations held from April to August.  The research was done by Avril Joffe and Chris Lloyd of labour consultants Labour Market Alternatives.<BR><P>
HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE AUDITED <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The Parliamentary Portfolio Committee on Environmental Affairs and Tourism has called for a national audit of all hazardous and toxic substances in the country as a first step in formulating policy on these substances.
