<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 26 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>


EU BACKS MANDATE FOR SA TRADE <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
BRUSSELS - European Union foreign ministers last night approved a negotiating mandate for a free trade agreement with South Africa to evolve in the next 10 to 12 years.  However, as feared, the list of farm produce to be excluded from the deal amounted to 38,6% of SAs current exports to the EU, worth nearly R1,3bn.<BR><P>
GENGOLD DISMISSES STRIKING WORKERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gengold dismissed 259 underground rock drill operators after they embarked on an unofficial strike at the Unisel gold mine near Welkom in the Free State province, management said yesterday.<BR><P>
US FIRMS HAVE A MORAL OBLIGATION TO INVEST IN SA<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
United States companies have a moral and tactical obligation to invest in SA now that it is a democratic country, says well-known human rights lawyer Alan Dershowitz.<BR><P>
LIEBENBERG COMPARES TAX SYSTEMS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA tax system did not generally have a negative effect on the country as an investment destination, Finance Minister Chris Liebenberg said in Parliament yesterday.<BR><P>
RAND WILL NOT HELP NORTHAM<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The weakening of the rand against the dollar last month would not offset high operating costs at Gold Fields of SAs Northam Platinum when the ailing mine reports for the March quarter next month, analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
IMPLATS HOPEFUL ON SETTLEMENT<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Impala Platinum has rejected proposals from the Bafokeng tribe to settle their dispute over royalty payments on its Deeps Area in the Northwest province.<BR><P>
UNEMPLOYMENT THE MOTHER OF ALL OTHER CRISES, IMF TELLS SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Unemployment, the International Monetary Fund is telling SA, is not just another big problem.  It is the mother of them all, the crisis of crises, upon whose resolution SAs economic, political and social prospects all depend.<BR><P>
"TRADE UNIONS' FAULT THAT MILLIONS CAN'T FIND WORK" <I>(Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
It is the fault of trade unions that millions of South Africans cannot find work, Deputy President F W de Klerk said in the main address at the annual congress of the Institute for Life and Pension Advisers yesterday.<BR><P>
INDEX SURGES ON EXPECTATIONS OF GOLD REACHING $400<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
The all gold index surged 2,16% or 38,4 points to close at 1814,4 yesterday, with some analysts predicting the gold price could break through the $400 level in the near future, possibly even this week.<BR><P>
BUDGET REVEALS RANGE OF TAX BREAKS FOR MINING INDUSTRY<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
The Budget, while already old news, continues to reveal new insights to those who carefully peruse its content.  An instructive revelation not yet fully explored is the substantial tax breaks for gold mines, which reduce the top tax rate from 55 to 48,5%.<BR><P>
TRADE UNIONS NEED TO TAKE NOTE OF GLOBAL WAGES <I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
Trade unions would have to take note of average hourly wages in other countries if SA was to remain internationally competitive, said Mof Terreblanche, president of the Afrikaanse Handelsinstituut, representing predominantly Afrikaans-speaking businesses.
DIAMOND PLANT HEADING FOR TANZANIA<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
A second modular dense-medium separation diamond plant leaves for the Williamson Diamond Mines in Tanzania this week.<BR><P>
WESTWITS'S SHARE PRICE FALLS SHARPLY <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The share price of West Witwatersrand Gold Holdings fell a further 50c yesterday to a new low of 75c because of fears that the life of the mine was to be curtailed.<BR><P>
ASEAN CONGRESS CAN OPEN DOORS FOR SA<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
A congress at Midrand (midway between Johannesburg and Pretoria) today can open important doors between South Africa and members of the Association of South-East Asian Nations (ASEAN), and expectations are that this can be the start of a new era in South African trade history.<BR><P>
ANGLO DENIES NAIL BID FOR JOHNNIC<I> (The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Anglo American has not received any bid for Johnnies Industrial Corporation from New Africa Investments, Anglo public affairs director Michael Spicer says.<BR><P>
