 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 25 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>

EU TRADE LIST ANGERS SA NEGOTIATORS<I> (Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
South African  trade diplomats have reacted angrily to news that European Union ambassadors have bowed to pressure from the protectionist EU farm lobby and backed plans for a trade deal which would be far less generous to SA than previous proposals.<BR><P>
SWISS BANK GIVES NOD TO SA ECONOMY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA is better placed than most emerging markets to ensure that its sound economic policies survived, and fears about life after Mandela were exaggerated, Switzerlands Union Bank said.  The bank expected the economy to grow 4% this year, which is at the upper end of economists forecasts.<BR><P>
HULETT GIVES ALUMINIUM PLAN THE GO-AHEAD <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Tongaat-Hulett gave the go-ahead for its R2,5bn aluminium expansion plan on Friday, after governments rethink on import tariffs.<BR><P>
EXPORTERS UNABLE TO INCREASE COAL PRICES  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA steam coal exporters have failed to push through a price increase for contracts into Japan, despite earlier hopes of a rise on last years level.<BR><P>
DUBAI GOLD DEMAND PIVOTS ON WORLD PRICES - TRADE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
DUBAI - A further and rapid rise in world bullion prices could put the brakes on Indian subcontinent demand for gold in the Gulf trading hub of Dubai, traders in the United Arab Emirates (UAE) said on Sunday.<BR><P>
TAIWAN GOLD DEMAND SEEN DROPPING AFTER POLLS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Taiwanese overbought gold as tensions with China grew, but demand is expected to drop after the islands presidential election, local traders said on Monday.<BR><P>
CHINA RAISES 1995 GOLD OUTPUT TO 108 TONNES<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BEIJING - Chinas gold output in 1995 was 108 tonnes, the Xinhua news agency on Friday quoted officials as saying, and is expected to reach 150 tonnes by 2000.<BR><P>
CONS. MINING WARNS<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
Consolidated Mining has announced that it is engaged in negotiations that could have an effect on its share price.<BR><P>
EAST DAGGA RESTRUCTURED IN UNIQUE WAY <I> (Beeld)</I><BR>
East Daggafontein gold mine is to be restructured to improve the company's future prospects, chairman Peter Bieber announced at the weekend.<BR><P>
FOREIGNERS CRITICAL OF SA's LABOUR SYSTEM  <I> (Beeld)</I><BR>
The international policy board of Grant Thornton International has serious reservations about South Africa's labour market because while it is strictly regulated there is still an unemployment figure of over 40% in the country.<BR><P>



