<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 22 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>



<A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/fincttee.htm">BUDGET NOT HELPING TO CREATE JOBS</A> - CHAMBER OF MINES<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
The Budget presented last week not only did too little to promote economic growth, but also only postponed real cuts in State expenditure, Chamber of Mines CE Mr Tom Main said in Cape Town on Wednesday in a Chamber statement over the Budget.<I> [See also the <A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/96budcom.htm">Chamber's comment</A> on the Budget - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
PROVINCE AIDS MINERS<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The Northern Cape government planned to help small-scale mining groups buy mineral rights from De Beers, the province said yesterday.<BR><P>
FOUR MINES POISED TO GO OVER TO FULL CALENDAR <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Four of SAs largest gold mines are poised to convert to full calendar operations - a move the industry has vaunted as crucial to bolstering profitability in the besieged sector.<BR><P>
<I>... but Johannesburg's other morning paper aimed at the business community, Business Report , says ...</I><BR><P>
STUDY SUGGESTS RE-THINK OF PRODUCTIVITY<BR>
The mining industry can more than double operating profit without introducing Sunday work, a study presented last week by the Council for Scientific and Industrial Researchs Mining Tek shows.  This goes against conventional thinking that working on Sundays and holidays is the shortest route to improved gold-mining profitability.<BR><P>
AUSTRALIAN GOVT PLEDGES CERTAINTY FOR MINERS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
CANBERRA - Australian Resources Minister Warwick Parer on Friday pledged to boost the mining industry by increasing certainty in government decision-making - a situation sadly lacking in SA.<BR><P>
MINING REFORM GROUP PRAISES CLINTON BUDGET <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - Supporters of mining reform said Thursday they applauded measures in President Clintons budget proposal that would eliminate a tax loophole for the mining industry.<BR><P>
S. KOREAN COMPANIES EAGER FOR GOLD TRADING <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SEOUL - Trading houses of South Koreas diversified conglomerates, known as chaebol, have their eyes fixed on a fresh new business opportunity in world-wide gold trading, company officials and analysts said on Friday.<BR><P>
STONE MEMENTO TURNS OUT TO BE NEW MINERAL <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
A bright blue stone bought as a cheap holiday memento in Morocco fifteen years ago was found to be a previously unknown mineral when it was taken to the Natural History Museum in London for identification.<BR><P>
GOVERNMENT LOOKING AT LIFTING EXCHANGE CONTROL<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The Department of Finance is busy studying a Reserve Bank report on the various possibilities in connection with the lifting of exchange control measures.<BR><P>
SA MINERAL TECHNOLOGY TO BE MARKETED IN AUSTRALIA <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Mintek has appointed the company Chemical, Mining and Industrial Services in Brisbane as an agent, and South African mineral technology will soon be marketed in Australia.<BR><P>
H J JOEL RIGHTS TO PROCEED<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The rights issue of 84 H J Joel shares for every 100 owned at 250c each is to proceed.<BR><P>
CMI BUYS ASSETS OF JCI<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The shareholders of Consolidated Metallurgical Industries have approved the purchase of JCI's Thorncliff mineral and surface rights.<BR><P>
ORYX ISSUES 100m SHARES <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The rights issues of Oryx Gold Holdings involves the issuing of 100 598 764 new shares to shareholders who are registered today.<BR><P>
CANADIANS MINING IN ZAMBIA <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The Canadian Caledonian Mining Corporation of Toronto has signed a contract for exploration drilling in its Nama cobalt licence area.<BR><P>
WRC TO SPEND R40m<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
West Rand Consolidated Mines is going to spend another R40-million over the next 18 months to put the Goldridge opencast mining project between Vryburg and Mafikeng fully into operation.<BR><P>
CORRIDOR'S GEMS:  ADVICE SOUGHT <I>(The Citizen,Jhb)</I><BR>
Northern Province's environmental affairs department said on Wednesday it was seeking legal advice on the prospecting of alluvial diamonds in the Madimbo Corridor between South Africa and Zimbabwe, after an Australian company obtained a court interdict on Monday to start prospecting.<BR><P>
WORLD OIL GIANTS STUDY SA PROSPECTS <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Major international oil companies are assessing technical data on South African offshore oil and gas exploration blocks, and hopes are high that there will be applications to acquire oil prospecting rights from Soekor.<BR><P>

