<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 20 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>



MBOWENI MEETS MINING DELEGATION<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Labour Minister Tito Mboweni has defended the new  Labour Relations Act, saying it is flexible. Following a meeting between representatives of his ministry and a delegation from the Chamber of Mines led by its President,  At du Plessis yesterday, Mboweni said "anyone who says the LRA is inflexible has a major problem".<BR><P>
<I>... and another Johannesburg morning paper, The Citizen, reports ...</I><BR><P>
SA MINING SUMMIT IS POSSIBILITY:  MBOWENI<BR>
There appeared to be "no problem" between the mining industry and government on the holding of a summit meeting, Labour Minister Tito Mboweni said yesterday after talks with a Chamber of Mines delegation led by President At du Plessis.<BR><P>
<I>...while the Afrikaans language daily, Sake-Beeld, reports ...</I><BR><P>
NEW LABOUR ACT COMES INTO EFFECT ON 1 MAY<BR>
Everything is in place for the implementation of the new Labour Relations Act on 1 May, Labour Minister Tito Mboweni said yesterday.  He had met with the Chamber of Mines to discuss the new Act, among other things.<BR><P>
GOVT WILL NOT INSIST ON SOFT INVESTMENTS<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Government yesterday assured a delegation of business people that private-sector involvement in infrastructure investments would be on a strictly commercial basis - it would not expect "soft" loans or investments.<BR><P>
SA, RUSSIAN BUSINESSMEN HAVE OBSTACLES TO OVERCOME<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
SA and Russian businessmen would have to overcome a number of obstacles before trade between the two nations could develop, Trade and Industry Department Export Promotion Deputy Director Hennie Erasmus said yesterday.<BR><P>
SA MINES FEEL EFFECTS OF DOWNSIZING - SCARGILL<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA mining industry was starting to feel the effects of downsizing in the form of shaft closures, retrenchments and the destruction of communities, British unionist Arthur Scargill said.<BR><P>
IMF PUTS BLAME FOR UNEMPLOYMENT ON PROTECTIONISM <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - Continued high levels of protection for domestic manufacturers and a shortage of skilled labour were key factors in SAs unemployment crisis, Peter Doyle, an economist on the International Monetary Funds SA desk, said yesterday.<BR><P>
REGION RELIES ON SA<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The economic fortunes of southern Africa were linked to the success of SA, visiting British Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke said yesterday.<BR><P>
AMPLATS LOOKS AT PLANS FOR R300M EXPANSION <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American Platinum Corporation was expected to consider expansion plans of almost R300m at the end of this month, analysts said yesterday.  The groups plans were expected to focus on the Amandelbult section of its Rustenburg Platinum mine, where production would be bolstered to 520 000 tons a month from the current 440 000 tons.<BR><P>
JAPANS DAIWA LAUNCHES GOLD MINING INVESTMENT FUND <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
TOKYO - Japans Daiwa Asset Management Co Ltd, a unit of Daiwa Securities, set up a fund investing in gold mining shares earlier this month, to take advantage of investors growing interest in gold.  It is the first world gold investment fund set up by a Japanese company, a senior official of Daiwa Asset said. <BR><P>
TAJIKISTAN TO FREE PRECIOUS METALS EXPORTS<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
DUSHANBE - Tajikistan will liberalise exports of precious metals by allowing local and joint venture producers to sell for hard currency, according to a decree by President Imomali Rakhmonov published on Tuesday.<BR><P>
GOLD DISCOVERED IN NORTHERN SWEDEN <I>(Sake-Beeld)</I><BR>
The Terra mining group has discovered a deposit at Barsele in northern Sweden that could contain 12 tons of gold.<BR><P>
SA WILL GROW 4% THIS YEAR, SAYS SWISS BANK<I>(Sake-Beeld)</I><BR>
The South African government has followed "model policy trends" during the past two years to place the country on the road to economic success, the Union Bank of Switzerland says.<BR><P>
GOLD SPIKE LIFTS JSE SHARES <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Gold shares bounced off their lows to end only slightly weaker on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange yesterday as sentiment and activity improved in the afternoon following a brief spike in the gold price to $396 an ounce, dealers said.<BR><P>
</DOC>
