<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 19 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>



NUM TO PRESSURE GOVT ON MINERAL RIGHTS<I> (The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Among  resolutions adopted by the National Union of Mineworkers at its annual congress which ended yesterday were those to pressure the government to take control of the country's mineral rights to help achieve what it called "economic justice".  The NUM also said the government should have access to development plans to ensure that responsible mining took place, and that the state should give temporary assistance to marginal mines and intervene to determine whether mines said to be unprofitable were in fact economically viable.  The NUM added that it intended holding an international conference on alternatives to mine "down-scaling" and planned to make "down-scaling" as expensive as possible. The union also said it wanted to make "down-scaling" as expensive as possible, and would oppose industry efforts to reduce the number of public holidays in SA. <I>[This report follows NUM's annual congress and precedes the start of annual wage negotiations with the Chamber of Mines - Editor]</I><BR><P>
BRITAIN TO AID SA PRIVATISATION<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The British government has pledged its support for SAs privatisation programme, offering its experience, skills and the opportunity of raising foreign investment.<BR><P>
SURVEY FINDS US STILL MOST COMPETITIVE<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
LAUSANNE - World business leaders rate the US the most competitive nation, followed by Singapore and Japan according to a global survey released yesterday by the International Institute for Management Development.<I>[The report does not give a listing for SA, but it certainly did not make the top 10 -Editor]</I><BR><P>
SAMANCOR CUTS PRICES FOR JAPAN <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Ferroalloys producer Samancor had slashed export prices for ferro-silico manganese to Japan by $60 to $690 a ton as the European carbon steel market continued to ebb, manganese division GM Richard Linnell said yesterday.<BR><P>
<A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/statistics/g-output.htm#GOLDPRODFEB96">FEBRUARY GOLD OUTPUT</A> INCREASES<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
Gold output increased by 8,7% last month to 42 794 tons compared with 39 348 tons in January, the Chamber of Mines said yesterday.<BR><P>
JOHNNIC PRICE TAG COULD RISE TO R9BN<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
The bidder for Anglo Americans 48% stake in Johnnic would need to have financial backing of R9-billion, market analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
GOLD ENTERS NEW BULL MARKET<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
Gold is expected to offer a safe haven when the financial bubble bursts.  Has gold entered a new bull market or has it just experienced a rally on the coat-tail of the huge financial asset bubble that central bankers are inflating?<BR><P>
GOLD -INDIAN RUPEES RISE SEEN BOOSTING DEMAND <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BOMBAY - The Indian rupees rise against the US dollar is expected to boost gold imports into India, fuelled by the traditional wedding season demand that will peak by May, bullion dealers and analysts said on Monday.<BR><P>
ABARE SEES GOLD PRICE RISING BUT VOLATILE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
CANBERRA - The price of gold is forecast to average US$400 an ounce in 1996 despite a bull run in the first two months of the year when the price hit US$417, the Australian governments key commodity analyst said.<BR><P>
TURN IN PROSPECTING CASE <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The wrangling over the Madimbo corridor and what is going to happen to it took a turn yesterday afternoon when legal advice was sought over possible steps to stop diamond prospecting in the area.<BR><P>
MINE PROFITS DOWN<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The profits of companies in the mining industry in the fourth quarter of last year were 3,4% down on the previous quarter, the Central Statistical Services reports.<BR><P>
SHARE PRICE OF H J JOEL FALLS SHARPLY<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The shares of H J Joel fell sharply by about 10% to 280c yesterday morning after the closure of a rights issue on Friday, brokers said.  The shares closed at 285c, not far from their low point of 275c in July last year.<BR><P>
<A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/safebill.htm">MINE SAFETY BILL</A> DEBATE ON 9 MAY<I> (The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
The new Mine Health and Safety Bill will be debated and probably passed by Parliament on 9 May, National Assembly Mineral and Energy Affairs committee chairman Marcel Golding said yesterday.<BR><P>
ORYX OFFER PITCHED AT 60c A SHARE<I> (The Citizen)</I><BR>
Gencor's Oryx Gold Holdings' proposed R600-million rights offer will be in the ratio of 70 new shares for every 100 shares held at an issue price of 60c per Oryx share, after the consolidation of ordinary shares on a one-for-10 basis.
