<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 18 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>

SMALL MINERS WELCOME JCIS LIMITED RIGHTS SELL-OFF <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
JCIs decision to sell some of its mineral deposits has been resoundingly greeted by the small-scale mining sector with up to 80 companies clamouring for a piece of the groups innovative sell-off, executive director Nick Segal said at the weekend. <BR><P>
SARAFINA 2 A BLOODY DISASTER SAYS NUM <I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
The controversial R14-million Aids education play <I>Sarafina 2 </I>was harshly criticised as ineffective by Fleur Plimmer, the head of health and safety at the National Union of Mineworkers (NUM), at the unions annual congress on Friday.<BR><P>
WAGES AND HOUSING AMONG MINEWORKERS TOP DEMANDS<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
Wage hikes 2% above inflation, large increases in minimum wages, radical changes in worker housing and an end to racial discrimination are among the top bargaining demands for this year agreed to by the NUM at its annual central committee congress at the weekend.<BR><P>
UNION CONFRONTS AUTHORITIES OVER CRIME<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
The labour movement must challenge the government over its failure to fight crime adequately, James Motlatsi, NUM president, said on Friday.<BR><P>
DE BEERS TO SELL MINING RIGHTS<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
The De Beers group is to sell certain rights for the mining of diamonds and other minerals in South Africa, relating particularly to properties with documented alluvial diamonds.<BR><P>
<I>... but the Johannesburg morning daily, Sowetan reports...</I><BR><P>
DE BEERS SALE 'NOT MEANINGFUL' <BR>
The decision by De Beers to sell 53 of its holdings with rights to diamonds and other minerals would only be meaningful if it included cutting and polishing operations, NUM has said.<BR><P>
BUSINESS SPELLS OUT TAX INCENTIVE POLICY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Business has called for "limited use" of tax-based incentives to encourage investment.  The proposal is contained in the response document of business forum, Business South Africa (BSA) tothe  National Economic Development Labour Council (Nedlac) debate on supply-side economic measures.<BR><P>
COMPANY TO MINE IN SENSITIVE AREA<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
PIETERSBURG, NORTHEN PROV. - Madimbo Diamond Company intends to go ahead with a controversial alluvial diamond mining and prospecting project in the Madimbo corridor along SAs border with Zimbabwe from today.<BR><P>
SA PRODUCERS FACE A 10% CUT IN FERROCHROME PRICES<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
SA ferrochrome producers face a cut of up to 10% on prices to Japan for the second quarter, leaving prices nearly 25% down on their level at the end of last year.<BR><P>
VIETNAM APPROVES LONG-DELAYED MINING LAW <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
HANOI - Vietnam said on Saturday its National Assembly had given final approval to a new mining law which analysts have said could unleash a flood of foreign investment.<BR><P>
RoC INVESTORS TURN TO GOLD AS SAFE HAVEN <I>(The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Republic of China investors cleared banks of bullion bars during China's military exercises off the island last week and the effects rippled through the international market, traders and analysts say.<BR><P>
EXCHANGE CONTROL MUST GO, SAYS BRITISH PAPER <I>(Rapport, Sunday,)</I><BR>
There is a strong case to be made for going ahead with the lifting of the remaining exchange control regulations now, the Financial Times of London says in its comments on this week's South African Budget.<BR><P>
