<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 15 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>
MERRIESPRUIT DISASTER:  COURT IMPOSES FINES OF R151 000 <I>(Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
Fines totalling R151 000 were yesterday imposed on the former General Manager and two employees of the Harmony gold mine following the Merriespruit tragedy in which a slimes dam burst and flooded a suburb.  The magistrate said the scope of the disaster was hard to put into words, but it was gratifying that safety measures at slimes dams had improved and better channels of communication had been created.<BR><P>
MINORCO POWERS TO 51% PROFIT INCREASE<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Anglo Americans offshore arm, Minorco, lifted net earnings before exceptionals 51% to $365m for the year to December, powered by strong performances in its agribusiness and paper and packaging operations.<BR><P>
LABOUR AIMS AT BALANCE IN PLAN TO ACHIEVE GROWTH<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Labour will seek a balance between promoting social equity and job creation as opposed to big businesss "systematic attack on organised workers" to pursue growth.  This emerges in what could be a draft labour response to the SA Foundation Document, "Growth for all".<BR><P>
GENCORS INVESTMENT IN MOZAMBIQUE WORTH $500M <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Gencors mineral sands project in Mozambique would represent an investment of R500m, the mining house said yesterday.<BR><P>
GOLD FIELDS NEEDS R200M FOR DEELKRAAL<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold Fields of SA would need to tap shareholders for at least R200m to fund the development of its Deelkraal gold mine, analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
GENCOR HAS LOW BUDGET FOR THIS <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Although Gencor is engaged in exploration for gold and base metals and minerals in several areas outside South Africa, the R45-million budgeted for this in the current financial year is relatively low.  This is because many of the projects are still at an early stage, Mineral Sources CE John Raubenheimer said yesterday at a presentation of the group's exploration activities.<BR><P>
BRAZILS CVRD TO PRODUCE 19 TONNES OF GOLD IN 1996 <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
TOKYO,- Brazils mining giant Companhia Vale do Rio Doce (CVRD) will produce 19 tonnes of gold in calendar 1996, up from 17 tonnes in 1995 and 15 tonnes in 1994, the president of CVRD said in Tokyo on Friday.<BR><P>
TAIWAN BANKS STEPPING UP GOLD IMPORTS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
TAIPEI,- Taiwans Pan Asia Bank has imported 5.1 tonnes of gold since March 8, including the tonne of gold it expects to arrive on Friday, a bank executive said on Thursday.<BR><P>
HONG KONG GOLD UNAFFECTED BY TAIWAN BUYING <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
HONG KONG, - A surge in demand for gold in Taiwan as insurance against a possible military confrontation with China was having little or no impact on Hong Kongs bullion market, local dealers said on Friday.<BR><P>
RUSSIA 1996 PLACER PLATINUM OUTPUT SEEN UP 15% <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
MOSCOW - Independent Russian miners and firms are expected to boost production of placer platinum and platinum group metals by 15% in 1996, compared to the previous years levels, Interfax news agency said on Thursday.<BR><P>
ECONOMY AT TURNING POINT - STALS <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The economic upswing can reach its peak this year and level off next year, Reserve Bank Governor Chris Stals said before the Parliamentary Standing Committee on Finance yesterday in reply to a question about what the prospects for the current account of the balance of payments were.<BR><P>
'ANNOUNCEMENT OVER EXCHANGE CONTROL LATER' <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Reserve Bank Governor Chris Stals and Finance Minister Chris Liebenberg have not yet decided what the next step will be in the long process of phasing out exchange control, but such step will nevertheless be announced this year.<BR><P>
GOLD'S 1996 BREAKOUT FALSE START?<I> (The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
On the charts that track the ups and downs of the financial market, the jump in the gold price that caused such a stir early in 1996 is starting to look more like a molehill than a mountain.<BR><P>
ZCCM GETS NEW CHAIRMAN<I> (The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Former finance minister and IMF executive director Luke Mwanashiku has been appointed the new chairman of Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines.<BR><P>

