<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 14 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>

<B><A HREF="http://www.saica.co.za">THE 1996/97 BUDGET</A>:</B><BR><P>

TAX SHAKE-UP STEALS THE SHOW<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Finance Minister Chris Liebenberg set the stage yesterday for wide-ranging tax reform and a shake-up of the public sector, while reducing the deficit before borrowing to a notional 5,1% of GDP.<BR><P>
<A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/96budcom.htm">BUDGET POLITICALLY TIMID - MINES CHAMBER CHIEF</A><I> (The Citizen,Jhb)</I><BR>
The Budget was "politically timid, postponing the day of serious deficit and expenditure reduction," Chamber of Mines President Mr At du Plessis said.  Although the Chamber welcomed the reductions in STC and formula tax rates for gold mines, there would be no job creation and necessary growth unless there was significant tax relief.<BR><P>
SECONDARY TAX ON COMPANIES HALVED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
STC will be reduced to 12,5% from 25% for all dividends declared after March 13, while marketable securities tax (MST) and stamp duty on the sale of shares are to be cut from 1% to 0,5% from April 1.<BR><P>
FOREIGN AFFAIRS LOOKS AT PRIORITY ISSUES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Foreign Affairs was already looking at its priorities in terms of opening new missions and right-sizing existing embassies and consulates, Minister Alfred Nzo said in response to a Budget increase below the inflation rate.<BR><P>
FEW CRITICISMS FROM FOREIGN COMMENTATORS<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
LONDON - The Budget is positive for foreign investment say bankers and brokers, but they doubt that there will be large capital inflows in the coming months.<BR><P>
<B>OTHER MINING NEWS:</B><BR><P>
FOREIGN FLOWS INTO SA REMAIN SMALL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - SA was not living up to its promise as a destination for direct foreign investment, the World Bank noted in its latest annual review of external finance for developing countries: "Inflows remain small".<BR><P>
MALAYSIAN MODEL HOLDS LESSONS FOR SA LABOUR ARCHITECTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Pending "employment equity" legislation and a social agreement on affirmative action in SA again raise the questions of labour market flexibility and deregulation.  Malaysia has often been held up as a useful model for study on these subjects, and a new look at the Malaysian experience provides a timely contribution to the SA debate and resolutions.<BR><P>
GOLD MINING PROFIT IS TIED TO PRODUCTIVITY<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
Should productivity in SAs gold mines improve, profitability would surge dramatically, enhanced by a local gold price R100 higher than last years average.<BR><P>
AUSTRALIAN GOLD SEARCH NEEDS BOOST - NORMANDY <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
KALGOORLIE - Australias gold sector needs to boost exploration in order to maintain gold production at present levels, Normandy Mining Ltds group general manager exploration, Bruce Kay, said on Thursday.<BR><P>
AUSTRALIAN GOLD SECTOR SEEN FACING CHALLENGES<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
KALGOORLIE - High costs, a lack of marketing and an unwillingness to fund moves offshore could hamper Australias gold sector which otherwise had a bright future, Canada-based academic Peter Richardson said on Thursday.<BR><P>
AUSTRALIAN GOLD PRODUCERS REASSESSING HEDGING<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
KALGOORLIE - Some Australian gold producers were reassessing their hedging policies in the light of the recent market changes, Sons of Gwalia Ltd managing director Peter Lalor said on Wednesday.<BR><P>
SPECULATORS RETURN TO AUSTRALIAN GOLD-ANALYST<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
KALGOORLIE - Speculators are back in Australias gold sector, many with North American backing, and the trend is likely to continue for the rest of 1996, gold analyst Robin Widdup of broker JB Were & Son said.<BR><P>
US GOLD INDUSTRY NO LONGER PRIORITY-HOMESTAKE<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
KALGOORLIE - Gold production in the US was certain to decline if American miners continued to channel more exploration funds overseas, Homestake Mining Co said on Wednesday.<BR><P>
PACIFIC RIM SEEN AS HOT SPOT FOR GOLD<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
KALGOORLIE - The Pacific Rim is the worlds most promising new area in the immediate future for gold, the annual Australian Gold Conference was told on Wednesday.<BR><P>
DIZZY HEIGHTS FOR GOLD RECEDE INTO MEMORY<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Investors looking for gold prices to return to their dizzy heights of the early 1980s are conjuring up a world lost in the mists of time, according to a leading market observer.  Ever since stories about gold appeared briefly on the front pages of newspapers this year when the price rallied after years of slumber, fans of the metal looked back wistfully to 1980 when their favourite investment was worth more than $800 an ounce.<BR><P>
'REMOVE ST LUCIA FROM MONTREUX REGISTER'<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
South Africa is to request that the St Lucia wetlands be removed from the Ramsar treaty's Montreux register for endangered wetlands.<BR><P>
ANGLO AMERICAN ACQUIRES SHARE IN LONRHO <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Anglo American is to acquire 45,52-million shares in Lonrho, which is 5,9% of the issued capital.<BR><P>
