<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 13 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>

Finance Minister Chris Liebenbergs 1996/97 Budget speech will be available on the Internet at <A HREF="http://www.saica.co.za"><I>http://www.saica.co.za</I></A> or <A HREF="http://www.iafrica.com"><I>http://www.iafrica.com </I></A>
shortly after its delivery which begins at about 14h15 GMT +2 today.<BR><P>

 
<Center><B>1996/97 BUDGET PREVIEWS</B></Center><BR><P>
JOBS, TAX AND DEFICIT THE MAJOR ISSUES <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The South African Government is expected to announce a Budget today that attempts to tackle the problem of growth in joblessness while addressing the need to cut the deficit, expected to be about 5,2% of Gross Domestic Product.<BR><P>
BUDGET WILL REFLECT PUBLIC SERVICE CUTS<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Todays Budget is expected to reflect governments commitment to freeze and downsize the public service in line with its objective to reduce expenditure, in the wake of a broad commitment by public service unions to link wage increases to right-sizing.<BR><P>
BUDGET OUTLOOK <I> (Business Day - Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
It is too late for Finance Minister Chris Liebenberg to alter the Budget he is to present today, but he will be well aware that the structure that emerges will profoundly influence business confidence and fixed investment spending.<BR><P>
BUDGET EXPECTED TO SPUR SPENDING <I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
Todays Budget is expected to be investor-friendly and good for company profits, thereby underpinning or spurring gains in equity prices.  Some form of taxation on the retirement industry has been discounted by the bond market, economists said yesterday.<BR><P>
INVESTORS AWAIT TAX BREAKS TODAY<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
Changes to indicate investor-friendliness, such as cutting the secondary tax on companies (STC) and abolishing marketable securities tax, are the most that can be hoped for from todays Budget, insurance giant, Old Mutual's,  chief economist David Mohr warned yesterday.<BR><P>
<center><ALIGN=MIDDLE><IMG SRC="line3.gif" ></center><br><p>
MINE AUTHORITIES CALL FOR REVAMP OF SAFETY BILL<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Substantial sections of the new draft <A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/safebill.htm">Mine Health and Safety Bill were unconstitutional </A>and should be scrapped to avoid a Constitutional Court challenge, Gencor and the Chamber of Mines said yesterday.<BR><P>
NUM TO SEEK HELP ON RETRENCHMENTS<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers is to adopt a more vigorous approach to challenging job losses, including using independent consultants to test management claims on mines viability.<BR><P>
<I>... and the Johannesburg morning paper, The Star, reports ...</I><BR><P>
COSATU FACES SPLITS AND PARALYSIS, SAYS CONSULTANT'S REPORT<BR>
The 1.5-million-strong Congress of SA Trade Unions is in crisis and could become incapacitated if it did not resolve its internal problems, a labour consultant Steuart Pennington of SPA Consultants has warned in a report prepared for more than 250 company directors. The report also cautions that the union federation's long-standing alliance with the African National Congress and the SA Communist Party could end because of increasing differences between the ruling party and the federation over issues such as privatisation.<BR><P>
<I>... and the Afrikaans daily, Beeld, reports ...</I><BR><P>
FOREIGN TRADE UNIONS IN SA<BR>
Representatives of several foreign mining trade unions will attend the annual meeting of the central committee of NUM in Pretoria this weekend.<BR><P>
MERRIESPRUIT:  GOLD MINE ADMITS GUILT AFTER DISASTER <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The Harmony gold mine has unexpectedly acknowledged guilt on the charge of culpable homicide in the Merriespruit disaster.<BR><P>
<I>... and Business Day concludes this story ...</I><BR><P>
HARMONY FOUND GUILTY OF CULPABLE HOMICIDE<BR>
Harmony Gold Mine was found guilty in the Virginia Regional Court yesterday of culpable homicide relating to the 1994 Merriespruit slimes dam disaster, while three of its employees were found guilty of contravening the Minerals Act.<BR><P>
LONG-TERM INFLOWS SHIELD BOP<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
SAs capital account grew by  R21,7bn last year after swallowing R12,5bn worth of long-term capital, shielding the balance of payments (BoP) from a R12,7bn deficit on the current account, according to the Reserve Banks quarterly bulletin.<BR><P>
BOOM HAS ADDED ONLY 12 000 JOBS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
A sparse 12 000 jobs have been created since the economy started growing in May 1993 and the average individuals income is at a similar level to what it was 25 years ago, the Reserve Banks latest quarterly bulletin showed.<BR><P>
SA GOLD OUTLOOK NOT SO BLEAK, BANK SAYS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
KALGOORLIE - The outlook for SAs gold sector was not as depressing as some shareholders perceived with signs of a new bout of entrepreneurial spirit, according to Paul Harris, managing director of rand Merchant Bank.<BR><P>
AUSTRALIA GOLD MINING MOVES UNDERGROUND<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
KALGOORLIE - Australias gold industry was entering a new era with an increasing move underground, Western Australian premier Richard Court said on Wednesday.  Officially opening the annual Australian Gold Conference, Court said Australias gold production was rising, forecast to climb to 360 tonnes by 2000 from 274.2 tonnes in 1995/96, with a new focus in the industry.<BR><P>
CPM SEES GOLD PRICE RISING IN 96 BUT NO SURGE<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
KALGOORLIE - The price of gold was expected to rise this year to close 1996 at between $420 and $440 an ounce but no higher, said analyst Jeffrey Christian, managing director of the New York-based CPM Group.<BR><P>
ANALYSTS EXPECT RISE IN GOLD PRICE <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
It is reported from San Francisco that analysts expect the gold price to go beyond the $500 per ounce level in the next few years.<BR><P>
TAIWAN GOLD BUYING STRONG ON CHINA THREATS  <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Retail gold buying remained strong in Taiwan as the island braced itself for Chinas planned military exercises, dealers said on Tuesday.<BR><P>
SOUTH AFRICA HAS ALREADY ATTRACTED R31bn CAPITAL <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
From the middle of 1994 to the end of last year, South Africa had already succeeded in attracting a capital inflow of R31-billion from abroad, according to figures published by the Reserve Bank yesterday.<BR><P>
FOREIGNERS BUY <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Foreign investors bought South African stocks on a large scale on Monday when return rates rose sharply in response to the weakness of the American capital market.<BR><P>
DIAMOND GROUP RECONSIDERS MARKETING <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The Australian Ashton mining group yesterday announced a lower profit on the eve of an important decision on the marketing of its diamond production.  Shareholders of Argyle mine, a member of Ashton, have threatened to cease selling through the Central Selling Organisation.<BR><P>
