<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 12 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>


SACOB CALLS FOR SUBSTANTIAL CUT IN DEFICIT<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The SA Chamber of Business yesterday called for a substantial cut to the deficit as part of urgent measures in the Budget needed to create conditions for sustainable economic growth.<BR><P>
US EXPORTS TO SA SURGE TO R2,75BN<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - US exports to SA surged 27% last year to a record high of $2,75bn and the US trade surplus with SA rose to $540m, according to the US Commerce Department.<BR><P>
SLIMES DAM DISASTER ACCUSED IN COURT<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Four Harmony Gold Mine employees and an ex-employee appeared briefly in the Virginia Regional Court in the Free State yesterday in connection with the Merriespruit slimes dam disaster in 1994.<BR><P>
FIVE-YEAR TAX HOLIDAY TO BOOST FOREIGN INVESTMENT<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
South Africa needs to create incentives - including measures such as a five-year tax holiday and a 25% ceiling on corporate income tax - to attract more foreign investment into the country, says Taiwans Ambassador to SA, I-Cheng Loh.<BR><P>
NUM CALLS FOR ACTION AT DE BEERS<I> (Business Report. Jhb)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers has encouraged its local branches to take industrial action against De Beers mines this week in a dispute over holiday pay.<BR><P>
SALOMON ANALYST SEES GOLD AT $500 IN COMING YEARS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SAN FRANCISCO - Salomon Brothers analyst Leanne Baker said on Monday she believed the gold price would reach at least $500/ounce in the next few years .<BR><P>
TAIWAN RETAIL GOLD DEMAND UP ON CHINA THREATS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
TAIPEI - Retail demand for gold bars remained strong in Taiwan on Monday after a marked upturn on Thursday and Friday due to tension with China, gold dealers said.  "After Chinas announcement of missile tests gold demand was up by about 20-30%."<BR><P>
INDIAN SUB-CONTINENT DEMAND FOR GOLD TO RISE  <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BOMBAY - Demand for gold in the Indian sub-continent is likely to firm after last weeks dip in global prices, but much will also depend on the dollars movement against local currencies, dealers and analysts said on Monday.<BR><P>
GOLD IMPORTS SLIDE IN KEY MARKETS - ANALYST  <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Imports of bullion into the six largest import markets have been sliding since mid-1995 an in January fell by about 25% year-on-year, a London analyst said.<BR><P>
ASHTON SAYS DIRECT DIAMOND MARKETING VIABLE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
MELBOURNE - Direct marketing of diamonds from the Argyle mine in Western Australia was a viable alternative to sales through the CSO, Ashton Mining Ltd managing director John Robinson said.<BR><P>
DIAMOND PROSPECTING 'INDEED RESTRICTED'<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
The permit issued to Duo Corporation to prospect for alluvial diamonds in the Madimbo corridor contains a clause stating that the Department of Environmental Affairs and Tourism can indicate areas within the corridor where no prospecting may take place, according to Department of Mineral and Energy Affairs spokesman Jackie de Klerk.<BR><P>
SA SOLD R10m WORTH OF GEOLOGICAL DATA<I> (The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
South Africa sold R10-million worth of geological and borehole data to parties interested in its offshore oil and gas fields, Mineral and Energy Affairs Minister Pik Botha said yesterday.<BR><P>
ANALYSTS TIP GENCOR TO BID FOR LONRHO MINES <I>(The Citizen)</I><BR>
Buying the mining assets of Lonrho could make a lot of sense for Gencor by boosting its gold and exploration portfolio and strengthening its platinum interests, analysts say.<BR><P>
<I>... meanwhile Reuters reports ...</I><BR><P>
PREDATORS SEEN HOLDING FIRE ON LONRHO<BR>
LONDON - Lonrho became the subject of renewed bid speculation on Monday, but most analysts believe predators will hold their fire until Lonrho has split itself up.<BR><P>
