<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 8 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>

PALAMIN PROJECT MIGHT RECEIVE INTERNAL FUNDING <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Palabora Mining (Palamin) could get funding for its R1,5bn underground copper mining project from long-term borrowings and from retained earnings which could be partly written off as a tax benefit, analysts speculated yesterday.<BR><P>
<I>... meanwhile Johannesburg's Beeld newspaper reports ....</I><BR><P>
PALABORA TO BECOME A ROCK 'FACTORY'<BR>
The underground mine to be developed by the Palabora Copper Company at a cost of R1,5-billion will be a rock "factory", MD Frank Fenwick said in reference to the mechanised caving-in method of mining that will be employed there.<BR><P>
RACE ON FOR ANGLOS STAKE IN JOHNNIC<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
The National Empowerment Consortium headed by Wiseman Nkuhlu and Nthato Motlanas Corporate Africa have emerged as the contenders in what has become a two-horse race for Anglo Americans 48% stake in Johnnic.<BR><P>
<I>... and Beeld newspaper reports ....</I><BR><P>
JOHNNIC CORPORATION HAS FOUND ITS FEET QUICKLY<BR>
Johnnies Industrial Corporation has found its feet quickly after its formation early last year - in the six months to the end of December last year, earnings per share of 99c were achieved on its ordinary activities, which is 46% more than the pro forma figure for the corresponding period in 1994.<BR><P>
SPATE OF NEW MINES TO HIT COPPER PRICE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Plunging copper prices were on the cards for the next three years as a result of a spate of recently announced new mines, analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
ANGLOVAAL KEEPS PROFIT UP <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Anglovaal was hit by difficult trading conditions and low-priced imports in its core industrial operations, which dampened the interim earnings reported yesterday for the six months to December.<BR><P>
TRADE UNIONS INTEND TAKING ACTION AGAINST DE BEERS <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Trade union supervisors at all De Beers mines are meeting over the weekend to decide about industrial action against the group over the reduction of leave from 37 calendar days to 21 working days.<BR><P>
ROWLAND SELLS R346m STOCKS IN LONRHO<I> (The Citizen,Jhb)</I><BR>
Colourful former head of Lonrho, Tiny Rowland, finally severed ties yesterday with the international conglomerate he founded more than three decades ago by selling his 6% stake for around R346-million.<BR><P>
SUNTER SEES HIGHER GOLD <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
There will be an increased demand for gold at higher prices, Western Deep Levels, Elandsrand and Vaal Reefs chairman Clem Sunter predicted in his 1995 annual reviews.<BR><P>
CURRENCY CHAOS KNOCKS RESERVES<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The Reserve Banks gold and foreign exchange reserves shrank R733m to R14,72bn in February after massive intervention in the chaotic currency market, the scale of which the Bank disclosed last night.<BR><P>
STALS:  FALL IN RESERVES MISLEADING<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
The fall in Februarys gross gold and foreign reserves of almost 5% as the rand dived was misleading, Chris Stals, the governor of the Reserve Bank, said yesterday.<BR><P>

