<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 7 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>

REPORTED DISMISSAL OF 25 000 MINERS DENIED<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Claims that 25 000 gold miners would soon lose their jobs were false, Chamber of Mines CE Tom Main said yesterday, and he did not know where those figures came from.<BR><P>
MINE INSPECTORATE DECISION PENDING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Public Service Commission this week would take a decision on the formation of an independent inspectorate to monitor health and safety in the SA mining industry, commission director general Lucas Stoop told the parliamentary public accounts committee yesterday.<BR><P>
CABINET OUTLAWS MINING AT ST. LUCIA, BACKS ECOTOURISM <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA Cabinet decided yesterday no mining would be allowed on Lake St. Lucias eastern shores and urgent steps would be taken to declare the area a world heritage site.<BR><P>
GREEN LIGHT FOR PALAMINS R1,5BN MINE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Palabora Mining (Palamin) had given the green light to developing its R1,5bn underground mine after a five-year, R85m  feasibility investigation, MD Frank Fenwick said yesterday.<BR><P>
MOSSGAS WINS GO-AHEAD FOR SATELLITE FIELDS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Cabinet gave the go-ahead yesterday for Mossgas to invest a further R485m in satellite gas fields, which would make the beleaguered parastatal operate more profitably, enhancing its appeal for potential buyers.<BR><P>
NKOMATI NICKEL PROJECT TO PROCEED  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Joint venture partners Anglovaal and Anglo American Corporation would proceed with the development of the Nkomati nickel project to exploit the massive sulphide zone at an estimated capital cost of R140m, the companies announced yesterday.<BR><P>
R400M INVESTMENT TAG PUT ON GHANA GOLD CONCESSION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Gold Fields-backed Tarkwa gold concession in Ghana needed an estimated investment of about R400m to mine 300 000 tons of ore a month on a heap leach basis, new business executive director Richard Robinson said yesterday.<BR><P>
KEY CONFIDENCE INDEX SLIPS TO FIVE-MONTH LOW<I> (Business Report,Jhb)</I><BR>
South African business confidence fell to a five-month low in February because of the rands recent weakness and concern ahead of next weeks Budget, SA Chamber of Business (Sacob) said yesterday.<BR><P>
LYDENBURG MAY UNBUNDLE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Lydenburg Platinum, one of the worlds key producers, said yesterday that it was considering unbundling by distributing shares in the companys investments to existing shareholders.<BR><P>
RTZ-CRA SEES GRADUAL DEMAND EXPANSION IN 1996 <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Recently merged Anglo-Australian mining giant RTZ Corp Plc-CRA Ltd said 1996 had opened on an uncertain note, but that it expects demand for metals and minerals to expand gradually as the year develops.<BR><P>
VIETNAM TACKLES MINING LAW AMID GOLD FEVER CHAOS<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
HANOI- Vietnam began work on a new mining law this week, focusing initially on reports of a rag-tag army of prospectors, including children, working in very poor conditions at illegal gold mines in the north.  The law, due to be passed by the National Assembly during its spring session, is expected to enshrine foreign investors rights to exploit deposits such as coal, ore and gemstones.<BR><P>
TAIWAN FEB. GOLD IMPORTS DOWN ON 1995<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Taiwans imports of gold bars, coins and plate fell in February to 8.055 tonnes from 12.028 tonnes in February 1995, the Finance Ministry said in a statement on Thursday.<BR><P>
FOREIGNERS STILL BUYING<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
Foreign investors were net buyers of South African securities on the JSE last week again, with purchases amounting to R192,63-million.<BR><P>
NEW DIRECTOR FOR AMALIA<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
The new mining group Amalia has appointed former JCI executive director Mr Mike Hawarden as a director.<BR><P>
FINE ACHIEVEMENT FOR KLOOF<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
The Leeudoorn A section of the Kloof mine completed its 1 000 000th fatality-free shift on 4 March.<BR><P>
DE BEERS EYES OTHER PRODUCERS<I> (The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Fresh from a new marketing agreement with Russia, diamond giant De Beers will next look to deals with Australia, Canada and Angola, analysts say.<BR><P>
