<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 6 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>



DIAMOND DEMAND BOOSTS DE BEERS<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Higher diamond sales, a growing contribution from South Africas Venetia mine and a resumed dividend from Namibian mining operation Namdeb combined to lift De Beers turnover and attributable earnings in financial 1995, the diamond group reported.<BR><P>
BIG DEFICIT AFTER SURGE IN IMPORTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SAs trade balance hit an unexpectedly huge R942m deficit in January from a R258m surplus in December last year after a 19% surge in imports and a minimal rise in exports.<BR><P>
LABOUR-INTENSIVE GROWTH PATH URGED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A country concerned with poverty and welfare should promote a labour-intensive growth path to achieve a sustained and significant drop in unemployment, a report in the latest edition of the SA Labour Bulletin says.<BR><P>
DEELKRAAL MINERS BUILD SHACKS TO CHANGE HOUSING POLICY<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
The desire to escape hostel life and to live with wives or girlfriends in their own homes led mine workers to a struggle with management at Gold Fields Deelkraal mine this week.<BR><P>
GENCOR COULD INVEST R1BN IN MOZAMBIQUE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gencor could invest R1bn in a heavy minerals sand project on the northern Mozambican coast if explorations proved viable, sources said yesterday.<BR><P>
WEAKER RAND BRINGS TEMPORARY RELIEF FOR GOLD MINES<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
South African gold mines should be able to announce significantly better results in the first quarter of this year than for the previous quarter despite the gold price having fallen back in the past few days.  Analysts say the weaker rand should be more than adequate compensation for the fall in the gold price.<BR><P>
CURRENT GOLD SELL-OFF "A MINOR CORRECTION" <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - The current gold sell-off was"a minor correction" of a technical nature and not a matter for concern, a market analyst said on Tuesday.  "A 50% retracement should be expected in any reasonable rally", Michael Simon, a director of New York-based consultants CPM Group said.<BR><P>
ASIAN BUYERS SEEN RESCUING GOLD AFTER FUNDS SELL<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Asian buyers fascination with gold should limit further losses for the precious metal after a New Year price rally evaporated in a wave of fund selling in New York, analysts and traders across the region said on Tuesday.<BR><P>
CHINA TO BOOST GOLD PRODUCTION<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BEIJING - Chinas State Council has approved policies to boost gold production in the 1996-2000 period, the official China Gold newspaper said on Tuesday.<BR><P>
CANADA SELLS 18 000 OUNCES OF GOLD IN FEBRUARY<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Canada sold 18 000 ounces of gold in February, bringing reserves down to 33,3m ounces, the Finance Department said on Tuesday.<BR><P>
TRADE DEFICIT IS BAD NEWS FOR THE ECONOMY <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The South African economy received bad news yesterday when it was announced that the country's trade account had a deficit of R942-million in January.<BR><P>
BANK 'NOT READY TO LIFT EXCHANGE CONTROLS'<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Reserve Bank governor Chris Stals says the central bank is not yet ready to recommend to the Government that the remaining exchange control measures should be lifted.<BR><P>
CHINA HAS 400t IN GOLD RESERVES<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
China has announced it has estimated gold reserves of 400 tons - the first time it has made the extent of its reserves known.<BR><P>
RUSSIA WILL NOT SELL GOLD<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Russia has sufficient money to finance its federal budget and it will no longer have to sell any of its gold or diamond reserves, says First Finance Deputy Minister Vladimir Petrov.<BR><P>
DE BEERS NEGOTIATING AGAIN<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The De Beers group says it has begun negotiations with the Argyle mine in Australia over a new contract for the marketing of the mine's diamonds.<BR><P>
LYDENBURG ISSUES WARNING<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Lydenburg Platinum has warned its shareholders that its board is considering the possibility of unbundling the company.<BR><P>
10 000 MINE JOBS MAY GO<I> (Sowetan, Jhb)</I><BR>
The Anglo American Corporation yesterday said it was doing all it could to save 10 000 jobs in three marginal gold shafts that are due to close at the end of the month.  AAC spokesman James Duncan said one of the shafts had run out of ore and was doomed to close, while the lives of the other two could be prolonged, although their ultimate closure was inevitable.<BR><P>

