<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 5 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>


SA ON BRINK OF DIPLOMATIC ROW WITH US<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - SA is on the brink of a major diplomatic fracas with the US that could include the suspension of the US-SA Binational Commission chaired by SA Deputy President Thabo Mbeki and US Vice-President Al Gore, and other high-level exchanges, ambassador Franklin Sonn said yesterday. The crisis follows the Clinton administrations refusal to drop the 1991 indictment of Armscor for massive and prolonged violations of the US Arms Export Control under the previous government.<BR><P>
BID TO END DEADLOCK OVER SAFETY ON MINES<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Parliaments mineral and energy affairs committee next week will attempt to break a deadlock between mine owners and unions on a proposal that mine managements be required to prove they were not responsible in the event of an accident.<BR><P>
MINING HARMS GAME RESERVE'S FISH<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
Researchers feel that drastic measures will have to be taken to reduce the effects of mining activities on the Selati and Lower Olifants Rivers, which flow through the Kruger National Park, as dangerous concentrations of copper in particular have been traced in them.<BR><P>
GRASS PLANTED, BUT SLIMES DAM DUST STILL A NUISANCE <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Minister of Mineral and Energy Affairs Pik Botha yesterday started the planting of grass on a slimes dam on the West Rand in order to prevent the fine white dust blowing about, but local residents are still unhappy about the 30m high slimes dam on their doorsteps.<BR><P>
VISITING EXPERTS CAUTION UNIONS ON PRIVATISATION<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
International experts yesterday warned the Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu), National Council of Trade Unions (Nactu) and Federation of SA Labour (Fedsal) that the real beneficiaries of privatisation, apart from international consultants, were multinational companies contracted to provide services.<BR><P>
PLAN TO LINK TRADE WITH LABOUR STANDARDS<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Government negotiators at the National Economic Development and Labour Advisory Council (Nedlac) are to give a formal undertaking to their counterparts this week to link trade with labour standards.<BR><P>
MINING NOT FOR WOMEN<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
National Party and African National Congress members agreed on one thing yesterday - women should not be allowed to work at the "coal face" in SA mines.<BR><P>
INVESTMENTS, SALES EXPECTED TO LIFT DE BEERS EARNINGS <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Diamond producer De Beers was expected to lift earnings a share almost 20% for the year to December as maiden income from the groups joint Namibian operation Namdeb kicked in, analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
EU TRADE PACT WILL EVOLVE<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The trade liberalisation agreement between SA and the EU would evolve over 10 years once finalised, but the EU had already begun reducing its protection against SA imports, British consul Debbie Goldthorpe said recently.<BR><P>
MANUEL MOOTS CANADIAN INVESTMENT<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Trade and Industry Minister Trevor Manuel last night called on SA and Canadian firms to follow their governments examples by tapping each others vast markets.<BR><P>
BOTSWANA PINS HOPE ON DIAMOND DEAL<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
GABORONE - Botswana hopes its diamond industry will benefit from the signing of last months understanding between De Beers and Russian producers.<BR><P>
GOLD FALLS TO 2-MTH LOW AS INVESTORS LOSE FAITH <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
NEW YORK - Gold prices fell Monday morning to their lowest levels in two months as a new years rally that one month ago took prices to six-year highs faded from view and disappointed investors unloaded long positions.<BR><P>
AUSTRALIAN ELECTION - WHAT IS MEANS FOR MINING<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Australias resource sector was cautiously positive on Monday about the nations change of government, expecting less industrial strife, action to ease land access problems and reviews of proposed tariff changes.<BR><P>
TAIWAN GOLD DEMAND SEEN RISING ON CHINA EXERCISE<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
TAIPEI - Taiwans gold demand is expected to increase further after China announced on Tuesday it will conduct ground-to-ground missile tests at sea just off Taiwan between March 8 and 15, dealers said on Tuesday.<BR><P>
CHINA GOLD RESERVES ESTIMATED AT 400 TONNES<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BEIJING - China revealed its gold reserves for the fist time, estimating their size at 400 tonnes, the Xinhua news agency said on Tuesday.  China will continue to give preferential treatment to its gold industry in the 1996-2000 Ninth Five-Year Plan to boost production, Xinhua quoted an official in charge of gold production as saying.<BR><P>
INVESTORS FLOCK TO CANADAS SMALL MINING STOCKS<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
VANCOUVER - Investors are pouring money into fledgling Canadian mineral exploration companies at a torrid pace, hoping for a repetition of the successes of Diamond Fields Resources Inc and Bre-X Minerals Ltd.<BR><P>
RUSSIAN DIAMOND GIANT SETS OUT TO MATCH DE BEERS<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
MOSCOW - Russias biggest diamond producer and the official exporter of rough stones, Almazy Rossii-Sakha, announced on Monday its plans to become a transnational corporation, similar to SA diamond group De Beers.<BR><P>
RUSSIAN DIAMOND CUTTERS STILL NOT SATISFIED<I> (Beeld)</I><BR>
Russian diamond cutters are still dissatisfied over the proposed agreement between the CSO of De Beers and Russia's largest diamond producer Almanzy Rossii-Sakha.<BR><P>
LITTLE RESPONSE TO STEPS AGAINST MANDELA RUMOURS<I> (Beeld)</I><BR>
President Nelson Mandela intervened yesterday to try to end the negative effect that continuing rumours about hisailing health are having on the financial markets, but this did not have the expected positive results.<BR><P>
COPPER PRICE FALLS 11,25% <I> (Beeld)</I><BR>
The local supplier's price of copper bars is R10 796,12 per ton for this month, which is 11,25% lower than in February.<BR><P>
BOTSWANA IN TRANSITION FROM DIAMOND ECONOMY<I> (The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Botswana is classified as an "upper middle income" country by the World Bank, thanks to its diamonds, however in last month's budget speech Finance Minister Festus Mogae said growth in the mineral sector had fallen in recent years.<BR><P>

