<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 9, 4 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>

ANC DRAWS UP NEW LABOUR RELATIONS CLAUSE (Business Day Pg.1)
The ANC had come up with a new labour relations clause in a bid to break the impasse over whether the new constitution should include a lockout clause, sources said yesterday.

ANGLO SEEKS BIGGER STAKE IN LONRHO (BD Pg.1)
Anglo American is seeking to secure an option on the 18,5% stake in Lonrho owned by Lonrho CE Dieter Bock.

GOVT FACES THREAT OF GEIS LAWSUITS (BD Pg.1)
The government could face a barrage of lawsuits from business over its plans to phase out its general exports incentive scheme (GEIS) much faster than previously agreed to.

BANK FORCED TO REVERSE ITS HEDGING POLICY (BD Pg.1)
Turmoil in the currency markets has dealt a blow to the Reserve Banks plans for freer forex markets, forcing it to intervene heavily in the forward cover market and to hold off on easing exchange controls.

FRAUD INVESTIGATION SHIFTS OFFSHORE (BD Pg.1)
Government legal experts are to move offshore in their investigation into hundreds of millions of rands in export incentive fraud by certain motor components manufacturers.

ACTION GROUP WANTS AUCTION OF TELKOM (BD Pg.1)
An independent consumer organisation has slammed the telecommunications white paper for its wishful thinking, and has suggested an immediate, conditional auction of Telkom instead of a five-year gradual deregulation of the industry.

DIAMOND MARKETING TALKS STILL UNDER WAY (BD Pg.4)
Talks between De Beers and the Russian federation about a new diamond marketing agreement are taking longer than expected.

ESTIMATED JOBLESS RATE MAY BE TOO LOW (BD Pg.4)
South Africas unemployment rate is nearly four times the average for developing industrial countries, yet nearly three quarters of jobless Africans are not looking for work, reports the South African Institute of Race Relations' survey Fast Facts.

MAJORITY TREND (BD Pg.6)[Editorial Comment]
The Gauteng cabinet reshuffle may have attracted less attention than the national one a week earlier.  But it does illustrate a trend which is becoming ever more apparent - the taking over, at all levels, of the most strategic ministerial and executive positions by the ANC.

MINIMUM WAGE NO REMEDY FOR THE JOBLESS (BD Pg.6)
Contrary to economists' revisionist claims, minimum wage legislation is, in fact, a foolish way to help low-income workers.  If the price of a commodity goes up, less of it will be demanded.

PRIVATE SECTOR MUST HAVE ROLE IN ECONOMIC GROWTH (BD Pg.7)
WASHINGTON - Pat Buchanan may have faded from the political scene in the run-up to Novembers US presidential election, but his relatively successful campaign for the Republican Party nomination was fuelled by an anger over the falling living standards of many Americans which is unlikely to subside.

ISCOR TIES UP $112M-A-YEAR CONTRACT FOR NICKEL SUPPLY (BD Pg.11)
Iscor has tied up a long-term contract with an international trader to supply its Pretoria stainless steel plant with nickel worth about $112m a year.

RISE IN STEEL PRICE NOT JUSTIFIED (BD Pg.11)
Columbus Stainless was not convinced that a rise in stainless steel prices was justified, despite reported moves by European mills to force a 5% hike on the market, the company said last week.

RUSSIAN THREAT EXPECTED TO CAP PLATINUM PRICE (BD Pg.11
The platinum price was likely to spend most of the next four years languishing between $410/oz and $414/oz, hemmed in by the threat of Russian supplies, analysts said at the weekend.

WORK TO BEGIN ON ALUMINIUM PLANT (BD Pg.11)
Site work on Tongaat-Huletts R2,5-billion aluminium rolling mill expansion in Maritzburg would begin in three months, the company said last week.

GOVERNMENT TO OFFER GENEROUS SEVERANCE DEAL (Business Report Pg.18)
The government and employee organisations have agreed on a generous voluntary severance package, to be offered to public servants in the next two weeks, in the hope of cutting the public service by at least 80 000 before the end of October. 

RAND LIKELY TO REMAIN UNDER PRESSURE (BR Pg.18)
Although consolidation in currency markets was likely over the next week, the rand would remain at a minimum of R4,00 to the dollar, analysts said on Thursday.

FMF SLATES COSTLY HEALTH CARE PLAN (B TIMES Pg.3)
If you think health care is expensive now, wait until it is free:  the actual cost of providing free primary health care to all could top R15-billion by 2000 - double the current estimate.

M3 MANIPULATION DISRUPTS MARKETS, SAYS ECONOMIST (B TIMES Pg.5)
Inflation is in danger of returning to double digits by 1997 unless the Reserve Bank does something quick to arrest M3 money supply growth, says Richard Grant, Chamber of Mines chief economist.

DUBAI TRADE HOPES GOLD PRICE WILL STAY BELOW $400 (Reuters 07.04.96)
DUBAI - Gold prices will have to stay under the psychologically important $400 an ounce mark to ensure robust local and re-export demand for Dubai gold in April, souk retailers and wholesalers in the Gulf emirate said on Sunday. 

INDIAN SUB-CONTINENT GOLD SUPPLIES SEEN IMPROVING (Reuters 08.04.96)
BOMBAY - A reduction in entry tax on gold brought into Bombay and a Pakistani move to boost jewellery exports could improve gold supply in the Indian sub-continent, bullion dealers said on Monday.

TAIWAN MARCH GOLD IMPORTS UP AFTER CHINA TENSIONS (Reuters 08.04.96)
TAIPEI - Taiwans imports of gold bars, coins and plate rose sharply in March to 25,238 tonnes from 9,618 tonnes in March 1995, the Finance Ministry said in a statement on Monday.

MANILA TO CHARGE BOSSES OVER MINE-WASTE SPILLAGE  (Reuters, 08.04.96)
MANILA - Philippine officials said on Monday they were filing criminal charges against executives of Marcopper and threatened to blacklist the partly Canadian-owned mine firm after its waste swamped a 25 km long river. 

SENATE MAY BE SCRAPPED THIS YEAR (Beeld, p1)
The Senate will apparently be scrapped this year and be replaced by a Council of Provinces as the second chamber of Parliament if constitutional negotiators have their way.

ECONOMISTS MORE OPTIMISTIC OVER RAND (Sake-Beeld, pS1)
Economists still expect that South Africa will not achieve a growth rate of 4% this year, according to the monthly survey in which 21 economists make predictions on eight economic variables.

DIRECTORS DON'T EARN AS MUCH AS TRADE UNIONS CLAIM (Sake-Beeld, pS1)
Executive directors earn less than half of what the labour sector claims they do in its controversial document Social Equality and Job Creation.

TRANS-HEX TO CLOSE DIAMOND MINE (Sake-Beeld, pS2)
Trans-Hex, the listed diamond group in the Rembrandt stable, is going to close its loss-making diamond mine in Swaziland.

VOGELS CAN EARN THE SAME (Sake-Beeld, pS2)
The prospects for metal prices this year and expected weakening in the exchange rate of the rand against the dollar should ensure that the investment income of Vogelstruisbult Metal Holdings shows little change this year, Mr John Hopwood says in this chairman's review.

IN SA FOUR O'CLOCK IS TIME TO START PACKING UP (Sake-Beeld, pS3)
Visiting foreign businessmen are constantly astonished at the lack of work etiquette in South Africa.  They find it strange that South Africans want to go home at half past four already, take long annual holidays and wouldn't dream of coming to work on a public holiday.

DE BEERS VENTURES BACK INTO ANGOLA (Citizen, p5)
Diamond giant De Beers is venturing back into Angola, hoping this time war won't interfere with business.  De Beers officials have announced the signing of a prospecting deal in north-eastern Angola.

BIG ORDERS LINKED TO RAND SLUMP (Citizen, p21)
Two big corporate orders for dollars contributed to the rand's collapse last week, analysts say.  The first order was linked to Iscor and involved the steel producer buying capital equipment for expansion, and the second to Anglo American's acquisition of a stake in Lonrho.

JO'BURG CBD FACELIFT IN THE PIPELINE (Sowetan, p4)
Efforts to give the Johannesburg CBD a facelift are finally in the pipeline after the establishment of the Johannesburg Inner City Development Forum.

A SUCCESS PLAN FOR THE SA ECONOMY (Finansies & Tegniek, 5/4/96, p18)
The South African economy is growing too slowly to make any real difference to the poor and the unemployed.  Now there is a set of practical proposals from the business world for substantial faster growth.

DO WORKPLACE FORUMS HAVE A FUTURE? (Finansies & Tegniek, 5/4/96, p34)
Despite the prominence given to workplace forums in the new Labour Relations Act, there are now serious questions about whether the system will work because Cosatu is showing less and less enthusiasm for it.

ED HERN BACK WITH BLACK BROKERS (Sake-Rapport, 7/4/96, p1)
One of the country's best known sharebrokers, Ed Hern, is returning to the JSE at the beginning of May as an executive director of the first directly controlled black brokers' firm in South Africa.




Input from ECONOMIC SERVICES, PUBLIC POLICY UNIT & COMMUNICATION SERVICES. Edited by LLEWELLYN KRIEL. 




%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
BANKS WAIT FOR CHANCE TO SPREAD OFFSHORE<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Financial institutions which own huge chunks of SAs assets would seek to draw between 10% and 50% of their business from offshore once exchange controls were lifted, the groups said at the weekend.<BR><P>
WAITING FOR THE CASUALTY LISTS OF RANDS MELTDOWN<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The Reserve Banks gold and foreign exchange reserves for last month should be the first of many economic indicators scarred by the rands recent meltdown.<BR><P>
MINORCO SELLS ITS STOCK IN NORMANDY AND POSGOLD<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Minorco has sold its stakes in Australian mining companies Normandy and Posgold for $250m, after deciding Normandys merger plans had effectively killed the companies long-running strategic partnership.<BR><P>
ANGLOS RESHUFFLE COULD BE START OF A NEW ERA<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
Will the traditional South African mining house survive in the long term?  The answer last week was no, according to some mining industry analysts who expressed the hope that the management reorganisation announced by Anglo American and Gencor marked a further shift away from traditional management practice and structure.<BR><P>
JOINT INDUSTRIAL MINERALS PROCESSING FACILITY SET UP <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The conclusion of an equal joint venture between Rhino Andalusite Mines and the Eggerding Group of Amsterdam has resulted in a new industrial minerals processing facility being established in Richards Bay.<BR><P>
WMC MULLS ZAMBIA COPPER MINE STAKE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SYDNEY - Australian mining group WMC Ltd said it was considering buying into Zambias Konkola Deep copper project, joining a consortium led by Anglo American Corp of South Africa Ltd.<BR><P>
GRASS IS SOLUTION TO MINE DUMP DUST<I> (The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Soweto's Meadowlands community will today be presented with an environmentally friendly solution to the problem of their homes being invaded by dust from nearby mine dumps, Mineral and Energy Affairs Minister Pik Botha said yesterday announcing plans to grass the dumps.<BR><P>
IMPLICATIONS OF DE BEERS DEAL<I> (Finansies & Tegniek, 1/3/96, Jhb)</I><BR>
The grip that the latest agreement with Russia gives De Beers over the world diamond market probably places it in one of the strongest positions in its existence.<BR><P>
PAY PROPOSALS CAN BE SERIOUS FOR MINING INDUSTRY<I> (Finansies & Tegniek, 1/3/96,Jhb)</I><BR>
The mining industry, in particular, could be seriously affected if the Government's new proposals for overtime pay are taken up in legislation.<BR><P>
