<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 1 MARCH 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>


<I>The Johannesburg morning newspaper, Business Days weekly "INSIDER TRADING" column reports:</I><BR>
It seems the ailments afflicting the mining industry have caught up with its central lobbying body, the Chamber of Mines.<BR>
	Reports earlier this week suggested Anglo American gold division CE Bobby Godsell had proposed that the chamber be shut down. Godsell dismisses such talk, adding that the issue was not raised at the chamber executive committee meeting he attended on Wednesday.<BR>
	However, the axe is being swung within the quiet cloisters of Hollard Street - out of a staff of less than 200 about 30 have left in recent weeks.<BR>
	The job losses are part of a larger downsizing plan, CE Tom Main tells us."The chamber will continue to adapt its organisational structure. This is the only way the chamber will be able to satisfy its members requirements in a dynamically changing national environment."<BR><P>
REVIEW BODY WILL OVERHAUL SA GOVT<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
President Mandela appointed a 16-member presidential review commission yesterday to oversee an overhaul of government at national and provincial level.<BR><P>
GODSELL APPOINTED TO TOP ANGLO POST<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American announced a top-level management shake-up last night, appointing Bobby Godsell gold and uranium division chairman in place of Clem Sunter, who is to head its corporate affairs division from today. Anglo American Industrial Corporation chairman Leslie Boyd would become chairman of Anglo American Platinum Corporation, succeeding Pat Retief, who is retiring. Tony Redman, currently consulting engineer for the export side of collieries, was appointed MD of Amcoal to succeed retiring Ken Trueman. De Beers industrial diamond division MD James Campbell is also to become deputy chairman.<BR><P>
BUSINESS LAYS OUT STRATEGY FOR GROWTH<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Business sent a strong signal to government yesterday that dramatic economic reforms were needed to push economic growth above 5% - the pace required to cut unemployment.<BR><P>
RAND WEAKENS ON FLURRY OF NEW RUMOURS<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The rand weakened sharply yesterday as a flurry of new rumours dogged the currency in skittish trade.  New reports that President Mandela was ill and that UK investment House Goldman Sachs had issued a report saying the rand was 25% over-valued were both swiftly denied.<BR><P>
FRANCE, SA SIGN PACT ON URANIUM<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
SA and France would collaborate on developing uranium enrichment technology in a pact which could add about R200m a year to SAs uranium exports, Minerals and Energy Affairs Minister Pik Botha said yesterday.<BR><P>
EU TALKS ON SA TRADE CALLED OFF<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Discussion by the EU on a mandate to negotiate a free trade accord with SA were called off yesterday until next week because France was not ready, European Commission sources said.<BR><P>
PRIVATISATION WILL HELP GOVT DODGE LOOMING DEBT TRAP<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA Foundation is puzzled over why privatisation has been rejected so widely in SA.  In its growth-for-all strategy, it said it was nonplussed at the trade union movements opposition to privatisation. <BR><P> 
GOLD FIELDS GAMSBERG ZINC MINE PROJECT ON HOLD<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold Fields proposed R1,9bn Gamsberg zinc mine project was on hold because its orebody was too marginal at current prices, the group said yesterday.<BR><P>
MINES STOIC ON RUSSIAN THREAT<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
SAs mining industry was unfazed yesterday by reports that Russia could flood international markets with precious metals in a bid to cover a shortfall in its revenue.<BR><P>
BRAZILS VALE LIKELY TO BE SOLD IN Q1 1997 <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SAO PAULO - Brazils mining giant Vale do Rio Doce is likely to be privatised only in the first quarter of 1997, O Globo newspaper reported. <BR><P>
STANDARD BANK PEGS 96 PLATINUM RANGE AT $390-440  <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Standard Bank London Ltd, subsidiary of Standard Bank Investment Corp Ltd, estimated in its sixth annual Platinum Yearbook the core range for platinum prices in 1996 would be $390 to $440 an ounce.<BR><P>
LARGE RUSSIAN DIAMOND EXPORTS<I> (Sake-Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
The Russian export of uncut diamonds last year was 43,54-million carats with a value 
$2,979-billion.<BR><P>
WORKER KILLED AT IMPLATS <I>(Sake-Beeld)</I><BR>
A worker has been killed at the Impala Platinum refinery after an explosion occurred in a sulphur dioxide tank.<BR><P>
INMINS EYEING MINING INDUSTRY CLOSELY <I>(Sake-Beeld)</I><BR>
Inmins, which is largely dependent on purchases in the gold mining industry for its turnover, is keeping a close watch on the position of the gold mines, according to W A R Wenteler in his chairman's report for the financial year to the end of September last year.<BR><P>
AFFIRMATIVE ACTION WILL ONLY WORK IF ... <I>(Sake-Beeld)</I><BR>
Affirmative action will only work in South Africa if the economy grows more swiftly, nothing is done too hastily and there is political stability in the country, according to Anglo American economist Ian Emsley.<BR><P>
LAST 31 MINERS RESCUED AT EAST DRIEFORNTEIN<I> (The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
The last 31 of 104 employees awaiting rescue at the East Driefontein gold mine have been brought to the surface after an underground fire broke out on Wednesday morning.<BR><P>
ANALYSTS UPBEAT ON DE BEERS RESULTS<I> (The Citizen)</I><BR>
De Beers would turn in a resilient 20% increase in earnings when it reports results for the year to 31 December, on Tuesday, analysts say.<BR><P>
HIGHER COPPER BOOST PALAMIN <I> (The Citizen)</I><BR>
Palabora Mining says it is in the final stage of evaluating the 30 000 ton-a-day underground project, and to date the results were more promising than those for the large scale operation abandoned in 1994.<BR><P>


