<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 30 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </b></h1></b></center></center>
<BR><P>




<Center><B>TOMORROW, 1 MAY, IS A PUBLIC HOLIDAY IN SOUTH AFRICA - WORKERS' DAY. THIS SITE WILL BE UPDATED AGAIN ON THURSDAY - ED.</B></Center><P><P>


<B><I>THE CONGRESS OF S.A. TRADE UNIONS (COSATU), THE COUNTRY'S LARGEST UNION FEDERATION, HAS CALLED A ONE-DAY<A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/releases/nostrike.htm"> NATIONAL STRIKE</A> TO PROTEST THE RIGHT OF EMPLOYERS TO LOCKOUT STRIKERS (A BALANCE TO THE RIGHT TO STRIKE) BEING ENTRENCHED IN THE NEW CONSTITUTION. NEWS REPORTS ...</I></B><BR><P>
COSATU GEARED FOR NATION-WIDE PROTEST <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Cosatu members country-wide take to the streets today in support of labour's demand for the exclusion of the lockout clause from the final constitution - amid uncertainty regarding the outcome of NP-ANC negotiations.<I>[See also <A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/releases/worksame.htm">media release from the Chamber of Mines]</A></I><BR><P>
ANC, COSATU AT ODDS OVER WORKER LOCK-OUT RIGHT<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
Cosatu and the African National Congress were at odds yesterday over employers' constitutional right to lock out striking workers, following a draft agreement between the ANC and the NP recognising employers' internationally accepted rights.  Cosatu general-secretary Sam Shilowa said yesterday they would accept no compromise or reformulation of the lock-out right, it had to scrapped from the constitution.<BR><P>
IS COSATU OR THE ANC GOVERNING SA, FW ASKS <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The question should be asked whether Cosatu or the ANC is governing South Africa, because the ANC still listens to everything Cosatu says, deputy president F W de Klerk said yesterday.  He added that the NP had done nothing to contribute to the fall of the rand, but its weak performance was brought about by mistakes on the part of the ANC and its allies.<BR><P>
MORE STRIKES POSSIBLE - COSATU BOSS<I> (Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
Brushing aside Democratic Party claims that todays strike is illegal, the Congress of South African Trade Unions vowed to continue with its plans to protest against a proposed lockout clause in the new constitution. Todays planned action was endorsed yesterday by ANC MP Mr Cameron Dugmore and SA Communist Party member Mr Phillip Dexter, an ANC MP.<BR><P>
THE STRIKE <I>(Editorial Comment, The Citizen,Jhb)</I><BR>
Cosatu is going ahead with its nation-wide strike today, which will cost the country millions in manhours lost.  With tomorrow's public holiday, the effect on productivity will be doubly bad. Even if the strike is the exercise of workers' rights, we cannot accept the fact that it is being held to blackmail the Constitutional Assembly to meet Cosatu's wishes.<BR><P>
WITH NO APOLOGIES<BR>  
by Zwelinzima Vavi, Cosatu's assistant general-secretary <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
"While millions of people support today's Cosatu-led stay-away, others have voiced outrage.  Cosatu has been accused of "bullyboy" tactics and attempting to ride roughshod over the consensus-seeking style which has characterised the constitutional negotiations. The strike is also claimed to have caused the value of the rand to plummet and to have put off potential investors. Cosatu rejects these spurious attacks and defends the legitimacy of the stayaway."<BR><P>
<B><I>OTHER NEWS ...</I></B><BR><P>
INFLATION MAY BE FORCED UP TO 10% - STALS<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The rand's plunge could add as much as three percentage points to the overall inflation rate this year, taking it to a maximum of 10%, Reserve Bank governor Chris Stals said yesterday.<BR><P>
BITE HAS BEEN TAKEN OUT OF SA CURRENCY<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The rand's collapse was a bit overdone and has left the currency undervalued by at least 30%, says <I>The Economist's</I> latest Big Mac indicator.<BR><P>
WEST DRIEFONTEIN SHAFT ABLAZE<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Fire-fighting teams were still battling last night to contain a blaze detected at the weekend about 1 000m below the surface at West Driefontein mine about 75km west of Johannesburg, a Driefontein Consolidated Ltd spokesman said.<BR><P>
EMPLOYMENT STANDARDS GREEN PAPER TALKS BEGIN <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The implementation of a 40-hour week, and the extent to which collective bargaining agreements could override statutory minima, emerged yesterday as possible issues labour, government and business could disagree on during negotiations on the employment standards green paper.<BR><P>
MOVES TO PHASE IN NEW LABOUR ACT <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The Labour Department was moving in the direction of a phased-in implementation of the new Labour Relations Act with the hope that many, if not all, aspects of it would come into effect by August this year, Labour Minister Tito Mboweni said yesterday.<BR><P>
SASOL MINING BEGINS TO EXPORT HIGH-GRADE COAL<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Sasol Mining started to export high grade coal for the first time this week, after the first vessels had been loaded at Richards Bay coal terminal with trial cargo from Twistdraai colliery.<BR><P>
RATE HIKE TO PUT FURTHER PRESSURE ON SA ECONOMY <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The Reserve Bank's decision to lift the Bank rate would further pressure the economy, but on its own could fail to halt SA's economic slide, business said yesterday.<BR><P>
SA POSTS TRADE SURPLUS FOR SECOND CONSECUTIVE MONTH <I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
SA posted a positive trade balance for last month for the second consecutive month, recording a surplus of R652,9m, down from R1,27b in February, the Customs and Excise Department said yesterday.<BR><P>
SA NEEDS 'MUCH MORE INVESTMENT FOR ECONOMY TO GROW'<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
SA needs a much higher level of investment for its economy to grow at a meaningful rate, At Engelbrecht, the economic adviser to the Northern Transvaal Chamber of Industries, said in the chamber's latest Facts and Figures newsletter.<BR><P>
HIGHER INTEREST STABILISES RAND <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The rand recovered initially yesterday after the increase in the bank rate over the weekend, but later fell back somewhat again.  Johannesburg Stock Exchange investors had to pay a high price, however, because share prices fell sharply in response to the bank rate increase.<BR><P>
NEW LABOUR LAW NO LONGER IN OPERATION TOMORROW <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The Labour Relations Act, which was supposed to come into operation tomorrow, will now probably only come fully into operation by August because the Commission for Conciliation, Mediation and Arbitration has not been formed yet.  The success of this very sensitive piece of legislation will depend to a large extent on the effectiveness of this commission.<BR><P>
CYRIL LEADER OF TEAM TALKING TO ANGLO<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Cyril Ramaphosa, general secretary of the ANC and chairman of the Constitutional Assembly, has been appointed chief negotiator for the black National Empowerment Consortium business group, which is to enter negotiations with Anglo American in connection with taking over the latter's interest in the Johnnic Industrial Consortium.<BR><P>
FOREIGNERS STILL BUYING<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Foreign investors were net buyers on the JSE last week of shares to the value of R164-million.<BR><P>
<A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/statistics/g-output.htm#GOLDPRODMAR96">GOLD PRODUCTION</A> STILL FALLING<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
South African gold production was 41 919 kg in March this year, as against 42 794 kg in February and 44 905 kg in March last year.<BR><P>
KRUGERRAND NOT ALWAYS GOLD THAT GLITTERS FOR INVESTOR <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Some investors are attracted by gold and put their money in Krugerrands, but they should be aware that Krugerrands have no scarcity value.  The coins are only worth the ounce of gold they contain.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD SET TO GRAB TWO MARGINAL MINES<I> (The Citizen)</I><BR>
Randgold is involved in talks to acquire two more marginal mines, West Wits Gold Holdings and Benoni Gold Holdings, which could provide rich pickings if costs can be cut back, analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
CENSUS TO IDENTIFY SPECIFIC NEEDS<I> (Cape Times)</I><BR>
South Africas first post-apartheid census aims to count every person in the nation and to identify the countrys specific needs.  The 1996 National Population Census, which will cost R365 million, will be held between October 10 and 31 and will be preceded by an extensive education and publicity campaign - to be launched today.<BR><P>

