<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 29 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </b></h1></b></center></center>
<BR><P>



CONSTITUTION ACCORD FAILS TO AVERT STRIKE<I> (Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The African National Congress and National Party yesterday agreed in principle on three of the four main outstanding constitutional issues, including a formulation on a lock-out clause in the final constitution, but unionists insist tomorrows national strike is still on.<BR><P>
WHY COSATU REALLY WANTS TO STRIKE <I>(Finansies & Tegniek, weekly 26/4/96)</I><BR>
The Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu) apparently intends having the lock-out provision amended out of the new Labour Relations Act next year, and that is why they are striking against it being included as a right in the constitution.<BR><P>
ECONOMY POISED ON A KNIFE-EDGE<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The economy is poised on a knife-edge, with another plunge in the rand likely to destroy economic growth and jobs while fuelling inflation.  However, if calm returns to the market, SA will be able to avoid paying a massive price for the depreciation.  Economic growth will remain positive and inflation will probably stay in single digits if the currency stabilises.<BR><P>
POLITICS BEHIND RAND'S MOST RECENT FALL, ECONOMISTS<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
A snap survey of economists on Friday confirmed that politics was the main culprit behind the rand's most recent setback when it dropped to a record low of R4,58 early on Friday.<BR><P>
STRIKE GOES ON - MANDELA <I>(The Citizen,Saturday, Jhb)</I><BR>
Pres. Mandela said on Friday the national strike called for Tuesday by Cosatu would not be called off.<BR><P>
ALUSAF SEEKS PARTNERS FOR MAPUTO PROJECT<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gencor's Alusaf will invite several international aluminium producers and traders to join it in funding its proposed $1bn Maputo-based aluminium smelter.<BR><P>
CALL TO PROTECT POOR FROM GLOBALISATON <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
World leaders and international financial executives have called for multilateral efforts to protect the world's 2-billion marginalised people from the harsh effects of globalisation of the economy.<BR><P>
LONRHO MERGER A 'QUANTUM LEAP' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Impala Platinum believed its merger with Lonrho's platinum interests represented a quantum leap for the company, but it was not vital to its future success.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD WANTS TO SPREAD WINGS <I>(Finansies & Tegniek)</I><BR>
It was striking with what confidence Randgold's top management presented the quarterly reports of the group's four gold mines this week, as well as the half-yearly report.  And indeed the central message of this group, which was nearly down and out 2½ years ago, is that it is now on the takeover path.<BR>
<B><I>... and Business Day reports today ...</I></B><BR>
RANDGOLD MOVES TO ACQUIRE MINES<BR>
Randgold's expansion plans moved up a gear at the weekend as the mining house announced talks to buy two listed marginal gold mines worth nearly R85m.  The group  said it was negotiating to buy the entire share capital of Consolidated Mining Corporation's West Wits and Benoni Gold operations.<BR><P>
ECONOMISTS: ROSY INFLATION IN MARCH, COULD WITHER IN APRIL<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
While the rest of the world is writing inflation's obituary, SA is girding its loins for a new attack. But last month's figures, due for release today, will not yet provide evidence of the assault on the rand.<BR><P>
EDITORIAL COMMENT <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The rise in interest rates announced by Chris Stals, the Reserve Bank governor, late on Friday night is an admission of defeat for a government that has lost its way in economic policy.  It would make sense only as a precursor to an imminent lifting of exchange controls.<BR><P>
FINLAND BACKS SA'S EU FREE TRADE BID <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Ole Norrback, Finland's Minister for EU Affairs, threw his support behind SA's hard-fought negotiations over a free trade agreement with the union last week.<BR><P>
MINING INDUSTRY COULD FACE BILLIONS IN PAY-OUTS OVER OCCUPATIONAL DISEASE <I>(Saturday Star)</I><BR>
Hundreds of thousands of ex-miners could be suffering from occupational disease, and compensation payable in terms of the law could run into several billion rands.  This disturbing evidence of the high burden of mining-related disease in SA rural areas has emerged from a recent scientific study in the former Transkei.<I>[The Sunday Independent ran a similar story yesterday, and todays daily Star runs the first of three feature articles on the Epidemiological Research Units study in the Libode district in Transkei - Ed.)</I><BR><P>
SA RATE HIKE SEEN SPUR TO GOLD HEDGING <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SA gold producers were holding back from locking in a higher rand gold price, believing a likely rise in interest rates could offer a more attractive contango, analysts said on Friday.<BR><P>
IMF NOT ASKED FOR AID TO SUPPORT THE RAND <I>(Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
South Africa has not yet asked the International Monetary Fund for assistance to protect its reserves against large-scale capital outflow because of the falling rand, IMF head Michael Camdessus said at Midrand, midway between Johannesburg and Pretoria and site of the UNCTAD conference, over the weekend.<BR><P>
AMALIA WILL 'ACHIEVE LARGE CAPITAL PROFIT' <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The Amalia gold mine stands to make a considerable profit from its decision to sell its interest in the Zimbabwean Minehead project, chairman George Julyan said at the AGM over the weekend.<BR><P>
RACE TO ACQUIRE JCI's MINING GIANT <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
The race for the industrial portion of the unbundled JCI is almost over, but the scramble for the mining portion is getting hotter and four groups are known to be keen on acquiring JCI Ltd.<BR><P>
CONCERN OVER LABOUR LAWS<I> (Finansies & Tegniek)</I><BR>
Evidence before the Parliamentary Standing Committee on Labour has revealed that there is considerable concern among employers over the way labour legislation is being dealt with, among other things because the Labour Market Commission has not yet commented on important legislation now being formulated.<BR><P>
ANGLO WANTS TO RULE THE ROOST <I>(Finansies & Tegniek)</I><BR>
Anglo American's recent moves around the Lonrho group are considered by informed sources as only the beginning of a strategy which will eventually ensure the South African giant the role of undisputed leader of mining in Africa.<BR><P>
THINGS LOOKING BRIGHT - DE BEERS  <I>(Finansies & Tegniek)</I><BR>
The De Beers annual report not only gives the overall impression that things are going particularly well with the group and with the diamond industry, but that they will go even better this year.<BR><P>
FOR EUROPEANS VIOLENCE, CRIME A PROBLEM<I> (Rapport, Sunday)</I><BR>
Poor labour relations, low productivity and the continuing wave of violence and crime have brought South Africa down in a recent survey by the Investor Responsibility Research Centre, in which it was found that Europeans in particular are uncertain about South Africa.<BR><P>

