<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 26 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </b></h1></b></center></center>
<BR><P>



<B><I>THE CONTROVERSY OVER COSATU'S STRIKE CALL CONTINUES ...</I></B><BR>
ALLAY FEARS OF INVESTORS - SEXWALE <I>(The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
The labour movement had a right to strike, but it was necessary to allay foreign investors' fears of an unstable labour force, Gauteng Premier Tokyo Sexwale said in Midrand yesterday.<BR><P>
MANDELA'S REASSURANCES DON'T HELP, RAND FALLS <I>(Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
An attempt by President Nelson Mandela to reassure the exchange markets did not prevent the rand falling dramatically to new lows yesterday.  The main reason for the fall is the Congress of South African Trade Unions' (Cosatu) planned strike on Tuesday, which is causing concern among foreign investors.<BR><P>
TEMPORARY WORKERS CAN HELP<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The Confederation of Employers of South Africa has arranged with labour agencies for more than 100 000 temporary workers to be available during Cosatu's planned strike next week to help businessmen and industrialists continue with production.<BR><P>
COSATU'S REACTION TO THE RAND IS NAÏVE <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
According to a statement yesterday, Cosatu says the weakening of the rand is a propaganda move by business to hit out at the labour movement.  It is tragic that an organisation with so much influence can issue such a naïve statement, commentator Curt von Keyserlingk writes.<BR><P>
ANC CLINGING TO COSATU SKIRTS<I> (BD pg 10 - by Thami Mazwai, editor of Enterprise, a business magazine aimed at black business)</I><BR>
Can somebody out there please inform the ANC that it is the political party in power? It cannot endorse mass action <I>(by Cosatu</I>) as it did when it was still operating from the bush. Governments do not do this. It is like passing a motion of no confidence in itself.<BR>
<B><I>See also <A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/releases/nostrike.htm">Chamber President's statement</A> ...</I></B><BR><P>
SUPPORT FOR LIBYA IS A FACTOR<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
The rand plunged almost 4 percent to a record low of R4,4375 against the dollar yesterday amid concern about the governments support of international pariah states like Libya and as the dollar strengthened globally.<BR><P>
MINES' INCOME UP 3,5% TO R5,8bn <I>(Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
Gold mine managements must start accepting the reality of the new political dispensation, and not put the blame on labour, politics and public holidays for bad performances.  This is the opinion of brokers approached by <I>Beeld </I>for their opinions on the major mining groups' reports for the quarter to 31 March.<BR><P>
GOLD TRADERS UNIMPRESSED BY RALLY <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
NEW YORK - Gold prices rallied strongly Thursday, giving gold bugs their first good news in weeks as investors and traders who had bet on a continued slide in prices were forced to cover their short positions.<BR><P>
RAND CAN FALL FURTHER<I>(Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
The rand exchange rate, which yesterday virtually went into free fall to its lowest level ever, is expected to continue its downward trend today, although perhaps not at the same rate.  Reserve Bank Governor Chris Stals said  the markets may leave him no choice but to increase interest rates to support the unit.<BR><P>
GOLD SHARES ASSISTED, CAPITAL MARKET HIT <I>(Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
The sharp fall in the value of the rand gave the  Johannesburg Stock Exchange share prices a massive boost yesterday, however capital market investors suffered heavy losses.  Gold shares in particular benefited, and the rand gold price rose to a new record R1 746 per fine ounce.<BR><P>
MANUEL MAY HAVE TO WAIT TO PROVE HIS CRITICS WRONG<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
A few ill-chosen words by SA Finance Minister Trevor Manuel on his foreign tour may drive the rand lower still, despite the view among many currency analysts that it is already substantially undervalued.<BR><P>
GOVT BACKED PLATINUM MERGER<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The European Commissions claim that the SA government supported its decision to reject Impala Platinums merger with Lonrhos platinum interests is false, according to evidence obtained yesterday.<BR><P>
SEARCH IS ON FOR <A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/releases/krparis.htm">KRUGERRAND MILLIONS IN PARIS</A> (Business Report)<BR>
PARIS - The South African Chamber of Mines today tackles one of the worlds most mysterious markets by offering Krugerrands directly to the French for the first time via the Paris Bourse.<BR><P>
GOLD PRICE BAILS OUT MINES<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The gold industry had relied heavily on the higher gold price for its March quarter performance, with the mining houses yet to prove they could bring costs to heel, analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
UNCTAD TRADE CONFERENCE PUTS SAS ROLE UNDER MICROSCOPE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Tomorrows United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (Unctad) in Midrand, halfway between Johannesburg and Pretoria, represents a significant opportunity for South Africa to establish its credibility in the world diplomatic community and influence trade policy.<BR><P>
NO AGREEMENT ON ECONOMIC POLICY SOON <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
It is highly unlikely that business and labour sectors can come to agreement on broad economic policy, but restricted agreements will have to be reached now on issues such as productivity, taxation policy and State debt, observers said yesterday after the first meeting of the National Economic Development and Labour Council (Nedlac) executive board.<BR><P>
BLYVOOR'S OFFER<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Blyvooruitzicht mine has received applications for 216,2% of the approximately 6,6-million linked units offered in the company's rights issues.<BR><P>
CONSMINING RESTRUCTURING<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Consolidated Mining appears to be involved in radical restructuring, to judge from the range of cautionary announcements issued last night.<BR><P>
KNIGHTS RECORDS A PROFIT <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Knights Gold Mining recorded a net profit of R3,097-million in the quarter to 31 March, compared with the previous quarter's profit of R678 000.<BR><P>
DUIKER LIFTS INTERIM DIVIDEND 143% <I>(The Citizen)</I><BR>
Duiker Mining moved into financial overdrive for the six months ending 31 March, leaping to record-breaking profits by nearly doubling mining income to R97,5-million compared with the corresponding period last year.<BR><P>
US COMPANIES RELUCTANT TO INVEST IN SA <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
Contrary to expectations, only one American company has invested in South Africa following a marathon visit by a high-powered delegation from South Africa.  It was reported yesterday that the delegation could confirm only one investment to the value of R400-million by a New York company called Pro Ventures.<BR><P>
