<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 25 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </b></h1></b></center></center>
<BR><P>

<B><I>COSATUS PLANNED STRIKE: REPORTS:-</I></B><BR>

ANC FORMALLY PROPOSES LOCKOUT CLAUSE BE KEPT OUT OF CONSTITUTION
<I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The African National Congress yesterday formally proposed exclusion of a clause in the constitution giving employers the right to lock out striking workers.<BR><P>
COSATU WARNS ON LOCK-OUT CLAUSE<I> (Sowetan, Jhb)</I><BR>
The Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu) has given constitutional negotiators five days to drop the controversial lock-out clause from the final constitution before it goes ahead with a general strike next Tuesday.  "There could be no compromise,"  its general-secretary Sam Shilowa said yesterday.<BR><P>
ISSUES WILL BE RESOLVED IN TIME TO AVERT STRIKE<I> (Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
Cosatu general-secretary Sam Shilowa says he is willing to discuss calling off Tuesdays general strike if his organisations demands are met.<BR><P>
CALL FOR LOCKOUT AFTER COSATU STRIKE<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
A Pretoria company, Silk & Textile Industries, has called on other companies to join it in a planned lockout of Cosatu-affiliated union members on May 3.<BR><P>
COSATU WARNS WORRIED INVESTORS ABOUT FURTHER STEPS<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
Investors who are worried about Cosatu's country-wide strike and protest action planned for next Tuesday should also be worried about what Cosatu is planning after this, its general-secretary Sam Shilowa said yesterday.<BR><P>
MUSCLE-FLEXING, AGAIN <I>(Financial Mail - weekly 26/4/96)</I><BR>
The rights to strike and to lock out are generally accepted as creating a fair balance and mutuality in industrial conflicts. If the right to lock out is dropped and the right to strike entrenched, it will put off the growing number of foreign and local businesses which already view the new Labour Relations Act as too union-friendly and a bar to investment. (Cosatus strike called for late last year) achieved nothing. Cosatu, it seems, desperately needs some issue over which to flex its muscle periodically and mobilise a constituency bereft of causes since the election of a popular government. <BR><P>
<B><I>OTHER NEWS OF THE DAY ...</I></B><BR>
IMF, BUNDESBANK 'BACK SA APPROACH' <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - Government was drawing support from the International Monetary Fund and the Bundesbank for its gradualist approach to exchange controls, Finance Minister Trevor Manuel said earlier this week.<BR><P>
COMMISSION REJECTS IMPLATS, LONRHO MERGER <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The European Commission blocked Impala Platinum's merger with Lonrho's platinum operations yesterday.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
EU WARNS ANGLO AMERICAN NOT TO TAKE OVER LONRHO <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BRUSSELS - European Competition Commissioner Karel Van Miert warned Anglo American against taking control of Lonrho saying it would create the same problem as that presented by the proposed merger of the platinum interests of Gencor and Lonrho which the European Commission blocked on Wednesday<I>.... but ... </I>Gencor Ltd's Impala Platinum Holdings said on Wednesday it would appeal against the European Commission ruling.<BR><P>
NAFCOC NO TO SHORT WEEK, HIGH MINIMUM WAGES <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The National African Federated Chamber of Commerce (Nafcoc) said yesterday it was opposed to a 40-hour week and "an excessively high minimum wage" as these would have a negative effect on black business.<BR><P>
FOREIGN MULTINATIONALS BULLISH ABOUT SA<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - Foreign multinationals, responding to a new survey by the Washington-based Investor Responsibility Research Centre, sounded a generally bullish note about doing business in SA, and nearly 40% said they planned to make new investments in the country this year.<BR><P>
MINE SHIFT SYSTEM 'NO CURE-ALL'<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
New Anglo American gold and uranium division chairman Bobby Godsell does not believe the recently adopted shift system at some shafts at the group's embattled Freegold mine is the panacea for SA's shrinking gold mining industry. <BR><P>
SA MIGHT JOIN LOMÉ BY THE MIDDLE OF JUNE<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
South Africa might joint the Lomé Convention if the African, Caribbean and Pacific countries (ACP) and the European Union Council of Ministers ratify an agreement to be negotiated in three weeks' time, a spokesman for the Trade and Industry Department said yesterday.<BR><P>
WTO CHIEF URGES GLOBAL FREE MARKET<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
SINGAPORE - The head of the World Trade Organisation cautioned regional trade groups yesterday not to stand in the way of making the world a single market.<BR><P>
IMF, WORLD BANK HAVE DIFFICULTY ADAPTING <I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - For two organisations that have made it their business to preach the gospel of economic modernisation, the IMF and World Bank are having a tough time following their own advice.<BR><P>
ASHANTI SAYS NO COUNTRY TOO RISKY <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
ZURICH - No country is too risky for Ashanti Goldfields to establish mining operations, the firm's Executive Director of Strategic Planning, John Clarke said.  Ashanti, the largest African mining firm outside South Africa, has recently acquired property concessions in Mozambique, Angola and Sudan, Clarke told the ABN Amro Gold Conference in Zurich. <BR><P>
FOCUS SEEN ON MID-/SMALL AUSTRALIAN GOLD MINERS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
ZURICH - Robust take-over and merger interest in mid-size and small Australian gold miners will buoy the sector this year while the major producers are held back by stagnant profit margins, analysts at a gold conference said.<BR><P>
GEFCO WARNS AGAINST HIGH EXPECTATIONS <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
A warning has to be issued against the too-high expectations that Griqualand Exploration and Finance Company (Gefco) will distribute dividends, chairman H P Hart says in his review.  The reason is the rationalisation costs the group has to incur to cut overheads because of the shrinking world market for blue asbestos.<BR><P>
GOLD PRODUCERS STARTING TO HEDGE MORE AND MORE <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Gold producers are concentrating more and more on hedging, although there was a tendency to move away from this practice in the past.  Regret over this trend was expressed by some of the delegates at a conference in Zurich yesterday.<BR><P>
AMALIA SELLS ITS INTERESTS IN ZIMBABWE  <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The Amalia gold mine recorded a profit of R37,299-million in the six months to 31 March, compared with a loss of R2,1-million in the same period last year.  The profit is attributable to capital profit from the sale of the company's interest in the Zimbabwean Minehead Mining gold mining company.<BR><P>
ZIMBABWE HALTS EXPORT OF CHROME ORE  <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Zimbabwe has halted the export of its chrome ore to protect the country's ferrochrome industry from competition.  Ore exports are being prohibited with immediate effect in order to allow the State's mineral authorities to rationalise activities and to set realistic export quantities.<BR><P>
DIAMOND CUTTERS CAN BENEFIT FROM TIES WITH C.A.R. <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The new diplomatic ties between South Africa and the Central African Republic can hold great advantages for diamond cutters in particular, because they could lead to price cuts, says Johan Erikson, one of South Africa's leading diamond processors and jewellery dealers, and now the CAR's official representative here.<BR><P>
MINES BIG PROFIT JUMP MASKS DEEPER PROBLEMS <I>(The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Gold mines had a big turnabout in the March quarter, increasing earnings by a massive 201% to R444,5-million from R147,5-million in the previous quarter, but Fedsure Asset Management analyst Nick Goodwin still emphasises negatives like lower production, higher costs and lower capex.<BR><P>
