<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 24 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </b></h1></b></center></center>
<BR><P>


ERWIN MOOTS TAX INCENTIVES FOR SA TRADE <I>(Business Day,Jhb.)</I><BR>
South Africa should follow an active industrial policy - including tax incentives - to boost potential world-class players in the global trade stakes, newly appointed Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin said yesterday.<BR><P>
IMPALA, LONRHO DEAL COULD BE RESHAPED<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Gencor's Impala Platinum will reshape its merger with Lonrho's platinum operations to prevent the venture falling under the jurisdiction of the European Commission if the commission rules against its current merger plans.<BR><P>
<B><I>... but Reuters reports ...</I></B><BR>
EU PLATINUM VETO WOULD HIT GENCOR MOST<BR>
LONDON - Any European Commission veto of the planned merger to create one of the worlds largest platinum firms would be a blow to Gencor, while it would leave Lonrho fairly unscathed, analysts said on Tuesday.<BR><P> 
MASIRE CALLS FOR REGIONAL ECONOMIC INTEGRATION <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Botswanan President Ketumile Masire, in SA yesterday on a state visit, stressed the need for regional integration, calling for the speedy conclusion of talks on the SA Customs Union deal.<BR><P>
NUM MASS ACTION<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers, dissatisfied with talks at Duiker Exploration, has announced a mass action campaign lasting more than two weeks, starting from today.<BR><P>
COSATU WILL GO IT ALONE IF NECESSARY <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu) last night reiterated its call for a national strike on April 30 - in support of its outstanding constitutional demands against employers' right to lockout - and its position that it would "go it alone" if it did not receive support from other trade union federations and mass democratic structures.<BR><P>
INVESTORS CALL FOR LIFTING OF CONTROLS<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
MUNICH - Set against the backdrop of an ailing rand and the introduction of SA's new Finance Minister Trevor Manuel, German investors are calling for SA's exchange controls to be dropped at the earliest possible opportunity.<BR><P>
SOUTHERN AFRICA NEEDS 'INTEGRATED ECONOMY' <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Southern African nations needed to co-ordinate their standards and align them with international levels to be able to compete in the world marketplace, Trade and Industry director-general Zavareh Rustomjee said in Pretoria yesterday.<BR><P>
PRIVATISATION NOT TO BE RUSHED <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin told Italian investors yesterday that the SA government was treading cautiously on its path to privatisation.<BR><P>
HOLIDAYS BLAMED FOR MINING LOSSES <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold mines in the JCI stable suffered a fall in income before capex to R77m (R79,8m) for the March quarter, as higher costs and lower production overshadowed gold price gains.<BR><P>
ECONOMIC GROWTH TOO LOW TO END UNEMPLOYMENT - SANLAM<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
SA was falling short of the level of economic growth necessary to eliminate unemployment and make a lasting impact on the lives of its people, Sanlam group chairman Marinus Daling said.<BR><P>
RAND'S TURMOIL SEES INVESTORS THINK TWICE ON ASSET SWAPS <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The rand's recent turmoil was making many foreign investors think twice about pursuing asset swaps, local institutions said yesterday.<BR><P>
EXPORT DRIVE TO COINCIDE WITH MANDELA'S UK VISIT<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
President Mandela's state visit to Britain would mark the start of SA's biggest export promotion this year.<BR><P>
SURVEY SHOWS FALL IN BUSINESS CONFIDENCE<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
A national survey conducted by the Bureau for Economic Research at Stellenbosch University and released yesterday showed that indications of weaker demand at home and abroad caused business confidence in the South African manufacturing sector to slump in the first quarter of this year.<BR><P>
IMF EXPECTS GLOBAL ECONOMIC EXPANSION<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - The outlook for economic growth in developing and industrialised countries looked fairly promising, top economic officials said on Monday.  Greater currency stability, diminishing inflation, lower interest rates and the absence of big economic crises meant the world could be poised for expansion. <BR><P>
GENGOLD TO RELEASE EVANDER MINE PLANS SOON <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
ZURICH - Gengold expects to announce details soon about its grouping of gold mines in the Evander area in a single company, managing director Tom Dale said on Tuesday. <BR><P>
BRAZIL EASING REGULATION TO BOOST MINING <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
MIAMI - Government officials responsible for Brazils mining sector on Tuesday said the South American nation is moving toward a regulatory environment that should make it easier for foreign companies to become involved in its mineral business.<BR><P>
CAMDESSUS FAVOURS GOLD SALES OVER PLEDGES <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - International Monetary Fund managing director Michel Camdessus said on Tuesday he would prefer to sell part of the IMFs gold reserves rather than pledge it in order to raise funds to help the worlds poorest nations.<BR><P>
CONS MURCH EARNS MORE <I>(Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
JCI antimony-producing subsidiary Consolidated Murchison earned an after-tax profit of 
R4,571-million in the quarter to 31 March, as against a R4,295-million profit in the previous quarter.<BR><P>
AMALIA GOLD'S PRICE RISES SHARPLY <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Amalia Gold's share price yesterday rose 20c to a closing price of 170c.  Its price on 29 December was 35c.<BR><P>
HOW BENEFICIAL ARE SA MARKET INVESTMENTS? <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
It is reported from New York that Merrill Lynch market analyst Doug Johnson is doing a presentation showing the benefits of investing in South Africa and other markets.  "Political instability can offer excellent buying opportunities if the share market is fundamentally sound," he says.<BR><P>
MINORCO 'CAN PRODUCE GOOD YIELDS'  <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The management of Minorco is convinced the benefits of the turnabout to market-driven economies in the developing countries will ensure that the growth in world economies will remain strong, according to chairman Julian Ogilvie-Thompson and president and CE Henry Slack.  Against this background, Minorco is in a good position to give shareholders attractive yields in the next few years, they say.<BR><P>
THIS WON'T HALT WEAKENING RAND - NP <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The weakening of the rand cannot be halted by overseas visits by Finance Minister Trevor Manuel or mere pronouncements by Pres. Mandela, the National Party said yesterday.<BR><P>
DIAMOND MINE CLOSES<I> (Sowetan, Jhb)</I><BR>
Swaziland's only diamond mine at Dvokolwako is to cease operations shortly, according to Natural Resources and Energy Minister Muntu Dlamini.<BR><P>
