<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 22 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </b></h1></b></center></center>
<BR><P>



ANC STILL 'TO DECIDE' ON SUPPORT FOR STRIKE<I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The ANC declined yesterday to give its full-backing to the 30 April strike called by Cosatu at the weekend in support of outstanding constitutional demands.<BR><P>
TAIWAN 'COMMITTED TO SA' <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The Taiwanese government, which enjoys diplomatic relations with Pretoria, has played down the implications of the improving relations between rival mainland China and South Africa, dismissing speculations of a possible withdrawal from South Africa.<BR><P>
'MINE NOT IN A POSITION' TO GRANT COMPENSATION<I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Arguments were presented in the Industrial Court yesterday on the compensation of 300 Zulu workers unfairly dismissed by ERPM after violent clashes between workers.  The workers were paid a retrenchment package and the mine was not in a position to grant further compensation.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD BOUNCES BACK INTO THE BLACK <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The Randgold-managed group of mines staged a remarkable turn-around in the March quarter, achieving a R30-million taxed profit, as against a R39,4-million loss in December, after higher average revenues and a reduction in average costs.<BR><P>
COSATU SEEKS THE REVIVAL OF WEAK UNION STRUCTURES <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Cosatu emerged from its three-day living wage conference with a range of campaigns which the federation hopes will revive weak local union structures.<BR><P>
US CONSIDERING IMF GOLD SALE <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - In a move to relieve Third World debt, US treasury secretary Robert Rubin said yesterday his country would consider joining other countries to allow the sale of IMF gold.<BR><P>
POSSIBLE BLOCK ON MERGER QUESTIONED <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
BRUSSELS - Some of the 20 European commissioners were unhappy with a draft decision to block the merger of the platinum interests of British based Lonrho and South Africa's Gencor, commission sources said yesterday.<BR><P>
SWAZILAND INCLUDED IN MAPUTO CORRIDOR PLAN<I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
NELSPRUIT - Plans were afoot to include Swaziland in the R5-billion Maputo corridor development initiative, Mpumalanga premier Mathews Phosa said yesterday.<BR><P>
ASHANTI LISTS AT Z$185<I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
HARARE - Ashanti Gold Fields, the Lonrho-controlled company thought to be Anglo American's main target in its tie-up with the UK conglomerate, listed on the Zimbabwe Stock Exchange yesterday, following its take-over of Cluff Resources Zimbabwe.<BR><P>
RIGHT TO STRIKE?<I>(Business Day, Jhb: EDITORIAL)</I><BR>
One way to view Cosatu's call for a national strike on 30 April would be for business simply to build into its budgeting and other planning an assumption that the federation will make such a call once a year, regular as clockwork.<BR><P>
COSATU REITERATES OPPOSITION TO PRIVATISATION <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Cosatu reiterated its opposition to privatisation as a means of restructuring the public sector at its Living Wage Conference held at the weekend.<BR><P>
GOLD MINING INDUSTRY CONSOLIDATES<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
TORONTO - North American gold mining companies face a ruthless dilemma:  buy or be bought.  While they gobble up home-grown producers, predatory North American gold goliaths are extending their global reach in a bid to satisfy an apparently insatiable appetite for new reserves.<BR><P>
IMF GOLD SALE STILL OPTION TO FUND <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - The IMF is considering a number of options, including limited gold sales, to finance its lending facility for the world's poorest nations, Philippe Maystadt, head of its policy-making Interim Committee, said on Monday.<BR><P>
JSE REACHES NEW PEAK<I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Johannesburg Stock Exchange broke through the "sound barrier" yesterday when the general index passed the 7 000 level for the first time ever.<BR><P>
FOREIGNERS SELL <I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Foreign investors were once again net sellers of South African securities on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange last week, selling to the value of R81-million.<BR><P>
MINES PRODUCE LESS<I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
South Africa's overall mining production in the three months to the end of January was 0,8% less than in the previous three months.<BR><P>
RANDEX DISCUSSING MINERAL RIGHTS<I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Negotiations are under way between Randex, Lydenburg Exploration, Randgold and Harmony over the possible acquisition of the mineral rights of the farm Vermeulenskraak Noord.<BR><P>
STRIKE<I>(Beeld, Jhb.: EDITORIAL)</I><BR>
Cosatu's planned strike for 30 April has placed the ANC in an awkward position.  It has expressed support for the strike for reasons of solidarity, but the strike will have a negative effect on the country's image for foreign investors.  The ANC must be aware of the negative implications of its support for the strike.<BR><P>
COSATU STRIKE WILL HIT RAND, SAYS DE KLERK <I>(The Citizen,Jhb.)</I><BR>
Deputy President F W de Klerk said yesterday the national strike being called by Cosatu next week would lead to a further fall in the value of the rand.<BR><P>
MINES STUDY HEDGING, BUT REMAIN WARY<I>(The Citizen,Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gold mining houses were investigating selling forward production to lock in current high rand gold prices won at the expense of the weak local currency, foreign exchange dealers said yesterday.<BR><P>
SA CANNOT AFFORD COSATU STRIKE <I>(Burger, Beeld)</I><BR>
Cosatus plans for a nation-wide strike to influence constitutional provisions were yesterday described by political parties as irresponsible and something that the country cannot afford.  Parties expressed their surprise at the ANC's support for the planned strike.<BR><P>
