<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 22 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </b></h1></b></center></center>
<BR><P>


WEAKER RAND LIKELY TO BOOST THE ECONOMY <I>(Business Day,Jhb.)</I><BR>
The weaker rand should benefit the economy without taking too high a toll on inflation - provided foreign confidence was restored, analysts said at the weekend.<BR><P>
COSATU STRIKE WILL TARGET BUSINESS, NP AND DP <I>(Business Day,Jhb.)</I><BR>
The April 30 national strike called by Cosatu would target big business, the NP and DP - to press them to accede to Cosatu demands on the constitution, particularly exclusion of a lockout clause, Cosatu said yesterday.<BR><P>
US MAY SUBSIDISE SA PLANTS PLANNING <I>(Business Day,Jhb.)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - The US government is likely to agree to subsidise planning for the giant R2,5bn iron carbide-to-steel plant that the Industrial Development Corp is considering building at Phalaborwa.<BR><P>
EUROPEAN UNION DOCUMENTS INDICATE SPLIT OVER FREE-TRADE DEAL<I>(Business Day,Jhb.)</I><BR>
Internal EU documents suggest its representatives doubt whether a proposed free-trade area between SA and the union can be negotiated because members want so many agricultural products excluded.<BR><P>
MANDELA OPENS ALUSAF SMELTER<I>(Business Day,Jhb.)</I><BR>
RICHARDS BAY - President Mandela officially opened aluminium producer Alusaf's new Hillside smelter on Friday, hailing the development as a major boost for SA's economy.<BR><P>
OBSERVERS FEAR SA MAY LOSE US TRADE LIMELIGHT <I>(Business Day,Jhb.)</I><BR>
The appointment of US trade representative Mickey Kantor as commerce secretary following previous incumbent Ron Browns death has been welcomed in SA trade circles.  Observers fear, however, that SA could lose the prominent spot it previously enjoyed on the US trade agenda.<BR><P>
BOP DEFICIT WILL DISAPPEAR, SAYS ECONOMISTS <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The slowdown in the business cycle and the resulting drop in imports could cause the deficit on the current account of the balance of payments (BOP) to disappear by the end of this year, Nick Barnardt and Thea Dreyer, economists at the Board of Executors Nat West Securities, have said.<BR><P>
ABSA EXPECTS 3,5% GROWTH <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The economy was likely to grow 3,5 percent this year because of an improved performance by the agricultural sector, Absa Bank said in its latest quarterly economic monitor.<BR><P>
SAS EXPORT DRIVE CAUSES HAVOC IN AFRICA<I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
NAIROBI - Is South Africa using its trade policy to balkanise the rest of the continent?  This question is becoming increasingly common as the countrys commercial tentacles penetrate poverty-stricken sub-Saharan nations.  From the tiny islands of Mauritius and Reunion to Nigeria, Africas most populous nation, South African exports are causing havoc among local industries.<BR><P>
DISMISSED MINERS HEARING CONTINUES TODAY<I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A court hearing to decide whether East Rand Proprietary Mines has to pay compensation for dismissing miners to diffuse faction fighting on its premises two years ago, resumes in the Pretoria Industrial Court today.<BR><P>
GOLD GIVES UP NEARLY ALL 1996 RALLY GAINS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Gold gave up the last of its 1996 gains on Friday as a speculator sell-off dragged it back down to where it began a rally in January.  Dealers said the bullion market now looked ready to sink back into the torpor that characterised it throughout 1995.<BR><P>
IMF PLANS PLACE PRESSURE ON GOLD <I>(Business Day,Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gold is likely to remain under pressure this week, with markets watching for confirmation of International Monetary Fund plans to dip into its $40bn bullion reserves to underpin its controversial debt relief programme.<BR><P>
INDUSTRIAL NATIONS DISAGREE ON SALE OF IMF GOLD <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - The Group of Seven richest industrial nations came no closer on Sunday to agreeing on the sale of IMF gold reserves to help the worlds poorest and most heavily indebted nations.<BR><P>
LEAP IN RAND GOLD PRICE BENEFITS FORWARD SELLING<BR><I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
South African mining houses are taking advantage of depressed rand rates and are hedging gold production again, said dealers.<BR><P>
SA GOLD MINES ON WINNING STREAK FOR JUNE QUARTER <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
JOHANNESBURG - South African gold mines can look forward to even richer profits in the June quarter, owing to their change in fortune due to the weaker rand, analysts said.  With most mining houses having posted bigger March quarter earnings, analysts believe the industry has started to throw off the doom and gloom of last years productivity decline.<BR><P>
SA MUST STRIKE OVER CONSTITUTION <I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Cosatu has called a country-wide strike for 30 April to marshall support for its constitutional views which are now being negotiated in the CA.  The 24-hour strike will be accompanied by other protest action extending over five days.<BR><P>
ANC & NACTU AGREE ON COSATU ACTION <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The ANC and Nactu yesterday expressed their support for the Cosatu call for a national strike next week over the inclusion in the new constitution of the clause to lock out workers during a dispute.<BR><P>
FOUR WORKERS KILLED IN MINE AT KLERKSDORP <I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Four workers were killed in an earth tremor at the Buffelsfontein gold mine yesterday morning.<BR><P>
COSATU CAN DAMAGE RAND FURTHER <I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
With another country-wide strike planned for the end of the month, businessmen fear that the value of the rand can be damaged further.<BR><P>
JOHNNIC MAY BE UNDER BLACK CONTROL BY AUGUST<I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
If everything goes according to plan, Johnnic should be under black control as early as August, according to National Empowerment Consortium joint chairman Tommie Oliphant.<BR><P>
BUFFELS SHARES CAN BE EXCHANGED FOR BGM SHARES <I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Buffelsfontein shareholders are now entitled to receive ordinary BGM shares in exchange for their Buffelsfontein share certificates.<BR><P>
GOLD MINES STEM ROT ON RAND SLIDE <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gold mines can look forward to even richer profits in the June quarter, owing their change in fortune to the weaker rand, analysts say.<BR><P>
STORM AROUND THE RAND <I>(Finansies & Tegniek, 19/4/1996)</I><BR>
Contrary to most impressions, prospects for the South African economy have actually improved slightly following the sharp drop in the rand exchange rate.  Buyers of now considerably more expensive foreign products can hardly be expected not to be disturbed over the devaluation of the unit, but the key point is that the rand is now no longer overvalued, which of necessity means a more stable basis for the economy.<BR><P>
BSA TRYING TO SAVE GROWTH ACCORD <I>(Finansies & Tegniek, 19/4/1996)</I><BR>
With its document on the economy this week, Business South Africa (BSA) is trying to inject a new urgency into the process for the Government, business and labour to reach agreement.  The three parties, whose co-operation is essential if the problems of unemployment and poverty are to be overcome, have recently started talking against each other rather than with each other. The gap has been widened in particular by the confrontational reaction of organised labour to the South African Foundation's growth plan.<BR><P>
SUN BREAKING OUT FOR GOLD MINES <I>(Finansies & Tegniek, 19/4/1996)</I><BR>
Judging from Gengold's quarterly report, the sun has now broken through for the gold mining industry after a long bleak period.  There are indications that the far-reaching rationalisation under way in the industry is now beginning to pay off.<BR><P>
MINES AND NATURE CONSERVATION IN CONFLICT  <I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The decades-long struggle between environmentalists and mining companies in the Magaliesberg reflects the growing worldwide tension between economic development and the preservation of nature.<BR><P>
BUSINESS, UNIONS ASK GOVT TO FOCUS ON JOBS <I>(The Citizen,Jhb.)</I><BR>
Business and trade unions have called on the Government to focus its economic muscle on the problem of unemployment, rather than spending millions on projects that do not materially benefit the people of South Africa.<BR><P>
MINES BRACE FOR TOUGH WAGE TALKS <I>(The Citizen,Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gold mining companies expect annual wage negotiations due to start next month to be very tough following the current higher rand gold price and the better-than-expected March quarterly results of leading mining houses.<BR><P>
WEAK RAND MAKES GOLD SHARES SHINE <I>(Rapport, Jhb. {Sunday:21/4/96})</I><BR>
Despite the dollar price of gold which just cannot seem to be able to break through the $400 level, the latest sharp fall in the exchange rate of the rand has now reawakened investors' interest in gold shares.




