<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 19 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </b></h1></b></center></center>
<BR><P>




FOR FULLER REPORTS ON <B>VAAL REEFS</B>, click <A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/news/180496.htm">HERE</A>
OR CONTACT<A HREF="mailto:lkriel@bullion.org.za"> LLEWELLYN KRIEL </A><BR><P>

PROSECUTE VAAL REEFS, INQUIRY URGES<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
A joint inquest-inquiry has recommended that Vaal Reefs mine and five of its employees be prosecuted for culpable homicide following the death of 104 mineworkers a year ago.<BR><P>
MINE & 5 WORKERS CARRY BLAME FOR HORROR DEATH OF 104 <I>(Beeld,Jhb)</I><BR>
Vaal Reefs mine and five of its employees are responsible for the horror death of the 104 workers at the mine last year and may be criminally charged.  When announcing his findings yesterday, head of the commission of inquiry into the disaster Justice Ramon Leon recommended that the company should be charged with culpable homicide.<BR><P>
MINING DISASTER:  LOCO DRIVER ACQUITTED <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The Leon commission of inquiry into the Vaal Reefs disaster yesterday found the loco driver who caused the cage carrying 104 workers to plunge down the shaft negligent, but not guilty of culpable homicide.<BR><P>
MINE OFFICIALS 'WANTED TO HIDE EVIDENCE' <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The Leon commission revealed yesterday that a midnight meeting was held shortly after the Vaal Reefs disaster and a group of mine officials at the meeting tried to hide evidence of what had happened.<BR><P>
UNION WELCOMES MINE DISASTER FINDING<I> (The Citizen,Jhb)</I><BR>
NUM yesterday welcomed a recommendation by the Leon inquiry that the mining company should be prosecuted for culpable homicide.<BR><P>
COMMENT<I> (Editorial, Sowetan,Jhb)</I><BR>
Safety on the mines is an emotive topic, and we understand the concerns of the mining industry over the<A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/releases/safebill.htm"> Mines Health and Safety Bill</A>, but the question of occupational safety is so serious that we have to support the proposed legislation.<BR><P>
ANGLO SET TO CLOSE A FREEGOLD SHAFT<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American's troubled Free State gold mine Freegold would close its Freddies No 9 shaft which could see up to 600 job losses in the next few months, gold and uranium division senior manpower consultant Viv du Plessis said last night.<BR>
<B><I>... and the Johannesburg daily, Business Report, says ...</I></B><BR>
FREEGOLD SAVES 10 000 JOBS
Anglo American announced yesterday that four of Freegold's five threatened shafts would remain operational, saving about 10 000 jobs - for the time being, at least.<BR><P>
IMMIGRANTS TO SA LESS THAN EMIGRANTS <I>(Die Burger, Cape Town)</I><BR>
More people are emigrating from South Africa as opposed to the legal immigration of people to the country.  The 1994 figures for emigration came close to the 1940 figures which show the highest loss of emigrants in the countrys history.<BR><P>
NKUHLU, RAMAPHOSA DISCUSS JOHNNIC DEAL<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
National Empowerment Consortium chairman Wiseman Nkuhlu met New Africa Investment's newly appointed deputy executive chairman, Cyril Ramaphosa in Cape Town yesterday to iron out the uncertainties and media speculations surrounding the Johnnic deal.<BR><P>
UNIONS FACE CRUCIAL QUESTIONS OVER BID <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
With the National Union of Mineworkers (NUM), other Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu) affiliates, National Council of Trade Unions (Nactu) and various union-owned investment companies vying for a significant role in the forthcoming bid for Anglo American's 48% stake in Johnnic, organised labour faces crucial questions over how to walk the tightrope of conflicting roles of owner and worker representative.<BR><P>
ANGLO MINES BOOST PROFIT TO R225,4M<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American's gold and uranium division boosted available profit 66% to R225,4m in the March quarter, benefiting from the higher gold price during the review period.<BR><P>
WORLD QUEUES TO BUY FROM HILLSIDE SMELTER <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
International buyers are queuing for supplies from SA aluminium producer Alusaf's new Hillside smelter, and some are being turned away empty-handed.<BR><P>
PLATINUM PRICE FALLS ON RUSSIAN SALES<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
Continuing Russian inventory selling took platinum's London afternoon fixing yesterday down to $400 an ounce, $1,50 off Wednesday's fix of $401,50.<BR><P>
ANGLO SAYS RAND CRISIS DUE TO MISMANAGEMENT <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Anglo American Corp of SA Ltd, SA's biggest company, on Thursday said the dramatic fall in the rand since mid-February was due to mismanagement by the government. <BR><P>
STABLE GOLD PRICE DESPITE SLOWER FAR EAST DEMAND <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Anglo American Corp said on Thursday it expected a stable dollar gold price in 1996 despite some slowdown in enthusiasm for the metal among Far East investors.<BR><P>
FEWER BASOTHO MINERS WORK IN S AFRICA<I> (The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
The number of Basotho miners recruited for South African gold mines in the first quarter of this year had fallen by more than 1 000 compared with the same period last year, The Employment Bureau of Africa (TEBA) announced yesterday.<BR><P>
ASIA GOLD-LOW PRICES SEEN BOOSTING FAR EAST DEMAND <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
HONG KONG - Hong Kong and Singapore gold dealers said prices would not move significantly next week, but they expected regional gold demand to pick up if prices slid further.<BR><P>
GOLD MARKET SEES RISING POSSIBILITY OF IMF SALES <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Gold analysts said the chances seem to be rising that the International Monetary Fund will approve a proposal to sell some of its gold although the amounts are likely to be small and the market impact muted.<BR><P>
ARGENTINE OFFICIAL SAYS CHILE MINE TREATY NEAR <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BUENOS AIRES -  Argentina and Chile reached technical agreement on a mining integration treaty seen as vital for top mining projects and only details remain to be hammered out, Argentina's top mining official said.<BR><P>
ZIMBABWE PLATINUM MINE STARTS AHEAD OF TARGET  <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
HARARE - Commissioning began this week, over two months ahead of schedule, at Zimbabwe's Hartley platinum mine which is owned by Australian companies, The Broken Hill Co. Pty. Ltd and Delta Gold.<BR><P>
BRITISH MINISTER IN SA <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
British Minister of Trade Anthony Nelson arrived in South Africa yesterday for a five-day trade visit to KwaZulu-Natal province.<BR><P>
ANGLO AGHAST AT MINE RACISM CLAIM<I> (The Citizen)</I><BR>
Anglo American last night denied claims by NUM of racist time-keeping practices at its Elandsrand gold mine.<BR><P>
MINEWORKERS PROTEST <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
Five thousand mineworkers went underground at Anglo American's Elandsrand gold mine yesterday, but did not report to work stations, NUM says.<BR><P>
