<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 18 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </b></h1></b></center></center>
<BR><P>



<FONT SIZE=5><B><Center>SPECIAL ADDITION TO DAILY MINING NEWS -- OUTCOME OF ENQUIRY INTO 1995 VAAL REEFS MINE DISASTER. </Center></B></FONT><I>[Other reports can be requested from the Editor]</I><BR><P>
    JOHANNESBURG April 18 SOUTH AFRICAN PRESS ASSOC.<BR>
   JUDGE SAYS VAAL REEFS SHOULD BE CHARGED FOR MINING DISASTER<BR>
   An inquest and inquiry into a disater at Vaal Reefs gold mine which
killed 104 people last year on Thursday recommended the mining company
be prosecuted for culpable homicide.<BR>
   Justice Ramon Leon who headed the inquiry and joint inquest into
the disaster in No 2 Shaft near Orkney on May 10 last year also found
acts and/or ommissions by five employees amounted to culpable homicide.<BR>
   Delivering his report in Johannesburg, Leon said the Vaal Reefs
Exploration and Mining Company was liable for prosecution for culpable
homicide.<BR>
   He said the mine manager at the time, I K Muir, had been negligent
in his duties but this did not amount to culpable homicide.<BR>
   Soon after the report was delivered National Union of Mineworkers
president James Motlatsi said Leon's judgment was straightforward and
had clearly found the mine guilty.<BR>
   He said the mineworkers named in the report as being liable for
prosecution for culpable homicide had been following instructions.<BR>
   "In the mining industry the worker has to follow instructions at
all times even if there is danger ...," he said. "He has no option but
to report the faults at a later stage.<BR>
   "We are going to wait for the outcome of the criminal charge
against the company and we will then lodge a civil case where the
families of victims will be included."<BR>
   Motlatsi said he hoped by court action to obtain more compensation
for the families of the deceased.<BR>
   In a report in terms of the Minerals Act released at the same time
as the Leon report, the chief regional mining engineer for the Free
State region, A J McKenzie, said the five workers operating a
locomotive on the day of the accident were responsible for culpable
homicide.<BR>
   The 104 miners were killed when the locomotive was sent driverless
down the shaft, crushing a cage lift carrying the miners to their work
stations.<BR>
   McKenzie, who was an assessor in the Leon inquiry, said Vaal Reefs
were liable for prosecution for culpable homicide.<BR>
   Leon named the five as Ndwandwe Frank Khoza, Victor Cako, Mlindeli
Quluba, Hendrik Jacobus Wood Sr and Marthinus Wessel Jansen van
Rensburg. He found they had contravened Minerals Act regulations.<BR>
   Leon described the disaster as "a dreadful accident" resulting in
"terrible deaths."<BR>
   In a summary of the events on the day of the accident he said a man
carriage and a locomotive had passed through a prohibited area on 56
level and plunged down No 2 shaft. At the same time a cage carrying 104
workers had been travelling down the shaft.<BR>
   "The man carrriage and the locomotive fell down, striking steelwork
in the shaft, both vehicles breaking into several parts."<BR>
   He said some parts had collided with the cage, detaching it from
its cables and causing it to fall to the bottom of the shaft.<BR>
   Dealing with the cause of the accident the Leon report said it
could not be attributed to a single cause but a series of events caused
by negligence.<BR>
   These included;<BR>
   -- The locomotive had been standing in a prohibited area;<BR>
   -- The locomotive's electic circuit had been damaged to such an
extent that it would run away at the slightest touch;<BR>
   -- The driver had continued to operate the locomotive despite it
being defective;<BR>
   -- No inspections had been made of the locomotive before use; and<BR>
   -- The absence of an adequate safety device to prevent the
locomotive entering the shaft.<BR>
   The report said there were also many indirect causes that had
contributed to the accident. These were;<BR>
   -- Failure to comply with the procedures for the parking of
locomotives;<BR>
   -- The poor condition of the electrical components of the
locomotive;<BR>
   -- Failure to monitor the maintenance of electrical connections;
and<BR>
   -- The need for better communication between staff and the clearer
demarcation of duties.<BR>
   Leon said in his report there appeared to be a perception among
miners they should accept the industry was inherently dangerous. He
said even senior managers had put forward this argument.<BR>
   "The evidence, however, suggests that his perspection is erroneous.
The accident of 10 May 1995 was not caused by inherent problems such as
the instability in the rock mass but by poor practice and controls."<BR>
   He said it was possible to improve the situation through active
intervention.<BR>
   A similar accident had ocurred in 1992. A locomotive had fallen
down a shaft but not caused any deaths. This should have alerted the
relevant officials of the possibility of a recurrence.<BR>
   "No proper steps were taken to install an adequate safety device
which would have prevented this accident."<BR>
   Steps had ultimately been taken, but in a "leisurely fashion".<BR>
   The report will be submitted to the attorney-general for his
decisions on the prosecution of the mine and the employees named in the
findings.<BR><P><P>
   
   OFFICIALS TRIED TO HIDE EVIDENCE ABOUT MINE DISASTER<BR>
   Soon after a locomotive plunged down a mine shaft killing 104
people a group of mine officials met at a midnight meeting to try to
conceal evidence about the dangerous condition of the locomotive, it
was revealed in a report on the disaster released on Thursday.<BR>
   The report is the result of a joint inquest and inquiry into the
disaster at Vaal Reefs gold mine on May 10 last year, headed by Justice
Ramon Leon.<BR>
   The report said that shortly aftr the accident electrician Nwandwe
Khoza had told a a group of mine officials the locomotive had been in
poor working order.<BR>
   At a midnight meeting the officials conspired to withhold the
information about the poor condition of electrical circuits on the
locomotive.<BR>
   "Those gentlemen concealed this information from senior management,
the police and from officials of the Department of Mineral and Energy
Affairs," the report said.<BR>
   "While such conduct was undoubtedly reprehensible, it does not show
any that of those present, save for Khoza, had knowledge of this before
the accident."<BR>
   Leon recommended in the report that Khoza be charged with culpable
homicide.<BR>
   He said the locomotive had been in a highly dangerous state at the
time of the accident as a result of Khoza's actions. He had known the
locomotive's electrical circuits were "bridged out" and it would run
away at the slightest touch of the control lever.<BR>
   "He knew it was highly dangerous but sent this potentially lethal
instrument back into the work place ... .<BR>
   "Such a person would appreciate that that the locomotive could well
behave in a highly dangerous, erratic and uncontrollable fashion and
would therefore see the possibility of death."<BR><P><P>

<B>OTHER NEWS OF THE DAY: </B><BR>
MARKET PLAYING YO-YO WITH THE RAND <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The market continued playing yo-yo with the rand yesterday, frustrated by the lack of action on exchange controls.  Finance Minister Trevor Manuel, in London on the first day of his international roadshow, said he might be in a better position at the end of the month to take a view on exchange controls.  The market, still smarting from Manuel's defiant stance on Tuesday, was not impressed.<BR>
<B><I>... meanwhile ...</I></B><BR>
POLICY UNCERTAINTY UNDERLIES RAND'S FALL - IMF<BR> 
WASHINGTON - Uncertainties about government's economic policies were behind the continuing depreciation of the rand, the IMF said in its latest World Economic Outlook, released yesterday.<BR>
<B><I>... and the Afrikaans language daily, Beeld, reports ...</I></B><BR>
MANUEL TO LOOK AT EXCHANGE CONTROL AT END APRIL<BR>
The South African Government should be in a better position to decide over further lifting of exchange control at the end of this month, Finance Minister Trevor Manuel said in London yesterday.<BR><P>
CYRIL WILL NOT LEAD NAIL-JOHNNIC TALKS<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
African National Congress secretary-general Cyril Ramaphosa said yesterday he would not lead talks to buy Anglo American's stake in industrial holding group Johnnic.<BR><P>
IMF PREDICTS STRONGER GLOBAL ECONOMY <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The world economy, underpinned by controlled inflation, low interest rates and stable currencies, should see solid growth of about 4% this year and next, the International Monetary Fund predicted yesterday.<BR><P>
SA TRADE CERTAIN TO BE SCORCHED BY CHINESE DRAGON <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Companies in SA, and indeed the world over, are flocking to the People's Republic of China to invest, to trade and to do business.  This in spite of the fact that most, if not all, of the traditional indicators which point to potential investment success are missing.  Indeed, with specific reference to our own trade with mainland China, SA could find itself in a most disadvantaged position.<BR><P>
HARTEBEESTFONTEIN MINE IS ANGLOVAAL'S STAR PERFORMER<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglovaal Minerals' Hartebeestfontein gold mine reported a 75% increase in taxed profit in the March quarter, offsetting poorer showings by other group mines.<BR><P>
NICKEL PROJECT TO BENEFIT GENCOR<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Gencor has earned a 50% interest in an Australian nickel project after spending $5m on exploration, boosting its chances of securing an offshore nickel resource.<BR><P>
GOLD INDEX SLIPS AS BULLION FALLS <I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
Golds London afternoon fix of $391,10 an ounce yesterday, the lowest since January, pushed the JSEs all gold index 19,4 points lower to 1837,7.<BR><P>
FUND LOOKS TO MINING AND CYCLICALS<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
Cyclical stocks and certain mining shares should offer better returns than industrials this year, Denzil Newman, a fund manager at Syfrets Managed Assets, said yesterday.<BR><P>
EU TO RULE ON LONRHO/GENCOR DEAL BY END APRIL <I>(Internet)</I><BR>
BRUSSELS - The European Commission is to rule either next week or the week after on the merger of British-based Lonrhos and Gencors South African platinum interests, Commission officials said.<BR><P>
ARGENTINE GOLD RUSH TO BRING JOBS, CASH <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - A mounting copper and gold rush is likely to net a tax bonanza and create thousands of new jobs for an economy suffering crippling unemployment, Argentinas Industry Minister said on Wednesday.<BR><P>
FOREIGNERS SELL STOCKS <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Foreigners were once again net sellers of South African stocks on Tuesday, the Stock Exchange Association has announced.<BR><P>
NEW ACT NEARLY COMPLETE<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The Parliamentary Standing Committee on Mineral and Energy Affairs says it has almost completed its work on the proposed Mine Health and Safety Act.<I> [The Johannesburg daily, Sowetan, ran a story today claiming the issue had already been resolved and the controversial clause had remained intact. This is not true. The Standing Committee is expected to meet later today and, hopefully, resolve the remaining two outstanding issues. For further details click <A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/releases/safebill.htm">here </A> - <A HREF="mailto:lkriel@bullion.org.za">Editor</A>]</I><BR><P>
RAIN HITS LINDUM <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The heavy rain prevented opencast gold mine Lindum Reefs from benefiting from the stronger gold price during the first quarter of this year.  Rain disrupted mining operations and led to a drop in gold production from 408kg to 209kg.<BR><P>
RATING FOR ANGLOVAAL <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Credit-rating agency Republic Ratings has given Anglovaal short-term A1+ (the highest possible) and long-term AA credit ratings.<BR><P>
MODDER PROFITS UP A FIFTH <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Consolidated Modderfontein recorded an increase of 20,8% in its net profit, now up to R2,02-million, in the three months to the end of March, despite a 6,2% rise in operating costs to R43 705 per kilogram.<BR><P>
FAR-REACHING CONSEQUENCES OF ANGLO INTEREST IN LONRHO<I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The transaction whereby Anglo American obtained an option to buy Lonrho CE Dieter Bock's interest in this company has far-reaching consequences not only for Africa, but also for South Africa, says Frankel Polack [sic] analyst Ross Gardiner.  He says Anglo is being restricted by limited investment possibilities in South Africa and has to make use of such opportunities that are large enough to have an effect on its final profit.<BR><P>
DE BEERS & RUSSIA RENEW TALKS <I>(The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Russia's biggest diamond producer, Almazy Rossii Sakha, and De Beers renewed discussions yesterday aimed at working out a new marketing deal for Russian stones, De Beers' officials say.<BR><P>


