<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 17 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </b></h1></b></center></center>
<BR><P>

STATE ADVISERS WATER DOWN BILL ON MINING SAFETY<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The controversial proposal in the draft <A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/releases/safebill.htm">Mine Health and Safety Bill</A>, which places the onus on mine owners and managers to prove that their negligence was not the cause of a mining accident, has been watered down by the state's law advisers.<BR><P>
METLIFE MAY PLAY ROLE IN JOHNNIC DEAL<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Sankorp, New African Investments Ltd.(Nail) and their jointly owned insurance operation, Metropolitan Life (Metlife), are discussing plans to let Nail use Metlife as its vehicle to pursue Anglo American's stake in industrial holdings group, Johnnic.<BR><P>
I WILL NOT BE BULLIED, WARNS FINANCE MINISTER <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel yesterday responded fiercely to critics who accused him of dragging his heels on easing exchange controls, by saying he would not be bullied.<BR><P>
HEDGE STOCKS RALLY AS RAND FALLS <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Commodity and rand hedge stocks rallied on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange yesterday as the beleaguered SA currency sank to yet another record low against the dollar.<BR><P>
<B>GOLD FIELDS OF S.A. RESULTS:</B><BR>
DRIES ADDS LUSTRE TO GOLD FIELDS <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold Fields of SA lifted after-tax profit 11% to R298m for the March quarter after an improved gold price and an outstanding performance from East Driefontein mine, Gold executive director Alan Munro said yesterday.<BR>
NORTHAM BOUNCES BACK AS COST CUTS BOOST PROFIT<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold Fields of SA 's Northam Platinum reported a profit of R5,8m in the March quarter, eclipsing the previous quarter's R22,7m loss, after cost of sales was reined in significantly, Coal, Base Metals and Platinum executive director Peter Janisch said yesterday.<BR>
WHY G.F.N. RECORDS ONLY A SMALL PROFIT<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
The fall in the international copper price, the mining of weaker ore and greater expenditure on exploration led to Gold Fields Namibia only just showing a profit in the three months to the end of March.<BR>
RAIN HITS G.F. COAL <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The high rainfall in the three months to the end of March affected the activities of Gold Fields Coal badly because underground working areas were under water, there was damage to property and equipment, and pumping costs led to abnormal expenditure.  The profit after tax for the past three months amounted to R8,72-million, as against R12,87-million for the previous three months.<BR><P>

DE BEERS IN COURT ON FRIDAY<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) is to take De Beers to the Industrial Court this Friday on charges on unlawful and unfair practice for allegedly breaching employment contracts at the Venetia and Namaqualand diamond mines.<BR><P>
GULF WIDENING BETWEEN WORKERS, MANAGERS<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The National Union of Metalworkers of SA (Numsa) officials warned yesterday that the widening gulf between workers and management was developing into a major crisis for SA industry.<BR><P>
DONORS ASKED TO FACILITATE DIALOGUE <I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
World Bank vice-president for Africa, Callisto Madavo, has called on the donor community to facilitate dialogue between member states and to back growing regional partnerships.<BR><P>
ASHANTI WELCOMES ANGLO INVOLVEMENT<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Ashanti Gold Fields, viewed as Anglo American's main target in its moves to build up a stake in Lonrho, has cautiously welcomed the prospect of Anglo playing a greater role in its affairs.<BR><P>
BRIGHT FUTURE FOR DIAMOND SALES<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The outlook for diamond retail sales was good, with consumer demand for diamond jewellery having set another record last year, De Beers chairman Julian Ogilvie Thompson said in the diamond producer's annual report.<BR>
<I><B>... and ...</B></I><BR>
AGREEMENT WITH RUSSIA ENSURES STABILITY - DE BEERS <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The agreement signed by the De Beers group recently with Russia over the marketing of that country's diamonds will play a major role in ensuring stability in the diamond market, De Beers group chairman Julian Ogilvie-Thompson said in his annual review yesterday.<BR><P>
RECEIVER ASSURES INVESTORS ON RETROACTIVE LEGISLATION<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
The SA Revenue Service (SARS) yesterday assured investors that legislation to tax interest on the accrual basis will not be made effective retroactively.<BR><P>
LONRHO MERGER MAY BE BLOCKED<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
LONDON - The European commission would almost certainly block the proposed merger of Impala Platinum and Lonrho's Western Platinum, Brussels officials said.<BR><P>
DESPITE INDICATORS, DOLLAR'S RISE IS NOT EXPECTED TO LAST  <I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
LONDON - A fuss in the United States's stock market has distracted attention from the behaviour of the country's currency, and confounded many economic forecasters who were convinced that the dollar would rise for most of this year.<BR><P>
AMERICANS UNCERTAIN ABOUT POLITICS IN SA <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
Analysts in New York expect the sharp fall in the rand to continue, and say the present economic and political uncertainty in South Africa will lead to large amounts of speculative foreign capital being withdrawn.<BR><P>
NEW TRADE UNION FEDERATION ON THE WAY <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
A new federation of 14 trades unions, the Federation of Independent and Public Service Trade Unions (Fipstu) is to be established in Johannesburg on 28 May.  Fipstu was initially going to open membership only to public services, but under pressure it was decided to allow construction workers, mineworkers and others into it as well.<BR><P>
GOLD MINE MAY BE CHARGED OVER RADIOACTIVE WASTE <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
It is reported from Welkom in Free State province that a gold mine (which is not named in the report) is facing legal proceedings after tons of radioactive waste metal, allegedly sold to businesses in the city, were confiscated by the Police.<BR><P>
RUSSIAN GEM LEAKS PLUGGED:  DE BEERS<I> (The Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
De Beers said yesterday the flood of Russian diamonds leaking on to world markets had virtually dried up recently, ahead of a new deal between Russia and the De Beers CSO coming into force.<BR><P>
ANGLO SIGNS $1bn LOAN AGREEMENT <I>(The Citizen)</I><BR>
Anglo American and its wholly-owned subsidiary ARH Limited SA have signed a $1-billion multi-currency loan agreement with a number of banks.  ARH is Anglo's Luxembourg-based subsidiary through which the group's non-diamond interests outside South Africa are held.<BR><P>
