<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 16 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </b></h1></b></center></center>
<BR><P>

LABOUR VIES FOR HEFTY STAKE IN JOHNNIC <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
South Africa's largest trade unions are aiming to pull together R2bn of the funds needed to buy Anglo American's stake in industrial holding group Johnnic.<BR><P>
ST HELENA FACES CLOSURE, SAYS GENGOLD <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gengold has warned that its St Helena mine in the Free State province faces closure with a loss of 4 000 jobs, despite the higher price of gold.<BR><P>
GOLD PRICE GIVES GENGOLD A BOOST IN MARCH QUARTER<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gengold boosted bottom-line income 81% to R51,5m in the March quarter, benefiting from an increased gold price and a reduction in overall working costs, the company said yesterday.<BR><P>
CHANGES ENHANCE PROVINCES' POWERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Major amendments have been made in the fifth draft of the new constitution published yesterday, enhancing provincial powers in relation to those of central government.<BR><P>
MANUEL TRIES IN VAIN TO BOOST AILING RAND<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel tried in vain again yesterday to provide a shot in the arm for the rand as the ailing currency set yet another record low against the US dollar.<BR><P>
SUNDAY WORK TO DOMINATE TALKS<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The introduction of full calendar operations (Fulco) in the SA mining industry seems set to dominate discussions this year as the parties grapple with formulating a common approach to the removal of the Sunday work restriction from legislation.<BR><P>
KEY CHANGES IN GOVT RELATIONS WITH DONORS<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Deputy Finance Minister Gill Marcus announced far-reaching changes yesterday in government's relations with the donor community as well as in intergovernmental financial relations ... <I>[and] </I>... has called on its partners in the international donor community to generate higher levels of economic growth to address problems of poverty and underdevelopment in SA.<BR><P>
TWO ZIMBABWEAN FIRMS WIN LICENCE TO BUY GOLD <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
HARARE - Zimbabwe's central bank, until recently the sole legal buyer of gold in the country, has, for the first time, given approval for private companies to purchase the metal produced within the country.<BR><P>
DIAMOND DEAL A SPARKLING SUCCESS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Namibian government and De Beers, partners in the new diamond giant Namdeb, are satisfied with performance and progress 15 months after the state bought a 50% stake in De Beers' Consolidated Diamond Mines.<BR><P>
ENDING THE RAND LINK<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The rand is likely to be declared non-legal tender as part of Namibia's plan to strengthen its own dollar and assert economic independence from SA.<BR><P>
SMALL-SCALE MINING LEADS HOPES FOR RECOVERY<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Mining, once the mainstay of the Namibian economy, has been in decline for years, but new interest in especially small-scale mining has prompted hopes of a recovery.<BR><P>
PRIVATE SECTOR HELPS GOVT PREPARE RESPONSE TO EU OFFER<I> (Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The private sector has set aside resources to help government prepare for upcoming negotiations with the European Union on a trade agreement, a National Economic Development and Labour Council (Nedlac) spokesman said yesterday.<BR><P>
ZAMBIA MAY TURN TO SA FOR COPPER EXPORTS<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
LONDON - Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines would ship more copper from Beira in Mozambique and SA ports if the Tanzania-Zambia Railway Authority strike threatened exports further, a London-based source at the company said.<BR><P>
LONRHO INQUIRY IS FREE OF 'FEAR OR FAVOUR'<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
BRUSSELS - EU officials said this week they were operating without fear or favour in investigating the planned merger between the platinum interests of Lonrho and Gencor.<BR><P>
SA RAND HAS FURTHER TO FALL - US EXPERTS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
NEW YORK - The SA rand, which slumped to a record low of 4.22 to the dollar on Monday, is likely to fall further as political and economic jitters continue to fuel an exodus of speculative money, traders and analysts said.<BR><P>
ASHTON PREFERS DIRECT MARKETING <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
MELBOURNE - Ashton Mining Ltd said on Tuesday direct marketing of its diamond production was a more acceptable alternative to renewing its contract with De Beers' Central Selling Organisation.<BR><P>
E DAGGA INCOME IS SHARPLY UP <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
East Dagga Mines posted net pre-tax income of R9,2-million for the quarter to the end of March - almost 40% up on the previous quarter (R5,6-million) in spite of production having been hit by heavy rains.<BR><P>
NUM PROPOSALS ON HOUSING NOT INTENTIONALLY SOCIALISTIC <I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers' proposals on housing are not put forth to reflect a socialist state system, but if this is what they amount to, so be it, NUM executive committee member Frans Mahlangu said yesterday.<BR><P>
DISPUTE ON R9m MINERAL RIGHTS<I> (Sowetan, Jhb)</I><BR>
Police are investigating a mineral rights dispute between two factions of a small North West community arising from R9-million royalties paid by vanadium mine Vametco which is mining the area.  The factionalism is so serious that it is threatening to shut down the multi-million rand mine.<BR><P>


