<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 15 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </b></h1></b></center></center>
<BR><P>

ANGLO TARGETS MORE LONRHO MINING ASSETS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Anglo American has positioned itself to bid for Lonrho's mining assets following confirmation at the weekend that it effectively controls nearly 29% of the UK conglomerate.<BR><P>
DEEP DIVISIONS OVER SA ECONOMIC POLICY<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Deep divisions between business, labour and government on South Africa's economic policy are clear in Business SA's (BSA) policy document, which will be negotiated at the National Economic Development and Labour Council (Nedlac).<BR><P>
ELIAS LINKS APPOINTED SA'S NEW AMBASSADOR TO THE EU<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Finance Department chief director Elias "Elty" Links has been appointed SA's new ambassador to the European Union in Brussels to spearhead the drive to free up European markets to SA products.<BR><P>
GOVT, AID DONORS PLAN CONFERENCE<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Government would hold a two-day conference next week in a bid to get the international donor community to buy into its growth and development strategy, sources said at the weekend.<BR><P>
MANUEL'S OUTBURST SHOWS RACISM IS STILL FEARED - DEEP DOWN<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
At some stage during his torrid first week in office, new Finance Minister Trevor Manuel asked angrily whether the markets lacked confidence in him because he was black.  The answer is unclear.  But the fact that he asked says important things about the key unsettled, and unspoken, issue in our new democracy.<BR><P>
TIME FOR SA BUSINESSES TO CONSIDER GOING GLOBAL<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
In light of the accelerated phase-down of General Export Incentive Scheme (GEIS) benefits, SA businesses will be forced to consider ways in which to recover this lost revenue.  The potential international tax planning has for boosting a company's bottom line has thus become increasingly relevant.<BR><P>
MINORCO HAS FIVE-SEGMENT CONSOLIDATION PLAN<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
Just six years ago Minorco had a huge cash pile, a strategy and very little else.  Its transition to a natural resources group of substance has been, if not sudden, then certainly rapid.  And while the rate of acquisitions may moderate compared with the hectic pace of the past two years, the group has plans which will consolidate its position in its five operating segments.<BR><P>
GOLD PRICE EXPECTED TO BOOST MINES' QUARTERLIES<I> (Business Day)</I><BR>
The gold industry would show the benefit of a higher gold price and operational improvements in results for the March quarter, despite damage inflicted by public holidays at the start of the period, analysts said at the weekend.<BR><P>
DUBAI GOLD AND SILVER DEMAND HOLDING UP IN APRIL <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
DUBAI - Indian and Pakistani gold demand in the Gulf re-export centre of Dubai is firm because of flat bullion prices, but demand may ebb after May when gold purchases for the main marriage season peak, Dubai gold traders said.<BR><P>
FREEPORT GRANTS ONE PERCENT OF INCOME TO IRIANESE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
JAKARTA - Freeport-McMoRan Copper and Gold Inc said it would set aside one percent of its annual revenue, or R15m, to help local people in Indonesia's Irian Jaya province, Antara news agency reported on Sunday. Freeport closed its mine in Tembagapura, 3 000km east of Jakarta, for 2½ days in March after tribespeople rampaged through the town and nearby Timika, attacking buildings and a gas store.<BR><P>
QUEENSLAND THREATENS NEW LAWS TO FORCE MINE GO-AHEAD <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BRISBANE - The new conservative government in Australia's northern state of Queensland said on Sunday it may bring in laws to force the go-ahead of a stalled A$1b (US$790m) zinc project in the face of aboriginal objections.<BR><P>
BSA WANTS TO SPEED UP PRIVATISATION<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
Privatisation must be speeded up.  By proper regulation, the Government can ensure that after privatisation the poor gain access to its benefits, Business South Africa says in its discussion document submitted to Nedlac on Friday.<BR><P>
SA's HUGE DIAMOND WILL GRACE CROWN <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The world's biggest diamond, the Golden Jubilee, discovered in the Premier mine 10 years ago, is soon to grace the sceptre of King Bhumibol Adulyadej of Thailand.<BR><P>
ANGLO's FIVE SHAFTS GET NEW LEASE OF LIFE<I> (Sowetan Business, Jhb)</I><BR>
Production at Anglo American's five shafts which were threatened with closure earlier this year has improved, but it is not certain yet whether they are out of danger.<BR><P>
NUM's SCHEME TO HELP RETRENCHED WORKERS<I> (Sowetan Business)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers' (NUM) job creation branch has launched a marula nuts venture as part of a job-creation programme for those worst affected by mine retrenchments.<BR><P>
WEAK RAND TO BOOST GOLD PROFITS<I> (Finansies & Tegniek, 12/4/96)</I><BR>
With the rand gold price breaking one record after another these last few weeks, good profit increases are expected for marginal mines in particular.<BR><P>
