<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 12 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </b></h1></b></center></center>
<BR><P>

RAND GYRATES AS FOREIGNERS CALL THE SHOTS<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Reserve Bank is investigating the extent to which foreign players are moving the local currency market.  This was confirmed yesterday as the rand gyrated in a confused market amid talk that foreign speculators were calling the shots.<BR><P>
FOOD PRICES COMBAT PRODUCER INFLATION <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A drop in food prices pushed producer inflation below market expectations to 6,3% in February - its lowest figure since April 1994 - compared to 7,2% in January, figures from the Central Statistical Service showed yesterday.<BR><P>
CONFERENCE COULD HELP TO REVERSE AFRICAN FATIGUE<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
South Africa, the host of this years UN conference on trade and development, could play a pivotal role in reversing 'African fatigue', Deputy Foreign Affairs Minister Aziz Pahad said yesterday.<BR><P> 
SA COMMITTED TO OPEN MARKETPLACE<I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
South Africa committed itself to working towards opening international markets and stimulating development at the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development during a media conference yesterday.<BR><P>
ERWIN HAPPY WITH MANUELS POLICIES<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
New Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin pledged yesterday to continue on the path laid by his predecessor in dismantling tariff barriers and sharpening South Africas global competitiveness.<BR><P>
BUSINESS, GOVERNMENT STILL WRANGLING OVER BUDGET CUTS<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Government and business are continuing their long-running wrangle over the planned cut in export subsidies, with no solution in sight, sources close to the National Economic, Development and Labour Council say.<BR><P>
TRADE AND INDUSTRY DID GIVE ADVANCE WARNING OF GEIS CUT <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Business Day's comment of 10 April accuses the Trade and Industry Department of being thoughtless, of failing to provide advance warning of the GEIS cut and neglecting to discuss the matter with business.  These accusations are provocative, factually incorrect and grossly misleading, Zavareh Rustomjee writes.<BR><P>
THE HIDDEN HAND OF GEIS <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
So far there has been little response from the JSE to news that the Trade and Industry Department intends to reduce the general export incentive scheme (GEIS) allowances. <BR><P>
FOREIGN BANKS EXPECTED TO GROW<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Foreign banks in South Africa expected to more than double their net income by the turn of the century, but this would not see them entering the retail market, said a Price Waterhouse study released yesterday.<BR><P>
NATALS FOUR-YEAR PLAN FOR GROWTH IS LAUNCHED<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
KwaZulu-Natal Economic Affairs and Tourism Minister Jacob Zuma yesterday officially launched the provinces growth and development strategy for the next four years, aimed at achieving high employment and a balance between growth and distribution.<BR><P>
ESKOM FACES HIDDEN COSTS IN LOW PRICE BID<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Eskoms aim to provide South Africa with the cheapest electricity in the world had hidden costs which would have a huge effect on the future environment, according to a study under the Cosatu-linked industrial strategy project.<BR><P>
BUSINESS URGED TO HELP CREATE JOBS<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
New Africa Investments Limited chairman Ntatho Motlana says that the business community will have to create jobs and help the Government fulfil its promise to the millions of South Africans outside formal employment.<BR><P>
RANDSLIDE!<I> (Mail & Guardian)</I><BR>
As the rand continued to plumb new depths this week, there was a growing sense among economists that the negative sentiment had gone far enough.<BR><P>
INDIAN OBSESSION WITH GOLD PUSHES DEMAND <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BOMBAY - In India, the land of myth and myriad gods, gold is an obsession, deep-rooted in Indias mythology, religious rites and its very psyche.  Indians obsession with gold is pushing up its demand, said bullion analyst Madhusudhan Daga.<BR><P>
GOLD-DIGGERS STEAL WEATHERMENS MERCURY  <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
ACCRA - Ghanas weather stations are under threat from thieves thought to be illegal gold miners who steal instruments in search of mercury to process gold ore.<BR><P>
FOURTEEN DEAD IN CHINA MINE FLOOD <I>(Internet)</I><BR>
BEIJING - Fourteen miners died in a coal mine flood in northern Chinas Hebei province, Chinese officials said yesterday.<BR><P>
MANILA FILES CHARGES AGAINST MINE OFFICIALS<I>(Internet)</I><BR>
MANILA - The Philippine government filed criminal charges on Thursday against five officials of partly-Canadian owned Marcopper Mining Corp. in connection with a massive mine waste spill on the island of Marinduque.<BR><P>
GOLDEN SHAMROCK TO MERGE WITH ASHANTI<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Australia's Golden Shamrock Mines has announced plans to merge with Ghana-based Ashanti Goldfields to create the biggest gold mine in Africa outside South Africa.  Under the merger Ashanti, which is the biggest gold producer in Ghana with annual output of nearly one million ounces, will take control of GSM through a share swap.  Based on current and expected gold production over the next three years, the merged Ashanti-GSM group would have a gold output of nearly two million ounces by the year 2000, making it one of the world's largest gold mines.<BR><P>
BSA TO SEND ITS PROPOSALS TO NEDLAC TODAY <I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The proposals from Business South Africa for economic growth and development have been completed and will be sent to Nedlac today.  The content of the proposals will be made available to the media on Monday.<BR><P>
GENCOR STILL INVESTIGATING VIABILITY OF NEW PLANT<I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
It is reported from East London that Gencor is still busy conducting viability studies over the opening of a zinc plant in the Eastern Cape at a cost of R1,5-billion.<BR><P>
EERSTELING RECORDS LARGE LOSS<I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Eersteling Gold Mining Company recorded a net loss of 
R4,826-million in the 18 months to 31 December, as against a profit of R661 000 in the previous 12 months.<BR><P>
GFN SPENDING MORE ON EXPLORATION IN '96<I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The financing of exploration by Gold Fields Namibia will increase significantly this year, Mr R L Robertson says in his chairman's review.<BR><P>
BETTER RESULTS PREDICTED FOR GOLD MINES<I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Analysts predict that the profits of South African gold mines in the first quarter of this year will be some 23% higher than in the last quarter of last year.<BR><P>
TRAINING OF 50 NEW MINE INSPECTORS PROGRESSING WELL<I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The 50 mine inspectors being trained by the Department of Mineral and Energy Affairs at a cost of R3-million have already completed three months of practical training.<BR><P>
HOT SMOKE AS GROUND SINKS AWAY NEXT TO HOUSE <I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A huge sinkhole of a few hundred metres has appeared in Boksburg next to a house being leased from the J C Goldmine, formerly Primrose Goldmine.<BR><P>
EU TIGHT-LIPPED ON PLATINUM DEAL <I>(Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The European Commission declined to comment yesterday on reports that a merger of the platinum operations of Lonrho and Gencor may be blocked.<BR><P> 



