<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 11 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </b></h1></b></center></center>
<BR><P>

STALS HAD BEEN READY TO EASE FOREX<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Former Finance Minister Chris Liebenberg and his successor Trevor Manuel had discussed Reserve Bank proposals for easing exchange controls at a meeting before Liebenberg's resignation, a Finance spokesman confirmed yesterday.<BR><P>
CONFIDENCE INDEX AT SIX-MONTH LOW <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The rand's spiral and growing evidence that SA's economic recovery had suffered a relapse bruised business confidence last month, the SA Chamber of Business said yesterday.<BR><P>
BID TO END WAR OF WORDS IN NEDLAC<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Nedlac conveners met yesterday to discuss a way to end the acrimonious debate between labour and business on economic policy and to begin negotiations in earnest.  Formal negotiations in Nedlac have failed to get off the ground, while relations between labour and business soured after a war of words on economic policy.<BR><P>
BIDS INVITED FOR R1BN MAPUTO CORRIDOR<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Transport Department this week kick-started the R1-billion Maputo corridor process after inviting the private sector to bid for the development of the toll road between Witbank and Maputo.<BR><P>
INVESTORS SEEN CHANGING TO MINING, COMMODITIES<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The rand's slide would encourage investors to change to mining-related and commodity stocks, with the weakening currency boosting earnings of stocks with high exposure to exports, Old Mutual senior portfolio manager Arnold Shapiro said yesterday.<BR><P>
AUSTRALIAN DIAMOND MINE THREATENS TO BYPASS CSO<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Australian diamond producer Argyle increased pressure on De Beers yesterday, warning that it would go it alone on marketing unless the CSO gave it better terms.<BR><P>
RAND PARALYSIS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Currency market apprehensions are becoming self-fulfilling as the rand spirals down against hard currencies.  And as long as the Government continues to hesitate over the next stop in relaxing exchange controls, market sentiment will continue to outweigh logic, to the rand's detriment.<BR><P>
SPEED UP REFORMS TO ATTRACT INVESTORS<I> (Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A quicker pace of exchange-control reform could inspire increased foreign investment in SA, Aart de Jong, the senior vice-president of ABN Amro Bank, said yesterday.<BR><P>
US GOLD INDUSTRY FACING 'CRIPPLING' DELAYS - STUDY <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON.  A US gold industry sponsored report released on Wednesday charged that delays in securing necessary permits for gold mining threaten the long-term viability of the US gold industry.<BR><P>
NEW PLATINUM GROUP MAY BE STOPPED BY EU<I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
It looks as if the proposed amalgamation of the platinum interests of Lonrho and Gencor will not be realised because EU officials, who first have to approve the transaction, are opposed to it.<BR><P>
FOREIGNERS BUY SHARES<I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Despite the turmoil surrounding the rand last week, foreign investors were still net buyers of South African shares to the value of R146,3-million.<BR><P>
AMALIA STILL ENVISAGES DISTRIBUTIONS THIS YEAR<I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Amalia gold mine still plans the payment of a first interim dividend of 4c per share next month and a final dividend of 6c by November, the directors say in the annual report.<BR><P>
BEWARE OF EU TRADE DEAL, SA WARNED <I>(Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
South Africa's negotiators should be given the political space to reject a free trade agreement with the European Union, whose proposals currently did not benefit South Africa and her neighbours, a top EU official and a European parliamentarian said in Cape Town yesterday.<BR><P>
LONRHO'S AFRICA SWEETENER SPURS ANGLO'S INTEREST<I>(Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Anglo American's drive to acquire a more substantial stake in multinational conglomerate Lonrho Plc is driven by more than the enticing lure of Lonrho's mining interests.  Anglo sent a clear signal last year of its aim to concentrate on Africa when it hived off other international operations into Minorco.<BR><P>


