<BR><P>

US RATES FEARS A FRESH BLOW TO SA MARKETS<I>(Business Day, Jhb.1)</I><BR>
Fears that the next move in US interest rates would be higher dealt a new blow to SAs embattled markets yesterday, as the dollar strengthened and SAs bond yields followed the US market higher.<BR><P>
ANGLO NOW OWNS 10% OF LONRHO <I>(Business Day, Jhb.1)</I><BR>
Lonrho shares worth more than R715-million were traded on the JSE yesterday morning as sources close to Anglo American said the corporation had amassed a 10% stake in the UK conglomerate and was looking for more.<BR><P>
ANGLO POISED FOR BIGGER LONRHO STAKE:  ANALYST<I>(Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Anglo American was setting its sights on a 30% stake in Lonrho Plc's mining interests when they are unravelled from the group's industrial assets, analysts say.<BR><P>
NEW SAFETY BODY TO ADVISE GENCOR <I>(Business Day, Jhb.1)</I><BR>
In what has been hailed as a bold initiative from labour and a first in the mining industry, Gencors board of directors has appointed a subcommittee which includes labour representation to advise the board on health, safety and environmental issues.<BR><P>
GEIS MOVE APPROVED<I>(Business Day, Jhb.1)</I><BR>
The major labour federations, Cosatu and the National Council of Trade Unions, yesterday threw their weight behind government plans to cut export subsidies available under the controversial general export incentive scheme.<BR><P>
SYFRETS EXPERT PREDICTS GROWTH OF 4% THIS YEAR<I>(Business Day, Jhb.1)</I><BR>
The economy should grow at close to 4% in 1996 despite slower growth in a number of the main economic sectors, Syfrets chief economist Peter Hilsenrath said yesterday.<BR><P>
GREEN PAPER TO BE TABLED ON EMPLOYMENT EQUITY<I>(Business Day, Jhb.1)</I><BR>
A green paper on employment equity, expected to be tabled in Parliament on 25 April, could act as a mechanism to achieve organisational transformation to create a climate for employment equity.<BR><P>
RUSSIA NEEDS $6BN, KEY LAW TO BOOST GOLD OUTPUT<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Russia needs to invest about $6-billion in its tarnished gold industry to boost output 45% by 2000, and it hopes to attract some of the cash from abroad, senior government officials said on Tuesday.<BR><P>
INDONESIA PLANS TO REVIEW MINING CONTRACT RULES <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
JAKARTA.  Indonesia said on Monday it was planning to review mining contracts in order to control big operations in Indonesia following riots at the giant PT Freeport Indonesia gold and copper mine in March.<BR><P>
INTEREST REDUCED<I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gold Fields of South Africa has reduced its interest in the Tarkwa gold concession in Ghana to 70% by allowing the Ghanaian government and the Social Security and National Insurance Trust in the country to increase their interest to 25%.<BR><P>
SA WANTS BIGGER GULF TRADE SLICE:  FW<I>(Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
South African Deputy President FW de Klerk yesterday said the country wanted a "bigger slice" of the Gulf region's $100-billion annual imports bill.<BR><P>
R3bn GOLD MINE VETOED OVER AUSTRALIAN BIRDLIFE<I>(Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Shares in Australian mining company North Ltd fell 2% yesterday after the New South Wales government vetoed a A$1,2-billion gold mine, citing concern for a surrounding wetland teeming with birdlife.<BR><P>


