<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 9 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>

ANC DRAWS UP NEW LABOUR RELATIONS CLAUSE <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The ANC had come up with a new labour relations clause in a bid to break the impasse over whether the new constitution should include a lockout clause, sources said yesterday.<BR><P>
ANGLO SEEKS BIGGER STAKE IN LONRHO <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Anglo American is seeking to secure an option on the 18,5% stake in Lonrho owned by Lonrho CE Dieter Bock.<BR><P>
GOVT FACES THREAT OF GEIS LAWSUITS<I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The government could face a barrage of lawsuits from business over its plans to phase out its general exports incentive scheme (GEIS) much faster than previously agreed to.<BR><P>
BANK FORCED TO REVERSE ITS HEDGING POLICY<I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Turmoil in the currency markets has dealt a blow to the Reserve Banks plans for freer forex markets, forcing it to intervene heavily in the forward cover market and to hold off on easing exchange controls.<BR><P>
DIAMOND MARKETING TALKS STILL UNDER WAY<I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Talks between De Beers and the Russian federation about a new diamond marketing agreement are taking longer than expected.<BR><P>
MINIMUM WAGE NO REMEDY FOR THE JOBLESS<I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Contrary to economists' revisionist claims, minimum wage legislation is, in fact, a foolish way to help low-income workers.  If the price of a commodity goes up, less of it will be demanded.<BR><P>
ISCOR TIES UP $112M-A-YEAR CONTRACT FOR NICKEL SUPPLY<I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Iscor has tied up a long-term contract with an international trader to supply its Pretoria stainless steel plant with nickel worth about $112m a year.<BR><P>
RISE IN STEEL PRICE NOT JUSTIFIED <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Columbus Stainless was not convinced that a rise in stainless steel prices was justified, despite reported moves by European mills to force a 5% hike on the market, the company said last week.<BR><P>
RUSSIAN THREAT EXPECTED TO CAP PLATINUM PRICE<I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The platinum price was likely to spend most of the next four years languishing between $410/oz and $414/oz, hemmed in by the threat of Russian supplies, analysts said at the weekend.<BR><P>
WORK TO BEGIN ON ALUMINIUM PLANT<I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Site work on Tongaat-Huletts R2,5-billion aluminium rolling mill expansion in Maritzburg would begin in three months, the company said last week.<BR><P>
RAND LIKELY TO REMAIN UNDER PRESSURE <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Although consolidation in currency markets was likely over the next week, the rand would remain at a minimum of R4,00 to the dollar, analysts said on Thursday.<BR><P>
M3 MANIPULATION DISRUPTS MARKETS, SAYS ECONOMIST<I>(Business Times,Jhb.)</I><BR>
Inflation is in danger of returning to double digits by 1997 unless the Reserve Bank does something quick to arrest M0 money supply growth, says Richard Grant, a Chamber of Mines economist.<BR><P>
DUBAI TRADE HOPES GOLD PRICE WILL STAY BELOW $400<I> (Reuters)</I><BR>
DUBAI - Gold prices will have to stay under the psychologically important $400 an ounce mark to ensure robust local and re-export demand for Dubai gold in April, souk retailers and wholesalers in the Gulf emirate said on Sunday. <BR><P>
INDIAN SUB-CONTINENT GOLD SUPPLIES SEEN IMPROVING <I> (Reuters)</I><BR>
BOMBAY - A reduction in entry tax on gold brought into Bombay and a Pakistani move to boost jewellery exports could improve gold supply in the Indian sub-continent, bullion dealers said on Monday.<BR><P>
TAIWAN MARCH GOLD IMPORTS UP AFTER CHINA TENSIONS<I> (Reuters)</I><BR>
TAIPEI - Taiwans imports of gold bars, coins and plate rose sharply in March to 25,238 tonnes from 9,618 tonnes in March 1995, the Finance Ministry said in a statement on Monday.<BR><P>
MANILA TO CHARGE BOSSES OVER MINE-WASTE SPILLAGE  <I> (Reuters)</I><BR>
MANILA - Philippine officials said on Monday they were filing criminal charges against executives of Marcopper and threatened to blacklist the partly Canadian-owned mine firm after its waste swamped a 25 km long river.<BR><P>
ECONOMISTS MORE OPTIMISTIC OVER RAND<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
Economists still expect that South Africa will not achieve a growth rate of 4% this year, according to the monthly survey in which 21 economists make predictions on eight economic variables.<BR><P>
TRANS-HEX TO CLOSE DIAMOND MINE <I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
Trans-Hex, the listed diamond group in the Rembrandt stable, is going to close its loss-making diamond mine in Swaziland.<BR><P>
VOGELS CAN EARN THE SAME <I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
The prospects for metal prices this year and expected weakening in the exchange rate of the rand against the dollar should ensure that the investment income of Vogelstruisbult Metal Holdings shows little change this year, Mr John Hopwood says in this chairman's review.<BR><P>
DE BEERS VENTURES BACK INTO ANGOLA <I>(Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Diamond giant De Beers is venturing back into Angola, hoping this time war won't interfere with business.  De Beers officials have announced the signing of a prospecting deal in north-eastern Angola.<BR><P>
BIG ORDERS LINKED TO RAND SLUMP <I>(Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Two big corporate orders for dollars contributed to the rand's collapse last week, analysts say.  The first order was linked to Iscor and involved the steel producer buying capital equipment for expansion, and the second to Anglo American's acquisition of a stake in Lonrho.<BR><P>
A SUCCESS PLAN FOR THE SA ECONOMY<I>(Finansies & Tegniek, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The South African economy is growing too slowly to make any real difference to the poor and the unemployed.  Now there is a set of practical proposals from the business world for substantial faster growth.<BR><P>
DO WORKPLACE FORUMS HAVE A FUTURE?<I>(Finansies & Tegniek, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Despite the prominence given to workplace forums in the new Labour Relations Act, there are now serious questions about whether the system will work because Cosatu is showing less and less enthusiasm for it.<BR><P>
ED HERN BACK WITH BLACK BROKERS<I> (Rapport, Jhb.)</I><BR>
One of the country's best known sharebrokers, Ed Hern, is returning to the JSE at the beginning of May as an executive director of the first directly controlled black brokers' firm in South Africa.<BR><P>



</DOC>
