<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 4 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>


MANUEL TAKES STEPS TO TRY TO SALVAGE RAND<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Economic policy-makers launched a major damage control exercise yesterday as the bottom fell out of the rand.  The currency nose-dived from its opening level of R4,02 to the dollar to its worst close on record of R4,14 amid talk that a major US investment bank had taken a massive speculative position against it.  A huge import order for dollars was also still affecting the market yesterday, spurring other importers to scramble for cover and adding to the panic.<BR><P>
QUESTIONS ABOUT MANUEL'S PLANS MAKE RAND FALL<I> (Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The rand fell to new lows yesterday amid continuing speculation that new Finance Minister Trevor Manuel was going to announce far-reaching slackening of exchange control within days.<BR><P>
NO BIG BANGS FROM MANUEL<I> (Cape Times)</I><BR>
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel moved to calm financial markets yesterday as the rand plummeted to a new low against the US dollar.  The rand closed at R4,14 to the US dollar, a drop of about 14 cents in the day and an all-time low that coincides with Manuels replacing of outgoing Finance Minister Chris Liebenberg.<BR><P>
MEDIA SHOULD AID IN CHANGE<I> (Cape Times)</I><BR>
The recent mad dance of the rand was based on a perception that a black government could not properly manage an economy as sophisticated as South Africas, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said last night.  Speaking at a banquet attended by members of the national and provincial cabinets, business people and Cape Newspapers executives, he said those who had vision of the transformation which faced SA had to redefine the news and position the media so they would also become an important element in leading the country to its destination.<BR><P>
JOHANNESBURG STOCK EXCHANGE MAY GET BLACK STOCKBROKING FIRM<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The National Council of Trade Unions has teamed up with the Foundation for African Business and Consumer Services and retired broker Ed Hern to launch the JSEs first black stockbroking firm.<BR><P>
SA HITS BACK AT PROTECTIONIST GRIPES<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SA trade observers yesterday dismissed a barrage of US criticism over protectionist trade policies, claiming the allegations were unjustified and that the US trade record was far from unblemished.<BR><P>
UNIONS BLAME BUSINESS FOR HIGH UNEMPLOYMENT<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Organised labour this week challenged business on its attempt to lay the blame for the high unemployment levels at the door of workers and organised labour for being a 'labour elite' and attempting to create 'inflexible labour markets'.<BR><P>
ASHANTI LISTING A BOOST TO ZIMBABWEAN BOURSE<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Zimbabwes stock exchange was poised to almost double its market capitalisation to $4bn and enhance its international image with the planned listing this month of Ashanti Goldfields, exchange officials said.<BR><P>
GOVERNMENT SUCCESSFULLY WOOS PRIVATE SECTOR INVESTORS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Government is doing a hard sell to the business sector to get it to invest in public infrastructure projects.  Is the private sector buying the idea of a partnership with the public sector?<BR><P>
LABOUR GETS TO WORK <I>(Business Mail)</I><BR>
Labour and business were in direct conflict this week with the release of labours proposals on growth, development, and job creation.  The document says hard choices have to be made by the economic elite if social equity is to be achieved.<BR><P>
COSATU FAILS TO CONSULT MEMBERS <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Cosatus official alternative economic strategy document, tabled this week, was never referred to its affiliates.  It was drawn up by specialists, discussed by the executive and decreed the official position.<BR><P>
DECISION ON ST LUCIA 'COULD (NOT) BE DELAYED'<I> (Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Cabinet's decision last month to ban mining on the eastern shore of St Lucia could not have been delayed any longer, Environment Minister Dawie de Villiers said yesterday in response to reports that communities in the St Lucia area were planning to blockade Northern Zululand game reserves over the Easter weekend in protest against not having been consulted about the decision.<BR><P>
MINE'S PAYOUT PROBED<I> (Sowetan,Jhb.)</I><BR>
An eight-man committee involved in a dispute with a North West community over the mismanagement of millions of rands worth of royalties for mining rights paid out by vanadium mine Vametco Minerals Corporation is being investigated by the OSEO.<BR><P>
LONRHO ESTABLISHES AFRICA UNIT<I> (Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Lonrho of Africa has established a new company, Lonrho Central Africa, as part of its restructuring programme.<BR><P>
SAUDI ARABIA PLANNING FOUR NEW GOLD MINES<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
DUBAI - Saudi Arabia is pursuing a plan to develop four new gold mines in the desert kingdom over the next two years, a Saudi official said on Wednesday.  The mines would be the biggest expansion seen in the kingdoms gold mining industry and would more than double Saudi gold production by the turn of the decade.<BR><P>
CANADA SELLS 46 000 OUNCES OF GOLD IN MARCH <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
OTTAWA - Canada sold 46 000 ounces of gold in March, reducing reserves to 3,3 million ounces, the Finance Department said yesterday.<BR><P>
PAKISTAN LETS BANKS FINANCE GOLD JEWELLERY<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
KARACHI - The State (central) Bank of Pakistan on Wednesday authorised bank financing of gold jewellery exports against firm export orders or letters of credit.<BR><P>
POLLUTERS SHOULD BEAR COSTS - GREEN PAPER<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The principle that those who cause pollution should bear the costs should guide SA environmental policy, says the green paper on the environment, released yesterday.<BR><P>
SA MAY GET TOUGH GREEN WATCHDOG<I> (Cape Times)</I><BR>
South Africa may soon have an Environmental Protection Agency - a green watchdog, reporting directly to Parliament, and auditing government departments and institutions to ensure they stick to environmental policy.  This is one of the proposals in the discussion document of the Consultative National Environmental Policy Process released yesterday by the Department of Environment Affairs.




