<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b>
<font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 3 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>

STRONG OUTLOOK FOR GOLD DEMAND - WORLD GOLD COUNCIL <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LOS CABOS, MEXICO - Global gold demand is a broad based strong picture, said Michael Barlerin, CEO of the Americas of the World Gold Council.  At the World Gold and Silver Institute's annual conference here on Tuesday, Barlerin, although not giving a forward projection for gold demand for 1996, said demand in 1995 rose 8% to 3 550 tonnes from 3 272 tonnes in 1994.<BR><P>
US GOLD MINING SEEN HAMSTRUNG BY REGULATIONS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LOS CABOS - The future of US gold mining depends mostly on the number of regulations imposed by Washington and on the ability of the industry to shed its negative image, gold mine experts said on Monday.<BR><P>
CHAMBER CONTESTS GOLD OUTPUT DATA (<I>Citizen, Johannesburg</I>)<BR>
South Africa's gold output will be more than 460 tons in 1997, the Chamber of Mines of SA, CE Tom Main, told the World Gold and Silver Institute's annual conference in Mexico.<BR><P>
AFRICA OUTPUT ON RISE <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
African gold output, excluding South Africa, is set to increase to 200 tons by the year 2000, Scotia Mcleod senior gold analyst Ted Reeve told the Gold and Silver Institute's annual conference in Mexico.<BR><P>
SA GOLD INDUSTRY TO PLAY ROLE FOR LONG TIME (<I>Beeld, Johannesburg</I>)<BR>
Anglo American gold and uranium division chairman Bobby Godsell said at the World Gold and Silver Institute's annual congress in Los Cabos, Mexico, that South Africa would remain a very important gold producer for a long time to come, and that it is a fallacy to think that South Africa's gold is virtually exhausted and gold production was going to fall drastically in the next few years.<BR><P>
RUSSIAN PACT RAISES PRICE OF DIAMONDS <I>(Business Report, Jhb</I>)<BR>
LONDON - Diamond prices have risen on world markets since De Beers negotiated an agreement with Russia in February, international dealers said yesterday.<BR><P>
GOLD MINES EXPECTED TO DO WELL <I>(Business Report, Jhb</I>)<BR>
Hopes are high that the next round of quarterly results from the gold mines will show a distinct profit improvement over the December quarterly figures, mainly because of an improvement in the gold price.<BR><P>
SNBS LUSSER RULES OUT SELLING SWISS RESERVE GOLD <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
ZURICH - Swiss National Bank head Markus Lasser ruled out gold sales from the reserves of his institute, saying Swiss law effectively barred the bank from capitalising on its gold holdings.<BR><P>
SA COPPER PRICE INCREASED  (<I>Beeld, Johannesburg</I>)<BR>
The copper price in the country for this month has been increased to R11 417,32 per ton, free on rail at Phalaborwa, as against R10 796,12 per ton last month.<BR><P>
DE BEERS AWAITING APPLICATIONS  (<I>Beeld, Johannesburg</I>)<BR>
De Beers is awaiting applications from small mining undertakings wanting to take over 56 mineral rights holdings.<BR><P>
DISPUTE OVER IMPALA'S MINERAL RIGHTS NOT RESOLVED SOON  (<I>Beeld, Johannesburg</I>)<BR>
The Bafokeng tribe in North-Western Province which is involved in a dispute with Impala Platinum over the mineral rights of the ground where Impala is situated does not expect the dispute to be resolved in the near future.<BR><P>
LABOUR TABLES ITS BLUEPRINT FOR THE FUTURE<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Organised labour has called for a review of trade and financial market liberalisation policies, the raising of corporate taxes, ensuring the role of the state in economic activity and the strengthening of unions and maintenance of labour standards.<BR><P>
LABOUR WANTS 55% TOP TAX RATE <I>(Business Report,Jhb)</I><BR>
Organised labour has called for an increase in corporate taxation and the introduction of a tax rate of 55% for those earning more than R200 000 a year.<BR><P>
NUM GEARS UP FOR TALKS <I>(Sowetan,Jhb)</I><BR>
Ending discriminatory regulations and racially based wages on the mines top the National Union of Mineworker's list of demands in the coming annual wage negotiations.<BR><P>
GOLD MINES' RESULTS TO HIGHLIGHT INDUSTRY WOES <I>(Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Gold producers are expected to show slightly better results in the March quarter, aided by a higher average rand gold price of around R1 496 an ounce and marginally better production.  The quarterly results due mid-month will also be boosted by the new tax formula applicable to mines, but the results will not disguise the fact that the industry is still troubled by holidays, low grades, high costs and low tonnage milled, say analysts.<BR><P>
STALS DENIES TALK HE HAS PLANS TO RESIGN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The markets are refusing to believe that Reserve Bank governor Chris Stals is staying in his post - despite Stals repeated denials of rumours that he is about to quit.<BR><P>
FREEGOLD MERGES SHAFTS TO CUT COSTS  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo Americans Free State Consolidated Mines (Freegold) had merged several shafts to reduce overheads following declining ore reserves and a squeeze on margins, regional GM Dave Hodgson said yesterday.<BR><P>
NZO MOOTS AN ASSOCIATION OF SOUTH ATLANTIC RIM COUNTRIES  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The possibility of a broad association of Latin American, African and Indian Ocean nations being created to enhance the regions power in international forums was raised yesterday by South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo.<BR><P>
G-7 SPLIT OVER INCLUSION OF SOCIAL CLAUSE IN TRADE DEALS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
LILLE - Deep divisions emerged at the G-7s world employment meeting last night over whether social clauses protecting workers should be included in future trade agreements.<BR><P>
WORLD-BEATING RETURNS LURE FOREIGNERS<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
Real rates of return on SA bonds were higher than in most other countries and foreigners continued to buy local gilts despite the rands volatility and uncertainty in global capital markets, analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
THANKS TO REFORMS AND GEOLOGY, ETHIOPIAN MINES BLOSSOM<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
ADDIS ABABA - Ethiopia has caught the eye of the worlds mining industry, thanks to promising geology and a policy revolution by former rebels who saw Albania as their role model.  The hunt is on for gold, tantalum, platinum and nickel as well as natural gas and petroleum.<BR><P>
AFRICA GOLD OUTPUT SEEN UP TO 200 TONNES BY 2000 <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LOS CABOS, MEXICO - African gold production, excluding the traditional high SA output, is set to increase to 200 tonnes by the year 2000 from the current 126 tonnes, a top gold expert said here on Monday.<BR><P>
US GOLD MINING SEEN HAMSTRUNG BY REGULATIONS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LOS CABOS - The future of US gold mining depends mostly on the number of regulations imposed by Washington and on the ability of the industry to shed its negative image, gold miners and experts said on Monday.<BR><P>
SA SEES 97 GOLD OUTPUT AT LEAST 460 TONNES <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LOS CABOS - SAs gold output will be more than 460 tonnes in 1997, the chairman of the SA Mining Chamber <I>[sic - the error has been pointed out to Reuters. It should have read 'chief executive officer of the Chamber of Mines of SA' - Ed.)</I> told the World Gold and Silver Institutes annual conference here.<BR><P>
LATAM GOLD OUTPUT SEEN CLIMBING TO 400t BY 2000 <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LOS CABOS - Latin American gold production is seen rising to around 400 tonnes in 2000 from the 266 tonne output in 1995, a top gold analyst said.<BR><P>
AUSTRALIA GOLD OUTPUT SEEN AT 360 TONNES IN 2001 <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LOS CABOS - Australia is set to become the worlds second-biggest gold producer after SA by the year 2001, said Peter Ellery, the CEO of the Chamber of Mines and Energy of Western Australia.<BR><P>
FOREIGNERS NET BUYERS <I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Foreigners remained net buyers of South African shares on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange (JSE) last week, buying shares to the value of R641-million and selling to the value of R595-million.<BR><P>
GENCOR SELLS TO MYCON <I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gencor intends selling its 57,3% interest in Kelgran to Mycon SA, a subsidiary of the Malaysian Mycom group, for 393c per share, subject to certain conditions.<BR><P>
AMALIA WARNED<I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The JSE has warned that the listing of the Amalia Gold Mining Co. and RMS Properties can be suspended for not submitting their annual financial statements within six months of the end of the financial year, as required by the rules of the JSE.<BR><P>
MANDELA TO VISIT GERMANY IN MAY  <I>(Citizen, Jhb)</I><BR>
Pres. Mandela will visit Germany next month, said a statement issued yesterday by German President Roman Herzog's office.<BR><P>


