<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><h1><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 1 APRIL 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2</b></h1></b></center></center><BR><P>

SADC TO WORK TOWARDS LIFTING EXCHANGE CONTROLS<I> (Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The long-term objective and top priority of central bankers in the Southern African Developement Community was to work towards the lifting of exchange controls in all member countries, Mauritius Central Bank chief manager Bud Gujadhur said at the weekend.<BR><P>
FAST-GROWING ECONOMY WILL LURE INVESTORS<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
LONDON - SA will attract much more direct foreign investment in a fast-growing economy, British bankers and analysts said at the weekend.<BR><P>
SAS FUTURE LIES IN DEREGULATION AND LIBERALISATION<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
SA must make itself as attractive as possible to foreign investors, and its hope for the future lies in deregulation and liberalisation, said a United States government official.<BR><P>
INVESTORS GIVE HJ JOEL ANOTHER GO <I>(Business Times, Sunday)</I><BR>
Third-time lucky investors seem prepared to follow their rights to the HJ Joel rights offer at 250c after a comprehensive presentation from management.<BR><P>
STAY LEAN IN PLATINUM FOR NEXT FOUR YEARS, RESEARCHER<I> (Business Times) </I><BR>
Investors should maintain an underweight exposure to platinum in the medium term because the metal price is unlikely to improve significantly for four years - other than for speculative plays on the price.<BR><P>
DUBAI GOLD SELLERS HOPE FOR STABLE BULLION PRICES <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
DUBAI - Golds reluctance to hold above $400 an ounce is a useful foundation to attract healthy Indian demand for Dubai bullion re-exports in April, traders in the Gulf Arab emirate of Dubai said on Sunday.<BR><P>
FALLING RUSSIAN SALES TO PROP PLATINUM PRICE-REPORT <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Russias diminishing ability to fill the platinum markets supply gap will put a solid floor under the price, according to a study published this week.<BR><P>
DE BEERS MAY NOW PROSPECT IN ANGOLA<I> (Beeld, Jhb)</I><BR>
De Beers has been granted permission by the ministers' council of Angola to carry out prospecting activities in three regions of the country.<BR><P>
ECONOMISTS EXPECT DROP IN RESERVES <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The position of South Africa's gold and foreign exchange reserves is expected to be made known on Thursday.  Economists do not expect the news to be good.<BR><P>
TIN PRICE COULD CLIMB TO $7 500  <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
The price of tin could climb to between $7 000 and $7 500 per ton within 12 months, as against the recent $6 350 per ton, according to a forecast by a CRU International research worker.<BR><P>
MORE THAN 500 MINEWORKERS KILLED <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
A total of 532 mineworkers died in mining accidents in 1995, Minerals and Energy Affairs Minister Pik Botha said in Parliament last week.<BR><P>
INER KILLED AT JCI MINE<I> (The Citizen, Saturday, Jhb)</I><BR>
A miner was killed in a rockfall at JCI's Randfontein Estates on Friday morning while replacing wire mesh on a roof 932m underground in Cooke 2 shaft, Corporate Affairs Manager Mark Gonsalves has said.<BR><P>
AMALIA EXPANDING ABROAD<I> (Rapport, Sunday)</I><BR>
The Amalia gold mining group will have interests in Britain and Canada within three months, and is also acquiring interests in New Zealand.  MD Gerhard Potgieter told <I>Rapport </I>these steps were being taken to ensure further financing for the development of its gold mining activities.<BR><P>
PIK LEADS THE WAY ON NEW JOBS APPROACH<I> (Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The director-general of Public Service and Administration, Dr M P Ncholo, disclosed at an international conference on affirmative action in the civil service over the weekend that only the Department of Mineral and Energy Affairs, whose minister is Pik Botha, had so far registered a programme.  Furthermore, in terms of set procedure, affirmative action initiatives may only take place after being registered with the commission.<BR><P>




