<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 30 AUGUST 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>






NEC FUNDING STILL TO BE FULLY SECURED <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Some of the smaller National Empowerment Consortium (NEC) members had not yet secured any funding for their share of the Johnnic acquisition and could turn to New Africa Investments Ltd for finances, NEC deputy chairman Tommy Oliphant said yesterday.<BR><P>
NEXT TWO MONTHS WILL SHAPE THE FUTURE OF JOHNNIC DEAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
As the largest black empowerment deal yet, with the broadest base of investors, the Johnnic deal has great symbolic significance.  That is important in itself.  The question to be answered in coming years is whether it has real significance, in that it puts black shareholders firmly in the driver's seat of a major industrial conglomerate.<BR><P>
JOHNNIC, NEC DEAL GETS THUMBS UP  <I>(Sowetan, Jhb)</I><BR>
Business, political organisations, unions as well as individuals have welcomed the Johnnic deal as a milestone for black economic empowerement.<BR><P>
BLACK-RUN COAL MNE OPENS SOON <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
South Africas first black-owned coal mining company has been formed and is to start operations in November. The company, Kuyasa Mining is to start its operations in Delmas, Mpumalanga Province.<BR><P>
CORRUPTION AT HEART OF CRIME-FIGHTING PROBLEMS, LEADERS WARN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Police corruption was so rife that one of SA's provincial police commissioners had been appointed even though he had a criminal record, President Nelson Mandela told Western Cape religious leaders yesterday.<BR><P>
SURGE IN EXPORTS CHEERS MARKETS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Exports surged an astonishing 55% in July from June to push SA's trade balance into a huge R2,58bn surplus for the month from a R27m deficit, Customs and Excise figures released yesterday.<BR><P>
COSATU AFFILIATES URGED TO TAKE STAND ON PRIVATISATION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu) affiliates have been warned that a failure to take positions on privatisation could result in their exclusion from processes under way.  The message was conveyed in a discussion document on state asset restructuring being circulated by Cosatu to affiliates to assist them in formulating mandates before the next Cosatu central executive committee meeting in September.<BR><P>
LABOUR BILL AMENDED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Parliament passed several technical amendments to the Labour Relations Act yesterday after the Senate voted unanimously to adopt it.  The amendments Bill was necessary to correct technical issues, grammar and revisions omitted from the Act, Labour Minister Tito Mboweni said.<BR><P>
DELAYED INTEREST RATE CUT MAY KEEP MARKETS VOLATILE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
South African financial markets were expected to remain volatile in the next few months, troubled by a rising trend in the inflation rate and a delayed cut in interest rates, Syfrets economist Sandra Gordon said yesterday.<BR><P>
MINE TEAMS GIVEN ACCLAIM <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Increased productivity at Impala Platinum Mines in the past year has been attributed largely to the introduction of the self-directed work teams headed by a crew captain, who has replaced the traditional white miner <I>[sic].</I><BR><P>
TAIWAN AIMING TO INCREASE TRADE WITH SA '10% A YEAR' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA and Taiwan could sustain higher levels of trade and a target increase of 10% a year for the next three years had been set, Taiwanese Vice-President Li-teh Hsu said yesterday.<BR><P>
SA, AUSTRALIA IN R4BN TRADE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Trade between SA and Australia had risen dramatically in the past year to more than R4bn, Australia's Foreign Affairs and Trade Department said yesterday.<BR><P>
REGIONAL PACT CONFOUNDS SCEPTICS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The 10-member Southern African Development Community (SADC), representing all countries in the region, confounded sceptics at its summit in Maseru this week by signing a trade protocol to create a free trade area in eight or nine years.<BR><P>
STRIKES MAR GOOD YEAR FOR TSUMEB CORP <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Base metals producer Gold Fields Namibia's Tsumeb Corporation is facing revenue losses of about N$7,5m so far due to a strike which entered its eighth day yesterday.<BR><P>
DE BEERS WORRIED ABOUT INSTABILITY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
LUANDA - The De Beers diamond company said yesterday it was worried by instability in Angola's diamond-rich areas and by the country's political problems.<BR><P>
SA UNHAPPY WITH EU TRADE PROPOSALS <I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
SA parliamentarians are unhappy with European Union proposals for a trade pact and want negotiators to push for greater concessions, according to a document seen by Reuters.  The EU mandate for negotiations with SA has been criticised as too tough for a developing economy.  Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin said last month that SA hoped to re-open the trade talks towards the end of this month.<BR><P>
NUM TO HOLD STRIKE BALLOT <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) will hold a strike ballot today after an impasse in wage negotiations among its 4 700 miners at De Beers, Judith Weymont, the union spokesman, said yesterday.  The results of the ballot are expected early next week.<BR>
<B><I>...but ...</I></B><BR>
LAST MINUTE WAGE OFFER <I>(Business Mail, Jhb weekly on Fridays)</I><BR>
NUM assistant general secretary Gwede Mastashe says the last-minute wage offer by De Beers Consolidated Mines closes the gap "to an extent" on the parties' difference in their deadlocked negotiations.  But he was unsure whether the offer will induce members to halt the strike ballot proposed for today.<BR><P>
ANGLO AND NUM POSTPONE ANNOUNCEMENT <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Anglo American and NUM jointly agreed to postpone an announcement about this year's wages and working conditions until agreement was reached throughout the industry, Anglo said yesterday.<I>[SA media assumed the "announcement" was to be on wages and conditions of employment. This is false. No mention of wages or working conditions was made, and the "Advice to Editors" from Anglo referred to the signing of "an agreement" between Anglo and NUM - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
FREEGOLD AND BLYVOOR EXCELLENT BUYS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Freegold and Blyvooruitzicht have been called outstanding buys in an undervalued SA gold sector, where market sentiment is poised to improve ahead of a positive revaluation.<BR><P>
IMF MIGHT SELL GOLD TO HELP POOR COUNTRIES <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
NEW YORK - The International Monetary Fund has said for the first time that it might sell some of its $40-billion supply of gold to reduce the debts of the poorest developing countries, the <I>New York Times</I> reported on Friday.<BR><P>
PLAN NOT ENOUGH  <I>(New Nation, Jhb. weekly on Fridays)</I><BR>
Multi-national Anglo American Industrial Corporation (Ltd) (Amic) this week outlined what it described as "critical" measures government urgently needs to address to improve business climate.<BR><P>
"SHOP FLOOR" <I>(column by Labour Reporter Amrit Manga, New Nation)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) decision not to release its general secretary Kgalema Motlanthe to the ANC is indeed a sober one. The decision came after the mass exodus from Cosatu and its affiliates of senior leaders to the ANC. The decision suggests that organised labour may well have come to realise that its 1993 special congress decision to release officials on the scale that it did might not have been in its best interest.<BR><P>
