<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 29 AUGUST 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>
   



SA POPULATION GROWTH BOOSTED BY BLACK SECTOR <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
South Africa's black population increased by 713 200 between last year and this year - virtually the total population of the Northern Cape, Unisa's Bureau of Market Research said yesterday.<BR><P>
NEC BUYS JOHNNIC STAKE AT A DISCOUNT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
In SA's biggest black empowerment deal, Anglo American and the National Empowerment Consortium have signed an agreement for Anglo to sell most of its 47,7% stake in industrial group Johnnic to the NEC over the next 18 months.<BR><P>
CREDIT GROWTH STILL STUBBORNLY HIGH <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Private sector credit growth remained high in July, with latest Reserve Bank figures showing only a slight fall in the annual rate of increase to 18,5% from 18,65% in June.<BR><P>
SMELTER DAMAGED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold Fields Namibia said yesterday the copper smelter at Namibian subsidiary Tsumeb Corporation had been badly damaged by striking mine workers and would be out of action for a long time.  The strike continued, with strikers blocking access to all mines and the smelter complex yesterday.<BR><P>
UNION DEBATE ON INVESTMENT ROLE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Cosatu (SA's biggest labour federation, the Congress of SA Trade Unions) affiliates appear divided on the establishment of union-controlled investment companies, especially because such companies have been bidding for radio stations and this could undermine the broad opposition of labour to privatisation.<BR><P>
ECONOMIC TRAIN SMASH HAS BEEN PREVENTED<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA had succeeded in a few short years to prevent a "train smash" and to stabilise the economy, Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin said at <I>Business Day's</I> Business Achievement Award 1996 function last night.<BR><P>
SA TO WEIGH PERFORMANCE NOT PROMISES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Promises of investment would not influence government policy concerning Taiwan and the People's Republic of China, ANC MP and parliamentary trade and industry committee acting chairman Rob Davis said yesterday.<BR><P>
ECONOMIC APARTHEID REALITY FOR MAJORITY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Economic apartheid remained despite political transformation and this meant that when it came to wages, jobs, income distribution, ownership and control, the economy continued to cater for the few, Cosatu general secretary Sam Shilowa said yesterday.<BR><P>
NUM MEMBERS RETURN TO WORK AT LEEUDOORN MINE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Production resumed at Gold Fields Leeudoorn gold mine near Carletonville last night as National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) members returned to work after an agreement was reached  - after three days of mediation - to set up peace structures.<BR><P>
INVESTMENT DEPENDS ON GOVTS' ACTIONS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
In the mid-1950s Ghana and Thailand had much the same income per head;  so did Nigeria and Indonesia.  By 1994, Thailand's real income per head was almost three-and-a-half times Ghana's and Indonesia's three times that of Nigeria's.  Countries facing the same international economic environment and possessing very similar resources have succeeded wonderfully or failed miserably.  Why is this - and can more countries shift from the latter to the former category?<BR><P>
GOVT TO KEEP FOREIGN FUNDS ABROAD <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Finance Department is investigating the possibility of opening a foreign bank account to limit its losses if the rand continues to fall, Hannes Smit, the director-general of state expenditure, said in parliament yesterday.<BR><P>
UNEXPECTED DROP IN MONEY SUPPLY SET TO PLEASE RESERVE BANK <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The Reserve Bank announced yesterday that the M3 money supply grew only 14,69% last month, below the 16,2% consensus forecast of economists in a recent Reuters poll and June's revised growth figure of 15,74%.<BR><P>
RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IS THE TICKET TO SUCCESS<I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The subject of industrial research and development is hardly discussed in our daily quest to refurbish SA's economy.  It is, however, one of the most critical subjects in today's competitive global environment.<BR><P>
LET ZULUS RETURN TO WORK, PLEADS NUM PRESIDENT <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
NORTHAM, NORTH WEST PROVINCE - James Motlatsi, the president of NUM, pleaded yesterday with about 1 000 Northam Platinum workers to allow Zulu-speaking workers to return to work.<BR><P>
ECONOMISTS EXPECT STABLE INTEREST RATES <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The money-market shortage of almost R9b a day was among the many reasons interest rates should be higher, Mike Leeming, a divisional director of Nedcor Bank, said yesterday.  He said it was difficult for banks to operate with the present money-market shortage.<BR><P>
ECONOMIST SOUNDS WARNING ON SA <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The economy was in a worse shape than it seemed, and the best that could be hoped for was a soft landing next year and a modest recovery in 1998, Luke Doig, the senior economist at Credit Guarantee, said yesterday.<BR><P>
SOUTH AFRICA MINING EXHIBITION  <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
South Africa is to host the 1996 ElectraMining international mining exhibition from September 30 to October 4 at the National Recreational and Exhibition Centre (Nasrec) outside of Johannesburg. Interested people can telephone (+27 11) 835 1565 for more information.<BR><P>
TOURISM TO BECOME SCHOOL SUBJECT <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The National Curriculum Committee is evaluating a syllabus for a subject called Travel and Tourism, which is to be written for Std 8 and Std 9 pupils.  This new school subject is aimed at creating a tourism culture.<BR><P>
CHINA CLOSES 430 ILLEGAL GOLD PITS IN JAN-JUN <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BEIJING - China closed 430 illegal gold pits in two central provinces in the first six months of 1996 and rounded up members of eight armed gangs guarding illegally excavated mines, the China Daily said on Wednesday.<BR><P>
JAPAN GOLD IMPORTS PLUNGE ON FRAGILE DEMAND <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
TOKYO - Japan's gold imports plunged in the first seven months of this year compared with the same period last year, pushed down by fragile demand from the investment and jewellery sectors, precious metal industry officials said on Wednesday.<BR><P>
