<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 15 AUGUST 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>



NUM, CHAMBER TO MEET OVER DISPUTE <I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
The Chamber of Mines and the National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) will begin conciliation talks this morning in a bid to break the dispute between the two parties.  The union declared the dispute over wages and working conditions at the beginning of the month.<BR><P>
FRESH TROUBLES AT MINE AFTER WORKERS SHOT <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Thousands of mineworkers at Gold Fields' East Driefontien gold mine near Carletonville did not report for work yesterday following the death of two mine workers on Tuesday - one of whom was a senior NUM branch committee member.<BR><P>
MPs ADOPT CODE OF ETHICS <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
A code of ethics for parliamentarians, which will require them to disclose all their financial interests, was approved by the National Assembly without opposition yesterday, although the Inkatha Freedom Party abstained on the issue.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
CODE SHOULD INCLUDE OTHER HIGH-RANKING OFFICIALS <I>(Die Burger, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The code of conduct for parliamentarians should be extended to include other influential public figures such as senior employees of parastatals, members of provincial legislatures and MECs, Minister of Water Affairs and Forestry Kader Asmal told the National Assembly yesterday.<BR><P>
INFORMATION NEEDS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A delegation from the business representative body, Business SA met Central Statistical Services head Mark Orkin yesterday to discuss information needs.  This follows fears that the CSS was neglecting the need for broad economic statistics because it was paying too much attention to tracking the Reconsttuction and Development Programme.<BR><P>
RAND 11,5% UNDERVALUED, SAY US BANK <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
US investment bank Goldman Sachs believes the rand is 11,5% undervalued and should appreciate in real terms during a 12-18 month period.  That view, expressed in the bank's publication, The Weekly Analyst, ironically knocked the rand to yet another three-month low against the dollar yesterday.  The markets focused on the bank's short-term concerns about the rand instead of its longer-term view.<BR><P>
LOSS OF POLICEMEN 'UNAFFORDABLE' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA Police Service would have lost about 15 000 trained police officers due to death, resignation and sacking when additional officers were recruited in July 1998 and government's recruitment moratorium was lifted, the Johannesburg Community Policing Area Board said yesterday.<BR><P>
NAMIBIAN DEBT DEAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Outstanding issues preventing SA from writing off Namibia's N$1,4bn, pre-independence debt have been resolved following a meeting between Namibian Finance Minister Helmut Angula and his SA counterpart, Trevor Manuel, in Pretoria last week.<BR><P>
GOVT TARIFF POLICY JUSTIFIED - ERWIN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin yesterday denied government was fast-tracking tariff cuts at the expense of sensitive SA industries.  While briefing the parliamentary trade and industry committee, Erwin admitted, however, that tariff cuts would take place in the clothing and textile industries quicker than the World Trade Organisation tariff ceiling which had been negotiated.<BR><P>
ELECTRICITY INDUSTRY REVAMP 'NEXT YEAR' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Restructuring of the electricity supply industry should get off the ground early next year, with recommendations to go to a Cabinet committee before the end of the month.<BR><P>
LEGISLATION NOT READY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Competition legislation would be ready for Parliament only early next year, Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin said yesterday.  The National Economic Development and Labour Council (Nedlac) would examine key principles of the proposed legislation in September, he said.  Earlier proposals for competition legislation drew fire from business.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
OBSERVER STATUS AT NEDLAC <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The parliamentary trade and industry committee indicated yesterday that it would be seeking observer status at Nedlac and would be particularly keen to be present during the debate on competition policy.<BR><P>
NEDLAC EXTENDS TALKS ON BILL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Negotiations on Employment Standards Draft Bill within Nedlac have been given a reprieve after labour negotiators requested additional time for the parties to try to reach a settlement.<BR><P>
MARKET MAKERS <I>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
The proposal that the Reserve Bank should transfer its responsibility for market making in government stock to private banks has considerable merit.  It goes beyond the Bank's own wish to reduce its unrelated responsibilities - it also wants to shed responsibility for banking supervision - to focus more closely on the central issue of managing monetary policy.<BR><P>
AGGRESSIVE PACKAGING NEEDED TO BOLSTER RAND <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Finance Department's new team will have to do some "aggressive packaging" in terms of exchange control abolition if it wants to avoid a vicious depreciation in the rand, says Southern Life chairman Neal Chapman.  In the group's latest annual report Chapman said SA had missed golden opportunities towards the end of last year and early this year, when the timing for the dismantling of exchange controls had seemed appropriate.<BR><P>
RAMAPHOSA SPELLS OUT EMPOWERMENT PRIORITIES<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
New African Investment deputy chairman Cyril Ramaphosa yesterday called on the government, private sector and black community to introduce programmes and direct efforts towards ensuring that black economic empowerment did not remain a dream.  He told a two-day conference on black economic empowerment the programme had to include equity ownership, entrepreneur promotion and skills transfer.<BR><P>
SA FIGHTS BACK TO DULL EDGE OF POOR PRODUCTIVITY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The recent World Competitiveness Report may have put SA second last of 48 countries, but a fightback is under way, according to the National Productivity Institute.  NPI figures show that SA has made productivity gains for three consecutive years.  Although the gains are small, the NPI believes it could pave the way for a significant resurgence.<BR><P>
SUNTER: SA FACES PLAGUES, ECONOMIC HARDSHIP, WARLORDS (Cape Times)
South Africa faces economic hardship, warlords, plagues and a labour force badly hit by HIV if the current problems regarding these issues are not tackled decisively by the countrys political and business leaders.  Sketching possible scenarios facing the country in the not-too-distant future, Anglo American executive director Clem Sunter told a large gathering of business people attending the Cape Times/Sanlam Breakfast Club yesterday that South Africa had to undergo an "economic miracle" on the scale of the countrys political miracle of 1994.<BR><P>
