<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 14 AUGUST 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>


IMPLATS INCOME CUT BY CHANGING MARKET <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Impala Platinums attributable income fell 37% to R176m for the year to June, knocked by lower prices and production, and higher costs. <BR><P>
NUM OFFICIAL KILLED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A National Union of Mineworkers official was shot dead at East Driefontein mine, near Carletonville west of Johannesburg, by an unknown gunman last night.  Police said the man could not be named until his family had been notified. <I>[Gold Fields today reported that 12 000 workers at East Driefontein gold mine had stayed away from work following this and another killing early this morning, SAPA reports - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
NATAL EMPLOYERS WONT SIGN SEIFSA AGREEMENT WITH UNIONS<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The 11th-hour refusal by the Natal Engineering Industries' Association to sign a wage pact reached in the metal industry yesterday could overshadow the agreement, which lays the foundation for the industrys restructuring.<BR><P>
USE OF PRIVATE BANKS MOOTED FOR GOVT STOCK <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Finance Department and the Reserve Bank are investigating the possibility of appointing private banks to make a market in government stock.<BR><P>
RECORD DIAMOND SALES HELP BOOST DE BEERS' EARNINGS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Record diamond sales and a solid contribution from investments helped lift De Beers' combined attributable earnings 18% to $482m in the six months to June, the diamond group said yesterday.<BR><P>
LABOUR BILL APPROVED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Labour Relations Amendment Bill, which paves the way for the 1995 Labour Relations Act, was approved by the National Assembly's labour committee yesterday.<BR><P>
BILL TALKS CONTINUE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government, labour and business negotiators were expected to continue discussions on the Employment Standards Draft Bill late last night.  Contrary to a report in <I>Business Day</I> of August 13, a Cabinet committee would not be considering a report submitted by Nedlac as Nedlac itself was not empowered to table reports directly to Cabinet.  Today the committee is expected to consider the revised Bill.<BR><P>
NUM, JCI SIGN JOB GRADING DEAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers and JCI signed a job grading agreement yesterday which will facilitate the redesign of jobs, a crucial element of the company's overall restructuring process.<BR><P>
ECONOMIC PLAN AN IMPROVEMENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Government's macro-economic strategy represented an advance on the Reconstruction and Development Programme (RDP), which did not take into account current government financial constraints and represented a statement of what government wished to deliver but had not costed, Rand Merchant Bank economist Rudolph Gouws said yesterday.<BR><P>
RANDFONTEIN PLAN WILL EXTEND MINES LIFE <I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
Randfontein Estates directors have given the nod to the exploitation of the south reef at the mines Doornkop shaft, the company said yesterday.  The project will involve R805,5-million in capital expenditure and will extend the life of the mine from 2005 to 2024. <BR><P>
MANUEL SUPPORTS STALS IN HIS STANCE ON INTEREST RATES <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel said yesterday he supported Chris Stals, the Reserve Bank governor, in his plan to avoid a rise in interest rates for as long as possible.<BR><P>
DRAFT COMPETITION POLICY READY FOR DISCUSSION BY NEDLAC <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The draft legislation on competition policy is finally ready and will be discussed by the National Economic Development and Labour Council next month, Minister of Trade and Industry Alec Erwin said yesterday. <I>[He also said]</I> - The Department of Trade and Industry had identified projects worth $5-billion associated with the Maputo Development Corridor.<BR><P>
UNIONIST SAYS BOSSES EARN 60% OF SA WAGES <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Sixty percent of South Africas wage bill is paid to the countrys senior managers, who constitute a small percentage of the workforce, Zwelinzima Vavi, the Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu) assistant secretary general, said yesterday. <BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
COSATU EDGED CLOSER TO ANC CLASH<I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Cosatu, South Africas largest labour federation, has rejected out of hand the governments stance that its macro-economic strategy, released in June, is non-negotiable.  Zwelinzima Vavi, Cosatus assistant general secretary, edged closer to a rift with the ANC, its alliance partner, in his keynote address, "The Union Movements Key Challenges", at Cosatus "Them and Us" conference in Johannesburg yesterday. <BR><P>
CHINA TO MEET SA ON TRADE PROBLEMS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
A Chinese trade delegation will visit South Africa for three days next week to try to smooth the waters after complaints by four South African industries that cut-price imports from China are disrupting the local market. <BR><P>
ZIMBABWE TRADE DEAL A BASIS FOR OTHERS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Zimbabwes new trade agreement with South Africa - agreed to earlier this month after four years of negotiation - falls in line with World Trade Organisation rules and forms the basis for trade deals with other Southern African Development Community countries. <BR><P>
THE GEM OF SOUTHERN AFRICA IS FAST BEING TARNISHED <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
GABORONE - Botswanas economy is steadily deteriorating and the prognosis is negative.  Despite years of growth, the nations people are losing their jobs and the only growth sector is an unproductive public service. <BR><P>
US LONG-TERM AVERAGE GROWTH POTENTIAL IS 2%  <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
PORTLAND - Robert Parry, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco, on Tuesday estimated the long-term potential growth rate of the economy is around 2% a year.  Turning to whether or not the US would return to a gold standard, Parry said he was doubtful that would occur.  He did not believe the economy should be "shackled" with the gold standard, calling the system "too rigid".<BR><P>
LONRHO WILL NOT SUPPORT IMPLATS APPEAL  <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Lonrho Plc is not joining SA's Impala Platinum in an appeal against the European Commission's decision to block the merger of their platinum mining interests, the Financial Times said.<BR><P>

