<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 13 AUGUST 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>
   



GOVT WILL NOT VEER OFF COURSE, MANUEL <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
South African Finance Minister Trevor Manuel vowed yesterday to prove wrong those currency speculators who were betting that government would fail to implement its macro-economic strategy.<BR><P>
YANKEE BOND WILL RAISE $250M IN US <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA's government is planning to raise $250m on the US market by issuing a "Yankee" bond this fiscal year.  The planned Yankee bond would differ from the global dollar bond issued in December 1994 as it would tap the US market only.  The need to extend the maturity structure of SA's debt would be taken into account.<BR><P>
FUMES KILL MINER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The body of a mine worker, who apparently died when he was overcome by fumes from explosives, had been found at the Gravelotte coal mine in Benoni, east of Johannesburg, on Saturday.<BR><P>
BANKING BILL TABLED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Draft legislation to regulate banks investments in joint ventures was tabled yesterday. <BR><P>
HOME AFFAIRS FIGURES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A total of 16 892 people obtained SA citizenship between January 1995 and April 1996.<BR><P>
600 MINERS MISS WORK<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
An estimated 600 Zulus from Gold Fields' Northam Platinum Mine near Thabazimbi in Northern Province failed to report for work yesterday, and asked to be moved out of the hostel because of weekend clashes which left six mine workers dead.<BR><P>
ADVISER TO SPEED UP PRIVATISATION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The appointment of a goverment adviser on privatisation was a major step forward and should speed up the process, a Public Enterprises Ministry spokesman said yesterday.<BR><P>
CRUCIAL DEBATE ON DRAFT BILL'S PROBLEMS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Negotiations on the employment standards draft Bill enter a crucial stage tonight when labour, government and business negotiators meet to table areas of debate so that Nedlac can present a report to the Cabinet tomorrow.<BR><P>
ANGLO SALE TO ZIMBABWE IS ON COMMERCIAL TERMS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The proposed sale by Anglo American Corporation of up to 22% in Bindura Nickel Corp to the Zimbabwean government would take place on strictly commercial terms, an Anglo spokesman said yesterday.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
POST-COLONIAL FOLLIES <I>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
Anglo American's sale of an interest in its Bindura nickel mine to Zimbabwe's goverment does not appear at this distance to have the same motivations as its proposed sale here of its Johnnic interest to the National Empowerment Consortium.<BR><P>
ANGLOVAAL TO SELL TO SMALL GROUPS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Mining house Anglovaal is poised to begin selling off various properties to fledgling mining groups.<BR><P>
LONRHO AIMS AT £700M FROM HOTEL DIVISION SALE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
LONDON - Lonrho would float off its hotel division, with an estimated market value of £700m, in early October, it said yesterday.<BR><P>
VIOLENCE SENDS RAND PLUMMETING <I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
The rand slumped yesterday to its weakest-ever level against the pound - its second record low in less than two weeks. Traders said calls by the ANCs Western Cape provincial leader Chris Nissen for a state of emergency in Cape Town to combat vigilante violence sparked new fears of political instability among foreign investors.<BR><P>
CABINET GIVES HSBC 'OPEN BRIEF' <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The government would have to lift exchange controls before the privatisation of any large state asset dependent on large-scale foreign investment could go ahead, Chris Niehaus, a director of Simpson McKie James Capel, the investment house appointed to advise the state on privatisation, said yesterday.<BR><P>
TOURISM VERSUS CRIME <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
SA's tourism boom is over and has been killed by international television coverage, travel trade executives said yesterday.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD'S WEST WITS TO BECOME A DRD SUBSIDIARY<I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
West Wits is to be reconstituted as a wholly owned Durban Roodepoort Deep subsidiary, Randgold said yesterday.<BR><P>
DE BEERS EXPECTED TO REPORT SPARKLING HALF-YEAR RESULTS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
De Beers Consolidated Mines is to announce a sparkling first-half profit today, and analysts expect further growth in the second half.<BR><P>
IVORY COAST SIGNS FOUR MINERAL EXPLORATION DEALS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
ABIDJAN - Ivory Coast has signed two mineral exploration deals with US-based Golden Star Resources and two with Australia's Western Mining Corp (Africa) Ltd, a government statement said.<BR><P>
INDONESIA TO SIGN 60 MINING CONTRACTS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
JAKARTA - Indonesia said on Monday it would sign around 60 new contracts, possibly next month, for the mining of coal and gold.<BR><P>
