<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 12 AUGUST 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>



BE PATIENT WITH SA ECONOMY <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
South Africa's Reserve Bank governor Chris Stals has appealed to market players to be patient with SA's economy, saying they are expecting instant solutions to problems that will be resolved over a couple of months.<BR><P>
AIRLINES TO RESIST HIGH FUEL PRICES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Airlines operating in and out of SA are to present Mineral and Energy Affairs Minister Penuell Maduna with evidence that they pay about 30% more for fuel in SA than at typical airports abroad - boosting oil company profits at the expense of air ticket prices.<BR><P>
VALUE OF ROUGH DIAMOND LEAKS LEAPS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A big jump in the value of rough diamonds leaking on to the market is jeopardising the relationship between Russia and De Beers' Central Selling Organisation again.<BR><P>
HIGHER RAND GOLD PRICE BENEFITS MARGINAL MINES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The higher rand gold price, combined with cost containment in the three months to June, has cut the number of marginal mines to just four, bringing the number of employees on such operations to less than 30 000 from nearly 60 000 this time last year. <BR><P>
<B>THE ECONOMIC WEEK AHEAD: </B><I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
CAPITAL & MONEY MARKETS ARE AT MERCY OF RAND<BR>
The attention of capital- and money-market participants this week will be focused on the foreign-exchange market, where the rand will fight for its life against speculation and importers scrambling for cover.  Under the circumstances, the fact that no main economic indicators will be released this week will probably be welcomed.<BR><P>
ANGLO IN DEAL WITH ZIMBABWE GOVT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American executive director Nicky Oppenheimer has agreed to sell a 35% holding in Bindura Nickel Corporation to the Zimbabwean government after secret talks with President Robert Mugabe. <BR><P>
ANGLO APPOINTS BOARD MEMBERS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Julian Ogilvie Thompson, chairman of Anglo American Corporation, has announced the recent appointment of James Campbell and Clifford Elphick to the corporation's board of directors.<BR><P>
COSATU WARNED OF POTENTIAL FOR SPLIT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu), SA's largest labour federation, could be a divided and increasingly marginalised federation with no power to influence ANC policy by 1999 if it did not constructively address its crucial challenges and develop strategic policy positions.<BR><P>
NEDLAC BEGINS DIALOGUE WITH PARLIAMENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The National Economic Development and Labour Council (Nedlac) this week begins a process of dialogue between various parliamentary standing committees and the corresponding Nedlac chambers to ensure better co-ordination of processes.<BR><P>
PARANOIA <I>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
SA faces huge tasks, most notably where the economy and crime are concerned, if it is to emerge as one of the world's successful nations.  It would be foolish to underplay them.  By the same token, the tendency towards paranoia, whereby the gravity of problems is intensified, is hardly helpful.  Very often, commentators and the media are in danger of creating self-fulfilling prophecies.<BR><P>
GOVT FIGURES SET TO DISAPPOINT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
There are ominous signs that the SA government is battling to meet its revenue targets for this fiscal year.  Figures due for release this week are likely to show a disappointing tax performance - raising questions about government's ability to meet its deficit target.<BR><P>
SA PRODUCERS MAY ESCAPE CUTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Recent strengthening in the spot coal price could allow SA coal producers to escape price cuts in their export contracts into Europe for next year, industry sources said at the weekend.<BR><P>
FRANCE EYES SA COAL <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
French industry, desperate to cut energy costs, was having a hard look at low-priced SA coal, French trade sources said.  This was after a report by the Charbonnages de France (the national coal board) which said that French coal was the most expensive in the world, and SA coal one of the cheapest.<BR><P>
DEAL SIGNED TO EXPORT NATURAL GAS FROM PANDE TO SA <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
MAPUTO - Mozambique, SA and the US's Enron Corp signed a deal in Maputo on Friday to secure the export of natural gas to energy-hungry SA.<BR><P>
INDIAN OCEAN NATIONS TO DISCUSS DETAILS OF BLOC <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
MUSCAT, OMAN - Oman and six other countries bordering the Indian Ocean, including SA, would meet next month to discuss the details to set up an economic bloc, the Commerce Minister of Oman said yesterday.<BR><P>
GOLD RUSH IN BRITAIN <I>(Reuters</I>)<BR>
It may not quite be the Klondike or Kimberley, but Britain could be on the brink of a miniature gold rush.  Researchers from the British Geological Survey have identified 11 areas from the Scottish Highlands to south-western England where mines might be viable and dozens more where gold-bearing rocks exist.<BR><P>
CHINA FINDS POSSIBLE GOLD RESERVES IN XINJIANG <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
China has found two areas showing possible gold reserves in the far western region of Xinjiang, the official Xinhua news agency said on Thursday.<BR><P>
