<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 8 AUGUST 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>



RESERVES FALL AS ASSAULT ON RAND TAKES TOLL <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The South African Reserve Bank's gold and foreign exchange reserves plunged R883m in July to R10,37bn as the attack on the rand took its toll.<BR><P>
INTEREST RATES KEEP RISING IN MONEY MARKET <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Money-market interest rates rose further yesterday despite the Reserve Bank's intervention to combat sudden swings in liquidity.<BR><P>
LOWER COMMODITY PRICES KNOCK AMIC <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American Industrial Corp's attributable income fell 9% to R427m in the six months to June this year, knocked by lower commodity prices and weaker local demand.<BR><P>
CABINET APPROVES BURUNDI SANCTIONS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA Cabinet yesterday formally decided to uphold sanctions against Burundi in an attempt to restore democracy in the central African state.<BR><P>
NUM PAY DISPUTE UNRESOLVED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers and De Beers met in mediation yesterday without being able to resolve their wage dispute, but plan a conciliation board meeting next Friday.<BR><P>
CONCILIATION ON MINE WAGE TALKS <I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
NUM and the Chamber of Mines will go to conciliation next week in a bid to resolve the wage deadlock afflicting the industry.  The 350 000-strong NUM declared a wage dispute with the Chamber last Thursday.  The Chamber represents coal and gold mining management.  The union has demanded a 13% wage increase.  Frans Barker, the Chamber's spokesman, said goldminers had been offered increases of between 5% and 7,5% and coalminers increases of between 6,75% and 10%.<I> [The parties jointly agreed on the appointment of the national director of Independent Mediation Services of SA, Thandi Orleyn, as chairman of the CB. NUM plans to march on the Chamber of Mines to hand over a memorandum in support of their demands on Saturday, 17 August, before moving on to a rally to commemorate the 50th anniversay of the 1946 miners' strike - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
HOPE OF PRODUCTIVITY-BASED MINING WAGE DEAL DWINDLES <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
It looks like the mining industry's chances of achieving a productivity-based wage deal are dwindling as negotiations last week went into the dispute stage between the Chamber of Mines and NUM.<BR><P>
SA FIRMS EXPECT INCREASING FRAUD <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Nine out of 10 SA companies expect to experience increased fraud in the coming months, citing as reasons rising economic pressures, an erosion of society's values and the perception that the criminal justice system is inefficient, with sentences too lenient.<BR><P>
VISAS UNNECESSARY BY YEAR END SAYS BOLGER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
From the end of the year South Africans would no longer require visas to travel to New Zealand, New Zealand Prime Minister James Bolger said yesterday.<BR><P>
ZIMBABWEAN GOLD OUTPUT UP <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
BULAWAYO - Gold output in Zimbabwe rose 27% on last month to reach 2 370,41kg worth Z$287,1m, says Zimbabwe's Chamber of Mines.<BR><P>
FIRE HAMPERS MINE OUTPUT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The fire which has hampered production since April at Gold Fields East Driefontein gold mine has been put out - but production from the area will not restart immediately.<BR><P>
SA STILL AILING FROM LOW COMPETITIVENESS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The declining rand is providing a margin of protection against imports, but this will be only a passing respite from SA's ailing level of competitiveness, says Professor Saul Klein, visiting Wits Business School from the National University of Singapore.  SA was recently ranked in 44th place out of 46 nations in the world competitive survey.<BR><P>
CABINET CHOOSES PRIVATISATION ADVISER <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The Cabinet approved the appointment of an adviser to the government on privatisation and the restructuring of state assets yesterday.  The name was withheld to allow the Ministry of Public Enterprises under Stella Sigcau to "tie up a few loose ends".  The name is expected to be released today once the contenders on the shortlist have been notified.<BR><P>
STITCHING UP THE BOSSES <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
At a time when the government and business are calling for wage restraint to increase productivity and competitiveness, trade unionists are becoming increasingly irked that companies will not disclose their executives' pay. There will be a growing campaign over the coming months to force all companies to disclose what their directors and managers earn.<BR><P>
WHITHER THE GOLD PRICE? <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Gold has a way of flattering only to deceive.  The first part of this observation is repeating itself and the weeks ahead will reveal whether or not the deception will materialise again.<BR><P>
GROWTH STILL ON TARGET <I>(Business Mail, weekly with the Mail & Guardian)</I><BR>
The sharp reversal in the business confidence index for July came as no surprise, says Dr Ben van Rensburg, chief economist of Sacob, which compiles the monthly measure.  "Inflation, interest rates and the exchange rate climate were all wrong - and we see little chance of improvement in the short term", he says.<BR><P>
BOLGER OUTLINES NZ ECONOMIC SUCCESS <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Reduced state intervention had turned New Zealands economy into one of the highest performing ones in the world, NZ Prime Minister Jim Bolger said yesterday.<BR><P>
LEON HITS AT SOCIAL ENGINEERING BY ANC <I>(The Citizen)</I><BR>
Democratic Party leader Tony Leon last night lashed out at indiscriminate affirmative action, saying the government deemed it more important to try its hand at social engineering.<BR><P>
ANC ADMITS VIOLATIONS <I>(New Nation, weekly)</I><BR>
The African National Congress is to admit to executing a number of "enemy agents" who had infiltrated them and committed "serious crimes against the people" during the struggle against apartheid. These admissions, according to reliable sources, will be made by the organisation in its submissions to the Truth and Reconciliation Commission in two weeks time.<BR><P>
GINWALA TO CO-CHAIR US TRADE BODY <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The Speaker of South Africa's National Assembly, Frene Ginwala, is to become a co-chairperson of the Global Coalition for Africa, a Washington-based body which links the continent with its main trading partners.  The organisation, which was established in 1991, is a forum which monitors Africas most critical social and economic developments and seeks consensus on policies and programmes of action.<BR><P>
REMAINS OF MYSTERIOUS CITY FOUND IN KRUGER <I>(The Citizen)</I><BR>
The remains of a 16th century king and queen, possibly linked to the mysterious ruined city of Great Zimbabwe, have been uncovered in a walled citadel in the Kruger National Park, archaeologist have revealed.<BR><P>
SOON MORE INTERNET USERS THAN TV WATCHERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Internet has caught the imagination of businesses, businesspeople and individuals alike, despite its origins as a means of sharing and communicating information between universities, government and commercial researchers. The Internet has grown into a worldwide network with about 50-million users. It is estimated that within the next few years there will be more users of the Internet than television viewers across the globe.<BR><P>
SA RUGBY JOINS THE INTERNET <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA Rugby Football Union yesterday entered the hi-tech world of computers with the launch of its Internet homepage at Newlands. The address is <I>http://www.sarfu.org.za</I>.<BR><P>
