<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 7  AUGUST 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>




HIGHVELD STEEL BATTERED BY MARKET SLUMP <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The slump in the steel market has claimed its biggest scalp so far with Anglo American's Highveld Steel & Vanadium suffering a 60% drop in earnings for the six months to June.<BR><P>
PPI POINTS TO BRAKE ON INFLATION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Producer price inflation (PPI) in June rose to 6,1% from 5,8% in May, surprising economists who had expected a steeper increase because of the weaker rand.<BR><P>
PUBLIC HOLIDAY PENALTY CLAUSE DROPPED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Metal sector employers agreed to the National Union of Metal Workers of SA's demand for the removal of a controversial penalty clause from the industry's council agreement after the intervention of the Labour Department.<I> [The clause related to workers not being paid for public holidays if they were absent without leave the day before or after the holiday - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
IMPALA WAGE STRIKE ENDS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The four-day strike by 28 000 National Union of Mineworkers members at Impala Platinum Mines has been resolved and an agreement on wages reached.  The agreement signed yesterday provided for an average increase of 8,5% and improvements to the housing allowance.<BR><P>
SA, NIGERIA TIE KNOT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
President Mandela yesterday accepted the credentials of Nigeria's first High Commissioner of SA, Alhaji Shehu Malami, indicating a strengthening of diplomatic relations with the West African state.<BR><P>
ZAMBIAN CRISIS REALLY ONLY SA MEDIA 'MISPERCEPTION' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The media - and in particular the SA media - were responsible for the false perception that there was a political crisis in Zambia, said Zambian presidential aide Richard Sakala at a Johannesburg media briefing yesterday.<BR><P>
ZAMBIA WANTS TRADE DEAL WITH SA <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Zambia is set to demand a preferential trade agreement with SA after last week's preferential trade pact with Zimbabwe that forced the local clothing and textile industries to compromise on tariffs and local-content provisions.<BR><P>
BARRIERS COME DOWN <I>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
SA's regional reputation has been done a great deal of good by the sensible way in which its trade dispute with Zimbabwe has been settled. Not only has Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin retreated from an increasingly untenable position, but he has emerged with an agreement which will serve as a forerunner for trade deals with all of our neighbours.<BR><P>
CHILE IS A MODEL FOR SA, SAYS OGILVIE THOMPSON <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Africa's policymakers still sought to extract high levels of direct rents from mining rather than wait for indirect benefits accruing from resultant investment opportunities, Anglo American Corp chairman Julian Ogilvie Thompson said yesterday. Commonalities between SA and Chile - which included economies where mining played a central role, and their emergence from periods of autocratic rule - made the Latin American experience of "more direct relevance" to SA than Southeast Asia, he said.<BR><P>
FULL AGENDA FOR BOLGER, BUT STILL TIME FOR RUGBY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
New Zealand Prime Minister Jim Bolger arrived in SA yesterday for a four-day visit.  Bolger, accompanied by his wife, Joan, was met at Johannesburg International Airport by Sports Minister Steve Tshwete and Foreign Affairs director-general Rusty Evans. During his visit he will hold talks with political and business leaders and is scheduled to accompany President Nelson Mandela to Saturday's rugby Test between the All Blacks and the Springboks at Newlands in Cape Town.<BR><P>
SANDF CAN PLAY VITAL ROLE IN ENSURING INVESTOR CONFIDENCE<I>(Business Day)</I><BR> 
<I>by Ronnie Kasrils, Deputy Defence Minister</I><BR>
The recent visits abroad by President Mandela and Deputy President Mbeki illustrate the fund of goodwill that exists towards SA.  Crucial to the prospects for our country is our ability to translate this support into substantial long term investment. The stability is what Defence Minister Joe Modise is seeking through his positioning of defence in our new economic vision.<BR><P>
COERCION WILL NOT AID EMPLOYMENT EQUITY PROGRAMME <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
While the recently released green paper on employment equity rejects set quotas, it nevertheless introduces an element of coercion into the labour relations field in SA.  All companies will be required to conduct audits to provide information on possible discriminatory practices in areas such as hiring, promotion, training, pay benefits and retrenchments and submit this information regularly to the Labour Department.<BR><P>
NEC DRAWING UP VOTING POOL AGREEMENT FOR JOHNNIC DEAL <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Members of the National Empowerment Consortium are drafting a voting pool agreement that will effectively govern the consortium's running of Johnnies Industrial Corp if it acquires the conglomerate from Anglo American.<BR><P>
BUSINESS CONFIDENCE NOSEDIVES <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
South African business confidence nose-dived last month to its lowest level in 10 months as industrial unrest unsettled business and a further rand depreciation shocked the market.<BR><P>
ALLIANCE SHOWDOWN ON THE CARDS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The government may have declared its macro-economic plan to be non-negotiable, but its allies in organised labour have yet to get the message. Zwelinzima Vavi, assistant general secretary of Cosatu, said this week that continued debate over economic policy could not be silenced. <I>[The strength of the alliance between the African National Congress, the Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu) and the SA Communist Party has come into sharp focus in SA, especially against the backdrop of the government's stated commitment to privatisation and other measures to liberalise the economy - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
GOLDEN GAMBLING GOOSE READY TO LAY <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
With billions of rands and thousands of jobs at stake, SA's economists will need to factor the embryonic gambling industry into their calculations for next year.  Prospective participants in the bonanza ahead are not playing games.  They are looking at huge complexes, with investments in the 30 licences up for grabs likely to range from R70m to R700m for the casino alone. Additional funding for peripherals like hotels and convention centres could boost the figure by anything up to R300m a complex. <BR><P>
LONRHO INVESTS $20M IN ZAMBIAN PROJECTS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Lonrho has invested more than $20m in capital projects in Zambia in the past 12 months, Dieter Bock, Lonrho's CE, said.<BR><P>
CANADA SELLS 32,000 OUNCES OF GOLD IN JULY <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Canada sold 32 000 ounces of gold in July, bringing reserves to 3.1m ounces as of July 31, the Finance Department said on Tuesday.<BR><P>
GOLD-BACKED BONDS COULD HELP EUROPE TO EMU <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Gold-backed bonds could address two of the main concerns about Europe's adoption of single currency, according to precious metals analyst Andy Smith of Union Bank of Switzerland.<BR><P>
COAL STRIKE - RUSSIA <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Russia's independent miners' union on Tuesday threatened to stage a national coal strike on August 25 unless the government paid their wages and forced other companies to settle their debts to collieries.<BR><P>
