<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 6 AUGUST 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>




GOLD BREAKS ITS SHACKLES TO TEST $390 <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Gold broke out of its stubborn trading range yesterday, bursting through $389/oz to test $390 amid a surge of speculative buying in Japan and short-covering on the New York commodities exchange.<BR><P>
SAMANCOR POWERS TO 82% INCOME HIKE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Surging ferrochrome contract and spot prices and a weaker rand exchange rate powered Samancor to an 82% increase in attributable income of R676m for the year to June.<BR><P>
INDUSTRY PROMISE SEES STRIKE ABORTED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Countrywide mass action by 100 000 metal workers planned for tomorrow has been called off in the wake of an employer undertaking to remove a contentious penalty clause from the main agreement, paving the way for a settlement in the metal industry.<I> [The "penalty clause" relates to workers not being paid for public holidays if they are absent the day before or day after a holiday - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
WORKPLACE RIGHTS DIVISION - POLL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
South Africans remain divided over the right to strike and lock-out, a survey conducted by Markinor shows,<I> [with most whites supporting the right to lock-out over the right to strike, and blacks support indicating an opposite stance - Ed.]</I>.<BR><P>
SA CAN RAISE 'CHUNK OF CASH' ON GERMAN MARKET <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA could easily raise much more than R1bn when it tapped the German bond market later this year, market sources said yesterday. <BR><P>
WORKERS REPORT AT RUSPLATS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The majority of workers from Rustenburg Platinum's Rustenburg section and about half the workforce at Union section had reported for work yesterday, Rustenburg Platinum Mines said.<BR><P>
MAJOR CONFLICT RISK - SUNTER<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The world now risks slipping into a situation where a major conflict becomes inevitable, maintains Clem Sunter, author of SA and international high- and low-road scenarios, and chairman of Anglo American corporate affairs.<BR><P>
GAP IN GOLD SUPPLY ECONOMIC RUBBISH <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
LONDON - The concept that there is a growing "gap" between conventional gold supply and demand - frequently used by gold bulls to explain why the price inevitably must go up sharply and soon - is "economic rubbish", according to Merrill Lynch investment group metals specialist Ted Arnold.<BR><P>
MALAYSIA'S INVESTORS LOOK TO LONG-TERM SA PROSPECTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Malaysian businesses have blazed an acquisition trail across SA during the past two years, pumping resources into sectors ranging across property, energy, food and banking.<BR><P>
EMPLOYERS AIM FOR OWN 'COSATU' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The National Employers' Forum planned to recruit a membership of about 20 000 businesses in the next six months in its efforts to become the "Cosatu of employers", marketing director Henry Holland said yesterday. <I>[Cosatu - the Congress of SA Trade Unions and a close alliance partner with the African National Congress - is SA's largest trade union federation - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
US ECONOMY APPEARS TO BE ON EXPANSION PATH <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - With the US at a crossroads between moderate and above-trend growth, the economy appears well on a path toward continued expansion.<BR><P>
STILL NO DECISION ON PRIVATISATION ADVISER<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
The intergovernmental committee on the restructuring of state assets met yesterday to discuss the appointment of a private-sector firm to advise the government on restructuring and privatisation, but by late yesterday it had not released a statement.<BR><P>
GOVT TARDINESS HURTS INDUSTRY <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Decision-makers in the government are paralysed by the obligation to make decisions in the open and are soft-pedalling on issues confronting industry, Doug de Jager, the chairman of Lenco Holdings, said at the annual meeting yesterday.<BR><P>
IMPLATS AGAIN REVISES WAGE OFFER TO STRIKERS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Impala Platinum Mine management presented the National Union of Mineworkers with a second revised wage offer last night in an attempt to break the strike at the mine during a third bout of negotiations. <I>[Details of the revised offer are not disclosed in the report - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
BRAZIL GOLD MINE PROTEST COSTS CVRD $5M SO FAR <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
RIO DE JANEIRO - A protest by prospectors in Brazil's Para state, which has halted surveys at a giant gold mine, has cost state mining giant Companhia Vale do Rio Doce $5m so far, a CVRD spokesman said.<BR><P>
CHILEAN MINING OUTPUT CLIMBS 17% IN JUNE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SANTIAGO - Chilean mining production climbed 17% in June compared with the same month last year, said the National Statistics Institute.<BR><P>
FACING UP TO DECLINING RAND <I>(The Star, Jhb., Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
The punches can no longer be pulled. SA now faces a straight choice - it either takes a strong stand against militant labour unions or faces the bleak prospect of a chronically weak currency. Economists ascribe the rands slide to several factors, among them labour opposition to governments macro-economic policy; recurring rumours that Reserve Bank governor Chris Stals plans to resign; and slow progress on privatisation and the removal of exchange controls. <I>[Despite President Mandelas reassurances regarding Stals post]</I> At the end of the day, however, there is little room for argument that the major reason foreigners are selling rands is disillusionment with a nation which displays a marked unwillingness to work for its living. This goes hand in hand with their doubt about the governments ability to deliver effective economic management. The government must contain the strike epidemic from which the country is suffering.<BR><P>
WHITE MALES STILL DOMINATE IN AFRICA <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
It is not only in SA where whites still hold the lions share of company directorships. In many African countries - with the exception of Nigeria - white men dominate the boards of leading companies , according to a survey by MacGregor Information Services.<BR><P>

<I>BUSINESS DAY</I> MOVES TO NEW OFFICES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
<I>Business Day</I> is moving offices this week. The editorial department will leave 11 Diagonal Street on Thursday and Friday for its new premises in Bierman Avenue, Rosebank. Business Day TV  and the I-Net news service will move at the same time. The new address is Second Floor, TML House, 4 Bierman Ave, Rosebank. Postal: PO Box 1745, Saxonwold, 2132. Telephone and fax numbers are:<BR>
Switchboard:	(+27 11) 280-3000<BR>
Faxes:	News Desk		280-5600<BR>
