<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 2 AUGUST 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>



NUM DECLARES WAGE DISPUTE WITH MINES <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers has declared a dispute with the Chamber of Mines after nearly two months of intense negotiations. [Click <A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/releases/dsput96.htm">here </A>for full text of a Chamber release issued lastnight.]<BR><P>
GUARD KILLED, 'MUTILATED' NEAR PLATINUM MINE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A white security guard was abducted and killed near Rustenburg Platinum Mine on Wednesday, allegedly by workers fired after a strike last month.<BR><P>
MENELL MEMORIAL<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A memorial service is to be held for Anglovaal deputy chairman Clive Menell, who died last week after a long illness - at the Market Theatre in Johannesburg on Sunday [4/8/96].<BR><P>
HOLOMISA RISKS EXPULSION AFTER ATTACK ON ANC <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Sacked Deputy Environment Affairs Minister Bantu Holomisa risks expulsion from the African National Congress after he attacked the party and certain of its leaders yesterday, claiming that they had received financial favours from hotel magnate Sol Kerzner.<BR><P>
STALS BEST MAN FOR THE JOB, SAYS MANDELA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
President Mandela threw his support behind Reserve Bank governor Chris Stals yesterday, reiterating Stals' denial of market talk that he might quit his post early. <BR><P>
WARNING ON RESERVE BANK POWERS ISSUED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Reserve Bank would be powerless to defend the currency if capital inflows into SA were halted or reversed, Board of Executors Asset Management said in its latest investment outlook.<BR><P>
BIG CAPITAL MARKET REFORMS ON THE CARDS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Major capital market reforms are in the pipeline to bring SA in line with international practice - to the disgust of some speculators in the market.<BR><P>
GOVT POSTS FACE THE AXE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
More than 120 000 public service posts are vacant and 100 000 of them will be abolished, Public Service Minister Zola Skweyiya has confirmed in reply to a parliamentary question from Democratic Party MP Kobus Jordaan.<BR><P>
POLICE UNION WARNS OF POSSIBLE STRIKE ACTION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA Police Union yesterday warned of possible labour action, saying anger was mounting among members over the new salary grading system which came into effect on Wednesday.<BR><P>
COSATU DEBATE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu) officials meet today to finalise a position on a response to government's macro-economic strategy.  This comes in anticipation of the weekend alliance meeting which will focus extensively on the issue and is expected to generate intense debate.<BR><P>
UNIONS OPPOSE TRANSNET WAGE OFFER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Three predominantly white unions within transport parastatal, Transnet, declared a wage dispute with the company yesterday after they refused to accept a wage option which would effectively narrow the wage gap between the lowest and higher paid workers.<BR><P>
LABOUR WARNED AGAINST RELYING ON PARL. DEMOCRACY<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
An Australian trade unionist has warned SA labour against relying on parliamentary democracy to deliver on union objectives.<BR><P>
ZIMBABWE PAPER 'INSULTED MANDELA IN EDITORIAL<I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The South African  High Commission in Harare accused the state-controlled <I>Herald </I>newspaper yesterday of insulting President Nelson Mandela in an editorial which suggested SA was reviving Cecil Rhodes' dream of dominating the region.<BR><P>
US EMBASSY CLEARED OF REFUGEES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Fifty eight African refugees who demanded resettlement aid yesterday forced their way on to the premises of the US embassy in Pretoria and were removed by police, SAPS spokesman Dave Harrington said.<BR><P>
RIDING IT OUT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The rand's sudden plunge this week has raised the fear that the Reserve Bank could be forced into another hike in Bank rate.  The worry that economic growth might have to suffer even more as SA hangs on to its meagre foreign exchange reserves has prompted a lot of soul searching.<BR><P>
ANGLOVAAL DYNASTY TO STAY INTACT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglovaal is set to become the first mining dynasty in the history of the industry in this country to see family control pass on to a third generation.<BR><P>
MINING GREEN PAPER DELAYED <I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
The Green Paper on mineral and mining policy, which was due to be released for public discussion this week, had been delayed for a month, Jan Bridell, a deputy director-general at the Mineral and Energy Affairs Department, said yesterday.  He said the government steering committee was still reviewing a draft of the paper, which will initiate a review of mining policy.<BR><P>
SA AND SENEGAL SIGN INVESTMENT AGREEMENT <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Presidents Mandela and Abdou Diouf, his Senegalese counterpart, signed a declaration of intent in Pretoria yesterday to negotiate the promotion and reciprocal protection of investments.  In the past two years, Senegal has granted mining licences to a number of SA miners.<BR><P>
GOLD OUTPUT RISES <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
SA gold output rose 2,8% to 41 800kg in June from May, the second consecutive monthly increase, the Chamber of Mines said yesterday.  Cumulative production for the first half of the year was 247 096 tons, 4,3% down on last year.<BR><P>
IMPLATS REVISES WAGE OFFER <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Implats revised its wage offer in negotiations with the NUM last night in an attempt to end a strike which enters its second day today, company spokesman Anne Dunn said yesterday.<BR><P>
GOVT TO SELL R1BN IN DM BONDS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The SA government will borrow about R1bn in Deutschmarks later this year by selling bonds denominated in that currency for the first time since it came to power in 1994, a senior official in the Finance Department said yesterday.<BR><P>
MINING OLD ORE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Raymond Pomario is a mine owner, a partner in the Dancarl diamond mine in Barkly West.  To the National Union of Mineworkers, he is the epitome of the old apartheid order, which regarded labour relations in the uncompromising, almost feudal, terms of master and servant.  That is why the union is about to launch an action against Dancarl for a series of claims on behalf of the mine's employees.<BR><P>
JOHNNIC BOARD SHAKE-UP LOOMS <I>(Business Mail, weekly)</I><BR>
The Johnnic board will have to be substantially restructured once the National Empowerment Consortium secures control of Anglo American's 48% stake in Johnnic, valued at R2,5bn.<BR><P>
STALS HITS BACK AT COSATU/US BANK'S RACISM CLAIM <I>(Business Mail)</I><BR>
The Reserve Bank has hit back at accusations of racism, brought by Cosatu at last week's bank collusion hearings and based on a confidential report by CS First Boston.<BR><P>
US SPECIALIST WARNS AGAINST UNBUNDLING <I>(Business Mail)</I><BR>
Do not unbundle or break up SA conglomerates;  rather hit them with heavy fines if they abuse their power, says a United States specialist.  "Breaking up a monopolist does not necessarily create competition," says Charles Stark of the US Government Antitrust Division.<BR><P>
COLUMBIA'S '96 COAL OUTPUT UP 15% OVER '95 <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BOGOTA - Columbia produced 15,02-million metric tons of coal in the first half of 1996, a level indicating production for the entire year will outstrip 1995 by about 15%, a government report said.<BR><P>
CHINA SHUTS ILLEGAL PITS, ARRESTS PROSPECTORS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BEIJING - China has closed 498 illegal gold pits and arrested 678 prospectors in two central provinces to try to stop gold being wasted through crude extraction techniques, the Economic Daily said on Thursday.<BR><P>
RUSSIAN MINERS ON STRIKE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
MOSCOW - Angry Russian miners on strike in the Far East were joined by their fellow workers in the south as the government failed to stem a tide of unrest among unpaid workers, a trade union official said on Thursday.<BR><P>
NP - OPPOSITION WITH A MISSION <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The National Party would develop a workable anti-poverty strategy as an alternative to the floundering Reconstruction and Development Programme, NP leader F W de Klerk announced yesterday.  Opening the partys first federal congress since it quit the government, he said the NP supported the RDP, but was deeply concerned about the way it was being managed. The NP also re-launched itself as "an opposition with a mission" and set 2004 as the year it would regain power.  The congress, the first the party has held since it quit the government of national unity at the end of June, is aimed at re-focusing the party in its new role as the largest opposition party in South Africa.<BR><P>
