<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 1 AUGUST 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>

RAND PLUMBS NEW DEPTHS AGAINST POUND <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
South Africa's unpopularity with foreign investors plunged to new depths yesterday when the rand hit a record low against the British pound and the Deutschmark.<BR><P>
ADDING VALUE TO THE PRECIOUS<I> (Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
Restrictions to going downstream in value-added projects in SA's mining industry pose a dilemma.  The irony is that in spite of the multiplier effect on the economy and its attractive job-creation prospect, downstream business development beyond first-stage beneficiation is relatively embryonic.<BR><P>
BENEFICIATION WILL SOLVE UNEMPLOYMENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA's pressing economic problems, such as unemployment and low foreign reserves, could be solved if local management embarked on a policy of beneficiation.  This is the view of Rex Glanville of international management consultants, Decision Processes International.<BR><P>
SA'S GOLD MINES HAVE A FUTURE - IF THEY CONSOLIDATE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The message coming through loud and clear from the gold mines' June quarterly reports is that the SA gold mining industry has a future.  It will be a very different industry from the one investors are used to though.<BR><P>
AMPLATS SHRUGS OFF LABOUR DISRUPTIONS  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American Platinum Corp lifted attributable income to R319,5m (1995: R265,3m) for the year to June as the higher rand platinum price offset production disruption from increased public holidays and lacklustre dollar prices.<BR><P>
4 000 BEGAN STRIKE AT IMPALA PLATINUM   <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Impala Platinum Mines reported last night that about 4 000 workers from Bafokeng North mine had failed to report for the night shift.<I><B> [Reuters reported earlier this morning that all 25 000 mine and smelter workers had now gone on strike - Ed.]</B></I><BR><P>
FREE STATE BUSINESS HURT BY UNCERTAINTY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Political uncertainty in the Free State province and the suspension of five senior tourism and economic affairs department officials were seriously undermining business and investment confidence in the province, leading business representatives said yesterday.<BR><P>
SA DOES BADLY IN ECONOMIC SURVEY  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA had fared badly in a new international competitiveness report for not spending enough on developing its human resources, bringing up the tail-end in a 46-country survey.<BR><P>
COAL STRIKE CUT RAILAGE 30% <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The industrial action at Richards Bay Coal Terminal had cut the daily throughput of coal railed to the terminal by 30%, railways parastatal, Spoornet said yesterday.<BR><P>
BID TO MEET BILL DEADLINE  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The National Economic Development and Labour Council (Nedlac) outlined an agenda yesterday whereby labour, government and business could finalise negotiations on employment standards legislation to ensure the parliamentary deadline was met.<BR><P>
NIGERIA FOCUSES ON COAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
PORT HARCOURT - African oil giant Nigeria has shipped its first consignment of coal in more than 20 years as it moves to diversify its oil dependent economy.<BR><P>
DEELKRAAL'S THROUGHPUT TO RISE BEFORE CASH CALL  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold Fields of SA's gold mine Deelkraal needed to lift its milled throughput before it could tap shareholders for funds for vital development at the mine, the group said yesterday.<BR><P>
PORTNET TO TIGHTEN 'CRITICAL' SECURITY AT SA HARBOURS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Security at SA's ports would be beefed up amid growing concern about the extent of illegal imports and exports slipping through the country's harbours, tarnsport utility, Transnet's executive director Sipho Nyawo said yesterday.<BR><P>
HARDY IS KEY TO GOLD MINE'S TURNAROUND  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gengold believes it has a secret weapon in the form of mine manager Joe Hardy, whose track record in turning around failing gold operations has won him the nickname of "firefighter".<BR><P>
GAUGING COMPETITIVENESS IS INEXACT SCIENCE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The International Institute for Management Development, a business school in Lausanne, Switzerland, and the World Economic Forum, also based in Switzerland, had a scrap late last year which ended in divorce.  The organisations parted company, but the break-up had positive consequences.  It reminded international businessmen and policy-makers that the forum's annual ranking of economies according to their competitiveness had always had shortcomings.<BR><P>
NEWMONT Q2 GOLD OUTPUT UP 30% TO RECORD <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Newmont Mining Corp said on Wednesday gold production in the second quarter rose 30% to a record 549,800 equity ounces.<BR><P>
BRAZIL PREPARES FOR CVRD PRIVATISATION <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BRASILIA - Brazil's National Privatisation Council approved on Wednesday the execution of several bureaucratic measures standing in the way of the privatisation of mining conglomerate Companhia Vale do Rio Doce.<BR><P>
ULTIMATE CAPE NET SITE LAUNCHED TODAY <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
Almost everything you ever wanted to know about the Western Cape will be accessible at one address with the launch today of a unique Internet home page.  The Cape Connection - on the world wide web site<A HREF="http://africa.cis.co.za/cape/cape.html"> http://africa.cis.co.za/cape/cape.html</A> - is being launched by the Council for Scientific & Industrial Research (CSIR) to provide users of the Internet with a one-point source of information on the Western Cape.<BR><P>
