<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 30 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>




IMF GIVES NOD TO GOVT'S FOREX STRATEGY <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - The International Monetary Fund signalled at the weekend that the rand's fall was overdone and that government was following the right strategy on easing exchange controls.<BR><P>
SA STILLS NEEDS EXCHANGE CONTROLS - IMF <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - SA should continue to improve its standing in financial markets before eliminating exchange controls, a senior official of the IMF's African Department said on Saturday.<BR><P>
GERMANS FIRM ON BLOCKING SALES OF GOLD TO HELP POOR <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - Germany is refusing to budge on allowing the IMF to sell about $2bn of its gold stocks to help finance debt relief for poor countries. Germany's tough stance looked set yesterday to delay a decision until long after this year's joint IMF/World Bank annual general meetings.<BR>
<B><I>... but ...</I></B><BR>
IMF LEAVES OPEN QUESTION OF GOLD SALES - AGAIN <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - The IMF's policy-making Interim Committee pledged on Sunday to find the money needed to finance stepped-up aid to the world's poorest nations, but stopped short of spelling out where the funds would come from.  The decision, announced in a communiqué issued after a day of talks, effectively left open the question of whether the IMF will eventually sell off some of its gold for that purpose.<BR><P>
GOLD PRODUCTION IN SA HEADS FOR A 40-YEAR LOW <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SAs gold production was set to slide to a 40-year low of 500 tons this year before beginning a slow ascent as new and enlarged mines started to contribute from next year, analysts said at the weekend.<BR><P>
BIG GOLD MINERS SEEK EL DORADO AROUND GLOBE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - The world's biggest gold miners, with an eye to expansion, are enthusiastically staking out projects in gold-rich countries recently considered too politically risky for investment.  In sharp contrast SA, still the world's top producer, is struggling to stem a decline in output and the mature industry here holds little interest for expansion.<BR><P>
DRINK MOOTED AS MINE VIOLENCE CAUSE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Excessive drinking among mineworkers could have been a major factor in recent mine violence, the Myburgh commission into the violence heard on Friday.<BR><P>
NEDLAC REPORT CALLS FOR TAX INCENTIVES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The grant-based regional development programme - an investment support scheme linked to the former homelands - should be changed into a tax-based scheme, says a National Economic Development and Labour Council (Nedlac) report due for release today.<BR><P>
LOST 'MAN DAYS' UP IN FIRST NINE MONTHS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Man-days lost for the year to end-September rose to 1,35m compared with 870 000 for the same period last year, according to the Andrew Levy & Associates strike survey released at the weekend.<BR><P>
MANY EU FIRMS TO EXHIBIT AT ELECTRA MINING EXHIBITION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
About 35 European Union-based companies will take part in Electra Mining 96 - the mining, electrical engineering and industrial exhibition to be held at Nasrec, Johannesburg, this week.  This is partly the result of the EU including SA in its export promotion programme for the first time.<BR><P>
DEPT BUDGET OF R10M FOR CONSULTANTS 'TOO LITTLE' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The R10m budget allocation to the Public Enterprises Department for advice from privatisation consultants would probably be insufficient in the long term and the Cabinet would be approached for an increase after all, a Departmental source said at the weekend.<BR><P>
DEVELOPING NATIONS DECIDE ON NEW ATTITUDE TO G-7 <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - The G-24 group of developing countries decided at the weekend to drop its traditionally confrontational attitude towards the Group of Seven leading industrialised nations.  Finance officials of the G-24, which groups African, Asian and Latin American countries, said after meeting at the annual gathering of the IMF and World Bank, they now wanted to try a more constructive approach to influence world financial policies.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
G-7 FORECAST ECONOMIC GROWTH, PLEDGE DEBT-RELIEF PLAN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - The Group of Seven richest industrial nations delivered an upbeat outlook for the world economy at the weekend, saying inflation was low and forecasting faster growth into next year. <BR><P>
SA NEEDS TO WEIGH OPTIONS CAREFULLY BETWEEN CHINA AND TAIWAN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The recent visit by Hsu Li-the, vice-premier of Taiwan, has brought to a head what is for SA a particularly vexing problem.  In the terrain of our international relations, no other problem is at present more intriguing, or has as great an effect on SA's approach to East Asia than that of the recognition issue between China and Taiwan.<BR><P>
PSYCHOTIC POLITICIANS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A British Psychological Society research report says politicians often have "the same personality profiles as criminal psychopaths".  Their traits include "a high sense of self-worth, failing to accept responsibility for actions, having a socially deviant lifestyle, needing constant stimulation, remorselessly using others and being glib" <I>[as if we didnt know ...</I>].<BR><P>
DUTCH PROBE SA INVESTMENT SCOPE <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The Dutch Queen is being accompanied on her state visit by Dutch Foreign and Economic Affairs ministers and 29 businessmen who have come to assess investment opportunities.<BR><P>
