<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 27 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>


<I>RECENT VIOLENT INCIDENTS ON SOME S.A. MINES ...</I><BR>
SOWETAN EDITORIALCOMMENT <BR>
"What is it about the mines that people from different ethnic groups are kept in separate accommodation?<BR>
 "It was understandable for the apartheid regime to force people from different ethnic backgrounds into different townships and separate bantustans. Mining houses furthered the policy by keeping workers in separate living quarters at the mines and made them work different shifts. <BR>
"We expected that rubbish from people who did not have the interests of the majority of South Africans citizens at heart. 
"Today this is no longer acceptable. It is no longer politically correct. It stinks of apartheid.<BR>
 "Some mining houses integrate their workers and at such mines, there has been little or no ethnic violence. 
"Other mines are guilty of iniquitous acts against humanity for continuing with apartheid. <BR>
"When people are forcibly kept apart and told that they are different, and suspicions are cast on other groups there will be trouble. That trouble has manifested itself many times in the form of violence. <BR>
"This week more than 20 people were killed in clashes between Xhosa-speaking and Sotho-speaking people.<BR> 
"The mining houses that practise apartheid among their workers have to answer to South Africa. There is a lot of blood on their hands as a result of practising apartheid."<BR><P>
<I>[The following letter, under signature of the President of the Chamber, has been sent to Sowetan:</I><BR>
<B>27 September 1996<BR>
The Editor<BR>
Sowetan<BR>
Dear Sir,<BR><P>

The Chamber of Mines of South Africa, representing the bulk of this countrys mining interests, wishes to voice its objection to the ill-informed and unhelpful editorial on "mine violence" published in your edition of Friday, 27 September 1996.<BR><P>

At a time of highly sensitive and charged human relations on our mines, editorial comments such as yours neither contribute towards finding workable solutions to very real problems nor help in building a climate of reconciliation so necessary in our country. It is both naïve and simplistic to suggest, as you do, that so-called segregation of mine hostels is the single cause of the recent deplorable and wholly unacceptable incidents of violence on some mines. This point has been supported by none other than Labour Minister Tito Mboweni. In fact, one of the mines on which violence recently occurred has fully integrated hostels.<BR><P>

A judicial Commission of Inquiry, appointed by President Nelson Mandela and under Judge President of the Labour Court Mr Justice John Myburgh, is currently conducting a serious and intensive investigation into recent violent incidents on three mines. Its findings are due to be made known within a few days. We await the outcome in the belief that it will provide a far better explanation than the superficial and ill-informed one you have put forward.<BR><P>

The Chamber of Mines and all its members unequivocally condemn all incidents of violence, be they on mines or in the broader community. The mining industry has given its uncompromising support to the new South Africa and the democratic principles upon which it is founded. In the present emotionally charged atmosphere your inflammatory and ill-conceived accusations will more likely fan the flames of violence than quell them. They will also more likely exacerbate divisions between people than reconcile them. <BR><P>

Yours sincerely,<BR>
At du Plessis<BR>
President<BR>
Chamber of Mines of South Africa</B><BR><P>

MINE PEACE IS SHATTERED  <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A precarious peace in Stilfontein mine hostels was again shattered on Wednesday night with the killing of another three miners in an ethnic-based conflict. Three more employees of Buffelsfontein Gold Mine were injured in the clash between Xhosa and Sotho workers, while a man who had been severely  slashed in the face during a previous incident died in the intensive care unit at the Tshepong Hospital in Klerksdorp at 5 am yesterday.<BR><P>
NUM PROTEST FANNED MINE VIOLENCE - OFFICIAL <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Premature industrial action by the National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) during wage negotiations played a part in the recent outbreak of violence at Gold Fields'  East Driefontien mine, chief personnel officer Victor Raison said yesterday during an inquiry into mine violence.<BR><P>
FEARS MOUNT OVER MINE INQUIRY  <I>(Mail and Guardian, weekly on Fridays)</I><BR>
In the week when at least 24 mineworkers were slain, fears are mounting that a major judicial inquiry into mine violence will be torpedoed by the absence of the United Workers Union of South Africa (UWUSA) from the proceedings. The commission of inquiry is concentrating on the spate of killings at [three] Goldfields mines in recent months which has left 48 workers dead. The battle, mainly between Uwusa and the National Union of Mineworkers (NUM), has stripped almost R70-million from Goldfields profits.<BR><P>
WEST RAND CONSOLIDATED MINES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
West Rand Consolidated Mines said today it would distribute to shareholders for no consideration 17,5m ordinary shares of 1c each in Kalahari Goldridge Mining Co. in the ratio of 100 distribution shares for every 100 West Rand shares held.<BR><P>
TRANS HEX GROUP <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A unit of SA diamond producer Trans Hex Group would raise up to $22m Canadian in a private placing.  Toronto-based Trans Hex International said yesterday the proceeds would be used to expand exploration on diamond properties in Zimbabwe, the Central African Republic, Indonesia, Namibia and Brazil.<BR><P>
OZ FIRM BUYS 24% OF KNIGHTS  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Australian gold mining company, Continental Goldfields has acquired 24,3% or 63,9-million shares of South African gold producer Knights Gold Mining Company for R25,6-million or A$7,22-million. Knights produces 50 000 ounces of gold annually, primarily from the retreatment of tailings dumps located adjacent to Johannesburg, Continental Goldfields said.<BR><P>
ACCUSATIONS FLY AT SOUTH WITS MEETING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The struggle for control of Southern Witwatersrand Exploration continued at the company's annual general meeting yesterday, with directors and shareholders trading accusations of insider trading and breach of fiduciary duties.<BR><P>
DEVELOPMENT BANK SCRAPS 55 SENIOR MANAGEMENT JOBS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Development Bank of Southern Africa has axed 55 of its 75 senior management posts in a major restructuring of its business.<BR><P>
UNION MAJORITY IN FAVOUR OF POLICY TALKS WITH GOVT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The majority of National Union of Metalworkers of SA (Numsa) regions are willing to negotiate with government about its macro-economic policy, debate at the union congress at Kempton Park showed yesterday.<BR><P>
MBEKI DODGES THE CRUCIAL QUESTION <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, guest speaker at the Numsa fifth conference on Wednesday night, spoke of 350 years of colonialism and how difficult it was to transform an animal which had serviced a white minority.  He spoke of how political emancipation was achieved with President Mandela's inauguration, but not economic equality.  He promised 400 000 new jobs a year within four years.  The applause was courteous, probably two or three claps by two thirds of the audience.  The sound that lingered longest was a statement tagged on to the end of a privatisation question:  "We keep on being told that we are not free.  When are we going to be free?"  Unlike May 10 1994, there was no date forthcoming from Mbeki.<BR><P>
GOLD KNOCKED BY HINT OF IMF SALES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The rand and the gold price came in for a drubbing yesterday with the currency breaking through the critical R4,5250 level and the metal losing $1,60 on news of <I>[possible]</I> International Monetary Fund gold sales.<BR><P>
IMF GOLD SALE PLANS IRK WORLD'S BIG GOLD PRODUCERS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Big gold producers on Thursday said the IMF's plan to sell gold reserves was helping depress the price of gold bullion.  "There is uncertainty hanging over the market right now as to what the IMF will do", said Sam Jonah, CE of Ashanti Goldfields Company Ltd.<BR><P>
IMF IS MODESTLY UPBEAT ABOUT SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - While it is worried about inflation, fiscal imbalances, the weakness of the rand and unemployment, the IMF sounds a modestly upbeat note about SAs short-term economic prospects in the latest release of its semi-annual publication, World Economic Outlook.<BR><P>
STALS, IMF BEG TO DISAGREE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
In the latest World Economic Outlook publication, the IMF distances itself from central bankers who, like Stals, aim to bring inflation down to zero.  The IMF heaps praise on central bankers who set official inflation targets, something Stals has refused to do.<BR><P>
MANDELA PROMISES TIGHT BAIL CONDITIONS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Legislation to tighten bail conditions would go ahead despite threats by 'idealists' to take the government to the Constitutional Court over the matter, President Mandela said yesterday.<BR><P>
UNIONS MODERATE DEMANDS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Overall wage settlements of 9,9% for the year to date indicated that unions were moderating their demands in the light of the current economic reality, an Andrew Levy & Associates survey says.<BR><P>
SA-EU TRADE AGREEMENT UNLIKELY BEFORE 1998 <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA was unlikely to conclude the proposed free trade agreement with the European Union before 1998, given delays in resuming formal negotiations, Brussels sources said yesterday.<BR><P>
ERWIN TO ADDRESS IDC TO CLARIFY GOVT EXPECTATIONS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin is to meet the board and staff of the Industrial Development Corporation to outline the parastatal's mandate - a move designed to reassert government's control of state-owned enterprises.<BR><P>
WORKERS WEIGHED DOWN BY LEGACY OF COLONIALISM, APARTHEID <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Some are questioning whether the preconditions for corporatist-type decision-making exist in SA.  It is argued labour lacks the capacity to participate effectively in these "social democratic-type institutions".  Furthermore it is argued government and employer associations have not demonstrated political readiness to accept union participation in policy making.<BR><P>
SA TO RECEIVE US DEVELOPMENT AID <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
SA will receive R250m in development aid from the US under a formal agreement to be signed on Monday by Gill Marcus, Deputy Finance Minister, and James Joseph, US Ambassador to SA.  The aid will be used to finance housing, healthcare, education and economic development, among other things.<BR><P>
STEEL LOAN 'ON HOLD' <I>(Business Mail - with Mail & Guardian)</I><BR>
The European Commission has not blocked a $74m loan to the Saldanha Steel project, merely reserved judgement.  The EC has sent the file back to the European Investment Bank for further consideration, says Erwan Fouere, EU's Ambassador to SA. <BR><P>
PRIVATE FINANCE GROWS <I>(Business Mail)</I><BR>
The World Bank's private sector financing organisation approved a record $3,2b in loans for the fiscal year ended June 30, reflecting the increasing emphasis placed by the bank on private sector aid.<BR><P>
POSITIVE PROSPECTS <I>(Business Mail)</I><BR>
Developing countries will post growth of more than 6% this year and next in response to economic recovery in Mexico and Argentina, stronger momentum in Africa and a more sustainable pace in Asia, the IMF said this week.<BR><P>
BRITAIN IS SQUEEZING THIRD WORLD DEBTORS <I>(Business Mail)</I><BR>
Britain is squeezing cash out of the world's poorest countries by demanding levels of debt repayment far outweighing new loans or aid, according to figures published this week.  As representatives of the world's richest creditor nations met in Paris on Monday to discuss initiatives intended to reduce the debt burden on the developing world, aid agencies say the first comprehensive analysis of lender countries undermines the British government's claim to be at the forefront of the campaign to help the world's poor.<BR><P>
DONT LEAVE SA, URGES MANDELA  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
President Mandela yesterday renewed calls on skilled South Africans not to leave the country, saying their expertise was vital to transformation. Reacting to reports linking emigration to crime and violence, he said in Pretoria his appeal applied especially to those who had enjoyed education and other opportunities which the majority had been denied.<BR><P>
JOBS AND ECONOMY ARE MAIN CONCERN IN SA  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
South Africans appeared to be more concerned about job provision and the economy than about crime, the Human Sciences Research Council said yesterday. Of 2 241 respondents to a recent countrywide survey, 41% said job creation was their main concern, 16% cited the economy, 13% cited crime and 10% cited housing, it said in a statement in Pretoria.<BR><P>
</DOC>
