<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 26 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>



POLICE SEIZE MINING EXPLOSIVES, WEAPONS  <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A large quantity of mining explosives and traditional weapons were seized during a police swoop at a mine hostel in Stilfontein in North West yesterday following three days of violence in which 21 people died. Police spokesman Captain Louis Jacobs said yesterday the explosives were found in rooms at the Scott hostel at the old Stilfontein mine.<I> [During SAfms morning talk-show, "Talk at Will" today, Labour Minister Tito Mboweni said a pressing issue was to determine how access to the explosives had been gained. He went on to say "many tensions - some not directly related to working conditions or language" were behind the recent incidents of violence on some SA mines, and "it is too superficial to say it is just tribalism". - Ed.]</I><BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
THIRD FORCE IS FANNING MINE CONFLICT <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Investigations of recent violence at Goldfields SA's East Driefontein mine pointed to the possibility that a 'third force or criminal interest' was fanning ethnic conflict, SA Police Service Captain Eugene Potgieter said yesterday.<BR>
<B><I>... and furthermore ...</I></B><BR>
ETHNIC UPHEAVALS <I>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
The sudden upsurge of ethnic violence on the mines in recent weeks may seem surprising, given larger moves towards national reconciliation and the forging of one SA identity.  It is less disconcerting if one considers that certain contributory factors remain unchanged, and the ethnicity may mask deeper, economically based conflicts.<BR><P>
BID TO RESOLVE FIVE-WEEK NAMIBIAN STRIKE <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Mediation efforts started yesterday morning to try to resolve a five-week-old strike at Tsumeb in Namibia, Gold Fields Namibia, the owner, said.  The mines and smelters have been shut down since August 23 when Mineworkers' Union of Namibia members went on strike over pay.  The strike is costing Tsumeb about 80 tons a day in lost copper production and a similar amount in lost lead.<BR><P>
INGWE PROJECT AIMED AT LOST COAL TONNAGES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gencor coal company Ingwe is investigating reclaiming unmined portions of disused Witbank mines (in Mpumalanga province), with initial estimates indicating reserves capable of yielding 2,5m tons a year - worth about $80m a year at current export prices.<BR><P>
CANADIANS SEEK GOLD IN SWAZILAND <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
SouthernEra Resources, a Toronto-based mining company, said it had been granted rights to explore for gold in Swaziland at two sites which were large producers of gold in the last century.<BR><P>
PHILANTHROPY MAKES GOOD BUSINESS SENSE <I>(by Nick Segal, JCI, Business Day)</I><BR>
Business has to be concerned about the quality and potential of its workforce, as well as those factors that go to shape that quality.  Getting  involved in education, housing, environmental improvement and other community projects makes good business sense if it results in a more stable, motivated and productive work force<I>.[an edited version of a recent speech by Nick Segal, JCI Limited's director of Strategy and Corporate Affairs. Dr Segal is also one of two vice-presidents of the Chamber of Mines - Ed.] </I><BR><P>
MBEKI CALLS FOR STRONG UNIONS AND A FIRM ALLIANCE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Strong and independent trade unions and a strong ANC alliance were crucial to achieving a non-racial and democratic SA, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki told delegates to the fifth congress of the National Union of Metalworkers of SA (Numsa) in Kempton Park last night.<BR><P>
PACIFIC RIM EXAMPLE FOR SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
DURBAN - Government had to get moving with privatisation and exchange control relaxation to retain foreign investment levels, McCarthy Group chairman Brian McCarthy said in his annual review. He also said government, business and labour had to co-operate if targets set out in the macro-economic strategy were to be met.  "Look no further than the Pacific Rim countries whose economic growth rates have been the envy of the western world and whose hardworking management and staff accept that a market economy brings both sacrifices and benefits at different times", he said.<BR><P>
A 'COMPETITION TRIBUNAL' MIGHT POLICE BUSINESS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A task team responsible for rewriting SA's competition policy appears to have thrown out the US antitrust model in favour of a mixture of British and Canadian competition laws, sources close to the team say.<BR><P>
INTEREST RATES TO MOVE SIDEWAYS BEFORE DIPPING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Interest rates were likely to move sideways for the remainder of the year before moving lower over the next 12 months, World Group Software said in its latest survey.<BR><P>
SA GETS R14M IN AID <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The US Agency for International Development yesterday pledged a R14m grant to a consortium of non-governmental bodies involved in public interest law and human rights.<BR><P>
NEIGHBOURS BEAT SA FOR INVESTMENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - Worldwide, foreign direct investment by trans-national companies reached a record $315bn last year, but only $4m landed in SA, says the UN Conference on Trade and Development (Unctad) in its 1996 World Investment Report. The flow to SA was negligible even in comparison with that to its neighbours. Swaziland, for example, received $54m, Mozambique $36m, Zambia $66m, Zimbabwe $40m and Lesotho $23m.<BR><P>
PROSPECTS DIM FOR EARLY SOLUTION TO CONSTITUTIONAL DIFFERENCES <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
Prospects for an early resolution to constitutional differences between political parties dimmed on the first day of new talks yesterday when the IFP postponed a return to the process and the NP demanded a thorough review of disputed provincial powers.  The negotiators were meeting at Parliament to correct 10 defects in the draft adopted by the Constitutional Assembly on May 8.  The parties met last week and gave themselves until October 11 to remedy the defects the Constitutional Court ruled were reasons for its refusing to certify the draft.<BR><P>
POVERTY GAP TAKES CENTRE STAGE AT UN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
NEW YORK - The growing gulf between the world's rich and poor has taken centre stage at the UN General Assembly, with warnings of dire consequences if more is not done to close the "poverty gap".<BR><P>
RUSSIA SHOWS FIRST SIGNS OF GETTING OUT OF THE RED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
MOSCOW - The figures look good on Russia's long-suffering economy before next week's meetings of the World Bank and International Monetary Fund, but political doubts and concern on the budget have cast a shadow over the achievements.<BR><P>
CRIME, VIOLENCE SPURS BRAIN DRAIN  <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Most people emigrating from South Africa cited crime and violence as the reason, a report released yesterday shows. Five percent of middle management and high level specialist staff in 400 South African companies who resigned in the past year emigrated, human resource consultants FSA-Contact said in the report.<BR>
<B><I>... and, while reporting on FSA-Contact  ...</I></B><BR>
PAY HIKES LOWER THAN EXPECTED  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Private sector wage and salary increases in the year to August 1996 were slightly lower than had been predicted, however, pay rises remained above the inflation rate, matching those granted in 1995, FSA-Contact said in its finding.<BR><P>
IMF GOLD SALE CAN HURT SA, SAYS DP  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
International Monetary Fund proposals to sell off its gold reserves to help impoverished countries could result in jobs being lost and mines closing in South Africa, Democratic Party leader Tony Leon said yesterday. He called on the government to "make the most strenuous effort " at the IMF meeting in Washington to oppose any proposal on the sale of IMF gold reserves.<BR><P>
NEDLAC GIVES R3-M TO LABOUR MOVEMENT  <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
The National Economic Development and Labour Council (Nedlac) has spent R3-million towards education programmes on the new Labour Relations Act (LRA). The money was divided among the countrys three major trade union federations and small businesses according to size.<BR>
<B><I>... also on the LRA ...</I></B><BR>
NEW LABOUR ACT SPELLS END FOR FREE RIDERS  <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
The new Labour Relation Act is bound to change the face of industrial relations for the better, but workers will soon discover the ironies of democracy in the agency shop agreement clause. The clause is aimed at protecting trade unions against "free riders" and it entails that workers who choose not to belong to unions will now have to pay contributions equivalent to union members subscriptions.<BR><P>
SA MOVING TO PROVIDE SKILLS  <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
South Africa is trying hard to address a skills crisis attributed to policies of the past which ignored people development . Director-general of the Department of Labour Sipho Pityana says the problem is being addressed through the National Training Strategy initiative. A Green Paper on training and development is expected to be completed before the end of this year.<BR><P>
DONT MISJUDGE COSATUS WILLINGNESS TO ENTER NEW ERA  <I>(The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Cosatus (the Congress of SA Trade Unions) acceptance last week of the partial privatisation of some parastatal companies is a cautious but crucial step towards a new labour relations compact that can help South Africa cope with the formidable challenges of global competition. Some elements of the business press have described the policy shift as a sign that the labour federation is going soft. One headline said so in as many words. It was an observation as harmful as<I> [it was]</I> inaccurate. The decision in fact required considerable courage. Both business and unions have to move away from old, fixed positions if the accord is to be reached, and given our history of racist exploitation of labour, that is particularly difficult for union leaders.<BR><P>
</DOC>
