<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 25 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>


FAILURE TO PROSECUTE BEHIND MINE VIOLENCE - EXPERT <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The visible prosecution of perpetrators and an unequivocal commitment to peace by all mining industry stakeholders were the first steps needed to halt the <I>[current] </I>cycle of violence on SA mines, independent labour analyst and industrial anthropologist John Kent McNamara has said. <BR><P>
VIOLENCE FLARES AGAIN AT MINE  <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Violence flared again yesterday morning at a mine hostel in Stilfontein, where 21 people have already died, but police dispersed the about 200 fighting mineworkers and reported one casualty with serious head wounds. Rubber bullets and teargas were used to break up the opposing Xhosa and Sotho factions at Scott Hostel, part of the old Stilfontein Gold Mine complex and removed from Buffelsfontein Gold Mines Pioneer Hostel and Springvale where the violence originated.<BR><P>
SA DISCUSSES LOAN WITH WORLD BANK <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA had begun talks on a possible World Bank loan to help finance improvements to its international competitiveness, Finance Minister Trevor Manuel said this week.  <BR><P>
DEBT GROWS AS GOVERNMENT SELLS STOCK AT DISCOUNT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA government has been forced to add to its debt mountain to escape the short-term pressures of a more massive interest bill than it already has.<BR><P>
HIGHER VAT NOT ON THE CARDS<I> (Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
For now, the government is not planning to raise the rate of value-added tax in next years Budget despite pressure on its budget deficit targets, Maria Ramos, the director-general of Finance, said on Monday.<BR><P>
NEDLAC ENDORSES ANTI-CRIME STRATEGY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Social partners at the National Economic, Development and Labour Council (Nedlac) executive council meeting on Friday endorsed a range of strategies to fight crime and ensure the successful implementation of the new Labour Relations Act and housing policies.<BR> 
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
SACOB CALLS FOR A MINISTRY OF CRIME  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
A single Ministry of Crime should be created to end the situation in which crime has overwhelmed the capacity of law enforcement to contain it, says the quarterly political review of the SA Chamber of Business (Sacob).<BR>
<B><I>... and, also ...</I></B><BR>
LABOUR ACT CALL FOR CO-OPERATION  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
The Nedlac's executive council yesterday called on employers and shop stewards to ensure the smooth introduction of the new Labour Relations Act. Employer and worker co-operation was the key to the Acts successful implementation on November 11, the council said in a statement.<BR><P>
NATAL NETS R181M IN NEW FOREIGN INVESTMENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The KwaZulu-Natal Marketing Initiative helped attract R181m in foreign investment into the region in the 1995/96 fiscal year, chairman Peet Marais said this week.<BR><P>
TRANSPORT SECTOR FACING NATIONWIDE WAGE STRIKE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Seven transport unions representing 60 000 transport workers meet on Friday to finalise arrangements for a strike ballot in the goods transport sector following failure to resolve a wage dispute.<BR><P>
SAS WATER SCHEME DELEGATE RELIEVED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SAs delegate to the joint permanent technical commission of the Lesotho Highlands Water Project, Hans Pettenburger, was "relieved of his responsibilities" yesterday after giving an interview to the media.<BR><P>
DUTCH MORE LIBERAL ON SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
THE HAGUE - The Dutch government had a more "liberal position" on a trade pact with SA than many of its European partners, Dutch Prime Minister Win Kok said this week.<BR><P>
IMF TO USE RESERVE FUND TO FINANCE DEBT RELIEF SCHEME <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - The International Monetary Fund had found the means through one of its reserve funds to finance its participation in a debt relief scheme targeting the worlds poorest countries, a senior IMF official disclosed on Monday.  However, he said the IMF could still consider selling off some of its gold holdings to join the World Bank in easing the burden carried by heavily indebted poor countries.<BR><P>
STALS BACKS MODERATE AND NON-DISRUPTIVE IMF GOLD SALES <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
SA would support a decision by the IMF to sell some of its gold reserve on condition it was done moderately and in a way which would not disrupt the gold market, Chris Stals, the governor of the Reserve Bank, said on Monday.<BR><P>
RUBIN SEES GOLD SALES, PRICES UNDER CONTROL <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SINGAPORE - US Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin predicted in an interview published on Wednesday the IMF would sell part of its gold reserves, and said inflation in the US and other G7 countries is "not re-igniting".<BR><P>
BUSINESS GLOBALISATION SOARING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
LONDON - Business globalisation is increasing dramatically and foreign investment by transnationals soared last year, says the world investment report from the UN Conference on Trade and Development. <BR><P>
DONT TURN BACK ON FREE TRADE, EU WARNS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
BRUSSELS - The European Unions development chief has warned African countries that they must not turn their backs on the global move towards free trade.<BR><P>
ZIMBABWE SEEKS FOREIGN INVESTMENT IN MINING <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
HAMBURG - Zimbabwe was seeking foreign investment in its promising minerals and metals sector, government officials told a German business gathering.<BR><P>
OVERSOLD GOLD EDGES UP ON SHORT-COVERING  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Gold and silver popped higher on a spate of short-covering yesterday afternoon, but dealers said the market was holding back ahead of the FOMC meeting. Bullion fixed at $382,30 an ounce, versus $381,60 in the morning and $381 on Monday afternoon. Bids were quoted as high as $382,70.<BR><P>
SA ON RISK PLATEAU SINCE APRIL 1995  <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
South Africa has achieved an international risk reputation which is well clear of some deeply troubled and economically unstable emerging markets in the world like Russia, Mexico and Venezuela, says the SA Chamber of Business.<BR><P>
</DOC>
