<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 23 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>



FUEL INDUSTRY TO MAKE TAIWAN DEAL DECISION <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A group of South African petrochemical and oil companies is poised to make a decision this week on whether to pursue a Taiwanese proposal for a $3,5bn greenfields petrochemical complex to be built somewhere on the SA coast.<BR><P>
EC BLOCKS SALDANHA PROJECT LOAN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The European Commission has blocked a $78m loan to SA iron and steel giant, Iscor's R6,8bn Saldanha Bay steel project, casting a pall over free trade negotiations between Europe and SA.<BR><P>
TRADE BETWEEN SA AND INDONESIA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Trade between SA and Indonesia had risen to R900m last year from R500m in 1994 with the balance in SA's favour, Indonesia's ambassador Rachadi Iskandar told a trade cultural mission at the weekend.<BR><P>
20% OF WORKERS ARE UNION MEMBERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
One fifth (20,4%) of South Africas economically active population of around 14,3-million people are members of registered and unregistered trade unions, according to the Labour Department's annual report.<BR><P>
INQUIRY INTO MINE VIOLENCE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The commission of inquiry into the recent spate of mine violence at three Gold Fields gold mines - headed by Judge John Myburgh - will begin today with the state leading its evidence.<BR>
<B><I>... however ...</I></B><BR>
ATTACK ON MINE KILLS TEN  <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Ten people were killed in an early-morning attack yesterday on a settlement of mine contract workers at Springvale, Stilfontein, (part of the Randgold group and located about 150km south west of Johannesburg) in which eight explosions ripped through dwellings, and victims fleeing the mayhem were caught and murdered by the attacker. At least 18 people other people were wounded by shrapnel from the explosions or as a result of skirmishes with the killers, police said yesterday.<BR><P>
LEADERS OF DUTCH BUSINESS EXPRESS CONFIDENCE IN SA'S INVESTMENT CLIMATE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
THE HAGUE - Dutch business leaders have expressed confidence in SA's investment climate ahead of a visit to the country by an economic delegation from the Netherlands scheduled for next week.<BR><P>
US OFFICIALS RUN WORKSHOPS FOR SA POLICE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The US treasury officials are in the country to help prepare the SA police for the enforcement of new measures to curb white-collar crime.<BR><P>
THE FISCAL SQUEEZE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Finance Minster Trevor Manuel and his Cabinet colleagues have left no doubt that they remain determined to achieve the 4% of Gross Domestic Product Budget deficit target in fiscal 1997/98 as set down in the macro-economic framework.  Less clear is what recipe of revenue and expenditure factors they are going to prepare in order to do so.<BR><P>
RUSSIANS GRAB CAPE PROPERTY <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Catapulted into capitalism seven years ago, Russians are now shopping for SA property.  The interest in SA property among the moneyed elite in Russia is so strong that it has prompted the first tie-up between property groups in the two countries.<BR><P>
IRANIAN AGRICULTURAL DEALS DENIED <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
SA agricultural bodies said on Friday that they had no knowledge of negotiated deals worth $100m for the import of SA agricultural products, claimed by the visiting Iranian delegation earlier this month.<BR><P>
GHANA LOOKS TO GAS TO POWER BOOMING GOLD SECTOR <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
CAPE TOWN - Ghana is adopting innovate ways to tap into its undeveloped gas reserves to provide secure electricity supplies for its booming gold mining sector, delegates attending the African Upstream conference heard on Friday.<BR><P>
WORRIES KNOCKING PRECIOUS METALS  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Precious metals futures ended sharply lower on Friday, as chart-based speculative trading strategies by commodity funds accelerated the decline of the past three weeks, traders said. Investors had little incentive to buy gold while US inflation remained low, the Fed was poised to move pre-emptively to tighten monetary policy, and the US share and bond markets remained healthy, analysts said.<BR><P>
JAPAN FIRMS IN R95M LOCAL ORE VENTURE  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Feralloys Limited (FAL), a subsidiary of The associated Manganese Mines of South Africa (Assmang), has formed a joint venture with two Japanese companies which will expand its product base and enhance the groups global market exposure. The joint venture for refined ferro-manganese follows an agreement with Mizushima Ferroalloys Company (MZK) and Sumitomo corporation.<BR><P>



