<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 20 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>


DURBAN ROODEPOORT DEEP <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Durban Roodepoort Deep has extended from today to 4 October the closing date for its offer to acquire all West Wits shares and options.<BR><P>
UPBEAT AMIC PLANS R1,2BN RIGHTS OFFER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American Industrial Corporation is to tap shareholders for R1,2bn to finance a string of new projects and developments.<BR><P>
RICK MENELL GIVEN TOP ANGLOVAAL POST <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Mining house Anglovaal lifted attributable income before exceptional items 18% to R496m for the year to June as its resurgent mining operations offset a flat performance from its industrial arm.  The directors appointed 40-year-old Rick Menell as deputy chairman yesterday, succeeding his father Clive, who died in July.<BR><P>
ANGLO RESOLVES DISPUTE WITH ZIMBABWE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American appears to have resolved its dispute with the Zimbabwean government over the 'indigenisation' of its management and has received a work permit for new Chief Executive Phillip Baum of Johannesburg.<BR><P>
GENCOR CONSIDERS STAKE IN ALUMINIUM BUSINESS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gencor was considering bidding for a stake in a Venezuelan state-owned aluminium business valued at about $2bn, the SA mining house said yesterday.<BR><P>
POLICE SEIZE UNREFINED GOLD WORTH R1,6M <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Police have recovered unrefined gold worth more than R1,6m and arrested at least 89 suspects since Tuesday.  Captain Jan Combrink said the arrests were made by the West Rand organised crime unit after investigating the theft of gold at various mines, including Kloof, East and West Driefontien, Blyvooruitsig and West Wits.<BR><P>
MINE UNIONS IN JOINT PEACE RALLY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
In a public display of reconciliation, the majority of East Driefontein's 12 000-strong workforce gathered yesterday at a peace rally organised jointly by the National Union of Mineworkers and the United Workers Union of SA at the mine.  The rally follows closely on the peace rally held by NUM on Sunday where NUM president James Motlatsi denounced violence and encouraged workers to help end it.<BR><P>
DATE ANNOUNCED FOR LABOUR RELATIONS ACT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Labour Minister Tito Mboweni announced yesterday that the new Labour Relations Act would come into effect on 11 November - more than a year after Parliament approved the passing of the Bill.<BR><P>
DISTRESS BUYING MARKS SECOND QUARTER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Reserve Bank's Quarterly Bulletin suggests the economy had a last gasp in the June quarter of this year which should not be seen as evidence of a second wind.  The Bank noted domestic expenditure had jumped an annualised 9% in the second quarter after falling 1,5% in real terms in the first.  It ascribed the surge largely to distress buying to escape price increases resulting from the rand's fall.  It said companies and individuals had stepped up purchases of consumer and capital goods for fear of higher prices.  Inventories had also been accumulated much faster than originally anticipated.<BR><P>
FOOD PRICES LIFT INFLATION TO 7,5% <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Food prices rose in August to lift the inflation rate to 7,5% from 7,1% in July, Central Statistical Services figures released yesterday show.<BR><P>
HIGH INTEREST RATES ARE HERE TO STAY <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
High interest rates are here to stay for the time being and there is no political pressure on the Reserve Bank to lower them, Chris Stals, the Reserve Bank governor, said yesterday.<BR><P>
TREVOR TACKLES CRITICS<I> (Business Mail - weekly on Fridays)</I><BR>
Trevor Manuel and Chris Stals, went to Europe to get back into the Deutschemark market and set a new benchmark with a longer maturity profile, as part of SA's debt management strategy.  They left with an objective - DM450-million, five to seven years;  what they got is DM500-million with seven years.<BR><P>
SLUGGISH WORLD GROWTH <I>(Business Mail)</I><BR>
The world's economy is slowing down, with growth sluggish, despite an upswing in world trade, according to a United Nations agency.<BR><P>
WORLD BANK TURNS TO PRIVATE CAPITAL <I>(Business Mail)</I><BR>
The World Bank has admitted that it is fighting a losing battle with Western governments over aid to the world's poorest countries and is secretly looking for ways to use private capital to replace the lost funds.<BR><P>
DISSATISFACTION WITH ANC, BUT NO GAIN FOR ITS RIVALS - SURVEY <I>(Busisness Day)</I><BR>
Satisfaction with SA's political and economic situation had declined drastically since 1994, but this was unlikely to hamper the ANC's chances of re-election in 1999, says a Human Sciences Research Council survey released yesterday.  Conducted among 2 241 respondents countrywide during June and July, the survey found that 45% of people were satisfied with current political developments, compared to 76% in May 1994.<BR><P>
ASMAL RECALLS DELEGATE AFTER LESOTHO REPORTS <I>(Busisness Day)</I><BR>
The SA permanent delegate to the joint permanent technical commission on the Lesotho Highlands Water Project was recalled to Pretoria yesterday after Water Affairs Minister Kader Asmal objected to his statements, reported in the media.<BR><P>
SOUTH AFRICAN TRADE GROUP TO VISIT IRAN  <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A South African trade delegation will probably visit Iran within two weeks, according to Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin. Speaking at the opening of Plesseys R50-million electronic product manufacturing facility in Retreat, Erwin said.<BR><P>
MINING INTEREST BOOST FOR ANGLOVAAL  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Anglovaal increased earnings before exceptional items by 18 percent to R496-million in the year to June mainly due to better performances from its mining interests. Earnings per share before exceptional items increased similarly to 784c while the dividend was raised 24% to 183c.<BR><P>
