<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 19 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>

JCI LOOKS AT REVAMP OF ITS OPERATIONS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Mining house JCI is investigating restructuring to refocus on gold operations throughout Africa and beyond.  The group declined to comment yesterday.  However, analysts say creating a separate, focused gold division similar to Anglovaal's proposed Avgold is one possible outcome of JCI's plan once it is sold by Anglo American in an imminent black empowerment deal.<BR><P>
REPORT CONFIRMS DROP IN GOLD DEMAND <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
LONDON - Gold demand in the Far East, and China in particular, slumped in the first half of the year, Gold Fields Mineral Services Chief Executive Stewart Murray said.<BR><P>
IMF LEAVES OPEN QUESTION OF GOLD SALES TO AID POOR <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - The International Monetary Fund on Wednesday endorsed stepped-up  aid for the worlds poorest nations, but stopped short of spelling out how it planned to pay for that.  The fund left open the question of whether it would sell some of its gold to help the world's poor.<BR><P>
SEAMS OF MATURITY <I>(Financial Mail - weekly 20/9/96)</I><BR>
Hailed by the industry as mature, sophisticated and pragmatic, this years wage agreement between the Chamber of Mines and the National Union of Mineworkers marks a trend towards decentralised bargaining, based on union recognition that circumstances differ at the various mines.<BR><P>
NO SHIFT IN COSATUS POLICY ON PRIVATISATION, SAYS ANGRY SHILOWA <I>(The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu) has denied changing its stance on privatisation. Speaking from his Cape Town office, Cosatu general secretary Sam Shilowa angrily accused some media reports of "going overboard". He said the tripartite alliance - Cosatu, the ANC and SA Communist Party - was still discussing the issue.<BR><P>
GAUTENG MOOTS INCENTIVES TO REJUVENATE CITY, TOWNSHIP CENTRES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Gauteng government is to launch a plan next month to rejuvenate the province's city and township centres.  Financial incentives to boost business and infrastructure development, closed-circuit television to combat crime and a special tourist police force are mooted in the plan, which has been described as the beginning of a provincial green paper on inner-city renewal.<BR><P>
DECLINE IN NATAL POLITICAL KILLINGS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A steady fall in political killings had boosted the fight of SA police against violent crime in KwaZulu-Natal province, police spokesman Director Bala Naidoo said yesterday.  "The decrease in the number of politically motivated incidents since the local government elections has enabled us to focus attention on fighting crime", Naidoo said.<BR><P>
JSE AGREES TO BACK DRAFT BILL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Johannesburg Stock Exchange has agreed to abide by the money-laundering legislation if it is approved by Parliament in spite of serious objections to elements of the Proceeds of Crime Bill.<BR><P>
COMMISSION RECOMMENDS DRAMATIC CUTS IN MAINTENANCE GRANTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A government commission has recommended dramatic cuts in state maintenance grants, citing racial inequities in the current R1bn-a-year scheme and the demands of government's macro-economic policy as reasons.<BR><P>
WATER COSTS GO UP TO COVER LESOTHO PROJECT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Rand Water announced a 12,5% increase in the price of water it supplied to local authorities yesterday, following a 59% increase in the Water Affairs Department's levy for the Lesotho Highlands Water Project.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
HIGHLANDS PROJECT GO-AHEAD 'DEPENDS ON STABILITY' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The go-ahead for the multibillion-rand phase two of the Lesotho Highlands Water Project, which could be given by the end of next year, rested on political and labour stability in Lesotho, SA's permanent delegate to the project's joint technical commission, Hans Pettenburger, said yesterday.  Work on the project was halted following the shooting by police over the weekend of four workers, who were killed after an illegal strike when 2 300 workers were fired.  <BR>
<B><I>... and, furthermore ...</I></B><BR>
BLOOD MIXES IN TROUBLED WATERS <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
What started out as one of the most ambitious cross-border projects in the southern hemisphere 10 years ago is fast losing its shine as a pathfinder of southern African regional co-operation.  The water-transfer scheme, which would export water from the mountains of Lesotho to the industrial heartland of SA, threatens to fall from engineering marvel to a quagmire beset by labour disruption and diplomatic aggravation <I>[sic]</I>.  Instead of bringing two countries together, the project is firing animosity among local Basotho workers towards "foreign" contractors and is stoking rivalries within the Basotho Congress that rules Lesotho.<BR><P>
NEW COMPETITION POLICY IN WINGS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The team working on SA's new competition legislation is expected to recommend that political control by the Trade and Industry Minister be brought to an end.  Such a move, if implemented, will mean that the Competition Board's decisions will be final.  <BR><P>
IBA GRANTS LICENCE FOR PRIZED STATION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Independent Broadcasting Authority has granted the licence for lucrative SABC radio station Highveld Stereo to Africa On Air, of which Radio 702 owner Primedia Broadcasting owns a large stake.  Last night's decision, which amounts to the largest privatisation of a state asset yet, brings months of intense speculation to a close. <I>[The National Union of Mineworkers also holds a large stake in Africa On Air - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
MBOWENI TO ANNOUNCE IMPLEMENTATION DATE FOR ACT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Today Labour Minister Tito Mboweni will announce the date for implementing the new Labour Relations Act, amid speculation that the Act will come into effect in the latter part of October.  Labour Ministry spokesman Zintle Filtane  said yesterday Mboweni would also provide an update explaining which institutions were fundamental to the implementation of the Act.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
COSATU TO TRAIN 1,5M WORKERS ON NEW ACT <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Cosatu began a trickle-down campaign yesterday to educate its 1,5m members on the ins and outs of the soon-to-be promulgated Labour Relations Act. <BR><P>
FRAGMENTED UNION UNABLE TO REACH SETTLEMENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A wage agreement was reached at the end of last week between the Chamber of Mines and the whites-only Mineworkers' Union (MWU).  However, agreement with the Federated Mining Unions (FMU) <I>[sic - the correct title is the Federation of Mining Unions - Ed.]</I> still hangs in the balance after a majority vote in favour of striking.  The agreement with the MWU was similar to to that reached with NUM. However, during negotiations with the FMU, which represents mainly artisans and maintenance workers, problems developed. The FMU not only faced internal divisions, but also threatened industrial action. The FMU was suppoed to notify the Chamber yesterday whether it had accepted the final offer, but one of the four unions making up the FMU, the SA Electrical Workers' Association, broke ranks and announced its intention to withdraw from the federation saying it was unlikely  a strike would be called. However, the general secretary of the FMU's largest union, the National Employees, Trade Union, said workers, especially on Amcoal collieries, were threatening strike action. <BR><P>
UNIONS SUE FOR BEING CALLED RACIST <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The SA Railways and Harbour Workers' Union is being sued for defamation to the tune of R180 000 for accusing its formerly white rival unions at Transnet, the Technical Workers' Union and the SA Footplate Staff Association, of racism.<BR><P>
'SYMBOLIC' PRESIDENCY TO BE REWORKED' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
<I>[Nelson] </I>Mandela is already assured of a place in history as the great reconciler and unifier of the nation, and he can make a further contribution in his last years in office by allowing the emphasis to shift from the president as symbol, his advisers suggest.  The symbol should be replaced, they believe, by a vision of the presidency as the management centre of a government intent on attaining the socio-economic goals at the heart of its policies.<BR><P>
NEW INVESTMENT ACCORDS APPROVED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Bilateral agreements <I>[between SA and]</I> Cuba, France, Denmark and South Korea for reciprocal protection of investors' interests and the creation of conditions for greater investment were approved by Parliament's trade and industry committee yesterday.<BR><P>
INDIAN OCEAN NATIONS SEEK TO ESTABLISH TRADE NETWORK <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Fourteen countries on the rim of the Indian Ocean came together in Mauritius last week to take forward an initiative to create a trade network between them.  The SA business community was represented by the SA Chamber of Business (Sacob) and Business SA.  <BR><P>
SA AND ZAMBIA AGREE ON RELAXING BORDER PAPERWORK <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA and Zambia agreed yesterday to relax visa requirements for holders of diplomatic or official passports following a meeting between Home Affairs Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi and his Zambian counterpart, Chitalu Sampa, in Cape Town earlier in the day.  Representatives of the SA Police Service and the Foreign Affairs Department also attended.<BR><P>
WESTERN FRAMEWORKS NOT SUITABLE FOR AFRICA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
In Africa, where political adjustments were taking place, there was a need to question the wisdom of importing frameworks from the West where the role of such organisations<I> [presumably "frameworks" whatever they may be - Ed.] </I>was different.<BR><P>
CALL FOR EQUALISING SA ENERGY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The existing energy system in SA had discriminated against the country's poorest communities, Deputy Minerals and Energy Affairs Minister Susan Shabangu said yesterday.  Shabangu said this was because the system failed to use solar energy resources.  After returning from the world solar summit in Harare, Shabangu said she was eager to see solar energy used more among developing communities in SA and would soon take up the matter with the organisations concerned.<BR><P>
FREED SA MINERS KEEN TO GET BACK  <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The 18 South African miners arrested and held captive in Angola for nearly two weeks, arrived back at Johannesburg International Airport yesterday afternoon confident they would be back in Angola within a week to fulfil their contracts with Angolan mining companies.<BR><P>
POOR CONTROLS COST SA MILLIONS  <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Government performance has not been up to scratch and in some cases poor management in several departments has cost the taxpayer millions of rands, a 32-page special audit report tabled in Parliament yesterday by Auditor-general Henri Kluever has revealed.<BR><P>
MINERS CHARGED  <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
More than 200 former miners at the Amandelbult platinum mine in North West have appeared in court on charges of public violence.<BR><P>
EMPLOYERS DISLIKE INFORMATION CLAUSE  <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
Employers are concerned about the Labour Relation Acts compulsory disclosure of information clause as they believe it infringes on their right to disseminate or withhold confidential information, says business and labour consultant Joe du Preez of Gavin Weiner and Association.<BR><P>
SA FIRMS STILL EXCLUDE WORKERS  <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
South African businesses are still excluding their employees at decision-making level despite the new Labour Relation Acts provision for worker participation in policy making and the running of companies. A survey by Ernest and Young, shows that, while the involvement of workers has increased, their participation has been restricted to non-core business.<BR><P>
POLICY CHANGE OPENS FUTURE FOR BLACK MINERS  <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
Over the past two years Impala has flattened the management hierarchy, reduced the number of supervisory levels and introduced the position of crew captains which replaced the miner level previously reserved for whites. The crew captains have taken over the jobs of team leaders and miners, and are responsible for teams of 12 workers instead of the previous 150. Ken Field says smaller "self-directed" teams are easier to manage and work faster. This has led to a six percent increase in production.<BR><P>
</DOC>
