<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 18 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>


MINING STILL THE MOST DANGEROUS INDUSTRY <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A total of 942 people, excluding miners, died in the workplace last year, according to the Labour Department's annual report for last year.  However, mining remains the most hazardous industry in the country. According to statistics from the Mineral and Energy Affairs Department, 533 people died on the mines last year. During the same period 7 739 were injured and there were 7 900 reported accidents. <BR><P>
CRIMINAL-FRIENDLY CONSTITUTION CRITICISED <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Some lawyers believed the only thing the Constitutional Court had done since its inception last year was to make things easier for criminals, Transvaal Law Society vice-president Piet Langenhoven said yesterday.<BR><P>
ASSEMBLY LIMITS REDRAFTING OF CONSTITUTION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Constitutional Assembly decided unanimously yesterday against reopening negotiations on the whole constitution.  This, together with the outstanding issue of international mediation, could spell the end of any chance of the IFP reversing its 18-month boycott of the assembly at its national council meeting at the weekend.  "There will be no opening of other issues.  We are going to concentrate on those issues sent back by the Constitutional Court", said chairman Cyril Ramaphosa.<BR><P>
LABOUR COURTS 'DELAYED BY GOVT INCOMPETENCE' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Labour Court Judge President, Judge John Myburgh, launched a scathing attack yesterday on the Justice and Public Works departments, saying their inefficiency was helping delay labour courts being set up.  A dispute between the Judicial Service Commission and Nedlac, both of which are to make recommendations to President Mandela on the appointment of judges, had remained unresolved for seven weeks, causing further delays, Myburgh said.<BR><P>
INSURANCE BILL ALLOWS FIRMS MORE OFFSHORE INVESTMENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The parliamentary finance committee yesterday supported another step in the phased lifting of exchange controls in SA by approving legislation that will allow insurance companies to extend their offshore investments.<BR><P>
ISCOR BLAMES MARKET CONDITIONS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Steel producer Iscor's earnings before exceptional items for the six months to December <I>[1996] </I>would fall short of the more than R400m reported for the same period last year, the group said yesterday.  It blamed persistently weak market conditions.<BR><P>
REVENUE SERVICE CHIEF ASKS TREVOR TO STOP THE ROT <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The new chief executive officer of the SA Reserve Services, Piet Liebenberg, will ask Finance Minister Trevor Manuel in the next few days to increase the autonomy of the service in a desperate attempt to "stop the rot".  He told the standing committee on public accounts yesterday that the staff situation at the SARS was critical and "might deteriorate further as staff take early retirement packages".<BR><P>
SA WILL NOT SEEK IMF LOAN <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The Finance Ministry yesterday scotched speculation on financial markets that the government would seek a loan from the International Monetary Fund at the monetary fund's meeting in Washington at the end of the month.  Banking officials and analysts had reported widespread speculation that the government would seek a loan to help finance imports of capital goods to restructure the economy.<BR><P>
NO SPACE TO BREATHE ON THIS TRACK <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Despite complaints from some captains of industry about the pace of change, the programme to place the SA economy on an internationally competitive footing appears to be bearing fruit.  Since 1994, the Trade and Industry Department has reduced tariffs on imports and scrapped excessive export subsidies.  The programme has exposed those industries that compete with imports - textile, motor, tyre and chemical - to foreign competition and world markets.  It has meant that local industry and the economy has had to adjust to lower levels of tariff protection.<BR><P>
SA'S TRADE WITH CHINA ON THE INCREASE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Trade between mainland China and SA was worth more than R4,5b last year and had grown even more this year, Zhou Guangyao of the China Council for the Promotion of International Trade said at a China Expo in Cape Town yesterday.<BR><P>
PROBE INTO PAYMENTS TO OIL INDUSTRY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The auditor-general is investigating government payments totalling R1,2bn to the oil industry - paid as compensation for market share lost to synthetic fuel production - amid claims that the industry overstated its opportunity costs.  The investigation, thought to have been requested by the Minerals and Energy Department, centres on payments made between 1986 and 1994 for market share lost to Sasol's synthetic fuel output.  The payments were funded by consumer levies.<BR><P>
KEY LESOTHO OPERATIONS GRIND TO A HALT <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
BUTHA BUTHE, LESOTHO - Operations have ground to a complete halt on the key water transfer and hydro-electricity components of the $4b Lesotho Highlands Water Project after the sacking last week of half of the project's workers and a bloody weekend clash with police.<BR><P>
LEBOWA PLATINUM <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Lebowa Platinum was not ordered by the Appeal Court to pay royalties to Trojan for mineral rights it exploited on the Lydenburg farm Umkoanestad, as reported by <I>Business Day</I> on Monday. <BR><P>
ANGLO-NUM PACT SIGNALS END OF AN ERA <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Anglo American Corporation may have unwittingly triggered seismic activity recently, which could reverberate all the way to its 44 Main Street headquarters.  Last week, Anglo's gold division and NUM (the National Union of Mineworkers) said they planned to review all work and management practices at Anglo's five gold mines, with a view to improving productivity and securing jobs.<BR><P>
MESSINA REPORTS SPARKLING RESULTS  <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Messina Investments, the diamond mining company, said yesterday attributable earnings excluding exceptional items in the year to June 30 rose 86% to R5,4m from R2,9m the year before.<BR><P>
BROKE UNION MINES MAY MAKE AN OFFER TO CREDITORS  <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Union Mines, the debt-ridden manganese operation, has been negotiating with a private company to make a minimum R1,5m offer of compromise to creditors.<BR><P>
NAMIBIAN UNION TO ADDRESS LABOUR COURT  <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The 26-day strike at Gold Fields Namibia's Tsumeb operations continues in the labour court in Windhoek as both parties make applications to it.  <BR><P>
ZIMBABWE INFLATION FALLS TO THREE-YEAR LOW  <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Zimbabwe's inflation rate dipped to a three-year low of 17,7% last month, surprising many economists, who had expected it to increase on a spate of price rises. <BR><P>
SIGCAU WELCOMES SHILOWA STAND ON PRIVATISATION  <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Public Enterprises Minister Stella Sigcau yesterday welcomed the Congress of South African Trade Unions (Cosatu) statement by general secretary Sam Shilowa endorsing partial privatisation of state assets. Shilowas statement was an encouraging development in line with the investment trends announced by Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin and the macro-economic strategy released by Finance Minister Trevor Manuel  she said.<BR><P>
NACTU SUPPORTS PART PRIVATISATION  <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The National Council of Trade Unions (Nactu) yesterday said it supported partial privatisation provided jobs and the use of local material were guaranteed. Nactus general secretary Cunningham Ngcukana said his federation believed that state intervention in the economy was crucial, but it was also aware of the countrys need to service its R280-billion debt and deliver basic services.<BR><P>
JUDGE MOVES QUICKLY IN MINE PROBE  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Judge President of the Labour Courts John Myburgh is wasting no time launching his Commission of Inquiry into the violence that has plagued South Africas vital mining industry <I>[Once again the media fails to draw the important distinction between a commission charged with probing violence on three mines and creating the impression that the investigation will cover the entire industry - Ed.]</I>. He has called the first full meeting of all affected parties to discuss Commission procedures on Friday, barely a week after President Nelson Mandela appointed him to head the Commission. And  - provided the Commission is promulgated in Fridays Government Gazette - he hopes the first hearings will be held on Monday.<BR><P>
ANGLO DIGS DEEPER TO SURVIVE  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Anxious to compete globally and to disprove talk of its imminent demise, South Africas gold mining industry is seeking new ways to survive - even if it means sending men five km underground.  The countrys gold mines are already the deepest in the world extending down to 3 170m. Now the biggest mining group, Anglo American, plans a quantum leap to snatch the riches it knows lie far beneath the earth.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD GETS TO GRIPS WITH MALI MINE  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
South Africas Randgold Resources aims to raise output at the Syama gold mine in Mali to 200 000 ounces a year from 125 000 by bringing in new machining methods and boosting staff morale, a senior company official said.<BR><P>
TANZANIA - JCI COY ON BRIAN HESTER <I> (Africa Focus - weekly 18/9/96)</I><BR>
JCIs head of new mining business, Rob Still, told <I>Africa Focus</I> that JCI is currently involved in a joint venture with Colorado-based Patrician Mining, but would not elaborate on the details. Still also confirmed that JCI is looking at other companies, leases and/or individuals, one of whom may be Brian Hester. Hester, a Canadian consultant to Patrician, and an acknowledged expert on Tanzanian mining, holds interest in three companies active in Tanzania. They are Canyon Resources, Sampo Resources and African Minerals Specialists. AMS has two prospecting licenses in Tarime (Mara region) and another in Nyaragusu (northwest Mwanza). Sampo also has two licenses in Mara, around Musoma. <BR><P>
ERITREA - MINING CONCESSIONS BIDDING SET  <I>(Africa Focus)</I><BR>
The Eritrean Ministry of Energy, Mining and Water Resources will open a second round of bidding for mining concessions in the western lowlands. "We have seen delineated areas in the western and eastern lowlands close to the coast," said Asmaron Mesfin, head of administration at the Ministrys mining department. "These will be open for exploration licenses. Apart from that, bidders can choose other areas for prospecting,: said Asmaron. Although there is no fixed date, bidding will commence sometime between October and the new year. However, Ashanti has already submitted a proposal for a concession in the western lowlands.<BR><P>
ZAMBIA - EMERALDS BOOM FOR SMALL FIRMS   <I>(Africa Focus)</I><BR>
A year after temporary closure, locally incorporated Kagem Mining Limited remains Zambias most productive emerald mining company. In 1995 Kagem was closed for alleged illegal mining activities. It has since resumed production, selling about $1-million worth of rough emeralds from stock in 1996. Most of the 66 companies involved in the mining of precious minerals are small. However, heavyweights including Western Mining (a private Australian company) Anglovaal, Phelps Dodge and Tan Range Exploration of Canada are prospecting for gold silver and emeralds.
<I>1995 Emerald Production: 166,146.g.  Sales  - $2.874 million  Cut - $1.378 million</I><BR><P>
KENYA - PANORAMA FINDS GOLD IN MIGORI  <I>(Africa Focus)</I><BR>
Investor interest is focusing on the Migori prospect where a recently completed 72-hole programme of reverse circulation drilling outlined mineralisation over a stride length of 4.5km. Panorama Resources, which has a portfolio of international exploration projects in Africa, Europe and Australia, is holding exploration rights over approximately 70% (1,063 km) of the Migori greenstone belt. This interest has been gained via an agreement to earn a 60% stake in tenements held by Kenyan Mid-Migori Mining.<BR><P>
GHANA - ASHANTI GOLD DEAL DEFINED  <I>(Africa Focus)</I><BR>
Last Thursday the exact amount of gold to be delivered by Ashanti Zimbabwe (formally Cluff) to two banks in a $40-million pre-paid forward gold sale was fixed at 135,600 oz, Ashantis group treasurer Mona Caesar-Addo said. "We will start delivery in March 1998, over a period of five years. The yearly amounts are roughly equal, and represent about 25% of annual production (95,00 oz) of Zimbabwes Freda Rebecca Mine."<BR><P>

<B>INTERVIEW</B> - SA MINING MINISTER LOOKS TOWARDS EMPOWERMENT AND INDUSTRIALISATION <I> by Barry Baxter (Africa Focus)</I><BR>
<B>BAXTER: </B>Penuella <I>[sic] </I>Maduna says the major challenge the new South African government faces from the mining industry is how to bring blacks into [the] industry; not as purveyors of cheap labour but as owners of equity.<BR>
<B>MADUNA: </B>The legacy of apartheid is still in the <I>[mining] </I>industry. Blacks must be managers at critical levels - decision-makers. At those levels, mining in SA is still very much a white-only business. The National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) wants its members on the boards of the mining houses within 10 years, but that is too long. I would be much happier if there were signs of it beginning to happen now. "Im not talking about good Samaritans <I>[acting] </I>out of sheer altruism, or the goodness of their hearts, throwing money at blacks. Im talking about creating opportunities for blacks to come on their own initiative and through the front door. I dont want any little black token at the top."<BR>
<B>BAXTER </B>:The Chamber of Mines has expressed concern over proposed new legislation providing worker forums at mine level and bargaining councils with regional and national responsibility.<BR>
<B>MADUNA: </B>"They must wait and see how things crystallise. We are still at the preparatory stages [of a white paper]. Luckily for them and all the key players, we started this legislation in a different way. Normally a white paper is published as government policy, and that is that. What has happened here is, from the very word go, a decision was taken that all players must be brought together so they could help in formulating the new policy. They are very lucky, the policy will be formed with input from all of them. The best and broadest interest of this country will form part of the final policy. There is still a lot of room for discussion and debate."<BR>
<B>BAXTER:  </B>On oft-repeated comments by the gold mining industry that refining to 99,99 is beneficiation enough, Maduna said,<BR>
<B>MADUNA: </B>I am not sure what they mean when they say further beneficiation is a non-starter. We think that some of our resources must have value added. We need to develop a better jewelry <I>[sic] </I>industry. If it makes sense for Europeans to buy our gold and then make jewels out of it there, why cant we do it here?"<BR>
<B>BAXTER: </B>With the gold industry admittedly declining, what is your scenario for the future?<BR>
<B>MADUNA:  </B>"Some of us are advocating that this country must embark on industrialisation on a scale we have never seen before. The economy has been skewed in favour of mining, but mining is based on wasting assets. If we develop industry and technology, we will begin to focus on other areas and the country will survive."<BR><P>
PROJECT LAUNCHED TO STUDY MIGRATION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
CAPE TOWN - A joint research and policy formulation project by the Institute for Democracy in SA (Idasa) and a Canadian university dealing with cross-border migration in southern Africa was launched last night. The three-year Southern Africa Migration Project has the financial backing of the Canadian International Development Agency acting through Queens University in Kingston. Acting project manager Vincent Williams said yesterday the project would focus on both legal and undocumented migrants (illegal aliens), examining which countries they came from and what sectors they entered when they arrived in SA.<BR><P>
</DOC>
