<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 17 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>

<p align=left>MINES BACK TRAPS TO FIGHT GOLD THEFT <em>(Business Day, Jhb.)</em><br>
South Africa's mines yesterday called for the revision of a draft law to ensure that police could continue to use traps in their 
fight against gold theft costing the country an estimated R1,5bn a year.<br>
<br>
SA'S FINANCIAL JOURNALISTS FAIL TO CARRY OUT THEIR DUTIES <em>(Business Day)</em><br>
SA&#146;s economic journalists confirm the truth of the bitter joke that an economist thinks the long-term began last week, a print 
journalist thinks the long-term started yesterday and a television journalist thinksusiness iayrted this morning. Nowhere is this 
better reflected than in the reporting of the decline in the rand since February this year.<br>
<br>
SPEND YOU LOSE, SAVE YOU LOSE <em>(Business Report, Jhb.)</em><br>
The South African Reserve Bank's annual report has shown that increases in the government's consumption expenditure are 
being financed by poor people getting deeper into debt, while business surplus have risen, benefiting the rich.<br>
<br>
CALL TO DELAY CHANGES <em>(Business Day)</em><br>
Affirmative action in the criminal justice system should be delayed until crime was under control, Democratic Party leader 
Tony Leon said yesterday. Efforts to make the system more representative of the population were leading to the loss of 
competent staff.<br>
<br>
MANUEL HONOURED BY IMF AND WORLD BANK <em>(Business Report)</em><br>
The International Monetary Fund and the World Bank have asked SA Finance Minister Trevor Manuel to act as one of two 
vice-chairmen at the ordinary plenary sessions of their yearly meetings in Washington from October 1 to 3. A Finance 
Department spokesman said Manuel would co-chair the plenary sessions with the Chilean Finance Minister if the chairman, 
Eritrea's Finance Minister, could not attend.<br>
<br>
THE UNION PROBLEM <em>(Business Day - Editorial Comment -</em><em><u> full text</u></em><em>)</em><br>
A couple of developments in the past week suggest, once again, that SA&#146;s much-lamented &quot;union problem&quot; is not nearly as 
intractable as local and foreign conventional wisdom would have it. Those developments also suggest, however, that dealing 
successfully with the unions takes a degree of skill and enlightenment (of the self-interested type) that often seems in short 
supply.</p>
<p align=left>The first development is, of course, Cosatu&#146;s <em>[the Congress of South African Trade Unions is SA's largest labour 
federation, staunchly socialist and a close alliance partner with the ruling African National Congress- Ed.] </em>new 
official stance on privatisation. This policy has been in the making for some time. Even as Cosatu&#146;s public platform rhetoric 
vowed to fight this manifestation of the evil neo-liberal agenda, leading union officials - seeing the fiscal and market pressures 
their ANC allies were under - were creating space to facilitate a change of direction.</p>
<p align=left><br>
Cosatu&#146;s conversion is neither graceful nor wholehearted. It is a matter of acknowledging economic realities rather than a new 
conviction that privatisation is inherently &quot;a good thing&quot;. The semantics suggest that Cosatu has only <em>[now]</em> reached the stage 
that the ANC did around 1993 when it began preparing to govern. And the policy statement is vague, and peppered with &quot;ifs&quot; 
and &quot;:buts&quot; that the purist will find distasteful. <br>
</p>
<p align=left>This all suggests that there is a lot of fighting ahead over detail. Nevertheless, the shift signals that the issue is no longer 
&quot;whether&quot; but what, when and how. To an appreciable extent, it moves consideration of SA&#146;s economic future off the streets 
and into the debating chamber.<br>
</p>
<p align=left>The other important developments occurred in the mining industry. They go to the heart of labour market flexibility, and 
suggest progress is possible in the new labour framework if handled sensibly on both sides. It gives substance to some of the 
ideas contained in the Labour Market Commission&#146;s recommendations regarding the relationship between centralised 
bargaining and the need for flexibility in this highly competitive era. <br>
</p>
<p align=left>The significance of the <a href="/Welcome.htm">Chamber of Mines</a>/<a href="http://www.anc.org.za/num/">NUM</a> <em>[the National Union of Mineworkers] </em>wage settlement lies in its 
decentralised nature. Its unifying features address such areas as retirement funds, a training policy framework, sick leave, 
occupational disease and injury compensation. Those are issues where national industry standards can be useful and 
constructive. But where the bulk of direct costs are concerned , particularly wages, the agreement provides for differentiated 
settlements for individual groups and, in some cases, individual mines. The agreement recognises the existence of different 
needs and priorities of individual operations, which is what modern labour market policy demands.<br>
Beyond that the NUM and Anglo American&#146;s gold and uranium division were able to negotiate a framework for productivity 
enhancement. This innovation could well set a benchmark for South African labour relations at a time when creative 
union/management efforts to enhance efficiencies are critical to economic development.<br>
</p>
<p align=left>South African managers and union leaders, instead of spending their time shaking fists at their adversaries, would do well to 
look at the example set by their counterparts in the mining industry.<br>
<br>
FIRST STEP TODAY IN REVISING CONSTITUTION <em>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</em><br>
The Constitutional Assembly meets in plenary session today for the first time since May to address defects in the constitution, 
but work will begin in earnest next week in producing a revised document for the Constitutional Court.<br>
<br>
</p>
