<head>
<title>Monday 16 September 1996: Chamber of Mines of SA News</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#0000A0">
<p align=center><font size=4><b>MONDAY, 16 SEPTEMBER 1996 at 12H00 GMT +2 </b></font><br>
</p>
<p align=left>SKILLS EXODUS RAISES BUDGET CONCERNS <i>(Business Day, Jhb.)</i><br>
The Finance Department has suffered a 'brain drain' of its budget team which has left it with only one of the original nine 
members - raising concerns about the department's ability to draw up and monitor the Budget. The latest to leave is 
economist Boyce Lloyd, who started work at a blue chip company in Johannesburg this month. Former colleague Murto 
Wickens landed a job with the International Monetary Fund in Washington. Finance officials have acknowledged the 
staff problems, but denied that last week's R5,5bn revenue mistake had anything to do with the exodus of experienced 
technicians.<br>
</p>
<p>COMPETITION POLICY DISPUTE EXPECTED <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin signalled on Friday that he expected major disagreements with business on 
competition policy. Erwin was speaking at a briefing arranged by the National Economic Development and Labour 
Council (Nedlac). The briefing was held after a session between government, labour and business on industrial policy.<br>
</p>
<p>RATING AGENCY TO REVIEW SA <i>(Business Report, Jhb.)</i><br>
Standard and Poor's, the US rating agency, will visit SA this week for its yearly review of the country, a Finance 
Ministry official said on Friday.<br>
</p>
<p>IRON MAN SAM 'IS SOFTENING' <i>(Business Report)</i><br>
Government sources said yesterday they were 'most encouraged' with the support given by Sam Shilowa, general 
secretary of the Congress of South African Trade Unions (Cosatu), for partial privatisation as one way of restructuring 
state assets.<br>
<b><i>... but ...</i></b><br>
COSATU STILL AGAINST WHOLESALE PRIVATISATION <i>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</i><br>
Cosatu has reaffirmed its opposition to wholesale privatisation, and reasserted its position that &quot;strategic nationalisation&quot; 
be considered where appropriate in restructuring state assets. At its two-day meeting which ended on Friday, Cosatu&#146;s 
decision-making body, the Central Executive Committee, said the restructuring debate should consider all forms of 
ownership.<br>
</p>
<p>NUM HOLDS RALLY <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
About 2 000 National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) members held a peace rally at West Driefontein mine yesterday 
to promote peace in the strife-torn West Rand mines.<br>
<b><i>... but, despite it being a &quot;peace&quot; rally ...</i></b><br>
GOLDFIELDS BLAMED FOR MINERS&#146; DEATHS <i>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</i><br>
The death of about 60 mineworkers should be blamed on Gold Fields management, James Motlatsi, president of NUM, 
said yesterday. Motlatsi said mine security heads should roll after miners were killed in sporadic fighting in the past two 
months. <i>[For details see news bulletins from the past two weeks via the links below - Ed.]</i><br>
</p>
<p>BACK TO SQUARE ONE ON IRAN OIL DEAL <i>(Business Report)</i><br>
Iran's high-profile visit to SA last week failed to break the impasse over a stalled agreement between Pretoria and its 
main oil supplier over storage of 15m barrels of Iranian crude at Saldanha Bay.<br>
</p>
<p>STALS CONFIDENT ON GOLD MARKET <i>(Business Times, Sunday)</i><br>
Reserve Bank governor Chris Stals said on Friday the sale of gold by the International Monetary Fund, expected over 
the weekend, would not have a major effect on the gold market if it was done &quot;in a responsible way&quot;.<br>
<b><i>... and ...</i></b><br>
NO IMF DECISION ON GOLD SALES, BOARD TO MEET AGAIN SEPT. 18 <i>(Reuters)</i><br>
The IMF on Friday put off a decision on a controversial proposal to sell a small amount of its gold to help the world's 
poorest nations until next week.<br>
</p>
<p>LEBOWA PLATINUM <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Leplats is holding talks with Pyramid and Trojan exploration to solve their mineral rights dispute, Amplats says in its 
latest annual report.<br>
</p>
<p>&#145;RANDGOLD CHANGES YEAR-END <i>(Business Report)</i><br>
Randgold &amp; Exploration has changed its year-end to March 31 from September 30, the company's advisers said 
yesterday. This means Randgold's next financial statement will reflect the 18-month period from October 1 last year 
(1995) to March 31 next year (1997).<br>
</p>
<p>DUIKER LIFTS EXPORT QUOTA <i>(Business Report)</i><br>
Duiker Mining has bought an additional 0,5% stake in the Richards Bay Coal Terminal from Shell SA in a deal that 
boosts the company's export entitlements by 9% and may account for some of the strength of its share price.<br>
</p>
<p>GOLD FIELDS GHANA TO GO AHEAD WITH NEW MINE <i>(Reuters)</i><br>
Gold Fields Ghana is to launch the initial phase of an open-cast mining project in Tarkwa, south west Ghana, after 
getting the go-ahead from the board, managing director Helgo Kahle said.<br>
</p>
<p>BANKS WELCOME NEW MONEY LAUNDERING LAWS <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
The Council of SA Banks has welcomed anti-money-laundering legislation, which is being rushed through Parliament, 
because SA's banks stand the risk of becoming ostracised by foreign banks for distributing &quot;dirty&quot; money.<br>
</p>
<p>PRODUCTION AT MINE BOOSTED <i>(Sowetan)</i><br>
Impala Platinum Mine&#146;s radical affirmative action programme may have sparked off an exodus of white miners, but it has 
also boosted production. The mine is currently flattening its hierarchical management structure and is training black 
workers to fill the newly introduced positions of &quot;crew captains&quot; which replaced the traditional &quot;miners&quot; positions 
previously reserved for whites.<br>
</p>
<p>MANDELA&#146;S KNEE OP A SUCCESS <i>(Citizen)</i><br>
President Nelson Mandela left 1 Military Hospital in Pretoria early yesterday morning after undergoing a small knee 
operation and he was in excellent health, presidential aide Parks Mankahlana said.<br>
</p>
</body>

