<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 13 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>



PAY INCREASES TROUBLE MINING INDUSTRY  <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The mining industry yesterday expressed concern that the cost of mining gold and coal would escalate following an <A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/releases/wages96.htm">agreement </A>on Wednesday granting workers above-inflation wage increases. Working costs at gold mines are expected to double and those on coal mines to increase by between 2,25 and three percent.<I> [Although the report, emanating from the SA Press Association, purports to represent "industry" views, it only quotes Ingwes MD Dave Murray, who says the increases awarded are "as realistic as we are going to get, but, in terms of our costs, it is a problem" - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
LOW RAND THREATENS POSITIVE SENTIMENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The rand pierced the R4,50-to-the-dollar barrier yesterday, threatening to burst the bubble of positive sentiment in the money and capital markets.<BR><P>
SLUGGISH REVENUE FALLS BELOW BUDGET <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government revenue for the first five months of the fiscal year was surprisingly low, with the increase from last year running at less than 4%.<BR><P>
NUM, ANGLO SIGN LANDMARK PACT  <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) and Anglos gold and uranium division have signed a landmark agreement to review the way work is done on Anglos mines. Detailing the objectives of the agreement yesterday, NUM president James Motlatsi and the chairman of Anglos gold and uranium division, Bobby Godsell, said the accord was mainly geared to saving jobs.<BR><P>
MAN KILLED ON MINE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A man died of stab wounds and two others were injured after violence flared up again at the East Driefontein Mine, near Carletonville on the West Rand, police said yesterday.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
NUM WELCOMES VIOLENCE PROBE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
NUM yesterday welcomed the appointment of a commission of inquiry into mine violence<I> [on three Gold Fields mines - East Driefontein, Leeudoorn and Northam - Ed.]</I> but it expressed concern about the time allocated for the commission to make recommendations to President Mandela <I>[10 working days from commencement of sitting].</I><BR><P>
DEELKRAAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Deelkraal warned shareholders today to continue exercising caution in share dealings.<BR><P>
NEGOTIATORS STICK TO JAN 1 DATE FOR CONSTITUTION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Negotiators hope to rectify the sections of the draft constitution rejected by the Constitutional Court in the next four weeks so that it can be implemented on schedule on 1 January 1997.<BR><P>
SAPS UNVEILS UNDERCOVER OPERATIONS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA Police Service's organised crime unit currently has 103 undercover projects operating inside the country and abroad, national police Commissioner George Fivaz said yesterday.<BR><P>
NEW TAX LEGISLATION COULD TAKE IN COSATU PROPOSALS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Proposals by the Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu) on government's plan for tax incentives for investment could be accommodated under the relevant legislation, Trade and Industry chief director Alan Hirsch told the parliamentary finance committee yesterday.<BR><P>
DE BEERS HEADS OFF A STRIKE AS LATE AGREEMENT IS REACHED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A wage strike by thousands of members of NUM was averted at the 11th hour yesterday when De Beers agreed to drop its demand to abolish a premium paid to some five-day workers when a public holiday fell on a Sunday.<BR><P>
WARM WELCOME FOR IRAN PRESIDENT  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Irans President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani received a warm red-carpet welcome from President Mandela at the Johannesburg International Airport yesterday afternoon. Rafsanjani, who is on the sixth leg of his African nation tour, was honoured with the hoisting of the green, white and red Iranian flag when he was led to the podium by Mandela.<BR>
<B><I>...and ...</I></B><BR>
LEADERS BOOST TIES BETWEEN SA, IRAN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Iran and SA would not allow the US to determine their fates and destinies, Iranian President Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani said in Pretoria yesterday.  "They can recognise the enemy from friends <I>[sic, ?</I>]", he said at a banquet hosted in his honour by President Mandela.<BR><P>
MBEKI TELLS US INVESTORS PRIVATISATION IS PROGRESSING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki called on US businesses yesterday to invest in SA and said government plans to privatise industry were moving forward.<BR><P>
IMF MIGHT NOT VOTE ON GOLD SALE PLAN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The International Monetary Fund board might not vote today on a controversial proposal to sell gold to help poor countries, the president of the IMF interim committee, Philippe Maystadt, said yesterday.<BR><P>
TENSION, FRUSTRATION WEIGH ON RELATIONS BETWEEN GOVT, BUSINESS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Although present levels of dialogue and interaction between business and government on a broad front are still relatively active, signs of frustration and tension are starting to show.  Business people are impatiently waiting for government to emerge from the so-called 'learning curve' to start demonstrating the ability to govern and manage the economy of the country.<BR><P>
MINERAL SALES SLIP 0,9% TO R14BN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Mineral sales were R14bn in the three months to June, down 0,9% on the preceding quarter due to a drop in gold sales, the Central Statistical Service said yesterday.  <BR><P>
STRIKERS SURRENDER TSUMEB SMELTERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold Fields Namibia said yesterday it would resume mediation efforts with striking workers after regaining control on Wednesday of mine and smelter operations at Tsumeb.<BR><P>
GOVT EXAMINES ITS LOSSES TOO LATE <I>(Business Mail, in Weekly Mail & Guardian - Fridays)</I><BR>
Fears that the country will lose the essential skills of its scientists, engineers and technicians is driving a government investigation into the brain drain from the public sector.<BR><P>
JOIN THEM IF YOU CANT BEAT THEM <I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
The biennial congress next week of the National Union of Metalworkers of SA (Numsa) will be the key meeting to decide the future of Cosatu and the relationship of the labour movement to the government.  The main debate at the congress will be the governments growth and redistribution strategy with its commitment to privatisation.<BR><P>
HIGHEST COURT FINDS COSATU WAS RIGHT AFTER ALL - by John Gomomo, Cosatus president <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
"Those wanting to undermine the will of the people, and two years of hard negotiations in the Constitutional Assembly, by using legal action to pursue what they could not achieve through the democratic process, have been dealt a severe blow by last Fridays judgement of the Constitutional Court.  A number of key issues raised by ourselves, together with the ANC, were in effect endorsed by the court.  These include recognition of the right to strike as a fundamental human right; rejection of constitutional entrenchment of the right to lock out; and the right of the central government to set national norms and standards should not be undermined by powers of the provinces." <BR><P>
RTZ WONT BE PINNED DOWN ON DIAVIK <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
SYDNEY - It is too early to say if De Beers Consolidated Mines will have a role in the marketing of diamonds from the Diavik project in Canadas Northwest Territories, said Robert Wilson, the chief executive of RTZ-CRA, which owns 60 percent of the project.<BR><P>
INVESTORS WAITING TO CASH IN ON TAX HOLIDAY <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Several projects, worth hundreds of millions of rands, were set to be announced by the Department of Trade and Industry in the weeks after the tax holiday comes into operation on October 1, Alan Hirsh, the chief director of the Department of Trade and Industry, said yesterday.  <BR><P>
GENBEL SPREADS IT WINGS  <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
In 1949 a small company, Capital Mining Areas Limited, was formed to hold exploration rights for gold over half a dozen farms, some 100 kilometres east of Johannesburg, and today the company is one of the countrys leading investment trusts, Genbel South Africa.<BR><P>
ANGLOS OVERSEAS EARNINGS DECLINE  <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
Anglos off-shore arm, Minorco, has reported mediocre results in the six months ended June 30. The company, which looks after Anglos interests in North America, said bad weather in the North America, Europe and Latin America was the major contributor to the lukewarm performance in the first six months of the year.<BR><P>
</DOC>
