<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 12 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>



<BR><P>MINING AGREEMENT MAY BE LAST DEAL IN TRADITIONAL FORUM <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The <A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/releases/wages96.htm">mining industry wage deal</A> signed yesterday between the Chamber of Mines and the National Union of Mineworkers could represent the last agreement signed between the parties in the traditional bargaining forum.  Both parties indicated that in the current circumstances the overall package agreed on was honourable.  However, it became evident during the protracted and very tough negotiations that the bargaining system within the Chamber would have to change as it could not accommodate growing differences between the mining houses and between gold and coal mines<I>.[Click <A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/speeches/96wagsgn.htm">here </A>for the full text of the address by the President of the Chamber of Mines at yesterday's signing ceremony - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
TAXPAYERS TO FOOT BILL FOR FAILED AIDS PLAY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The taxpayer is to foot the bill for the failed AIDS awareness musical <I>Sarafina 2</I> following a secret donor's withdrawal yesterday of a R10,5m government bale-out.  President Mandela has blamed the withdrawal on a "media uproar" over the donor's identity. The <I>Cape Times</I> reports that Health Minister Nkosazana Zuma told a Press conference yesterday the R10,5m would now be regarded as "unauthorised expenditure" and be dealt with in the normal way.<I> [This debacle has already been called "a national scandal" and various media reports tell of mounting anger among ordinary citizens who feel they have been lied to or "kept in the dark" by government - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
SHELL HOUSE ISSUE RAISED AGAIN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Shell House shootings in March 1994 rivalled<I> Sarafina 2 </I>as one of the African National Congress' worst bungles and would not go away until  satisfactory answers had been provided, opposition parties said yesterday.<BR><P>
DRAFT CORRUPTION LEGISLATION TABLED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Draft legislation allowing the president to appoint special investigating units and tribunals to deal swiftly with claims of maladministration, corruption and misappropriation of public funds was tabled in Parliament yesterday.  At present these problems are combated by independent institutions which do not share the same objectives.<BR><P>
ANGLOVAAL INDUSTRIES HELD BACK BY RISING COMPETITION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglovaal Industries lifted earnings before exceptional items by 4% to R511,8m for the year to June, reined in by tough conditions and rising foreign competition.<BR><P>
MID WITS TO PAY ET CONS R70M FOR STAKE IN NICO <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglovaal's restructuring plans moved a step forward yesterday with subsidiary Middle Witwatersrand buying Eastern Transvaal Consolidated Mines' stake in the Nkomati nickel venture.<BR><P>
JCI MAY BUILD IRON ORE PLANT IN AFRICA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
JCI is investigating building an iron ore plant in Africa costing up to R2bn.<BR><P>
IMPLATS MISLEADS SHAREHOLDERS - BAFOKENG <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The long-running dispute between Impala Platinum and the Bafokeng nation took a new twist yesterday with the Bafokeng accusing Implats of misleading its shareholders about the matter.  In an advertisement published yesterday the Bafokeng said portions of the 1995 and 1996 annual reports by chairman Michael McMahon on the dispute were "factually incorrect".<BR><P>
PROBE INTO MINE CARNAGE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Labour Court judge-president John Myburgh has been appointed to head a commission of inquiry into mine violence at three Gold Fields mines over the past two months, the Labour Ministry said last night. <I>[Several media have presented a misleading picture of the terms of reference of the commission saying it would probe "violence on SA mines" - implying its ambit would cover all SA mines. This is incorrect. Labour Minister Tito Mboweni said during a radio interview this morning the commission would only focus attention on the recent events at East Driefontein, Leeudoorn and Northam. No reports of violence on other mines have been received. He did add he was in favour of a wider ranging investigation to include all mines, and that the Myburgh Commission might thus serve as a "precursor" to such a probe - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
MANUEL 'DOING PRETTY GOOD JOB' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel and his team are actually doing a pretty good job, says the Inkatha Freedom Party.  While other political parties used recent budget debates in Parliament to berate Manuel for everything from the high crime rate to the Springbok rugby team's poor showing, the IFP stopped just short of congratulating him on his performance.<BR><P>
CAUTIOUS NOD FOR TAX INCENTIVES PLAN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu) has reluctantly approved the Trade and Industry Department's plan for tax incentives for new investments, proposing only minor changes.<BR><P>
COSATU EXPECTS FIERY DEBATE ON CRUCIAL ISSUES AT MEETING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Heated debate is expected around the adoption of positions on government's macro-economic strategy, state asset restructuring and the employment standards statute, at Cosatu's last central executive committee meeting of the year which starts today.<BR><P>
FW PLEDGES SUPPORT FOR SA'S ECONOMIC STRATEGY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The opposition National Party fully endorsed government's macro-economic strategy and would work to ensure it was implemented, NP leader FW de Klerk assured US businessmen and international bankers yesterday.<BR><P>
NEDLAC TO DEVELOP TRADE POLICY ON FRIDAY <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Nedlac (the National Economic Development and Labour Council) is expected to develop a clear strategy for the future direction of trade and industry policy at a negotiating session on Friday.  The implications of the internationalisation of the country for business, labour and government will be the main subject of debate.<BR><P>
JP MORGAN OPENS FIRST OFFICE IN SA  <I>(Sowetan, Jhb)</I><BR>
NEW YORK - JP Morgan, one of the worlds biggest financial, banking , investment and consulting institutions, is to open its first office in South Africa in more than 160 years. The companys announcement coincided with Deputy President Thabo Mbekis visit to New York to receive the Business Council of the United Nations Award on behalf of President Nelson Mandela.<BR><P>
GOLD FIELDS FOUNDATION MAKES IMPACT <I>(Sowetan:Mineral Wealth survey)</I><BR>
In line with a new policy, the Gold Fields Foundation has become much more selective, focusing on specific projects rather than spreading resources too thinly. Consequently, a more substantial impact has been made in a number of key areas, including tertiary education, primary health care, environmental education and welfare. The Foundation supports tertiary education to get a greater number of appropriately qualified people into the workplace and the economy.<BR><P>
GOLD FIELDS COMMITS TO NATURE   <I>(Sowetan:Mineral Wealth survey)</I><BR>
Gold Fields has become one of the major contributors to the development of environmental education in South Africa. Over the past ten years, the focus of the Foundations efforts has been to establish environmental education at primary, secondary and tertiary levels. This has led to a network of environmental education centres throughout the country.<BR><P>
RBMS SOCIAL PROJECT   <I>(Sowetan:Mineral Wealth survey)</I><BR>
In its endeavour to empower the community, Richards Bay Minerals has focused its social corporate investment on education, health, job creation and rural upliftment. The Umbonambi Co-op in rural KwaZulu-Natal was started with R1000 donation from RBM five years ago. The company built the premises and then left it to the community to manage.<BR><P>
IMF GOLD TO HELP POOREST COUNTRIES.  <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
Tomorrows meeting of government representatives in the International Monetary Fund is expected to pave the way for as much as R9-billion of IMF gold to be used to reduce the debt of the worlds poorest countries, many of them in Africa.<BR><P>
LAW TO BAN WORKPLACE BIGOTRY   <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
Legislation banning discrimination at the workplace and requiring employers to conform to the Government employment equity plan will be tabled in Parliament early next year; so says the head of the Labour Departments equal opportunities' directorate, Mpo Makwana.<BR><P>
NP TO MEET IRANS PRESIDENT  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
The National Party will meet Iranian President Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani during his two-day visit to South Africa, but the Democratic Party has refused, accusing the Gulf country of international terrorism and an appalling human rights record.<BR><P>

