<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 11 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>



COMMITTEES ANXIOUS TO SPEED UP CRIMINAL LAWS <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
Extraordinary measures have been invoked by Parliament's justice committees to ensure that six new laws to tighten up criminal justice are passed.<BR><P>
DUARTE HELPS ESTABLISH PEACE COMMITTEE AT MINE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gauteng safety and security minister Jessie Duarte yesterday facilitated the establishment of a peace and security committee at Gold Fields' East Driefontein gold mine near Carletonville after violence at the mine which has left at least 30 people dead.<BR><P>
CONFERENCE SETS PACE FOR DEFINING FOREIGN POLICY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The consultative process on SA's future foreign policy framework should continue with workshops to refine the diplomatic approach to specific issues, Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad said in Johannesburg yesterday.<BR><P>
MBEKI ATTACKS INDUSTRIAL CONGLOMERATES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - The unwillingness of SA's biggest industrial conglomerates to compete was a greater obstacle to increased inflows of foreign direct investment than crime or fears about the country's prospects after President Mandela's departure, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said in an interview published in this week's international edition of <I>Newsweek.</I><BR><P>
A TEMPTING BUT TREACHEROUS MORSEL<I> (Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
For many investors, SA started to look like a tempting target after the multiracial elections of more than two years ago.  In the meantime, lack of confidence in the state of the nation has been expressed through the battering of the currency in the capital markets.  While the new government is grappling with the vicissitudes of governance, corporate SA is wanting a world-class, quality-orientated characteristic reminiscent of the better performing countries in the world.  Signals sent to the market are those of a bungling leadership lacking a basic grasp of global economic events and unable to solve domestic problems such a crime and unemployment.<BR><P>
THEORY AND REALITY <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
One of the latest theories circulating around SA's financial markets explaining why the government is so painfully slow in relaxing exchange controls is that the Reserve Bank wants to get all the money that would flee the country swapped before economic freedom follows in democracy's footsteps.<BR><P>
SHORTAGE IN MONEY MARKET SHOOTS UP <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The money market shortage shot up R850m this week to breach the R9bn mark as foreign exchange outflows resumed, traders said yesterday.<BR><P>
MEASURING BOTH PROFILES OF THE DRAGON <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA needs to sort out its relationships with the two Chinas before its dithering costs it its ties with both.  President Mandela has stated categorically that SA will not establish diplomatic relations with the People's Republic of China at the expense of Taiwan.<BR><P>
US GOVT TO MONITOR SA-IRAN DEALINGS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - The US said it would examine business links between SA and Iran case by case before deciding whether the ties violated the new Iran/Libya sanctions law.  <BR><P>
LABOUR ACT PUBLISHED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Labour Amendment Act, which paves the way for implementation of the 1995 Labour Relations Act, was published in the Government Gazette yesterday.<BR><P>
IMPORTANT SECTORS STILL LOSING JOBS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The mining, quarrying, manufacturing and construction sectors of the economy are still shedding jobs, the Central Statistical Services said yesterday.<BR><P>
PUBLIC WORKS DEPT MIGHT HALVE WORKFORCE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The Public Works Department could cut its staff by more than half and force other government departments to pay for their accommodation as part of a drive for greater efficiency, Sipho Shezi, the director-general, said yesterday.  The department has embarked on a transformation process, he said.  Commercialisation of some activities could enable it to reduce staff from about 8 000 to 3 000.<BR><P>
STRIKE CRIPPLES TSUMEB PRODUCTION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Copper and lead production at Gold Fields Namibias Tsumeb operation remained crippled by strike action yesterday as the firm sought further redress in the Namibian courts.<BR><P>
JCI'S HEADLINE EARNINGS BOOSTED BY BETTER PRICES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
JCI boosted headline earnings 31% to R349m in the year to June, as prices for the company's major commodities - particularly coal and ferrochrome - improved markedly.<BR><P>
MORE DEATHS AT LEEUDOORN <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Four workers were killed and three injured at Gold Fields' Leeudoorn mine during an underground inspection on Monday night, a mine official said yesterday.<BR><P>
NUM THREATENS STRIKE AT DE BEERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Production at De Beers mines could be brought to a standstill from Tuesday when about 7000 members of the National Union of Mineworkers planned to strike in support of wage demands, the union said last night.<BR><P>
MINE UNIONS CO-OPERATE TO SAVE SHAFTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The endangered Saaiplaas shafts at Anglo American's Freegold  gold operation have revived the productivity agreement with unions which saved thousands of jobs earlier.<BR><P>
DEBSWANA LOCKED IN LABOUR TUSSLE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
De Beers producer in Botswana, Debswana, is locked in a tussle with labour - centred on shifts - over the proposed introduction of continuous operations at Orapa Diamond Company, which would increase the mine's annual ore throughput about 15% to almost 9-million tons.<BR><P>
UNION MINES LIKELY TO BE LIQUIDATED DESPITE COMPROMISE OFFER <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Union Mines, the embattled manganese operation that was provisionally liquidated earlier this year, is teetering on the edge of final liquidation.  If creditors accept an offer of compromise to be made next week, however, the mine could be saved.  Sources said the offer would be about R1,5m, which would not meet the company's debt of more than 
R6-million.<BR><P>
SA TO STORE IRANIAN CRUDE AT SALDANHA BAY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA would be storing and trading Iranian crude oil at Saldanha Bay, north of Cape Town,  by March next year, the Central Energy Fund said in its 1995/96 annual report.  Iran is not mentioned by name - the report refers to a "crude oil-producing country".  However, Iran is the only nation to have publicly expressed interest in the fund's 45-million-barrel Saldanha storage site.<BR><P>
CANADIAN FIRMS DISCOVER DIAMONDS IN CENTRAL AFRICA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Canadian companies United Reef and Trans Hex International have discovered diamond-bearing gravels in the Central African Republic.<BR><P>
SA NEIGHBOURS MAY GET DIAMONDS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Zimbabwe and Zambia hope to get a share of SA's diamond wealth following their discovery that they own the mineral rights to a property which used to belong to Rhodesia Railways. <BR><P> 
SHAKE-UP INEVITABLE IN SA POLITICS <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
A regrouping of political parties has become inevitable - even though the process might be restricted by the anti-defection clauses in the constitution, and the ethnic support base of political parties.  Despite these restraints, former minister Pik Botha could be correct in his prediction that "theres a new movement coming into being which will undo the divisions of the past" according to political writer, Barry Streek.<BR><P>

