<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 10 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>




CHAMBER TABLES FINAL OFFER TO NUM <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Chamber of Mines has tabled a final wage offer ranging between 6% and 10% for gold mines and between 8,5% and 13% for collieries during tough negotiations with the National Union of Mineworkers (NUM).<I> [There is little new in this report since the Chamber tabled final offers some two weeks ago - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
STRONG NUM ESSENTIAL TO MINE PEACE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Mine violence since the 1980s had become about <I>[sic]</I> maximising union solidarity - punishing those who refused to collaborate and resisting management attempts to destabilise the union by using scabs, vigilantes or "the Russians", NUM president James Motlatsi said yesterday. Faction fighting divided and weakened the work force.  "Mine mangers know this and, not surprisingly, over time they have often instigated tribal conflicts by using various devious tactics to divide us. Over the past 10 years the ethnic composition of the labour force had changed, with the foreign complement falling from 80% to more than 50%.  This has created a greater ethnic awareness among foreign ethnic groups.  The NUM had a role to play in resolving violence.  The union had to ensure the removal of tribalism from the organisation and had to impose its own non-racial morality in the mines.  This could be achieved only if the union fully organised the work force".<BR><P>
INQUIRY AT MINES WELCOMED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR> 
The NUM and Gold Fields have welcomed a decision by the Labour and the Mineral and Energy Affairs departments to ask President Mandela to appoint a commission of inquiry into mine violence <I>[on three Gold Fields mines - Ed.]</I>.<BR><P>
GOLD PRICE FALL EXPECTED TO CONTINUE <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gold broke through its resistance level of $385 an ounce yesterday to a London afternoon fix of $384,60 with brokers expecting further falls.  William Adams, an analyst at Rudolf Wolff, said the main reason was that the International Monetary Fund would vote this week on whether to sell 5m ounces of gold to help third world countries.  Analysts predicted that gold could fall to $382,50 an ounce or even $380 in the short term.<BR><P>
EMU COULD WEAKEN DOLLAR AND GOLD  <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BRUSSELS - The creation of a single European currency could prompt participating national central banks to sell excess dollar and gold reserves, a new study by Goldman Sachs in London showed on Monday.  At the expected start of economic and monetary union in 1999, a European Central Bank will likely be saddled with far more foreign exchange and gold reserves than it needs for trade or currency management purposes, the study argues.<BR><P>
ASHANTI GETS FINANCING PACKAGE  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Lonrho-controlled Ghanaian gold mine, Ashanti Gold Fields, has arranged a Z$400m financing package, based on a seven-year forward gold sale, to provide working capital and cut debt.<BR><P>
UNISEL BECOMES WHOLLY OWNED SUBSIDIARY  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Unisel became a wholly owned subsidiary of Randgold-managed company, Harmony Gold Mining, following its acquisition of Unisel's entire share capital yesterday.<BR><P>
DE BEERS CLOSE TO DEAL WITH RUSSIANS  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
De Beers Central Selling Organisation appeared close to a new deal yesterday to market Russian diamonds, with Russian diamond officials reported as saying the text of an agreement was due to be completed this week.<BR><P>
GENCOR CONSIDERS OFFSHORE REFINERY PARTNER  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gencor is considering selling a stake in its proposed R1,7bn zinc refinery to an offshore mining group to help fund the project.<BR><P>
INTERNATIONAL ANTI-CRIME PACTS SOUGHT  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Justice Minister Dullah Omar has tabled legislation which will allow international co-operation in the "freezing" of assets and the proceeds of crime across international borders, and the imposition of sentences of SA's courts overseas.<BR><P>
HUMAN RIGHTS COMMISSIONERS TO DISCUSS RISING CRIME WITH MANDELA  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A delegation of SA Human Rights Commissioners would meet President Mandela today to discuss the escalation of crime and the violation of human rights of ordinary people and prisoners, Commission chairman Barney Pityana said yesterday.<BR><P>
CONSTITUTION CAN INCLUDE DISPUTED RIGHTS - COURT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Constitutional Court has dismissed complaints that the inclusion of socio-economic rights in the new constitution, including the right to access to housing, health care and water, breached the constitutional principles agreed to by multiparty negotiators.<BR><P>
EU LIST OF BARRED ITEMS 'NOT FINAL'  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The list of 'sensitive' products excluded from the European Union's negotiating mandate for the proposed free trade area agreement with SA was not the final word on the matter, as it contained a number of 'soft spots' open to negotiation, European Commission director-general of development Steffen Smidt said yesterday.<BR><P>
NZO SAYS THERE IS A DRASTIC NEED TO RESHAPE SA'S FOREIGN POLICY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
South African foreign policy was still in transition and a detailed framework based on a national consensus could be expected only after discussion, Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo told a workshop on his department's discussion document in Johannesburg yesterday.<BR><P>
PARASTATALS PREPARE FOR PRIVATISATION  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The imminent privatisation of a number of parastatal organisations - including Sun Air and Aventura - has been facilitated by concerted marketing efforts which have smoothed their transition to commercial enterprises.<BR><P>
A NEW PERSPECTIVE ON AID PURSE STRINGS  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Can it be that US Aid is finally getting the idea that SA is not a place to dump the US's technical assistance surplus and practise extraterritorial affirmative action?  A kind word about the US Agency for International Development's SA mission:  on paper, at least, it appears to be learning.<BR><P>
LABOUR NAMES FIVE PRIVATISATION ADVISERS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
After the recent high-stakes race by international investment houses to advise the government on privatisation, SA's main labour federations named a team of largely unknown consultants to advise them on the restructuring of state assets:  Patrick Bond, a senior researcher at the National Institute for Economic Policy, to advise on housing; Tessa Marcus, an academic at Durban Westville, on agriculture;  Patrick Brennan, principal researcher at Cape Town-based firm Builder's Design Matter, on trade and industry; Simon Roberts, an economics lecturer from Wits University, on transport; and Michael Schwemmle, a German citizen advising trade unions on the restructuring of German telecommunications, on telecomms. in SA.<BR><P>
JUMP IN LOCAL COSTS LIFTS PRODUCER INFLATION TO 6,6%  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Economists were surprised at the failure of the weak rand to make its presence felt in producer inflation figures.  Even though the rand has lost about a quarter of its value against the dollar since it began plunging in February, imported prices are still less than 5% higher than a year ago.  <BR><P>
FRENCH TECHNICAL EDUCATION GRANT SEALED  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The first payment of a R22m French government grant for a new French/SA Technical Institute of Electronics was confirmed on Friday by Deputy Finance Minister Gill Marcus and French Ambassador Tristan d'Albis.<BR><P>
MANDELA CHAIRS SADC  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
President Mandela took over the chairmanship of the 12-nation Southern African Development Community (SADC) yesterday from Botswana head of state, Quett Ketumile Masire, during a brief meeting in Gaborone.<BR><P>
US PROBES KERZNER'S CONTRIBUTION TO ANC  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - A month before Sol Kerzner is due to open his first American casino, on the ancestral soil of the Mohegan Indian tribe in Connecticut, state gambling regulators have asked police to check out former Deputy Environment Affairs Minister Bantu Holomisa's allegation that the Sun International chairman tried to buy favours from the ANC in 1993.<BR><P>
<I>TIME </I>COMMENDS SA, BUT WARNS ON ECONOMY  <I>(The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
<I>TIME </I>magazine has commended the African National Congress for "trying to get it right" after the 1994 election, but has warned the SA needs to boost its economy faster if it is to survive in an aggressively competitive world and not fall to poverty. In a 10-page special report on SA in next weeks edition, titled "After The Miracle", correspondent Peter Hawthorne looks at all aspect of SA society after the transition. If the country could meet the objectives of delivering jobs, an educated workforce and a climate to generate investor confidence as well as boost productivity, it could yet become a global player. "If not, the nation will end up not the best hope and commercial engine for sub-Saharan Africa, but one more poor, illiterate, over-populated and unstable country," he says.<BR><P>
CA WONT REOPEN DEBATE ON CONSTITUTION <I> (Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The major architects of South Africas new Constitution agree that its referral back to the drawing board will not reopen debate on the entire document. The decision by the Constitution Court not to certify the Constitution gave negotiators an opportunity to fine-tune the final constitution, said Provincial Affairs and Constitutional Development Minister and African National Congress negotiator Mohamed Valli Moosa.<BR><P>
TALKS MOVING FAST ON JCI DEAL  <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
Negotiations are taking off at a fast pace between the Anglo group and black consortiums interested in buying the mining arm of Johannesburg Consolidated Investment - JCI Limited. This follows the successful conclusion of the Johnnic talks between the National Empowerment Consortium an Anglo last month.<BR><P>
MANDELA TO VISIT MIDDLE EAST  <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
President Mandela will pay his first visit to the Middle East in November with a tour that includes Israel and Palestinian territories, his office said yesterday.<BR><P>
</DOC>
