<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 9 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>


MBEKI TO SELL SA TO U.S. INVESTORS AND ACCEPT PRIZE <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki will try to reassure Wall Street that government's macro-economic strategy is on track when he visits New York this week to accept an award from the UN Business Council on behalf of President Mandela.<BR><P>
IFP WANTS CHAMBER TO END MINE VIOLENCE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
DURBAN - The Inkatha Freedom Party would seek an urgent meeting with the Chamber of Mines to bring to an end "ethnic cleansing" at mines in Gauteng, Northwest and Northern Province, the party decided at its national council meeting on Saturday as renewed clashes took place between hostel residents at Carletonville's East Driefontein.<BR><P>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
IFP TO MEET GOLD FIELDS OVER KILLINGS  <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Inkatha Freedom Party is to send a top delegation to meet the management of Gold Fields in a bid to end the spate of violent incidents on mines owned by the company. Violence on mines owned by Gold Fields has claimed at least 20 lives since July.<BR><P>
MINERS OUTSIDE MANDELAS OFFICE  <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
A group of disgruntled workers from Rustenburg Platinum Mines has been camping near the Pretoria office of President Nelson Mandela for two weeks seeking his intervention in a labour dispute. The group of about 27 workers is part of thousands of RPM workers who were dismissed in June following in an illegal strike. Some of them were re-employed following intervention by Mandela.<BR><P>
WEAK RAND FAILS TO SLOW GROWTH OF SA'S TRADE DEFICIT WITH THE US <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - The weak South African rand failed to slow the growth of SA's trade deficit with the US in the first six months of this year amid continuing strong demand for US capital goods, Commerce Department statistics show.<BR><P>
RESERVES DROP TO TWO-YEAR LOW <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SA's gross gold and foreign exchange reserves dropped a modest R292-million last month to record their lowest level since the 1994 elections, the Reserve Bank said on Friday.<BR><P>
PPI FIGURES THIS WEEK EXPECTED TO REGISTER AN INCREASE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Producer price inflation figures were expected to have succumbed to a variety of pressures in July, notably costlier imports, economists said on Friday.<BR><P>
SA GOODS TO BE ACCREDITED <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The SA National Accreditation System, a not-for-profit company set up under the guidelines of the Trade and Industry Department, will provide accreditation for SA goods and companies in line with the standards fixed by the International Standardisation Organisation.  <BR><P>
DISRUPTIONS OF JSE TRADING TO BE PROBED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Johannesburg Stock Exchange President Roy Andersen will be "asking some difficult questions" today following networking problems on Friday that caused a five-hour suspension of trade - the third disruption since the exchange completed the move to an automated system two months ago.<BR><P>
SA'S CUSTOMS PARTNERS FEAR LOSSES FROM EU FREE TRADE AGREEMENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA's partners in the Southern African Customs Union fear the European Union's negotiating mandate for a free trade agreement with SA will have devastating effects on their economies.<BR><P>
WELSH IN 12-DAY TRADE VISIT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A Welsh trade delegation of 20 company representatives from small and medium-sized businesses, arrives today on a 12-day visit with the aim of providing goods and services to SA's expanding market.<BR><P>
UNEMPLOYMENT RATE FOUND TO BE INFLATED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA's official unemployment rate - derived from social survey findings or the population census - is significantly inflated, according to an SA Institute of Race Relations bulletin which has been published this month. Unlike most highly industrialised economies, but in common with most of the developing world, SA had no accurate register of unemployment, the bulletin said. It said the last census in 1991 was outdated and its accuracy questionable, and that official unemployment rates had been largely on household surveys by the Central Statistical Services.<I> [The report fails to give any clear indications of the bulletin's equivalent estimates of SA's unemployment rate - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
BRITAIN TO ADMIT IT TOOK LOOTED GOLD <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
LONDON - The British government was expected to admit this week that Britain had taken a share of the $400m worth of gold looted from Jews by Nazis, <I>The Independent</I> reported yesterday.<BR><P>
IRAN AND SA TO EXPAND OIL TIES <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Iran and SA will expand oil ties and set up joint ventures to invest in the sector, the Tehran Times daily newspaper reported on Saturday.  It quoted Gholamreza Aqazadeh , Iran's Oil Minister, as saying that Iran supplies SA with 70% of its oil.  He said Iran wanted to work with the local public and private sectors in oil-refining projects.<BR><P>
SEEKING TO CONTAIN AFRICA'S ECONOMIC GIANT <I>(Business Times, Sunday)</I><BR>
SA's regional trading partners are hoping the newly signed Southern African Development Community trade protocol will speed up the opening of South African markets to regional imports. <BR><P>
TAVISTOCK MAY BOOST JCI <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A strong contribution by its unlisted coal unit, Tavistock, was likely to fuel JCI's profit, pushing it up about 30%, analysts said on Friday.<BR><P>
SMALL INCREASE EXPECTED AT AVI <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Profit was expected to edge up at Anglovaal Industries when it posts year figures on Wednesday as its wide spread of businesses continued to encounter patchy markets, analysts said on Friday.<BR><P>
GENCOR EYES NICKEL GIANT <I>(Business Times)</I><BR>
Colombia will sell its minority stake in Cerro Matoso SA, the world's fourth-largest nickel producer, by mid-December, says Finance Minister Jose Antonio Ocampo.  "We expect to approve the sale on September 16," he said, adding that Gencor, which already owns a 52,3% interest in the mine, was among possible buyers of the government's 47,7% stake. Colombia expects to receive more than $100-million from the privatisation.<BR><P>
RICHARDS BAY PROCESSES RECORD COAL EXPORT TONNAGES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Richards Bay Coal Terminal has processed record tonnages in recent months, as coal exporters work to catch up on production lost due to heavy and unseasonal rains earlier this year.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD PURSUES AFRICAN AMBITIONS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The value placed on Randgold's Jersey-registered exploration arm, Randgold Resources Ltd, has more than doubled since February, when it placed its shares with Australia's North, and UK and North American investors, at US$10 a share.
