<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 6 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>


BUSINESS CONFIDENCE SHOWS SLIGHT RECOVERY <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The SA Chamber of Business Business Confidence Index (BCI) recovered almost half a point in August after the announcement of measures to curb crime and an apparent stabilisation of the economy, Sacob director-general Raymond Parsons said yesterday.<BR><P>
FINAL DECISION ON ELECTRICITY RESTRUCTURING IMMINENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Cabinet is expected to make a final decision on the restructuring of the electricity supply industry within the next three weeks, says the National Electricity Regulator.<BR><P>
CRIME BILLS TO BE RUSHED THROUGH PARLIAMENT SOON <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Important anti-crime legislation will be rushed through Parliament by extraordinary means by the National Assembly and the Senate justice committees in the next few weeks.<BR><P>
FIND COULD BOOST GENCOR ORE RESERVES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gencor has discovered high-grade nickel deposits that could boost its jointly held western Australian ore reserves by 40% to about 20-million tons.<BR><P>
EAST DRIEFONTIEN DEATH TOLL NOW AT 25 <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Mine violence continues to plague Gold Fields' East Driefontein gold mine near Carltonville, with two more deaths this week bringing the death toll to 25 since July 18.<I> [This morning radio news broadcasts report the situation is tense, but calm at the mine with a high police and mine security profile - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
PAC TO LOOK AT ITS FUTURE IN NEW SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A special convention of the Pan-Africanist Congress this month will pave the way for the election of a new party leadership, for some time a thorny issue in the organisation.<BR><P>
ANGLO TO SHOW HUGE PROFIT ON SALE OF JOHNNIC STAKE <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Anglo American will show a huge capital profit, or surplus, on the sale of its 20% stake in Johnnies Industrial Corporation to the National Empowerment Consortium.<BR><P>
MANUEL TO VISIT EUROPE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel, Maria Ramos, the director-general of finance, and Chris Stals, the Reserve Bank governor, are to visit Europe next week, in part to market SA investments, the Finance Department said yesterday.<BR><P>
MADUNA ADDS FIRE TO FUEL <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Penuell Maduna, Minister of Mineral and Energy Affairs, says state regulation - retail price fixing, controlled wholesale margins and restrictions on competition - was introduced as an incentive to secure the international oil companies' services during apartheid and guarantee them a return on their investment.  Deregulation is inevitable and would benefit the economy, he says.  He also intends to shake up the oil supply arrangements that have made SA dependent on Iran since the Shah's imperial days.<BR><P>
MARCUS: TAX HOLIDAYS OPEN TO ALL FORMS OF INVESTMENTS <I>(Business Mail, weekly on Fridays)</I><BR>
This week the government tried to quell fears among some that the incentives set out in the macro-economic plan would favour new investment at the expense of existing companies and jobs. Deputy Finance Minister Gill Marcus said the incentives would be granted on the basis of criteria that were weighted in terms of labour intensiveness and training, and special steps would be taken to ensure all projects were monitored. Some concern has also been expressed that the incentives would divert the economy from a labour-intensive to a capital-intensive path.  Marcus admitted this was an issue, but said the emphasis was on encouraging the installation of a new plan to make industry more competitive and ideally a spin-off benefit would be job creation as well.<BR><P>
HARRY O BLASTS SHAFT  <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Anglo American former chairman Harry Oppenheimer triggered the first blast yesterday marking the start of the R1,1-billion Western Deep Levels South Shaft deepening project. The project would deepen the mines south shaft by 670 metres to a world record 3 841 metres.<BR><P>
ANGLO WILL PROBE NEW MINE DEPTHS  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Anglo American Corporation will launch a R33m rand seismic survey into developing two new ultradeep gold mines that will bore up to five kilometres below surface. The survey, using a seismic technique similar to sonar scanning, will cover some 60 square km south of Western Deep Levels mine.<BR><P>
IMPLATS ACTS TO UP PRODUCTION  <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Impala Platinum Mines and National Union Mineworkers have set a benchmark for the mine industry through their participative management approach, improving production by six percent from last year.<BR><P>
SOUTH AFRICANS CALMER OVER PRESIDENCY  <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
South Africans appear to be calmer about what will happen when President Nelson Mandela relinquishes his position and retires to Qunu. This is not so with many Americans and South African expatriates here who believe that peace and tranquillity may go with the President.
