<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 5 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>




EMPLOYMENT DROP <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Employment in the non-agricultural sector in South Africa fell 1% or by 52 506 workers to 5 176 976 at end-March compared with a year ago, Central Statistical Service figures released yesterday showed.<BR><P>
GOVT EXPENDITURE CUTS UNDER ATTACK <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Financial and Fiscal Commission yesterday sharply criticised government's macro-economic plan, saying expenditure was being cut too fast and would hit provinces' ability to deliver vital services.<BR><P>
TWO SHORT-LISTED FOR CORRIDOR DEAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Two consortiums have been short-listed for the key Maputo Corridor project - a 30-year R600m-R800m contract to build and maintain a road between the Gauteng-Mpumalanga border and Maputo.<BR><P>
VIRGIN ATLANTIC TO MAKE ITS DEBUT AMID PRICE WAR <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Richard Branson's Virgin Atlantic airline, scheduled for take-off in SA next month, is set to fly into heavy weather - a price war has broken out between the international carriers serving SA.<BR><P>
FORMER CISKEI RULER GUILTY OF ILLEGAL DIAMOND DEALING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
MOTHIBISTAD - Former Ciskei military ruler Brigadier Oupa Gqoza was convicted of illegal diamond dealing yesterday after pleading guilty and telling the court how he was arrested in a police trap.<BR><P>
ROBBEN ISLAND TO BECOME WORLD HERITAGE SHOWCASE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Robben Island, once the house of political and common law prisoners, would be developed as a world heritage site and a national monument and museum, Arts and Culture Minister Lionel Mtshali said yesterday.<BR><P>
ORGANISATIONS INTEND UNITING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The National Federated Chamber of Commerce (Nafcoc) and the Afrikaanse Handelsinstituut (AHI) signed a partnership initiative yesterday with the long-term intention of combining both of the organisations "to do everything in their power to work together" to form a single body representing SA business.<BR><P>
MANUEL REJECTS EARLY LIFTING OF EXCHANGE CONTROLS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel yesterday rejected a Democratic Party argument that exchange controls be lifted immediately, and defended governments policy of "no undue haste" on the issue.<BR><P>
GOVT COMMITMENT CAN PLACE SA ON 6% GROWTH <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA had the potential to accelerate its economy towards 6% growth provided government adhered strictly to its macro-economic plan, Standard Bank chief economist Nico Czypionka said yesterday.<BR><P>
COURTS TO RULE ON FINAL DRAFT OF CONSTITUTION TOMORROW <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
After almost two months of speculation the Constitutional Court will deliver its ruling tomorrow on whether SA's final constitution has passed muster to become the supreme law of the land or whether it must go back to the Constitutional Assembly for redrafting.<BR><P>
EXPERTS FROM UK HELP SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Thirteen British businessmen and water consultants are visiting SA to see what can be done to help the local water industry.<BR><P>
SA WARNS FRANCE ON WATER DEALS <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SA issued a veiled threat to the French government yesterday that business opportunities for its companies would be restricted unless France softened its opposition to South African access to the European market for agricultural produce.<BR><P>
DIALOGUE 'THE MOST EFFECTIVE REGULATOR' IN THE WORKPLACE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Dialogue between government, business and labour was the most effective regulatory mechanism to define a co-operative approach to rights and obligations between workers and employers, Labour Minister Tito Mboweni said this week.<BR><P>
MANUEL WILL NOT GIVE SPEECH AT IMF'S ANNUAL MEETING UNTIL 1999 <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The Minister of Finance Trevor Manuel will not deliver a speech at the annual meeting of the International Monetary Fund in Washington this year.  Instead, Barnabas Dlamini, the executive director of the English-speaking group of African countries and the incoming president of Swaziland, will speak on behalf of SA and the other members of the interest group.<BR><P>
ANGLO UNHAPPY WITH ZAMBIA <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Anglo American, the minority shareholder in Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines, was unhappy with the Zambian government's privatisation plans to split up the mining concern into four units before it is sold off by the government, an Anglo spokesman said yesterday.<BR><P>
ADAPT AND DON'T WORRY ABOUT THE RUSSIANS, DE BEERS IS TOLD <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
There are two sides to every story, and the opposing points of view to De Beers boomed out loud and clear at this week's diamond industry conference in Johannesburg.  In a nutshell, key speakers pointed out the fundamentals of the diamond business are changing fast and whether or not the De Beers cartel survives will depend on how well De Beers adapts, rather than worries over specific marketing deals with producers such as the Russians or the Canadians.  "The only people who can screw up the diamond business are De Beers, and they can do it by ignoring the demand side of the equation," said Martin Rapaport, president of Rapaport Corporation.<BR><P>
CRIME POSES A BIGGER RISK THAN THE RAND <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
SA's crime risk is worse than its currency risk, says Nicola Stock, the executive vice-president of Italy's largest bank, Banca di Roma, which has just returned to SA after an 11-year absence.<BR><P>
COSATU CALLS FOR 4% DEDUCTION FROM PAYROLL TO PAY FOR TRAINING <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The introduction by companies for a 4% payroll deduction to finance worker training would help to alleviate SA's poor production levels, blighted by its apartheid past, Connie September, Cosatu's (the Congress of SA Trade Unions) vice-president, said yesterday in an address to the World Productivity Assembly.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
LOW PRODUCTIVITY: MANAGERS BLAMED  <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Insufficiently skilled managers, low wages and apartheid obstacles to black education were the reason for poor productivity in South Africa, Cosatu vice-president Connie September said yesterday.<BR><P>
BLEAK FUTURE FOR SA GOLD <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The gold price would have to reach $500 an ounce to make it worthwhile to mine the bulk of SA's remaining gold because of the rising expense of deep mining and increased labour costs, a report by the London-based Economist Intelligence Unit says.<BR><P>
SURVIVAL TAKES RANDLORDS OVER THE BORDER <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
SA mining houses are forging ahead with the internationalisation of their business, particularly in Africa, where they feel they have a competitive advantage.  Only a few years ago it would have been a rare sight to meet SA mining executives and engineers in other parts of Africa, never mind Latin America or Asia.  Now it is commonplace.<BR><P>
MINE UNIONS ACT ON SAFETY  <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Trade unions in the mining industry took the first bold step towards ensuring that the safety of workers was in their own hands when they met Minister of Mineral and Energy Affairs Penuell Maduna for top-level discussions on the issue on Tuesday. The decision to meet the Minister was to discuss the implementation of the Mine Health and Safety Act which for the first time allows employees to take part in health and safety matters in their work place.<BR><P>
FIRST FORMAL SOUTH AFRICAN ARBITRATION FORUM  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
South Africas first formally administered arbitration facility has been set up in Sandton, north of Johannesburg. It provides a forum for a much speedier dispute resolution than in formal court, with the advantage that parties can select a date of hearing suitable to them.<BR><P>
GOVT NEEDS INSPIRED LEAKER<I> (Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
South Africa could soon get an authoritative US-style press secretary to speak on behalf of the government.  This is among recommendations to be made by the government-appointed Communications Task Group.  Comtask chairperson Mandla Langa said in an interview it was clear a new professionalism was needed in the governments dealings with the media.<BR><P>


