<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 4 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>



GULF TURMOIL IS LIKELY TO PUSH FUEL PRICES UP <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
South African fuel prices are likely to rise again in early October after the US strike against Iraq put pressure on oil prices.<BR><P>
FINNISH MINISTER TO VISIT SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Finland's Finance Minister, Arja Alho, would visit SA from today to Sunday to address a number of conferences, including a seminar concerning the position of women in society, the SA embassy in Finland announced yesterday.<BR><P>
AUSTRALIAN DIAMOND PRODUCER TO STAY IN SOLITAIRE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Australia's Argyle diamond producer had no intention of marketing its diamonds jointly with Russia or any other large producers, Mark Hooper, commercial GM of Ashton Mining, Argyle's parent company, said yesterday.<BR><P>
GOVT MOVES TO ENACT TAX INCENTIVES LAW <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Legislation introducing a range of investment tax incentives in SA is likely to be squeezed through Parliament in the current session, in spite of misgivings about the short period allowed for public comment.<BR><P>
MINING UNIONS LAUNCH LABOUR CAUCUS IN LINE WITH NEW ACT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Mining unions including the Congress of SA Trade Unions-aligned (Cosatu) National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) and the white Mineworkers' Union launched the mining labour caucus yesterday to ensure proper labour representation on the tripartite structures - government, employers and labour - established in terms of the new Mine Health and Safety Act.<BR><P>
SA WILL NOT ENTER A PROLONGED RECESSION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
There is no question of SA entering a prolonged recessionary period, despite recent short-term economic indicators pointing to a distinct economic slowdown, Boland Bank said in its latest economic review.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD MOVES INTO MALI <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Randgold Resources, Rangold's exploration and new business arm, has consolidated its West African foothold by buying BHP Holdings' Mali operations, including control of the Syama gold mine, one of the largest in the area.<BR><P>
LABOUR ACT TO BE ENFORCED <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Labour Minister Tito Mboweni said yesterday a date had finally been set for the implementation of the new Labour Relations Act.<BR><P>
SA NEEDS FLEXIBILITY AND BASIC SAFETY NET <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
A South African productivity strategy would have to combine the promotion of greater labour flexibility with a minimum standard safety net, Labour Minister Tito Mboweni said at the 10th World Productivity Assembly which started in Johannesburg yesterday.<BR><P>
NORTHAM TO RETURN TO NORMALCY <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Northam Platinum mine hopes to resume normal production soon, Gold Fields of SA said yesterday.  <BR><P>
STOPPAGES HIT BARBERTON MINES <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Illegal work stoppages hit the Anglovaal-owned Eastern Transvaal Consolidated gold mines near Barberton yesterday and spread to Sheba and New Consort mines.<BR><P>
NEDLAC TO EDUCATE BUSINESS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Jayendra Naidoo, the chairman of the National Economic Development and Labour Council, said yesterday that Nedlac and the National African Federation of Chambers of Commerce and Industry would run a series of national conferences to educate business on the implications of the new Labour Relations Act.<BR><P>
SUPPLY GAP TO PUSH GOLD PRICE TO $580 BY 2010 - EIU  <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
London - A supply gap too great to be filled by central bank sales and Far Eastern investor liquidation will push gold prices to $580 per ounce by 2010, the Economic Intelligence Unit (EIU) said in a report.<BR><P>
ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP WINS AWARD  <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Natal Parks Board yesterday awarded the Conservation Award to the Campaign for St. Lucia for its "selfless" campaign to stop the dune mining at St. Lucia on the KwaZulu/Natal north coast. Environment and traditional affairs MEC Inkosi Nyanga Ngubane presented the award to the lobby group at a function held in Durban.<BR><P>
RoC VICE-PREMIER IS REASSURED ON SOUTH AFRICAN  TIES <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Taiwanese Vice-Premier Li-teh Hsu said yesterday he was reassured that South Africa would continue to be the islands diplomatic ally even after the retirement of President Mandela, because he believed the Pretoria government would not dump Taiwan after Mandela retires in 1999 <I>[as president of the republic]</I>.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
SOUTH AFRICA. RoC TIES TO STAY SAYS NZO  <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Mainland Chinas criticism this week of  South Africas decision to maintain ties with the Republic of China would not change the governments stance on the matter, SA's Foreign Affairs Minister Alfred Nzo said yesterday.<BR><P>
BUSINESS TO DEBATE DEVELOPMENT POLICY  <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Two watershed government policy documents dealing with human resource development are to be debated by big business next week in an attempt to find an employee training system that will be compatible with economic growth.<BR><P>
SABC RADIO AND TV SIGNAL OPERATIONS TO BE SEPARATED (BD Pg 13)
The SA Broadcasting Corporations radio and TV signal distribution operations would soon be formally separated by Parliament to create what is believed to be the largest entity of its kind, with assets of R382-million and a turnover of R20,9-million.<BR><P>
