<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 3 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>



OIL DECISION DELAYED <I>(Business Day, Jhb)</I><BR>
The decision on the storage and marketing of Iranian oil had been delayed at least until October as possible contamination of groundwater and soil at Saldanha Bay was being assessed, Central Energy Fund GM Kobus van Zyl said yesterday.<BR><P>
NORTHAM PLATINUM <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Northam Platinum said yesterday that concentrator plant throughput fell to 130 000 tons last month, from 150 000 tons in July, following violence on the mine last month.<BR><P>
GOLD FIELDS TARGETS TARKWA PRODUCTION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold Fields of SA could reverse Ghanaian opencast gold mine Tarkwa into a listed vehicle or it could tap shareholders to fund the $125m project, among other options, the group said yesterday.<BR><P>
DRIEFONTEIN MINERS RETURN TO WORK <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Most workers at Driefontein Consolidated's east gold mine reported for work yesterday after staying away since Wednesday, Gold Fields of SA said.<BR><P>
EU UNDER FIRE FOR ITS TACTICS IN TRADE TALKS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Three parliamentary committees have agreed to get tough with the European Union over its mandate for a free trade agreement with SA, and have sharply criticised EU tactics as threatening the integrity of domestic policy-making.<BR><P>
ANC 'GLOVES OFF' IN FIGHT AGAINST CRIME <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The ANC's weekend security summit has recommended a range of tough new crime-fighting measures, including the creation of a special state crime-fighting fund, a category of non-bailable offences and the imposition of minimum sentences for certain serious crimes.<BR><P>
CAPE'S 2004 HOPE STILL ALIVE - RAMSAMY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
National Olympic Committee of SA president Sam Ramsamy said yesterday he did not believe recent vigilante violence against gangs and drug lords in the Western Cape had damaged Cape Town's chances of winning the bid for the 2004 Olympics.<BR><P>
TANZANIA DRAWS UP PRIVATISATION LIST <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Tanzania has earmarked 128 state-owned firms for privatisation by the end of next year.  A detailed list and timetable for the exercise would be made public in a fortnight, a senior official said yesterday.  Tanzania Breweries, owned jointly by an SA firm and the Tanzanian government, is among firms slated for listing.<BR><P>
NUM STRIKE BALLOT RESULTS DUE TOMORROW <I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
The results of the National Union of Mineworkers' (NUM) strike ballot at De Beers diamond mines is expected tomorrow, Ben Molapi, a union spokesman, said yesterday.  The ballot was called last month after the company and the union failed to reach a compromise between their wage offer and demand of 9,25% and 11 percent.<BR><P>
MONEY-LAUNDERING LEGISLATION IN THE WORKS <I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
The Law Commission is investigating widening money-laundering legislation to force banks and other financial institutions to report suspicious cash deposits above a set limit to the police, the commission said at a meeting of the National Assembly's justice portfolio committee yesterday.  The committee is considering three Bills aimed at crimes like drug trafficking, including the Proceeds of Crime Bill, which will make money laundering an offence.<BR><P>
A LEAF OUT OF MALAYSIA'S BOOK <I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
The SA government and business leaders would do well to take a leaf out of the book of Malaysia if the country's success, as measured by economic growth, foreign investment and a general increase in living standards, is anything to go by.<BR><P>
ROOIBERG TIN DENIES HAVING HELD NEGOTIATIONS WITH UNION MINES <I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
Rooiberg Tin was not and never had been involved in negotiations with Union Mines, Simon Malone, chairman of Rooiberg Tin said last night,  The emphatic denial that any transaction was in progress followed an article in Friday's Business Report in which a terse letter signed by Nico Lotterie, the chairman of Union Mines, referred to a scheme of arrangement with Rooiberg.<BR><P>
ISCOR FAVOURS RICHARDS BAY FOR PROCESSING PLANT<I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
South African iron and steel giant Iscor has chosen the Richards Bay-Empangeni area for the proposed R1,5b heavy minerals mining project and central processing complex.<BR><P>
SA GOLD PRICE TO CLIMB-MORGAN GRENFELL <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Spot gold should hit $400 per ounce this year and the SA bullion price a minimum of 1,833 rand per ounce by year end, Deutsche Morgan Grenfell said.<BR><P>
NEW CABINET MEMBER <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
Lionel Mtshali was sworn in yesterday as Minister of Arts, Culture, Science and Technology at Tuynhuys by Judge President of the Cape, Justice Gerald Friedman.  Mtshali replaces Ben Ngubane, who has become an MEC in KwaZulu-Natal province.<BR><P>
CHINA UPSET AT SAS TAIWAN POLICY  <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
China (Beijing) is "greatly concerned" over South African President Mandelas recent decision to maintain ties with Taiwan, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen Guofand said yesterday.<BR><P>
WORRY AS COMMERCIAL CRIMES GO UNSOLVED  <I>(The Citizen)</I><BR>
The South African Police Services yesterday expressed concern that the Commercial Crime Unit had managed to solve only six percent of the cases reported to it in the first six months of this year.<BR><P>
CARDOSO TO VISIT SOUTH AFRICA  <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Brazils President Fernando Cardoso is to pay a three-day state visit to South Africa from November 26 at President Nelson Mandela's invitation, the Department of Foreign Affairs announced yesterday.<BR><P>
GOLD FIELDS MINE STILL TENSE  <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
A veil of tension hangs over Gold Fields Leeudoorn Mine despite a peace agreement reached between warring members of the National Union of Workers (NUM) and United Workers Union of South Africa (UWUSA) last week.<BR><P>

</DOC>
