<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 2 SEPTEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center>
<BR><P>

NP WANTS RAFSANJANI'S VISIT TO BE RECONSIDERED <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The NP is to ask President Mandela to postpone Iranian President Akbor Hashemi Rafsanjani's visit to SA - scheduled for later this month - until the FBI has finished investigating the TWA Flight 800 air crash off Rhode Island last month.  <BR><P>
GHANA DELEGATION IN SA TO FORGE LINKS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A high-powered trade and investment delegation from Ghana led by presidential adviser Paul Obeng arrived yesterday on an eight-day visit seeking import and export opportunities for a variety of goods and services.<BR><P>
VAT RATE RISE WILL GIVE GOVT CREDIBILITY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A two percentage point hike in the Value Added Tax (VAT) rate could help lend credibility to government efforts to reduce state borrowing, one of the economic structural weaknesses responsible for the fragile rand, Board of Executors Asset Management said in its latest investment outlook.<BR><P>
DE BEERS BLAMED FOR INDIAN DIAMOND CHAOS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Blame for the turmoil in the Indian diamond cutting industry lay squarely with De Beers and its Central Selling Organisation, which is responsible for the international rough (or uncut) diamond cartel, Ashton Mining MD John Robinson said last week.<BR><P>
PETROL PRICE TO FALL, DIESEL GOING UP <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA petrol price will drop 3c/l on Wednesday, but diesel will be up 2c/l in the wake of divergent trends in international prices for oil products.  In Gauteng, the pump price for petrol will be 209c/l, while diesel will be 198c/l.<BR><P>
INGWE AND BLACK GROUP PLAN NEW COLLIERY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gencor's Ingwe coal interest is on the verge of concluding a deal with Kuyasa - SA's first black-owned coal mining company - which will see the development of a new opencast operation near Delmas Colliery after capital expenditure of about R5m.<BR><P>
DECLINE EXPECTED IN GOLD, FOREX RESERVES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA's gold and foreign exchange reserves were likely to have declined further in August following an attack on the rand which saw the currency reach a new low of R4,59 to the dollar last month, economists said on Friday.<BR><P>
KEY TO OIL PRICE POLICY STILL SASOL'S ACCORD WITH OIL FIRMS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The further the oil price debate progresses in SA the more intractable the issues become.  It is trite to say we need a liberated market, free of price controls and open to any serious new entrants, but more difficult working out how to get there.<BR><P>
UNIONS SHOULD BUY INTO PRIVATISED COMPANIES: SHILOWA <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Union investment arms should buy into privatised companies when state assets were restructured, Sam Shilowa, general secretary of the Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu), said at the weekend.  "We can't say that a state asset should be sold and then sold only to the bourgeoisie", he said.<BR><P>
MOST LEEUDOORN WORKERS BACK AT WORK <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Most of the employees at Kloof Gold Mining Company's Leeudoorn division had returned to work on Friday after an agreement was signed on Wednesday to end mine violence, the company said on Friday.  But mine managers at Gold Fields said at least 16% of Leeudoorn's workforce of 6 700, all Zulu-speaking and members of the United Workers Union of SA, had left the mine. <I>[Radio news reported this morning that two more bodies, one decapitated, had been found at Leeudoorn at the weekend - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
OPTIMISM IN FINANCIAL MARKETS FACES SEVERAL TESTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The wave of optimism that has been building in the financial markets since last week's release of the encouraging money-supply and trade-account figures is set to be tested a few times this week.  Unforeseen external shocks aside, this upbeat attitude may still be intact by the time the Reserve Bank releases last month's gross reserve figures on Friday.<BR><P>
CYRIL SETS HIS SIGHTS ON JCI'S POT OF GOLD <I>(Business Times, Sunday)</I><BR>
Not content to rest on the laurels of this week's historic Johnnic deal, Cyril Ramaphosa has set his sights on a new target - Johnnic's sister company, gold mining group JCI Ltd.  In an interview with Business Times, Ramaphosa, who led the National Empowerment Consortium in the Johnnic negotiations, talked about the NEC's strategy and his personal ambitions.  <BR><P>
GENCOR PROVES THERE'S LIFE BEYOND THE GLITTERING ROCKS <I>(Business Times)</I><BR>
It was not long ago, says Gencor's executive chairman Brian Gilbertson, that the group was largely a gold mining house.  Its results, released this week, confirmed the wisdom of its decision to diversify across a range of products - notably aluminium - and regions, not to mention its strategy of increasing exposure to investments which pump cash into the group.<BR><P>
FAR EAST GOLD - MORIBUND MARKET SEEN CONTINUING <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
HONG KONG - Far East gold traders thumped foreheads in frustration at the market's foot-dragging this week and forecast on Friday that next week would not be much better.<BR><P>
BEMA SAYS CHILE GOLD LODE MAY TOP 15-MILLION OUNCES <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
VANCOUVER - Bema Gold Corp said on Friday it believes its Cerro Casale deposit in Chile will ultimately prove to contain more than 15-million ounces of gold, although more exploration work is needed.<BR><P>
IMF GOLD SALE PLAN STILL TO BE RESOLVED <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - The future of a plan to sell a small portion of the International Monetary Fund's gold holding to help relieve the debt of the world's poorest countries still hinges on the attitude of key wealthy nations, monetary sources said on Friday.<BR><P>
QUEENSLAND BACK ON AUSTRALIAN GOLD MINING MAP <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SYDNEY - A number of new gold mines slated to come on stream later this year and in 1997 are securing Queensland's position as Australia's second largest gold-producing state, analysts and miners say.<BR><P>
NATIONAL STRATEGY ON SKILLS TRAINING MOOTED  <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A decision on a national strategy to improve the skills of the South African workforce will be taken before the end of the year, according to National Economic Development and Labour Council executive director Jayendra Naidoo.
</DOC>
