<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 31 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>





STRONG PERFORMANCE FROM DUIKER <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Duiker Mining, the Lonrho group's coal and gold producer, posted a 79% rise in taxed earnings to R164m in the year to September as coal sales rose 27% to 9,5m tons and prices in both the export and inland markets rose sharply.<BR><P>
GENGOLD STANDS BY BRACKEN SHARE VALUES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Mining house Gengold has rebuffed claims that the pro rata distribution of Bracken for Kinross share did not accurately reflect the market value for Bracken.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD BENEFITS FROM EFFICIENT OPERATIONS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The gold mines managed by Randgold & Exploration reported one of the most impressive results in the September quarter, capping a year in which the group has established its credentials as a major low-cost SA mining house.<BR><P>
MOTHER OF ALL FORECASTS FOR HJ JOEL, BUT ON TRACK SO FAR <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A striking feature of the last two sets of quarterly reports from the SA gold mining industry is the continuing improvement in the level of disclosure from the mining houses, some of which, like Gengold, Randgold and JCI, are now prepared to give precise forecasts for production and costs on the quarter ahead.<BR><P>
ANGLO AMERICAN FIRMS GRIP ON ASHANTI <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Anglo American Corporation has firmed its grip on highly-prized Ashanti Goldfields of Ghana by becoming the largest shareholder in Britain's Lonrho Plc, analysts said on Wednesday.<BR><P>
RAND WILL STABILISE OVER THE COMING MONTHS, SAYS SWISS BANK UBS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Swiss Bank UBS predicted yesterday that the rand would stabilise over the coming months and that it would appreciate relative to inflation differentials next year.<BR><P>
WELCOME TO DISNEYRAND <I>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
The rand's continuing fall is no longer a measure of fundamental economic factors or technicalities such as purchasing power parity.  It clearly shows that investors and currency traders are convinced that neither the SA government nor the Reserve Bank will do what is necessary to internationalise the economy fully.<BR><P>
GOVT DEBT REACHING 'DANGEROUS' LEVELS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA's state debt was seriously understated, suggesting that the country was "dangerously close" to falling into a debt trap, if not there already, the Board of Executors warned in its latest investment outlook.<BR><P>
POLLS SAYS RESERVE BANK SHOULD QUIT MARKET <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
A snap survey yesterday revealed support in the financial markets for the final withdrawal of the Reserve Bank as a market-maker in government bond and the replacement of the central bank by local and foreign private sector market-makers.<BR><P>
SPOORNET CHARGES 'MAKE CAPE COAL COSTS PROHIBITIVE' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Cape coal industry was in dire straits due to severe upward pressure on coal prices and 'prohibitive' Spoornet rail transport charges, industry sources said yesterday.<BR><P>
CALL FOR MEDIA'S RESTRUCTURING  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Press should be restructured at the ownership level to create full diversity of media, and should change the way it approaches political and economic transformation in future, Nail deputy executive chairman Cyril Ramaphosa said yesterday.<BR><P>
GOVT MUST DEVELOP SKILLS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Black Management Forum president Lot Ndlovu has criticised government and big business for failing to deliver skills as a core requirement for economic growth in SA.  He said while there was a consensus that economic growth should be achieved, government and the private sector were slow in addressing the skills shortage.<BR><P>
SA ON TRACK TO CUT NATIONAL DEFICIT: MIN <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
CAPE TOWN - South Africa was "on track" to bring down its national deficit to the level of four percent  of Gross Domestic Product next year, Finance Minister Trevor Manuel told the National Assembly yesterday. <BR><P>
TAX HIKES MAY LEAD TO HUGE BRAIN DRAIN <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The plan to increase tax on retirement funds from 17% to 30% next year could lead to a massive brain drain, two labour federations warned yesterday. The Federation of SA Labour Unions (Fedsal) said SA would experience a repetition of last years mass scale early retirement of senior employees if the increase was implemented.<I> [The other labour body quoted is the National Council of Trade Unions (Nactu) - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
COAL MINE REHABILITATION WINS AWARD <I>(The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Coal dumps can be rehabilitated to look like flat-topped mountains covered with indigenous plants. This has been proved by a team from the Department of Water Affairs and Forestry who project to rehabilitate 16 abandoned collieries<I> [in northern KwaZulu/Natal]</I> and their associated coal dumps has scooped the top honours of the environmental division of the SA Institute of Civil Engineers.<BR><P>
</DOC>
