<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 24 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>








<p>TWO MINERS KILLED <i>(Business Day, Jhb.)</i><br>
Two miners were killed in a mudslide at Elandsrand Gold Mining
Company yesterday. Mine Manager Anglo American said the incident
would be probed.<br>
</p>

<p>JCI AIMS FOR 'STAFF FRIENDLY' RESTRUCTURING PROGRAMME <i>(Business
Day)</i><br>
The trend of SA's mining houses to streamline their operations
continues with JCI's decision to restructure its non-core interests.
Chairman Bill Nairn said the group had embarked on a review of its
strategy, structures and systems. Nine internal business areas
are affected, including head office security, organisational
development, vehicle services, investments, pension administration and catering
and cleaning. <br>
</p>

<p>ANGLO HOLDS COPPER TALKS WITH ZAMBIA <i>(Business Report,
Jhb.)</i><br>
Nicky Oppenheimer, the deputy chairman of Anglo American,
confirmed yesterday that the group was negotiating with the Zambian
government over its role in the reprivatised copper mining industry. <br>
</p>

<p>ZAMBIAN COPPER MINE SACKS 68 STRIKING WORKERS <i>(Business
Day)</i><br>
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines has sacked 68 miners at its
Nchanga Division for staging a one-day strike and vandalising
company property on Monday, the state-run Times of Zambia said yesterday. <br>
</p>

<p>REVISED WAGE OFFER LIKELY TO SATISFY NORTHAM MINERS <i>(Business
Report)</i><br>
NUM said yesterday workers at Northam Platinum were debating
management's latest wage offer and a planned strike at the mine
was likely to be averted. <br>
</p>

<p>RAND WEAKENS IN THIN TRADING AFTER INFLATION <i>(Business
Report)</i><br>
The currency markets did not take kindly to the disappointing
September inflation data released yesterday, with the rand taking
another knock against the dollar. The rand ended the day at R4,5710
from the previous close of R4,5670.<br>
</p>

<p>FOOD PRICES FUEL SHARP INCREASE IN THE INFLATION RATE <i>(Business
Day)</i><br>
SA's inflation rate in September rose sharply to 8,4% from 7,5%
in August slightly higher than expected - as food prices took their
toll. Central Statistical Service figures released yesterday showed
the consumer price index (CPI) rose 1% month on month bringing
the annual inflation rate to its highest level since July last
year.<br>
</p>

<p>GOLD RALLIES AS DEMAND INCREASES <i>(Business Report)</i><br>
International gold prices rallied yesterday as speculators
started buying again on figures that showed physical demand had picked
up, analysts said yesterday.<br>
</p>

<p>SA MAY NEED LOAN FROM IMF, SAYS STALS <i>(Business Report)</i><br>
Chris Stals, the governor of the Reserve Bank, will advise the
government to apply for a loan from the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) if there are no signs over the next few months of South Africa's
balance of payments improving. &quot;We don't think we really
have a crisis on our hands,&quot; Stals said on Tuesday. &quot;We
think the process is already in progress to reduce the deficit on
the current account.&quot;<br>
</p>

<p>PREMIERS DISSATISFIED WITH BUDGET CUTS FOR 1997/98 <i>(Business
Day)</i><br>
Cabinet and provincial premiers were briefed yesterday by the
Finance Department on the 1997/98 Budget amid indications of high
levels of dissatisfaction with provincial budget allocations.
Cabinet secretary Jakes Gerwel acknowledged that provincial
premiers were not satisfied with their allocations, but said it
would be difficult to imagine how any department could be
satisfied, given the constraints placed on the overall budget.<br>
</p>

<p>ERWIN CALLS FOR RAPID OPENING OF SA MARKETS TO AFRICA <i>(Business
Day)</i><br>
HARARE - SA would have to open its markets more rapidly to the
Southern African Development Community than to trading blocks
like the European Union, Trade and Industry Minister, Alec Erwin
said yesterday. SA exports to the region were growing too fast to
facilitate long-term growth and this would create problems, he
told the second International Herald Tribune trade and investment
meeting.<br>
</p>

<p>LIMITED TARIFF REDUCTIONS WILL ASSIST IMPORTERS <i>(Business
Report)</i><br>
The Trade and Industry Department plans to reduce tariffs on
certain inputs to provide some relief after the recent drop in value
of the rand, Alan Hirsch, the Department's chief director of
industry and technology strategy, said yesterday.<br>
</p>

<p>PRIVATISATION PROCESS GAINS MOMENTUM <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Almost a year since the privatisation initiative was announced by
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki and organised labour accused
government of &quot;betrayal&quot;, there are clear signs that
the process is moving ahead. Nonetheless, market perception is that
too little action is taking place and that the process is bogged
down, in part at least, by consultation and negotiation. When
labour and government reached a National Framework Agreement on
state asset restructuring, big business and some political
parties accused government of conceding to labour demands and
effectively placing privatisation on the backburner. Recent
events regarding Telkom and Sun Air, in particular, should go
some way to placating these elements. Yet there remains a
perception at local and international level that government and
particularly the Public Enterprises Ministry - is unfocused and unprepared,
and has yet to spell out policy on the restructuring of state
assets.<br>
<b><i>... however ...</i></b><br>
OLD HABITS DIE HARD <i>(Business Report)</i><br>
Stella Sigcau, Minister of Public Enterprises, has launched a new
communications strategy to convey her ministry's progress in the
restructuring of public assets to the world at large. At a privatisation conference
this week, Sigcau said the new strategy sought to remedy wild speculation
in the media about what her ministry was up to. &quot;It's a
great pity that so far our efforts have gone unnoticed. Very often
we see wild speculation by the media about our programmes and
this can lead to a distortion of facts&quot;, she said. The move
might well have been spurred by what she called &quot;unnecessary
and negative publicity&quot; that arose from the revelations
about Transnet's pension fund and directors' salaries last week.<br>
</p>

<p>DIVERSITY 'KEY TO STAFF UPLIFTMENT' <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Affirmative action in the US had not completely levelled the
playingfield for minorities and women, General Motors' human resources
director Elmer C Jackson yesterday told delegates at the Institute of
Personnel Management convention at Sun City. Jackson, who has
been in human resources for 34 years, said he had witnessed the
US journey from segregation and legally sanctioned discrimination
to civil rights legislation, affirmative action plans and
diversity programmes. And, although they had made progress since
then, &quot;we are far from finished&quot;, he said.<br>
</p>

<p>NAFCOC LASHES OUT AT RACIAL IMBALANCES <i>(Business Report)</i><br>
Exploding population growth allied to high unemployment could
overtake all efforts to create a viable economy unless SA achieved
acceptable participation by blacks in corporate structures within
a reasonably short period, Joe Hlongwane, the national president
of the National Federation of Chambers of Commerce (Nafcoc),
warned at the annual congress of the Afrikaanse Handelsinstituut
yesterday.<br>
</p>

<p>ANC'S SUPPORT DROPS, NP STATIC <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
The ruling African National Congress has recorded a 10% loss in
support since the general elections, while the National Party support
was at the same level as in 1994, a Human Sciences Research
Council survey has found. The survey said ANC support had dropped
from 63% in May 1994 to 53%, but no other party had picked up the
10% in lost voters. &quot;This may be an early indication that
dissatisfied ANC supporters may decide not to vote, rather than
vote against the ANC (in 1999)&quot;, the HSRC said.<br>
</p>

<p>REPORT CITES BORDER CHAOS <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
A national agency should be created to oversee control of SA's
borders, stemming the flood of illegal immigrants and the escalating
cross-border crime, an SA Police Services report recommends.<br>
</p>

<p>SMUGGLING JEOPARDISES SAA FLIGHTS <i>(Business Report)</i><br>
SAA may be forced to cut the Johannesburg-to-Cape Town leg of 13
international flights a week if the SA Revenue Services insists
on stopping it from taking on domestic passengers during the hour-long
stop the flights make at Johannesburg, a spokesman said
yesterday.<br>
</p>

<p>BRAZIL STILL SEEN COMPETING FOR MINING INVESTMENTS <i>(Reuters)</i><br>
BRASILIA - Brazil has come a long way in removing barriers to
foreign investment in its mining sector, but must still compete fiercely
against numerous other countries, said the designated chief economist
for the concern.<br>
</p>

<p>GOLD REFINERS NEED TO ADD VALUE <i>(Reuters)</i><br>
PERTH - Australia's largest gold refiner, GoldCorp, said on
Wednesday it must provide value-added services if it is to compete
in an increasingly overcrowded marketplace. <br>
</p>

<p>ARGENTINE FOOTHOLD FOR LONRHO <i>(Reuters)</i><br>
BUENOS AIRES - British mining group Lonrho Plc has taken a small
foothold in southern Argentina and is set to start exploring at
an abandoned mine site in the next few weeks, the firm's local
partner said.<br>
</p>

<p>19% RISE IN EMIGRATION FIGURES <i>(The Star, Jhb.)</i><br>
CAPE TOWN - Emigration in the first six months of this year was
up by almost 19% compared to the same period last year. Mangosuthu
Buthelezi, the Minister of Home Affairs, told the National Assembly
yesterday that 2 599 economically active people left the country
between January and June. In the same period there were 751
immigrants, a 2,5% drop compared to the first six months of last
year.<br>
</p>
</DOC>
