<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 23 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>




JCI BUCKS TREND WITH 30% LEAP IN PROFITS<I> (Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
JCI bucked the downward trend in gold mining quarterly results yesterday, posting a 30% rise in aggregate operating profit in the September quarter to R129m from R99m in the June quarter.<BR><P>
HJ JOEL TURNS IN A WELCOME PROFIT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
JCI's gold mines boosted their aggregate operating profit 28% to R116m as increased gold production and an improved gold price overshadowed the 9,6% rise in working costs.  The best news was HJ Joel turning in another of its rare profitable quarters, although this looks set to change.  The mine's operating profit of R29m was more than double September's level (R12,7m), and there was money left after capital expenditure.<BR><P>
MINES DEAL COULD UNLOCK LAND VALUED AT R100M <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Randgold & Exploration could unlock land valued at about R110m in a deal which will see four of its mines sell unused property to foreign-owned Rand Leases Properties.<BR><P>
GENCOR, AUSTRALIAN FIRM IN INDONESIAN DEAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gencor and an Australian base-metals company have signed a letter of intent to conduct a preliminary evaluation of an integrated nickel and cobalt resource in Indonesia.<BR><P>
MINE SHAREHOLDERS TOLD TO EXERCISE CAUTION <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Durban Roodepoort Deep, East Rand Proprietary Mines, Rand Leases Properties and Stilfontein Gold Mining said they were involved in talks about their property interests.  Shareholders were advised to exercise caution in their share dealings, the companies said.<BR><P>
ANC, MINING HOUSES FIND COMMON GROUND ON FUTURE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
SA mining houses and the ANC have found areas of agreement on the future of mining in a green paper that was delivered to Penuell Maduna, Minerals and Energy Affairs Minister, last Friday.  The paper was produced by a tripartite steering committee comprising industry, labour and government, a source close to the negotiations said yesterday.<BR><P>
MBOWENI CALLS FOR MODERATE WAGE RISES <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
SUN CITY - Labour Minister Tito Mboweni called for moderate wage increases yesterday, saying this would increase the net wealth of the national economy and ensure that all had a fair and equal chance at creating and benefiting from that wealth.<BR><P>
MBEKI WANTS HUMAN DEVELOPMENT TO DRIVE MACRO-ECONOMIC PLAN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Distinct differences of emphasis emerged yesterday between Finance Minister Trevor Manuel and Deputy President Thabo Mbeki on macro-economic strategy and human development.  During a parliamentary hearing on reducing poverty to mark the international day for the eradication of poverty, Mbeki called for a "comprehensive strategy for growth and development".  This comprehensive strategy could include a "coherent and comprehensive macro-economic framework" and also a human development strategy which should "influence the design of macro-economic policies at the outset".  Earlier, Manuel scorned suggestions that the macro-economic strategy should be amended to include RDP social goals.  He repeated his frequently propounded explanation that the plan was a framework into which other important aspects of government policy would fit.  The plan specified the parameters within which other aspects of government strategy would be contained - not the other way around.<BR><P>
CONFIDENCE 'KEY TO SA GLOBAL SUCCESS' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Confidence needed to be instilled in SA's business and labour organisations for SA to compete successfully in the global market, Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin said yesterday.  "We are in a tough world where there is a high degree of competition and if we do not compete with them, we will be left behind", Erwin said at the annual SA International Trade Exhibition yesterday.<BR><P>
SLOWER SA GROWTH PREDICTED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA's economic growth could slow to 2.5% next year from an expected 2.9% this year as sustained high interest rates and negative business confidence started to take their toll, insurance group, Sanlam economist Johan Louw said yesterday.<BR><P>
STATE ASSET RESTRUCTURING 'VITAL TO INVESTOR CONFIDENCE' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The restructuring of state assets had to show significant progress over the next three years if government's macro-economic strategy was to succeed as envisaged, government economic policy consultant André Roux said yesterday.  Roux, who played an integral role in drawing up the strategy, said that while privatisation was unlikely to have a big effect on economic variables in the short-term, it was vital to boost investor confidence in the longer term.<BR><P>
DEVELOPING COUNTRIES MUST INSIST ON FREE AND FAIR GLOBAL TRADE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
At the heart of the phenomenon of globalisation is a massive experiment in economic restructuring;  a process spearheaded by the Western powers.  This "gamble" is being executed under the rubric of better living standards for all.  But there is no guarantee that this noble goal will be the end product.  On the contrary, globalisation may very well exacerbate gaps between rich global blocs and poor regions.  This is already the reality in many parts of the world.  Yet the dividend of international "free" trade is taken as given by the architects of the World Trade Organisation (WTO).  Such trade is ostensibly the be-all-and- end-all of the problems of global poverty.  A country's "comparative advantage" is seen as the only root to prosperity.  SA and others should, therefore, beef up their "comparative advantage edge" if they are to survive in this self-help post-Cold War era.<BR><P>
AFFIRMATIVE ACTION COULD ERODE HUMAN RIGHTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The anti-discrimination provisions in the new Labour Relations Act, the equality clause in the final constitution and the proposed employment equity legislation are based on the principle of equal treatment.  But what does equal treatment mean in the context of employment?  "Legal scholars argue that a job applicant does not have the right to a particular position just because other applicants are appointed or employed", says JD Verster, a labour lawyer at Webber Wentzel Bowens.  "But a job applicant does have the right to be treated in the same manner as any other applicant", he says.  No constitutional rights to affirmative action exist, and employment equity legislation will have to comply with the equality provisions in the Constitution.  But while affirmative action is commonly accepted as essential to equality, there is a danger that its application could make inroads into the human rights or other protected rights of individuals.  "Retrenching white males to achieve employment equity could, for example, constitute unfair discrimination," says Verster.<BR><P>
SA'S ROLE TOPS AGENDA AT SOUTHERN AFRICAN SUMMIT <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
HARARE - SA's role in the region will top the agenda of the two-day southern African trade and investment summit conference which starts in Harare today.  The conference hopes to capitalise on regional developments like the end of apartheid in SA and the start of peace in Mozambique and Angola.  It also hopes to attract foreign investment and boost trade.<BR><P>
COMMUNICATION REPORT DUE <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The Task Group on Government Communications will hand over its report to Deputy President Thabo Mbeki next week.  It is expected to recommend the disbanding of the R50-million-a-year SA Communication Service and its replacement with a leaner body.<BR><P>
</DOC>
