<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 22 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>






NORTHAM CONCESSIONS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Northam Platinum Mines made concessions on a minimum wage to the National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) yesterday, bringing the parties closer to an agreement, a union official said.  About 96% of NUM members voted in favour of a strike last week.<BR><P>
LEEUDOORN MINE DEATHS NOT LINKED TO CLASHES BETWEEN UNIONS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Alcohol, and not clashes between unions, appeared to be the cause of two unrelated deaths at Gold Field's Leeudoorn Gold Mine at the weekend, police said.  Police did not view the incidents as serious enough to warrant a presence on the mine, West Rand SA Police Services spokesman Sergeant Patrys Greyling said.  They were  investigating the deaths, which did not seem to be the result of clashes between NUM and United Workers' Union of SA (Uwusa) members.<BR><P>
LONRHO WELCOMES LABOUR LAW <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SUN CITY - Tony Frost, the human resources director of Lonrho, yesterday welcomed SA's new Labour Relations Act, which will come into effect later this year.  Frost said the legislation was in line with international trends.  The most significant aspect of the new Act was its provision for tripartism through workplace forums, he said.  "This country has no chance unless we learn to live with each other", he said.  "The most important way of managing our people is through getting their agreement on how they should work".  But Frost warned against "half-hearted attempts at co-determination that could back-fire on management". <BR><P>
ANOTHER 48 HOURS FOR NEC MEMBERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The National Empowerment Consortium's deadline to raise funds for Johnnic has been extended a further 48 hours to cater for those members who have yet to secure financing.<BR><P>
RAND STAGGERS TO ANOTHER RECORD LOW <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The rand crashed to yet another record low against the British pound yesterday, reaching R7,2727 as currency traders warned that sterling's ascent was far from over.  Local traders said SA's beleaguered currency was suffering from the double blow of a strong dollar and even stronger pound on international markets.  "It is the worst of both worlds, as the pound is the only currency to beat the dollar", one said.<BR><P>
HIGH REAL INTEREST RATES 'HERE TO STAY' <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
SAs real interest rates might be high, but they were lower than those of some other emerging economies, and of the developed New Zealand economy, JP Morgan, a US bank, said in an emerging-market report released at the weekend. The bank said a cut in interest rates was unlikely in SA until after next year's Budget was released in March.<BR><P>
MAPUTO CORRIDOR IS 'JUST A START' <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Individual spatial development projects like the Maputo Corridor, aimed at making the SA economy more adaptable to global trade trends and more sensitive to events in regional  trade blocs, are on the cards, Alec Erwin, Trade and  Industry Minister, said at the Durban Metro Business Conference yesterday.  He said these projects would dwarf the Olympic initiative and the $4-billion corridor development itself. <BR><P> 
GOVT IDENTIFIES IDC AS ENGINE FOR BLACK ECONOMIC EMPOWERMENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Black economic empowerment has been identified by government as one of the main goals of the Industrial Development Corporation.  In a state document outlining a reshaped IDC mandate, government says other key objectives should be a focus on job creation and exports, rather than "growth for its own sake".  The document, which is seen as providing a strategic vision for the organisation as it begins to shed its image as an "Afrikaner economic empowerment vehicle", says additional policy-based lending should be considered for black economic empowerment, for medium-sized firms facing defined opportunities and constraints, cluster development and training.<BR><P>
GOVT TO ADD RDP GOALS TO ITS GEAR PROGRAMME <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The government plans to amend its Growth, Employment And Redistribution strategy (Gear) <I>[also known as the macro-economic strategy - Ed.]</I> by adding the RDP's social goals to it.  That will put job creation and the reduction of poverty back on the agenda, after the closure of the RDP office earlier this year.  A spokesman in the office of Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said yesterday these goals would be added to those of Gear as an addendum.  The spokesman said the government would decide on the content of the addendum "as a matter of urgency".  Sources said yesterday the government appeared to be trying to appease the labour movement by marrying the RDP goals with those of Gear.  The labour movement has criticised the Gear strategy since it was tabled in parliament in June, to acclaim from the local and international business sectors and the International Monetary Fund.<BR><P>
IMF "MUST RECOGNISE SA TRADE UNIONS" <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The relationship between the SA government and the International Monetary Fund will spell doom for the country if organised labour is not involved in all discussions between the two parties. This warning was sounded by assistant general secretary of the Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu), Zwelinzima Vavi yesterday. <I>[And yet]</I> Cosatu and the SA National Civics Organisation (Sanco) rejected two invitations to meet IMF MD Michel Camdessus when he visited the country last week.<BR><P>
EMPOWERMENT FUND TO PLAY PRIVATISATION ROLE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Public Enterprises Ministry has approved the creation of a national empowerment fund to allow disadvantaged communities to play a role in the privatisation of SA's parastatals.  Initial proposals are to establish the fund as a loan vehicle which will avoid the "onerous conditions and high interest rates" that disadvantaged communities are facing when dealing with financial institutions.<BR><P>
INERTIA PERVADES OUR BUSINESS CULTURE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
If corporate inertia is the persistence of existing business practices regardless of their relevance in the new world, then you stumble over it all the time in SA companies today.  Past and present inertia is the prime reason for our lack of "world-class practice" and the pervasive pessimism about our ability to compete.  Not that there aren't good reasons for such inertia.  But good reasons for bad performance never improved anyone's bottom line.  It's like not taking control over your own fate, and blaming others for your "bad luck" or saying, "What else could we do?"  The hostile world of global competitiveness gives executives two options: drastically revitalise your company and reposition yourself in your industry so as to learn your way to efficiency faster;  or shore up your comfort zones and secure your low-to-no profit position right at the tailend of global competitiveness.<BR><P>
SA TIGHTENS VISA RESTRICTIONS FOR ZIMBABWEANS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
HARARE - The SA High Commission has been forced to tighten the issue of visas after more than 90 000 Zimbabweans violated the terms of six-month permits to cross the border in 18 months.  Many market "shoppers" who earn a living buying goods in SA for resale on the informal market now find their livelihoods in jeopardy.  The 90 000 visa violators are in addition to unknown tens of thousands who crossed the border illegally, joining an estimated 500 000 Zimbabweans putting additional strain on SA's already inadequate urban housing, health and policing infrastructure.<BR><P>
COSATU HAS TOO FEW WOMEN LEADERS <I>(Sake-Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
CAPE TOWN - Although more and more women are entering the SA labour market and joining unions, they still do not occupy positions of leadership in their unions, especially in Cosatu. An article on glass ceilings in the latest edition of the <I>SA Labour Bulletin</I> says women do not easily become workplace representatives because of a lack of faith in them. However, the major reason is rather that "women are not available for elections". <BR><P>
PRESS WARNED TO PURSUE TRUTH <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
Top Zimbabwean editor, Trevor Ncube last night warned the South African Press not to repeat the mistakes of media in other African countries, including Zimbabwe. Speaking at the <I>Sowetan/New Nation</I> media banquet in Johannesburg, Ncube, who is editor of the<I> Zimbabwe Independent</I> said it was critical the Press in SA did not shy away from asking the authorities all the awkward questions in pursuit of the truth.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
SA MEDIA MUST WORK WITH GOVT. <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
SAs media industry should form a partnership with the government in building a non-racial democracy that should be people-centred and guard against the erosion of basic human rights. Speaking during the Media Freedom Day, Broadcasting and Telecommunications Minister Jay Naidoo called on the media not to bury good stories under negative aspects of the "slow and painful" transformation.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
ROW OVER MANDELAS CRITICISM OF SOME SENIOR BLACK JOURNALISTS <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The ANC yesterday sprang to the defence of President Mandela - under fire from the new South African National Editors Forum (Sanef) for remarks he made about some senior black journalists.  Sanef "wondered" in one of its first resolutions at the weekend why Mandela, in his criticism, made to a University of the North audience a fortnight ago, "indirectly cast suspicion on all senior black journalists".  Mandela told the <I>Cape Times</I> at the weekend that some senior black journalists seemed not to want to be part of the transformation.  "They seem to regret that we destroyed white supremacy, and are very hostile to us - you cant expect us to keep quiet and not respond," he said.<BR><P>
</DOC>
