<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 21 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>


ANGLOVAAL'S MINING EARNINGS 'TO RISE' <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Anglovaal's mining earnings were expected to increase in real terms in the current financial year as it benefited from higher contributions from investment company Saturn, the group said in its latest annual report.<BR><P>
EVANDER RESTRUCTURING HANGS IN THE BALANCE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Shareholder approval for Gencor's restructuring of its Evander gold mines remains in the balance, despite strenuous efforts to persuade a major British investor to support the transaction when the issue is put to the vote in early November.<BR><P>
STRIKE THREAT AT LEBOWA MINES OVER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American Platinum said the threat of a strike at Lebowa Platinum Mines had been averted.  "A settlement was reached and production has not been affected", the company said, without giving details of the agreement.  It said earlier that wage talks had deadlocked and the union had proceeded with a strike ballot.<BR><P>
MINE FUNDS LIFT RETURNS TO 28,7% <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA's two largest privately administered pension funds, the Mine Employees' Pension Fund and the Mine Officials' Pension Fund, pushed up their combined investment returns for the year to June to 28,7% from 9,2%.<BR><P>
BID TO EXTEND DEADLINES IN JOHNNIC DEAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Minority interests within the National Empowerment Consortium, which is buying a 35% controlling stake in Johnnic worth about R4bn from Anglo American, are calling for an extension of deadlines to allow smaller groups to raise affordable finance to fund their shares in the deal.<BR><P>
NUM, ANGLO MOVE ON IMPROVING PRODUCTIVITY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The regional leadership of theNational Union of Mineworkers (NUM) and Anglo American's Vaal Reefs operations have agreed on a set of guidelines to be used in giving effect to an undertaking signed at national level to increase productivity.  <BR><P>
IMF BOSS SAYS SA PLAN FOR GROWTH IS SPOT ON <I>(Business Times, with the Sunday Times)</I><BR>
International Monetary Fund head Michel Camdessus on Friday pledged support for South Africa's macro-economic plan, saying it was the right strategy for the country.  "We in the IMF consider that the strategies for growth, employment and redistribution which the government announced on June 14 are exactly right", Camdessus said after a meeting with President Nelson Mandela.<BR><P>
EU URGES GOVT, LABOUR SYNERGY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA labour movement and government had to address development challenges together, European Union (EU) ambassador Erwan Fouéré said on Friday.   Speaking at the launch of the Labour Development Trust, funded by the European Union, Fouéré said SA was facing key internal and external challenges that required the development and building of skills.<BR><P>
EMIGRATION FIGURES RING WARNING BELL <I>(Business Times)</I><BR>
The exact cost of crime is imponderable, but its effects are increasingly evident.  The most damaging consequence of crime is the exodus of skilled South Africans, skills which the economy has not been able to replace.  According to the Central Statistical Services, 5 627 people emigrated from South Africa in the first six months of this year, a 24% increase on the first half of 1995.  The majority of emigrants cited crime as their main reason for leaving.<BR><P>
ESTIMATES OF ENTERPRISES IN SA WRONG, SAYS OFFICIAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government estimates that there were at least 800 000 formal enterprises in SA were exaggerated by at least 20%, a senior government research official said at the weekend. <BR><P>
WORLD'S LARGEST MINING GROUP PLANS NEAR-DOUBLING OF PRODUCTION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
RTZ-CRZ, the world's biggest mining group, plans a near-doubling of production from its US coal mines by 2005.<BR><P>
DUBAI GOLD MARKET TO SHINE WITH INDIAN REFORMS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
DUBAI - Dubai's gold market should get a shot in the arm as a result of Indian  monetary reform and the upcoming festival season, Dubai gold traders said on Sunday.  "The new monetary policy announced by the Reserve Bank of India will improve the liquidity, and the upcoming festival and wedding season augurs well for the bullion market", Sultan Satani, managing director of Satco Global Trading said.<BR><P>
