<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 18 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>

<p>PHYSICAL GOLD MARKET IN EQUILIBRIUM <i>(Reuters)</i><br>
The physical gold market has reached a state of equilibrium around current price levels, Anglo American marketing director 
Kelvin Williams said on Thursday.<br>
</p>
<p>TEPID GOLD MINING CONTINUES AT ANGLO <i>(Business Day, Jhb.)</i><br>
The uninspiring September gold quarterlies season continued yesterday, with Anglo American Corporation's gold mines 
reporting a 3% fall in aggregate earnings to R312,3m, in spite of a 4% rise in the average gold price received, to R54 919kg.<br>
</p>
<p>ANGLO'S STANCE ON LONRHO DENIED <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Lonrho said it saw no foundation in a newspaper report saying that Anglo American declined to exercise an option to give it a 
25,7% stake in the British group. &quot;There is no foundation whatsoever in that report&quot;, a Lonrho spokesman said.<br>
</p>
<p>GOLD FIELDS CLAIMS IGNORANCE OF STRIKE VOTE <i>(Business Report, Jhb.)</i><br>
Gold Fields management yesterday claimed complete ignorance of Wednesday's overwhelming union vote for strikes at their 
Northam Platinum mine. The National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) informed management in writing late on Wednesday that 
about 4 000 union members at the mine voted by 96,8% in favour of industrial action, Mahlakeng Mahlakeng, the NUM's 
Rustenburg co-ordinator said yesterday.<br>
</p>
<p>IMPARTIALITY QUERIED <i>(New Nation, weekly on Fridays)</i><br>
Government&#146;s judicial inquiry into violence at three Gold Fields mines is coming up against a serious credibility challenge with 
questions being posed about aspects of the commission&#146;s report. When released earlier this week, NUM cautiously welcomed 
some of the commission chairperson Judge John Myburgh&#146;s recommendations. However, the Congress of SA Trade Unions 
(Cosatu), in a preliminary response expressed extreme concern at the impression that &quot;holding peaceful demonstrations and 
marches of necessity leads to violence&quot;. <i>[Judge Myburgh's, who is also President of the Labour Court, report was 
critical of both labour and management in the underlying causes for the violence which claimed 43 lives - Ed.]</i><br>
<b><i>... and ...</i></b><br>
COSATU CALLS OFF MEETING WITH IMF HEAD OVER TIME ALLOCATION <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Cosatu called off a meeting yesterday with International Monetary Fund MD Michel Camdessus, saying that 30 minutes was 
insufficient time to discuss a range of issues. Cosatu media officer Nowetu Mpati said Cosatu reiterated its dislike of both the 
IMF and World Bank because of their record in developing countries and the conditions imposed on impoverished countries 
in terms of their policies which, [Cosatu] said, undermined such countries&#146; sovereignty. Meanwhile, a group of protesters 
representing the National Progressive Primary Healthcare Network stormed the VIP lounge at the airport yesterday. They 
were protesting against Camdessus&#146; visit to SA because of the IMF's influence on government policy.<br>
</p>
<p>MBOWENI SEES A REVOLUTION IN LABOUR RELATIONS <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
A major revolution is taking place in SA labour relations which is moving away from an adversarial system towards one of 
greater co-operation, says Labour Minister Tito Mboweni. Addressing a National Business Initiative seminar yesterday on 
proposals for an employment and occupational equity statute, Mboweni said the intense confrontational approach traditionally 
adopted by the parties was subsiding.<br>
</p>
<p>BANK REPORT FINDS HOPE OF SUCCESS FOR SA ECONOMY <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
LONDON - SA may yet deliver an economic surprise that matches its recent political feats, UBS Global Research says in its 
latest quarterly report on the SA economy. Compiled for the Union Bank of Switzerland, the report painted a much more 
positive picture of the country's prospects than previous statements, which some analysts have identified as the trigger for the 
rand's collapse earlier in the year.<br>
</p>
<p>EU BOOSTS LABOUR DEVELOPMENT <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
The building of skills and resources within the labour movement will be given a boost when the Labour Development Trust, 
funded by the European Union, is launched in Johannesburg today. The EU said yesterday it would provide a R23,6m grant 
towards the establishment of the trust, whose board would consist of union representatives, two observers from the EU and 
the Labour Department, the National Council of Trade Unions, Cosatu and the Federation of SA Labour Unions( Fedsal). 
The trust formed part of the EU's programme for reconstruction and development which had agreed to grant SA between 
R500m and R600m a year until 1999.<br>
</p>
<p>GOVT REGULATION &#145;SCARES INVESTORS&#146; <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Excessive government regulation in the business sector could scare off foreign investors, losing offshore investment which was 
the single biggest driver of economic miracles, life insurer, Old Mutual's, senior economist Terence Moll said yesterday. He 
told an Institute for Futures Research seminar that foreign investors were both selective and discriminating. About 90% of the 
developing world's $90bn in direct foreign investment last year was directed to only 15 countries; SA received a mere 0,4% of 
last year's foreign investment pie. He said government should be taking its own growth, employment and redistribution polices 
more seriously, with a priority being to modify the economic environment to boost business.<br>
</p>
<p>LEADERS DISCUSS CORRIDOR PLANS <i>(Business Report)</i><br>
A high-level delegation of Cabinet ministers from SA, Mozambique and Swaziland conducted an aerial survey yesterday of 
Swaziland's northern and eastern regions through which the proposed Maputo corridor routes from SA to Mozambique's 
southern Maputo province will be constructed.<br>
</p>
<p>ERWIN SLAMS LOAN CRITICS <i>(Business Mail, with the Mail &amp; Guardian on Fridays)</i><br>
Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin this week dismissed suggestions that the proposed $70m World Bank loan signalled a 
deviation from stated government policy. &quot;This is not a new borrowing initiative. We have set borrowing limits for this financial 
year and coming years, sourced from the domestic capital market, the international market and international financial 
institutions (IFI). This is merely the first slice of the IFI component.&quot; The World Bank doesn't just hand out money; funds have 
to be targeted towards certain projects. So this particular programme seemed the perfect starting point, being a scheme 
designed to promote export competitiveness, worked out in close co-operation between the departments of Finance and 
Trade and Industry.<br>
</p>
<p>WHERE THERE IS SMOKE, THERE ARE BOUND TO BE MIRRORS <i>(Business Report)</i><br>
In a world where the political left seems in general retreat and the globalisation of capital holds sway, SA is in a unique 
position. It is the only country which contains in government a trade union federation with a recent and militant history and a 
communist party, both of which remain committed to &quot;socialism&quot;. This gives rise to a situation where sometimes fierce debate is 
inevitable. It also means that, while the government will continue to govern, it will also continue to face criticism, pressure and 
debate from within its own ranks. Such pressure is about to intensify over coming weeks. Despite declarations about its 
general non-negotiability, the government's macro-economic GEAR (Growth, Economy, And Redistribution) strategy remains 
the focus of sharp argument. Much of the debate has been raging within the SACP. It is about to spill into the public arena 
which should have a considerable ripple effect throughout the trade union movement from which the SA Communist Party 
draws the bulk of its support.<br>
</p>
</DOC>
