<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 17 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>


CHAMBER PREDICTS DROP IN GOLD OUTPUT <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
ISTANBUL - Gold miners of SA, the world's main gold producing country, said yesterday they were expecting output for this year to fall to about 500 tonnes from 522 tonnes last year in line with a decline in productivity and pressure from prices and costs.<BR><P>
DEVELOPING WORLD SET TO TAKE LEAD IN MINING <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
ISTANBUL - Gold production in Latin America, Asia and the former Soviet Union is growing more rapidly than in SA, the US, Australia and Canada, Gold Fields Mineral Services CE Stewart Murray said yesterday.<BR><P>
DEFT MANAGEMENT MAKES DUIKER A STAR <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Duiker Mining, which recently celebrated its 50th anniversary, has been one of the Johannesburg Stock Exchange's star performers over the past five years and, judging by the upbeat mood of its executives, it seems there is more to come.<BR><P>
JCI RESTRUCTURES TO FOCUS ON CORE BUSINESS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
JCI Ltd has announced a plan to hive off nine of its internal non-core business units, affecting a third of the company's strategic focus.  About 250 people would be affected by the move, including members of the company's head office security and organisational development. Chairman Bill Nairn said this would focus the group on its core business and further growth strategy ambitions. Options open were to out-source non-core services or establish the service as a free-standing business unit.<BR><P>
BLYVOOR BUYS INTO ANGLO MINE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Randgold's Blyvooruitzicht has bought part of Anglo American's Western  Deep Levels mine for R25,5m in an area where the companies already co-operate.  The area lies in the Carbon Leader Reef where the two mine operations almost touch.  Anglo finds it expensive to mine the tribute because of a geological fault on its side, but has allowed Blyvoor to work the area since 1992, splitting costs and revenues.<BR><P>
WAGE STRIKE LOOMS AT NORTHAM <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) voted overwhelmingly to strike at the Gold Fields-owned Northam platinum mine yesterday.  About 4 000 union members at the mine, 3 400 paid-up and 600 signed-up members, carried the vote by 96,8% in favour of industrial action over Gold Fields' pay offer.<BR>  
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
WALKOUT COULD PRECIPITATE MINE MERGER <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
A strike by unionised workers at SA's troubled Northam Platinum Mine could hasten a merger with neighbouring Rustenburg Platinum Mines, analysts said yesterday.  NUM said 96,8% of its 3 300 members at Northam had voted in favour of strike action over wages .<I>[These two reports, one under the other, are by different reporters - hence the numbers discrepancy. Although, in fairness, NUM seems to have been the source in both cases... - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
<A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/releases/myburgh2.htm">CHAMBER BACKS MINE INQUIRY</A> <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The Chamber of Mines, the umbrella organisation for SA's mining houses, has pledged its 'unreserved' support for the extension of the terms of reference of the Myburgh commission of inquiry into mine violence.  Judge John Myburgh was appointed by President Nelson Mandela to investigate the violence at three Gold Fields-owned mines after the death of 42 miners and injuries to 203 others.<I> [The Citizen, Business Day and Sowetan carried this story, from a Chamber media release, yesterday. - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
SA (PTY) LTD SUFFERS AS ASSETS DRIBBLE AWAY <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
SA's biggest asset is widely regarded as its abundant mineral wealth.  All assets, however, require to be turned to account. Further reflection, therefore, points to the nation's skills base as an even more important asset.  SA's untapped mineral resources exceed those that have thus far been tapped.  They are there and they are not going away.  In alarming contrast, the nation's other major asset is dribbling away fast - and precious little is being done about it.<BR><P>
JOB NEEDS WILL BE THE SOLE TEST, SAYS CONTRACTOR <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Rehiring 1 700 sacked workers on the Lesotho Highlands Water Project would be based solely on operational requirements and not on personalities, Peter Streng, the contractors' industrial relations manager said yesterday.<BR><P>
EU CALLS FOR REALISTIC WATER PRICE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The European Union should only fund water projects in SA if the government's long-term aim is to sell water at a price that would cover its true costs, Manfred Vohrer, a consultant to the EU, said yesterday.  Vohrer said the scarcity of water, in both clean water supply and sanitation, should be reflected by its price to consumers.<BR><P>
CHASM BETWEEN POOR AND RICH NATIONS WIDENS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Poverty has soared despite unprecedented growth in the world economy in the past 50 years, with the gap between rich and poor nations becoming even starker, the UN Development Programme said yesterday.  The programme released the figures to mark World Anti-poverty Day today, and used the symbolic day to urge rich nations to boost their development aid contributions to poorer countries.<BR><P>
LETS RID SA GOLD MINES OF FINITE HORIZONS <I>(Mining Weekly, 11/10/96)</I><BR>
South African mining companies are duty-bound to improve the worth of their assets to international investors. Failing to do so could seriously under-capitalise SAs mining effort at a time when it needs optimum investment. There are regular complaints about the lack of labour productivity in SA. But what about poor investment productivity implicit in outdated company structuring?<BR><P>
