<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 16 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>


FALLING SA GOLD OUTPUT TO CAUSE WORLD SHORTAGE <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
ISTANBUL - A sharp squeeze on global gold supply can be expected, mainly because of an expected decline in the output of SA, the world's largest producer of the precious metal, Alan Mackie, a gold specialist at the London-based Economic Intelligence Unit said yesterday.<BR><P>
OUTLOOK POSITIVE FOR GOLD DEMAND <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - The many influences which will decide gold demand as the market moves into its five months of peak consumption are "fairly benign and possibly even positive", says the chief executive of Gold Fields Minerals Service.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD & EXPLORATION  TAKES OVER BHP <I>(Business Day,Jhb.)</I><BR>
Randgold & Exploration's Randgold Resources formally took over BHP Minerals Mali, renamed Randgold Resources Mali, after settling the $30m cash component of the deal, the group said yesterday.<BR><P>
AVMIN HURT BY LOW PRODUCTIVITY, RISING COSTS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Anglovaal Minerals gold mining companies reported a 34% drop in taxed profits to R49,1m for the September quarter after experiencing rising costs and low productivity.<BR><P>
ET CONS TAKES A SLIDE INTO THE RED AFTER TWO DECADES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Eastern Transvaal Consolidated (ET Cons) provided the low point in Anglovaal Minerals' September quarter as the annual negotiated wage increase and lower productivity took their toll, the group said yesterday.<BR><P>
GENGOLD OUTLINES PLANS FOR BETTER MINE SAFETY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gengold was hoping to improve productivity and safety on its mines through its policy of promoting black workers to leadership positions, Gengold MD Tom Dale said yesterday.  The fatality rate in deep-level SA gold mines was unacceptable, Dale said.<BR><P>
ANGLO UNBUNDLING A POSSIBILITY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
On the face of it, there was nothing new to the restructuring of Anglo American's assets referred to by Anglo's Michael Spicer in an interview with the <I>Financial Times</I> last week.  In his June chairman's statement, Julian Ogilvie Thompson stressed that Anglo was not about to unbundle.  "We have said before that within Anglo's broad South African portfolio there are interests that may not be core holdings if circumstances were to change".  However, he said, there are two material considerations:  exchange controls would have to be abolished, "new mining opportunities, for instance, are more likely to be found elsewhere in Africa and internationally", and alternative investment opportunities, at least matching returns from existing assets, would need to be identified.<BR><P>
NORTHAM COULD FACE MORE TROUBLE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The result of a National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) strike ballot expected today will determine whether Northam Platinum mine begins the fourth quarter in the same grim vein in which it finished the past quarter.<BR><P>
GOLD FIELDS' QUARTERLIES  <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The atmosphere at Gold Fields' quarterly results conference earlier this week was crypt-like:  a dark room and gloomy faces giving out some of the worst results for a gold mining house in SA for some time.  Mine violence and underground fires had slashed earnings, and the impression was that the new SA had passed them by.  Zulus were  basically interested in earning money and working rather than joining unions, said one senior board member.<BR><P>
JOHNNIC FUNDRAISING UNDERMINES DEAL'S OBJECTIVES <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Members of the National Empowerment Consortium (NEC) are planning to approach Anglo American to persuade it to interfere in a divisive fund-raising exercise that threatens to undermine many of the objectives of the company's sale of its stake in Johnnic to the NEC.<BR><P>
NEDLAC LAUNCHES LABOUR WORKSHOP PROGRAMME <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The National Economic Development and Labour Council (Nedlac) announced in Johannesburg yesterday that it had launched a R2m programme of labour-management workshops to meet the challenge of SA's workplace.  The aim was to enhance co-operation between workers and management to boost the country's competitiveness, and employment creation by improving industrial performance and productivity, the council said.<BR><P>
EU TRADE OFFER DELAYED TO PROTECT REGION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government had taken months to respond to the European Union's offer because it wanted to ensure that the EU was not granted generous market access at the expense of SA's neighbours, Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin said yesterday.<BR><P>
SYFRETS ECONOMIST PREDICTS INTEREST RATE CUTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Slowing consumer demand, a shift in investment spending and the improvement in export earnings were likely to ease pressure on the balance of payments, paving the way for at least three interest rate reductions next year, Syfrets chief economist Sandra Gordon said yesterday.<BR><P>
UNION LETTER ON RESTRUCTURING 'IS REAL' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Federation of SA Labour Unions (Fedsal) yesterday denied claims by the SA Railway and Harbour Workers' Union that a letter signed jointly by Cosatu (the Congress of SA Trade Unions) and Fedsal representatives and sent to transportation parastatal, Transnet, SA Airways and rail company, Spoornet management was fictitious.  The letter in question accused Spoornet and SAA of breaching and circumventing the process outlined in the national framework agreement on state asset restructuring.<BR><P>
HOW FOREIGN AID CAN DO MORE HARM THAN GOOD <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Nobody concerned with SA's future economic welfare can question the desirability of genuine foreign investment.  We need access to foreign savings to fund enterprises that will be profitable to borrower and lender alike.  Such investment, however, should be distinguished from, on the one hand, foreign aid for Reconstruction and Development Programme (RDP) purposes and, on the other, soft loans for foreign countries whose own interests may conflict with ours.<BR><P>
PRESS FREEDOM A COMPLEX ISSUE, SAYS CHASKALSON <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Rights were never absolute and Press freedom was no exception, Constitutional Court president Justice Arthur Chaskalson said yesterday.  "Press freedom does not entitle journalists to trample upon the dignity and privacy of others - a constraint that some journalists and newspapers are reluctant to acknowledge", he told a Commonwealth Press Union conference in Cape Town.<BR><P>
TREVOR MANUEL <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Trevor Manuel has being growing in confidence ever since he became Minister of Finance earlier this year, but unfortunately he has elected to become more hard-nosed with the media as his confidence grows. On Monday he again reacted aggressively in front of the nine ministers of finance of the provinces to a reporter's question, saying that what was discussed in a meeting of the budget council in parliament "has nothing to do with" the journalist, and warned that "there will be big trouble if anything said in the meeting is to leak out".  At the same time, the Press is berated by Deputy President Thabo Mbeki for not reporting on government activities and pronouncements.<BR><P>
ASSETS CANNOT BE NATIONALISED <I>(Sake-Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
CAPE TOWN - The new Minister of Mineral and Energy Affairs, Penuel Maduna, told the standing committee on mineral and energy affairs that legislators who try to make mineral rights available to blacks must be realistic. Nationalisation of mineral rights was an option which could not be considered and mine companies could not be expected to make mineral rights available to the state free of charge.<BR><P>
SOUTH AFRICA: HOW WRONG IS IT GOING? <I>(The Economist - 12/10/96)</I><BR>
Following on <I>TIMEs </I>recent cover report on the "post-miracle phase" in South Africas development, <I>The Economist</I> has published a three-page cover piece which, while not as broad-ranging as <I>TIME, </I>offers greater perspicacity and is more critical. It lists lawlessness, unemployment and political accountability as the three "new anxieties" in SA. It says "lawlessness feeds the feeling that the government is not in control" and that "part of the solution must be political will". Turning to unemployment, the weekly says: "SAs unresponsive labour market is not the result only of strong unions and labour protection. True, there are government-imposed non-wage costs, and it is costly to hire and difficult to fire. So companies look for capital-intensive, not labour-intensive, ways to grow. But the markets stickiness is also a product of apartheids inferior education for blacks; unskilled black labour is cheap, but unproductive; skilled is scare, and costly." In the short-run, joblessness will probably worsen since foreign investments have been mostly in existing companies, and "not in greenfield investments creating immediate jobs". Finally, <I>The Economist</I> lists the new constitution, the fact that the Western Cape and KwaZulu/Natal are not governed by the ANC, the rise of informal organisations and a vigilant Press as the best safeguards against SA going the way of Zimbabwe - "a supposed multiparty democracy ruled as a de facto one-party state, with a government that rides in limousines, periodically clamps down on the Press, and blames white ownership of the economy for the countrys ills". The report concludes: "Asia-like economic success or stagnant African disappointment? Mundane reality will surely lie in between". <I>[summarised by Editor]</I><BR><P>
