<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 15 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>


FIRES, VIOLENCE TAKE TOLL AT GOLD FIELDS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Violence and underground fires took their toll at gold mines managed by Gold Fields of SA in the September quarter, reducing pre-capex profit 23% to R275m. Operating profit was one-third lower as all but one mine failed to sustain or increase gold production. This contrasts with Gencors gold division, Gengold, which kicked off the quarterly reporting period with earnings growth of 1,8% to R57,4m.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
GENGOLD MINES' EARNINGS OFFSET 9% WAGE INCREASE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gengold took a 9% mid-year wage increase on the chin in the September quarter by lifting bottom-line earnings for the five Gengold mines 1,8% to R57,4m after increased output and a higher average gold price.<BR><P>
NUM MEMBERS BALLOT FOR STRIKE AT NORTHAM <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers began balloting for a strike at Gold Fields' Northam Platinum mine yesterday after a dispute over wages that was declared before the outbreak of violence at the mine in August.<BR><P>
UNION WASHES ITS HANDS OF LETTER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA Railway and Harbour Workers' Union yesterday distanced itself from a document allegedly written jointly by the Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu) and the Federation of SA Labour (Fedsal) representatives, accusing SA Airways and rail company Spoornet of breaching the national framework agreement (NFA) on state asset restructuring. <BR><P>
GOVT SWITCH ON INFRASTRUCTURE POLICY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government was steering away from its R60bn-R90bn "grand 10-year plan" for the provision of municipal infrastructure, towards a year-on-year spending programme, Constitutional Development Department director-general Andrew Boraine said yesterday.<BR><P>
SA 'MUST LURE LONG-TERM INVESTMENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The volatility of capital movement over the past two years was a stark indication of the need for SA to attract long-term direct investments rather than portfolio and short-term capital, Reserve Bank economic adviser Ernie van der Merwe said yesterday.<BR><P>
DAIMLER-BENZ HEAD MAKES CASE FOR BELIEF IN SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Daimler-Benz AG chairman Jurgen Schrempp has reaffirmed his company's commitment to SA's economic future, saying opportunities associated with investing in SA far outweigh the risk.<BR><P>
NOT A RECIPE FOR PEACE AND GOODWILL <I>(Business Report, Jhb)</I><BR>
The Reserve Bank recently expressed its concern about the low level of net personal saving.  It has been low before.  In 1990 it amounted to about 1% of personal disposable income.  Then it made a welcome revival to about 5% in 1993, but has fallen again to 0.9% in the second quarter of this year.  This is not a tenable situation.<BR><P>
SA UNEMPLOYMENT RATE IS NOT AS BAD AS IT SEEMS, ILO REPORT SHOWS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The SA unemployment rate is not as high as figures usually show, the International Labour Organisation said in a government-requested report published in Geneva yesterday.  The 500-page study said unemployment was substantial, but the generally suggested unemployment rate of 33% was probably exaggerated and a rate of 20% was closer to reality.  It stressed the risk of loss of international confidence that might result from an erroneous view of the labour market.<BR><P>
LABOUR STANDARDS 'VITAL TO SUSTAIN ECONOMIC GROWTH <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A set of minimum and socially acceptable labour standards and re-distributive policies did not compromise economic growth as suggested by critics, but were necessary for sustainable and long-term success, Labour Minister Tito Mboweni said yesterday.<BR><P>
LABOUR READY TO REOPEN TALKS ON SOCIAL PACT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Fresh attempts would be made to negotiate an overarching social accord on growth, despite major differences between key social partners at the National Economic Development and Labour Council (Nedlac), labour sources said yesterday.  Efforts to hammer out an accord hit a snag earlier in the year following the release of two contrasting documents, first by business and then by labour.<BR><P>
PLAN AIMS TO CUT POPULATION GROWTH <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government yesterday published a draft programme to cut population growth, but without the controversial targets set by the previous government.  The document lists 24 strategies for population development, ranging from improved data collection and analysis to interdepartmental co-ordination of legislation.  It identifies poverty as 'one of the most formidable enemies of choice' and highlights the need to take medical services to rural women.<BR><P>
