<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 14 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



WEAK RAND WILL AID SA'S STRUGGLING GOLD MINES <I>(Business Day,Jhb.)</I><BR>
Rising costs and a weak dollar gold price will be key factors in the performance of SA's gold mines, due to report on the September quarter from today, analysts said at the weekend.  However, the continued slide in the value of the rand against the dollar, currently about R4,55, would come to the aid of struggling mines as in the previous quarter, they said.<BR><P>
ANGLOVAAL FOLLOWS MINING INDUSTRY TREND <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The decision by Anglovaal to cancel its management contracts with its group mines has invited comparison with similar decisions by Randgold and Gengold, amid rumblings from overseas investors about the way some of these contracts have been valued.<BR><P>
UNIONS TAP FUNDS FOR STAKE IN JOHNNIC <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The labour component of the National Empowerment Consortium will form a new investment vehicle to finance the unions' 17,5% stake in Johnnic, raising capital from union-linked institutions by offering Johnnic shares at a discount.  The unions would essentially tap their members' pension and provident funds to fund their shareholding in Johnnic.<BR><P>
COSATU TEAMS UP TO MAKE BID FOR PROTEA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Congress of SA Trade Unions', the country's largest union federation, investment trust Kopano Ke Matla, has put together a consortium with other black groups to submit a bid for a controlling stake in Protea Assurance, owned by UK group Royal Sun Alliance.<BR><P>
UNION INVESTMENT UNDER FIRE FROM LABOUR BULLETIN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Trade union investment companies surrounded by confusion and secrecy would force unions to decide whether they were in the business of business or of trade unionism, an article published in the latest <I>SA Labour Bulletin</I> suggests.  The article, "union investment new opportunities, new threats", written by an unnamed <I>Labour Bulletin</I> special correspondent, questions whether labour's foray into the companies was an appropriate way for unions to invest their money.<BR><P>
PARTIES POSITIVE ON CONSTITUTION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The adoption of the revised constitution by the Constitutional Assembly on Friday was without the pomp and ceremony of the first time, but parties were more confident about the Constitutional Court certifying it this time.  Assembly Chairman Cyril Ramaphosa cautioned though against premature celebration as happened in May when the first draft was adopted.<BR><P>
SLOW SPENDING OF JAPANESE AID FUNDS COULD HARM TALKS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government has been slow in spending the $1,3bn two-year Japanese programme awarded in 1994 - a delay that could undermine development officials when they lobby for an extension of the package.  In London, Japanese Overseas Economic Co-operation Fund chief representative Nobuo Hazeyama said at the weekend the reasons for the slow pace at which the official aid component was being drawn included SA officials' cautiousness <I>[sic]</I>.  "They say they don't want to make mistakes', he said.<BR><P>
JUDGE FINDS MULTIPLE CAUSES FOR MINE VIOLENCE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Mine violence has to be viewed in the context of factors such as continuing political conflict between ANC and IFP supporters, fear of job displacement  and the migrant labour and single-sex hostel system, a commission of inquiry into mine violence has concluded.  Chairman of the inquiry into violence at Gold Fields' East Driefontein, Leeudoorn and Northam mines, Judge John Myburgh said in his report released at the weekend that these and other factors influenced developments on the three mines.<BR>
<B><I>... but ...</I></B><BR>
NUM WARY OF STRONGER WITNESS PROTECTION PLAN <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) rejected immediate implementation of a witness protection programme at the weekend because it was inappropriate to conditions in the mine hostel environment.  The programme seeks to protect witnesses to the violence which left 42 Gold Fields miners dead and 203 injured earlier this year:  Judge John Myburgh recommended that the programme be strengthened in his commission of inquiry into violence.<BR><P>
TELKOM PRIVATISATION STAKE MAY RISE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The sale of 10% stake in Telkom, SA's telecommunications parastatal, to a black economic empowerment group could boost the total stake government would sell to 40%, a Posts and Telecommunications Ministry spokesman said at the weekend.  Government had previously indicated that between 20% and 30% of Telkom would be sold to a strategic equity partner.  The latest development would not only boost the stake, but could also increase the amount of funding government would receive as a result of the sale.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
PHONE CONNECTIONS <I>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
Telkom's decision to make 10% of its equity available to black economic empowerment groups and worker organisations displays a pragmatic understanding of political and social needs.  There has never been any question that SA state assets could be sent along the privatisation route based on price alone.  Political realities have to be taken into account.  And this is where the word empowerment is significant.  Empowerment does  not and should not equate to enrichment.  There would be little point in selling state assets preferentially to black interests if those assets are merely sold on promptly at a quick profit.<BR>
<B><I>... and, also ...</I></B><BR>
PRIVATISATION WILL BE A KEY THEME OF TONY BLAIR'S VISIT <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Tony Blair, the leader of Britain's Labour Party, is visiting SA this week.  Economics will occupy an important role in his agenda, especially given its importance by the recent visit to SA of the Lord Mayor of London, who officially opened the British consulate-general's new offices in Dunkeld, Johannesburg.  While opinions differ as to which country is SA's largest trading partner, because of the way the statistics are derived, Britain claims this distinction with last year's exports to this country of £1,8b and imports of £1,1b.<BR><P>
INDUSTRY ACCEPTS PROTECTION IS NOW PAST <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA has until recently been notorious for its complex tariff structure.  The complexity stemmed in part from the high degree of protection given to the country's industries, a direct legacy of the apartheid past.  However, with the country's offer to GATT - the ambitious global project to liberalise trade - SA committed itself not only to breaking down its high tariff walls, but also to simplifying the 8 000-item tariff structure.<BR><P>
SA'S DIPLOMATIC RELATIONS UNDER FIRE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA's foreign policy has again come under fire following the disclosure that diplomatic relations have been established with more countries that have poor human rights records.  In reply to a parliamentary question from opposition National Party MP Boy Geldenhuys, Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo gave a list of countries with whom full diplomatic relations have been established since January last year.  The most controversial on the list are Myanmar (formerly Burma) and Burundi.<BR><P>
R10M LOST IN LESOTHO STRIKE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The cost of the month-long standstill at the Lesotho Highlands Water Project since an illegal strike brought operations to a halt early last month is estimated at R10-million, David Darcy, the contractors' project director, said at the weekend.<BR><P>
ESKOM TO SPEND R5BN OVER FIVE YEARS TO EXPAND ELECTRICITY NETWORK <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The electricity supply giant, Eskom, is planning to spend R5bn over the next five years on upgrading and expanding the electricity transmission network in SA and Africa.<BR><P>
GOLD USE IN COINAGE UP 32% IN 1995 <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
NEW YORK - World-wide use of gold in coinage rose 32% in 1995 to more than 3.3-million ounces, up from 2.5-million ounces in 1994, according to a report published annually by the Gold Institute.<BR><P>
PROPOSED MINING LAW HEADING TO GUATEMALAN CONGRESS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
The Energy and Mines Ministry will present a bill to the Guatemalan Congress next week designed to attract foreign investment in mining, a government official said Friday.<BR><P>
