<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 10 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



ANGLOVAAL RESTRUCTURES <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Mining house Anglovaal yesterday announced details of the restructuring intended to transform the group's mining division from what it describes as a "passive investment" vehicle into a focused, "growth-orientated operating company" with international pretensions in Africa and beyond.<BR><P>
CRIME NOT A DETERRENT TO BRITISH INVESTMENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Visiting Lord Mayor of London Sir John Chalstrey was confident UK investment in SA would reach about £55bn from the present £10bn, he said yesterday.  Chalstrey said the British business community was confident about SA and did not see crime as a deterrent to investing in SA, nor did people think it was specific to Johannesburg or SA.<BR><P>
UNIONS HAVE RIGHT TO COMPANY INFORMATION  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The new Labour Relations Act would force employers to rethink past practices of either withholding information from unions or disclosing information only when it suited them - such as sharing poor financial results in order to effect retrenchments.<BR><P>
AFRICA FACES MARGINALISATION, MANDELA SAYS  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Africa was still threatened by marginalisation within the world economy, despite the 'fabulous wealth' of its resources, President Nelson Mandela said in Kololo, Uganda, during his first official visit to the country yesterday.<BR><P>
AFRICA'S PROTECTIONISM 'REDUCED ABILITY TO COMPETE GLOBALLY'  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Protectionist policies imposed by African governments have cost sub-Saharan Africa as much as $11bn a year, equivalent to the total aid to the region from developed countries in 1991, according to a World Bank research paper.<BR><P>
ISCOR DIVISION CONSIDERS ENTERING NICKEL MARKET  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Iscor's mining division was considering entering the nickel market and had identified a number of possible deposits for exploration in Australia.<BR><P>
KLOOF AND DRIEFONTEIN MINES <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
This week's yearly meetings of Kloof and Driefontein, the gold mining companies in Gold Fields of SA's stable, highlighted the level of shareholder apathy in SA.  Despite violence in East Driefontein and Kloof's Leeudorn division, which has resulted in a commission of inquiry, not one shareholder quizzed the directors and the management of the two companies on the issue.<BR><P>
WR CONS APPLIES TOUGH LESSONS AT NEW MINE  <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
While SA mining houses are scouring Africa for open-cast gold mining projects, West Rand Consolidated Mines is developing one in SA's own backyard.  Next week, it will list the new mine, near Mafikeng, as Kalahari Goldridge (Kalgold).<BR><P>
TUTU CHAMPIONS FREE PRESS <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
South Africas new democracy would be stillborn without a vigorous and free press, chairperson of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission, Archbishop Desmond Tutu said last night.  "We need a sycophantic kow-towing, lickspittle media as much as we need a hole in the head," he said at the University of the Western Cape when he opened the Commonwealth Press Unions editors forum.<BR><P>

