<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 9 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>

TOYOTA JAPAN SEALS R446M JOHNNIC DEAL</I><I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Toyota Motor Corporation (TMC) of Japan has acquired a 27,8% stake in Toyota SA in a R446m cash deal, the largest direct investment by a Japanese company since sanctions against SA were lifted.<BR><P>
FOOD PRICES RAISE PRODUCER INFLATION </I><I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Higher food prices helped lift producer inflation to 7,4% in August from 6,6% in July, with the expected increase in the imported component still failing to materialise, Central Statistical Services figures show.<BR><P>
MANY MINE LOCOMOTIVES 'TAMPERED WITH' </I><I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
More than half the underground locomotives at Vaal Reefs mine had been lethally tampered with in the same fashion as the train that caused the accident which claimed 104 lives in May last year, a parliamentary committee heard yesterday.<BR><P>
BUSINESS CONFIDENCE SLUMPS AS SA SLOWDOWN BITES </I><I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A general slowdown in key areas of the economy, especially dropping export volumes, had knocked business confidence in September, with the SA Chamber of Business (Sacob) business confidence index slumping to a year low, the chamber said yesterday.<BR><P>
FOREIGN COMPANIES INVESTED R18BN IN SA</I><I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Forty-six US companies had spent about R8bn in direct investment in SA over the past two years, according to a manufacturing survey by the Industrial Development Corporation (IDC).  The US investment was followed by three German companies which had invested R3,2bn.<BR><P>
'RAND'S FALL LIFTED FOREIGN INVESTMENT'<I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Foreign direct investment in South Africa has been boosted over the past eight months by the rand's depreciation against the dollar, the Washington-based Investor Responsibility Research Centre said yesterday.<BR><P>
CUSTOMS UNION MEMBERS MEET TO RESOLVE OUTSTANDING ISSUES </I><I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Negotiators from the Southern African Customs Union meet today under increasing pressure to resolve outstanding issues that are holding up talks to modernise the five-nation trade arrangement.<BR><P>
GOLD FIELDS MAY SEEK EQUITY PARTNER FOR GHANA MINE </I><I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gold Fields of SA was considering a foreign equity partner among other financing options for its $125m Tarkwa surface gold mining venture in Ghana, a senior Gold Fields official said yesterday.
<BR><P>
COMMODITIES FOR LOCAL CONSUMPTION MOVE IN LINE WITH EXPECTATIONS <I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The production price index for commodities for local consumption rose 7,4 percent in the year to August 31, 0,8 of a percentage point higher than the figure for the year to July 31 and much in line with expectations.<BR><P>
<B><I>  amongst many reports in the various daily papers, Business Report and the Cape Times print as follows: </I></B><BR><P>
SAA TO LOCK OUT 2 200 UNION MEMBERS <I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
South African Airways (SAA) will lock out about 2 200 union members this morning and warned that retrenchments could follow.  Leon Els, the carrier's spokesman, said the lockout was "the only resolution" and pre-empted the call by the South African Aviation Engineering and Allied Union for a strike over wage increases.<BR><P>
CHAOS AT AIRPORT AS SAA STAFF ACTION DISRUPTS FLIGHTS <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The work-to-rule by South African Airways engineering and technical staff has led to cancelled flights and produced chaos at Cape Town International Airport.  Last night the SAA rejected a conditional offer by striking union members to suspend their action and said they would be locked out from the start of the 6.30am shift today.  The SAA said the unions conditions for suspending the action were unacceptable.<BR><P>
SAPPI MAN CONFESSES TO LONE CRUSADE <I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Roland Mazery, the managing director of Sappi Saiccor, the KwaZulu Natal dissolving-pulp manufacturer, is the man behind the campaign to alert prominent international leaders to the "state of near anarchy prevailing across South Africa".<BR><P>
BUSINESS CONFIDENCE DROPS TO A 12-MONTH LOW <I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Business confidence, as measured by the South African Chamber of Business's business confidence index, fell to a 12-month low last month, the chamber said yesterday.<BR><P>
'GDP SHOULD GROW 3% THIS YEAR' <I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A slump in business activity and confidence in the third quarter could be offset by good conditions in the farm sector and work on infrastructure projects, the University of Stellenbosch's Bureau for Economic research said yesterday.  The bureau said it expected average GDP growth of 3 percent this year, slowing to 2,7 percent only if there was no further growth the rest of the year.<BR><P>
MINE SAFETY LAW ALMOST READY<I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Derek Baker, the inspector of mines, said yesterday that new legislation to prevent mine accidents like last year's Vaal Reefs tragedy which killed 104 miners, would be in place by January.  The Mine Health and Safety Act, already approved by the Cabinet, was geared to ensuring improved training and safety standards on mines, he said.<BR><P>
NEW CHAIRMAN FOR ANGLO DIVISION <I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Anglo American said yesterday that it had appointed Robert Danchin as the chairman of its new-mining business division with effect from October 1.  Danchin succeeds Alan McKerron, who has retired but will continue to be associated with Anglo on a consultancy basis.  Danchin will also become group deputy technical director for geology when Barry Hawthorne retires on March 31.<BR><P>
NEW GROUP OUT TO WOO COLOUREDS<I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
A broad Western Cape grouping - concerned with the extent to which coloureds in the region have been politically marginalised - are to launch a new "broad social movement", the "December 1st Movement".  The name of the movement symbolises the linking of the movement to the freeing of slaves in the Cape 162 years ago. The movement has stressed it is not a coloured nationalist movement, but rather that it should be seen as a structure committed to drawing people into the process of nation building and transformation.<BR><P>
IFP STILL NEGOTIATING - BUT INFORMALLY<I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The IFP would pursue a constitutional settlement informally, but would "revert to other tactics" if it failed to get its vies reflected, its negotiator Mr Ben Skosana said last night.  At a press conference to explain its withdrawal from the sub-committees of the Constitutional Assembly, its negotiators emphasised that the IFP had never returned to the Constitutional Assembly.<BR><P>
