<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 8 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>


IFP CAME CLOSE TO ACCEPTING ANC DEAL BEFORE WALKING OUT <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The IFP was within a whisker of accepting a package deal offered by the ANC before IFP leader Chief Mangosuthu Beuthelezi chose to withdraw his negotiators from the constitution-making process.  The draft constitution seems likely to be unanimously approved by the Constitutional Assembly on Friday - but the IFPs 48 senators and MPs will not be there.<BR><P>
60% IS NOT ENOUGH  <I>Editorial Comment</I><I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The deal reached with most alacrity between parties to the Constitutional Assembly is that related to the appointment and dismissal of the public protector and auditor-general.<BR><P>
ANGLO MAY SHAKE UP ITS ASSET BASE<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Anglo American has entered a new phase in its evolution into a focused industrial and mining financial group by launching a strategic review which is likely to lead to the group disposing of non-core assets.<BR><P>
FOUR MINERS KILLED<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Four miners were killed and another four admitted to hospital after a seismic event at the Western Deep Levels gold mine yesterday, Anglo American said.<BR><P>
PRODUCTION RESUMES<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
An underground fire at Anglo American's Freegold mine near Welkom on Sunday night forced the evacuation of the night shift at Saaiplaas No 3 Shaft and the cancellation of yesterday's shift.  No injuries were reported and the blaze, which followed two earth tremors, was brought under control.  Production resumed last night.<BR><P>
GOLD THEFT ARRESTS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Police arrested 27 workers yesterday for stealing pure gold worth about R300 000 at three gold processing plants sin Welkom, and have identified another 58 suspects.<BR><P>
BOOST FOR COMMUNICATIONS<I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
A bill tabled in Parliament yesterday would pave the way for a R32 billion investment in telecommunications over five years, taking South Africa from illiteracy to computer literacy, Communications Minister Mr Jay Naidoo said yesterday.  The Telecommunications Bill would also lead to the restructuring of telecommunications in South Africa and establish an independent regulator, the South African Telecommunications Regulatory Authority.<BR><P>
GOVT WARNED OF DANGERS OF SINGAPORE LABOUR DEBATE<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SA could lose its moral high ground among developing nations if it joined industrialised countries in calling for labour standards to be discussed at the ministerial meeting of the World Trade Organisation (WTO), trade experts said yesterday.<BR><P>
SERVICES BODY SEEN AS NEGLECTED <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The essential services committee - an important element of the administrative structure of the new Labour Relations Act - has received limited attention in comparison to the Commission for Conciliation, Mediation and Arbitration, and the Labour Court.<BR><P>
CAPACITY UTILISATION FALLS IN 18 INDUSTRIES <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Capacity utilisation fell in 18 of the 20 major manufacturing industries in May, and by the end of June nearly 10 000 workers had lost jobs, Central Statistical Service figures show.<BR><P>
SOME QUESTIONS NEED ASKING BEFORE PRIVATISATION BEGINS<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
It is hardly surprising that SBC Warburg is winning the investment bank beauty competition as chief adviser for key SA parastatals, notably Telkom and SAA.<BR><P>
BUSINESS MAN SMEARS SA<I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A smear campaign by a local businessman to deter foreign investors from putting their money into South Africa has been brought to the attention of Thabo Mbeki, the deputy president.<BR><P>
MOSSGAS' MYSTERY VENTURES <I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Mossgas, the much-maligned fuel-from-gas producer, is negotiating several joint ventures, including offshore gas exploration and an onshore chemical plant, its chief executive, David Day, said yesterday.<BR><P>
SQUEEZE ON STEEL EXPORTERS <I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The European Union has revised its stainless steel specifications, a move which could put a squeeze on South African exports and boost the competitiveness of imports unless local industry adapts to these new standards, David Slater, the executive director of the Southern Africa Stainless Steel Development Association, said yesterday.<BR><P>
SA URGED TO TREAD CAUTIOUSLY WITH EU <I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The South African Chamber of Business and Afrikaanse Handelsinstituut<I> (Afrikaans Business Institute)</I> urged the government yesterday not to rush into a free trade deal with the European Union (EU), saying that the continent's mandate was too harsh on vulnerable industries.<BR><P>
REFINERIES 'CANNOT KEEP UP' <I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
South Africa could run out of petrol refining capacity this year, forcing the country to import the refined product, John Greensmith, the managing director of BP Africa, said yesterday.<BR><P>
FAR EAST GOLD DEMAND DOWN THROUGH SEPTEMBER - CRU<I> (Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Imports by the six major eastern gold destinations were down 16 percent during the first eight months of 1996 compared with the same period last year, according to CRU International's latest Precious Metals Monitor.<BR><P>
