<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 7 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>

MINE VIOLENCE REPORT CRITICAL OF NUM AND MIGRANT LABOUR SYSTEM
<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
NUM and the migrant labour and hostel system will come under fire when a commission of inquiry into mine violence presents its report to President Mandela today.<BR><P>
CAPITAL DRAIN TAKES TOLL ON FOREX RESERVES <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The foreign capital drain has continued to take its toll on the Reserve Bank's forex and old reserves, which fell to R10,04bn, in figures released by the Reserve Bank show.<BR><P>
LAST-MINUTE BID TO BRING IFP INTO AGREEMENT ON RURAL GOVT <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Senior ANC and IFP negotiators are working frantically to bring the IFP on board the constitutional process on the crucial issue of rural local govt.<BR><P>
CENSUS ORGANISERS FLOODED WITH APPLICATIONS FOR TEMPORARY JOBS
<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
At lease half a million people had applied for 100 000 jobs as enumerators for the 1996 census, census deputy head Marinda de Lange said at the weekend.<BR><P>
NEW SETBACK IN ZIMBABWE AND SA TRADE RELATIONS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Confederation of Zimbabwean Industries president Jonee Blanchfield has accused SA of saying that it plans to restore the 1964 'most favoured nation' trade pact with Zimbabwe only so the country can obtain preferential access to the European Union.<BR><P>
SA MAY LOSE OUT ON WORLD BANK CONTRACTS<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SA businesses are ignoring the opportunity of winning extensive World Bank contracts and face losing out to international companies aware of the bidding process, says Development Bank Association MD Nick Ludlow.<BR><P>
ANC PUSHES FOR AGREEMENT <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The breakthrough ANC-NP agreement on outstanding constitutional issues is based on a narrow interpretation of the Constitutional Court's ruling, motivated by the ANC - except regarding policing powers, the auditor-general and the public protector.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD TO RESHAPE INTO FOUR UNITS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Randgold & Exploration has unveiled plans to reshape over the next 10 to 15 years - including the creation of an investment holding company with interests in offshore precious minerals mining.<BR><P>
DEBATE ON PRIVATISATION NEEDS DIFFERENT EMPHASIS<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
An incorrect emphasis was being placed on privatisation when dealing with the restructuring of state assets, public enterprises deputy director-general Sipho Shabalala said in a recent document.<BR><P>
PETROL PRICE COULD RISE 10C A LITRE, ECONOMETRIX WARNS
<I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
If the rand exchange rate and the oil price remain at present levels, the price of petrol could be increased by up to 10c a litre, equivalent to 5%, over the next two months, in the process adding 0,2% to the inflation rate, Econometrix, the economic research unit, said.<BR><P>
NUM IN FOR A TONGUE-LASHING<I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Judge John Myburgh, who heads the commission of inquiry into mine violence, will probably come down heavily on the NUM today when he delivers the commission's report to parliament, which might not be made public.  He said last week that the union wanted to blame everybody but itself.<BR><P>
IMF, WORLD BANK ZAMBIA PROGRAMMES THREATENED <I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A freeze on donor aid to Zambia has placed IMF and World Bank programmes in jeopardy, a Standard Chartered Bank Zambia report released on Friday said.  The suspension of balance-of-payment support by most western governments had made it difficult for Zambia to meet the economic benchmarks set by the institutions.  Western governments, led by the US, have cut or frozen aid because of laws they say limit Zambians' choice of a president.<BR><P>
NAMIBIA'S COSTLIEST LABOUR DISPUTE ENDS<I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Namibia's longest and costliest labour dispute has ended with an agreement on a 10,5% increase for mineworkers and further negotiations on the reduction of the workforce by up to a third, Namibian Prime Minister Hag Geingob said at the weekend.<BR><P>
INFLATION MAY HOLD STEADY, BUT RAND OIL PRICE IS A WORRY <I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A heightened focus on inflation, both domestically and internationally, will feature on the economic front in the week ahead.  Tomorrow will see the release of SA's producer price inflation statistics, a leading indicator of consumer price inflation, which in turn is a key determinant of the monetary authorities' interest rate policy.<BR><P>



