<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 4 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>

MONEY MARKET SHORTAGE JUMPS TO FIVE-MONTH HIGH <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The money market shortage jumped more than R1bn to just under R10bn this week - its highest level in five months and close to the figure which resulted in commercial banks' controversial rates hike in May.<BR><P>
DROP IN ECONOMIC ACTIVITY HURTS CAR SALES <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Sept car sales fell 9,5% to 19 928 units against the corresponding month last year, after lower economic activity and punitive interest rates affected the vehicle market.<BR><P>
NISSAN'S GAME FARM UNDER THE SPOTLIGHT <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The National Union of Metalworkers of SA has asked for disclosure of the operating costs of a Nissan owned golf course development, game farm and timeshare facility ahead of the motor manufacturer's planned retrenchment of 900 workers.  The union said yesterday the retrenchments - the first 200 took place this week - were partly based on Nissan's attempt to cut costs and focus on its core activities.  Numsa was therefore entitled to know whether the assets were part of the company's core operations or whether they should be sold to reduce costs.<BR><P>
MINE SECURITY STAFF ON THIRD DAY WITHOUT FOOD  <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Security staff trapped by striking miners at Namibia's Tsumeb Corp had been without food for three days, but a mine manager blockaded in his own home had been freed, Goldfields of Namibia said yesterday.<BR><P>
GOLD FIELDS, UNIONS' ACCORD ON VIOLENCE  <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gold Fields, NUM and Uwusa are expected to hand a signed agreement to commission on mine violence chairman Judge John Myburgh today, listing a number of steps which should be implemented to reduce mine conflict.<BR><P>
BUSINESS AND LABOUR COMMIT THEMSELVES TO TRANSFORMATION OF ECONOMY  <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Workforce restructuring and productivity was given a boost yesterday when labour and business committed themselves to a nation-wide programme which would lay the foundation for the transformation of the SA economy.<BR><P>
SA INVESTS R9BN WITH ITS NEIGHBOURS  <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
More than 30 SA firms have announced investment plans of about R9bn in neighbouring African countries since the ending of apartheid enabled economic exchanges, according to a leading Johannesburg research agency.<BR><P>
EMPLOYMENT TALKS, BUT NO BILL IN SIGHT  <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A number of bilateral meetings have been held in recent weeks between  labour and business on future employment legislation, but there are no clear indications whether a draft Fill will be tabled in Parliament this year.<BR><P>
ENOUGH OF LIP SERVICE<I> Comment & Analysis</I>  <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Peevish rejection by some African countries of IMF and World Bank strictures on economic and political governance should not be heeded by SA.  Compliance with sound government that is to be a condition of support by the two institutions does not represent unacceptable intrusion into national sovereignty, as claimed by states that pay only lip service to democracy and to the precepts of honest management of public affairs.<BR><P>
ASSET SWAP DEALS ARE 'FULLY LEGAL'<I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SA fund managers said yesterday that the asset swaps into which they had entered did not contravene US legislation, following Wednesday's disclosure that the US Securities and Exchange Commission was unhappy with quid pro quo asset swaps concluded between SA and US institutions.<BR><P>
A PROMISED LAND OF "PAP 'N VLEIS", WITH GRAVY, FOR ALL  <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SA's trade union movement is, by general admission, facing a time of massive uncertainty.  Born out of struggle as much against the state as the employers, it now finds itself part of an alliance in the govt and  a partner with business in forums such as Nedlac.  Here it is charged with policy formulation in a global economic environment of intense competition.<BR><P>
EMPLOYMENT FALLS ACROSS THE BOARD IN JUNE<I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The manufacturers of women's, girl's and children's clothing were the largest providers of employment in the manufacturing sector in June, the Central Statistical Service said yesterday.  It said the sub-sector employed 4,7% of the 1,4m people working in manufacturing.  The next-biggest work providers where in electrical equipment and the basic iron and steel industries.<BR><P>
ANGLO RATIONALISES MINING MANAGEMENT <I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Mining group Anglo American has rationalised its gold and uranium division management structure to remove a layer beneath chairman Bobby Godsell and regional managers.<BR><P>
TRADE IMBALANCE WITH AFRICA CONTINUES TO GROW RELENTLESSLY <I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The trade imbalance between SA and the rest of the continent continues to grow.  The most recent statistics analysed by Econometrix, reveal that SA's exports to Africa comprised 13.5% of the country's total exports for the eight months to end August 1996.  Imports from Africa, however, accounted for only 3.0% of SA's total imports.<BR><P>
BAD NEWS FOR BASE METALS<I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Aluminium and copper prices are expected to fall next year, the London-based Economist Intelligence Unit said yesterday in a new report.<BR><P>
RATE CUT COULD TRIGGER BULL RUN ON JSE<I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The SA stock market was set for strong growth right into 1998, and a fall in interest rates could trigger bullish advances, Arnold Shapiro, the senior portfolio manager at Old Mutual Unit Trusts, said yesterday.<BR><P>
DOUBTS GROW OVER LRA  <I>(Business Mail, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Business and labour are worried that the new Labour relations act (LRA) could trip up before it even gets off the starting blocks on Nov 11.  Its success hinges on whether the Commission for Conciliation, Mediation and Arbitration will be able to effectively hold together the fabric of the Act.<BR><P>
DIAMONDS ARE FOREVER <I>(Business Mail, Jhb.)</I><BR>
 but are cartels?  An unholy alliance of Angolan mercenaries, SA gangsters, Belgian mafiosi and Russian nationalists is threatening to blow apart the monopoly that ensures diamonds keep their sparkle.<BR><P>
GENCOR PUTS PREMIUM ON OVERSEAS EXPANSION <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
London - Mining giant Gencor is putting a high premium on exploration outside of its SA base, executive director Gary Maude told the Global Emerging Markets 96 conference on Thursday.<BR><P>
WORLD GOLD COUNCIL TO HOLD CONFERENCE IN NEW DELHI <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Bombay - The World Gold Council said it will host the first-ever gold economic conference to be held in India in New Delhi on Nov 28 and 29.<BR><P>
MINING EXPLORATION BOOM SEEN IN EMERGING MARKETS<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
London - A boom in mining exploration over the past few years promises to result in significant discoveries in the near future, analyst James Crombie told the Global Emerging Markets '96 conference on Thursday.<BR><P>



