<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 3 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>

THREE MINERS DIE<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Three miners died in a rockfall during a seismic event 1 100m below the surface at the West Driefontein gold mine in Carletonville yesterday, the mine said.<BR><P>

MINE'S SECURITY STAFF AND DOGS 'TRAPPED WITH NO FOOD' <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Up to 30 security workers and their dogs at Namibian copper mine, Tsumeb Corporation, were trapped by armed strikers and had been without food since Monday, mine manager Tony de Beer said yesterday.  He said that the 25 to 30 security workers had been blockaded by armed members of the Mineworkers' Union of Namibia at the Tsumeb site since last Thursday.<BR><P>

CALL MADE TO PHASE OUT MIGRANT LABOUR <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A leading economist has called for the establishment of a task force mandated to negotiate the phasing out of the migrant labour system by compelling mining houses, over a period, to raise the proportion of miners housed in family-type accommodation.<BR><P>

NORTHAM PROFIT COULD BE R50M, SAYS GOLD FIELDS<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gold Fields' Northam Platinum mine would make a R50m profit in its 1997 financial year if a throughput level of about 150 000 tons could be maintained, the group said yesterday.<BR><P>

ECONOMISTS UPBEAT ON GOVT FINANCES <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The finance dept obtained financing  of R3,02bn last month, bringing total financing for the six months to Sept to R21,44bn which will help govt meet its budgeted R45,01bn target for the current financial year.<BR><P>

WORK TO RESUME ON LESOTHO WATER PROJECT<I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Work is to resume on the tunnel and hydroelectricity components of the $4b Lesotho Highlands Water Project on Monday after an agreement was concluded between the Construction and Allied Workers' Union of Lesotho and a consortium of five international contractors yesterday.<BR><P>

AT HOME WITH A MACROPLAN<I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The labour movement ha not yet declared its acceptance of the macroplan, as it had done with the state's programme for state asset restructuring.  The ingrained mistrust by the labour movement of everything which emanates from the IMF and World Bank (and certain circles in parliament) may become an obstacle in the way of general acceptance of the macroplan.  But many of the IMF principles should be acceptable to labour, and it would be unwise for the unions to stand in the way of a plan which has become the model for others in the world, just because labour dislikes aspect of it.<BR><P>

EASING OF EXCHANGE CONTROLS BOOSTED INVESTMENT<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Washington - Moves to ease exchange controls had allowed SA companies to make foreign direct investments of more than R9bn over the past three years, Reserve Bank governor Chris Stals said yesterday.  He told a conference arranged by the economics dept of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology that SA had pulled off "major relaxations" in exchange controls.<BR><P>

MOOD IS UPBEAT IN WARDS OF DOCTOR DEBT <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The IMF and the bank say the world is reaping the benefits of their policy prescriptions.  But those policies, and the two organisations' modus operandi, have often been at the centre of controversy because of their effect on the poor and on the environment.  To their credit, the two organisations appear to have responded to the criticism.  Nowhere is that more obvious than in the initiative to provide debt relief to poor countries - a move that would have been unthinkable a few years ago.<BR><P>  

