<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 2 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



MANDELA HAILS NEW MINE ACT <I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
President Mandela said yesterday the SA mining industry was on the brink of a new era now that the Mine Health and Safety Act was in place.<BR><P>
SA SETTING AGENDA FOR FIRST WORLD BANK LOAN, RAMOS  <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - SA has been in the driver's seat in negotiations with the World Bank for its first loan, which could even be denominated in rands if the country gets its way.  Finance director-general Maria Ramos told journalists yesterday:  "We are setting the agenda".  Interviewed after the news conference, World Bank southern Africa head Pamela Cox said the loan would be small - less than $67m, which was the size of the total project for industrial competitiveness and job creation.<BR><P>
IMF WILL KNOW IN 97 IF GOLD MUST BE SOLD - OFFICIAL<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - The IMF should know sometime next year whether it will need to sell gold to finance stepped-up aid to poor nations, IMF Interim Committee Chairman Philippe Maystadt said on Tuesday.<BR><P>
IMF GIVE SA FINANCIAL STATUS ON THE WEB<I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The IMF has certified SA's financial and economic statistics as being of a high enough standard to feature on its new World Wide Web site for country statistics on the Internet.<BR><P>
INGWE BUYS AUSTRALIAN COAL COMPANY <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Ingwe Coal Corporation has reinforced its dominance of the global steam coal market by buying an Australian coal company in a deal worth R800m - a move which could boost its exports 80% by 2005.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD TO LIST 5 MINES ON NASDAQ<I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Randgold & Exploration was preparing to list five of its mines on the Nasdaq screen-based trading system in the US from today, industry analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
GOLD FIELDS WILL NOT ALTER RECRUITMENT SYSTEM <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gold Fields did not plan to alter its system of recruiting individuals from a specific ethnic group for particular jobs, gold division MD Alan Munro told a commission of inquiry into mine violence at three Gold Fields mines yesterday.<BR><P>
GOLD FIELDS PLEADS PRESSURE<I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Alan Munro, the executive director of Gold Fields of SA, said yesterday that he was under pressure from shareholders to close the Leeudoorn gold mine, which was not at all economically viable.<BR><P>
WORKERS HOLD TSUMEB MINE MANAGER HOSTAGE <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Striking copper miners at Tsumeb in Namibia had taken the mine manager hostage in the increasingly bitter labour dispute now entering its sixth week, owner Gold Fields Namibia said yesterday.<BR><P>
JCI SCRAPS COMPULSORY SERVICE CONTRACTS IN FAVOUR OF TENDERING <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
JCI has joined Randgold in ending the system of compulsory service contracts which SA mining houses have traditionally imposed on the mines they control.<BR><P>
INVESTMENT INCENTIVE SCHEME KICKS OFF <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Government's investment incentive scheme came into effect yesterday after the measures were bulldozed through from announcement to implementation in an attempt to fulfil a key element of the strategy for Growth, Employment And Redistribution on time.  The Trade and Industry and  Finance Departments said in a joint statement the accelerated depreciation tax allowance and the tax holiday scheme came into effect yesterday.<BR><P>
RESCUE TARGETS FINANCE PLANNING <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Central government was "very reluctant" to bail out financially stricken local councils and this was not the intention of its rescue plan for cash-strapped municipalities, Constitutional Affairs deputy director-general Andrew Boraine said yesterday.<BR><P>
SA SUPPORTS FOCUS ON GOOD GOVT <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - SA officials made moves to distance the country from other developing nations complaining about the World Bank and IMF's political agenda, despite some of its African partners voicing their opposition.  Finance director-general Maria Ramos said yesterday that SA was not uncomfortable with the bank and fund's increasing emphasis on good governance.  "It is not an issue for us.  We agree that good governance is fundamental to sustainable economic development".  But she disagreed with the view of some participants at the IMF/World Bank AGMs that big countries should put economic pressure on developing countries with bad human rights and corruption track records.<BR><P>
BANKS SOUGHT TO MARKET GOVT BONDS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Finance Ministry has sent a questionnaire to banks in a bid to find market makers to take over the Reserve Bank's role in placing state debt.<BR><P>
SA CENTRAL BANKER SAYS RATES STEADY FOR NOW<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Washington - SA Reserve Bank Governor Chris Stals said on Tuesday the central bank would not lower interest rates unless it sees improvement in the current account, and would hike rates unless the figures improved.<BR><P>
GOVT URGED TO BE CAUTION IN OPENING TRADE <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Two employer associations, the SA Agricultural Union and the Southern African Poultry Association, called on govt yesterday to move cautiously in liberalising trade with SA's neighbours in southern Africa.  The South African Development Community nations agreed on a trade protocol which would liberalise trade in the region over the next eight years.  In a written submission to the committee, the poultry association said it was "principally in favour of gradually expanding trade in southern Africa on even playing fields".<BR><P>
COSATU REJECTS ACCELERATED TARIFF REDUCTION  <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Cosatu yesterday rejected calls for a blanket acceleration of the tariff reduction programme following the recent tumble of SA's currency, and called for a rethink on  trade liberalisation.<BR><P>
TARIFF POLICY CRUCIAL FOR JOB CREATION (Business Report Pg.1)
The timing of SA's tariff policy is crucial in helping the govt meet its job creation targets, officials said yesterday.  Zav Rustomjee, the director-general of the trade and industry dept, said the challenge was to find a way of creating 403 000 jobs a year by the end of 2000.<BR><P>
AGGRESSIVE STRATEGY NEEDED <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Board of Executors economic consultant Rob Lee said that key policy makers continually reaffirmed privatisation would be gradual and that exchange control relaxation would be delayed whenever there was pressure on the currency.  "All this means is that the currency remains extremely vulnerable. Foreign exchange reserves remain low and precarious for the foreseeable future.<BR><P>
GOVT STARTS CHARGING VAT ON FINANCIAL SERVICES<I>(Business Report, The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The govt started charging VAT on financial services yesterday.  Absa and Standard Bank, two of the country's four largest commercial banks, said yesterday that they had increased their fees to account for VAT charges.<BR><P>


