<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 1 OCTOBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



TSUMEB STRIKERS TAKE CONTROL OF MINE HOSPITAL <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Striking Namibian mineworkers took control of a hospital owned by Tsumeb Corporation yesterday and took three people hostage as the 39-day-old wage strike continued with no end in sight, company spokesman Dermot Whyte said.<BR><P>
SIX TONS OF WEAPONS CONFISCATED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Police confiscated six tons of home-made weapons and commercial explosives at the Buffelsfontein mine hostel in Stilfontein in Northwest yesterday.  A spokesman said tensions at the mine were easing after 27 men died and 38 were injured last month.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
BUFFELSFONTEIN MINE BACK TO NORMAL <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Mining operations were back to normal yesterday though the situation in the North West mining town of Stilfontein was still tense, Sam Goodwin, the managing director of the mine, said. <BR><P>
JCI ASSESSES SEPARATE EXPLORATION PORTFOLIO <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Mining house JCI is considering a separate international listing for certain exploration activities in Africa, which would help it finance exploration and mine development from outside SA.<BR><P>
RANDGOLD SHIFTS ON KNIGHTS' STAKE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Randgold & Exploration would not bid for a controlling stake in East Rand gold operation Knights Gold Mining Company as the asking price had been too high, industry sources said yesterday.<BR><P>
INGWE COAL TO CUT 30% OF MPISI WORKFORCE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Ingwe Coal Corporation would cut 30% of its 500-strong workforce at underground colliery Mpisi Coal, mainly as a result of rising transport costs.<BR><P>
DRIEFONTEIN AND KLOOF PREDICT BETTER DIVIDENDS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The two largest gold mining companies in the Gold Fields of SA stable are predicting increased dividends in the financial year to June 1997, provided the gold price stays relatively stable.<BR><P>
WILDCAT ACTION AT PLATINUM MINE DISTORTS STRIKE FIGURES <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The wildcat three-week strike at Anglo American's Rustenburg Platinum Mine pushed SA's strike barometer for the first nine months of the year beyond last year's figure, labour analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
MIGRANT LABOUR SYSTEM 'MUST GO' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The ethnic nature of the migrant labour system and the undemocratic representative structures in mine hostels should be overthrown and miners allowed more space for their leisure hours, National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) assistant general secretary Gwede Mantashe told a commission inquiring into mine violence <I>[on four Gold Fields mines]</I> yesterday.<BR><P>
RAND'S FALL TO CONTINUE BUT AT MORE SEDATE PACE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The rand will continue to depreciate over the next 15 months, according to a Reuters quarterly rand poll of economists and analysts.  However, the pace of the fall may be slower than in the past seven months, when it fell 25%.  The currency was expected to depreciate to a quarterly average of R4,77 against the dollar in the fourth quarter of next year, from R4,51 in the fourth quarter of this year, the poll showed.<BR><P>
EXPORTS FALL, BUT TRADE BALANCE STAYS IN BLACK <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA's trade balance remained in the black in August despite a sharp fall in exports, reducing the surplus to R132,4m from July's R2,58bn, Customs and Excise figures showed yesterday.<BR><P>
EURO SINGLE CURRENCY BONDS SET TO OUTPERFORM OTHERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
International bonds denominated in the planned European single currency, including the newly issued SA Deutschmark bond, are set to outperform those of countries which will choose to stay outside the monetary union, according to a source at Deutsche Morgan Grenfell, the lead managers of the SA government's latest international issue.<BR><P>
LABOUR, GOVT STRATEGY TALKS ON TRACK <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Negotiations between labour and government on the macro-economic strategy released in June could move into top gear following the endorsement by the Congress of SA Trade Union's (Cosatu) second largest affiliate at the weekend of an economic vision for transformation.  The economic policy consisted of strategies to effect the implementation of a social welfare system and a trade and industry policy.  The union said the development of a social-welfare system required government to implement a national health-care system and address delivery of houses, public transport and retirement benefits.<BR>
<B><I>... but ...</I></B><BR>
GOVT AND UNIONS BEG TO DIFFER <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Enoch Godongwana, the general secretary of the National Union of Metalworkers of SA, said Numsa was opposed to the government's macro-economic plan, which advocated a reduction in the budget deficit and a tightening  of monetary policy.  "That document has all the elements of the prescription of the International Monetary Fund and World Bank for developing economies".  He said the congress had identified economic transformation as "where the battle is" and had begun to formulate the union's own economic platform as policy proposals.  He said the union had agreed on a universal social welfare system and trade and industry policy as two areas where they could influence government policy.<BR><P>
NISSAN SA RETRENCHES FIRST 200 OF POSSIBLE 900 <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Nissan SA's retrenchment programme kicked off yesterday when 200 salaried staff were given notice of their retrenchment, although there could be some concessions in the wake of an eleventh-hour attempt by the National Union of Metalworkers of SA.<BR><P>
SURVEY SHOWS DECLINE IN JOBS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Total employment declined by almost 1% in the first quarter of 1996, Labour Minister Tito Mboweni said in Johannesburg last night, quoting from Central Statistical Service data released last month.<BR><P>
IFP RETURNS TO SUB-COMMITTEES DRAFTING CONSTITUTIONAL CHANGES <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The Inkatha Freedom Party said yesterday it had decided to end its 18-month boycott of the drafting of the countrys final constitution.  Senior IFP official Walter Felgate said this did not amount to a decision to return to the full Constitutional Assembly, which is composed of all members of Parliament.  Clauses referred back to the assembly by the court include those dealing with the powers of provincial administrations, one of the main sticking points between the IFP and the ANC.  The IFP wants a great deal of autonomy for the provinces in a federal-type arrangement, but the ANC wants the central government to wield most power.<BR><P>
SOMEBODY COULD GET HURT IN LATEST CONSTITUTIONAL FREE-FOR-ALL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Cosatu and the ANC complained volubly - and not without justification - last week that the Democratic Party and National Party (and, they may have added, Business SA) were sneakily trying to reintroduce a lockout clause through the back door as the Constitutional Assembly seeks to redraft the constitution.  What the left-of-centre allies failed to mention is that they, equally sneakily, are trying to reinforce constitutional support for centralised bargaining.  So here we are in a situation where business and labour and their respective political allies are all rushing headlong for the back door, doing their best to elbow their adversaries out of the way so they can get in first and slam the door shut.<BR><P>
SA RESIDENCE DEADLINE EXTENDED  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Home Affairs Department said yesterday it had extended indefinitely the deadline for applications by aliens from neighbouring states for permanent SA residence.  The applications had doubled over the past two weeks - 84 815 had been received to date from citizens of Southern African Development Community (SADC) member states, the Department said.<BR><P>
WORLD BANK, IMF LAY DOWN 'GOOD GOVERNANCE' RULES (BD Pg.3)
This week the International Monetary Fund's policy making interim committee noted the need for "promoting good governance by ensuring the rule of law, improving the efficiency and accountability of the public sector and tackling corruption".<BR><P>
SA IS TAKING PART IN POLICY TALKS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - SA is taking part in discussions of the IMF's most important policy making committee after Finance Minister Trevor Manuel's election as an alternative member of the powerful interim committee.  SA has joined the constituency of English-speaking African countries after years of isolation.  Manuel's election means that, after two years, SA will become a full member.<BR><P>
CRIME THREATENS LOCAL CONFERENCE INDUSTRY <I>(Cape Times)</I><BR>
While Cape Town this week hosts one of the largest international conferences yet held here, a city-based conference organiser has appealed to President Nelson Mandela to give the international conference industry assurances that South Africa is a safe destination.  Hundreds of engineers from around the globe have congregated in the "Mother City" for the 1996 conference of the International Federation of Consulting Engineers, which is being hosted by the South African Association of Consulting Engineers.<BR><P>





