<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 29  NOVEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



3 MINERS KILLED <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Three miners were killed in an earthquake at Randgold's Buffelsfontein gold mine in North West yesterday. <BR><P>
'NO HOPE' FOR 18 MINERS STILL TRAPPED IN ROVIC MUDSLIDE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The government mining engineer would investigate the Rovic diamond mine mudslide disaster which killed 22 workers in the Free State on Wednesday, Minerals and Energy Minister Penuell Maduna said yesterday.<BR><P>
AIDS CUTS ITS WAY THROUGH SA MINES <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
One worker dies of AIDS every day at one of the world's biggest mining corporations.  Gencor Ltd. estimates that 20% of the 100 000-strong labour force at its coal, platinum and gold mines is infected by the HIV virus and 30 workers lose their lives to AIDS each month.<BR><P>
DEMAND FOR GOLD SET TO MATCH RECORD HIGH <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Strong fourth-quarter support for gold will push up this year's global demand to a level matching the record high of 2 725 tons achieved last year, an official of the World Gold Council said yesterday.<BR><P>
JCI SALE TO AFRICAN MINING GROUP MARKED BY IRONIES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
There are some rich ironies to the deal in which Anglo is to sell 34,9% of JCI Ltd. to a consortium, African Mining Group, led by Mzi Khumalo's young and relatively unknown financial services group, Capital Alliance.<BR><P>
BLACK CONTROL MAY OPEN AFRICA TO JCI <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Now ruled by a black business consortium, SA mining house JCI Ltd. will be able to venture more easily into Africa than before, new controlling stakeholders African Mining Group said on Thursday. <BR><P>
SA AND ZIMBABWE DISCUSS TRADE AGREEMENT <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The Foreign Affairs Department yesterday said SA and Zimbabwe had held talks this week on details of an agreement aimed at ending a four-year trade dispute.<BR><P>
BOE UPBEAT AT 'GOVT'S SHIFT' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Indications that policymakers were shifting towards improved disclosure and increased urgency in economic reform boded well for economic growth beyond next year, Board of Executors Asset Management said in its investment outlook.<BR><P>
ECONOMIC REFORM NEEDS SOCIAL SAFEGUARDS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
It is often suggested that SA has a lot in common with other semi-industrialised countries in transition from authoritarianism to democracy.  The countries that are closest to SA according to these criteria are Brazil, Argentina, Spain, Korea, Taiwan, and many of the countries of central Europe, in particular Poland.<BR><P>
EXPORT PROCESSING ZONES SEEN AS THREAT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Regional integration in the southern African region could be seriously threatened by the introduction of export processing zones, International Labour Resource and Information Group research officer Herbert Jauch said yesterday.<BR><P>
NUM COULD BECOME EQUITY PARTNER IN CONSORTIUM <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The National Union of Mineworkers has held talks with the African Mining Group, the successful consortium led by Capital Alliance, in Anglo American's unbundling of mining house JCI Ltd., which could see the union becoming an equity partner in the consortium.<BR><P>
SURVEY SHOWS 38% BLACK UNEMPLOYMENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Central Statistical Service's 1995 October household survey findings, to be released today, are expected to show that 38% of blacks are unemployed.  The survey used 3 000 sampling points with 10 households to a point and is used to track indicators of living standards.<BR><P>
LABOUR GROUP SETS UP TRAINING PROJECT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The International Labour Organisation would train 360 South Africans to become supervisors in the small business sector as part of a programme started last November, the organisation's chief technical adviser, Arvind Nante, said yesterday.<BR><P>
TAIWAN, PROTESTING OVER SNUB, SAYS IT WILL REVIEW AID PROJECTS IN SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Taiwan issued a formal protest yesterday over SA's decision to drop its diplomatic recognition in favour of Beijing, saying official aid projects would be reviewed, but trade ties were unlikely to be affected severely.<BR><P>
THE CHINA OPTION <I>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
President Nelson Mandela's announcement that SA is to cut diplomatic relations with the Republic of China in favour of the mainland is surprising and even bewildering because it constitutes such a marked departure from almost every-thing he has said before on the subject.  His repeated assertions that it would be immoral to make the change now appear to have been a string of empty promises.<BR><P>
STRANGE BEDFELLOWS IN BUSINESS <I>(Business Mail, Fridays with the Mail & Guardian)</I><BR>
It could be the most unlikely of marriages, both in terms of historical differences and future ambitions.  Yet the Afrikaanse Handelsinstituut [organisation representing predominantly white Afrikaans businesspeople] and the National Federated Chamber of Commerce [predominantly black] have agreed to begin working towards a single body representing business in SA.<BR><P>
PUBLIC INFORMATION ACCESS TO BE UPGRADED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A new cabinet committee chaired by Deputy President Thabo Mbeki should be established to provide top-level guidance and co-ordination in all matters related to the development of communications and information in SA, Mbeki's task group on government communications, Comtask, has recommended.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
TASK GROUP CALLS FOR PROBE OF PRINT MEDIA OWNERSHIP <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The concentration of ownership in the print media should be referred to the Competition Board for investigation, the Task Group on Government Communications recommended yesterday.  In its report, presented to Deputy President Thabo Mbekis office, Comtask also slammed South Africas "impoverished" journalistic standards, saying that "the apartheid years have damaged the profession of journalism".<BR><P>
BAIL GIVEN TOO EASILY - OMAR <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Serious offenders were still being granted bail too easily despite the introduction of a new bail law last year, Justice Minister Dullah Omar said yesterday.<BR><P>
</DOC>
