<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 28  NOVEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>





THREE DEAD, 37 MISSING AFTER MINE MUD SLIDE <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Rescue workers from Bloemfontein rushed to the Rovic diamond mine in the western Free State yesterday after a mud slide trapped at least 42 miners in a shaft.   Three miners were killed and two were injured while about 37 were unaccounted for.  The missing miners were thought to be trapped about 500m underground.<BR><P>
MINE DEATHS: 26 ARRESTED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Twenty-six North West mineworkers were arrested yesterday in connection with violence at two Stilfontein gold mine hostels in September in which 26 people died.<BR><P>
ANGLO WILL PROCEED 'WITH CARE' IN ZAIRE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American would proceed cautiously in war-torn Zaire, where the company was considering investments in the country's substantial base metal resources, chairman Julian Ogilvie Thompson said.<BR><P>
ANGLO TAKES POSITIVE VIEW ON SA'S FUTURE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American Corporation is leading an initiative to counter government and public perceptions that business is unduly negative about the country's prospects.  Anglo chairman Julian Ogilvie Thompson told a media briefing this week that there "remains much to be positive about in SA  - the levels of private sector investment are high, delivery in crucial socio-economic areas is beginning to be evident and the institutions of our market democracy remain vibrant".<BR><P>
AFRICAN MINING GROUP TO CONSIDER BRINGING FOREIGN INVESTORS TO JCI <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The African Mining Group could use mining house JCI - in which the consortium has bought a 34,9% stake from Anglo American for R2,8bn - to launch a global mining fund and is considering bringing international investors into JCI.  Sources said yesterday that a number of other black empowerment groups had teamed up with the African Mining Group, including Tiego Moseneke's Khotso Investments, Corridor Investments, and Northern Corporation Investment Holdings, which represented some of the interests of the Bafokeng clan.<BR><P>
JCI'S PRICE WAS TOO HIGH, SAY ANALYSTS <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Analysts expressed some concern yesterday about the size of the premium African Mining Group (AMG) has agreed to pay Anglo American for a 34,9% stake in JCI.  They said yesterday's market price of R50,50 represented a fairer value for the share than the R54,50 being paid by AMG.<BR><P>
COSTS AND OPPORTUNITIES <I>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
The premium Capital Alliance paid Anglo American for a 34,9% interest in JCI highlights the deal's importance and that it is not a token black empowerment exercise.  It contrasts with the discount to market at which Anglo sold control of Johnnic to the National Empowerment Consortium.  The reason for the apparent price discrepancies is clear.  Johnnic is a holding company largely owning  investments it does not manage, which means the NEC's opportunities to influence the operating companies' direction may be comparatively restricted.<BR><P>
TECHNICAL SNAGS ALLOW ONLY 30 MINUTES' TRADING ON JSE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Unrelenting problems with the electronic trading system, or Jet, brought the Johannesburg Stock Exchange to a halt for the third consecutive day yesterday.  The market opened for just 30 minutes frustrating traders who forecast heavy losses for their firms and putting a black mark on the JSE's reputation in global financial markets.<BR><P>
JCI TO SELL INDONESIAN GOLD PROJECT STAKE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SYDNEY - Lone Star Exploration NL said on Thursday it had bought out its partners in the Awak Mas gold project in Indonesia for a total of about US$41-million.  Lone Star, which is listed in Australia and Canada, said it would acquire the 45% interest of Gascoyne Gold Mines NL and the 10% stake held by SA mining house JCI Ltd.<BR><P>
CANADA'S BARRICK TO LEAD GOLD PRODUCERS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
TORONTO - Canada's Barrick Gold Corporation appears set to become the world's biggest gold producer under an unusual deal that will give it a majority share in Indonesia's rich Busang gold discovery.<BR><P>
MINERS BLAST INDONESIAN MOVE ON BUSANG <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
JAKARTA - The Indonesian government's attempt to force a settlement over the spectacular Busang gold find was criticised by local miners on Wednesday, who said the move could hurt investment in mining.<BR><P>
YEAR-END SUPPORT TO PUSH 96 WORLD GOLD DEMAND TO RECORD <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
NEW DELHI - Strong last-quarter support for gold will push up 1996 demand for the precious metal to match the all-time high of 2,725 tonnes achieved in 1995, an official of the World Gold Council said on Thursday.<BR><P>
GOLD CONTINUES FALL <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Gold continued to fall yesterday, trading as low as $372,60 an ounce late in the afternoon, with a quieter period expected today because the US markets are closed for a holiday. <BR><P>
DEALER WANTS STATE TO RETURN GOLD <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A Greek gold dealer arrested on charges of unlawfully possessing unwrought gold two years ago and later released has asked the Rand Supreme Court to order the Finance Ministry to return 15kg of gold worth R700 000.  After charges were withdrawn pending further investigation last year, he was told the gold had been forfeited to the state in terms of exchange control regulations.  Should the ministry fail to return his gold, he wants the matter referred to the Constitutional Court to have the exchange regulations declared invalid.<BR><P>
RAND SHOULD STABILISE BY END OF NEXT YEAR <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Further falls in the rand are likely to be short-term and the currency should be stable at R4,70 to the dollar by the end of next year, Sandra Gordon, group economist at Syfrets, said at a seminar yesterday.  Gordon said the rise in interest rates had made her revise her growth forecasts for next year and 1998 downwards, "given its likely impact on consumer and investment spending".  She now expected a growth rate of only 1,8% next year instead of her previous forecast of 2,3%.  This was likely to strengthen to 3,2% in 1998, below her previous forecast of 3,6%.<BR><P>
RAND RECOVERS GROUND AGAINST DOLLAR <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The rand hit its best level against the dollar for more than five weeks yesterday as demand rose when offshore banks developed a healthy appetite for South African bonds.<BR><P>
SA DROPS TAIWAN IN FAVOUR OF CHINA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
President Mandela announced yesterday that SA would cut formal diplomatic ties with Taiwan, recognising China instead.  The surprise decision, following a series of  statements in support of Taiwan, means SA might lose some large Taiwanese investments.  It will, however, bring SA in line with the international trend of recognising China.  <BR><P>
MANDELA SAVES FACE AND SOLVES THE CHINESE PUZZLE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Financial considerations kept the ANC-led government sweet with Taiwan.  It was  money that finally talked when President Mandela decided to cut political ties with the island and recognise the People's Republic of China.  There will be a price to pay for this decision announced by Mandela yesterday - but it will not be as high as Taiwan officials have been threatening.  The benefits of bringing SA in step with the rest of the world will far outweigh the negative implications.  Taiwan's development assistance for SA, now running at about R228m spread over projects involving vocational training for SANDF members, a vegetable farmers' training project, a special forestry project and educational assistance, might well dry up.  But the R1,6bn worth of Taiwanese investment in SA is unlikely to be removed.<BR><P>
BENEFITS OF GROWTH MUST BE SHARED BY ALL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
It is often assumed that, for all practical purposes, economic growth and development are synonymous.  In fact they are not and the distinction between them is critical.  Growth is a narrow measure of economic performance expressed in terms of increases in output.  Development is a broader concept and refers to upgrading of the skills and knowledge pool, distribution of national resources and spread of the benefits of economic activity through society, in such a way as to improve welfare and living standards.  It is a measure of how society can benefit from economic growth.<BR><P>
SA HAS A 'DISCOURAGED WORKFORCE' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA was saddled with about 1,5m "discouraged workers" - one of the highest rates in the world, Rand Afrikaans University economist Elsabe Loots said yesterday.<BR><P>
NEDLAC TALKS DEADLOCK OVER JOB CONDITIONS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Negotiations between the government, labour and business in the Nationa Economic Development and Labour Council (Nedlac) for a new set of minimum standards for employment have broken down, and negotiators have resorted to bilateral meetings to break the deadlock.<BR><P>
FEARS ON NEW COMPETITION LEGISLATION <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin may have sidelined more conservative elements in the team commissioned to draft new competition legislation by enlarging the team with people with little experience of competition policy.  <BR><P>
SA OIL INDUSTRY VOICES CONCERN ABOUT MINISTER'S LACK OF AVAILABILITY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The South African oil industry has appealed for an urgent meeting with Minerals and Energy Minister Penuell Maduna amid mounting concern about the industry's prospects.  Sources said industry representatives have been seeking a meeting since Maduna took office in July, hoping to discuss key issues affecting the future structure of the industry, including price rises for diesel and petrol.<BR><P>
EU AID TO SA 'SHOULD BE STREAMLINED' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The R600m-a-year European Union aid package to SA should be streamlined to focus on a few development programmes to facilitate its implementation, a senior EU official said last night.  <BR><P>
</DOC>
