<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 12  NOVEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>

<p>ANGLO CONFIRMS TALKS WITH EU OVER STAKE IN LONRHO <i>(Business
Day, Jhb.)</i><br>
Mining group Anglo American confirmed that it was in talks with
the European Union over a tie-up with Britain's Lonrho conglomerate.
It was reported at the weekend that the European Commission was
investigating the Lonrho deal over concerns about reduced
competition in the platinum market.<br>
</p>

<p>STOCKS FALL AS GLOOMY VIEW TAKES HOLD <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Stocks tumbled on the Johanesburg Stock Exchange yesterday as
players adopted a negative outlook on interest rates, and disappointment
over further delays to the abolition of exchange controls and an
investigation into foreign exchange forward cover affected
sentiment.<br>
</p>

<p>BUSINESS SET TO TRAIN GOVT OFFICIALS <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
The National Business Initiative has launched a programme to
engage its 140 member companies in training local government officials
in vital aspects of financial management and administration.<br>
</p>

<p>LABOUR RELATIONS ACT 'MARKS THE BEGINNING OF NEW JOURNEY' <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Politicians, labour and business pronounced themselves satisfied
with the new Labour Relations Act which took effect yesterday,
describing the occasion as the dawn of a new era. The Act was drafted to
create conditions for a mature industrial partnership that would
allow sustained economic growth and remove adversarial relations.<br>
</p>

<p>NEITHER HELL NOR HEAVEN <i>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</i><br>
Labour Minister Tito Mboweni may or may not agree, but it seems
symbolically appropriate that the new Labour Relations Act into
operation on Armistice Day rather than May 1, Labour Day, his original
target day. May Day originated with the intense 19th century
struggles of organised labour for very rudimentary forms of
workplace justice. SA is now some way beyond that. The philosophy underpinning
the new Act has more in common with cessation of hostilities
symbolised by the November 11 commemoration. If the Act achieves
its purpose, industrial conflict will become less adversarial and
more institutionalised.<br>
</p>

<p>RACIST UNIONS TOLD TO CLEAN UP THEIR ACT <i>(Business Report,
Jhb.)</i><br>
Labour Minister Tito Mboweni relegated discriminatory trade union
and employer bodies to the annals of history yesterday, and
warned that bodies which maintained discrimination in their constitutions
would not be registered under the new Labour Relations Act.<br>
</p>

<p>EUROPEAN MONETARY UNION OUTCOME DOUBLE-EDGED FOR SA BUSINESS <i>(Business
Day)</i><br>
The die is cast. Despite considerable financial and economic
obstacles, key European nations are determined to introduce European
monetary union by the end of the millennium. And the implications
for SA business people will be considerable. Forward planning is
thus essential, even though there is considerable debate among
European central bankers and economists who are concerned that
several nations will not meet the tough economic requirements for
a unified currency.<br>
</p>

<p>GERMANS REMAIN UNIMPRESSED BY MBEKI'S ASSURANCES <i>(Business
Day)</i><br>
If SA is to gain the status it so keenly seeks among Europe's
superpowers and their investment communities, some fast and fancy
footwork is necessary. Despite the interest among German companies
to move into new markets, there are several factors in SA which
are causing concern among potential investors. Leading them are
high levels of crime and violence, followed by trade union
militancy and the unions&#146; clear political alliances. And
many German business people are wary of the long-term
effectiveness of the aggressive affirmative action policies being
implemented.<br>
</p>

<p>SA DESPERATELY NEEDS A VISION OF ITSELF <i>(by commentator
Maja Mokoena, Business Report)</i><br>
There is no doubt in my mind that SA is judged more harshly than
many emerging market countries which are far from being as
democratic and having as free a market system as we do. Given
these conditions, there is no better advice SA can get than that
given recently by German industrialists - that the country should
look forward to lifting itself with its own bootstraps <i>[sic] </i>instead
of waiting for foreign redemption. The Germans have rightly urged
SA to take a fresh look at domestic economic polices and
investment strategies to enhance the country's attractiveness to investors.
One is tempted to say how uncouth for the Germans to tell us to
carry our own weight, at a time when SA needs foreign aid. Well,
effective bitter medicine is better than flattery.<br>
</p>

<p>SPEEDY EUROPEAN TRADE DEAL WITH SA UNLIKELY <i>(Business
Report)</i><br>
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki will be told this week that SA has
thrown away the chance of a speedy trade accord with Europe.
Mbeki is in Brussels on a tour of the European Union's capital to discuss
the offer of a free trade area made by the EU to SA. SA is
unhappy with this approach because about 40% of its farm exports
will be excluded from the accord. The approach will also leave
the South African industry vulnerable to cut-throat competition
and her neighbours will suffer.<br>
</p>

<p>US RESENTMENT OF AFFIRMATIVE ACTION RISES <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Americans are losing patience with blacks demanding special
treatment in compensation for past injustices, and this puts in context
a race row which has erupted at oil company Texaco. Texaco, America's
14th largest company, is in deep trouble. Senior executives of
the oil company, which does business in SA as a co-owner of
Caltex, have been caught on tape plotting to destroy evidence
which might have proved incriminating in a racial discrimination
suit filed by black employees. The plaintiffs allege they have
been subjected to a pattern of racist behaviour ranging from
abusive language, including terms such as &quot;orang-utang&quot;
and &quot;porch monkey&quot;, to a statistically palpable failure
of white managers to recruit or promote black staff.<br>
</p>

<p>RUSSIA HOPES TO LIBERALISE GOLD MINING - MINISTER <i>(Reuters)</i><br>
MOSCOW - Russian officials have agreed to end the state's
monopoly on mining for gold, but there can be no swift move to a
free market, Finance Minister Alexander Livshits said on Monday.<br>
</p>

<p>DEMOS LAW TO COME INTO FORCE ON FRIDAY <i>(Cape Times,Cape
Town)</i><br>
The national law controlling marches and demonstrations and
requiring organisers to apply for permission is to come into force
on Friday. It could affect the proposed Pagad demonstration at the Waterfront
this weekend. The Regulation of Gatherings Act, the so-called
&quot;Goldstone Act&quot;, would be published in the Government
Gazette on Friday, Maxwell Mulaudzi, a spokesman for Minister of Safety
and Security Sydney Mufamadi, said yesterday.<br>
</p>

<p>CABINET FOR RESHUFFLE IF MODISE, NZO RETIRE <i>(Cape Times)</i><br>
A cabinet reshuffle is on the cards as Defence Minister Joe
Modise and Foreign Affairs Minister Alfred Nzo may retire. With the
imminent retirement of Eastern Cape Premier Raymond Mhlaba and
the resignation of ANC secretary-general Cyril Ramaphosa, a
change in the ANC&#146;s senior ranks is also inevitable. <br>
</p>

<p>CALL TO CURB MARKETS&#146; CLOUT <i>(Cape Times)</i><br>
The SA Communist Party does not want to abolish the markets, but
merely to reduce their power, which is wielded mainly by conservative
whites, its deputy secretary-general, Jeremy Cronin, says. Cronin
told the Institute for Defence Policy yesterday that the balance
of forces needed to be changed by using the new Labour Relations
Act to strengthen the powers of workers, consumers and the public
sector.<br>
</p>
</DOC>
