<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 11  NOVEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>

<p>MINER STILL MISSING <i>(Business Day, Jhb.)</i><br>
Rescuers were still trying to locate the driver of a machine who
disappeared on Saturday when the machine cut into an accumulation
of water at Ingwe's Matla No 1 mine, causing a flood, MD Dave Murray
said. [Radio News reported at 10h00 that the search had so far
been unsuccessful - Ed.]<br>
</p>

<p>MINES CANNOT AFFORD LAY-OFFS <i>(Business Report, Jhb.)</i><br>
NDOLA - Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines is unable to lay off
sections of its bloated workforce because its cash flow is too
weak to pay retrenchment packages, company sources said at the
weekend. <br>
</p>

<p>TITO MBOWENI DEFENDS NEW COMMISSION <i>(Business Report)</i><br>
Labour Minister Tito Mboweni dismissed as &quot;absolute
nonsense&quot; the concerns of business about the quality of the commissioners
on the Commission for Conciliation, Mediation and Arbitration. &quot;Anybody
from business who says that is talking utter nonsense&quot;,
Mboweni said after an ANC national executive committee meeting
over the weekend. &quot;If it is white business, perhaps this scepticism
is that darkies can't organise anything. It makes me very
upset&quot;, he said.<br>
</p>

<p>STALS ENDS ALL HOPES FOR EARLY DEATH OF CONTROLS <i>(Business
Times, with the Sunday Times)</i><br>
Reserve Bank Governor Chris Stals has put an end to hopes that
exchange controls may be lifted early. Instead, he has announced
a four-to-five-year timetable on the phasing out of exchange restrictions.
By ruling out a &quot;Big Bang&quot; or once-off scrapping of
controls, Stals resisted calls by the local business community
and foreign investors for their rapid dismantling.<br>
</p>

<p>NEW REFINERY MAY HELP FREE UP SA GOLD MARKET <i>(Reuters)</i><br>
SA could launch its own bullion market once the Reserve Bank
lifts foreign exchange controls and grants mines the right to market
all their own gold, said Mike Brown, research head of broker Frankel
Pollak.<br>
</p>

<p>DEFICIT NOW MANUEL'S MANTRA <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel has staked his credibility on the
Budget deficit. Like a stuck record, he keeps repeating that government
will meet its deficit targets this fiscal year and next. Figures
due for release on Thursday evening should indicate whether he
has something to sing about or not. The monthly statement from
the Finance Department on the course of the Budget can be difficult
to interpret, as spending and revenue numbers are volatile.
However, it is possible to draw conclusions about the revenue
figures now that more than half the fiscal year has passed.<br>
</p>

<p>IMF LOAN POSSIBLE 'TO SUPPORT RAND' <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
A presidential report on the halfway mark of government's first
term in office contemplates the possibility of SA accepting a loan
from the International Monetary Fund, saying a loan may be necessary
to support the rand.<br>
</p>

<p>SA WILL NOT WALK AWAY FROM EU TALKS - OFFICIALS <i>(Business
Day)</i><br>
SA would not walk away from impending trade talks with the
European Union, senior government officials said yesterday. Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki's economic adviser, Moss Ngoasheng, said government
was on schedule to negotiate with the EU, although SA's position
might be different from that of the EU.<br>
</p>

<p>ILO WARNS OF BACKLASH AGAINST GLOBALISATION <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Rapid advances fostered by globalisation of the world economy
could be undermined and lead to a backlash over rising unemployment
and poverty, International Labour Organisation director-general Michael
Hansenne warned on Friday. Addressing delegates at an ILO
workshop dealing with &quot;promoting social progress and
enterprise competitiveness in a global economy&quot;, Hansenne
said as a result of the high growth of poverty and unemployment
there could be a &quot;backlash&quot; against globalisation.<br>
</p>

<p>COSATU 'MAY BECOME MORE FRAGMENTED' <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
The Congress of SA Trade Unions (Cosatu) could become
increasingly fragmented along racial and ethnic lines as the divisions
in a society obsessed with self-enrichment and the self-empowerment
of black business are felt and begin to undermine union
solidarity, says Karl von Holdt of the September Commission.<br>
</p>

<p>FIRST PORT OF CALL FOR BLACK COMPANIES COMING TO THE JSE <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
If Emmanuel Lediga could recruit every black stockbroker in town,
his new firm would boast two qualified staffers. However, the
29-year-old CE of Legae Securities, SA's first black-run stockbrokerage,
is not deterred by the scarcity of black professionals at the
Johannesburg Stock Exchange. &quot;I am an irrepressible
optimist. In 10 years we will be right up there with the top
guys&quot;. Legae is the only brokerage in SA owned and managed
by blacks, an achievement made more remarkable by the fact that
Legida qualified as a stockbroker only four months ago. A former business
reporter for <i>The Star</i>, he became the first black dealer on
the trading floor in 1993.<br>
</p>

<p>AUSTRALIA &#145;96 GOLD OUTPUT SEEN UP TO 290t <i>(Reuters)</i><br>
Australia's gold mines are expected to produce abut 290 tonnes of
gold in calendar year 1996, Melbourne-based mining analysts
Surbiton Associates said.<br>
</p>

<p>ANALYST SEES BIG CHANGES FOR GOLD AFTER EMU <i>(Reuters)</i><br>
European Monetary Union in 1997 may transform the world gold
market, says a leading bullion analyst, Andy Smith at Union Bank
of Switzerland. Smith said in interview comments on his latest published
market analysis that EMU had focused central bank thinking on
gold reserves as never before.<br>
</p>

<p>MINING GIANT RTZ-CRA TO LIFT OZ OUTPUT <i>(Reuters)</i><br>
Mining giant RTZ-CRA on Thursday said it wanted to raise
productivity at its Australian mines to meet increased coal demand
from Asian power stations.<br>
</p>

<p>MBEKI NOT MY HEIR APPARENT - MANDELA <i>(Cape Times, Cape
Town)</i><br>
President Nelson Mandela has told the African National
Congress&#146;s highest decision-making body, the national
executive committee, that he has not chosen his successor and
that his deputy, Thabo Mbeki, is not heir apparent. He said
&quot;democratic procedures would be followed in the election of the
ANC leader and president when he stepped down.&quot;<br>
</p>

<p>LABOUR COURT SEEKS SEAT AS ACT TAKES EFFECT <i>(Cape Times)</i><br>
The Labour Relations Act - which does not set a minimum wage - is
to come into force today. However, obstacles still stand in the
way of launching the Labour Court - which has the status of the Supreme
Court. Chief of these problems is the lack of suitable premises. <br>
</p>
</DOC>
