<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 8  NOVEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>





MINING PRODUCTION REMAINS THE SAME (Business Report, Jhb)
Central Statistical Service data released yesterday shows mining production has remained at nearly the same level since the middle of 1994, with the downward trend in gold production counteracted by an upward trend in non-gold production .  Total production and mineral sales for the three months to August 30 fell 1,4% and 6,4% after seasonal adjustments, from the previous period.<BR><P>
ANGLO LIFTS ITS STAKE IN 'THE PLUM' <I>(Business Mail, Fridays with the Mail & Guardian)</I><BR>
'Black empowerment may still leave a major gold mine under white control'.  -  Anglo American is lifting its stake in JCI's gold mine Western Areas - a move which could ensure it remains the mine's largest shareholder after JCI's planned sale to black business.<BR><P>
JOEL - BACK FROM THE DEAD WITH CONTINUOUS OPS <I>(Business Mail)</I><BR>
The introduction of continuous operations at JCI's HJ Joel gold mine played a major part in pulling the Free State operation back from the brink.<BR><P>
FULCO FAILS TO STRIKE GOLD <I>(Business Mail)</I><BR>
Continuous mining operations, long mooted as a lifeline for the mining industry, have proved less successful than hoped.  The principle that mines would move to seven-day operations - or full calendar operations (Fulco) - was finally agreed between management and unions last year, after years of negotiations. <I>[This article, unfortunately, indicates a superficial grasp of the realities surrounding Section 9 of the Mines & Works Act, which prohibits blasting on Sundays, and the laborious process involved in securing exemption in terms of government's requirements. The Chamber's view is quite simply that archaic regulations such as Section 9 dating back to the apartheid era have no place on statute books in the environment in which we operate today. Refer also to the <A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/speeches/1996/PresidentialAddress_1996.htm">Presidential address</A> (paragraph 26) given at the Chamber's AGM on Tuesday this week. - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
RANDGOLD TO GO AHEAD WITH HARMONY GOLD REFINERY <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Randgold and Exploration said on Thursday that the board of its Harmony Gold Mining Co. had given the go-ahead for the establishment of a commercial-scale gold refinery, only the second in SA.<BR><P>
INTEGRATED FINANCING <I>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
This week's separate integrations of Anglovaal's and Gencor's Evander gold mining interests need to be seen in perspective, not simply by investors, but by everyone responsible for SA's economic and fiscal planning.  Integration of gold mines and prospects is not consolidation for the sake of size, it is part of an industry-wide trend towards creating attractive investment vehicles for world capital markets.<BR><P>
NEW LABOUR ACT 'CONTAINS UNWORKABLE ASPECTS' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Aspects of the German industrial relations system, which was proving to be unsuitable to ensure Germany's  continued competitiveness, had been incorporated in the new Labour Relations Act, an employer said yesterday.<BR><P>
LABOUR COMMISSION TO BE SET UP ON MONDAY <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Labour, business and the government have pledged their support for the new commission that will try to solve SA labour disputes from next week.  The Commission on Conciliation, Mediation and Arbitration, set up under the new Labour Relations Act, will be established on Monday.<BR><P>
STRIKE COULD PARALYSE ECONOMY <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
An expected strike over wage increases by seven transport unions in the R8-billion-a-year road freight industry later this month threatens to bring the economy to a standstill.<BR><P>
PRECARIOUS BALANCE FOR THE RAND <I>(Business Mail)</I><BR>
The rand's latest fall will push inflation higher, demanding the restrictive monetary policy which has previously forced up interest rates, Reserve Bank Governor  Chris Stals warns.  In an exclusive interview with the Mail & Guardian, Stals also says it is anyone's guess where the embattled currency will settle.  "Any person willing to predict at which level the rand will stabilise, under the present circumstances, would be very brake", he says.<BR><P>
GERMANS NOT LIKELY TO HEED SA TRADE PLEA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The European commission has welcomed next week's visit by Deputy President Thabo Mbeki to the EU's executive arm, but Brussels observers say the Pretoria delegation is unlikely to come back home with anything more than sympathy.<BR><P>
PRIVATISATION 'HAS CRUCIAL ROLE' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
State Enterprises were inherently inefficient and privatisation was crucial to productivity and sustainable regional growth, Southern African Development Community executive secretary Kaire Mbuende said yesterday.<BR><P>
SURPRISE RISE IN FOREX AND GOLD RESERVES <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The value of the gross gold and foreign exchange reserves held by the Reserve Bank rose to R10,2b last month from R10b in September, even after a foreign credit line of R612m was fully repaid, Central Bank figures released yesterday show.<BR><P>
MORE BLACKS TO BALANCE THE BOOKS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The crusade to introduce more black accountants into the SA economy is gaining momentum.  Among those at the forefront of the initiative is Coopers & Lybrand SA, whose new national chairman, Arthur Kidson, is approaching the challenge with single-minded dedication. <BR><P>
LONGER STRIKES IN 1997 <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Longer and possibly more disruptive strikes, as well as a rash of disputes relating to the provisions of new labour legislation, are like to dominate the industrial relations arena in 1997, says Pierre Wolmarans, professional head: industrial relations, at FSA-Contact. "Labour is increasingly looking to business to deliver on the upliftment promises of the government which, so far, have not made a significant impact on the life of the average worker. At the same time, economic realities dictate that, from a business point of view, wage settlements will have to be more moderate," he said.<BR><P>
UNION ACTS ON MINE HOUSING <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SAs mining industry can provide housing for the millions of black migrant workers at a very low cost, if mine bosses are willing to work together with the workers. National Union of Mineworkers general secretary Kgalema Motlanthe says, contrary to belief, it will not cost mining houses billions of rands to put up family housing for their employees. "NUM has proposed that workers will use public holidays to work into a fund which will finance decent housing," he says.<BR><P>
FREE PRESS ESSENTIAL TO DEMOCRACY - NAIDOO <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
In an open letter to the Press yesterday, Jay Naidoo, Minister of Posts, Telecommunications and Broadcasting, said he was horrified at the treatment of journalists by Pagad leaders at the Gatesville mosque on Wednesday night.  Naidoo wrote, "I consider it a humiliation not experienced even at the height of apartheid repression - to parade journalists before a hostile crowd and make threats against them and their newspapers.  The freedom of the Press is a foundation of a democracy".<I> ["Pagad" = People Against Gangsterism And Drugs is a so-called vigillante group begun in the Cape and was recently involved in a clash with police - Ed.] </I><BR><P>
ZUMA, RASOOL DECLARE TB FIGHT A NATIONAL HEALTH PRIORITY <I>(Cape Times)</I><BR>
Tuberculosis was declared a national health priority by Health Minister Nkosazana Zuma and Western Cape Health MEC Ebrahim Rasool at a Press conference yesterday.<BR><P>
</DOC>
