<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 7  NOVEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>




AVGOLD GOES GLOBAL AFTER SHAKE-UP <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Anglovaal's gold division, Avgold, has launched itself on the international stage as a focused company with its long-term resources secured and the mines' frequently criticised management contracts at an end.<BR><P>
JCI IN BID FOR BIG STAKE IN AUSTRALIAN MINING GROUP <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
JCI has signed a letter of understanding to buy an option on a $250m stake in an Australian mining house, which would give the SA group 30% of a Russian gold resource, one of the biggest outside SA.<BR><P>
SA FIRMS 'SHOULD EXAMINE THEIR MOTIVES FOR GOING GLOBAL' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
South African companies need to focus on creating joint venture alliances, particularly with offshore companies, in order to extend their market share - but they also have to examine their motives for moving into the global market.<BR><P>
FOREX OUTFLOWS SQUEEZE BANKS' MARGINS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Foreign exchange outflows have triggered increases in money market interest rates and put pressure on banks' margins as they scramble for cash.
ALL PACKED UP WITH NOWHERE TO GO <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
There was a time when the slightest wobble in the finrand or rand caused a rush on any equity that had even the vaguest claim to being a "rand hedge".  Not any more.  Since the finrand was abolished and for most of this year, when the rand has experienced the most volatile period in its history, investors on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange do not appear to be interested in adopting a strategy that would reap some benefit from the rand's downward trajectory.<BR><P>
RAND'S DECLINE 'EXCESSIVE' <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The rand will stabilise at between R4,50 and R4,60 to the dollar towards the end of the year, Karin Schoeman, a Southern Life economic analyst, predicts in Southern's fourth-quarter Economic Comment.  Schoeman said the currency's level was "excessively" undervalued.<BR><P>
PAVING THE WAY <I>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
Reserve Bank governor Chris Stal's views on the conjunction of factors needed before exchange controls can safely be removed need consideration by a still non-committal Finance Ministry.  Last week when the market expected an announcement on controls, the rand firmed.  It weakened this week in the confusion of conflicting signals from the ministry and the Bank.  The dangers of official indecision are clear to corporate SA which has presumably conveyed its concerns to the governor and the minister.<BR><P>
TIME TO RETHINK THE METHOD OF LIFTING EXCHANGE CONTROLS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
There is something enviable about the glibness with which people in the financial markets are able to call for the scrapping of exchange controls.  They trot out their mantra with all the faith of devout worshippers, and display impatience with the agnostics around them.  But the need for a big bang to remove controls is not as obvious as it seems to the believers, and government and the Reserve Bank's delays are not as ridiculous as they might seem.  It is, quite simply, not as easy a decision as it might seem to the people who want to take their money out of the country.<BR><P>
RAMOS SPELLS OUT PLANS TO PROTECT CASH SAVINGS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The Finance Ministry is discussing measures with the Financial Services Board to protect savings after the abolition of foreign exchange controls, Maria Ramos, the director-general of the Finance Department, said yesterday.<BR><P>
MORE THAN HALF OF COSATU'S CONGRESS DELEGATES MISSING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
While SA's largest labour federation, the Congress of SA Trade Unions' (Cosatu) KwaZulu-Natal congress at the weekend highlighted the need for strong organisational structures, the federation's Witwatersrand region had to adjourn its congress when 1 000 of the 1 677 delegates failed to turn up.  It is understood that representatives from 18 of the 20 Cosatu affiliated did attend.  However, in terms of the federation's constitution the delegates present did not represent a quorum.<BR><P>
SA REVIEWS UNUTILISED MINERAL RIGHTS - MINISTER <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
The government was actively considering various ways in which SA's unutilised mineral rights could be used to create jobs and increase black ownership, Minerals and Energy Minister Penuell Maduna said on Wednesday.<BR><P>
BLACKS HOLD FUTURE OF SAS ECONOMY <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Blacks should be actively involved in the mainstream economy for SAs new democracy to succeed. This the view of National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) general secretary Kgalema Motlanthe, who argues that the current changes will collapse unless blacks play an active role in the economy.<BR><P>

<B><I>There is an interesting perspective on <A HREF="http://www.woza.co.za/cyril.htm">Cyril Ramaphosas new financial standing</A> at http://www.woza.co.za/cyril.htm on the Internet. Our "Mining News" webpage also has a link to Wozas homepage below - Ed.</I></B><BR><P>
