<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 6  NOVEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



<B><FONT SIZE=4>CHAMBER A.G.M. REPORTS:</FONT></B><BR><P>
CHAMBER CHANGES ITS FOCUS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Chamber of Mines of SA had been restructured to focus on its new primary function as a lobbying organisation for the mining industry, outgoing president At du Plessis said yesterday.  The remodelled organisational structure was "effectively equipped to engage government, labour and other significant protagonists in the national public policy arena.  What has evolved is a modernised entity competently positioned to represent the interests of its members in contemporary SA", said Du Plessis. <BR><P>
MINISTER UPBEAT ON FUTURE OF MINING <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Minerals and Energy Minister Penuell Maduna said the green paper on the future of mining in SA presented to him last month will be published this month and will culminate in a white paper next year.<BR><P>
SA CHAMBER SEES 1996 LOW FOR GOLD OUTPUT <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SA's gold mining industry is set for another substantial drop in output this year, but 1996 should prove to be the trough, outgoing president of the Chamber of Mines At du Plessis said on Tuesday.  Speaking at the Chamber's 106th annual general meeting he said there was likely to be a further "substantial reduction" in production in 1996 to around 500 tonnes. [Reports were also carried in Sake-Beeld (2)and Citizen (2) -Ed.]<BR><P>

<B><I>OTHER NEWS...</I></B><BR>
MERCURY DEAL OPENS WAY FOR EVANDER MINES MERGER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gencor won shareholder approval for the merger of its four Evander gold mines yesterday after a last-minute deal with dissident shareholder Mercury Asset Management.<BR><P>
SHAREHOLDERS TO DEBATE ANGLOVAAL RESTRUCTURING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The restructuring of Anglovaal's mining interests will be debated by shareholders of its listed companies today, amid claims that Hartebeestfontein is being sacrificed for uncertain gains at the group's Oribi and Sun gold explorations.<BR><P>
ERWIN SPRINGS COMPETITION BOARD SURPRISE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin appointed two outspoken critics of conglomerates and monopolies to the Competition Board yesterday in a move that could bring about a radical change in the way competition policy is treated.<BR><P>
FALLING RAND 'NEED NOT DETER INVESTORS' <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The rand's nearly 30% fall in value against the dollar so far this year was not necessarily a deterrent to long-term foreign investment in SA, Jeffrey Griffin, the principal investment officer of the International Finance Corporation (IFC), said yesterday.<BR><P>
REWORKED CONSTITUTION STILL DRAWS OBJECTIONS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Democratic Party and KwaZulu-Natal province have asked the Constitutional Court not to certify the amended constitutional text adopted by the Constitutional Assembly last month, on the grounds that various provisions still do not comply with principles enshrined in the interim constitution.<BR><P>
GOVT TO BE GIVEN PROGRESS REPORTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Labour, government and business representatives negotiating the draft legislation on employment standards will have to decide soon whether they will complete negotiations this year.  Sources close to the negotiations indicated government hoped the process would be completed by the end of this month so that a draft Bill could be ready for tabling in Parliament at the start of the first term next year.  Government will hold separate meetings with labour and business today to review progress.<BR><P>
STALS SPEAKS OUT ON FOREX 'BIG BANG' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Reserve Bank governor Chris Stals has spelled out the measures that would have to be in place for SA to contemplate a "big bang" lifting of exchange controls.  Stals said yesterday he welcomed the debate about the abolition of controls, although people did not seem to realise that "if you take the plunge, you have to take the consequences too.  I like to say it is like riding a tiger - it can be more dangerous to get off, because the tiger might eat you".<BR><P>
BLACK EMPOWERMENT 'A SHAM' <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Black empowerment initiatives in SA were only serving to enrich a small group of about 300 black people, Lawrence Mavundla, president of the Micro Business Chamber, said yesterday.  Speaking at the chamber's launch, Mavundla said private business in SA was "taking people who are already rich and making them richer" in the name of black empowerment.  He said business had targeted a small group of black people with whom it was prepared to do business.<BR><P>
MANUELS EQUIVOCATION MAKES MARKETS NERVOUS <I>(Sake-Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Minister of Finance Trevor Manuel yesterday again caused jitters in financial markets with his apparent equivocation on exchange control. Although markets still performed steadily, most dealers described the mood as "negative". What unnerved many people was an aside Manuel made during a Press conference in Cape Town. He said SA still had to finally decide whether all exchange controls would be abolished as is the case in Mexico, or whether SA would retain certain restrictions as in Chile. Analysts sharply criticised this statement saying it was contrary to the governments macro-economic strategy which clearly set the abolition of exchange controls as a goal.<BR><P>
