<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 5 NOVEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>





SA GOLD MINES WONT MAKE 500-TON MARK <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SA's gold mines would fail to produce the 500 tons of gold forecast for the year, mining analysts said yesterday.  The Chamber of Mines said the industry had produced only 39,6 tons of gold in September, less than August's 41,2 tons.<BR><P>
LEADING ECONOMIST PREDICTS A R6,90/DOLLAR BY 2004 <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The rand could depreciate to about R6,90 a dollar by 2004, Rudolf Gouws, the chief economist for Rand Merchant Bank said, scotching speculation that Cape Town's 2004 Olympic bid presumed an exchange rate of R22 to the dollar.  Gouws' estimate was based on five assumptions, according to a report on the SA economy released this month.  The first assumption was that SA's inflation rate would track estimates in the government's economic plan released in June, the report said.<BR><P>
FALLING RAND EXPECTED TO BOOST AMCOAL'S EARNINGS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The weak rand was expected to fuel Anglo American Coal's half-year earnings, analysts said yesterday.  They said the sharp decline in the rand's value against the dollar since mid-February had done much to boost export prices and increase Amcoal's earnings for the half-year to September 30.<BR><P>
ABANDONED COPPER MINE TO BE REOPENED <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
NDOLA, ZAMBIA - The Bwana Mkubwa mine, on the outskirts of the copperbelt town of Ndola, is set to become one of the first privately operated mines since Zambia's mineral resources were nationalised in the 1960s, when it goes into production in December next year.<BR><P>
LEON ATTACKS INABILITY BY GOVT TO MANAGE THE BUDGET <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Democratic Party leader Tony Leon lashed out at government last night for its inability to manage the Budget and warned that, unless radical steps were taken to bring the Budget under control, a further slide in the value of the rand was "inevitable and inexorable".  Leon told a public meeting in Johannesburg that government attempts to control public service spending were "awkward and potentially disastrous" and would lead SA into a "head-on-collision with global economic principles".<BR><P>
MBEKI TO LOBBY FOR BETTER DEAL FROM EU <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki is to lead a high-powered delegation on an eight-nation visit to Europe to lobby influential capitals for better market access before formal trade talks start later this month.<BR><P>
LAST DAY TO OBJECT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Today is the last day for political parties to file written objections to the certification of SA's new constitution.  All submissions will be argued orally on 18 November.<BR><P>
LEKOTA, FREE STATE LEADERS TO BE OUSTED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Free State province's premier Patrick Lekota, his entire cabinet and the ANC provincial executive would be removed from office, the party's national leadership said in Johannesburg yesterday.  The move follows months of internal warfare which paralysed the provincial government and saw the party's Free State membership plunge.<BR><P>
SA HEALTH REVIEW PAINTS BLEAK PICTURE OF RURAL HEALTH SERVICES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
This year's SA Health Review, released yesterday, shows that nearly half the clinics in the eastern Cape do not have adequate water supply, 52% have no electricity and 38% have no phone.  The situation is hardly better in the Northern Province, the Northwest and KwaZulu-Natal.  <BR><P>
SA WEIGHS PRIVATE SECTOR FUNDING FOR WATER <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SA might set up a national water corporation in partnership with private investors to manage the funding of capital projects, Water Affairs and Forestry Minister Kader Asmal said on Monday.  Asmal told reporters in Cape Town that future water supply projects would be determined by human need rather than political expediency and ultimately would have to be paid for by consumers.   His department was not authorised, however, to borrow money for capital projects that would be paid back by user charges over a prolonged period.<BR><P>
PEACEKEEPING FORCE 'ALREADY IN TRAINING' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Efforts to have a 10 000-strong SA National Defence Force contingent ready for peacekeeping duties in central Africa were being accelerated and it was expected that the "lakes states" would help determine SA's role in the troubled region, Deputy Defence Minister Ronnie Kasrils said yesterday.<BR><P>
SA MAY HAVE TO IMPORT PETROL <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
After years of almost total self-reliance, SA is set to become a net importer of petrol over the next year, industry sources said yesterday.  "From 1997 onwards, petrol production will be at the limit of capacity", said Colin McClelland, the director of the SA Petroleum Industry Association.<BR><P>
MUGABE TELLS DIPLOMATS TO 'GO TO HELL' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
HARARE - President Robert Mugabe appears to be heading for a crisis with donors after telling diplomats representing four Western donor countries to "go to hell" when they questioned his plan to sell Malaysians a 51% stake in the R3bn Hwange Thermal Station for a bargain R217m.  Mugabe fired the entire board of the parastatal Zimbabwe Electricity Supply Authority when its members warned that the deal would upset Western nations whose electrical conglomerates' tenders were ignored.<BR><P>
</DOC>
