<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 4 NOVEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>




<p>ROWLAND VOWS TO CHALLENGE ANGLO DEAL <i>(Business Day, Jhb.)</i><br>
Tiny Rowland, the deposed head of Lonrho, said at the weekend he
would challenge Anglo American's deal to increase its stake in
Lonrho - and any attempt by Anglo to gain a position on the board
of Ashanti Goldfields of Ghana, Lonrho's major gold mining asset.<br>
</p>

<p>FALLING RAND SAVES FREE STATE MINES <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
Troubled Free State gold mines had been rescued by the decline in
the rand and no mines were in imminent danger of closing, Mineral
and Energy Affairs Minister Penuell Maduna said on Friday. <i>[On
the same day, we confirmed with the Department itself that it is
henceforth officially to be known as the DEPARTMENT OF MINERALS
AND ENERGY - the word &quot;Affairs&quot; falls away and
&quot;mineral&quot; takes the plural. Obviously the
minister&#146;s title is &quot;Minister of Minerals and
Energy&quot;. - Ed.]</i><br>
</p>

<p>JCI DOWNPLAYS REPORTS ON THREAT TO IRON PROJECT <i>(Business
Day)</i><br>
JCI Ltd has downplayed reports that its R2,8bn hot briquetted
iron project could be threatened by Zimbabwean steel manufacturer
Zisco which said it was unhappy with the project's structure and was
considering withdrawing its participation.<br>
</p>

<p>KINROSS MAY RUE ITS DECISION TO BE EXEMPT FROM STC <i>(Business
Report, Jhb.)</i><br>
The Kinross acquisition of the mining operations of Winkelhaak,
Leslie and Bracken, for which their respective shareholders' approval
will be sought tomorrow, places the power of controlling shareholders
under the spotlight. Kinross will acquire these mining operations
by the issue of shares.<br>
</p>

<p>SA AND US AGREE TO NEW TAX TREATY <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
WASHINGTON - South African and US negotiators initialled a new
bilateral tax treaty at the weekend to replace the pact torn up
by the Comprehensive Anti-Apartheid Act 10 years ago.<br>
</p>

<p>CALL FOR ACCELERATION OF TARIFF CUTS TO AID RAND <i>(Business
Day)</i><br>
Tariff cuts should be accelerated to reduce the inflationary
impact of the rand's fall, a study by the Industrial Development Corporation
has found. The study forms part of a heated debate on tariff liberalisation,
with business and labour fighting moves by government to speed up
the pace of reform.<br>
</p>

<p>TALKS ON LABOUR LAW 'DIFFICULT' <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
The green paper on employment standards was proving to be a far
more difficult piece of legislation to negotiate than the Labour
Relations Act, Labour Minister Tito Mboweni said at the weekend.<br>
<b><i>... and ...</i></b><br>
MBOWENI INDICATES POSSIBLE CHANGE TO NEW LABOUR LAW <i>(Business
Day)</i><br>
Labour Minister Tito Mboweni has indicated that the new Labour
Relations Act could be amended next year to grant him discretionary
powers to ask a commission for conciliation, mediation and arbitration
commissioner to intervene and assist in resolving labour
disputes.<br>
</p>

<p>SA IN RACE FOR ZAMBIAN SPOILS <i>(Business Day)</i><br>
A number of leading South African companies have joined the
world's best corporations in the race to share in the spoils of privatisation
in Zambia, figures from the country's privatisation authority
have shown.<br>
</p>

<p>ANXIETY LEVELS HIGH ABOUT PENDING ECONOMIC DATA <i>(Business
Report)</i><br>
Over the past 10 days a growing number of commentators called on
the government to move forward with the abolition of foreign
exchange controls regulations, and many suggested the regulations
should be taken away in big-bang fashion. Speculation about an
announcement on exchange control regulations and maybe even a
standby arrangement with the International Monetary Fund reached
fever pitch when news broke on Friday that the &quot;big
four&quot; - Trevor Manuel, Maria Ramos, Hannes Smit and Chris
Stals - were meeting in Cape Town.<br>
</p>

<p>RESERVE BANK 'MEDDLES WHERE IT SHOULD STAY OUT' <i>(Business
Times, with the Sunday Times)</i><br>
Although food price increases of 10,4% are largely blamed for the
Consumer Price Index (CPI) increase which has seen a rise of
nearly 1 percentage point to 8,4% since August, Chamber of Mines
economist Richard Grant says excessive growth in MO money supply
last year will push inflation over 10% before April. The
inflation figures exceeded most economists' expectations, which
were clustered around 8,1%. &quot;The rise in food prices is not
itself a cause of inflation, but rather an effect enhanced by
inflation, which is caused by the growth in MO money
supply&quot;, says Grant. <br>
</p>

<p>GFSA SHAREHOLDERS SEEM HUNGRY FOR CHANGE <i>(Reuters)</i><br>
Disappointing third quarter results from Gold Fields of SA have
jangled the nerves of major shareholders, and they could push for
a restructuring or a take-over of the group, analysts said on Friday.<br>
</p>
