<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 1 NOVEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>




CAPITAL ALLIANCE GIRDS UP FOR JCI BID <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Financial services group Capital Alliance has secured sufficient financing to buy a 35% shareholding in mining house JCI from Anglo American, say sources close to the bid.  The interest is worth R2,6bn based on JCI's market capitalisation yesterday.<BR><P>
RAND YO-YOS BEFORE STAGING A COMEBACK <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA rand gyrated wildly yesterday, hitting a new low of R4,7670 against the dollar in the morning before staging a sudden comeback to below R4,70.<BR><P>
UNIONS TOLD TO KEEP AUTONOMY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Italian trade unionist, Andrea Amaro, president of Progetto Sviluppo, cautioned SA labour yesterday against becoming part-owners in companies which were being privatised and said unions should rather be negotiating processes whereby workers had the option of buying shares.<BR><P>
INCREASE VAT IN NEXT BUDGET - ECONOMIST <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Value Added Tax in SA, currently at 14%, should have been raised in the 1996/97 Budget and ought to be raised by up to 2% in next year's Budget, according to University of Cape Town economics Professor Charles Simkins.<BR><P>
INTERDICT SERVED ON STRIKERS AT HIGHVELD STEEL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American was granted an urgent Supreme Court interdict to stop about 2 000 NUM members from striking at Highveld Steel near Witbank.<BR><P>
'SA IS PREPARED TO PLAY A ROLE IN CENTRAL AFRICA' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
President Nelson Mandela said yesterday SA was prepared to play a role in central Africa, but did not say what form this might take.  Mandela, who was reluctant to be drawn in to the crisis in the Great Lakes region, said he had discussed the situation there with Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni yesterday afternoon.<BR><P>
ANGLO IN GRAND NEW PHASE OF EXPANSION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Tiny Rowland, the Englishman who became an icon by creating Lonrho, an eclectic collection of assets with one thing in common - Africa - has reason to be distressed:  The business (some would say fiefdom) he spent a lifetime building is almost certainly on the verge of disintegration.<BR><P>
WEAK RAND 'HAS SOME ADVANTAGES' <I>(Business Report , Jhb.)</I><BR>
The fall in the value of the rand was not a disaster and could help offset the greater danger of a rampant current account deficit, which would preclude long-awaited interest rate cuts, Dave Mohr, the chief economist for insurance group, Old Mutual, said yesterday.<BR><P>
COSATU TO REDEFINE ANC TIES <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
The Congress of South African Trade Unions must redefine its relationship with the African National Congress,  Cosatu general secretary Sam Shilowa said.  He dismissed claims that Cosatu and the African National Congress were opposed on policy issues, but stressed that the relationship between Cosatu, the SA Communist Party and the government had altered.<I> [The issue of the alliance between the ruling ANC, Cosatu - SA's biggest labour federation - and the SACP has become a constant debating point in SA, with each new development, especially regarding privatisation, which may impact on the strength of the alliance, unleashing a torrent of differing views from commentators - Ed.]</I><BR><P>

