<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 31 DECEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



NEW POLICIES LOOM FOR EU, AFRICAN TRADE <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SA's neighbours in southern Africa, which are enjoying generous trade concessions as members of the Lomé convention, could soon come under pressure to open their markets to the European Union when the trade and aid accord between the EU and its 70 African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) partners comes up for renewal in 2000.<BR><P>
SHORTAGE IN MONEY MARKET HITS RECORD <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The money market shortage shot up to a record high of R11,117bn on Saturday, compared with last Tuesday's R10,79bn, the Reserve Bank said yesterday.<BR><P>
RUSSIA PREPARES TO SIGN NEW EXPORT DEAL WITH DE BEERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Russia would sign a new commercial export agreement with diamond giant De Beers in January, an executive from Russia's biggest diamond producer, Almazy Rossii-Sakha (ARS), said yesterday.<BR><P>
FEWER S AFRICANS OPTIMISTIC, SAYS SURVEY<I> (The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Just more than half (52%) of all South Africans feel 1997 will be better than 1996, a 6% drop from the same time last year. This is one of the findings of Gallup poll carried out by Markinor research group in November among 3 500 South Africans of all races. Like last year, Northern Province is the most optimistic (70% believing 1997 will be better), while the Western Cape (40%) is the least optimistic, with Gauteng (42%) the second least optimistic.<BR><P>
IMPLEMENT ECONOMIC PLAN, GOVT URGED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
New Year messages from opposition party leaders have urged the ANC-led government to implement the macro-economic plan, remove exchange controls and act on the modest good news emerging from financial markets.<BR><P>
HOTEL SALE HOLDS LONRHO BACK <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Plans by Lonrho to divorce its African trading activities from its mining interests had been delayed by the need to first sell its Princess hotel chain, the company said yesterday.<BR><P>
LONRHO DECLINES COMMENT ON DEMERGER DELAY REPORT <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Lonrho on Monday declined to comment on a British newspaper report that the conglomerate's planned demerger was facing delays after a recent European Commission decision on voting rights.<BR><P>
LIBANON MINE WORKERS PLAN TO MARCH OVER 'EXTRA' DAY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
About 7 000 workers from Gold Fields' Libanon mine planned to march today to protest against the mine's insistence that they work on New Year's day to make up for lost production, the National Union of Mineworkers said yesterday. <I>[Management had earlier agreed to workers' demands that they be given 24 December off to do Christmas shopping - Ed.] </I><BR><P>
DEMOGRAPHICS ARE SPUR TO AFFIRMATIVE ACTION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Many South African businesses support affirmative action for demographic reasons as the slow growth of the white population will increasingly result in a shortage of white managers, according to a study by the South African Institute of Race Relations.<BR><P>
TOP TAIWANESE ENVOY TO VISIT SA, SIX OTHER AFRICAN STATES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Taiwan's top envoy would visit seven African nations in January in a damage-control mission following SA's plan to switch ties to Beijing from Taipei, the South African Foreign Ministry said yesterday.<BR><P>
AVGOLD LISTS DEPOSITORY RECEIPTS IN BRUSSELS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
South African gold company Avgold began listing international depository receipts (IDR's) on the Brussels Stock Exchange, said issue co-sponsor Banque Bruxelles Lambert (BBL).<BR><P>
'PRIVATISATION WILL BOOST ZIMBABWEAN GROWTH' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Zimbabwe's farm-based economy is expected to grow by up to 7% next year and economists say it could expand even more if a protracted privatisation programme finally comes on stream.<BR><P>
CENTRAL BANKS BIG SHADOW OVER 1997 GOLD PRICE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
ZURICH - Gold bugs head into 1997 gripped by the fear that European central banks will dump big chunks of their reserves to raise money to plug budget holes and qualify for Europe's single currency project. So, while many analysts think gold has found solid ground at $365 an ounce and should move in a relatively narrow range next year, they say the future depends largely on whether dust-covered official reserves come pouring on to the market.<BR><P>

