<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 24  DECEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>




EDITORIAL MISINTERPRETED MINING REPORT <I>(Business Day, Jhb. - written by Guy Mhone, chief director of labour market policy, Department of Labour)</I><BR>
<I>Business Day</I> has every right to interpret documents as it sees fit, but it owes it to its readers to at least give a faithful exposition of the contents of a particular document so that readers can make their own judgements on particular issues.  I refer to the editorial titled Mining Gold on Dec 19, which I do not believe lives up to the high standard we have come to expect from <I>Business Day</I>.  The editorial focuses on the issues of wage determination and the perceived interpretation of the views expressed in the paper as implying the need for the state to exert more control in their determination irrespective of the rights of the parties to do so through collective bargaining, and without regard of the economic consequences of doing so for the viability of marginal mines.<I> [The Department of Labour commissioned the report - Ed. Click <A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/releases/deplabor.htm">here</A> to see the Chamber's response to the report OR click <A HREF="http://www.bullion.org.za/news/mining~1/ bd1296.htm">HERE </A>to read the Business Day editorial which has so irked Dr. Mhone. ]</I><BR><P>
ANALYSTS SEE GOLD PRICE STAYING LOW IN '97-POLL <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Gold prices are likely to remain under $400 an ounce next year and will peak in the first six months of the year, according to a narrow majority of analysts polled by Reuters.<BR><P>
ROVIC DIAMOND MINE TO BE REHABILITATED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
DEALESVILLE - Plans are under way to return to production the ill-fated Free State Rovic diamond mine which collapsed under a mudslide, killing 20 people, last month.<BR><P>
SA'S MONEY MARKET <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA's money market shortage rose to R9,969bn on Saturday from R9,703bn on Friday, the Reserve Bank said yesterday.<BR><P>
TAX AGREEMENT SIGNED BETWEEN SA & SINGAPORE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
An agreement between SA and Singapore for the avoidance of double taxation and the prevention of income tax evasion was signed in Singapore yesterday.<BR><P>
MORE FUEL PRICE RISES IN STORE NEXT YEAR <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
More fuel price rises were in store next year, starting with one of 2c-4c/l on the first Wednesday of January, putting paid to motorists' hopes that the 18%-27% rise in petrol and diesel prices this year was the end of the story, economists said yesterday.<BR><P>
FIVE NEW AMBASSADORS APPOINTED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo has announced the appointment by President Nelson Mandela of new SA ambassadors to Angola, Argentina, Greece, the Netherlands and Senegal.<BR><P>
NEDLAC SHOULD PICK UP PACE IN NEW YEAR - NAIDOO <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The coming year is expected to bring an improvement in the pace of agreement-making at the National Economic Development and Labour Council (Nedlac), says executive director Jayendra Naidoo.<BR><P>
FOREIGN FIRMS SIGN MINING AGREEMENTS IN INDIA <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
NEW DELHI - Leading foreign companies are registering to conduct mining surveys in the western Indian state of Rajasthan, the Press Trust of India (PTI) said on Monday.<BR><P>
ALTHOUGH MANY WOULD SAY IT IS, SA IS STILL FAR FROM FREE <I>(Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SA claims to have a free economy. However, economists have a completely different view on this. According to the authoritative Heritage Foundation of America the SA economy is everything but free. In its most recent survey on the most free countries in the world, SA is placed in the category of countries classified as "mostly not-free". This penetrates to the core of the problem of low economic growth in SA because it has been proven again and again that the freer a countrys economy is, the faster its growth rate.<BR><P>
DE BEERS MONOPOLY WILL SHRINK - WSJ <I>(Beeld)</I><BR>
LONDON - The diamond war between De Beers and the Russian government will come to a climax next week. Last week De Beers announced that its sales had risen by 7% and that demand in America and Asia was healthy, but that the Russian "sabotage" of its market was seriously worrying. The Wall Street Journal then wrote that De Beers would follow the same path as other once-mighty monopolies like the Organisation of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) and would also shrink.<BR><P>
