SNB WANTS TO CUT GOLD REQUIREMENT TO BOOST PROFITS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
ZURICH - The Swiss National Bank on Friday said it wants to cut its legally-mandated gold reserve requirements and be given more freedom to manage its currency reserves so it can improve its financial performance.<BR><P>
AMALIA STARTS RESTRUCTURING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold mining and exploration group Amalia said today it had started a restructuring exercise, having achieved its stated objectives for the year to end September 1996.<BR><P>
TRADE SURPLUS SLIDE MORE THAN PREDICTED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A disappointing export performance and a high import bill dragged SA's trade surplus down to only R378m in November from October's bumper figure of R3,9bn.<BR><P>
FADING ECONOMY TO GET R107BN SHOT IN THE ARM <I>(Business Times, with the Sunday Times)</I><BR>
The South African economy, faced with stagnating consumer spending, is expected to get a major shot in the arm from large capital projects valued at R107-billion over the next five years.<BR><P>
GOVT HANDS TRADE MANDATE TO EUROPEAN UNION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government ended uncertainty over whether it would launch negotiations with the European Union on a co-operation accord, including a free trade area, by handing over details of its negotiating mandate to the EU on Friday.<BR><P>
CLAIMS OF SABC BANKRUPTCY ARE 'MISCHIEVOUS'  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The SA Broadcasting Corporation was aiming at a break-even budget for 1997/98 and reports that it was bankrupt were "mischievous", spokesman Enoch Sithole said yesterday.<BR><P>
GOVT MAY TAP R8,5BN SASRIA WAR CHEST <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government is preparing legislation which will allow it to divert up to R8,5bn from a special political riot insurance fund, the SA Special Risk Insurance Association (Sasria), to be used to reduce state debt.<BR><P>
POST OFFICE FINANCING OPTIONS IN FOCUS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A new subsidy structure is being examined for the SA Post Office, but the average R500m-a-year subsidy was likely to continue in the short term due to expected losses, sources close to the process said at the weekend.<BR><P>
