DE BEERS' DIAMOND SALES SURGE AS US DEMAND RISES <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Rough diamond sales by De Beers' Central Selling Organisation (CSO) rose 7% to $4,83bn (R20,4bn) this year - a new record for the cartel -as US demand for diamond jewellery surged 8%, underpinning a 5% rise in world-wide retail sales.<BR><P>
RUSSIAN FINANCE MINISTRY WANTS DE BEERS DEAL-TASS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Russia's official Itar-Tass news agency quoted an unidentified Finance Ministry official as saying on Wednesday that Moscow was ready to continue working with De Beers.<BR><P>
ZIMBABWEAN GOLD PRODUCTION FALLS <I>In Brief</I>  <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Zimbabwe's 1996 gold production might not reach the forecast 26 tons due to reduced output during the second half of the year, a Chamber of Mines<I>(of Zimbabwe)</I>official said yesterday.<BR><P>
ISCOR PICKS EMPANGENI SITE FOR MINERAL SMELTER <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Iscor said yesterday that it had identified the Hillview site in Empangeni, KwaZulu Natal, as the preferred location for the mineral separation plant and smelter associated with its planned R1,65b heavy minerals and mining project.<BR><P>
PHILIPPE GOVT SAYS MINING FIRMS TO PAY ROYALTY OF 1% OF OUTPUT TO TRIBAL LAND-OWNERS  <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
MANILA - The Philippine govt said on Thursday that mining companies operating in the country must pay 1% of output as royalty to indigenous tribes whose ancestral lands were being mined.<BR><P>
SEA TREASURE DRAWS SA DIAMOND MINERS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
The treacherous waters of southern Africa's west coast hold vast treasures - marine diamonds, risky to recover but worthwhile for the small ocean mining companies that have taken on the task.<BR><P>
MONEY MARKET<I> In Brief</I> <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The money market shortage surged to R10,6bn on Tuesday from almost R9,5bn on Saturday - its highest level since April 30, when it stood at R10,96bn.<BR><P>
RAND UP 4C AGAINST DOLLAR, 7C AGAINST POUND  <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The rand ended a volatile day almost 4c stronger against the dollar, with the Reserve Bank saying further gyrations were probably on the cards for the rest of the month.<BR><P>
SA'S CHRISTMAS SHOPPERS FEEL THE STRESS OF SMALLER BUDGETS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
South Africans are feeling the pinch of smaller budgets and higher-priced goods when doing their Christmas shopping, a stress survey has found.<BR><P>
SA SHOULD TAP INTO PROCEEDS FOR PRIVATISATION - BANK <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SA could tap into the proceeds of privatisation to finance the current account deficit before turning to the IMF for assistance, the Union Bank of Switzerland said in its latest report.<BR><P>
MINING JOBS <B><U>Editorial Comment</U></B> <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The report on gold mine labour commissioned by the labour dept from Wits University's Sociology of Work Unit is an outstanding example of the gap between SA's practical realities and utopian views of what should be.<BR><P>
NATAL EXPECTED TO ATTRACT R1,3BN IN NEW INVESTMENT <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
KwaZulu-Natal expected to attract R1,3bn in new investments in the 12 months to March next year compared with R2,02bn last year, as SA had to fight harder internationally to encourage commercial development, KwaZulu-Natal Marketing Initiative vice-chairman Arnold Griesel said yesterday.<BR><P>
MANUFACTURING INDUSTRY IS STILL SHEDDING JOBS - CSS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The manufacturing industry again shed jobs in Sept, bringing the total number of jobs lost in manufacturing since Jan to 38 302, Central Statistical Service figures released yesterday showed.<BR><P>
HIGHER EDUCATION DRAFT POLICY PROPOSES FAR-REACHING CHANGES
 <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
As the tertiary education sector gears up for what could be an even more tumultuous year than the previous one as a likely result of massive cuts in govt subsidies, the education dept yesterday published for comment in the draft policy on higher education transformation.<BR><P>



