<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 18  DECEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>

GOLD INDUSTRY 'NEEDS TO BE REMEDIED'  <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The international competitiveness of SA's gold mining industry remains hampered by a fragmented and inefficient labour process and a mining culture which has nurtured inefficient labour practices for the past 100 years, a recent study commissioned by the labour dept has found.<BR><P>
REPORT URGES INTO WAGES IN GOLD MINING<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A renewed call has been made for an investigation into basic wages and conditions of employment in the gold mining industry.<BR><P>
SOUTH AFRICAN UNIONS SHOULD BUY SHARES IN MINES<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SA trade unions should buy shares in local mining houses in a bid to raise safety and living standards for workers, NUM said on Tuesday.<BR><P>
FLAGGING SA GOLD OUTPUT SEEN UNDER 495 TONNES <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
The SA gold mining industry is set to finish a difficult year with just 490-495 tonnes of the precious metal, down from the 500 tonnes previously hoped for, the Chamber of Mines said on Tuesday.<BR><P>
AUSTRALIA SET FOR RECORD GOLD OUTPUT<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SYDNEY - Australia is on track to retain its position as the world's third largest gold producer behind SA and the US, mining a record 304 tonnes in fiscal 1996/97, a government commodities forecaster said.<BR><P>
RUSSIAN CENTRAL BANK GOLD RESERVES UP TO 400 T<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
MOSCOW - Russia's central bank bought about 100 tonnes of gold in 1996, boosting its reserves to around 400 tonnes, the bank's precious metals dept chief, Sergei Kyshtymov, told Reuters on Tuesday.<BR><P>
RUSSIAN 1996 GOLD OUTPUT SEEN AT 110 TONNES VS 122 TONNES IN 1995<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
MOSCOW - Russian 1996 gold output is likely to fall by about 10% to 110 tonnes this year from 122 tonnes in 1995, Itar-Tass news agency quoted an Industry Ministry report as saying on Tuesday.<BR><P>
SWISS 'MADE $3BN ON LOOT' <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
NEW YORK - Swiss National Bank made a profit of more than $3bn in dealings in looted Nazi gold, not $4,8m, as a top Swiss bank official had claimed last week, World Jewish Congress vice-president Kalman Sultnik charged yesterday.<BR><P>
ROUGH DIAMOND SALES In Brief <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Rough diamond sales by De Beers' Central Selling Organisation are set to reach record levels this year, mainly due to strong US demand.<BR><P>
THE RESERVE BANK In Brief <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Reserve Bank said the SA money market shortage held below R9,50bn on Friday and Saturday.  It quoted the shortage at R9,475bn on Saturday from R9,499bn on Friday, compared with Thursday's R9,788bn.<BR><P>
EUROBOND REDEMPTION UNLIKELY TO HARM RAND<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
About R1bn in Eurobond issues fall due in Jan, which could put pressure on the rand if investors take their losses and bail out of the rand.<BR><P>
FOREIGN VISITORS WILL EARN CAPE R3,3BN <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A surge in international visitors to the Western Cape over Christmas could help earn the region up to R3,3bn in foreign exchange this year compared with the R9bn generated by the tourism industry in SA as a whole last year, according to figures compiled by SA Tourism Board.<BR><P>
MBEKI IN ANGOLA TO BOOST TIES<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki and Deputy Foreign Affairs Minister Aziz Pahad would visit Angola today and tomorrow, the foreign affairs dept said yesterday.<BR><P>
RAND WATER HAS GOOD NEWS ABOUT THE COUNTRY'S DAMS In Brief<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Improved dam systems and recent heavy rains could mean that Gauteng will escape water restrictions until the turn of the century.<BR><P>
SA SCORES WELL ON FOREIGN INVESTMENT, BUT POORLY ON TRADE POLICIES <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
South Africas economic polices are "mostly not free", a US agency and an influential newspaper said in their index of economic freedom.  But even though the Heritage Foundation and the Wall Street Journal gave the country an overall mark of three (out of five) and ranked South Africa 73 out of 150 countries they surveyed, the index lauded the transition to democracy, saying it has gone well and national reconciliation has been impressive.  The paper and foundation gave South Africa three points in corporate taxation, government intervention in the economy, monetary policy, banking and property rights.  The best score is one (very free) and the worst is five (repressed).<BR><P>



