Anglo American subsidiaries Erabas and Namib Milling have bought Zambia's largest milling company, part of the country's privatisation of state-run enterprises.<BR><P>
RAND/DOLLAR<I> In Brief</I><I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The rand ended a turbulent week near historically weak levels on Friday.  It recovered from R4,7490 to the dollar to end the day at R4,7325, although Reserve Bank dollar sales had seen the local unit firm to a day's best of R4,725.  The currency's 8c drop on Thursday signalled the end to a period of stability.<BR><P>
CURRENCY 'ATTRACTING INVESTMENT' <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
LONDON - Foreign direct investment in job-creating factories, plant and construction in SA is starting to rise now that the rand has stabilised at depressed levels, says Nedocr chief economist Dennis Dykes.<BR><P>
WORST IS OVER FOR THE RAND - BOLAND BANK<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The worst was over for the rand with the rand-dollar exchange rate likely to settle at about R4,80 by the end of next year, Boland Bank said in its latest annual report.<BR><P>
CORPORATION'S R3BN PLANS 'SHOULD CREATE 9 000 JOBS' <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Industrial Development Corporation is planning to spend about R3bn on a range of projects in the first half of next year, a move that is expected to create 9 000 new jobs.<BR><P>
HERTZ TO USE SA FOR DRIVE INTO AFRICA <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Hertz Rent-a-Car is reinvesting in SA after leaving the country nearly 10 years ago and is promising stiff competition in the car rental market, particularly to Imperial and Avis, the biggest in the industry.<BR><P>
AUSTRALIAN GOLD OUTPUT IN 1997<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
CANBERRA - Australian gold mine production is forecast to rise by about 11% to about 304 tonnes in 1996/97 to June 30 from an estimated 272.9 tonnes in 1995/96 the Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource Economics said in its Dec Australian Commodities publication.<BR><P>
ETHIOPIA LOSES 1,000KGS GOLD A YEAR IN SMUGGLING<I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
ADDIS ABABA - At least 1,000kg of Ethiopian gold is smuggled out of the country each year, officials said on Friday.<BR><P>
AUSTRALIA STUDIES SEE GOLD PROCESSING SAVINGS <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
ADELAIDE - Australian researchers said on Tuesday they had unearthed savings of up to A$500,000 a year for the average-sized Australian gold mine through improved ore processing.<BR><P>
TURKISH BOURSE AIMS TO DRAW IDLE GOLD INTO ECONOMY <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
ISTANBUL - Istanbul's one -and-a-half years old gold exchange is seeking to expand its operations to draw the country's idle gold into Turkish economy while lowering the amount of gold imports and gold savings kept by individuals.  "Under the exchange's restructuring plans, the main target is to benefit from idle gold and use this source within the national economy", Kaan Aytogu, the general secretary of the Istanbul Gold Exchange, told Reuters in an interview.<BR><P>
TAIWAN BLOCKS SAA <I>In Brief</I><I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SAA's landing rights in Taiwan will be suspended from Feb 15 in retaliation for SA's decision to sever diplomatic ties with it in favour of China.<BR><P>
STANLEY MOGOBA TAKES OVER AS PAC PRESIDENT <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
A disappointed Clarence Makwetu handed over the presidency of the PAC to Stanley Mogoba, former head of the Methodist Church in SA, at an emotionally charged congress in Venda at the weekend.<BR><P>
AZAPO HEADS WALK OUT OF 'REPRESSIVE' ANNUAL CONGRESS<I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Dictatorial and authoritarian Azanian People's Organisation leadership, coupled with a "libellous" annual report, led senior Azapo members to walk out of the organisation's congress in Pietersburg at the weekend, Gauteng regional chairman Lybon Mabasa said yesterday.<BR><P>
SA COULD LEARN A FEW LESSONS FROM CHILE <I>Comment & Analysis</I> <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Chile's successful privatisation experience, particularly in telecommunications, could provide a model for SA.  - Wide-ranging privatisation in the 1980s was a key precursor to Chile's economic boom, but, like SA, the country is meeting opposition to proposed privatisation of further entities.  Among these is most notably the water supply.  Chile also faces the challenge of upgrading infrastructure without a large injection of govt funding.<BR><P>


