GOVT GIVES UP ON 'JOBS FOR SA' PLAN <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The Government's "Jobs for South Africa" project, in terms of which 11 000 affirmative-action posts were advertised in the public service, has been abandoned with fewer than a quarter filled.  Public Service Minister Zola Skweyiya said yesterday that, because of problems in filling the posts and "the length of time it has been dragging", it had been decided to stop the project.<BR><P>
BRAIN DRAIN SLOWS AS SKILLS POUR INTO SA <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SA's debilitating brain drain took a breather in September, according to the latest monthly immigration and emigration figures released yesterday by the Central Statistical Service.  They show a small drop in the number of skilled people leaving the country and a huge increase in the number settling here. <I>[The slant of this piece contradicts a statement by CSSs Alida Casteleijn reported yesterday that immigrants tended to be from family units in which only one or two members were economically active - hardly an issue of "skills" pouring in - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
'RETICENT' MANAGERS COULD HAVE PROBLEMS WITH LABOUR ACT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The new Labour Relations Act could pose serious problems for SA's historically reticent managers, says public relations company Sussens Group strategic communication designer Mamosedi Maleka.  A crucial difficulty for South African managers created by the act is a section which obliges managers to disclose relevant information to their workforce forums or unions to help consultation and joint decision making, says Maleka.<BR><P>
MORE THAN A THOUSAND EXTRA POSTS AT SARS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
More than 1 000 additional post would be filled in the SA revenue Service within the next month - irrespective of the downsizing of the public service - to make more resources available to find tax evaders, the Service said yesterday.<BR><P>
LONRHO IN TALKS WITH ZIM. GOVT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Negotiations are under way between the Zimbabwe government and London-based multinational, Lonrho, for the purchase of its mining interest in Zimbabwe as part of a policy of economic "indigenisation". Lonrho is the second multinational this year to begin talks with the government for the sale of assets.<BR>
<B><I>... but ...</I></B><BR>
MUGABE SAYS LONRHO BOSS IS WEIRD <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
HARARE - President Robert Mugabe yesterday said Dieter Bock, the German chief executive of London-based multinational Lonrho, was "a weird, weird person" who had no experience in the line of business his company dealt in <I>[sic].</I><BR><P>
AMALIA SELLS ZIMWEST <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Amalia Gold Mining & Exploration shareholders had unanimously approved the R39,45m sale of Liechtenstein-registered Zimwest Holdings, which owns Minehead in Zimbabwe, to London-based Commonwealth Gold, a statement said yesterday.<BR><P>
RUSSIA BOASTS LARGE DIAMOND RESERVES  <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
LONDON - Russia had huge diamond resources available for development, even though production was presently declining, according to Russian and Western geologists.<BR><P>
COST OF LOCAL CALLS SURGES AS TELKOM JOINS OPEN MARKET <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The cost of local calls is to rise 28,4% as part of Telkom's tariff restructuring plan and its move to a more open market.  The increase will be balanced by an 11,2% and 11,5% drop in national and international rates respectively.<BR><P>
FEW HAVE ANY CONFIDENCE IN POLITICAL PARTIES, SURVEY FINDS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
South Africans are not generally interested in politics and do not consider strikes and boycotts a viable option for political participation, according to a "Third World Values" survey.<BR><P>
NEW SYSTEM TO CUT VIOLENT CRIME <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A new ballistic identification system that allows police to solve violent crimes quickly would boost crime investigation when implemented in May, Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi said yesterday.<BR><P>
DEVALUATION 'HAS SILVER LINING' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA could learn from other global economies where a sudden depreciation in currency had acted as a spur to economic growth, Old Mutual International Asset Managers economic strategist, Nigel Morgan said yesterday.<BR><P>
EGG ON THE FACES OF LEADING ECONOMISTS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
In January this year, SA's leading economists were, almost without exception, predicting a fall in interest rates.  After two official interest-rate increases in the ensuing months, they are still predicting that now.<BR><P>
SA SHARE PRICES SEEN RISING IN SECOND HALF <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA shares may be flat early next year, weighed down by a sluggish economy, but fair earnings growth and improving confidence should lift prices in the second half, a <I>Reuters </I>survey has found.<BR><P>
MORE TO SA'S RELATIONSHIP WITH EU THAN FRUIT & FLOWERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The European position on the controversial free trade agreement between SA and the European Union could change - and it is worth noting that there is more that unites the two parties than divides them, argues EU ambassador Erwan Fouére. - The recent visit of Deputy President Thabo Mbeki to several countries in Europe has highlighted the political dimensions of the evolving relationship between the EU and SA - dimensions which are often underestimated.  There is much that brings the EU and SA together.  It is a relationship which has to do with shared values and the quest for a moral ethic in the world.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
EU TO CUT AID TO SA <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
The European Union is expected to cut its annual aid to SA today.  Next year's EU budget is due to be voted through by the European parliament in the last stage of the European budgetary process.  The figure, falling to R800-million.  The European parliament will halve the proposed reduction in aid, which EU budget ministers had wanted to fall by R30-million.  This will send a worrying signal to the South African government, which is preparing its stance for trade negotiations with the EU.<BR><P>
UN SCUFFLES INFLUENCED TAIWAN DECISION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The hullabaloo surrounding SA's abrupt decision to remove diplomatic recognition from Taiwan and grant it to mainland China is obscuring an important diplomatic scuffle taking place at the United Nations.  In addition, the link between SA's decision on Taiwan and the intense lobbying for the next UN secretary-general has also been overshadowed.<BR><P>
SA MINERAL EXPORTS DOUBLE VALUE WITHIN 10 YEARS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The value of SA's exports of minerals and mineral-related beneficiated products had doubled to R64bn over the past 10 years, but declined by about a third to R21,8bn in real terms, the Minerals Bureau said in its latest bulletin.<BR><P>
NORTH AMERICAN GOLD FIRMS RACE FOR WORLD LEADERSHIP <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
TORONTO - North America's major gold companies are waging an expensive battle to win the coveted title of world's biggest gold producer.  "We want more of the action," said Hugh Leggatt, spokesman for Placer Dome Inc.<BR><P>
SWISS NATIONAL BANK SCOFFS AT TALK IT MUST BUY GOLD <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
ZURICH - The Swiss National Bank dismissed as "pure speculation" a suggestion it might have to buy more gold to ensure it respects a government decree that its gold reserves cover at least 40% of banknotes in circulation.<BR><P>
AFTER THE MIRACLE: SOUTH AFRICA NOW <I>(FORTUNE 23/12/96)</I><BR>
Its political and social transformation has been nothing short of incredible. But to avoid ending up as one more poor, overpopulated and unstable country, it now has to speed up the pace of economic reform. Halfway through Mandelas five-year presidential term, could SA be on a roll? Virtually everyone in and outside the country desperately wants it to be, but, sadly its not - at least not yet.<I>[FORTUNE is now the 3rd influential international news organ to take a perspective on SA a few years into transformation following TIME and The Economist. - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
TWO HELD FOR THEFT, ARSON <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
A special Police team investigating the past weekends violence in Freedom Front <I>[sic - should read "Park". the Freedom Front is a conservative opposition political party - Ed.]</I> squatter camp north of Rustenburg, has arrested four suspects. The four are expected to appear in court soon on charges of theft and arson.<BR><P>
INDIANS PROTEST DE BEERS LEASE <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
NEW DELHI - Indias main opposition party of Hindu nationalists, the Bharatiya Janata Party,  staged a protest in Parliament yesterday over a lease given to De Beers to mine diamonds in the country.<BR><P>
MINE BLAST KILLS 3 <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
SEOUL - Three coal miners were killed and 12 others trapped underground yesterday when a dynamite blast caused a mudslide in a mine near Taebaek, a coalmining town in eastern South Korea.<BR><P>
NORTHFIELDS GOLD MINE SUSPENDED ON JSE <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
The Johannesburg Stock Exchange said yesterday it had suspended the listing of Northfields Gold Mine after being informed that it had been placed under provisional liquidation.<BR><P>
SO, WHAT WENT WRONG WITH 96? <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
When the economic history books are written 1996 will go down as the year that began with so much hope, but ended with business morale at its lowest ebb since economic recovery began in 1993. <BR><P>
96 - GOOD YEAR FOR SA LABOUR RELATIONS <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
1996 can be described safely as the best year in the transformation of the labour market disfigured by years of apartheid. Although the changes in the new Labour Relations Act, implemented on November 11, favour workers to an extent, little has changed in the treatment of blacks in the workplace and in white attitudes towards black people.<BR><P>
THEY SPEND THEIR LIVES DIGGING GOLD AND THEN DIE <I>(Sowetan)</I><BR>
James Nxele (57) has six children - and tuberculosis. For 36 years he worked as a driller for the Freegold Mining Company. In September he was dismissed unceremoniously on health grounds and paid R6 000 in recognition of his long service. Filing a complaint with the National Union of Mineworkers, Nxele describes the money he had been paid for his years of service as "next to nothing" and an insult. Recently he was hospitalised for a month and his family had to foot the bill.<BR>
	Fluer <I>[sic] </I>Plimmer, NUMs health and safety officer, says mineworkers who contract TB or other lung diseases are hospitalised for only two weeks and are not compensated. "Only workers with a permanent disability are compensated. The industry pays 75% of the workers wage as compensation. It is not really a good scheme because the less you earn, the less compensation you get," he <I>[sic] </I>explains. <BR>
	The failure of the mining industry to ensure optimum dust control standards has left thousands of mineworkers suffering from lung diseases. While employed, the miners live in mine compounds, but once they outlive their worth, they are immediately packed off home with meagre amount of compensation money. At home they struggle to earn a living, eventually to die from a lung disease. <BR>
	The extent of health problems suffered by ex-mineworkers is difficult to determine as no follow-ups are conducted once the workers leave the mine. While there are clear indications that the prevalence of lung disease among miners is high, government institutions monitoring these problems remain seriously underfunded. <BR>
	"Once a disabled or sick mineworker is repatriated to his home, he gets no support. Some cases are so severe that we cannot guarantee that they will last even five years after leaving the industry. Nobody follows up on them, neither the government nor the industry," says Dr M Berry, a medical practitioner experienced in dealing with mine diseases.<BR>
	The new Mine Health and Safety Act, to come into effect next year, is the only breakthrough for mineworkers in recent years. It is the product of nine months of consultations between government, the labour movement and mine owners. The Act accords workers the right to be informed of any risk assessment made on a mine, formulate and live by a mine code of practice, have the4 right to be t5rained and represented in health and safety regulations and, most importantly, the right to refuse dangerous jobs. - <I>Africa Information Afrique</I>. <BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=3 COLOR=FF0000>[Although clearly riddled with errors, misconceptions and factual inaccuracies, this "report" has been given here in full for you to reach your own conclusion. No attempt was made to achieve journalistic balance through getting an industry response or to verify facts. - Ed.]</FONT></I><BR><P>

