<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 11 DECEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>





ANGLO TO SPEND R30BN ON CAPITAL PROJECTS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Anglo American Corporation and its associates planned to spend a massive R30bn in SA until 2001 on capital projects to improve competitiveness and boost exports, deputy chairman Nicky Oppenheimer said yesterday.<BR><P>
ASHANTI'S RELATIONS WITH ANGLO 'CORDIAL' <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I>
Ashanti Goldfields said relations with Anglo American, its indirect shareholder, were cordial, but there was no talk of co-operation in any areas.  "We have a cordial relationship with the Anglo board, as with other major mining firms", Mark Keatly, Ashanti's finance director, said yesterday.<BR><P>
SA GOLD HEDGING NOT HEAVY - ANGLO OFFICIAL <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - South African gold miners have not been pressured into heavy forward selling because a weak rand has given them breathing space, an official of Anglo American Corporation said on Tuesday. He also said a slide in gold prices to three-year lows had ended, but the market would remain wary of central bank selling.<BR><P>
NEW RUSSIAN METALS CHIEF WANTS GOLD SECTOR CHANGED <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
MOSCOW - A senior Russian official said on Tuesday Russia's gold market needed radical, market-economy changes to survive, and called for the creation of a giant gold corporation.<BR><P>
RUSSIAN DIAMOND SECTOR TURMOIL DELAYS DE BEERS DEAL <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
MOSCOW - A big diamond deal between Russia and De Beers has been caught up in political manoeuvrings in Moscow.  Bickering ministries and a shake-up in the leadership of the Russian diamond industry are conspiring to delay a crucial agreement.<BR><P>
GENCOR, JAPANESE CONSORTIUM CLOSE TO SIGNING DEAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gencor is close to signing an agreement with a Japanese consortium of zinc operators to finance part of the feasibility costs for the group's R2bn zinc smelter, with an option to take an equity stake in the project if approved.<BR><P>
EAST RAND EXTENDS ITS SURFACE OPERATIONS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
East Rand Proprietary Mines should be able to continue surface operations for nine years at its current rates as a result of the R38m acquisition of a gold dump from Knights Gold Mining.<BR><P>
BASE METALS 'NEED INVESTMENT'<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
SAs copper industry could grow until the end of the century, but would shrink rapidly thereafter unless new investment and resources were found, analysts warned yesterday.  "As far as copper is concerned, the South African mining industry by the year 2000 could be up to 5% bigger than last year, but its share of the world total will either be static, or fall,"<I> [they said - Ed.].</I><BR><P>
MERCHANT BANK TO BECOME COAL MINE'S FUNDING PARTNER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Rand Merchant Bank had become the funding partner of a bituminous coal mine near Newcastle in KwaZulu-Natal following a management buyout estimated to be worth several million rands, the bank said yesterday.<BR><P>
IMPALA CONFIRMS ITS MINERS DIED IN ETHNIC CLASH <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Impala Platinum Holdings said yesterday that most of the 32 people killed in ethnic clashes at the weekend had been its workers.  The mining company said yesterday, "Investigation by police into the deaths is intense, but as yet no arrests have been made".<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
MBOWENI PLEDGES MINE DEATHS PROBE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
A full-scale investigation into the "root causes" of the violent clashes at the Freedom Park squatter settlement near Rustenburg, which claimed 32 lives at the weekend, would be launched as soon as possible, Labour Minister Tito Mboweni said last night.<BR><P>
SA's DEFICIT TARGET OF 5,1% THIS YEAR WILL BE MET : RAMOS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
LONDON - Maria Ramos, South African director-general of Finance, said SA's 5,1% budget deficit target for this fiscal year would be met.  Speaking at the third SA Economy, Investment & Trade Conference in London, Ramos also said SA was sticking to its 4% deficit target for 1998.<BR><P>
CRIME AND HIJACKING FAIL TO STOP IMMIGRANTS ARRIVING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
For the first time in nearly three years the number of foreigners moving to SA outnumbered people leaving the country, a Central Statistical Service report said yesterday. However, CSS senior statistician Alida Casteleijn said, while nearly all those people leaving SA were economically active, most of those entering were characterised by family groups with only one or two economically active members. <BR><P>
CAPITAL'S PATH IS NOT WITHOUT HAZARDS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Capital Alliance Holdings might have led negotiations for the African Mining Group's R2,8bn purchase from Anglo of control of JCI.  But the group - only a couple of months old in its present form - intends to grow in financial services, not mining.<BR><P>
MANDELA SIGNS NEW CONSTITUTION INTO LAW <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
An elated President Nelson Mandela yesterday signed into law South Africas new Constitution, ushering in a new period of constitutional democracy and finally consigning apartheid to the scrap-heap. <BR><P>
