<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 10 DECEMBER 1996 - at 11H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



EAST RAND PROPRIETARY MINES <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
East Rand Proprietary Mines had acquired the Cason sand dump from Knights Gold Mining Co. for R38m cash, a statement said.<BR><P>
ANGLO AMERICAN AND DE BEERS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American and De Beers Chairman's Fund head Michael O'Dowd will retire at the end of this year and be replaced by Anglo corporate affairs chairman Clem Sunter, said Anglo American spokesman Charmaine Russell.<BR><P>
DE BEERS SEALS RUSSIAN VENTURE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
De Beers has signed a joint venture agreement with Russian exploration company Terra to prospect two high-grade diamond deposits in northwest Russia, beating a string of other contenders including RTZ-CRA and Ashton Mining.<BR><P>
PLANS TO BRING WARRING FACTIONS TOGETHER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Police and Wildebeestfontein mine management were yesterday organising urgent meetings between two warring Freedom Park squatter settlement factions near Rustenburg in a bid to avoid further clashes in the conflict which claimed the lives of more than 30 residents at the weekend.<BR><P>
MUDSLIDE MINE MAY NOT REOPEN <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
KIMBERLEY - Retrieval of the bodies of 16 miners entombed after a mudrush at the Rovic Diamond Mine could take up to five months, during which time production will be unable to continue, a spokesman for the company said yesterday.<BR><P>
MINING CRUCIAL TO SOUTHERN AFRICAN ECONOMIC GROWTH <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Southern Africa was on the road to considerable economic growth, and mining would play a crucial role in the region's revitalisation, Standard Bank Ltd. economist Phillip Clayton said on Monday.<BR><P>
POWER MAKES SA A WORLD-CLASS ALUMINIUM SITE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SA will remain a world-class location for primary aluminium smelting provided power utilities continue to offer low-cost electricity, Resource Strategies Inc. president Robin Adams said on Monday.<BR><P>
OLYMPIC BID NOT BLOCKED BY NEED TO BUILD FACILITIES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
International Olympic Committee evaluation commission leader Thomas Bach confirmed that, although many of Cape Town's facilities included in the 2004 Olympic plan had yet to be built, this would not count against the city's chances of hosting the event.<BR><P>
SA, EU PACT WILL HIT SA'S NEIGHBOURS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA's customs union neighbours - Botswana, Lesotho, Namibia and Swaziland (BLNS) - could lose more than R1bn in crucial fiscal revenue if the proposed free trade accord between SA and the European Union (EU) was concluded, sources in the region said yesterday.<BR><P>
DISCORD LURKS IN THE WINGS AT WTO <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The World Trade Organisation's ambitions to advance global liberalisation and enhance its own authority face their biggest test this week when the two-year-old institution holds its first ministerial meeting in Singapore.  WTO director-general Renato Rugiero hopes the meeting will forge a broad political consensus to strengthen multilateral trade and galvanise efforts to tackle a demanding liberalisation agenda stretching into early next century.<BR><P>
LET'S HEAR THE VICTIMS' VOICES <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
South Africans are tired of promises, analyses, strategies and initiatives by the Government on crime.  People want visible success in the crime war.  Victims particularly demand their voices be heard.  They are trapped between the devil and the deep-blue sea, being doubly victimised, first by the criminals and then by a justice system which seems to cower before the needs of criminals without any regard for the needs of victims.  According to Professor Lawrence Schlemmer, 46% of South Africans say they personally, or through their families, have been the victims of crime in the past six months.  It is time for the criminal justice system to acknowledge the crucial role of the victim in reporting crime, furnishing evidence, identifying the offender and in acting as a witness in court.  What is required is that the system's agencies adopt policy measures capable of providing support mechanisms and a safety net for the victims.<BR><P>
PRIVATE SECURITY GROUPS A 'VIABLE OPTION' FOR AFRICAN CONFLICTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The use of private security groups such as Executive Outcomes may be one of the few remaining options to bring stability to conflict-plagued African countries until such time as an African or international "fire-fighting squad" became a reality.<BR><P>
RESERVE BANKS NEW ECONOMICS HEAD <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Reserve Bank had promoted Bernie de Jager to head the economics department from January 1, the Bank announced yesterday.<BR><P>
KWAZULU-NATAL DECIDES NOT TO CHANGE PROVINCE'S NAME <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Inkatha Freedom Party's KwaZulu-Natal caucus yesterday decided against changing the province's name to Kingdom of KwaZulu-Natal, even though the house of traditional leaders, led by IFP leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi, had asked it to do so.<BR><P>
BRUCE TAKES OVER FROM BRUCE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Business Report editor Peter Bruce will become editor of the Financial Mail in January. He replaces Nigel Bruce who resigned in November<I> [to take over editorship of Finance Week - Ed.].</I><BR><P>
SA ECONOMISTS MUCH MORE PESSIMISTIC ON GROWTH <I>(Sake-Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SAs economists are now much more pessimistic about economic prospects for next year than they were a few months ago. This is evident from the latest survey conducted monthly among economists taking part in <I>Sake-Beelds</I> "Economist of the Year" competition. <BR><P>
