<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 9 DECEMBER 1996 - at 12H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



VIOLENCE ERUPTS IN SQUATTER CAMP, 37 DIE <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
RUSTENBURG - Nightshift mineworkers at the Wildebeestfontein South mine went below ground as usual at 8pm last night after violence in an adjoining squatter camp claimed 37 lives at the weekend.<BR><P>
WESTERN MINING ZAMBIA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Western Mining Zambia completed the feasibility study for the reopening of Zambian copper mine Bwama Mkubwa, not Bateman Minerals & Industrial, as recently reported by Sapa, the South African company said at the weekend.<BR><P>
DE BEERS UNDETERRED BY PROTEST <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
De Beers would go ahead with a planned $30m joint venture with an Indian group, despite a 400-strong protest against the group last week, a spokesman said on Saturday.<BR><P>
GENCOR WEIGHS UP BRAZILIAN BID <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gencor is considering a bid for the mining assets of state-run Brazilian resource group Companhia Vale do Rio Doce set to be privatised next year.<BR><P>
MINING COMMUNITY WARY OVER INDONESIAN GOLD DISPUTE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
JAKARTA - The international mining community is watching the turmoil over one of the world's largest gold finds with apprehension, fearing it could make doing business in Indonesia more complicated.<BR><P>
STEEP RISE IN FOREIGN EXCHANGE RESERVES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Reserve Bank's holding of gold and foreign exchange reserves rose sharply in November, signalling that the balance of payments has turned the corner.  Figures released by the Bank on Friday showed total gold and foreign assets were up R651m to R10,9mb.  The rise reflected forex inflows, as the gold component was down.<BR><P>
TAIWAN LISTS SUSPENSION OF PROJECTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Taiwan yesterday announced it was suspending projects in SA worth $842m, including a plan for two commercial banks to deposit $500m with the Reserve Bank as "balance of payments support".  However, Taiwan also announced that much of its total investment of R20,6bn in SA would not be affected and that some projects and programmes still under negotiation would go ahead.<BR><P>
EXPORTERS COMING TO THE PARTY, AT LAST <I>(Business Times, with the Sunday Times)</I><BR>
Amid the general economic gloom of increased interest rates, high credit spending and a low gold price, SA's exporters are finally grasping the opportunity presented by the slump in the rand.  A R4b surge in exports to almost R15m in October and a more modest rise in imports from R10,3b to R11b pushed the trade surplus during the month to a record high of R3,9b.<BR><P>
LOWER GDP GROWTH PREDICTED FOR NEXT YEAR <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Sanlam has joined the ranks of senior economists forecasting a lower growth rate in gross domestic product for next year, in contrast to government's prediction last week of a 2,5% growth rate.<BR><P>
SA TAKES REGIONAL STANCE AT WORLD TRADE MEETING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA would not be joining developed countries in calling for a discussion of controversial labour standards at this week's World Trade Organisation (WTO) ministerial summit meeting in Singapore, it emerged this weekend.<BR><P>
CROSS NAMED RESERVE BANK DEPUTY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The cabinet had approved the appointment of James Cross as a deputy governor of the SA Reserve Bank, the president's office announced on Friday.<BR><P>
SA, NIGERIAN ENERGY MINISTERS MEET <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA's Energy Minister, Penuell Maduna, said he would consider a visit to Nigeria after his Nigerian counterpart briefed him on the west African country's human rights record.<BR><P>
BLACKS DON'T TAKE THE CALL WHEN MADIBA RINGS <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
President Nelson Mandela criticised SA's black business leaders on Friday, saying their inefficiency was hampering his efforts to promote their cause.  Mandela, addressing business leaders in Cape Town, also accused white conglomerates of resisting foreign competition and said some South Africans were engaged in economic sabotage.<BR><P>
