<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>FRIDAY, 6 DECEMBER 1996 - at 12H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



TOTAL MINING PRODUCTION <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Total mining production in the third quarter this year decreased 1,8% after seasonal adjustment compared to the second quarter as a result of lower output of gold, iron, copper, platinum and diamonds, the Central Statistical Service said yesterday.<BR><P>
SA'S COAL EXPORTERS HOPING FOR PRICE INCREASES <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
South African coal exporters are hoping for increases in their Far East sales contracts amid indications that their European agreements currently being negotiated should reflect price increases of about $1 a ton from January through December next year.<BR><P>
TAIWAN HALTS AID PROJECTS WORTH $130M <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA's relations with Taiwan finally cracked yesterday with Taipei's announcement that most of its aid projects and bilateral treaties would be suspended, while SA acknowledged it had opened negotiations with mainland China.<BR><P>
CAPITAL FLOWS OUT AGAIN AS DEBT REPAID <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA experienced its first capital outflow since the 1994 election when about R200m left the country in the third quarter of this year. The figure is tiny compared with the billions that left SA quarterly before it became a democracy.  The capital outflow related to large payments falling due on debt previously caught in the standstill net.  <BR><P>
CONFIDENCE LEVELS PLUMMET TO 15-MONTH LOW <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Increases in the inflation rate, interest rates and unemployment figures bruised business confidence in November, with SA Chamber of Business confidence index slumping to its worst level since August last year, Sacob said yesterday.<BR><P>
GOLD-TECK AND ANGLO REVIVE CHILE MINE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
SANTIAGO - The $250m deal between Canada's Teck <I>[Reuters does not explain the name discrepancy - Ed.]</I> Corporation and Anglo American to build a gold mine at the Lobo-Marte deposits in northern Chile will be the South African mining giant's second stab at the Marte property.<BR><P>
RUSSIAN BANKS HUNGRY TO FINANCE GOLD PRODUCTION <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
MOSCOW - Russia is trying to shift financing of its tarnished gold sector to commercial banks while keeping control of exports, putting it on a collision course with the banks who say sales abroad are what interest them.<BR><P>
RUMOURS OF CENTRAL BANK SALES ROCK GOLD MARKET <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LONDON - Rumours that a central bank has been selling gold from its reserves increased in intensity on Thursday after heavy sales rocked prices in the Far East and early European markets.<BR><P>
OIL PRICE, WEAK RAND CATCH UP WITH PPI <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The surge in oil prices and the rand's weakening had at last caught up with producer inflation, lifting the rate of increase in October to 8,3% from 7,6% in September, Central Statistical Service figures released yesterday showed.<BR><P>
RAND'S FALL OVERSTATED, SAYS ECONOMETRIX <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The rand's fall of between 25% and 30% this year has been exaggerated and rand watchers should not labour under the illusion that the currency cannot fall further, Econometrix, the economic forecasting unit, said yesterday.<BR><P>
CURRENT ACCOUNT DEFICIT SHRINKS AS RAND PLUMMETS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
One benefit of the diving value of the rand showed up in the nation's current account for the third quarter this year as its deficit shrank from a revised R4,7bn in the quarter to June 30 to R3,5b for the quarter to September 30, the Reserve Bank said yesterday.<BR><P>
EXCITING, DEREGULATING, METAMORPHIC <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Many will reflect on this year as a disappointing year of mixed fortunes in which expectations were not realised.  The year began with promises of massive foreign investment, a buoyant stock exchange and imminent exchange control abolition.  Sadly, this<I> [presumably "these"]</I> never eventuated.  The stock exchange was stagnant, the currency suffered a marked collapse, foreign investors did not show the confidence expected, and inflation and interest rates tended up as economic growth began to stagnate and the harsher-than-anticipated conditions for the man in the street manifested themselves.<BR><P>
NEW TRADE THEORY?  BAH, HUMBUG <I>(Business Mail, Fridays with the Mail & Guardian)</I><BR>
Is there such a thing as international competitiveness?  Paul Krugman thinks many of the arguments are bunk. Debates about international trade are, Paul Krugman of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology suggests, "a study in confusion and misconceptions, in which the 'experts' are usually misinformed about the most basic facts and concepts".  He goes on:  "The idea that the economic success of a country depends on its international competitiveness took hold in the late 1970s.  The World Economic Forum began issuing its World Competitiveness Report in 1980, and the rankings in that report soon became a major criterion by which national performance was judged.  By the 1990s, the concept was no longer even controversial.  Competitiveness was the key:  the only question was how to achieve it".  Krugman argues that people who use the term believe "nations compete for world markets in the same way that corporations do, that a nation which fails to match other nations in productivity or technology will face the same kind of crisis as a company that cannot match the costs of products of its rivals".<BR><P>
RESERVE BANK CALLS FOR HIGHER LEVEL OF SAVINGS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
In its latest quarterly bulletin released yesterday, the Reserve Bank has reiterated that one of the key brakes on the South African economy is still the nation's low level of saving.  But whether savings or economic growth comes first is still subject to debate.<BR><P>
COURT CHIDES ASSEMBLY OVER BILL OF RIGHTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Constitutional Court has gently chided the Constitutional Assembly for not doing more to protect and entrench the Bill of Rights - although it concedes that the safeguards provided by the new constitutional text meet the requirements for certification.<BR><P>
INCREASE IN POLITICAL VIOLENCE EXPECTED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
At least 27 people were killed in political conflict in KwaZulu-Natal last month, and the death toll was expected to rise during the festive season, Human Rights Committee violence monitor Makubetse Sekhonyane said yesterday.<BR><P>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
NAME STANCE MAY TRIGGER CRISIS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
IFP-aligned traditional leaders are set to trigger a crisis in KwaZulu-Natal by pushing for the province's name to be changed to <B>Kingdom </B>of KwaZulu-Natal, despite opposition from other parties in the legislature.<BR><P>
SA TO EXPORT CATTLE TO SENEGAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA would export cattle to Senegal in west Africa for the first time this week, effectively breaking into a market traditionally served by France and Germany, exporter Zais International director Pieter Louw said yesterday.<BR><P>
EU AND SA SIGN RESEARCH PROJECT CO-OPERATION PACT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The European Union and SA signed a co-operation pact yesterday allowing their researchers to take part in joint projects.  The move will allow researchers to co-operate on projects agreed within the bloc's $16bn research programme from 1994 to 1998.<BR><P>
EU APPOINTS DEVELOPMENT SPECIALIST TO LEAD TALKS ON FREE TRADE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
BRUSSELS - Philipp Soubestre, the deputy director-general of the European Commission's development division, has been appointed as the European Union's chief negotiator in trade talks with SA, a Brussels official said yesterday.<BR><P>
BATTLE FOR LEADERSHIP HOTS UP WITHIN PAC <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
Pressures to revamp the Pan Africanist Congress, including new leadership, at its congress next week, are mounting as the party faces electoral obliteration in 1999 unless it reverses its fortunes.  PAC president Clarence Makwetu, who narrowly held on to his position at the partys congress in Bloemfontein last year, will almost certainly be challenged, probably by Methodist Bishop Stanley Magoba.<BR><P>
