<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>THURSDAY, 5 DECEMBER 1996 - at 12H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>





RAND GOLD PRICE BOLSTERS MINES <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The devaluation of the rand against the dollar would outweigh the recent decline in the dollar gold price - which plunged to a $368/oz three-year low this week - and support South African gold mines' December quarterly revenues, industry sources said yesterday.<BR><P>
THE OFFICIAL MANUAL ON GOLD <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel will not have endeared himself to the gold industry by calling gold a "diminishing commodity".  Speaking at an Australian finance conference, he said "the short-term prospect for the gold price is certainly not very encouraging for gold-producing countries like ourselves  it's pretty scary".<I> [see also yesterday's news - Ed.]</I><BR><P>
LACK OF INVESTMENT 'FAULT OF THIRD WORLD GOVTS' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
MELBOURNE - The World Bank yesterday blamed developing nations' governments for the disappointing level of private-sector involvement in infrastructure projects.  "We are still not seeing regulatory frameworks from governments that allow investors to come in and feel comfortable to operate over the 20- to 30-year live span of the projects", said World Bank private-sector development group chairman Richard Frank.<BR><P>
IDC TO INVEST R20BN IN INDUSTRIAL DEVELOPMENT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Industrial Development Corporation was planning to invest R20bn in industrial development over the next five years, the parastatal said yesterday when it reported an 11,2% improvement in after-tax income to R258m for the year to June 1996.<BR><P>
COUNCIL FORECASTS CONFLICTIVE BARGAINING <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Rising inflation and a slowdown of economic growth indicate that next year will produce a tougher bargaining environment than this year, says a report in the December issue of the SA Labour Bulletin.<BR><P>
SA MINING HOUSES DENY REBELS' CLAIMS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Anglo American and De Beers have denied claims by Zairean rebels that the South African groups had active operations in the strife-torn central African country.<BR><P>
IMPALA'S SOUL-SEARCHING LEADS TO NEW VISION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The European Community's decision to reject the proposed merger of Impala Platinum and Lonrho Platinum inspired a period of soul-searching for the South African company - a period from which it has since emerged with a new vision.  MD Steve Kearney says Impala Platinum, in which Gencor has a 45,5% stake, still wants to unlock the value of its stake in Lonrho, but that it recognises its future success lies in developing its own resources at more economic levels.<BR><P>
<B>SOUTH AFRICA'S NEW CONSTITUTION:</B><BR>
CONSTITUTION WINS COURT'S APPROVAL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Constitutional Court yesterday unanimously approved the revised Constitution, which will be signed by President Mandela in Sharpeville on Human Rights Day next week.<BR>
CONSTITUTION READY FOR PRESIDENTS SIGNATURE <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
South Africas new constitution is to come into force in February before the new Parliamentary session, political sources said.  President Nelson Mandela will sign the constitution at a ceremony at Sharpeville on Tuesday.  <BR>
THE LAW ENSHRINED <I>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
When the Constitutional Court confirmed the Constitution yesterday, it did so more in an atmosphere of relief than of celebration, even though a celebration is clearly called for.  The judgement brings to an end an arduous, six-year political process, during which SA's political ship was buffeted by extremism and threatened by chaos.  But it held its course and emerged with its principles intact and its structures strengthened beyond expectations.<BR>
PARTIES WELCOME START OF 'NEW ERA OF DEMOCRACY' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The certification of the Constitution signified the end of a unique process begun during the most trying times in SA, President Nelson Mandela said yesterday.<BR><P>
RETRENCHMENTS IN PUBLIC SERVICE LIKELY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Government is expected to begin retrenching public servants next year after its efforts to cut staff numbers through voluntary severance packages failed to produce meaningful results.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
JOB SEEKERS FACE BLEAK PROSPECTS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
In the first eight months of the year, the economy (excluding agriculture) shed about 60 000 jobs.  On the basis of current trends, the job loss will be even bigger by the end of the year.<BR>
<B><I>... while ...</I></B><BR>
EMPLOYMENT RISES IN MANUFACTURING <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Employment in the manufacturing sector rose 0,1% or 818 workers in August, according to figures released yesterday by the Central Statistical Service.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
SA IMPERATIVES CALL FOR STATE INTERVENTION <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
According to a recent study by Hay Consultants, the salary-to-wage ratio between the wealthiest and the poorest has grown significantly since the elections in 1994.  Further, gross domestic product growth of about 3% has resulted in actual loss of jobs in manufacturing and other sectors during this period.<BR><P>
BLACK SA INVESTORS MOVING INTO NEW PHASE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
MELBOURNE - Black South African investment executives said on Wednesday their empowerment strategy was now seeking to build skills and employment through greater management involvement and greenfield operations.<BR><P>
MANDELA CONFIRMS DECISION ON TAIWAN <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
President Mandela reaffirmed government's decision to break diplomatic ties with Taiwan during a meeting yesterday with that country's Foreign Minister John Chang, who is understood to have asked for a two-year extension of the phase-down of formal relations.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
DITCHING TAIWAN WAS THE RIGHT MOVE <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Betrayal, appeasement, kow-towing to the communists.  Some of the damning comments following President Mandela's decision to switch diplomatic allegiance from Taiwan to China have been stronger than this, and even unpublishable.  All of these are wrong, though.  In fact, Mandela took the wisest and most courageous choice.  The "why" question answers itself with numbers.  China will be spending $1-trillion over the next 10 years on infrastructural projects alone.  Its 1,2-billion people make it the world's largest emerging market.  To have denied SA an opportunity to get a piece of this would surely have amounted to economic treason.<BR><P>
SA TO TAKE OVER DEBT <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The cabinet officially approved an agreement yesterday to take over Namibia's pre-independence SA government-guaranteed debt.  The debt take-over had been agreed to by President Mandela and Namibia's President Sam Nujoma. <BR><P>
EUPHORIA SOURED AS TRADE HOPES DASHED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
HARARE - Euphoria over last week's progress in the latest round of Zimbabwe-SA trade talks evaporated yesterday, apparently as a result of dashed hopes that SA would drop its 90% tariff on Zimbabwe's textile and clothing exports by year end.<BR><P>
INDIA AND SA SIGN 3 AGREEMENTS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
NEW DELHI - India and SA signed three agreements, including one on defence co-operation, on the first day of SA Deputy President Thabo Mbeki's four-day visit to India yesterday, Sapa reports.<BR><P>
PRETORIA 'PRETTIEST' <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Pretoria has been named the world's most beautiful garden city, the city council said yesterday, beating 300 other cities in an international garden city competition held in Bangalore, India.<BR><P>

</DOC>
