<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>WEDNESDAY, 4 DECEMBER 1996 - at 12H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



INGWE SELLS TO KANGRA <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Ingwe Coal Corporation yesterday said it had sold its Savmore/Mpisi and Maquasa land, reserves, buildings, plants and mining infrastructure assets as a going concern to Kangra Group.<BR><P>
LOWEST GOLD PRICE IN THREE YEARS PROMPTS ANOTHER PURGE ON JSE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The London gold price dipped to its lowest level since November 1993, prompting another purge of the Johannesburg Stock Exchange gold sector yesterday.<BR><P>
MINE DEATH TOLL CONFIRMED <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The death toll in the Roberts Victor Diamond Mine disaster was confirmed as 20 yesterday <I>[after management confirmed that two workers who were absent from work at the time had been located alive -Ed.]</I>.<BR><P>
RESERVE BANK SETS UP WORKING GROUP <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Reserve Bank has created a working group to develop a national standard for digital identification to ensure that "open architecture" electronic payment and trading systems, including the Internet, were as secure as possible.<BR><P>
ADVISERS' DIFFERENCES DELAYING COMPETITION POLICY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The task team advising government on reshaping its competition policy appears to be facing the spectre of disintegrating - fuelling speculation of further delays in revamping SA's impotent competition law, sources close to the team have said.<BR><P>
MOSSGAS GETS ISO 14001 <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Mossgas has become one of about 80 companies world-wide and the first in SA to obtain the International Standards Organisation's 14001 certification for environmental management and control for its full operations.<BR><P>
CONSTITUTIONAL COURT CERTIFICATION EXPECTED TODAY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Constitutional Court would deliver judgement today on whether the Constitutional Assembly's amendments to the proposed constitution could be certified, the court said yesterday.<BR><P>
JOE MODISE WILL APPLY FOR AMNESTY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
South African Defence Minister Joe Modise intended submitting an amnesty application to the Truth and Reconciliation Commission before the December 14 cut-off date, his military secretary Brigadier Kobus Botha confirmed yesterday.  And the ANC disclosed it had already handed in applications from 200 members.<BR><P>
'LIMITLESS' OPPORTUNITIES FOR TIES BETWEEN INDIA, SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, in Bombay on a five-day official visit at the head of a 33-member delegation, said yesterday SA wanted to increase trade and introduce defence relations with India.<BR><P>
EU TO 'TAKE SNAPSHOTS' OF DEVELOPMENT PLAYERS IN SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The European Union is to undertake a survey of development actors <I>[whatever that means...]</I> in SA ahead of the proposed reforms to its development strategy in the country.<BR><P>
TAIWANESE MINISTER IN BID TO REVERSE RECOGNITION OF CHINA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Taiwanese Foreign Minister John Chang arrived in SA yesterday in an attempt to stop the South African government from switching its diplomatic recognition from Taiwan to China, but officials said SA's foreign policy ambitions made any shift unlikely.<BR><P>
US INVESTIGATES CLAIM THAT SA IS DUMPING STEEL <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
WASHINGTON - The US commerce department has agreed to investigate a complaint that Iscor and Highveld Steel are dumping cut-to-length carbon steel plate in the US market.<BR><P>
FRAUD AMONG COMPANIES' BIGGEST RISKS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The growth of fraud during the past year has emerged as one of the greatest risks facing South African companies, an investigation has found - with costs to the country running at about R2,8bn.<BR><P>
GAUTENG GOVT FORMS TRIBUNAL TO CUT THROUGH RED TAPE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The Gauteng Provincial Legislature yesterday approved the appointment of 80 members of the new Gauteng development tribunal, created to accelerate investment in the province by removing much of the red tape traditionally associated with development projects.<BR><P>
DOMESTIC WORKERS JOIN FIGHT AGAINST CRIME WAVE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
They are not exactly fighting criminals off with their brooms and featherdusters, but domestic workers in the leafy Johannesburg suburbs of Emmarentia and Roosevelt Park are, nevertheless, teaming up with their employers to fight their common enemy.<BR><P>
CONSENSUS ELUDES BUSINESS AND LABOUR <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Negotiations on the green paper on employment standards would continue despite the Congress of SA Trade Unions' view that labour would not get anything beyond what was currently on the table, Cosatu general secretary Sam Shilowa said last week.<BR><P>
DISABLED'S ROLE IN SOCIETY DISTURBING, SAYS MINISTER <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Only 0,26% of SA's disabled people were employed in the open market, and less than half the country's disabled children had access to formal education, Welfare Minister Geraldine Fraser-Moleketi said yesterday.<BR><P>
IMPALA PROJECT MAY GET NOD SOON <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Impala Platinum could approve a R400m decline extension project in the first quarter of next year - the second of six such projects - which will contribute about 200 000oz a year, a fifth of total output, to metal production.<BR><P>
JAKES GERWEL VOICES DESPAIR OF HIGH FINANCE <I>(Business Report, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Jakes Gerwel, director-general in the office of President Mandela, became the second senior government official this year to express his dislike of the international financial markets yesterday. In an opening address to a board meeting of the International Institute for Democracy and Electoral Assistance, he said, "The world seems to be at the mercy of the ungovernable phenomenon of the international financial market," and suggested it be regulated in some way. His remarks were reminiscent of the comment by Finance Minister Trevor Manuel that the "amorphous" financial markets strip governments of their ability to govern.<I> [The remark resulted in international derision from economic experts and market analysts and, some suggested, shattered Manuel's credibility as a minister and cast grave doubt over his ability to handle his portfolio - Ed.] </I><BR><P>
<B><I>... but ...</I></B><BR>
MANUEL SAYS SA ECONOMY WILL GROW 3% DESPITE ITS DIFFICULTIES<I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
The South African economy will grow by 3% this year in spite of financial difficulties, Finance Minister Trevor Manuel told the National Trade and Investment Outlook conference in Melbourne yesterday.<BR><P>
STRENGTH OF DOLLAR TAKES TOLL ON RAND <I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
The rand has held up better against a basket of currencies of SA's trading partners this week than it has against the dollar alone, analysts said yesterday.<BR><P>
SA AMONG TOP EMERGING MARKET CLUB <I> (Business Report)</I><BR>
The United States' commerce department has classified SA on a short-list of "big emerging markets" alongside budding markets such as China, Indonesia, South Korea, Mexico, Brazil and Poland, Connecticut-based Southern African Analysis & Advice said in its newsletter for November/December released yesterday.<BR><P>
FOREIGN FUNDS NEEDED IN CHINA COAL MINING <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
BEIJING -China's inefficient coal sector needs foreign funds and technology to modernise, but must do more to create a better investment environment, industry officials and foreign businessmen said on Tuesday.<BR><P>
MINISTER CALLS FOR TOURISM OVERHAUL <I>(Cape Times, Cape Town)</I><BR>
Environmental Affairs and Tourism Minister Pallo Jordan, highly critical of the way in which the historical and cultural experiences of a large section of the South African population have been ignored, maintains that the countrys tourist potential is not being fully exploited.  "A paradigm shift is needed in how we market the country.  There are more dimensions to tourism in SA than only flora and fauna and beautiful beaches that are indistinguishable from the beaches of Majorca and Laguna."  Jordan said the country had "so much more to offer".  Its rich diversity of cultural and historical experiences could become a unique selling point internationally.<BR><P>


