<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>TUESDAY, 3 DECEMBER 1996 - at 12H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>



CENTRAL BANKS SPECULATORS SEEN BEHIND GOLD'S LOW <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
Gold's recent lows could be attributed to central bank selling and producers trying to make up shortfalls in their forward sales positions, South African gold analysts said on Monday.<BR><P>
SA INCREASES GOLD EXPORTS TO DUBAI <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
SA exported 10,29 tons of gold to Dubai in the first 10 months of this year, sharply up from the 8,96 tons exported for all of last year, the World Gold Council has disclosed.  <BR><P>
DIAMOND RUSH THREATENS ANGOLAN PEACE <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
LUCAPA, ANGOLA - One of the major threats to lasting peace in Angola is wrangling over control of the country's diamond fields, some of the richest on earth.<BR><P>
MEASURING PROGRESS <I>(Business Day Editorial Comment)</I><BR>
In years ahead, the Central Statistical Service's annual October household survey should become as important a document as government's annual budget.  They are, after all, the two sides of the same coin.  Taken over time, the survey is as comprehensive a measure as we are likely to find of the improvement or deterioration of the material aspects of our citizens' quality of life.  Those are, ultimately, the end to which government and society's efforts are directed.  The Budget, on the other hand, is the fiscal mechanism which determines - directly and indirectly - in large part how those ends are to be prioritised and financed.<BR><P>
E-CASH MAY CHANGE THE FACE OF BUSINESS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The advent of electronic cash could change the way we conduct business and the way governments run their economies - Let us say you are tired of living in SA and want to pull up stakes and start anew elsewhere.  Right now, because of exchange controls, you would have difficulty taking your savings with you.  The advent of electronic cash could change that.<BR><P>
SACP, COSATU PUSH FOR NATIONALISATION <I>(The Citizen, Jhb.)</I><BR>
CAPE TOWN - The SA Communist Party and Congress of SA Trade Unions, the ANCs two alliance partners, yesterday called for a move to economic socialism in SA. Yesterdays bilateral talks follow open dissatisfaction among Communist and socialist groups over the ANC governments commitment to a market economy, as set out in the macro-economic strategy. Cosatu and the SACP reaffirmed their commitment to the Tripartite Alliance with the ANC, but wanted a move towards nationalisation and away from privatisation.<BR><P>
EXPORTS BONANZA BOOSTS TRADE SURPLUS <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA enjoyed an export bonanza in October, with the weak rand and a surge in diamond sales pushing the trade surplus to a record R3,9bn.<BR><P>
STRATEGY TO CREATE JOBS <I>(Sowetan, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Creating a working nation instead of a nation of workers is Labour Minister Tito Mbowenis major task in his quest for employment <I>[sic]. </I>Mboweni says he is looking forward to the day when people create employment for themselves instead of waiting for somebody else to give them a job.<BR><P>
HEAD OF DIAMOND BOARD SUMMARILY SACKED <I>(Sake-Beeld, Jhb.)</I><BR>
Gerhard Bindeman, for the last 17 years CEO of the SA Diamond Board, was informed without any prior notice on Thursday that his services had been summarily terminated. Sake-Beeld has been told the decision to relieve Bindeman (55) of his post was taken at Cabinet level. No reasons for the step were given in the letter from Minister of Minerals and Energy Penuell Maduna delivered to Bindeman on Thursday.<BR><P>
CAXTON WILL TRY TO STOP FINANCIAL MAIL SALE <I>(Citizen)</I><BR>
Caxton Ltd. said yesterday it would seek a court order to prevent the possible sale of a stake in Times Media Limiteds <I>Financial Mail</I> magazine to UK group, Pearson Plc., following a court judgement. The Appeal Court on Friday ruled in favour of Caxtons bid to block Independent Newspapers Holdings Ltd., formerly Argus Newspapers, and Omni Media Corporation Ltd., owners of TML, from publishing magazines, suburban newspapers and "free-sheets".<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
MEDIA UPHEAVAL <I>(The Star, Jhb.)</I><BR>
The decision by the Appeal Court to uphold a restraint-of-trade agreement has had immediate and far-reaching effects within the media industry. <I>The Star</I> has lost its free-standing regional supplements<I> Looking North, South, East</I> and <I>West, </I>and Caxton has been prohibited from publishing daily paid newspapers.<BR><P>
BID TO FIGHT CYBERSPACE PIRACY <I>(Star)</I><BR>
GENEVA - Negotiators and industry officials met in Geneva yesterday to modernise copyright legislation for the multibillion-dollar information superhighway, with efforts to stamp out cyberspace piracy high on the agenda.<BR><P>

