<HEAD>

<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa: Mining News</TITLE></head>
 <BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080"><Center><b><center><b><b><font size=4>MONDAY, 2 DECEMBER 1996 - at 12H00 GMT+2 </font></b></b></center></center><BR>




NAIL TO FOCUS ON INDUSTRIALS AFTER MINING HOUSE BID FAILS <I>(Business Day, Jhb.)</I><BR>
New Africa Investments Ltd. (Nail) will pursue a business strategy focused on industrial assets in future after its failed bid to win control of mining house JCI Ltd. from Anglo American last week.<BR><P>
ANALYSTS SAY DE BEERS GROUP REMAINS A GEM <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Exactly one year ago, De Beers Consolidated Mines' shares were at a historic low of R102 - 38% below this Friday's closing price of R140,75. Although the share is off its record high of R152 reached in June this year, analysts still consider the group a gem.<BR><P>
RAND HAS PLENTY ROOM TO STRENGTHEN, SAYS MANUEL <I>(Business Report , Jhb.)</I><BR>
MELBOURNE - The rand is set to strengthen against major currencies in the near term, having been oversold during recent bouts of weakness, Finance Minister Trevor Manuel said yesterday.<BR><P>
SHOCK DATA SET TO SHAKE THE MARKETS <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Analysts in the financial markets were rudely surprised on Friday by a Reserve Bank announcement that private sector credit growth jumped from 18,05% in September to 18,86% in October and M3 money-supply growth rose from 14,51% in September to 15,81% in October.<BR><P>
REPORT FIRES SPECULATION ON ECONOMY <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Speculation spread again yesterday that the government, the Reserve Bank and business were working together on measures designed to bolster the rand and rebuild confidence in the economy.<BR><P>
INDIA GOLD MEETING HIGHLIGHTS GOLD'S USES - WGC <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
NEW DELHI - Delegates to a global conference on gold on Friday called for steps to use the precious metal for the benefit of national economies of the developing countries.<BR><P>
CHINA'S 1997 GOLD DEMANDS SEEN RISING BY 10% <I>(Reuters)</I><BR>
HONG KONG - Gold demand in China, one of the world's largest consumers, could surge by as much as 10% in 1997 to 246 tonnes, with the biggest increase coming from secondary cities, a World Gold Council official says.<BR><P>
MINES MAY SELL OWN GOLD <I>(Business Times, with the Sunday Times)</I><BR>
A deal permitting mines to market their own gold production is believed to be imminent.<BR><P>
GOLD FALLS THROUGH LONG-TERM SUPPORT LEVEL OF $372 <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Gold continued its downward spiral on Friday, breaking through the perceived long-term support level of $372/oz to fix in London in the afternoon at $371,30, close to a 31-month low.  It closed at $371,35, down $1,35 from Thursday's close.<BR><P>
MBEKI TO VISIT INDIA <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki will visit India this week to sign agreements on investment and double taxation, his office said on Friday.<BR><P>
HUGE REGIONAL IRON PROJECT IN PIPELINE <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
HARARE - Zimbabwean government ministers and JCI heads have announced the launch of feasibility studies for a giant iron project that would link three southern African states.<BR><P>
UNISA STUDY DETAILS SHIFTS IN SA ECONOMY <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
Economic activity in SA remained heavily concentrated geographically, but there had been significant shifts in relative sectoral strength, typical of a maturing economy, a University of SA study has shown.<BR><P>
GERMAN COMPANIES POISED TO INVEST IN SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
MUNICH - A flurry of new German investments and partnerships are to follow in the wake of a recent top-level business delegation visit to SA.<BR><P>
EMIGRATION SURGE HITS INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY <I>(Business Times)</I><BR>
A surge in emigration is adding to critical staff shortages in the technology industry, raising concerns about SA's ability to maintain and develop its computer systems.<BR><P>
DEMOCRACY FAILS TO WIPE OUT HISTORY'S INEQUALITIES <I>(Business Times)</I><BR>
Two years of democracy have done little to ease the plight of the black population, with racial and gender inequalities still a depressing factor of life in SA.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
SURVEY FINDS SOCIAL INEQUALITIES ARE STILL RIFE IN SA <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
SA still has a long way to go towards eliminating inequalities in key areas of its social life, Central Statistical Service's October 1995 household survey has found.<BR>
<B><I>... and ...</I></B><BR>
A THIRD OF SA 'CAN'T FIND WORK' <I>(Business Report)</I><BR>
Almost one-third of SA's economically active population is unemployed, the Central Statistical Service's October Household Survey for last year shows.<BR><P>
INCREASE IN OIL PRICE COSTS LOCAL COMPANIES R500M THIS YEAR <I>(Business Day)</I><BR>
The continued rise in oil prices this year has cost South African oil companies about R500m in lost revenue, a result of the way monthly petrol, diesel and paraffin price adjustments are calculated.<BR><P>
TAIWAN DEAL KEPT OPEN <I>(Business Times)</I><BR>
Taiwan state oil monopoly Chinese Petroleum says it will defer to the Taiwanese government when considering whether to continue its investment project in SA. <BR><P>
