<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Chamber of Mines of South Africa Mining and Minerals Policy</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000080">

<A NAME="resource"></A>
<B>3. RESOURCE MANAGEMENT</B><P>

<b>General Comment</B><P>

This section, in focusing on mineral rights and security of tenure, is central to policy on mining and mineral rights.  The great majority of employers who are familiar with the current system or who have invested heavily on the strength of the security of tenure assured by the current system support the arguments raised below for its retention.<P>

<B>3.1 	MINERAL RIGHTS</B><P>

<dl>
<dt><b>3.1.2	iii)</b><br>	<dd>It is misleading to speak of an international trend towards the 	public ownership of mineral rights.  There is a discernible 	international trend towards a reduced role for governments in 	economic activities, as evidenced by the reduction of the role of 	government in the mining industry, often by the privatisation of 	State controlled mineral lands and enterprises.<P>

	We disagree that private rights should be passed to the State. It has not been demonstrated that private as opposed to State ownership of mineral rights discourages mining.<P><br>

<dt><B>3.1.3	ii)</B><BR>	<dd>On the contrary, in South Africa private ownership has supported 	the development of one of the worlds most significant mining 	industries.  Despite the nature of South Africas geology there is a 	vibrant small-scale mining sector.  In many cases the small-scale 	mining enterprises are themselves the owners of mineral rights, 	which ownership has contributed to their success. It is not evident 	that the transfer of mineral rights to the State will result in 	successful exploration and mining;  the contrary is true where poor 	administration by the State impedes rather than promotes 	development.<P>


<dt><B>3.1.3	iv)</b><br> 	<dd>Agreed.  Nor has private ownership done so in South Africa.  	Although it is recognised that a system of State-held mineral rights 	has not prevented high-cost, long-term mining projects in countries 	such as Chile and Australia, it must be noted that neither country 	possesses the same degree of dominance that South Africa does in 	any one vital commodity. Any mineral rights dispensation in South 	Africa must recognise the countrys unique position of possessing 	vast resources of several critical commodities such as manganese, 	chrome, platinum/rhodium and vanadium resulting in South 	Africas ability to produce at a level far exceeding the worlds ability 	to consume. Countries usually suggested as models for a new South 	African mineral rights dispensation such as Chile, Australia, 	Canada etc., have no comparable position of dominance in even one 	such vital commodity. Private mineral rights owned by mining 	companies are largely related to deposits unsuitable for small-scale 	exploitation and are held as part of current or long term large-scale 	mining plans.  Local owners should be judged on their outstanding 	track record not only in terms of expanding production from their 	privately owned mineral resources in line with the growth in 	demand but also in the investment of substantial funds in long 	term market development and promotion to create such market 	growth. This track record clearly demonstrates that the exploitation 	of their privately held mineral rights represents the responsible 	husbanding of a commodity in line with market demand and not a 	dog in the manger sterilisation of mineral resources.<P>

<dt><b>3.1.3	vi)</b><br>	<dd>The majority of employers dispute the basis for the criticism 	referred to.  It is their view that under current South African law 	security and continuity of tenure derive from security of ownership 	and from a system of State authorisations to prospect or mine.  The 	system of private ownership is consistent with a free market in 	which rights may be held, acquired, encumbered and disposed of in 	a variety of ways within a regulatory framework that specifies 	appropriate standards for example on safety, health and the 	environment.<p>

	The point noted in the third sentence of paragraph 3.1.3 vi) is specious - South African companies exploring and mining in other states must operate in accordance with the laws applicable there<P>

<dt><B>3.1.4	iii)</B><br>	<DD>One should distinguish between the existing legal framework - 	which is adequate for small-scale mining - and the need to improve 	administration of the law.  A unique legal framework for micro-	scale mining suggests untenable distinctions between the 	health 	safety and environmental standards applicable to such mining and 	those applicable to small scale and large mines. Artisanal mining 	has created major problems elsewhere in the world. Whether or not 	to promote this sector in South Africa requires much further debate.<p>

<DT><B>3.1.4	iv)</B><br>	<DD>Joint ventures should be the product of business decisions.  Access 	to mineral rights currently held by the State should be improved.  	The reference to unused mineral rights is far too broad and would 	encompass rights acquired or held for future use.<P>

<DT><B>3.1.4	v)</B><BR>	<DD>The great majority of employers disagree. In their view, the 	statement in paragraph 3.1.4 v) presupposes that State ownership 	of mineral rights is superior to the current mixed system in which 	the majority of mineral rights are owned by the State and the 	minority by various private owners, including mining companies.  	The location of rights within the private sector places them nearer 	to the market and less immediately within discretionary powers 	available to the State.<P>


	The fact of significant private ownership of mineral rights within the current system of mining and mineral rights has attracted particular criticism.  Two lines of reasoning are implicit in this criticism, namely that the arrangement currently in place has -<p>
<ul>
<li>	not been conducive to the optimal exploration and exploitation of mineral resources;<p>

<li>	supported a maldistribution of the benefits derived from mining.<p>
</ul>
	The first of these lines of reasoning appears to ignore the enormous success achieved both in mining and the expansion and growth of the mining industry in South Africa.  The second line of reasoning is distorted and superficial because the distribution of benefits from mining is the product of a very complex interaction of factors such as past job reservation, conditions of employment, taxation, mining lease consideration, shareholding and investment in mining companies (whether directly or indirectly through pension funds) and so on.  It is therefore a mistake to suppose that had a system of State ownership of mineral rights existed in South Africa, it would have caused any different distribution of the benefits derived from mining.  It is not the system of mineral rights ownership that determines the distribution of benefits.  The State's policy towards encouraging the security of mining will affect the creation of wealth from mining and, if that policy is successful, result in a distribution of benefits through jobs, taxation, dividends and so on.<P>

	Private ownership of mineral rights makes it possible for mineral rights to be traded and exchanged.  A system of formal titles brings these assets into the market economy and affords sufficient security of tenure to allow the active participation of mining companies.  This security has also benefited the junior companies and individuals as the title to mineral rights can be pledged to obtain development finance.  The existence of private ownership of mineral rights within South African mineral law is consistent with a market economy and is part of the balance struck between private enterprise and State control.  The private ownership component of the system cannot be unscrambled on an equitable and efficient basis.  Expropriation of the relevant property rights would require payment of compensation not only in view of constitutional law but also because any taking of such rights by the State without compensation is likely to wipe out foreign investment interest.  The burden of compensating holders for their investment in acquisition and exploration and for the market value of their mineral rights would be enormous and have a high opportunity cost.  Furthermore, there would be no certainty that any compensation paid would be reinvested in mining.<P>

	There exists a very active market in the acquisition and disposal of mineral rights.  The relationship between a market economy and mineral rights goes far beyond any mechanism for transactions in mineral rights between private individuals, however.  The South African mining industry must also be competitive in world markets.  In order to be competitive in world markets minerals should not be exploited unless there is demand for them on those markets and not necessarily when they are discovered or because their presence has been proven.  The right to defer exploitation of mineral resources in the interests of optimal utilisation is one of the advantages of the South African system where the holder of a mineral right is a participant in a market system vis-a-vis a system ruled by the commercial judgement and political priorities of the State.  A market in which several individuals can participate freely on the basis of differing views offers opportunities for balance that would not be equally available if the State were to play the dominant role as sole owner.  Under conditions of private ownership the views taken by holders of mineral rights are frequently different from one another and are responsive to a wide range of factors including, for example, different perceptions amongst separate bodies of shareholders.<P>

	If one compares without prejudice the South African system of mining and mineral rights with foreign systems based upon licences granted by the State as the sole owner of all rights to minerals in the land, it becomes apparent that the South African system is not the only workable one.  The point to be made here is that the South African system provides the security of tenure that has enabled mining houses to take a very long view and bear the risk inherent in turning the minerals to account.  The South African system of mining and mineral rights has developed to suit South African geological conditions.  Other systems may work well in other countries.  There is no guarantee that they will work here.  One cannot entirely recast the South African system in the mould of a theoretical alternative system without enormous cost, risk of damage to and dislocation of the South African mining industry.<P>

	It must be noted that any move towards a system of coercive transfer of privately owned mineral rights to the State will almost immediately result in the cessation of market development and promotion programmes by the affected owners.  The consequence will be to change the emphasis of such industries from enhancing profit margins by expanding the market for the main benefit of South Africa to one of focussing only on maintaining market share through cost cutting.<P>


<DT><B>3.1.4	vii)</B><br>	<dd>The proposal outlined in the first sentence of paragraph 3.1.4 vii) 	in respect of State-held mineral rights may have merit, subject to 	its impact on security of tenure, particularly in relation to rights 	previously encumbered by the State in respect of that class of land 	previously known as alienated State land. The State, where it is the 	mineral right holder, has the capacity to promote mineral 	exploration and exploitation (including by foreign, domestic, and 	small-scale operators) by granting rights to prospect, rights to mine, 	and even alienating the mineral rights themselves, within existing 	provisions in the legislation.  In particular, small-scale mining can 	be promoted on areas formerly open to pegging (the rights to 	minerals in the majority of which are held by the State) by the 	State granting short-term mineral leases coupled with mining 	permits, with proper regard to safety, health and rehabilitation.<P>  

<DT><B>3.1.4	x)</B><br>	<DD>There is scope within the current law for the State to intervene 			against the sterilisation of mineral exploitation.<P>

	With regard to the proposed minerals tax we refer to our comments on paragraph 1.3.2 vii) and 1.3.3 iv) above.  In addition should the purpose of such a tax be to coerce the transfer of mineral rights from the private sector to the State, rather than to generate revenue, this would be wrong in principle.<P>

<DT><B>3.2.2	iii)</B><br>	<DD>One needs more than clear guidelines;  security of tenure and 	certainty in the law are essential.<P>

<DT><B>3.2.3	iv)</B><br>	<DD>This contains the seeds of a pernicious doctrine under which 	compliance with the law may be visited by punishment.<P></DT></DL></DL>

<center>
<a href="compol2.htm#top"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb2.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Top of Page" hspace=20></a>
<a href="#toolbar"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Toolbar" hspace=20></a>
</center><p><p>



<A NAME="exploration"></A>
<dt><b>4.  EXPLORATION</dt></b><p>

<B>General Comment</b><p>

The majority of employers take the view that the law currently in place does not inhibit exploration and gives proper protection to geological information obtained at risk and considerable cost.<P>


<dt><B>4.3	v)</B><br>	<DD>See comment on paragraph 1.2.2 vi) above.<P>

<DT><B>4.4	vi)</B><BR>	<DD>We do not reject the application of incentives in appropriate cases. 	Regard should be had to the view of the Katz Commission Into 	Certain Aspects of the Tax Structure of South Africa that incentives 	should be subject to a cost benefit analysis narrowed as far as 	possible and justified in terms of the objectives of the 	Reconstruction and Development Programme.<P>

<dt><b>4.4	viii)</B><BR>	<dd>We disagree with the so-called use it or lose it principle.<P>

<dt><b>4.4	x)</b><BR>	<DD>The establishment of the Council for Geosciences has led to an 	improvement in the work previously performed by the Geological 	Survey Branch of the Department of Mineral and Energy Affairs.  	However, this comment should be read with our comment on section 	15 below.<P>

<center>
<a href="compol2.htm#top"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb2.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Top of Page" hspace=20></a>
<a href="#toolbar"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Toolbar" hspace=20></a>
</center><p><p>

<A NAME="environment"></A> 
<dt><B>5.  ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT</DT></B><P>

<B>General Comment</B><P>

The South African mining industry has for many years taken a responsible attitude towards managing its impact on the environment.  For that reason it participated in and supported the development of environmental management programme reports (EMPRs) as a legal requirement.  The EMPR process follows integrated environmental management principles and ensures that a full assessment of environmental impacts will be made in regard to a prospecting or mining venture, in which the no project option can be considered.  If it is decided that prospecting or mining should take place, the process provides for responsible management of the environmental impact as well as for consultation with local committees and others affected by the operations. South Africas overwhelming need for economic development and job creation demands that a balance be struck between this need and environmental concerns.  It will be necessary to ensure co-ordination between the development of environmental management policy as part of a mining and minerals policy and parallel processes for example, CONNEP.<P>


<dt><B>5.2	ii)</B><BR>	<dd>The last part of paragraph 5.2 ii) fails to recognise that in terms of 	the current law site rehabilitation must be conducted 	simultaneously with mining operations, and not just when a mining 	activity has ceased.<P>

<dt><b>5.4	vi)</b><br>	<dd>The consultation should take place at the EMPR stage, but not 	necessarily at the planning stage. It should be at the discretion of 	the mining company to determine at what stage in its planning 	process to engage in external consultation.<P>

<DT><b>5.4	vii)</B><BR>	<dd>We disagree.  Catchment management schemes should be 	administered and managed by the relevant stakeholders, including 	mining companies.  Where feasible, the cost of remedying pollution 	- which would not necessarily be confined to pollution from mining 	operations - should be based on the polluter pays principle:  	provided that excessive costs should not be imposed on a mine for 	remedying pollution resulting from activities that in the past were 	consistent with regulatory requirements but do not meet current 	requirements.<P>

<DT><b>5.4	viii)</b><br>	<DD>We disagree.  This goes beyond issues of environmental 	management and implies the imposition of cost burdens on mines 	that could render them financially non-viable<p>

<DT><B>5.4	ix)</b><br>	<DD>Mines differ enormously in their impact on the environment and in 	their financial circumstances.  Appropriate measures for making 	financial provision for environmental expenditures would depend 	on particular circumstances in each case.  Great care must be taken 	to avoid an inflexible policy that would impose unduly onerous 	burdens that may destroy an enterprise.<p>

<DT><b>5.4	xi)</b><br>	<dd>We disagree. The polluter pays principle should be a cornerstone of 	national policy.  The proposed levy contradicts this principle.  	Where perpetrators cannot be identified, funding should come from 	the central fiscus.  For future damage, the EMPR process will 	ensure that the polluter pays.<p>

<center>
<a href="compol2.htm#top"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb2.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Top of Page" hspace=20></a>
<a href="#toolbar"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Toolbar" hspace=20></a>
</center><p><p>

<A NAME="small scale"></A> 
<DT><b>6.  SMALL-SCALE MINING AND MINERAL DEVELOPMENT</dt></b><p>

<b>General Comment</b><p>


For the sake of clarity, one should distinguish between small-scale mines and artisanal mines.  There are significant environmental and health and safety problems associated with artisanal mining, which form of mining is sometimes the only means of subsistence available to individuals.  For policy purposes great caution must be exercised before making any commitment to promoting such mining.<p>

For small-scale mines in the formal sector we believe that there should be equal treatment with large mines in respect of environmental and health and safety standards.  In addition, small-scale mines should be given adequate opportunity to participate in consultations on the formulation of policy and laws.<p>

New or emerging entrepreneurs in the formal small-scale mining sector should be encouraged and promoted where this can be done on sound economic and business principles and having regard to the nature of the mineral deposit.<p>

<DT><b>6.2	iii)</b><br>	<dd>We must stress in relation to the second sentence that the cost and 		availability of aggregate and sand will be determined by the 			market.<p>

<dt><b>6.3	 i)</b><br>	<dd>We disagree with the view that South Africa has an inactive small- 	scale mining sector.  The 1990 Mining Survey published by Central 	Statistical Services indicates that approximately 75% of the mines 	surveyed were small mines.  There is a sizeable small-scale	sector mining a wide variety of minerals used in South African 	industry.<p>

<dt><b>6.3	x)</B><br>	<dd>We disagree. No firms have closed down, but some operators have 	closed a number of quarries that were not economically viable.  A 	study by the Aggregate and Sand Producers Association of South 	Africa and the Minerals and Energy Policy Centre has indicated 	that the formal quarry industry can cope with the demands 	expected to arise from RDP construction with minimal exceptions.<p>

<dt><b>6.4	xiv)</b><br>	<dd>We recognise that the State can play a useful role in helping new 	entrepreneurs to formulate and implement business plans.  	However, given the existence of several competent bodies that can 	provide this service in the private sector the State should be wary 	about setting up additional structures.<p>

<DT><b>6.4	xvi)</B><br>	<DD>We disagree.  The underlying assumption that State ownership of 	all mineral rights is a precondition for the development of small- 	scale mining is untenable.<p>

<center>
<a href="compol2.htm#top"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb2.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Top of Page" hspace=20></a>
<a href="#toolbar"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Toolbar" hspace=20></a>
</center><p><p>

<A NAME= "exploit"></A>
<dt><B> 7.  EXPLOITATION</b><p>

<b>General Comment</b><p>

This section covers material dealt with in sections 1, 2, 3 and 4 which sections have been commented on above.<p>
<center>
<a href="compol2.htm#top"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb2.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Top of Page" hspace=20></a>
<a href="#toolbar"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Toolbar" hspace=20></a>
</center><p><p>

<A NAME= "downscale"></A> 
<dt><b>8.  DOWNSCALING</dt></b><p>

<B>General comment</b><p>

The society and employers recognise the hardships caused by closure, partial closure and job loss.  To that extent the legislature has imposed clear constraints upon individual and collective termination of employment which are among the most prescriptive in the world.  The addition of further obligations in respect of downscaling would add to the cost of employment, shorten the life of the mines and make employers less willing to employ.<p>

Employers are sensitive to the social consequences of job loss which may affect a community in which they operate or from which they draw their labour. It is, however, primarily the role of the State to attend to the jobless and to create an environment that will facilitate the generation of employment opportunities.<p>

The present and proposed Labour Relations Act imposes a requirement of consultation and collective bargaining with the employees affected.  The proposed Act moreover commands a duty of information disclosure and imposes a statutory, minimum, severance benefit.  The Unemployment Insurance Act requires employers (and employees) to contribute to a national unemployment fund.  In addition, many companies affected by closure or large-scale job loss have established specific retrenchment funds for programmes jointly agreed with the unions concerned.  Most retrenchment procedures negotiated at company level provide for the counselling, training and relocation (wherever possible) of redundant employees.<p>

The role of the State does not extend to the conduct of collective bargaining, which is properly left to the parties directly involved.  Legislation which commands the products of collective bargaining effectively denies collective bargaining to the detriment of corporate and labour market efficiency.<p>

The multiple functions of the State in respect of attending to the jobless, encouraging employment creation and sustainable growth requires co-ordination between ministries and national, regional and local levels of governance.  Employers need to be fully consulted as distinct from obligated to assume the public cost of job loss and unemployment.<p>

The government, nationally and locally, bears a particular responsibility.  The Unemployment Insurance Act is currently under review with the express intent of broadening its jurisdiction to attend to the concerns of the jobless.  Through established Regional Training Centres the Department of Labour provides ready access for employment skills training.  The Department of Trade and Industry is equally attending to programmes which encourage small and medium-size business development.  Many municipal authorities have established community forums inclusive of all stakeholders to manage and monitor the effects of closure and job loss on the community affected.  Evidently a need for the co-ordination of government initiatives arises.<p>

<dt><b>8.3	iii)</b><br>	<dd>The German experience is not instructive in South Africa;  it is a 	product of a unique political, economic, labour market and mining 	sector history. State and federal subsidy to the German coal mining 	industry is annually in excess of the revenues of the South African 	gold mining industry and the number of jobs involved is less than 	5% of the number of persons employed in the mining industry in 	South Africa.  The particular circumstances in Germany brought to 	bear financial resources and institutional capacity on a scale vastly 	in excess of what is available in South Africa.<p>

<DT><b>8.1	iv)</b><br>	<dd>Targeted State assistance to marginal mines returning to 	profitability is an established policy in South Africa.  Assistance to 	mines with no prospect of returning to profitability is an unjustified 	public expenditure and can, at best, only (temporarily) subsidise the 	employed at the expense of the unemployed.<p>

	Closure and job loss are the product of a multitude of factors not easily anticipated or predicted.  It is not effectively planned but has to be managed through disclosure of information, participation, collective bargaining and appropriate statutory assistance for the unemployed and for the creation of sustainable employment opportunities.<p>

<dt><b>8.4	i)</b><br>	<dd>A national plan cannot attend to the different circumstances of 	individuals, companies, communities and regions affected by job 	loss. The country has neither resources nor sufficient institutional 	capacity to apply a national plan.<p>

<dt><b>8.4	iii)</b><br>	<DD>Support for mining and employment creation in mining will require 	that mining authorisation be made easier rather than more 	difficult. Unreasonable entry barriers will discourage investment 	and persuade employers to choose capital rather than labour 	intensive methods of production.<p>

	The comparison with the environment is misleading.  It overlooks the fact that the employee chooses his employment and benefits from that employment.<p>

<DT><b>8.4	iv) & ix)</b><br>		<dd>The circumstances of closure or job loss on a mine, or part of a mine, 	are so diverse as to defy a single prescription.  A fund may be 	appropriate in certain circumstances and not in others, having 	regard to the particular needs, capacities and interests of the 	parties involved.  Reconciling the needs and interests of the parties 	will be best secured through dialogue (and bargaining) in each 	particular instance and cannot reasonably be imposed by statute.<P>

	Raising the cost of employment will lower the level of employment.<p>

	It is unrealistic to suppose that a mine engaged in a struggle for survival should itself be responsible for the redeployment of its workforce.<p>

<DT><b>8.4	vi)</B><br>	<dd>The new Labour Relations Act establishes an advanced 	jurisprudence of trade union (and employee) rights and confers 	wide powers of participation, bargaining (and co-determination) 	(probably equal to) or in advance of anything in the world.  Further 	labour-related legislation in response to special pleadings on 	particular issues around collective bargaining is not appropriate.  	Bargaining is suited to meet the requirements of fairness in the 	workplace while it is the role of the State to address the 	circumstances of the jobless, and the regulatory environment for 	new employment creation.<p>

	Introduction of a Social Plan Act could have disastrous consequences for the mining sector and the people it employs.<p>

<DT><b>8.4	vii)</b><br>	<DD>Downscaling cannot be nationally planned;  this is key to the 	manner in which free markets operate.  There is no single view of 	the market and the terms of its likely expansion or contraction.<p>

	We doubt that any permanent mining commission, anywhere in the world, could be successful in achieving what is suggested.  In any event measures are already being taken at provincial and national levels to promote foreign and domestic investment and we would imagine that such investment would be attracted to localities affected by closure where this is economically advantageous.<p>

<DT><b>8.4	viii)</B><br>	<dd>This is discredited policy which enjoys no currency locally or 	internationally.<p>

<DT><b>8.4	x)</B><br>	<dd>This topic should not form part of a mining and minerals policy 	review. The topic is not unique to mining.  We understand that the 	Department of Labour and the South African Law Commission are 	independently engaged in reviewing relevant aspects of the law of 	insolvency.<p>


<center>
