<DL>

<A NAME= "mining safety"></A>
<dt><b>9.  MINING SAFETY AND HEALTH</dt></B><p>

<b>General Comment</b><p>

The health and safety of mining employees is a key component in any policy on mining.  However, it has very recently undergone comprehensive examination that is likely to find expression in a new statute early in 1996.<p>

The Department of Labour has launched, in co-operation with the Department of Health, an initiative to create a health and safety council whose purpose, among other things, is to ensure harmonization and co-operation between the various health and safety laws and their application in different industries.<p>

On the subject of HIV/AIDS we make the point that HIV/AIDS knows no boundaries.  The formulation of national policy in respect of HIV/AIDS is a responsibility of the government which should develop a national HIV/AIDS plan in consultation with all stakeholders.<p>

For these reasons the current process for the development of mining and minerals policy should not deal with issues of safety and health which have either been settled or are of much wider scope than the mining industry.<p>

<center>
<a href="compol2.htm#top"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb2.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Top of Page" hspace=20></a>
<a href="#toolbar"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Toolbar" hspace=20></a>
</center><p><p>

<A NAME= "human"></A> 
<dt><b>10.  HUMAN RESOURCES</dt></b><p>

<b>General Comment</b><p>

This section is concerned with (a) education and training;  (b) housing and living conditions;  (c) migrant labour;  and (d) industrial relations and employment conditions.  We comment generally on these topics as follows.<P>

<DT><B>(a)</B><BR>	<DD>If the mining sector is to maintain and strengthen its position as a world-class industry, and while the demand for manual labour especially in very deep mines will continue for a long time, it must rely increasingly on the availability of well educated and trained employees.  Provision of an education system which underpins that vital objective is necessarily the responsibility principally of the government.  While the private sector, and most prominently the mining industry, plays a crucial role in seeking to upgrade the countrys primary and secondary education standards, as well as to protect the excellence of certain tertiary institutions, these efforts can only be on top of the core role of the government.  Education and training are being adequately dealt with in other forums and processes and therefore should not be dealt with in the process of formulating mining and minerals policy.<P>

<DT><B>(b)</B><BR>	<DD>Certain large-scale mining owners have for many years provided accommodation for employees.  For reasons rooted in the countrys history a large part of the industrys manual labour requirements was met from rural areas and the accommodation provided for these workers was initially exclusively single-sex and also rudimentary.  Over time there has been considerable upgrading of accommodation including, where affordable and appropriate to the level of the employee, provision of married accommodation.<P>

	More generally, for several years there has been an increasing diversity of practice in the housing of employees in the mining industry and in line with trends in other industries.<P>

	Housing provided by mines is often superior to alternatives that are available to the individual employee.  Improvements have been made in the standard of mine housing, such standards being well in excess of those in respect of accommodation provided by the State.  In the delivery of houses in the RDP, the most conspicuous successes achieved so far have been mine housing in Kutluanong and Kanana.<P>

	Housing is increasingly part of a remuneration package determined by collective bargaining and cannot be settled by national policy.  This subject should not be on the agenda of the current process for the development of mining and minerals policy.<P>

<DT><b>(c)</B><BR>	<DD>The pressure for jobs in South and Southern Africa, and particularly from the rural areas, will inevitable lead to a continuation of migrant labour well into the future.  It is not unique to South Africa and in South Africa it is not unique to the mining industry.  Organised recruitment from rural areas within South Africa and beyond has played crucial and positive roles in enabling development of the industry, shaping the economic geography of the region and providing much needed jobs for rural dwellers.  The practice has negative consequences, such as disruptions to family and community life in the source areas and the creation of a less-than-desirable living environment at the place of work.  But there are offsetting elements such as the generation of income for rural areas that would not have been available otherwise.  In addition, revised working schedules under continuous operating arrangements could offer further improvements.  It should also be borne in mind that permanent residence has recently been conferred upon foreign citizens, including migrant workers in the mining industry, who participated in the 1994 General Election but who were not at the time admitted to the status of permanent residents of South Africa.<P> 

	Migrant labour is a very complex matter and is the subject of continuing interaction between the NUM, the Chamber of Mines of South Africa, TEBA and relevant South African government departments and the foreign governments involved.  It is therefore unnecessary and inappropriate for the subject to be focussed upon in the current process for the development of policy on mining and minerals.<P>

<DT><B>(d)</B><BR>	<DD>Industrial relations matters are best left to arrangements agreed between employers and employees.  Government must recognise that wages and conditions of employment, as well as matters affecting the employment relationship, cannot be settled by the government but need to be determined by owners and employees with regard to their particular interests.  In this respect the government must give primacy to forms of engagement that are designed to ensure meaningful participation by the parties in decisions affecting their responsibilities.  To this end government should commit itself to ensuring a legislative and regulatory environment which secures opportunity for the workplace parties to settle their affairs without intervention.  The owners believe that the necessary institutional arrangements are in place for meaningful discussions with employees on all issues of mutual interest in the workplace.  We have noted that in some parts of the discussion document there is an inaccurate assumption that invariably employees are represented by trade unions.<P>

	Legislation governing employment generally will be developed with the involvement of employers, employees and other stakeholders in other forums adequate for the purpose.  Similarly, legislation relating to corporate governance is not peculiar to the mining industry and should, like labour legislation, not be developed in a process devoted to mining and minerals policy.<P>

<center>
<a href="compol2.htm#top"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb2.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Top of Page" hspace=20></a>
<a href="#toolbar"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Toolbar" hspace=20></a>
</center><p><p>

<A NAME= "mineral"></A>
<DT><B>11.  MINERAL BENEFICIATION</DT></B><P>

<B>General Comment</B><P>


For many decades, where there have been viable opportunities, the mining industry has invested in minerals beneficiation.  Minerals beneficiation projects should be initiated on the basis of market forces and of decisions taken by individual companies using well considered business objectives.  There is no justification for government intervention.<P>

<center>
<a href="compol2.htm#top"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb2.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Top of Page" hspace=20></a>
<a href="#toolbar"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Toolbar" hspace=20></a>
</center><p><p>

 <A NAME= "Mineral mark"></A>
<dt><b>12.  MINERAL MARKETING</DT></B><P>

<B>General Comment</B><P>

The mining industry is energetically involved in promoting, marketing and selling its products locally and internationally.  The promotion and marketing of mineral products in a competitive international milieu is a highly professional activity demanding the sustained application of technical and other specialised skills over many years.<P>

The industry is confident that its promotional and marketing efforts are conducted at the highest levels of competence.  There is no evidence to support the view advanced by some that the state could match the marketing and sales performance of the private sector.  On the contrary experience elsewhere has demonstrated that state marketing institutions have been unsuccessful and have too easily become corrupt.  For these reasons we are emphatically opposed to any government intervention in minerals marketing.<P>

Several of the observations made in the discussion document are entirely without foundation and indicate a lack of understanding of the workings of international markets.<P>

<center>
<a href="compol2.htm#top"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb2.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Top of Page" hspace=20></a>
<a href="#toolbar"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Toolbar" hspace=20></a>
</center><p><p>

 <A NAME= "research"></A>
<DT><B>13.  RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT</DT></B><P>

<b>General Comment</B><P>

Through sustained and concerted commitment to research and development, South African industry is the world leader in deep-level mining technology.  The depth, particularly of gold deposits, and the hardness of the rock in which the gold is embedded have demanded innovative technological solutions from the established mining houses.  Where the mining houses have found it advantageous they have undertaken R&D on a co-operative basis.  This has facilitated dissemination of information across the industry.<P>

The state is involved in R&D in and for the industry through Miningtek (CSIR) and Mintek.  The owners welcome the potential contribution that such R&D can make, provided the R&D agenda is strongly user-driven and genuinely complementary to private sector activity but would question the ability of the State to play a strategic roll in policy formulation for R & D.<P>

Co-operative research in health and safety is essential.  The Safety in Mines Research Advisory Committee (SIMRAC) is the vehicle through which research in the areas of health and safety is co-ordinated.  Such research should be funded in good part by Government.<P>

There is continuing interaction between companies, R & D organisations and universities both locally and internationally in respect of the industrys present and anticipated technological problems.  We do not believe that State intervention could add value to this process of interaction.<P>

<center>
<a href="compol2.htm#top"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb2.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Top of Page" hspace=20></a>
<a href="#toolbar"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Toolbar" hspace=20></a>
</center><p><p>

<A NAME= "regional"></A> 
<DT><B>14.  REGIONALISATION AND INTERNATIONALISATION</DT></B><P>

<b>General Comment</B><P>

For many years the mining industry has had interests and involvements in the Southern African sub-continent.  These initially revolved around the recruitment of labour, which remains a factor critically important to the industry and to several of the countries concerned.  We have also included prospecting and mining operations which, after a static period due to sanctions, are now increasing appreciably.<P>

Given this history as well as the compelling logic for the economic integration of the region in the long term, we are firmly in favour of regional co-operation.  We support a phased removal of the barriers to the free movement of labour, capital, goods and services in such a way as to avoid destabilisation of any countries involved.  The resulting economic benefits will be profound and enduring.<P>

In particular, South African mining companies have technologies and specialised skills in potentially great demand throughout the region and indeed more widely in Africa.  There are associated opportunities for South African equipment suppliers as well as for engineering and other consultancies.  The South African economy thus stands to benefit significantly from regional, indeed continental, co-operation.<P>

South Africa and mining companies within South Africa are at an early stage in developing new relationships with their counterparts in the region.  It is too early to know how matters will develop.  We believe it is premature to give this subject detailed consideration as part of the development of a mining and minerals policy for South Africa.<P>

<center>
<a href="compol2.htm#top"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb2.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Top of Page" hspace=20></a>
<a href="#toolbar"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Toolbar" hspace=20></a>
</center><p><p>

 <A NAME= "govern"></A>
<DT><B>15.  GOVERNANCE</DT></B><P>

<B>General Comment</B><P>

Sensible regulation requires an understanding of the nature and interrelated technical complexities of mining which make the existence of a single, central regulatory agency highly desirable.  That agency should be the Department of Mineral and Energy Affairs (DMEA), working as necessary through its own regional offices.  Because of the way the industry has evolved as well as of the need for consistency of policy and practice across provincial and local boundaries, there should be minimal devolution of authority to separate provincial or lower-level bodies.  Such bodies should not be empowered to create laws or regulations which impact on mining.  In cases where there is a need for issues to be dealt with below national level, a prior consultative process with all affected parties is essential.<P>

The discussion document contains a variety of proposals for new government institutions.  We believe that an overall review is needed of what organisations of government will best serve the industry.  The review should focus, in particular, on efficiency and competence in the administration and functioning of government agencies whose activities have a direct bearing on the mining industry.</DL>


<center>
<a href="/main.htm"> <IMG SRC="/images/nb1.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Main Menu" hspace=20></a>
