<a name="PAPERS"></a>
<h4>CALL FOR PAPERS</h4>
<b>Monday 19 February 1996</b><br><p>

Abstracts of 300-500 words written in English should be sent via e-mail to both symposium
chairmen:<p>
<ul>
<li>      <A HREF="mailto:sturgul@uidaho.edu">Dr. John R. Sturgul</a> (sturgul@uidaho.edu)
<li>      <A HREF="mailto:panagiotou@metal.ntua.gr">Dr. George N. Panagiotou</a> (panagiotou@metal.ntua.gr)
</ul>
and should include: paper's title, author(s)' name, e-mail address and affiliation.<p>

<B>Deadline for receipt of abstracts</B>:  <FONT SIZE=4 COLOR=FF0000>June 1, 1996</FONT><p>

The authors of accepted papers will receive a notification of paper's acceptance via e-mail
by June 28, 1996.<p>


All papers should be written in English. Authors have two choices:<br>
<ol>
<li> To prepare and submit the paper in the form of a .HTM formatted file with graphics
and pictures in .GIF format. If this is the case, the organizers will consider this paper as
ready for publication (i.e. "camera ready") and will make no changes, except of the title and
author's name that should be uniform for all papers.
<li>To prepare and submit the paper in the form of a  .DOC or  .TXT formatted file
with graphics and pictures in  .PCX format. In this case, the symposium's staff at NTUA
will code up the paper in HTML (HyperText Mark-up Language) and convert graphics in 
.GIF format.
</ul>
The deadlines for submission of papers are:<br>
<ul>
<li>HTML ready papers:         October 31, 1996
<li>Text file papers:          September 30, 1996
</ul>
Authors of papers can submit their own WEB pages to be included in the WEB site.  In
addition, WEB pages of their affiliations can be included.<p>

<center>
<a href="/main.htm"> <IMG SRC="/nb1.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Main Menu" hspace=20></a>
<a href="#top"> <IMG SRC="/nb2.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Top of Page" hspace=20></a>
<a href="#toolbar"> <IMG SRC="/nb3.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 alt="Toolbar" hspace=20></a>
</center><br><br><p><p><p>


<a name="STAT"></a>
<h4>STATUS REPORTS</h4>
<b>Monday 5 February 1996</b><br><p>
I have asked specific people to submit "benchmark" papers on certain subjects listed in the first circular.  The topics covered as: neural 
networks, mine system simulation, expert systems, computer assisted mine design, dispatching systems  and virtual reality.  I still need authors for papers on robotics and virtual reality as applied to mining.  (The person I asked to write the paper on virtual reality is not familiar with its development with regard to mining).  I will welcome any suggestions!!<p>

Someone wrote to me and asked if there will be any papers on the application of fuzzy logic in mining.  This is a good point.  Any suggestions???  I have quite a few commitments for "regular" papers.<p>

Remember that as a member of the organizing committee, your name and institution will be underlined.  If you are not familiar with how the WEB site works, anything that is underlined will have its own page.  One simply clicks on this and transfers to the page.  Remember that color photos are allowed in WEB pages.  (No fair putting your dog or cat's photo above your name).  I am going to set up my own WEB page in a week or two so you can surf over to it and see what mine looks like (and, of course, I will do the same for you).  George Panagiotou is working on the main WEB site.  It will not be operable until the dates of the symposium.  If you have any comments, suggestions, etc., let me know.  <p>

Gary Howell, CEO of the SME, suggested that we make the proceedings available on CD an nominal cost.  He said that he would assist us in this.  Sounds like a great idea.  Perhaps we can find a corporate sponsor to help underwrite the costs of this.  Any suggestions?  (I have one already but it will take a few months before I can approach the company).<p>

